A4700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BUSCH-HNS &LR;      03-26 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
FORT WORTH _ Eighteen Winston Cup drivers are trying to get in the
field for the Busch Grand National race at Texas Motor Speedway on
Saturday, but it was a former World of Outlaws sprint-car champion
who earned the top spot.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't take long Thursday to see the reconfigured racing
surface at TMS meant faster speeds on the 1.5 mile tri-oval, and
Dave Blaney led the way by winning the pole in Busch qualifying for
Saturday's Coca-Cola 300.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Ohio native guided the Amoco Pontiac to a lap at
183.082 mph, easily surpassing the Busch record at TMS of 180.054
mph that Mark Green set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing was we didn't make any mistakes for an entire
lap, which we didn't do in practice,'' said Blaney, the World of
Outlaws champ in 1995. ``But that was a little better and faster
than we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine drivers bettered the old mark, including Mark Martin,
18-year-old Adam Petty and Jeff Gordon. Martin will start next to
Blaney on the front row, and Petty will be inside of Gordon on row
2.
</P>
<P>
   The increased speeds were a result of the $3 million worth of
renovations on the track last spring after the 1998 NASCAR weekend
when complaints about the racing surface continued from the
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The track was completely reconfigured by leveling off the
banking transition, widening the entrance and exit to the
frontstretch, and adding a new drainage system to control a water
seepage problem.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers agree the changes are a success, but they learned
Thursday that the increased speeds have caused a new concern. The
cars are able to hold speed entering turn 1, but it has made things
a little tricky getting through turn 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are carrying so much speed coming off turn 1 that you need
to pay attention to stay out of trouble,'' Blaney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the frontstretch feels like Atlanta (Motor Speedway),
but turns 2 and 3 are a little different. The banking falls off and
it gets flat on you real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Things could get interesting today when the Winston Cup cars
will be on the track, because those cars usually are at least five
mph faster than the Busch cars.
</P>
<P>
   But Busch rookie Adam Petty, the grandson of Richard Petty and
the son of Winston Cup driver Kyle Petty, said any potential
problem lies with the drivers, not the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came here this year expecting it to be just like
Atlanta now,'' Petty said. ``At Atlanta you can hold the Busch car
wide open in the turns, but you can't do that here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little too tight to hold your speed and it comes up on
you quicker than you think. There's also a bump between 1 and 2
that can get you loose, but I have no complaints about the
racetrack. I say everybody should leave it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty feels the same way about the growing controversy over so
many Winston Cup drivers competing in the Busch races, which is
supposed to be a circuit for the up-and-coming drivers in NASCAR.
But more and more big-money Cup stars are driving in BGN races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say bring 'em on and let 'em run,'' Petty said. ``The only
way you learn is from somebody better competing against you. I
think the (Busch) guys that are complaining just need to step up
their game a little.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Busch drivers feel differently about the Cup guys
taking money out of their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille O'Neal can't go back to college for the NCAA
Tournament,'' said two-time Busch champion Randy LaJoie. ``Let us
have our series back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lajoie failed to make the top 25 Thursday while nine Cup drivers
earned a spot in the field. Dale Earnhardt Jr., the defending BGN
champion who earned his first Busch victory at Texas last year,
sees both sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' said Earnhardt Jr., who will
start on the outside of row 6 Saturday. ``It's pretty obvious they
are taking our points, taking our money and sending guys home that
otherwise would be racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the people who do get to race against guys like Mark
Martin and Jeff Gordon gain so much knowledge. There's no limit to
what these guys can teach you. Without racing against them, I
probably wouldn't be half the race car driver I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   Cup drivers have won three of five Busch events this season.
Seventeen Cup regulars started at Las Vegas earlier this month,
sending home several Busch teams that have full-season
sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Even Martin, who is the all-time Busch leader with 35 victories
in the series, admits the situation needs to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy whenever a (Busch) regular has to go home,''
Martin said. ``But it's something that somebody smarter than me is
going to have to look at and decide what is acceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
