</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AND SENATE APPROVE REPUBLICAN BUDGET PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs for updating and revisions throughout to reflect Senate
passage)  (bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House and Senate passed the Republican budget
Thursday night, driving toward a big tax cut and a showdown with
the Clinton administration over the nation's priorities in an
emerging era of fiscal plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Both chambers passed the measure on largely party-line votes,
uniting Republicans in the two chambers as they prepare for months
of budget battles with the White House and set an agenda they hope
to carry into the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the House was 221-208, with 4 Democrats voting in
favor and 2 Republicans voting against. The vote in the Senate was
55-44, with 1 Democrat voting in favor and 1 Republican not voting.
Both chambers also turned aside Democratic budget proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget calls for a tax cut of nearly $800 billion
over the next 10 years, an increase in Pentagon spending and more
money for education.
</P>
<P>
   But to remain within strict spending limits that both parties
have vowed to honor, the plan would require deep cuts in most other
programs, prompting sharp criticism from Democrats and leaving even
some Republicans uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting their competing visions of how to divide the
expected fiscal windfall in coming years, the two parties generally
agreed on setting aside the bulk of projected surpluses for Social
Security, which will come under financial strain as the baby boom
generation retires.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the enduring sensitivity of Social Security as
a political issue, they battled furiously over whose approach
walled off more money for the system and did more to reduce the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats attacked Republicans as putting tax cuts ahead of
dealing with the looming problems in Medicare, which will start
running short of money in less than a decade. And Democrats said
the Republican tax cuts would grow so big over the next decade that
they could send the budget back into deficit if the economy
falters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a budget means making choices,'' said House Speaker
Dennis Hastert. The Republican budget, he said, ``makes the right
choices for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday night, President Clinton called the
Republican plan a series of missed opportunities at a time when the
country is facing the welcome prospect of years of federal budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fails to lock in debt reduction, fails to extend the
solvency of Social Security and Medicare, and fails to protect key
investments for the American people, from Head Start to clean water
and law enforcement,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget resolution passed Thursday night does not become law
but serves as the blueprint for the tax and spending bills Congress
will take up in the coming months. While it gives the Republicans a
chance to emphasize what they see as their core values _ fiscal
austerity, tax cuts and smaller government _ it leaves until later
in the year the question of how to carry out the spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the appropriations committees that set spending
levels for specific programs say it will be politically difficult
if not impossible to pass spending bills requiring sweeping
cutbacks in the State Department, the environment, the FBI, Head
Start and NASA, among other programs.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the bipartisan demand for new spending, the
Senate on Thursday night approved an amendment adding $10 billion
to the budget over 10 years for child care. Earlier, the Senate
rejected a call for additional aid for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget does not specify what types of tax cuts
Congress should enact, leaving that decision to the tax-writing
committees in the House and Senate. The budget allows for a tax cut
of $15 billion next year, an amount that would increase rapidly in
subsequent years as the non-Social-Security surplus grows.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership has backed off its pledge earlier this
year to cut income tax rates by 10 percent. Instead, Republicans
are now looking at packages that could include some rate
reductions; reductions in the so-called marriage penalty that leads
many two-income couples to pay more in taxes than if they were
single; a cut in inheritance taxes, and a reduction in capital
gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the House Ways and Means
Committee, where tax legislation must originate, said he would not
draw up his tax bill until this summer.
</P>
<P>
   There are relatively minor differences in the House and Senate
versions of the budget resolution. Republican aides said they
expected the differences to be worked out quickly when Congress
returns after a two-week recess in April and the final version of
the measure to win quick approval in both chambers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest changes in the budget is a vow to end the
practice of using Social Security surpluses to offset spending or
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would require that all surpluses generated by Social
Security _ $1.8 trillion over the next decade under the assumptions
used by Congress _ be used only to reduce the national debt or to
help pay for an overhaul of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their plan would do more for Social Security
than Clinton's proposal, which in the first few years would allow
some of the retirement system's money to be used for spending but
would make up for it in later years. Using the Congressional Budget
Office's assumptions about the size of the surplus, the
administration's plan would wall off $1.52 trillion over 10 years
for Social Security, $275 billion less than the Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials argued that their plan set aside more
for Social Security and Medicare combined over the same period.
Using the budget office's assumptions, the administration's plan
would reserve $370 billion for Medicare _ bringing the total for
Social Security and Medicare over 10 years to nearly $1.9 trillion
_ while the Republican plan does not have any money explicitly set
aside for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in the House who voted against the bill were
Constance Morella of Maryland and Jack Quinn of New York. The
Democrats in the House who voted for the bill were Robert ``Bud''
Cramer of Alabama, Gary Condit of California, Ralph Hall of Texas
and Virgil Goode Jr. of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The only senator to cross party lines was John Breaux, D-La.,
who voted in favor of the Republican plan. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Republicans of shortchanging Medicare to
finance a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple choice,'' said Representative Richard A.
Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader in the House. ``They
choose the tax cut over extending the solvency of Social Security
and Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear sign of how reluctant lawmakers are to be seen as
dipping into Social Security money, the House rejected Clinton's
budget proposal, 426 to 2, because it allowed some of the Social
Security surplus to be spent over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The House also rejected two other alternative budget proposals.
One was backed by the House Democratic leadership and the other by
a group of fiscally conservative Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
