<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-STARWARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISGUIDED MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with the missile defense system that Ronald Reagan
proposed, the much derided ``Star Wars,'' was that no defense
system could guard against the tens of thousands of warheads that
the Soviet Union, now Russia, could pour down upon the United
States. But with rogue nations entering the missile age, the
Clinton administration sees some justification in building a
defense that would protect the United States from just one or two
incoming warheads _ a far simpler land- or sea-based system than
the space-based idea of the Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is how to square such a system with the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. The original thinking behind that
treaty was that an ABM system would provoke the Soviet Union and
the United States into a counterproductive arms race. That was back
in Soviet times. Russia today cannot afford an arms race. But we
still need the Russians to ratify the Start II agreement so they
will begin dismantling their 7,000 intercontinental missiles, which
remain a potential threat to the peace of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the kind of antimissile system that is being proposed
would not be designed to shoot down the huge Russian missile force,
and the United States has explained that to the Russians. Reagan
once proposed that the United States build a ``Star Wars'' system
for the Russians so as not to undermine the rationale behind the
ABM Treaty. But the Russians so far are not buying any of that.
</P>
<P>
   The technology to build an effective antimissile defense is
still far in the future, and it may be that one day the United
States will calculate that such a system is more in our interests
than sticking to the agreement we have with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington should tread carefully along this path. For the
time being the United States is getting more security out of the
ABM Treaty than it would from a defense against the North Koreas,
Irans, or Iraqs of the world, which do not yet have the capability
to attack this continent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
