<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MICROSOFTENING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A settlement is exactly how the antitrust court battle between
Microsoft and the US Department of Justice should end.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's steely grip on the operating systems of personal
computers needs to be loosened. And this is the time to act _ while
the case is in recess through mid-April. Otherwise the federal
government could find itself in the troubling position of telling a
private company how to operate. That could weigh the government
down with the complex and potentially damaging work of having to
micromanage Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Some like the idea of slicing Microsoft into small companies _
breaking it up the way the government broke up AT&AMP;T and Standard
Oil. But that is easier said than done. Splitting up Microsoft
might make it less of an industry bully, but it could also damage
the positive traits that have made Microsoft good for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a settlement could offer the best of two worlds: relief
from Microsoft's dominance and a chance for the government to
continue keeping its eye on Microsoft's actions.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only Microsoft's CEO, Bill Gates, has admitted that
settlement talks are occurring. The Justice Department is sticking
with a statement made Monday by Assistant Attorney General Joel
Klein. ``We have not received any settlement proposal from
Microsoft,'' he said, adding that ``if there are to be any
settlement discussions, it is best that they occur directly between
the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Some state attorneys general have called a reported settlement
offer from Microsoft ``minimalist'' and ``inadequate.'' Yet this
unimpressive start is a first step. It signals that a settlement is
possible but will take work. More talks between Microsoft, the
Justice Department, and the suing states are scheduled to take
place on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides might play tough. But they should quickly find their
way to this common ground: Both parties are better off with a
settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
