<HEADER>
A4706 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TPC-HNS &LR;      03-26 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ A couple of guys who used to battle it
out on the Texas junior golf circuit have taken different routes to
their current position atop the leader board after one round of The
Players Championship.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you plotted the courses Bob Estes and Brian Watts followed to
get where they were Thursday, it would look like two trucks
starting off in opposite directions and meeting head on at the
other side of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   But they are together again at 4-under-par 68, the best scores
from the best players in the world on a day when conditions were
ideal for low scores but nobody was able to manhandle the
Tournament Players Course at Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   Watts is a Dallas native who attended Oklahoma State, then made
a career out of playing in Japan, where he was one of the kingpins
on the Asian tour.
</P>
<P>
   Estes, meanwhile, grew up in Abilene, honed his game with the
Texas Longhorns and has won more than $4 million on the PGA Tour
since he came to the big time straight out of college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the same age,'' Watts said of the leading pair. ``We
played lots of junior golf against each other. He went to Texas. I
went to Oklahoma State. And we've taken a little bit different
paths as professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob has been out here since day one and done extremely well.
It took me five-plus years to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   But Watts is making up for lost time in a hurry. He burst onto
the scene last year at the British Open, when his bunker shot from
a half-cocked stance at the 18th hole at Royal Birkdale went in
from 50 feet and got him into a playoff against Mark O'Meara, to
whom he eventually lost.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was another 50-foot shot that got Watts' round
going. He started the day like a rank amateur, going 4 over par
after three holes when he triple-bogeyed the par-5 11th, then
bogeyed the 12th. But four birdies in a row ensued, including his
chip-in at the 14th. Before he was done, Watts would birdie eight
of the next 11 holes after his crummy start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 4-over, and then a miracle happened, I guess,'' Watts
said. ``You probably can't print what I said after No. 12. But then
I figured, `What the heck? The worst thing that can happen is I
either shoot in the 80s or I miss the cut.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever, I was still going to live through the day, most
likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shot on 14 was probably the one that got me thinking I
could turn the day around.''
</P>
<P>
   He went from 4-over to 4-under quickly, producing one of the
most exciting scorecards on a day when there were plenty of
noteworthy developments.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't Greg Norman recording four 6s on his card,
including a triple bogey at the treacherous island-green par-3
17th, it was Fred Couples hitting his tee shot into the water on
that hole, then teeing it back up and shooting the next ball into
the hole on the fly for a somewhat-less-than-routine par.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't Craig Stadler mixing in a triple bogey and a double
bogey but still shooting par-72, it was John Cook making only one
par on the front nine, which he needed 42 strokes to cover.
</P>
<P>
   And proving that mental demons can take up permanent residence,
John Daly started his round with the first of two triple bogeys and
ended up shooting 83. This is two years after Daly trashed his
hotel room at the TPC and entered alcohol rehab after withdrawing
following an all-night bender.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is plenty of trouble out there lurking,'' said Hal
Sutton, who was among three players one stroke behind the leaders
and was referring to the golf course rather than extracurricular
activities. ``The wind gets swirling, and you have to pay attention
to what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the TPC rarely is as exposed as it was Thursday. The
weather was gorgeous. The wind was off and on _ and never more than
a refreshing breeze.
</P>
<P>
   But the greens were similar to bedrock. And the rough has been
grown to U.S. Open proportions. Those traits, plus the fact that
the TPC simply is a difficult course, lifted the average score to
74.5 strokes per player.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that the two leaders were among the first
players who hit the course and took advantage of the calm, dewy
conditions in the early-morning hours to get a jump on the rest of
the field. Of the 14 players who shot 70 or better, 10 played in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was David Duval, who shot 69 to tie Sutton and Joe
Ozaki in third place.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is coming back after three weeks off but said he played a
lot of golf leading up to The Players. He visited Augusta National
for 36 holes and had at least two days when he played 27 holes each
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I played quite well,'' Duval said of his comeback. ``I
expect a lot of myself, so I'm not going to say I hit it better
than I might have expected after a break. But I'm very pleased
starting out like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As was Watts, who couldn't have seen his remarkable turnaround
coming after the way he started.
</P>
<P>
   He made 8 on the par-5 11th, which was his second hole, without
having any penalty strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But Watts is proof that it's possible to recover from a horrible
start.
</P>
<P>
   Estes, meanwhile, was somewhat more consistent, mixing six
birdies against two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of tournament where you want to start fast
because you know the course can get a lot tougher as the week goes
along,'' Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   As he was leaving the interview room, Estes bumped into Watts
and said: ``Don't tell them how bad you used to beat me in junior
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts declined to divulge how past matches between the two went.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
