<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS: NO MORE ONE-ON-ONE PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kurt Rambis and four assistant coaches sat in a
circle on the hardwood floor of the Southwest College gym Thursday
afternoon, looking like they would, at any moment, clasp hands and
chant in unison in a desperate attempt to drive away the Lakers'
demons.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it hasn't gotten (begin ital)that(end ital) desperate
yet, but the coaches have begun a program of modest changes to
break the bad mojo that has seen the Lakers go 4-4 over the past
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, Rambis is proclaiming a near-ban on
one-on-one offense, and he's adding wrinkles to put more movement
in a stagnant half-court game.
</P>
<P>
   Next up could be a shakeup in the starting lineup and the
rotation, possibly the demotion of starting power forward Travis
Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still kicking around ideas,'' Rambis said, ``and I'll
come up with a final decision (today).''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the changes will not involve the activation of rookie
guard Tyronn Lue from the injured list. But as for a change at
power forward, where Knight starts almost every game with two quick
fouls, Rambis offered only a long ``maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Rambis has redefined the roles of J.R. Reid and Sean
Rooks _ they'll split time at backup center, depending on the
opponent's lineup. Reid's minutes at power forward will diminish,
opening more playing time for Knight, Dennis Rodman and Robert
Horry.
</P>
<P>
   But only one change is certain: the ban on individual play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want one-on-one. You wanna play one-on-one, go down to
the `Y' (YMCA). That's where they play one-on-one,'' Rambis said.
``I think our team is much better when we do things off of movement
and quick baskets. I think we play right into somebody else's hands
when we play one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant is frequently criticized for such play but isn't the
only culprit. ``I was upset with several players for playing
one-on-one,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday, the Lakers spent practice working on
long-forgotten methods for creating open shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movement, that was the theme of today's practice,'' Bryant
said. ``Constantly cutting, spacing, reading each other. . . . I'm
really anxious to see how this movement plays out during the game.
If the movement plays out the way it should play out, we're gonna
have a lot more easy baskets. I'm not just talking about coming off
of screens. . . . I'm talking about guys getting layups off of
backdoor picks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily new _ movement was a frequent theme of Del
Harris' _ but coaches hope the renewed emphasis will eliminate some
bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he can ``go one-on-one all day,'' but acknowledged,
``if you wanna improve your basketball game you gotta work on
everything, and I'm ready and willing to move without the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis also hopes better offense will provide more scoring
chances for new acquisition Glen Rice. After Wednesday's loss to
Phoenix, Rice seemed upset over his shooting opportunities (he was
5 for 12) but said he didn't ``feel like talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably not getting enough shots based on how we've been
playing our offense,'' Rambis said. ``That's why I wanted to try
and make some changes today in how we ran things, just to clear up
more opportunities for everybody to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Shaquille O'Neal's self-described ``stomach
problems'' in Wednesday's game _ which caused him to sit for a long
stretch in the first half _ turned out to be nothing more than
digestive difficulties. He did not aggravate his chronic abdominal
muscle injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
