<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-CITYWALK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL STUDIO'S CITYWALK FEATURES MIX OF NIGHTCLUBS,
RESTAURANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., N.Y., S.C. Tenn.) (rk) 
 By   BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ In the ever-escalating theme park battles of
Central Florida, CityWalk is Universal Studios' answer to the
popular nighttime entertainment complexes at Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-acre CityWalk opened in February, strategically placed
near the entrance to the Universal Studios theme park. It's
city-like streets lead to nightclubs, restaurants and shops where
surprises wait inside each door.
</P>
<P>
   CityWalk is still growing but already boasts nine restaurants
and nightclubs including a reggae club that is a replica of the
house Bob Marley called home in Kingston, Jamaica. Marley looks
down from photos on a living room wall as reggae sways listeners
like the palm fronds overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street is Jimmy Buffet's Margaritaville, where parrot
heads cheer as a 6-foot volcano spews margarita mix into an
oversized blender.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, CityJazz doubles as Downbeat magazine's Jazz
Hall of Fame. It is a shrine where an original American art form
comes to life with saxes on stage and the wide-eyed images of Duke
Ellington and Miles Davis on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Joni Davis, who lives in Jacksonville, wasn't a reggae fan
before she and her husband walked into Bob Marley _ A Tribute to
Freedom. But as the music's live vibe poured forth from an open-air
courtyard stage, they decided it was worth exploring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of new to me, but I like it,'' said Davis, 34. ``And
I love this atmosphere: the music and the beat.''
</P>
<P>
   About a city block away, Debi Jester of Winter Park and a friend
munched conch fritters inside Margaritaville while dozens of others
crowded around the Volcano Bar and awaited its frozen concoction
eruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the island look to it,'' Jester said.
</P>
<P>
   CityWalk's design was no accident. Universal built the complex
at a junction where visitors _ including those heading to Universal
Studios and the under-construction Islands of Adventure theme park
_ pass through on their way from huge parking garages.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the parking garage via moving sidewalks, they
enter CityWalk through a walkway depositing them in the heart of
the complex, overlooking a plaza and lagoon complete with floating
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Those leaving the theme parks, on the other hand, will find an
Emerald City-like beacon of fun glowing ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point was to put the entire place on display to face the
people coming out of the two parks,'' says Gentry Akens, CityWalk's
director of venue design. ``So you will see this majestic,
neon-glowing thing coming out and you will want to investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   CityWalk restaurants include chains such as NASCAR Cafe, which
joins locations in Nashville, Tenn., and Myrtle Beach, S.C., and
Emeril's, the second eatery opened by chef and restaurant owner
Emeril Lagasse.
</P>
<P>
   Due to open soon are a Motown Cafe, where a 28-foot replica of
the Jackson Five's single ``ABC'' spins overhead as performers
emulate The Temptations and the Supremes on stage. The restaurant
is bigger than existing locations in Las Vegas and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to open in late April is a Latin Quarter, where
south-of-the-border music vies for attention with plantains, flan
and other delicacies.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned is a complex of 21 movie theaters, 13 specialty
shops and, across a lagoon, an NBA restaurant next to the already
open Hard Rock Cafe _ where acts such as Natalie Merchant, Ringo
Starr and B.B. King are slated to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Universal officials believe the number of CityWalk's nightclubs
compares favorably to Downtown Disney's West Side, which offers
such restaurants as Wolfgang Puck's Cafe and Bongos Cuban Cafe,
which is co-owned by Gloria Estefan.
</P>
<P>
   While Disney World's Pleasure Island charges an $18.95 admission
to enjoy all of its clubs, CityWalk is free to enter. At night,
however, CityWalk clubs charge covers that range from $3 to $9.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Dean writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
