<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-EXECUTIVE-NYT     03-26 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-EXECUTIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAL'S PRESIDENT WINS TOP JOB  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Completing a suddenly meteoric rise after 32 years at United
Airlines, James E. Goodwin was appointed chairman and chief
executive Thursday of the UAL Corp., United's parent. He will take
over in July, succeeding Gerald Greenwald, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by UAL's board ended a closely watched five-month
search that had narrowed the choice to Goodwin, who was named UAL's
president in September, and Louis R. Hughes, a top executive at the
General Motors Corp.. Goodwin appears to have had the edge because
he was an insider and had cultivated strong relations with United's
unions.
</P>
<P>
   Management and employees own 55 percent of UAL, making it the
largest employee-owned company in the world. The company said that
Goodwin, 54, was the unanimous choice of the six-member executive
committee, which includes Greenwald and representatives of the Air
Line Pilots Association and the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers, United's two largest unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly fitting in an employee-owned company that the CEO
come from within our own ranks,'' said Michael H. Glawe, the head
of the pilots union and a board member.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the search who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said that Goodwin emerged as a top candidate late in the
process, making his ascension all the more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Goodwin was a senior vice president, in charge of
North America, when he was named president in September. He
succeeded John A. Edwardson, Greenwald's hand-picked heir apparent,
who was forced out after losing a vote of confidence from the
pilots and machinists. Though Goodwin was named to UAL's board, the
company made clear that he was not necessarily a candidate to
succeed Greenwald.
</P>
<P>
   But in time his star rose. Some experts watching the
developments said the prospect of running a worker-owned company
had made it difficult for UAL to attract strong candidates. But
Greenwald said in a statement Thursday that the search committee
saw many exceptional prospects. Then he added: ``As we proceeded,
it became clear to us that Jim was the template against which we
were measuring everyone else. He emerged as the gold standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, 50, headed GM's international operations until last fall
when he was sidelined in a reorganization. He is now executive vice
president in charge of new business strategies. In addition to his
management experience _ Greenwald also came for the auto industry _
he was seen as an attractive candidate because of the time he had
spent at European companies where unions sat on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, in his three decades at United, has worked in nearly
every part of the airline, including finance, maintenance,
marketing, airport operations and reservations. A tall bear of a
man with a friendly mien, Goodwin had a few glitches, such as being
less accustomed to the public speaking required of a corporate
president. United executives and Wall Street analysts say that he
has improved markedly since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the main attribute that appeared to win him the top job was
the strong ties he developed with the unions. ``Since he has been
president, we've found him to be accessible, responsive to employee
concerns and aboveboard in his dealings with us,'' said Ken Thiede,
the president of United's machinists union local.
</P>
<P>
   Such a reserve of goodwill may well come in handy, as Goodwin
will take over at a critical time for United. He will have to
negotiate new contracts with both the pilots and the machinists and
decide whether to renew the employee stock ownership program that
expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main challenges I see ahead,'' he said in a statement
Thursday ``are meeting the needs of an increasingly sophisticated
customer on a global basis and building upon the strides we have
made already to improve the relationship among management, unions
and all employees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
