<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-26 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO FORKS IN THE ROAD OF FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The lessons of the old school are not so
easily dismissed. Leon Barmore never looked at the sport of women's
basketball as the land of opportunity, and for most of his two
decades-plus at Louisiana Tech, there was never a reason to.
</P>
<P>
   Barmore's career path had carried few, if any, to fame, or
wealth. He had a good job in his hometown, where he graduated from
high school, and went to college, and met his wife, and raised his
daughter, who went to the same high school and college as him.
</P>
<P>
   He was flattered when a team from David Stern's new professional
league called, tormented even, because the offer in Houston wasn't
that far from Ruston, La., his rural sanctuary of ``churches and
parking meters.'' The chance to coach in the Women's National
Basketball Association represented exciting new challenge, live and
in color on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Barmore remained in Ruston, with a recruiting class he believed
in and a sense of duty to a slumping program, at least by the
standards of where it had been. He let the pro job go, and another
veteran male women's college coach _ Van Chancellor of Mississippi
_ wound up with Cynthia Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes, a couple of titles
and all the trimmings.
</P>
<P>
   Barmore has been rewarded for his loyalty and faith, traveling
two more roads to the Final Four, but apparently not without a few
wistful moments. He couldn't stop himself from wondering about that
other road at the fork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one opportunity and I may never _ you know, I'm not
going into that,'' Barmore said, with a heavy sigh. ``I wish I
could have done both. You can't do both.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not so much about right or wrong, as it is about what he
knows, how he was raised.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Peck, running in a younger, can-do crowd, made no such
rationalizations last July when the telephone rang and the people
from the WNBA startup franchise in Orlando asked her to come for
the following summer.
</P>
<P>
   One year after assuming her first head coaching post at Purdue,
she said, of course, she would love to.
</P>
<P>
   If Barmore reflects the sport's organic past, Peck is about its
intriguing future. Their worlds collide when Louisiana Tech meets
Peck and No. 1 Purdue tonight in one of the national semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Peck will leave Purdue behind when the
weekend is over. She will take the leap, the first big-time college
coach to do so, not worried about risk.
</P>
<P>
   Barmore, for his part, didn't have the benefit of knowing the
W.N.B.A. would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it might get the crowds in five or 10 years,'' he
said. He let the train leave without him, a new-school lesson Peck
obviously learned.
</P>
<P>
   For people like her, women's basketball is an upwardly mobile
world of opening doors and potential rewards. She is 32, 6 feet 4
inches tall, a smart, composed woman who played the modern game at
Vanderbilt and coaches it with a Tennessee twang and a radiant
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Purdue, she had already been an assistant at
Tennessee and Kentucky, after playing professionally in Japan. In
1997, she took over a team in turmoil, steered it into the Elite 8,
and now the Final Four. She has a become a commodity, like the
young Rick Pitino, brushing off her departure with a politician's
elan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about what's going to happen,'' she said. ``We
are focusing on what's happening right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Barmore said he wished he didn't have to coach against Peck,
whom he admires, though the proud veteran in him added, ``I don't
think anybody will out-coach me.'' The train may have left him
behind, but not the game.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime practitioner of the half-court offense, he now
``bites his lip, sits down and watches a track meet.'' He loves the
sport. He just wishes he had more time to enjoy what it is going to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 10, 20 years, it will be unbelievable,'' he said. ``I
wish I could roll back the clock and be 30 again.''
</P>
<P>
   Barmore won a national title in 1988, developed his share of
Olympians and pros. When the inaugural WNBA season began without
him, he swelled with pride watching Teresa Weatherspoon and Vicki
Johnson from little Louisiana Tech play their opener in Los
Angeles, in Magic Johnson's house.
</P>
<P>
   That's one version of progress, of moving on. His daughter is
getting married on April 10th, and that is another. By then,
Carolyn Peck will be off to Orlando, preparing for the summer pro
season. Leon Barmore said he's happy for her. He looks forward to
watching on TV. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
