<HEADLINE>
EBAY TO PAY $75 MILLION FOR SPOTS ON SEVERAL AMERICA ONLINE SITES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ In one of the largest partnership deals in
the short history of the World Wide Web, the online auction site
Ebay announced Thursday that it would pay $75 million for prominent
placement on several services owned by America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year deal establishes Ebay as the official auction site
on America Online's proprietary service and its other online
properties, including AOL.com, Compuserve, the chat service ICQ and
the company's newest acquisition, Netscape Communications Corp.'s
Netcenter Web portal.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first such deal to encompass all of America Online's
services. The company's proprietary service alone has 16 million
members. ``This will bring us an enormous number of new users,''
said Steven P. Westly, Ebay's vice president for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But the real estate is not cheap. The deal is the third largest
for America Online, behind a $150 million, five-year deal with
Tele-Save, a long-distance company, and a five-year $300 million
deal with the credit card company First USA.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Ebay deal will see less cash changing hands, it is
not exclusive. The deals with Tele-Save and First USA are. Four
other auction sites _ Bid.com, Onsale, First Auction and Ubid _
will continue to be able to buy advertising on America Online, said
Wendy Goldberg, a spokeswoman for America Online, which is based in
Dulles, Va.
</P>
<P>
   But Ebay will be the only company marketed as America Online's
auction partner, with its services integrated into content areas.
For example, Ebay will have its own site within America Online, but
with the same auctions that are available on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``continues to confirm that AOL's real estate is
prime,'' said Marc Johnson, a senior analyst at Jupiter
Communications, a New York research company. He called the deal
``very substantial, even in Internet dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal also highlights Ebay's rapid rise to prominence. The
company went public in September at $18 a share. It closed Thursday
at $159.375, but the stock has already undergone a 3-for-1 split,
making each original share worth $478.125.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a smooth ride, however. Earlier this year, Ebay
was unable to keep up with traffic to its site, and several
government agencies have initiated investigations of other issues,
including allegations that the site was used to deal in fake sports
memorabilia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
