<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON TURNS UP THE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kings coach Larry Robinson gave a strongly
worded speech to his players at Thursday morning's practice before
the evening's game against the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson told the players that some of their careers _ at least
their careers with the Kings _ would be at stake over the next
three-plus weeks as the team tries to battle its way into playoff
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of this,'' Robinson said later. ``And I don't
care if we're 15 points behind. To me, the (measure) of a man is
when he fights right to the death. I don't give a damn if we're
two, five or 16 points behind. I want to see guys give their all
until the last buzzer goes on the 18th of April. Don't look at the
standings, don't look at anything else. Just give it your all.
That's all you can ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he'd been concerned about his team's level of
concentration at the end of a week in which the Steve Duchesne
issue was resolved, center Yanic Perreault was dealt to Toronto and
the trading deadline passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot went on the last two or three days,'' Robinson said.
``When you're not among the elite teams in the league, everybody
feels, `Gee, am I going?' It's always an uneasy feeling. Everybody
handles it differently. My job is to get these guys ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the crispness that marked recent practices was
missing the past couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw that the concentration level wasn't there,'' he
said. ``Preparation doesn't start when you walk in at 4:30 or 5 at
night (before a game). The last couple of days, the high tempo that
had been there wasn't there. Yes, I understand a couple of friends
moved on. Buy you've got to look after yourself. That's what the
games are all about _ preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Babych arrives: The newest King was not in the lineup Thursday
night, but he said he's ready to contribute when he gets the
chance, an opportunity that may come Sunday in Colorado when the
Kings begin a five-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Babych arrived in town Wednesday, and practiced with his
new team for the first time Thursday morning. Drafted in 1980 and
approaching his 38th birthday, Babych said he's planning to play
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing for sure,'' said Babych, acquired Tuesday in the
trade that sent Steve Duchesne to Philadelphia. ``I'm not ready to
stop. I've got no doubt about it. I feel too good to stop. I think
I'd be cheating myself if I didn't want to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Babych's contract expires after the season, but he said he'd
like to remain with the Kings next season. He also said he believes
he can help the team immediately, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got seven defensemen here,'' he said. ``They know they
can count on me to step in and not hurt the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Bodger, Robinson said: ``I think he's very similar to Dougie
Bodger, a real smart player, a big strong kid who can move the
puck. He played on the power play in Philadelphia. He's a cagey
veteran, is what he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
