<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIR-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MORE 737 HOMEWORK FOR BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   Despite significant modifications made after the 1994 crash of a
Boeing 737 jetliner near Pittsburgh, the National Transportation
Safety Board has rightly decided to withhold its approval from the
current design of 737 rudders. In a unanimous decision, the federal
safety panel found that the design ``is not reliably redundant'' _
meaning, essentially, that it does not have sufficient capacity to
compensate for its own failure.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB's findings reflected more than its analysis of that and
another 737 disaster in 1991 that together took 157 lives. They
also underscored the board's determination to push the aviation
industry to learn everything it can about the admittedly murky
world of rudder malfunctions on the very aircraft that is the
workhorse of domestic aviation. In February, for example, a Boeing
737 operated by Metrojet made an emergency landing in Baltimore
because of a rudder problem. But the precise nature of that problem
remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration says it does not know what
the NTSB means by a ``reliably redundant'' rudder design. As the
regulator of airlines and aircraft manufacturers, the FAA often
sounds defensive whenever the board issues a major safety
recommendation. In addition, the FAA has in fact approved several
changes that should eliminate rudder reversal, in which the rudder
moves in a direction contrary to the pilot's command. Rudder
reversal has been cited as the probable cause of 1994 crash as well
as one in Colorado Sprimgs in 1991 that took 25 lives. But the NTSB
is urging the FAA and Boeing to examine the entire universe of
potential rudder problems, including the mysterious malfunction
that afflicted the Metrojet flight.
</P>
<P>
   Redundancy is one of the primary tenets of aviation design. If
one engine fails, the other engine or engines allow the craft to
operate safely. Every system needs a reliable backup. For that
reason, the NTSB has wisely called upon the FAA to convene an
engineering and evaluation board composed of experts from
government, industry and academia to examine other possible sources
of rudder malfunction. The study is to be completed by March 31 of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing considers its system reliable and notes that the problem
of rudder reversal has occurred rarely in 77 million flights. That
is certainly true. But the standard should be as high as possible
for the 737, an aircraft that, as Boeing likes to crow, flies 1
million people a day and takes off every six seconds somewhere in
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
