A4732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-LEE-RIGHTS-NYT &LR;      03-26 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LEE-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN OPPORTUNITY ON CIVIL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is renewing the fight to get Bill Lann Lee
confirmed as assistant attorney general for civil rights, a
position Lee has filled admirably on an acting basis for nearly two
years _ since Republicans on the Senate Judiciary Committee first
blocked his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican response so far is perplexing. No hearings have
been scheduled, and the word on Capitol Hill is that Sen. Orrin
Hatch, the Judiciary Committee's chairman, plans to quietly kill
the nomination by ignoring it, much as he did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the circumstances now are quite different. For one thing,
Lee's record in the post only shows how wrong Hatch and others were
two years ago when they tried to depict his conciliatory approach
to civil rights enforcement as somehow out of the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Lee's nomination has returned to the Senate at a
moment when Republicans have a pressing need to distance themselves
from the bigotry of the Council of Conservative Citizens, a white
supremacist group that has cultivated ties with Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott and Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia. The party's image
was hardly helped this week when the House voted down a
disingenuous GOP resolution that condemned racism but intentionally
avoided any mention of the extreme group.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and his colleagues should wake up and see Lee's nomination
as a political opportunity. By promptly scheduling confirmation
hearings and allowing an up-or-down vote by the full Senate,
Republicans can begin to reassure the nation about their commitment
to racial fairness and civil rights. A party truly aspiring to be
seen as inclusive would not pass up this chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-26 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 McMILLAN'S IMPACT STRETCHES THE IMAGINATION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In his 12-year playing history, the guy has a
club-record 4,893 assists, yet the most important one belongs to
his brother, Randy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never flown alone, I'd never flown that far, I'd never
lived alone,'' Nate McMillan said of his first plane ride to
Seattle in the summer of 1986. ``I cried so much the night before
my flight, I almost didn't get on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, Randy got me on the plane, or I might never have
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the brotherly boot to the backside, Seattle would have
been denied the most earnest, selfless warrior in the city's
relatively brief time as a pro sports joint.
</P>
<P>
   Nate McMillan might be the first athlete whose jersey was
retired primarily because he was a good teammate and a better
person. That says a lot about the state of sports.
</P>
<P>
   It also says something about this place, rewarding someone whose
celebrity profile didn't much exceed the Aurora Avenue tunnel. For
a country son of the Carolinas, McMillan turned out to be as
Seattle as damp floor mats.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like McMillan, you don't enjoy summer, the feel of
300-yard tee shots and the smell of a new baseball glove. As with
all of those things, McMillan can't be quantified, so
numbers-obsessed sports fans won't understand the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   In a league where the garish is falsely feted, McMillan was a
subtlety, an acquired taste favored by connoisseurs. But before we
get too carried away in silly wine-critic analogies, here's a more
substantial measurement of his impact:
</P>
<P>
   McMillan was a key factor in taking the Sonics to two unexpected
appearances in Western Conference title series (1987 and 1993). But
after helping them gain an expected Western title in 1996, his
injury absence for the first half of the Finals against the Bulls
is seen by some as what kept the Sonics from rocking the basketball
world.
</P>
<P>
   Fanciful? Maybe. Such indulgences are acceptable upon ceremonies
such as Wednesday's jersey retirement. The Sonics haven't done one
of those in a couple of decades, so imaginations deserve to be
exercised.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a back ailment sustained a couple series earlier,
when the Sonics reached one of the franchise's all-time highs in a
4-0 sweep of the defending NBA champion Houston Rockets, McMillan
struggled through seven games against Utah. Then he sat out the
first half of the Bulls' series, which not coincidentally went 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know how the injury happened, but I was about
one doctor away from having surgery,'' he said of the disk problem
that sent pain down his legs. ``If I could have given Gary (Payton)
duties away from the ball, we could have done something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, with McMillan, rallied to win a pair at home and
force the Bulls to a sixth game in Chicago before losing.
</P>
<P>
   In the six Bulls' championships with Michael Jordan, no Western
team pushed the Bulls to a seventh game. As well as the Utah Jazz
played the Bulls in the subsequent two Finals, there are hoopheads
who think a healthy '96 Seattle team, with Shawn Kemp at his
unstoppable peak, a more rested Payton and 20 minutes of McMillan
defense on Jordan, would have been best equipped to flirt with
hoops immortality.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan's self-effacing nature won't let him accept the
flattery. Which doesn't mean he can't enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother always comes up with these sayings; I don't know
where she gets them,'' he said. ``She said, `God put me down (with
injury) to show how much I meant to the team.' I don't know how
true it was, but it made me feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a part of the Finals was the best thing about my career.
I'd never been involved in a championship before, at any level.
I'll never forget that atmosphere. So (sitting out the first three
games) was the toughest basketball thing I've ever gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   In a scene filled by Jordan, Dennis Rodman, Scottie Pippen and
the George Karl quote machine, the absence of McMillan was little
noted nor long remembered _ symbolic for a career that flourished
at the back of the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Because of chronic injuries, his last two seasons amounted to 37
and 18 games, so it was easy to lose sight of the fact that at his
peak, McMillan's defense, sense of the game, and sacrifice were
exquisite complementary skills that are rarely drafted, never
rewarded financially and always sought desperately by coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Wednesday, there was a little public recognition for
those less celebrated virtues. Acknowledgment of someone who gave
on the court and in the community was the best thing the Sonics
have accomplished this season _ until McMillan is activated off the
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Those unfamiliar with Sonic basketball will question how
McMillan's jersey rates hanging with championship-makers Lenny
Wilkens, Jack Sikma and Fred Brown.
</P>
<P>
   You hadda be here.
</P>
<P>
   You hadda be from here.
</P>
<P>
   Winners often are made of more than the sum of their W's.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
