<HEADLINE>
VETERAN ASSISTANT GRAHAM TO COACH WSU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vowing to turn around a program that has suffered
through three straight losing seasons, Paul Graham, an assistant
coach the past seven years at Oklahoma State, was hired Thursday as
the new head basketball coach at Washington State University.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who has spent nearly 17 years as a college assistant,
was named as the replacement to Kevin Eastman, who resigned at the
end of the season after the Cougars fell to 10-19.
</P>
<P>
   WSU athletic director Rick Dickson said he felt honored to name
Graham, 48, to his first head-coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a person who has prepared all his life to have this
type of opportunity,'' Dickson said. ``What he really needed was an
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham also was an assistant at New Mexico (1991-92) and SMU
(1982-88).
</P>
<P>
   Graham's five-year contract at WSU will pay him a yearly base
salary of $125,000 plus incentives.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that he has had the opportunity to work under one of
the nation's best head coaches, Oklahoma State's Eddie Sutton, who
has produced 13 other head coaches from the ranks of his
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing in March,'' Graham said in reference to his
goal of taking WSU to the postseason. ``A few years ago, I had the
opportunity to sit next to Eddie Sutton at the Final Four (in
Seattle) and it was really exciting. ... I've been spoiled in my
career going to the NCAA tournament. I kind of like that and I
don't like losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham also is known for helping to produce several quality NBA
players, most notably Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves at Oklahoma
State, Luc Longley at New Mexico and Jon Koncak at SMU.
</P>
<P>
   Graham wasn't making any predictions about a quick turnaround
for the WSU program, which finished last in the Pac-10 (4-14).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready for this challenge, and it is a challenge,'' he
said, comparing the task ahead to a new marriage. ``... Everyone
has told me when they talk about Washington State how tough the job
is. People told me marriage was tough and now I'm deeply in debt
and have two children at home. But I've succeeded as a husband and
I've succeeded as a father, and now I want to take that same
passion ... and succeed as a basketball coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham is a 1974 graduate of the University of North Texas. His
son, Nicholas, is 18 and will likely play for his father at
Washington State, Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a program like Oklahoma State that also is located
in a small community (Stillwater), Graham believes that WSU needs
to use its remoteness as an advantage by building an exciting
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this to be the toughest place to play in this league,
and we have to make it that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson said he has known of Graham for several years and first
became acquainted with him while Dickson was athletic director at
Tulsa in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since that time, I have heard over and over again how highly
regarded he is throughout the coaching fraternity around the
country,'' Dickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates for the post included Oregon assistant Don
Newman, Kentucky assistant George Felton, Utah assistant Donny
Daniels, UCLA assistant Jim Saia and Cal State-Northridge head
coach Bobby Braswell.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga coach Dan Monson discussed the vacancy with Dickson
before taking his name out of consideration.
</P>
<P>
   While Dickson said he considered the other candidates, Graham
quickly emerged as the leading contender for the job last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that struck me very clearly was his passion
for what he believes can be done at Washington State University and
his passion to teach and develop young men, not only in the sport
of basketball but with their lives as well,'' Dickson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
