<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS TOPPLE PENGUINS, 5-3, TIGHTENING THEIR GRIP ON FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Although Jaromir Jagr was having a quiet
game, the Pittsburgh Penguins were having their way with the New
Jersey Devils. Pittsburgh was leading by 3-2 at the start of the
third period Thursday night, in a game that would decide the
Atlantic Division leader.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils found another gear in the third period and found
the energy that had been lacking throughout a sluggish second
period. Playing perhaps their most complete 20 minutes of the
season, firing 17 shots at the Penguins' net, the Devils came back
on goals by Brad Bombardir, Petr Sykora, on the power play, and
Patrik Elias, into an empty net, to defeat the Penguins, 5-3, at
Continental Arena before 15,204 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat on our lead,'' Penguins coach Kevin Constantine said.
``We felt we could sit in our end and protect it and not play
hockey. When you quit playing, you allow the other team too many
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Devils' seventh in 10 games and provided
them with a 3-point cushion in their division and moved them to
within 2 points of the Ottawa Senators in the battle for first
place in the Eastern Conference with 12 games remaining in the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur made 11 saves for the Devils and Peter Skudra
made 34 saves for the Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scored when we needed it,'' said Robbie Ftorek, the Devils'
coach. ``They kept working, kept plugging away and took advantage
of some power plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Thursday night's match, the Devils led the Penguins by
1 point in the Atlantic Division, the difference between the
Eastern Conference's second-seeded and the fourth-seeded team in
the playoffs. The Carolina Hurricanes, leaders of the Southeast
Division, were the third-seeded team in the East before Thursday
night's games. As the season nears its end, these numbers become
more relevant as the teams fight for home-ice advantage in the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's third-period rally began with the team playing
aggressive, hard-nosed hockey in the opening minutes. And it didn't
take long for it to pay off. That's when Bombardir scored his first
goal of the season to knot the score at 3-3. The goal, only the
second of his career, sailed over Skudra's left shoulder and into
the corner of the net at 5 minutes 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get it in the air,'' Bombardir said with
a shrug. ``It found the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombardir, who hit the post earlier in the third period, was
assigned, along with his defensive partner Scott Niedermayer, to
mark the Jagr line. And for 60 minutes, they silenced the Penguins'
top forwards.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, who assisted on Matthew Barnaby's first-period goal on a
power play, entered the game with 15 points in his last eight
games. But that assist was a soft one, a dump-in that Brodeur
bobbled, allowing Barnaby to put in the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora's power-play goal at 11:28 of the third period gave the
Devils a 4-3 lead and all they would need to dispose of the
Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little meeting before the game,'' Sykora said of a
talk he had with his linemates, Elias and Jason Arnott. ``Something
was wrong, we didn't score in a couple of games.'' Sykora's line
scored three of the Devils' five goals Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The opening period was fast and crisp and featured plenty of
scoring. The Penguins emerged with a 3-2 advantage on goals by
Aleksei Kovalev, Jan Hrdina and Barnaby. Randy McKay and Arnott
scored the Devils' first-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer appeared to give New Jersey a 2-1 lead on the power
play at 12:36, but Referee Mark Faucette took the goal away because
Sykora's skate entered Skudra's crease before the puck did. The
fans howled in protest, but just as they settled down, Arnott got
them out of their seats again, 22 seconds later, after he scored on
the same power play. It was Arnott's 23d goal of the season.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
