<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-VS.-CUP-DRIVERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP DRIVERS CRASHING BUSCH PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sterling Marlin's head pops back and his
eyes widen. He has realized what's happening in his sport.
</P>
<P>
   There's a transition happening, and Marlin is in the middle.
He's also in the middle of the Busch Grand National garage, which
looks more like a get-together of recognizable Winston Cup drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Cup drivers, including Marlin, are flooding the Busch Grand
National series, and 17 of them will start in tomorrow's Coca-Cola
300. And that influx has helped the feeder series steadily become
more fan friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The increase of Cup drivers racing to Busch is adding to the
excitement and competition, but it's also adding to the
controversy. The concern, from some veterans, is about the future
of the series as Busch drivers are losing possible spots to
full-time Cup drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they trying to do, make this another Winston Cup
series?,'' said Randy LaJoie, who won back-to-back Busch
championships in 1996-97. ``The influx of money and technology is
outpricing the Busch guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think it only helps increase the interest in the Busch
Series.
</P>
<P>
   This year's race at the Texas Motor Speedway, which includes Cup
stars Jeff Gordon, Mark Martin and Terry Labonte, is expected to
draw a larger crowd. Tickets sales are up 15,000 over last season's
race, which drew more than 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past there wasn't enough Busch drivers to field a race,
and now they have enough and it's an issue,'' said Michael Waltrip,
a Winston Cup regular who drives the No. 21 Band-Aid Chevrolet in
Busch races. ``It's really kind of silly. I feel the Busch drivers
should be happy we're running with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cup drivers have made an impact on the Busch series this
season. Of the top 10 in the point standings, three are regular Cup
drivers _ Kevin Lepage, Jeff Burton and Martin. Lajoie, also in the
top 10, runs a part-time Cup schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the controversy surrounds the Cup drivers coming in and
bouncing young Busch drivers from qualifying. Younger drivers are
attempting to gain experience week to week and are now having to
fight past Cup champions like Gordon and Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that get hurt are the ones that can't say anything
about it,'' said Todd Bodine, who drives the No. 66 Phillips
Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   But Matt Kenseth, in his fourth year in the Busch series, hasn't
had much trouble running ahead of the new competition. He is the
current points leader, ahead of Lepage.
</P>
<P>
   While NASCAR has no rules concerning the number of Cup drivers
participating in the Busch series, some believe there should be.
But NASCAR manager of communications Tim Sullivan said there are no
immediate plans to legislate against the practice of driving in
both series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can really see the Busch guys' side,'' Marlin said. ``They
have a sponsor all year, and a Cup guy comes in and knocks you out
of the race. But I don't know what can be done to fix that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brett Bodine, ``I don't think it's right. To be honest, I
wish there were a way to prevent it. We're knocking people out of
Busch who are trying to make a living.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
