<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LABONTE SET FOR GRAND ENTRANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as he has done with sons Terry and Bobby, Bob Labonte will
be at a racetrack next weekend, to strap-in the family's next
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Labonte, the son of two-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion
Terry Labonte and Bob's grandson, is scheduled to make his NASCAR
Busch Grand National Series debut in the BellSouth Mobility 320 at
Nashville Speedway USA in Tennessee on April 3.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Labonte was not in the garage area at Texas Motor
Speedway yesterday, where his father qualified the No. 44 Slim Jim
Chevrolet Monte Carlo 14th. Justin was in class at Trinity (N.C.)
High School, where he plans to graduate this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he's only 18,'' Bob Labonte said. ``But when Bobby was
18, he'd already been racing for 13 years. Justin's been racing
about four years. When I'm out with him at the track, it's almost
scary sometimes. I think I'm with Terry again. Only now I'm 65, and
I was 40 back then. They're a lot alike. Their tempers are about
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin started racing in 1996, and Terry Labonte said he still
has mixed feelings about his son's impending career choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my case, how could I tell my son he couldn't do it?'' said
Labonte, the Cup champion in 1984 and 1996. ``I mean, there's
pictures of him hanging on the wall at home when I won my first
championship, and he was 2 or 3 years old. And if you're going to
be successful in this business, you've got to start young.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin has competed in Mini-Stocks, Grand American cars and most
recently in the Hooters ProCup Series. But everyone in the family
realizes the jump to BGN _ even on a relatively tight short-track
like Nashville _ is huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got mixed feelings about that,'' Terry Labonte said. ``I
told him, `If you don't want to race this thing, it doesn't matter
to me.' He tested there \RTuesday and Wednesday\S and didn't get
too many laps in. But I talked to him Wednesday night and he said,
`I think we'll be all right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Labonte carries the title of Shop Foreman/Pit Foreman on the
Labonte Racing duty roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bob's job description is being Bob,'' said Dick Conway,
the team's public relations representative. ``He's been doing this
for so long that he's the voice of wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Terry Labonte never really worries about Justin when
Bob is with him at the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty proud of his grandson,'' Terry said. ``And it
makes me proud. I've only gone to a few races with him, but when he
gets out of the car, I can't believe it's Justin. Looks like he's
been doing it for years.''
QUICK HITS
ATWOOD CRASHES, LEARNS
</P>
<P>
   Busch rookie Casey Atwood made headlines with a spectacular
tumbling crash on the final lap of the 1999 season-opener at
Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   And he learned a valuable public-relations lesson: There is no
such thing as bad publicity. There is just publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is still talking about it,'' said Atwood, driver of
the No. 27 Castrol GTX Chevy. ``It wasn't the way we wanted to get
attention, but it worked, I guess. The main thing is we were
running up front when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, an 18-year-old resident of Nashville, Tenn., was racing
in second when he got tapped from behind and went airborne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a shock break with about 12 laps to go, so I was trying
to hang on to what I had,'' Atwood said. ``I remember everything
that happened, but it's hard to explain. You can feel it going up
in the air and once it's up in the air, you don't know where you're
at, or how many times you've flipped. It's kind of a weird feeling.
You sit there and hold on, and wait for it to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all of it was over, I was real thankful I was OK. I knew
I wasn't hurt and hoped nobody else had gotten hurt. It was a wild
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said his father, Terry, was at the track that day. But
his mother, Jan, had the misfortune of watching it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the worst place to watch it because they
showed so many replays before they knew if I was OK or not,''
Atwood said. ``And then they still wanted to see me, and make sure
I was all right. I'm sure it was pretty scary for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was real nervous. Even on the plane ride home, he was
still shaking. That tore him up pretty good. He don't want me to do
that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood will start 18th tomorrow in the Coca-Cola 300 after
posting a lap at 179.497 mph. His best finish in four starts this
season is fifth at Rockingham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first win is right under our nose,'' said Atwood, who is
in the first year of a three-year contract with Castrol. ``We're
waiting for some good luck.''
BLANEY MOVES ON
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola 300 pole-winner Dave Blaney has not dwelled on the one
that got away _ his on again/off again victory in the Yellow
Freight 300 this month at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney originally finished second to Mike Skinner, who had his
first BGN victory taken away the next morning after NASCAR
inspectors discovered an illegal cylinder head during a post-race
inspection. Skinner's team appealed, however, and the victory was
returned to the No. 19 team the following Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have been satisfied with that win,'' said Blaney, driver
of the No. 93 Amoco Pontiac Grand Prix. ``It wouldn't have been as
much fun as winning it outright, but still we were running good
enough all day to win. And hey, you've got to be in that position
\Rto win\S. Heck yeah, it would have been good with me to get one
in the record book.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaney is winless in 25 BGN starts in a career launched last
year with car-owner Bill Davis. But Blaney knows how to win. He was
the 1995 World of Outlaws Sprint Car champion, and was runner-up in
the Sprint Car series in 1993, 1994, 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting there,'' said Blaney, speaking about the
transition from open-wheel cars to stock cars. ``The more laps I
can run, the better I feel.''
Burton got it right
</P>
<P>
   The right side Goodyear Eagle radial tires being run in the BGN
and Winston Cup events are the direct result of Cup star Jeff
Burton's tire test here in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the grip that the track had, most of the \Rright side\S
tires we had blistered up real bad,'' said Burton, who qualified
the No. 9 Track Gear Ford Taurus 11th yesterday at 179.922 mph.
``They had to come back with a different compound than what they
had for the test. The tire they brought back is a hard tire, but
it's going to be a safe tire.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
