<HEADLINE>
JUNIOR ACHIEVER: LITTLE E READY FOR LAUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ They started handing out boarding passes to
the Dale Earnhardt Jr. bandwagon in Victory Lane at Texas Motor
Speedway a year ago. And take corporate America's word for it: This
flight will be full by the time ``Little E'' makes his NASCAR
Winston Cup debut in May.
</P>
<P>
   Because as Earnhardt Jr. has come to learn in the months since
he won NASCAR's Busch Grand National series championship and landed
a blockbuster $10 million, five-year contract with Budweiser, there
always is room for one more.
</P>
<P>
   Just one more high-profile associate sponsor, one more
endorsement contract, one more autograph session, one more
one-on-11 with the media. And one more can of beer on the road to
``Countdown to E-Day,'' his sponsor's official promotional campaign
for the 24-year-old stock car driver many believe is the future of
motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   As of today, Earnhardt Jr. is 67 days away from competing in his
first points-paying Cup race, the Coca-Cola 600 at the renamed
Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect brings a mischievous grin to the gaunt face of
Earnhardt, a son of the seven-time Winston Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time anybody makes a comment about the `Countdown to
E-Day,' I re-correct them and tell them it's a countdown to my
first qualifying attempt,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``Because that's
what it is. Everybody knows how difficult it is to make these
\RCup\S races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you could sit there and let it pressure you _ `Countdown
to E-Day' _ because they're expecting me to be in that race.
Nobody's even thought that we might miss it. Know what I'm saying?
But that ain't the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr.'s best finish in five BGN races this season is a
third at Atlanta Motor Speedway. Fifth in the driver's points, he
qualified 12th yesterday for tomorrow's event with a hot lap at
179.850 mph.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a series-leading seven BGN victories, Earnhardt
Jr. posted three poles, 16 top-five and 22 top-10 finishes in 1998.
He crushed the single-season money record with $1,387,461 in
winnings. He finished 48 points ahead of friend and rival Matt
Kenseth, another rising Busch star who is not surprised by the buzz
surrounding Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, he's run awesome,'' said Kenseth, who also is
planning a five-race Cup schedule this year. ``If he was Dale
Earnhardt Jr. and ran 10th or 15th every week and never did
anything, I don't think everybody would be paying as much attention
to him. But he's earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cup star Jeff Burton, who races regularly against Earnhardt Jr.
in the BGN series, said he has been taken aback by the Little
Earnhardt Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of whack, but that's sports,'' said Burton, winner of
the first Cup race at TMS in 1997. ``It's like that in every sport.
But he hasn't been given anything, in the sense that his father's
been able to help him. But his father made him earn it. I think
everybody respects him for that. Everybody in here \Rthe Cup garage
area\S had somebody help them to get where they are. Nobody in here
did it on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a `name' is not going to win you races.''
</P>
<P>
   When he runs an abbreviated five-race Cup schedule with his
championship-winning Busch crew led by Tony Eury Sr. and Tony Eury
Jr., Earnhardt Jr. will need more than his name to qualify. No free
rides for stock-car racing's designated superstar. He will need to
post one of the top-36 fastest speeds to make the starting grid at
LMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kinda get mad about it,'' said Earnhardt Jr., driver of
the No. 3 ACDelco Chevrolet Monte Carlo owned by his famous dad.
``I'd be a complete idiot for not realizing the fact I might not
make that race. If I don't, I'll get death threats, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   He is kidding, of course. And if Earnhardt Jr.'s meteoric rise
to stardom has robbed him of his privacy, it has not completely
rubbed out his sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like you're doing stand-up comedy every time
you're up there,'' said Earnhardt Jr., who has learned on the fly
how to conduct himself before rooms full of executives, media and
fans. ``You're a race-car driver, you're not a spokesperson. You're
not an actor, so they're waiting on you to say something stupid.
You got to stand up there and do the best you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm enjoying it enough to where it's worth it, still. I'm
a long way before I get burned out. I sure hope I ain't. I still
enjoy, by far, driving race cars more than, I think, anybody on the
racetrack. I mean, I just have so much fun with it. It's a long
time before I get too fed up with everything else to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know?''
</P>
<P>
   Budweiser is counting on it. The brewery giant shocked the
NASCAR world last fall when it signed Earnhardt Jr., who had yet to
win his first BGN title, to a five-year contract. After running
five Cup events this year, Earnhardt Jr. will take on the full
schedule in 2000. His contract with Bud runs through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is the breadth and the depth of this
contract,'' said Don Hawk, the president of Dale Earnhardt Inc.,
and Earnhardt Jr.'s agent/negotiator. ``The kid's never driven a
Winston Cup car yet in his life, in a points race, and he's
probably already earned more money than a lot of people that have
driven for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange phenomenon. You look at him _ that's not a
cookie-cutter racer.''
</P>
<P>
   Little E was six races into the 1998 schedule, and coming off a
career-best runner-up effort at Bristol Motor Speedway, when he
rolled into TMS last April. He qualified 16th, his second-worst
effort of the season, on the track's ``old'' tight, 1.5-mile
configuration.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt Jr. was running second to Cup regular Joe Nemechek
when the green flag fell with six laps to go. Dale Jr. began to
reel Nemechek in and then made the race-winning pass exiting Turn 4
_ an area that continually had been criticized as being one-groove
and too narrow for side-by-side racing _ on the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raised my stock a whole lot, to where a lot of people were
paying attention to see if we could do it again,'' said Earnhardt
Jr., whose father watched the closing laps from the top of a
transporter in the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty neat, him being there, because I wasn't sitting
there expecting a win at any time,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``It was
such a special day for me, and the rest of the team. For him to
have been there, and seeing how happy he was, it was kinda cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Reigning and three-time Cup champion Jeff Gordon, who will join
Earnhardt Jr. in the BGN lineup here, said Little E has shown
tremendous talent on the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed by that,'' said Gordon, 27. ``But he's got a lot
of pressure on him. I feel for him because I know as a rookie the
type of pressure I felt. You'd like to go out and just do it _ and
not have everybody talk about it. I was able to do that because I
didn't have a `name' and wasn't driving for Dale Earnhardt.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
