<HEADLINE>
NASH NOT SINGING BLUES ABOUT BOOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The thought jolted Steve Nash like the boos that
rattled his eardrums Wednesday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they just don't like me, for whatever reason, which is
fine,'' the Mavericks' starting point guard said. ``They pay their
money to come watch us play, and they have every right to voice or
express their feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``they'' Nash was referring to are Mavericks fans who booed
him every time he touched the ball in the second half of
Wednesday's 88-78 loss to Houston. Nash, who was 0-of-8 from the
field in the first half, was greeted with a shower of boos when he
entered the game with about five minutes left in the third period,
and every time he touched the ball thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The only time the fans let up was when Nash took and made his
only second-half shot, a 3-pointer midway through the final
quarter. Otherwise, they treated the 6-foot-3, third-year veteran
as if he were an opposing ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the ``attack,' Nash got up early and did a
15-minute radio interview. He later headed to practice and was the
last player to leave the Mavericks' afternoon session at the Tom
Landry Center.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the most embarrassing moment of his basketball
life, Nash couldn't pinpoint why the fans singled him out when
almost every Mavericks player this side of Shawn Bradley and A.C.
Green is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates pointed out to me that a lot of guys were missing
shots,'' Nash said. ``I don't know if that meant don't worry about
it, or if that meant I don't know why they're getting on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson talked with Nash
before practice yesterday to assure him that he's firmly in his
corner, regardless of some fans' apparent disdain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said I'm sticking with you, and we'll just go through
this together,'' Nash said. ``That was nice to hear, because I
didn't know if he felt the same way the fans did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks acquired Nash in a trade with Phoenix in June. The
Mavericks will part with their first-round draft pick this summer _
probably a lottery pick _ because of the Nash deal. The Mavericks
also gave Nash a six-year, $33 million contract extension before
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nash is making only 34.6 percent of his field-goal attempts,
second worst on the team behind Chris Anstey's 29.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it is the contract,'' Nash said of the fan's reaction.
``Maybe I should point out to them that I'm a $1 million point
guard this year. I haven't gotten those big checks yet. I'll do my
work over the summer and be a $5 million point guard next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Nash nor Nelson knows what kind of reception to expect
when the Mavericks play host to Denver tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll go out there and the fans will boo me again, and
I'll just play my game,'' Nash said. ``I just have confidence in
myself. I had confidence before last night's game that I was going
to have a great game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just month or two of a long career in Dallas. So
you've just got to wait and be patient.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
