<HEADLINE>
TWO BY TWO, TCU BREEZES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Horned Frogs did their damage in pairs
yesterday at the TCU Baseball Diamond. Two runs here, two runs
there.
</P>
<P>
   But it added up to an 8-2 victory against San Diego State,
boosting the Horned Frogs into sole possession of first place in
the Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I don't think much about first now,'' TCU coach
Lance Brown said. ``But it's victories like this that will make a
difference when first is on the line at the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   This victory was built in two-run increments.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest pair was provided by first baseman David Wallace. He
sent a ball screaming over the right-field fence in the third
inning to drive in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   TCU (16-13, 8-2 WAC) also had scored two runs in the first
inning, both coming on groundouts, and catcher Mark Silva singled
in two more in the seventh inning. Triples by Mike Hamilton and
Eric McLamore along with a single by Wallace accounted for TCU's
two eighth-inning runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out before I had a chance to go very far,'' said
Wallace, who finished 3-for-5 with three runs batted in and also
scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs right-hander Shawn Thompson (5-4) assured the numbers were
enough. He went seven innings, allowing two runs on five hits while
striking out eight. It was the third strong outing in conference
play for Thompson, who came in sporting back-to-back complete games
in the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego State (15-15, 5-5 WAC) threatened in the third, fifth,
sixth and seventh innings, but Thompson managed to get himself out
of trouble each time.
</P>
<P>
   The Aztecs' best chance came in the seventh. They had runners on
second and third with two outs, but Thompson got a fly ball to
right field to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs entered yesterday's game tied for first with Rice and
San Jose State. Rice begins a three-game series against Nevada-Las
Vegas today; San Jose State has a nonconference game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so we're in first by percentages,'' Wallace said. ``That's
all right. We'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs and Aztecs play the second in the three-game series at
2:35 today at the TCU Baseball Diamond.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
