</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLAYTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING A WHOLE LOT BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Royce Clayton remembers the day Dodgers
outfielder Ken Landreaux came to his school in Los Angeles for
Career Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Does anybody here want to be a major-league baseball
player?' '' Clayton said. ``The whole class laughed and pointed at
me. He said, `If that's what you want to do, good for you.' He was
very positive and made me feel good about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also gave me a bat. I kept it in my closet for a long time,
then used it until it cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory, and many others from his Los Angeles childhood, left
Clayton determined not only to become an All-Star shortstop, but an
athlete who emulates the many positive influences in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always positive influences there for me,'' Clayton
said. ``Every time I started doubting myself, there was always
someone there for me being positive and telling me things were
going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' thoughtful, soft-spoken shortstop has other
motivating forces. He remembers a darker time, the day Shannon
Coleman, his close friend going back to nursery school, committed
suicide while at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things that a lot of black men go
through,'' Clayton said. ``It affects every race. He was at a point
in life where he felt he had no alternatives. So he chose that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of my closest friends, always encouraging me. He
really believed in me ... almost to the point more than he believed
in himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, talking outside the Rangers' clubhouse one morning
earlier this week, paused to consider one of the worst moments of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people do you know from growing up who committed
suicide?'' he asked. ``Any? I know four or five from when I grew
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've dedicated my career to Shannon.''
</P>
<P>
   That dedication has taken many forms.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton is not the cliche rags-to-riches story, someone who
fought his way out of bleak poverty to become a major- league
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   He was brought up by loving, devoted parents who stressed
education over athletics. He lived in a safe neighborhood in the
North Inglewood section of Los Angeles, where he could ride his
bicycle to school and walk to the local Little League field.
</P>
<P>
   He is a person who appreciates the tremendous support he
received in his youth from his parents, teachers, coaches and role
models, and has devoted his off-field energies to see that others
receive the same advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God for what I had,'' Clayton said. ``It's what every
kid needs growing up. If the support system is there and he
receives positive encouragement, he'll respond in a positive way.
Tell a kid he's a loser and he'll always be a loser and that
society dictates he's going to go bad, all the negatives, then he's
going to go the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   In appreciation of what he has been given, he and his parents,
Royal and Antoinette Clayton, have become involved in a number of
charitable causes under the umbrella of the Royce Clayton Family
Foundation, from their work with the Sickle Cell Disease
Association of America to endowing a college scholarship through
the Jackie Robinson Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Royce and \Rhis brother\S Royal were always taught that your
abilities are a gift from God,'' Antoinette Clayton said. ``But you
always have people who are not as fortunate as you are. You get to
a point in your life where you say, `thank you for my blessings,
now let me help somebody else.' That's the way we raised our kids,
and I think Royce understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton was not always such a perfect child. One Sunday, Mrs.
Clayton noticed something strange about one of the acolytes at the
altar of the Christ Good Shepherd Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed he was wearing his baseball uniform under his
acolyte robes,'' Mrs. Clayton said. ``I noticed because he was
wearing his white baseball socks. He said he had a game after
church and didn't know if he'd have time to go home and put his
uniform on.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball was that important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports kept me off the streets and out of trouble,'' Clayton
said. ``Anything like that is worthwhile and positive. It's not so
much developing kids into major leaguers but just to give them
something to do where they can get positive encouragement and
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports were not stressed in the Clayton household. Education
was, and both parents worked hard to allow their children to attend
parochial schools. Royal Clayton Jr. _ five years older than Royce
_ wasn't even allowed to play sports until he was 13.
</P>
<P>
   But when Antoinette Clayton discovered Royce was in love with
baseball, she told him about Jackie Robinson and the battles he
went through to integrate the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't forget about your roots, so you teach about the
people in your history so you have an understanding of where you're
from,'' Mrs. Clayton said. ``A lot of minority children aren't
exposed to who their heroes are. Many of them don't even know it
was Charles R. Drew who discovered blood plasma. So we made Royce
aware of the difficult times Jackie Robinson had and a lot of the
difficult times players still have.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton has shown he hasn't forgotten his roots. He bought new
baseball uniforms last year for his old high school, St. Bernard's
in Playa del Rey, Calif., and helped re-build his old Little League
Field in La Dera Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Yarnell, longtime baseball coach at St. Bernard's, said
Clayton has always had a strong impact on the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a tremendous leader,'' Yarnell said. ``When he was on a
baseball field, it was like a little kid going to Disneyland. Now
kids say, `Coach it's sprinkling, are we going to practice?' He
couldn't get wait to get on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would make practices fun. For example, if he and another
player were taking 50 ground balls at shortstop, he'd make a game
of it. He'd make them field a certain number of them cleanly, or
else they'd have to get down and start doing pushups.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton was one of the last of a steady stream of talented
African-American baseball players who came out of the Los Angeles
area in the 1970s and '80s, including Darryl Strawberry, Eric
Davis, Ozzie Smith, Chili Davis and Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   But the stream has almost stopped as facilities have become
rundown, budgets have been cut and programs have been shut down.
That bothers Clayton, who has become involved in Major League
Baseball's Returning Baseball to the Inner Cities (RBI) program.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Little League was in real danger of shutting down,''
Clayton said. ``To have so many memories playing there and then to
see the program dying was painful. So we dumped a lot of money into
it and now it's a much better facility than what I played on.''
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The lack of inner-city prospects has forced major-league teams
to rely heavily on Latin American players not subject to the draft,
and money is poured into those countries to build academies and
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   They can't do that in American cities because those players are
subject to the draft. The Los Angeles Dodgers could pour millions
of dollars into that city's youth baseball programs, only to have
the best players drafted by other teams. Any work in that area is
considered part of a team's community service program rather than
true scouting and player development.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, we had the Major League Scouting
Bureau, and they were there just to produce the talent for
everybody,'' Clayton said. ``You don't have that anymore. But I
guarantee, you have the same type of kids with the same talent in
Los Angeles as you do in the Dominican Republic. Teams just don't
put the same kind of money into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a business. But it's just disappointing to know
the same opportunities I had aren't there anymore. That's why one
of my goals is to become active promoting the game of baseball in
the inner cities and promoting the RBI program.'' END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers gave Clayton $18 million over four years this
off-season because they felt he would be the front-line starting
shortstop the franchise has been sorely lacking for much of the
past 20 years. Club president Tom Schieffer said knowing the kind
of person they were getting made it easier to commit that kind of
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Royce is going be a tremendous addition to this
franchise,'' Schieffer said. ``He's a great athlete and it's a
pleasure to watch him on the field. Off the field, people are going
to understand this is a substantive person who is going to make a
real contribution to our community.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
