<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING PLAYERS WOULD BE CAPITALIST IDEA FOR CASTRO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Much has been made of the international
intrigue and political implications that will swirl around Sunday's
baseball game in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   But in analyzing the whys and whats of the Baltimore Orioles'
visit to Cuba, all Americans should first consider the one major
humanitarian concern.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark is making the trip. Haven't the Cuban people already
suffered enough?
</P>
<P>
   On these pages several weeks ago, Brother LeBreton made many
pertinent points about the political fallacy of the Orioles falling
into Castro's trap. It's obviously true about this being more than
a simple pitching-batting-and-catching competition, at least for
Fidel and his powerful Cuban National Team.
</P>
<P>
   Castro was not exactly blowing cigar smoke in approving the
Orioles' visit for Sunday's game against Cuba's best. Fidel is up
to something.
</P>
<P>
   But why does it have to be a political foothold he's hoping to
gain across Latin America? That won't feed the hungry mouths on an
island starved for all the basic necessities of life, starting with
three square ones a day.
</P>
<P>
   What makes more sense is the economic impact that Castro can
achieve from suddenly being pals with Major League Baseball. What
if capitalist gears are now swirling in the head of Comrade Fidel?
Don't forget, the ol' Commie was once known as a pretty decent
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, you see, can be Castro's new sugar.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. won't buy his cane, or even his cigars, what about
his ballplayers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Open up Cuba to us, and put those players on the market, and
the stampede of major-league scouts into that place might sink the
entire island,'' said Sandy Johnson, the assistant general manager
and director of baseball operations for the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson added, ``That's why Castro, I don't think, would
ever open it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, why should he?
</P>
<P>
   If Castro simply served as an ``agent,'' and placed an
individual value on Cuban players, then sold their contracts direct
to major-league teams ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you're talking,'' said Johnson. ``I've got no way of
knowing what he's up to with Baltimore going in there, but Castro
being ready to talk business with baseball makes a lot of sense to
me. The way it appears, the most valuable commodity in Cuba is
ballplayers.''
</P>
<P>
   As was learned when Johnson spent more than a decade in the
Rangers' front office, no one in baseball knows or appreciates the
Latin market or Latin players more than he.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers once had the strongest presence in Puerto Rico and
were one of the first organizations to cultivate and farm the
hot-hot-hot market in the Dominican Republic. Sammy Sosa came out
of that first Dominican wave in the mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba always has been Johnson's dream conquest. ``It's the
mother lode _ the sleeping giant,'' he said. ``For 40 years under
Castro, that island has gone untapped, other than a handful who
floated their way out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   There has long been a school of thought that the Cubans are
better players overall than the Puerto Ricans or the Dominicans,
and if Castro ever lifted his curtain the majors would be swamped
with Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go that far,'' said Johnson, ``because we aren't on
that island to see the kids at 12, 13, 14 years old. But without
question, it would be big, real big.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 600 players from the Dominican Republic
were signed by major-league teams. That is more than from
California, the state that annually has the most signees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see Cuba being any less than the Dominican,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question there are players on Cuba's national team
who, if rafted off the island, would command a signing bonus of $5
million plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we aren't even talking about those of high school age who
play baseball 12 months a year,'' said Johnson. ``The best young
ones will go for a couple of million.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also not far-fetched to think Castro could produce 500
players a year signing major-league contracts for a total profit to
Cuba of some $200 million. And then if Castro also arranged to
receive a cut of their contracts after the players made the majors,
well ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What else does Cuba have to sell that would bring more?''
Johnson said. ``The few who have gotten out have received huge
dollars, and their success in the majors is certainly well-known in
Cuba. Every kid who is playing catch in that country is also
building a raft. He wants out.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fidel becomes directly involved in the baseball business,
then the profit is his. Could that be why the Orioles are in Cuba
on Sunday?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
