<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-PEOPLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR HANDYMAN POINTED SERIES IN RIGHT DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY D. BOGGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Bob Latford has been around NASCAR for as
long as there has been a NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1948 he has worked in concession stands, sold programs,
help score, spotted for radio and public-address announcers,
written books, published newsletters and compiled statistics for TV
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps most importantly, he developed the points system
used in NASCAR today.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you scoring at home, the system works like this:
175 points are given to the winner of a Winston Cup points event,
170 points to the runner-up and on down to 34 points for the
last-place finisher. Oh, even the drivers who fail to qualify for a
race earn points. Plus, there are five bonus points for leading a
lap (meaning the race winner automatically earns 180 points) and
five bonus points for leading the most laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I hated math in high school,'' the 63-year-old Concord,
N.C., resident says.
</P>
<P>
   At least the points system is fairly easy to figure out. In
1974, NASCAR was using its third system in four years. Among the
variables involved were the size of a track, the number of laps ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so complicated the competitors couldn't figure it
out,'' Latford said. ``And I said at the time if the competitors
don't know what they have to do, then the fans sure don't
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Latford met with NASCAR officials at a ``watering hole'' and
began diddling on the back of a napkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rationale at the time was that every race counts the
same,'' Latford said. ``Because the championship should be based on
not the races you won but what you did in the races you didn't
win.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR success is told in top 5s and top 10s. So the first
through six spots are separated by five points per position (175
for No. 1 to 150 for No. 6), and Nos. 7 (146 points) through 11
(130) are separated by four points per position. After No. 11, the
difference becomes three points (127 for No. 12, 124 for No. 13 and
so on).
</P>
<P>
   Latford compares it to golf. ``If I go out and get a hole-in-one
on all of the par-3s but triple-bogey all the others, and you par
every hole, you'll win the round.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Latford wanted to reward the Curtis Turners,
Fireball Roberts and Junior Johnsons _ drivers who never won a
championship but drove hard and put on a show but might not finish
a race because of how they raced.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he added the bonus points.
</P>
<P>
   Latford isn't opposed to change. He'd like to see bonus points
added for a pole. But he points out that ``the system works.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty won the last championship under the old rules in
1974. He also won the 1975 championship under the current system.
</P>
<P>
   And Latford does some other math thinking about the points
system, ``his'' points system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got paid for it,'' he said with a laugh. ``If I had a
tenth of 1 percent of the prize money distributed under the points
system, I wouldn't be here working.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
