<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURBY-McDONALDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO 
</HEADLINE>
 
McDONALD'S OFFERS MINI-FURBY FIGURES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Keith Lopaty saw business increase 50 percent at
the five San Fernando Valley McDonald's restaurants he owns when
the fast-food chain offered Teeny Beanie Babies toys with its Happy
Meal combos each of the last two springs.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to see something close to the same when 3-inch
Furbies -- that electronic interactive toy that was all the rage
this past holiday season -- start popping up with the ever-popular
Happy Meal beginning today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be popular. I'm optimistic,'' he said. ``I don't
think it'll be Beanie Babies -- Beanie Babies was our best ever.
This will probably be the second-best ever, would be my guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures attract youngsters who drag their parents into
McDonald's to buy them. And their parents, in turn, buy meals for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sell a lot of Happy Meals, it helps our business,''
Lopaty said. ``It helps pretty dramatically in certain instances.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Murray, a spokeswoman for Oak Brook, Ill.-based McDonald's
Corp., said the company had been working on turning the Furby into
a Happy Meals figurine since spotting the toy last year at the
International Toy Fair in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking for hot properties,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 80 variants of the little critters, all miniature
sculpted figurines resembling the furry mechanical toys that media
hype turned into the most coveted toy of December '98.
</P>
<P>
   Like the big Furby, the McDonald's figures can do things like
move their feet or wiggle their ears or let loose with a little
growl. Unlike it's big cousin, however, these little ones are not
electronic and don't need batteries to perform their feats.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the new figures so far has been positive, Murray
said. ``They capture the essence of the real retail Furby,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be available through April 22 or while supplies last.
They come in eight toy types and in 10 body and color combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Lopaty thinks the mini-Furby toys stand a good chance of
becoming collectors' items, in part because there are so many
varieties that some customers may make it a mission to capture them
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people will be driving around trying to collect them
all,'' he said. ``Who knows, maybe 20 years from now, they'll be
sitting back thinking, Wasn't I smart?''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
