   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ NATO launched an aerial bombardment on
Yugoslavia for a second night, firing on Serb targets from ships in
the Adriatic. Western leaders had promised a second night of
attacks by bombers and cruise missiles after a devastating first
round that reportedly killed at least 11 people and delivered a
serious blow to the Yugoslav military. By Francis X. Clines. WITH
PHOTOS and GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Washington) _ NATO's air campaign
intends to bomb Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic into
submission or pound his military to the point where it can no
longer be an effective killing machine. Thursday, though, the
Yugoslav offensive intensified in Kosovo, dimming hopes for a quick
end to the crisis. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Giving vent to their rage
over NATO bombings of their neighboring country, thousands of Serb
sympathizers marched on the U.S. Embassy here, throwing rocks,
setting embassy cars on fire and seeking to burn down the compound
with molotov cocktails. By Alessandra Stanley. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ For the first time since World War II,
German fighter jets have gone to war, participating in the attack
on Yugoslavia as part of a NATO force and marking Germany's
definitive emancipation from post-war pacifism. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REPORTERS (Undated) _ Foreign journalists from NATO
countries were ordered out of Yugoslavia by the Serbian government
Thursday at nearly the exact hour that they were assured by the
Yugoslav government that they could stay, travel freely and do
their job. Byline to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ China pressed an all-out verbal assault
on the NATO air strikes against Serbian forces, issuing multiple
demands that the attack be halted, while the flagship state
newspaper called the operation a ``dangerous precedent of naked
aggression.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ Russia has railed against the
Western alliance in terms that recall the tensest days of the Cold
War, but has been careful not to match its angry rhetoric with
deeds. With talks on IMF aid near, the Kremlin seems to have
calculated that this is no time to escalate its quarrel with the
West. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX (London) _ Europeans reacted with a mix of
dread at the return of large-scale combat to the continent where
two world wars were fought, apprehension that the conflict could
spread, and widespread if sometimes grudging support for the allied
action. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ITALY (Aviano) _ In Italy, the curious gather to watch
the warplanes take off. Security was high and the bars and
restaurants normally frequented by NATO troops were swept clean
Thursday night around this northern Italian air base that is the
launching pad for many of the NATO aircraft striking Yugoslavia. By
John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ A look at the behind-the-scenes
struggle in the Clinton administration leading up to the decision
to join the NATO attack on Yugoslavia. The impending visit of
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov became a focal point that
helped push the administration to act sooner than it had planned.
It was decided that the credibility of NATO was more important than
the sensitivities of the Russians. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE (Brussels) _ Wesley Clark, the four-star
U.S. general who as Supreme Allied Commander Europe is in charge of
the NATO air offensive against Serbia, knows his adversary well. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ After a night of heavy
explosions and fires, this city was strangely calm early Thursday.
Serbs seemed at ease, if angry at the NATO bombing; Albanians were
anxious, even terrified of what was to come. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Kievo, Yugoslavia) _ Serbian anger at the West,
and especially the U.S., is both media-fed and genuine in this
suburb of the capital. Ordinary Serbs are both stupefied that the
bombs are falling and outraged that the world is treating them
``like savages,'' he said, ``just because we want to keep our
country.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ Denouncing NATO's military
strikes against Yugoslavia as a ``threat to international peace''
and a ``flagrant violation'' of both the U.N. charter and
Yugoslavian sovereignty, Russia introduced a Security Council
resolution demanding an immediate end to the military action.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON-HISTORY (Undated) _ About a dozen historians and
Balkan specialists said President Clinton's use of history in
justifying the decision to bomb Serbia to the American people was
imprecise and misleading. Most said they approved of the decision
itself, but were troubled by the speech's allusions to World Wars I
and II. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from around the U.S. is examined in:
</P>
<P>
