<P>
   EUROPEAN-UNION (Berlin) _ Leaders of the European Union
struggled early Friday to reach an agreement on a reform of the
15-nation bloc's $92 billion annual budget that would eventually
make it possible for Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary to
join. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-BASE-TOKYO (Tokyo) _ Until now, the calls for Yankees to go
home have usually focused on the U.S. military bases in Okinawa.
But now the leading candidate for governor of Tokyo is chiming in
as well. Shintaro Ishihara, who has made a career in recent years
of urging Japan to stand up to the U.S., is demanding that the U.S.
military forces give up Yokota Air Base in Tokyo or at least share
it with civilians. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-VIOLENCE (Quito, Ecuador) _ For more than three
decades, Colombia has endured a conflict in which both left- and
right-wing guerrillas have regarded civilians as targets. But now,
as a result of recent developments in Colombia and in neighboring
countries, there are signs that the scope of the strife is
widening. By Larry Rohter. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-CAR-BLESSINGS (Copacabana, Bolivia) _ They drive from
all over Bolivia, Peru and even northern Argentina to this remote
town on the shore of Lake Titicaca _ taxi drivers, truck drivers
and other motorists seeking a Franciscan priest's blessings for
protection against drunken drivers, landslides, bad brakes and
broken axles. By Clifford Krauss. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BASEBALL (Havana) _ A look at Cuba and baseball, from
inside the country, setting up Sunday's widely anticipated
exhibition game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban
national team. By James McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GENERAL (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli Supreme Court ruled
that an army general disciplined for having sex with a female
subordinate three years ago could not be promoted. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
