<P>
   NATIONAL - GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-WASTE (Sante Fe, N.M.) _ After 25 years, hundreds of
studies, countless hearings and innumerable protests, the U.S.
Department of Energy loaded a truck with radioactive waste
Wednesday and prepared to send it to an underground dump in
southern New Mexico's salt beds. The rig will travel from Los
Alamos National Laboratory, birthplace of the atomic bomb, to the
$1.8 billion Waste Isolation Pilot Plant near Carlsbad. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-TRIAL (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Jurors began deliberating a
murder charge against Dr. Jack Kevorkian after a prosecutor told
them the euthanasia crusader killed Thomas Youk ``like a medical
hitman in the night with a bag of poison.'' Kevorkian, acting as
his own attorney, likened himself to civil rights heroes and
insisted that his helping to kill the victim of Lou Gehrig's
disease was not a crime. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   GAMMA-BURST (Undated) _ In January an explosion rated as the
largest since the big bang ripped across the universe, tripping
detectors on satellites and triggering telescopic observations from
earth. Now a series of papers being published in Science and Nature
are shedding light on some characteristics of this violent event
and what it might or might not have been. Among other things, it
appears now that the explosion was not a fireball but some kind of
directed beam, which means it was only about a hundredth as
powerful as originally estimated. Even then, however, it still
ranks as the most violent event in nature, more powerful than a
supernova. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-SCHOOLS (Detroit) _ Michigan's Legislature voted to
transfer control of Detroit's schools from the city's elected
school board to the city's mayor and the state's governor, the
latest in a series of efforts by state legislatures to improve test
scores by taking authority away from school boards. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION-KIDS (Undated) _ The Agriculture Dept. issued its
first guidelines on how to feed young children a nutritious diet,
emphasizing the value of grains, fruits and vegetables. A soft
drink can that illustrates the recommendation that children should
``eat less'' sugar in their diets has outraged the soda companies.
By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   YELLOWSTONE-MICROBES (Undated) _ A federal judge has ordered a
temporary halt to a precedent-setting arrangement under which a
biotechnology company is paying Yellowstone National Park for the
rights to search its geysers and hot springs for commercially
valuable microbes. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   PARADE-CATHOLICS (San Francisco) _ The Sisters of Perpetual
Indulgence, an irreverent and largely gay street theater group
whose members dress like nuns and use elements of Catholic ritual
in their performances, have angered Catholics here with plans for
an Easter street party to celebrate the troupe's 20th anniversary.
By Bill Staggs.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-INDICT (New York) _ As the Bronx grand jury
considering last month's police shooting of Amadou Diallo finished
its work Thursday, 219 people calling for justice in the case were
arrested for disorderly conduct in front of police headquarters,
and a high-profile group of black and Hispanic leaders scheduled a
conference to plot strategy for upcoming meetings with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   OHAIR-SUSPECT (Houston) _ In what may be a breakthrough in the
disappearance of atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair, an Austin
lawyer representing a former office manager for the missing woman
said federal officials told him that his client is suspected of
being part of a plot to rob and murder Ms. O'Hair. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ In a series of closed-door
negotiations and back-channel messages, the U.S. and China are
racing to reach a broad accord in the next two weeks that could
pave the way for Beijing to enter the World Trade Organization,
even as the White House fears the effort could be torpedoed by
Congress. By David Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   POOR-BANKS (Undated) _ Many people do not use banks, especially
in low-income neighborhoods, citing inconvenience, high fees or a
lack of branches nearby. But there is another reason: Banks often
do not tell people that anyone can open a basic low-fee checking
account. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ State and federal officials
were dismissive Thursday of Microsoft's proposal to settle its
antitrust suit, but they added that the two sides would meet for
settlement talks, probably beginning Tuesday. By Joel Brinkley.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES-DRUG (Undated) _ The market for oral diabetes drugs
will soon become more competitive _ but just how competitive may
depend on what action regulators take on a popular diabetes pill
that has been linked to 28 deaths and seven liver transplants.
Warner-Lambert Co., the maker of the pill, Rezulin, will defend the
drug before the FDA. By David J. Borrow. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   LYCOS-USA-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Not every dealmaker could
finagle a merger agreement that forbids his proposed partner from
negotiating with other interested parties. But that's what USA
Networks CEO Barry Diller has done in his deal with internet portal
Lycos Inc. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-STANLEY (New York) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter reported
its operating earnings soared 50 percent in the first quarter to a
record $1.037 billion, as global markets improved and its
securities businesses surged. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-HEARING (Undated) _ As the ``anything.com'' stocks
continue to gyrate on the NASDAQ stock market, the market's
governing board in Washington approved a rule Thursday that would
allow officials to halt trading in a company's stock in response to
market news or rumors, even if they cannot immediately reach the
company's executives. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BRADESCO (Sao Paulo) _ Testing an international aversion
to Brazilian debtors after the mid-January devaluation of the
nation's currency, a handful of Brazilian companies have resumed
borrowing in dollars on global debt markets. The trickle of new
debt issues is being led by financial institutions like Banco
Bradesco SA. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   PROCTER-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ One of the hoariest of advertising
devices, the man-on-the-street interview, is being overhauled for a
new generation of consumers by one of the most traditional of
advertisers, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ACCOUNTANTS (Undated) _ Concerned that their giant
accounting firm is not staying competitive at a time many companies
have global operations, the 5,000 accountants and consultants
working at KPMG in Canada are planning to move to the firm of
Arthur Andersen, top partners at both firms in Canada said. By
Melody Petersen.
