<SLUG> BC-SELLING-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. PROMOTERS LAUNCH FAREWELL BOOSTER CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After five years and an $18 million budget, the
group that brought you the slogan ``Together, we're the best. Los
Angeles'' goes out of business this month with a final advertising
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The New Los Angeles Marketing Partnership is saying goodbye in
advertisements that began Wednesday in which it brags about the
region and the role it played in boosting the city's image.
</P>
<P>
   A second advertisement boasts of the city's selection as host
city to the 2000 Democratic National Convention, by saying, ``The
donkey has landed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We promised that we would be in business only five years, and
this is it,'' said Tracy Olmstead Williams of Casey Sayre &AMP;
Williams Inc., the firm that provided public relations for NewLAMP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started when the mayor came and said we need to do
something to restore faith in the business community but didn't
want a quasi-governmental agency that would stay in business
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said NewLAMP has helped turn around the city's image
and worked to keep some 125 firms from leaving and saving 25,000
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this was started, the line going around was, the last
person leaving Los Angeles, please turn off the lights,'' Williams
said. ``That was when Los Angeles was noted for fire, floods,
earthquakes, the Rodney King beating and the O.J. (Simpson) trial.
We've turned that around.''
</P>
<P>
   NewLAMP Executive Director Regina Birdsell said she is most
proud that the organization was able to fulfill its promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``When NewLAMP started, there was a poll showing four of five
people wanted to leave Los Angeles,'' Birdsell said. ``We took
another poll recently and better than 70 percent said they were
optimistic about the city and its future.''
</P>
<P>
   NewLAMP was the brainchild of Mayor Richard Riordan, and he is
pleased with the group's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel more confident today than they did five years
ago,'' Deputy Mayor Noelia Rodriguez said. ``While the mayor is
never satisfied, he thinks they did accomplish getting the word out
to the people who live here, in the region and the rest of the
country, that Los Angeles is the greatest city.''
</P>
<P>
   With an initial contribution from the city and county, Riordan
turned to the business community for funds.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also grew to include a number of other cities, most
notably Long Beach, and groups as diverse as the Los Angeles
Chamber of Commerce and the Los Angeles County Federation of Labor,
AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of its work, the group has come up with other
themes, such as ``It's amazing what grows in L.A.,'' touting
different businesses and ``L.A.'s Amazing People.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take credit for the turnaround in the economy,''
Birdsell said. ``We were just there at the time. But we have been
able to educate people about the different businesses we have in
this city. Five years ago, people would have said the two main
industries here are defense and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, they know Los Angeles is first in fashion and
manufacturing, that the economy is so spread out we can afford a
hit in one.''
</P>
<P>
   NewLAMP's work will continue in the form of an organization
being called the New Alliance that will work through the Los
Angeles Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Birdsell said it will continue the advertising campaign and also
go into new areas of dealing with government at the state and local
level to work on behalf of entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
