<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLISLE'S HEROICS GIVE CAL THE TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geno Carlisle did not know whether it was the rigors
of the extended run into the post-season or simply the struggles of
an untimely slump, but throughout Thursday night's game here at
Madison Square Garden, he seemed a step slow, a bit sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he know why in the final seconds of the National
Invitation Tournament's championship game everything around him
suddenly seemed in slow motion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos, Carlisle, a senior at the University of
California, calmly moved through the crowd of players, ignoring the
pressure of the moment. He attempted a game-tying jump shot, which
was blocked, but somehow, between three Clemson defenders, Carlisle
knocked the loose ball back to himself, picked it up and elevated
into the lane. He hanged in the air, drawing a foul while calmly
dropping in an eight-foot jumper with 4.7 seconds to play to tie
the score, then converted the free throw that beat Clemson, 61-60.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Golden Bears' first post-season title since winning
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament 40 years
ago, also by a point, against West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny, the last two games were two of my worst
games of the season, offensively,'' said Carlisle, who was just 4
of 18 from the floor Thursday night. ``I got that shot blocked and
then everything went in slow motion. I knew I had to at least tie
it up. Everything was slow and on that play a rush just went
through me.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it was the NIT, a tournament in which bragging
rights consist of, ``We're number 65,'' rather than the NCAA
tournament, did not diminish the moment as Carlisle embraced his
father, Clarence, on the court, while teammates danced with the
California flag.
</P>
<P>
   In making its run to the title, California benefited from a
group of four seniors, each of whom transferred to the school two
years year ago and endured an NCAA-imposed ban from post-season
play last year. Sean Lampley, the lone starter this season not
among the seniors, was named the tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, it was Carlisle, who began his career at
Northwestern, stepping into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling for the coaches and players,'' coach Ben
Braun said. ``Those are the only ones who were there making the
sacrifice. This started last year with no prize on the horizon.
With Geno, he's as great a reflection of our team as anyone. When
it's the last shot, there was no question that we wanted the ball
in his hands. He deserved a chance to win the game, and he found a
way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California was forced to play without its second-leading scorer,
the senior Thomas Kilgore, whose bruised left thigh muscle
tightened Thursday night.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the consolation game, Xavier beat Oregon by 106-75 behind 34
points by Lenny Brown, who made 10 of 15 shots from the floor,
including six 3-point field goals. James Posey and Maurice McAfee
added 17 points each for the Musketeers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
