<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RAPTORS-ROCKETS-H     03-26 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RAPTORS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The NBA's Rookie All-Star Game was not canceled because of the
lockout after all. The prodigies of the Rockets and Raptors held
the game Thursday night at Compaq Center.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toronto's Vince Carter won the dunk contest and likely all sorts
of praise and endorsement deals. The Rockets won the game, with
Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley outgunning the spectacular
Raptors rookie to lift the Rockets to a 113-104 win, extending
their winning streak to six as they head to a five-game, nine-day
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dickerson and Mobley were hitting unconsciously, and it was
just impossible for us to win,'' Raptors guard Doug Christie said.
``I've never seen anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson and Mobley had their season highs by the first minutes
of the fourth quarter, so it hardly mattered that Rockets center
Hakeem Olajuwon, who had been enjoying another in a recent run of
sharp-shooting nights, was tossed out of the game with 2:55 left in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon was ejected for retaliating after taking a pair of
elbows to the chest from Toronto strongman Charles Oakley. Olajuwon
said Oakley was ``evil'' and had intentionally tried to injure him.
Olajuwon was cited for a Level 2 flagrant foul, which makes him
eligible for a suspension, although that would remain up to the
discretion of the NBA office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for a player like that,'' Olajuwon said. ``To see
someone who has that kind of mind, to injure somebody in the flow
of the game, I tried to think of some excuse for him, to see what
he's thinking, but there was no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Olajuwon was lost Thursday, Dickerson had taken
over the game and Mobley was about to.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carter) is being called Rookie of the Year, which he's
deserving of,'' Dickerson said. ``He's a great player; he's a tough
matchup for anybody. But Cuttino is such a competitor, Vince being
`Rookie of the Year,' I think Cuttino was competing with Vince. And
I saw Cuttino competing with him, and I just wanted to compete with
him. Cuttino and I just played off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley and Dickerson each made seven of nine 3-pointers to set
Rockets rookie records for 3s in a game and send the Rockets to a
team record of 17 treys. Dickerson finished with 28 points, making
10 of 15 shots and adding five assists and three steals, matching
season bests. Mobley added 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   Carter led all scorers with his season-high 32, including a
dunk-contest 360-degree slam, a high-flying finger roll and several
fadeaways that could be fairly described as Jordanesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of did feel it,'' Dickerson said. ``Every time I shot
the ball, I felt like it was going in. I knew Cuttino was feeling
it. I could see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, two games removed from an 0-for-5 while concentrating on
defending Sacramento rookie Jason Williams, followed his 7-of-11
shooting night at Dallas on Wednesday by making eight of 12 on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I hit that many 3s,'' Mobley said. ``I kept
shooting. I was in a slump awhile ago. I heard some commentators on
TV say some bad things about me. But I've got to roll with those
punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really feeling it out there. The slump hurt me because I
am a better shooter than that. The shots went in for me against
Dallas and again tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing was ideal. Besides losing Olajuwon in the third
quarter, the Rockets played the second of back-to-back games
weakened and short-handed. Sam Mack was out with a sprained right
thumb. Matt Bullard did not play while battling the flu. Scottie
Pippen played 42 minutes but was clearly feeling the effects of the
flu, doubling over several times early in the fourth quarter but
finishing with 16 points and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley spent much of the game battling pain in his back
and his left knee but came within one assist of a triple double,
with 16 points, 14 rebounds and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets took control of the game on the strength of
their rookies, and particularly Dickerson's third quarter and
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael played 48 minutes,'' Tomjanovich said, ``and I think
he broke a sweat. I don't know. That guy is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams were tied or traded the lead 15 times when the Rockets
suddenly took off from a tie at 63. Mobley hit a pair of 3s around
an Olajuwon jumper and a Dickerson free throw, before Dickerson
swished consecutive treys on three trips down the court.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets made all eight attempts from beyond the 3-point arc
in the third quarter, and the 18-2 run from the last tie pushed
them to an 81-65 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets held on to their 16-point lead through the quarter.
And when Mobley hit two more 3s, they led by 16 again, 103-87, with
7:45 left.
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers _ the Rockets had eight in the last eight minutes _
and the relentless Raptors offense kept the Rockets from putting
away the win more neatly. But a pair of rookies had outshot the
Raptors in a shootout to head to the road on a roll, leaving behind
an eight-game home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unbelievable,'' Carter said. ``I told them they had
to stop doing that. `You guys can miss one.' That was just sick.
They couldn't miss. I'm proud of them because they are part of the
rookie class.''
</P>
<P>
   At least for Thursday, even with Carter at his best, Dickerson
and Mobley jumped to the head of the class.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 0125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
