<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4776 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAKEEM-EJECTION-H     03-26 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAKEEM-EJECTION-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Hakeem Olajuwon is certain he will be vindicated when the NBA
reviews the tape of the incident that led to his ejection from
Thursday's 113-104 victory over the Toronto Raptors at Compaq
Center.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olajuwon was tossed by referee Joey Crawford with 2:55 remaining
in the third period for throwing an elbow toward the Raptors'
Charles Oakley. Olajuwon was given a level 2 flagrant foul, which
means he could be suspended for Saturday's game at Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets do not expect Olajuwon to be suspended, though,
since such a penalty is up to the league's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   And since videotape replays seemed to validate Olajuwon's claim
that he was retaliating for flagrant elbows thrown by Oakley just
seconds before, it is expected that the league will permit Olajuwon
to play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see on the film what he did,'' Olajuwon said. ``It was
totally unexpected. I was going for a rebound, and he wasn't even
trying to go for a rebound. He was trying to knock me out. That was
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, that play was terrible. That was totally unncessary. I
can understand if he was trying to make a play, but he wasn't. When
you have a player trying to hurt another in the flow of the game,
well, that's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley begged to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch the replay,'' Oakley said. ``He (Olajuwon) was running
in there. I was just trying to block him out and follow the
basketball. Things happen on the court every night. I wasn't trying
to take him out of the air or anything. Look, I'm not going to back
down just because he wants to complain.''
</P>
<P>
   The play began when Othella Harrington missed a baseline hook.
Olajuwon went up for the rebound, but Oakley turned and threw a
pair of elbows to Olajuwon's chest, as if he were doing a bit of
downfield blocking.
</P>
<P>
   As Olajuwon fell to the floor, Oakley threw another elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon staggered to his feet, caught up with Oakley and threw
an elbow of his own, which Crawford saw.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon called Oakley's play ``evil,'' saying the league should
do something to curtail his wild elbows and dirty play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand when you see somebody who is dirty,''
Olajuwon said. ``The intention, that was evil. He was trying to
hurt another player. That is totally unnecessary. I was trying to
find an excuse for why he did that. You can play physical, but to
try and injure somebody was totally beneath the professional level.
The NBA should definitely do something about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that he's dirty. His heart is dirty. He is not
clean from the inside. To look at another man and try to injure
him, that is totally unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon did not apologize for attempting to get back at Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was retaliation,'' Olajuwon said. ``But what he did was
unnecessary. I was surprised at the intent of what he was trying to
do. There's a difference between somebody playing physical and
somebody trying to hurt somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that he hit me; it's that he put the elbow right in
my chest. That is a big difference _ that's not somebody trying to
just hit somebody; he was trying to hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he surprised that the officials missed Oakley's
incident-sparking play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the nature of the game,'' Olajuwon said. ``When you
react, you see the second one. They never see the first one. I'm
very happy that they were able to catch it on the film. So it is
very clear what he did, and the NBA will see. It will speak for
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
