<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-26 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ If this were a meal served on expensive
china at a fine restaurant instead of a basketball feast inside a
dome, they would be three sprigs of parsley used as garnish.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a convention of Three Stooges impersonators rather
than crazed hoopaholics, they would be a trio of guys named Shemp.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State. Connecticut. Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and can we see your tickets, please?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the last stop in the Duke Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the Final Four the way we have come to know it in
recent years, with one favorite and three close contenders.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Final One, with the engraver already putting Duke's
name on the championship trophy and everybody else just in town to
hit the beach for spring break.
</P>
<P>
   Who's gonna win this thing? I ask the skycap at Tampa
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feeling all right?'' he asks, condescendingly. ``Duke, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Taxi driver: ``Duke, my man. Where you been all season?''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel bellman: ``I'll give you 2-1 odds and the other three
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   So, why wait for the games? Can we all go home now?
</P>
<P>
   This looks more and more like one of those old Columbo episodes,
where we saw who did it and how they did it before the first
commercial, then spent the rest of the show watching Peter Falk
work the story backward.
</P>
<P>
   But as Columbo would say, just one more thing.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, Connecticut and Ohio State are more than just
long, long shots. They are three pretty good stories, and there are
reasons to root for each.
</P>
<P>
   How can you not pull for the Buckeyes, 8-22 and last in the Big
Ten just a year ago and now flying in as the most improbable Final
Four guest in years? Did they even bother to use a plane?
</P>
<P>
   How can you not pull for the Huskies, who have been one of the
top teams in college basketball for the past decade and yet been
derided by some for never taking the last giant step in the Big
Dance?
</P>
<P>
   How can you not pull for the Spartans, who in the 20th
anniversary season of Magic Johnson leading Michigan State to its
only NCAA title are riding on the shoulders of four tough kids from
the tough streets of Flint, Mich.?
</P>
<P>
   If patience is indeed a virtue, then all three of these teams
are practically saints. It has been 31 years since Ohio State last
made it to the Final Four. Two decades have passed since the kid
with the Magic smile led the Spartans past Larry Bird and Indiana
State in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   And for Connecticut, this has been the most grueling trip by a
team of Huskies this side of the Iditarod to finally make the
school's first appearance in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And the reward for all three? Duke.
</P>
<P>
   It is the tale of three coaches who have overcome tragedy and
persevered and taken the long climb up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   What a priceless image Saturday when Ohio State completed its
wild ride to the Final Four and coach Jim O'Brien stood at midcourt
hugging his two daughters. O'Brien was married to his college
sweetheart but lost her to a heart attack in 1991, and here was a
portrait of two girls who had such pride in their father for
keeping their lives on track.
</P>
<P>
   What a hoot to see UConn's Jim Calhoun cut loose and dance a jig
on the sidelines as his team wrapped up its Final Four berth. Tiny
Gonzaga wore the label as the Cinderella team, but Calhoun and his
Huskies always have been outside with their noses pressed against
the glass during the ball.
</P>
<P>
   What an unusual team coach Tom Izzo put together at Michigan
State, mining the talent in the blue-collar city of Flint and
getting a group of former high school rivals to bond.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo, the son of a shoe repairman, began working in the same
business when he was 12 years old and knows all about labor and
family. That's why he had his first recruit, Antonio Smith, climb
the ladder with him to cut down his piece of the net when the
Spartans won the Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   In any other season, the spotlight would shine brightly on the
magical run of one of these teams to the championship, which is a
story line the NCAA Tournament, more than any of our other major
sports events, seems to serve up so consistently.
</P>
<P>
   The man selling souvenir T-shirts on the corner says it's a
lopsided market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the first time we have to discount the ones from
the other schools before they play the game,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The waitress sets the plate of buffalo wings on the table and
says: ``They're tasty, they're hot. Like Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else is bleu cheese dressing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
