<HEADER>
A4779 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     03-26 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' PLAYOFF HOPES GROW DIMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It was a night when the Kings desperately needed to
alter history and desperately needed to upend a nemesis that
quietly, calmly goes about its business.
</P>
<P>
   But some things obviously aren't meant to be for this team this
season. And some things don't seem meant to be for this team in any
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (27-39-5) took another big step away from this
season's playoffs with a 2-1 loss Thursday night to the Dallas
Stars before a crowd of 14,888 at the Forum. Third-period shots by
Rob Blake and Sandy Moger hit the crossbar and the right goal post,
respectively, seeming to symbolize the frustration and futility of
the Kings' efforts this season.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows when the Kings ever again will manage to defeat
the Stars? The streak now stands at an astonishing 17 games without
a victory against Dallas, an 0-11-6 litany of winlessness that
dates to the coaching reign of Barry Melrose.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are 0-5 against Dallas this season, all one-goal
losses, with one meeting remaining. The Stars (45-14-12) didn't
dominate and didn't outplay the Kings, but displayed a composure
that explained as well as anything else why they will finish the
regular season with the best record in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   It was another game where the Kings could justly feel they
deserved better than the outcome they got, a fact that provides
little solace at this point in their faltering bid for a playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the numbers: The Kings trail Calgary, which holds the
eighth and final Western Conference playoff berth, by eight points.
They trail ninth-place Edmonton by four points. They have 11 games
remaining, eight of those on the road. In other words, any playoff
hopes the Kings still have are purely mathematical.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings opened the game with a strong shift by the line of
Olli Jokinen, Craig Johnson and Donald Audette, a shift that set
the tone for how the Kings would play, but also for the strong
effort by Dallas goalie Roman Turek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we came out and did exactly what we wanted to do,''
defenseman Garry Galley said. ``We wanted to play in their end and
get the puck deep in their end and get our forecheck going and get
some chances at the net, which we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Turek at the other end, Stephane Fiset was sharp in the
Kings' goal, especially when he had to stop successive point-blank
shots by Derian Hatcher during a frenetic shift by Dallas midway
through the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was the Stars who scored the only goal of the opening
period, Benoit Hogue beating Fiset from the left faceoff circle
less than a minute after Glen Murray had missed an open net at the
other end of the ice for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings evened the score five minutes into the second period,
finally solving Turek when Luc Robitaille scored from the slot
after Ray Ferraro had stolen the puck from Dallas defenseman Sergei
Zubov along the right boards.
</P>
<P>
   Invigorated by the goal, the Kings almost got another one less
than two minutes later, but Jokinen was unable to get the puck past
Turek from point-blank range at 6:27.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the difference between the Kings and Stars became clear.
When the Kings got a chance, they couldn't capitalize. When the
Stars got a chance, they took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The chance came at 10:34. Philippe Boucher lost the puck to Mike
Modano, who passed to Brett Hull in the left circle. Hull
effortlessly snapped the puck over Fiset's left shoulder, and in
one weak moment, the Kings had a one-goal deficit for all their
earnest efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good hockey team we are playing,'' Galley said,
``and we can't afford to have even little letdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had their chances in the third period (including the
crossbar and post), but were unable to get the tying goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
