A4785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-1STLD-     03-26 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION REACHES BUDGET ACCORD AFTER INTENSE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs throughout with accord and other Friday developments)   (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Leaders of the European Union on Friday reached a
last-ditch accord on a reform of the 15-nation bloc's
$92-billion-dollar annual budget that would eventually make it
possible for Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary to join.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement only came after a bitter conflict that took the
summit meeting into the early hours of Friday, more than 18 hours
past its scheduled conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Protracted arguments had pitted northern nations, which tend to
be the main contributors to the budget, against southern states,
which are its main beneficiaries. But German arguments that a
failure would paralyze the European Union at a time when a show of
unity was critical eventually prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the states in the Union are also members of NATO and
engaged in the alliance's bombardment of Yugoslavia. To have seemed
divided at this juncture would have been devastating, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder argued.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout more than two days of talks, Germany, whose net
annual contribution of about $12 billion is by far the union's
largest, appeared determined to complete negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer described the talks as
``extremely difficult,'' because they involved ``large amounts of
money and legitimate national interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But having worked tirelessly on the budget issue over the past
10 days, Schroeder seemed unwilling to abandon an effort Germany
saw as necessary to cement the unity of Europe. After a shaky first
six months in office, the German Chancellor was also in acute need
of a conspicuous diplomatic success.
</P>
<P>
   Its came early Friday, when the 15 heads of state and government
agreed that the overall budget for 2000 through 2006 would not be
allowed to grow by more than inflation from its 1999 level of $92
billion, halting a relentless upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that although Germany compromised on reductions
in farm spending _ scaling back a proposal to cut payments for
cereals by 20 in three stages to 15 percent in two stages and
delaying reductions in payments for dairy products until 2005 _
most cuts were elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The chief stumbling blocks to an accord on the so-called
``Agenda 2000'' program were French resistance to reforms of a
European agricultural policy that benefits its more than one
million farmers, Spanish objections to cuts in a regional fund that
provides European Union money to poorer countries, and objections
from several delegations to a rebate Britain receives that is worth
over $3 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Farm spending, designed to shield the farmers from lower world
market prices, accounts for about half of the European Union
budget. Germany, with a relatively small farm sector and a
conviction that spending would increase rapidly with new members,
has insisted that farm spending be stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   Spain also spent many hours resisting reform, both in the farm
sector and in the various forms of regional aid that go to poorer
European countries. This aid accounts for close to a third of the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spain will not accept any cuts from the level of funding it
now receives,'' said Spanish Finance Minister Rodrigo de Rato a few
hours before the agreement was reached. Greek Minister Costas
Simitis also objected to any change. ``Our per-capital income is 20
percent below the European average,'' he said. ``You can't say we
do not need help any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Several countries focused on the more than $3 billion that
Britain has received each year since 1984. The payment, negotiated
by then-Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, represents about 60
percent of the difference between its contributions and the amount
Britain receives in Union spending. But the rebate was preserved.
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations, the leaders came under scathing
criticism from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who said
they were about ``dictate to Israel the results of the negotiations
with the Palestinians by supporting a Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's outburst was apparently based on a draft of a
statement the leaders intend to make on the situation in the Middle
East, which would refer explicitly to a Palestinian right to a
state and say that, while this state should emerge from
negotiation, Israel had no right to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Such wording, if approved, would go beyond any previous official
European positions about Palestinian statehood. As the European
meeting broke up, it was still not clear what the precise wording
of any statement on the Middle East would be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
