<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BLACKHAWKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHY SHOW BY BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It had all the earmarks of a potential disaster. The
Bruins were coming off a monumental high after beating the Eastern
Conference-leading Senators in Ottawa, 3-0, Wednesday. They were
playing on consecutive nights against a Chicago Blackhawks team
with nothing to lose, and Boston was without its leading scorer,
Dmitri Khristich, out with a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like trouble with a capital T.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who trailed, 2-0, midway through the second period,
managed to pull themselves up by their bootstraps and cashed in on
three power-play goals to wind up with a 3-3 tie Thursday &UR;  &LR; night at
the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out a little flat but we fought back,'' said coach Pat
Burns. ``One bad penalty and the puck was in the net but we picked
up a point. Three out of four points in 48 hours I don't find too
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze, who is like the prize in the Cracker Jack box in
that you never know what you're going to get, scored a pair of
goals on the man advantage. Ray Bourque pulled to within a goal of
tying Paul Coffey for most career goals by a defenseman (385) with
a third-period strike, also on the power play, to provide the
Boston offense.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is unbeaten in its last five games (3-0-2) and is six
points ahead of the Rangers and seven points ahead of Florida for
the final Eastern Conference playoff spot with 11 games remaining.
More importantly, the Bruins have pulled to within two points of
idle Buffalo for seventh place, though the Sabres have a game in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Bob Probert, known more for his fists than his touch
around the net, put the Blackhawks ahead at the 16:06 mark of the
first period. The Bruins were all over Chicago in the second, but
it took a little while for them to be rewarded. Just 39 seconds in,
Bourque rattled a shot from the right point off the post. P.J.
Axelsson forced Jocelyn Thibault to make a tough glove save at
5:42.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:25, Heinze did everything but score as he tried jamming the
puck past the goalie at the left post. Only 12 seconds later, the
Blackhawks made it a two-goal lead. Right wing Tony Amonte of
Hingham, among the only proven talent Chicago didn't deal before
Tuesday's trade deadline, took a pass from left wing Dean McAmmond
and sprinted up the ice. He teed up a slapper from the left circle
that sailed past Dafoe at 7:37, Amonte's 37th goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins got a bit of a boost from Ken Belanger, who went toe
to toe with Probert and clearly won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny did a good job,'' said Burns. ``He woke 'em up for sure.
We needed something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, who has seven goals in seven games, then went to work,
cashing in on two penalties drawn by Anson Carter. His first came
at 11:13 off a perfect feed from defenseman Kyle McLaren. McLaren,
at the left point, took a pass from Bourque and dished it down to
Heinze, who redirected it past Thibault to pull the Bruins to
within 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was Johnny on the spot,'' said Heinze. ``It was right
place at the right time. Kyle made an unbelievable play. He said he
even saw me and passed to me. It wasn't a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren figured in on the next Heinze goal, too, scored with
48.5 seconds left in the period. McLaren put the puck on net from
the point and center Joe Thornton tried to tip it past Thibault.
The puck bounced out to Heinze, who popped in the rebound to make
it 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Brad Brown was assessed a penalty at the end of the
second period that led to the go-ahead goal at 1:21 of the third.
Center Tim Taylor set up Bourque by winning the draw in the right
circle. Bourque, at the right point, launched a shot that Thibault
couldn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were in good shape but not good enough. Defenseman
Boris Mironov, taking advantage of a Carter penalty, pulled the
Blackhawks even with a power-play goal with only 1:24 left in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played us tough,'' said Carter. ``We were able to bounce
back from a two-goal deficit. We weren't able to pull it out down
the stretch but I think we're happy with the point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
