brisket, roasted chicken, carrot tzimmes, coconut and chocolate
macaroons, sponge cake, and almond and honey cakes.
 &HT;    The adults drank Kosher Wine while we enjoyed glass after glass
of cold grape juice. Each goblet, by tradition, was filled then
partially emptied to recall the suffering of others.
 &HT;    Childhood Passover is something that became part of me and part
of who I am as an adult. As a Jew, everything I do and everything I
think at this time of the year goes back to my family and the
religious traditions they instilled in me.
 &HT;    Like the preparations always made for a visit by the prophet
Elijah who was supposed to join the head table, bringing the family
good news. I was the one who usually created his place setting with
my Grandma Irma's Rosenthal Classic Rose pattern China and mom's
Reed &AMP; Barton Francis I silver goblet and flatware. I also opened
the front door expecting Elijah to arrive. But he never did.
 &HT;    To start things off, we dipped a vegetable in salt water and ate
it combined with unleavened matzo, the ultimate symbol of the
holiday, and horseradish, also called maror.
 &HT;    We discussed the meaning of each tradition. Unleavened matzo
symbolized the fact that there was no time to allow bread to rise
in the haste to leave slavery, cross the Red Sea and enter the land
of Canaan. Salt water was tasted to evoke tears; horseradish
recalled the bitterness of bondage.
 &HT;    As children, we took turns asking the Four Questions which began
with the familiar words, ``Why is this night different from all
others?'' I remember Grandpa Louis teasing us with a great line he
may have borrowed from a Jewish comedian: ``How many Jews ask only
FOUR questions?''
 &HT;    I never knew who hid the Afikomen (money in an envelope) in our
home. One of my cousins always found it before my brother and I had
a chance to search. We rationalized our never receiving the prize
by telling each other it was better to give then to receive.
 &HT;    But all of that joy and happiness became something different
when my parents died _ Mom eight years ago; Dad last May. In my
case, I learned more about my religion and its traditions from them
than from all of the studies I endured during a decade of Sunday
School classes.
 &HT;    For most of the years since my mother's death, we were invited
to the homes of friends for Seder dinner. Their family celebrations
were lovely ... yet lonely. I felt like an outsider on my own
holiday.
 &HT;    So last year, ironically my dad's last Passover, I hosted Seder
dinner in our Florida home for him, my brother, his wife and niece,
my Episcopalian husband, my oldest girlfriend from Indiana, other
friends, a childless couple from the area, and, of course, our Jack
Russell terrier who loves table scraps.
 &HT;    I worried about making matzo ball dumplings that would turn out
moist and flavorful so the soup would taste right. I sweated over a
hot stove in hopes that my roasted chicken would be tender and
juicy.
 &HT;    I devoured an old Jewish cookbook that my mother gave me years
ago to try and recreate the culinary wonders she could pull out of
her father's yarmulke. And yes, I ordered some of the side dishes
from gourmet caterers with desserts courtesy of Wolfie's Bakery in
Miami Beach. (Tradition never tasted so good!)
 &HT;    Although we had a good time, the evening seemed quite different
from that which I remember as a child. With grandparents gone and
cousins living too far to visit, Passover began to take on a new
meaning for me. I used many of my mother's traditional treasures
like Kiddush cups, Seder plates, matzo covers, child's Passover
book, Haggadah and Afikomen prize.
 &HT;    Yet most of my family members were replaced by friends. There
was less emphasis on the traditional service with more conversation
about current events than historic memories. Kosher wine was
replaced by Cabernet Sauvignon. People only nibbled on fatty foods
like chopped liver and gefilte fish rather than indulge every bite
from the nine-course meal.
 &HT;    This year will be tougher still with both parents gone. No
matter how much I love my newer family and friends _ especially the
laughs and lingering _ holiday traditions can never stay the same.
 &HT;    Mom used to call the grocer by his first name; I'm make my own
way to the unpersonal service of the bustling neighborhood super
market. While my parents put their children's needs ahead of
theirs, friends today seem more self-centered, constantly searching
for spiritual enrichment. The Seder service itself creates less
interest than what is on television.
 &HT;    Such is life. These changes remind me of a song we sang each
summer at Jewish camp, a song that provides me with solace:
 &HT;    Days pass and years go bye, ever and ever ...
 &HT;    and as our voices ring,
 &HT;    ring out with songs we sing,
 &HT;    life is a joyous thing,
 &HT;    ever and ever.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Linda Marx 
<TEXT>
