<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WARNINGS-COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV WARNINGS FOR `HOMOSEXUAL CONTENT' A BAD IDEA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Last month when the Rev. Jerry Falwell issued his Tinky Winky
``alert'' to parents, he wasn't the only Christian concerned about
a ``gay role model'' on television.
 &HT;    Martin Mawyer, president of the Christian Action Network, also
suggested that the Federal Communications Commission place a
warning label _ HC _ on TV shows that contain ``homosexual
content.''
 &HT;    The Christian Action network (CAN), a grassroots, ``pro-family''
organization, based in Virginia, claims to have 250,000 members.
 &HT;    ``Members of our organization have become increasingly disgusted
with the amount of homosexuality in television programming. More
than two dozen homosexual characters are portrayed weekly on
network television alone,'' Mawyer said in press statement.
 &HT;    ``Parents have a right to be warned about programs depicting
acts of homosexuality on television. TV broadcasters _ including
network, cable, and satellite _ already place warning labels on
programs containing violence, sex and `adult' language. Now it's
time to warn parents about homosexual sex,'' he said.
 &HT;    Mawyer and his organization are reacting _ perhaps overreacting
_ to the showing of a short film, ``Cowboy Jesus,'' which casts
Christ as a black lesbian, who has sex with Mary Magdalene. The
film ran on a public access cable station in Arlington, Virginia.
 &HT;    What also disturbs Mawyer and members of CAN is the 25 gay,
lesbian, bisexual, and transgender characters now airing in prime
time (as counted by the Gay &AMP; Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation's
(GLAAD)).
 &HT;    GLAAD is a national lesbian and gay media advocacy organization.
 &HT;    Some of the characters are ``more flamboyant and disgusting than
others,'' CAN told the Washington Post, but all of them ``ridicule
the traditional morals of conservative Americans,'' the
organization contends.
 &HT;    Hollywood has thrown a cold shoulder to Mawyer's suggestion for
an HC warning label. Top lobbyist Jack Valenti, president and CEO
of the Motion Picture Association of America and head of the
Television Ratings Committee, says it is an ``inhumane proposal
that should be ignored.''
 &HT;    Joan M. Garry, executive director of GLAAD went further: ``The
notion of adding a distinct label for `homosexual content' is
clearly based on ignorance and prejudice. Such a label could only
serve to stigmatize members of the lesbian, gay, bisexual, and
transgender community by suggesting that something is inherently
wrong with them.''
 &HT;    The liberal People for the American Way, a progressive advocacy
organization, also weighed in on Mawyer's proposal. ``The sad fact
that groups on the fringe of American politics would seek to target
gay and lesbian TV characters in this manner points out how far we
have to go to achieve the American dream of justice,'' said Carole
Shields, the organization's president.
 &HT;    What's really going on with Falwell and Mawyer is a conservative
backlash against the progress that gays and lesbians have made in
Hollywood. Two years ago Ellen DeGeneres opened the closet door for
prime time gay and lesbian characters, and there has been an
increasingly positive portrayal of gay people on television. This
season, for example, Eric McCormick, who plays a lawyer and is the
gay male lead on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' a show so successful that NBC is
moving it April 8 to the network's coveted ``Must See TV'' Thursday
lineup, at 8:30 p.m.
 &HT;    Another example is the Feb. 10 and 17 ground breaking episodes
of ``Dawson's Creek,'' which brought an openly gay teenager Jack
McPhee (Kerr Smith) of the fictitious Capeside High to prime time.
 &HT;    ```Dawson's Creek' stayed away from stereotypes on this one,''
said GLAAD entertainment media director Scott Seomin. ``Jack is a
strong character written with intelligence, depth, and integrity.
`Dawson's Creek' has added to the diversity of gay characters on
television with its positive portrayal of Jack,'' he added.
 &HT;    Keep in mind that the conservative call for a homosexual content
warning label _ modern day scarlet letters for television _ can't
be viewed in isolation. ``The religious right has a very long,
concentrated campaign against anything that will increase societal
tolerance and acceptance of homosexuality,'' said Peter Montgomery,
special assistant to the president of People for the American Way.
 &HT;    ``So when you say this one thing seems silly and ridiculous, you
must remember that the right is constantly putting out there the
message that gays are diseased, horrible, and don't deserve to be a
full part of the American community. Our speaking out was a matter
of challenging bigotry when it's outspoken and not letting things
go unanswered, especially when anti-gay bigotry leads to really
horrific crimes'' he said during a telephone interview.
 &HT;    There's no doubt about the horrific crimes and hostile climate
out there _ as the brutal murders of Matthew Shepard and Billy Jack
Gather serve to remind us.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Chuck Colbert 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
