A4832 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-BLACK-LIST:MON     03-26 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-BLACK-LIST:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL ACADEMY AWARD `BLACK LIST'
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer living
in Oakland, Calif., and a contributor to the forthcoming book
``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories and Practices.''
(1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Elia Kazan's honorary Academy Award was not the only controversy
at the 71st Academy Awards.
 &HT;    According to Chris Rock, a presenter, it ``looked like the
Million White Man March out there.'' Host Whoopi Goldberg chimed in
with ``I thought the black list was me and Hattie McDaniel.''
 &HT;    What both Rock and Goldberg were referring to was the lack of
nominations of black performers and filmmakers to the Academy
Awards. There was absolutely no chance that African Americans would
win any Oscars this year, because none was even nominated.
 &HT;    Years ago, Spike Lee called the Academy Awards racist. Last
year, in a film collage of previous Oscar Awards shows, the Academy
themselves showed a clip of Richard Pryor stating, ``I'm here to
explain tonight why no black people will be nominated for
anything.''
 &HT;    Also last year, the Academy gathered on stage the 73 winners of
acting awards in the past. There were only six African Americans on
that stage: Morgan Freeman, Lou Gossett Jr., Cuba Gooding Jr.,
Whoopi Goldberg, Sidney Poitier, and Denzel Washington. And owing
to the alphabetical alignment, three _ Goldberg, Gooding, and
Gossett _ were sitting next to each other. Five men and one woman.
Only one other woman of African descent has ever won a major award,
the late Hattie McDaniel.
 &HT;    So what are we to make at the dearth of African American
nominations?
 &HT;    African Americans comprise 25 percent of domestic box office
sales and an even larger percentage of key urban markets. And, as
in television _ where surveys that show what TV programs African
Americans are watching are entirely different from what polls
indicate as the top shows _ in film it's the same. Black filmgoers
see the big Hollywood hits as well as movies that African Americans
direct, produce, and star in _ films that will probably never
receive any Academy recognition.
 &HT;    Politics loomed large this year with the Kazan controversy and
last year in a much more subtle and largely ignored way.
 &HT;    At the Academy Awards in 1975, presenter Lillian Hellman chided
the industry for dealing with McCarthyism ``with the force and
courage of a bowl of mash potatoes.'' So I guess it was in fact
fitting that Kazan receive the Lifetime Achievement Award.
 &HT;    But Hollywood is rarely confused for being the bastion of
politics, ribbons of various colors aside. It just doesn't happen
that frequently. In the 71-year history of the Awards one can
probably count fewer than 10 overtly political statements. That is
if you don't count the streaker. Post-awards people were expressing
relief that no political statements were uttered in this show, the
longest Oscar ceremony on record.
 &HT;    Perhaps most failed to listen to the short, eloquent, quiet _
and yet political _ speech of Chris Tashima who won as a
co-producer for live action short film, ``Visas and Virtue.'' The
film, in which he also starred, was about Japanese diplomat Chiune
Sugihara, who while posted in Lithuania during World War II is
credited with saving the lives of thousands of Jews. Some call
Sugihara ``Japan's Oskar Schindler.'' Sugihara defied orders and
issued transit visas which saved lives.
 &HT;    And just what did Tashima say when accepting his Academy Award?
``I hope we can begin to embrace every race. Diversity is the
ingenue. She's the true American star. And she's ready for her
close-up,'' he said, keeping his discourse within the 20-seconds'
time limitation imposed by the show's producers.
 &HT;    If folks had been listening, they would have found Tashima very
political. And political in a subtle, not a knock-you-over-the-head
way. There was no hissing or other audible disapproval as there was
for Sasheen Littlefeather when she spoke on behalf of Marlon Brando
25 years ago. There was no voiced disapproval of the idea of
embracing diversity and of inclusion.
 &HT;    And certainly it did not elicit the same reaction as did Jesse
Jackson's protest in 1996 that the Oscars excluded people of color
from jobs and Academy Awards.
 &HT;    Last year, by my count, only four people of color were even
nominated for on-air awards. This year Tashima was the only one to
win an Oscar at the ceremonies, a show where cameras shamelessly
panned to someone of African descent in the audience when there was
a presenter of African descent.
 &HT;    African Americans and Latinos have in part dealt with their
exclusion from the Oscars. The NAACP Image Awards and the ALMA
(American Latino Media Arts, and Spanish for ``soul'') honor
filmmakers and performers who probably wouldn't be honored by the
Academy.
 &HT;    The concept of Affirmative Action seems to offend many people
and is rapidly being obliterated both on federal and state levels.
This, despite the lack of racial diversity in any facet of American
life. The concept of diversity, however, doesn't seem to have the
same negative connotations.
 &HT;    No one wants to play semantic word games, but someone has to
speak out for inclusion and diversity, particularly in the harsh
reality of organizations and systems which are clearly
exclusionary. Tashima, in his eloquence and simplicity, has words
of import for every element of American society.
 &HT;    It is time for the entertainment industry as well as other
industries to step up to the plate and redress this inequity. For
diversity, as Tashima said, is the true American star.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL;
</P>
