<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON.COM'S-BEZOS-NE     03-26 1879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON.COM'S-BEZOS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM'S JEFFREY P. BEZOS, LORD OF THE JUNGLE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By YLEANA MARTINEZ 
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It is the end of the 20th century. The stage is set for a very
modern clash of the titans. At stake is nothing less than world
domination of the electronic marketplace using high-tech computer
graphics as ammo and old-fashioned elbow grease as fuel.
 &HT;    The arena is a virtual bookstore frequented by spectators who
are coveted by the mighty opponents for their wallets, their
loyalty, and their repeat business. At this, the dawn of the
on-line revolution, which enterprise will win the hearts and minds
of these consumers?
 &HT;    A leading contender is the 35-year-old son of a Cuban immigrant,
Jeffrey P. Bezos, founder and CEO of Amazon.com Inc. _ the upstart
Internet company that boasts 4.5 million customers in 160
countries.
 &HT;    Bezos stands alone against his prime adversary, the very well
financed Barnes &AMP; Noble Corp., a behemoth on the brutish playing
fields of bookselling.
 &HT;    The media have often made comparisons to David and Goliath. But
in this showdown, it's no longer easy to tell who is David and who
is Goliath.
 &HT;    Bezos concocted the right formula for on-line selling when he
chose books as the product to move. In less than four years, he has
risen from Wall Street wunderkind to become one of cyberdom's kings
of the world.
 &HT;    In 1994 Bezos quit his job as a hedge fund manager to stake a
claim on the wild frontier of Internet retailing, or ``e-tailing.''
He moved to Seattle and started his business in a rented garage
with loans from family, friends, investment bankers and venture
capitalists.
 &HT;    Since its debut on the World Wide Web in July 1995, Amazon.com
has become the model to watch _ and to envy. Soon after the site
appeared, chat group participants praised its availability of
product and user-friendly style. Paradoxically, in the nonhuman
realm of cyberspace, it is the very pedestrian experience of word
of mouth that Amazon executives regard as a major reason for its
success.
 &HT;    What Amazon also did early on was spend millions of dollars on
advertising in such publications as the New York Times Book Review.
It also invested in banner links that touted the site in the ``hot
corner'' of browsers. The huge amounts of money spent _ $6.1
million in 1996 _ stirred excitement in the business world and
evoked highly positive press. The advertising blitz helped the
company reap $16 million in revenue, much of which went into
refining the site.
 &HT;    Amazon's warp-speed expansion rattled the nation's largest
physical bookstore chain, Barnes &AMP; Noble (B&AMP;N), which, along with
Borders, controls almost 12 percent of the nation's total book
sales.
 &HT;    Amazon left B&AMP;N to eat its dust, but it didn't take long for the
brand-name company to strike back-hard. Last year, B&AMP;N acquired the
book distributor, Ingram Book Co., and formed a partnership with
German media conglomerate, Bertelsmann AG.
 &HT;    Bezos' response: ``Our advantage is that we know more about
e-commerce than anybody else. We've been doing it longer, and we've
already leveled the playing field.'' Currently, Amazon claims 85
percent of on-line book sales. In the overall book market, however,
the Internet accounts for only 3 percent of the activity.
 &HT;    Last fall, Amazon acquired two leading Internet companies and
entered the European e-market by opening sites in the United
Kingdom and Germany. In June 1998, the company added music sales to
its offerings, claiming to offer 10 times the CD selection of the
typical music store, with savings for customers of up to 40
percent. Within four months, Amazon became the leading on-line
music retailer, with sales of $14.4 million.
 &HT;    For the fourth quarter of 1998, Amazon said its sales rose to
about $250 million, almost quadruple what it reported at the end of
1997 ($66 million). Based on these figures, the company trumpeted
that in its three-and-a-half-year existence, it had achieved a
staggering $1 billion in annualized sales.
 &HT;    Holiday sales helped Amazon to rack up some astounding figures.
Between Nov. 17, 1998, the day it launched its video and gift
stores, and Dec. 31, Amazon logged 1 million new customers and
shipped more than 7.5 million items, which was more than the
company shipped the entire previous year. On one day during that
period, the company shipped products worth $6 million.
 &HT;    As would be expected, Amazon.com is a Wall Street darling,
having declared two three-for-one splits on its common stock in the
last three months. It has also seen its shares rise from $9 in May
1997 to a little over $163 as of Jan. 11, 1999.
 &HT;    All these breathtaking figures, however, have not yet translated
into a stronger bottom line for the bookseller. Music and video
sales traditionally have had very thin profit margins, and the
company remains unprofitable. At press time, no specifics on 1998
fourth-quarter losses had yet been released, but industry analysts
forecast a loss of about 56 cents a share.
 &HT;    In the past, Bezos has attributed losses to aggressive
advertising campaigns and internal investment strategies. ``This is
an investment phase for Amazon.com,'' He told the Seattle Times
last summer. ``We've been totally straightforward with everybody
from the beginning that that's our strategy, and a lot of people
believe in our strategy and some people don't. Reasonable people
could disagree.'' (Bezos and his wife, Mackenzie, own about 45
percent of the company.)
 &HT;    For all the attention, wealth, and notoriety that Amazon has
garnered, the young billionaire behind it all remains a fairly
inaccessible person. Several requests to interview Bezos by phone
or by e-mail for this article were denied. Questions sent via
e-mail to a publicity assistant were not all answered.
 &HT;    According to other reporters, Bezos has a slight frame, often
wears white shirts and khaki pants, and has thinning brown hair.
But what stands out in photographs of this technology tycoon is his
apparently warm smile, his smooth, tanned skin, and his big brown
eyes. Bezos certainly looks boyish, and with his youthful
countenance he brings a decidedly fresh, counterculture approach to
his working environment. He reportedly drives a Honda Accord to
work and still rents an apartment month-to-month in Belltown, a
downtown Seattle neighborhood.
 &HT;    According to his assistant, Kay Dangaard, Bezos was the eldest
of three children, born in Albuquerque, New Mexico, to Mike and
Jackie Bezos. His father was a petroleum engineer; his mother, a
homemaker who hailed from Virginia. ``His father was just 15 when
he left Cuba, and has never returned,'' Dangaard said via e-mail.
 &HT;    The Bezos family grew up in Miami and Houston. Young Jeffrey
spent many summers on his grandfather's ranch in Cotulla, Texas,
learning the ways of the land and many unoffice-like skills such as
fixing windmills, driving bulldozers, laying water lines, building
fences, and castrating cattle.
 &HT;    All the while, he dreamed of a career as a physicist, and he
enrolled at Princeton University to pursue his goal. In his
sophomore year, Bezos switched tracks when he realized that his
talent was in computers. He graduated in 1986, summa cum laude, Phi
Beta Kappa, in electrical engineering and computer science.
 &HT;    In an extensive interview last fall with several staff members
of the Washington Post, Bezos discussed his next venture for Amazon
_ a shopping referral service to help his 4.5 million customers
discover new products for sale on the Web. One service already
provided to many repeat buyers is that, based on their choices, the
company compiles listings of offerings they might be interested in.
 &HT;    This is what Bezos considers a ``personalization tool'' that
will increase the number of return site visits and give Internet
retailing the human touch it so sorely lacks.
 &HT;    Although the Web customization process rankles privacy freaks,
Bezos told the Post that the service ``is like retreating to the
time when you have small-town merchants who got to know you, and
they could help you get the right products.''
 &HT;    Computers may be the muscle that moves Amazon.com, but the heart
of the business is in a warehouse located in South Seattle, across
from a pawnshop and a building housing a needle exchange program.
Another warehouse is located in Newcastle, Del., and a third is
slated to open later this year in Nevada.
 &HT;    Here you will find employees, mostly in their 20s, wearing
comfortable clothes and sensible shoes for walking the miles of
aisles to physically pick out books and CDs to fill orders.
Neckties are no-no's, but dogs are welcome to join their masters at
work.
 &HT;    Fortunately, not everyone involved in book commerce is waiting
with bated breath to see which of the cyber arch-enemies will
emerge victorious. Marina Tristan, assistant director at Arte
Publico Press, in Houston, says that on a personal level, on-line
book ordering will never match the pleasure of browsing through a
bookstore. ``You know what I mean,'' she says. ``Holding a book in
your hands, reading excerpts.''
 &HT;    Instead, the small press, which operates out of the University
of Houston, views Internet booksellers as an additional marketing
tool to advertise its catalog.
 &HT;    Tristan says small brick-and-mortar bookstores, which are the
major outlets for Arte Publico, are still reeling from the impact
of the dizzying changes in the industry in recent years.
Consolidations of major book chains, wholesalers, and distributors
have resulted in the closure of numerous independent bookstores
across the country. ``To tell you the truth, Amazon.com has not had
a huge impact on us,'' she says.
 &HT;    Not yet, maybe, but the consensus is that Amazon.com has indeed
had a great impact in certain areas, revolutionizing the Web as a
retail outlet. As it continues to grow, it should make book readers
out of still more unsuspecting surfers.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Hispanic magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
