 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT PASSOVER, AGE-OLD TRADITIONS COME ALIVE. Childhood Passover
is something that became part of her and part of who she is as an
adult, says columnist Linda Marx. ``As a Jew, everything I do and
everything I think at this time of the year goes back to my family
and the religious traditions they instilled in me,'' she writes.
``I learned more from them than from all the years of religious
studies.'' Linda Marx describes the Passovers of yesteryear with
countless relatives gathered round, and the Passovers of today with
friends old and new, who watch their waistlines and drink Cabernet
Sauvignon instead of Kosher wine. ``Nothing stays the same,'' she
observes sadly.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-PASSOVER-MEMORIES:MARX-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   BEFORE ALL THE CYPRESS ARE TURNED TO MULCH. Cypress trees
symbolize Florida almost as much as alligators and oranges. But
their disappearance, unlike that of mangrove trees, has gone
virtually unreported, writes columnist Bill Maxwell. Second only to
pines in sheer numbers, cypress occupy 1.6-million wetland acres
and are essential for water purification, flood control and as
habitat for wildlife. But tragically these mighty trees for the
most part are being cut down for mulch. ``For many homeowners, in
fact, cypress mulch is a horticultural must,'' Maxwell comments
bitterly. ``We are fools to let this continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-CYPRESS-TRAGEDY:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   TV WARNINGS FOR `HOMOSEXUAL CONTENT' A BAD IDEA. Last month when
the Rev. Jerry Falwell issued his Tinky Winky ``alert'' to parents,
he wasn't the only Christian concerned about a ``gay role model''
on television. Martin Mawyer, president of the Christian Action
Network, has also suggested that the Federal Communications
Commission place a warning label _ HC _ on TV shows that contain
``homosexual content,'' reports columnist Chuck Colbert. But what's
really going on with Falwell and Mawyer, writes Colbert, ``is a
conservative backlash against the progress that gays and lesbians
have made in Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-TV-WARNINGS-COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL ACADEMY AWARD `BLACK LIST.' The lack of nominations of
black performers and filmmakers to the 1999 Academy Awards was very
evident to columnist Akilah Monifa. Comprising 25 percent of
domestic box office sales and an even larger percentage of key
urban markets, black filmgoers see the big Hollywood hits as well
as movies that African Americans direct, produce, and star in _
``films that will probably never receive any Academy recognition,''
she writes. ``It is time for the entertainment industry to redress
this exclusion. As award winner Chris Tashima (the only person of
color) said, diversity is the true American star.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-OSCARS-BLACK-LIST:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON.COM'S JEFFREY P. BEZOS, LORD OF THE JUNGLE. Jeffrey P.
Bezos revolutionized book buying on-line with his internet company,
Amazon.com. ``He tapped into a gold mine when he began selling
books on-line. Now his expanded and fast-growing company is leading
the way, and competitors are hot on his trail,'' writes Yleana
Martinez in Hispanic magazine. Read how this 35-year-old son of a
Cuban immigrant started up in 1995 the company that today boasts
4.5 million customers in 160 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-AMAZON.COM'S-BEZOS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a'' general
news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
