<HEADER>
A4857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-HEINZE-BOS     03-26 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-HEINZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZE'S HIGHLIGHTS PILING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For someone who couldn't buy a goal early in the
season, Steve Heinze certainly has turned his season around.
</P>
<P>
   Heinze's two goals in Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's 3-3 tie with Chicago at
the FleetCenter gave the Bruins right wing seven goals in as many
games and also enabled him to crack the 20-goal mark.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Heinze's goals, the Bruins' first two of the game, were
on the power play, and both came in the second period. The second
came on a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of knowing where the openings are and where the
puck might bounce, so it's a matter of being in the right place at
the right time,'' said Heinze, whose longest goal drought this
season has been six games.
</P>
<P>
   Heinze's first goal was at 11:13, with Kyle McLaren and Ray
Bourque picking up assists. The second goal, which tied the game at
2-2, was off McLaren and Joe Thornton assists with 48.5 seconds
left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Two shots, two goals. Heinze isn't going to analyze his success,
though. He's just hoping the timing's right and will continue
through the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck's going in so I'll keep staying confident and I'll
keep going on the ice and, hopefully, I'll keep doing things I'm
doing, keep putting the puck in the net,'' said Heinze, no longer
bothered by the hip flexor that caused him to miss five games in
early February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great, I'm getting a lot of ice time, getting out there
on our power play and I feel like I'm skating OK and I'm getting
the puck. The games just go that way sometimes, so you just try not
to overthink and get in the right spot. It was certainly one of
those games and I just hope to get more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With the puck seemingly finding its way into the net easily for
him, Heinze wants to make sure he's on the ice as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting the ice time, you're playing so you always want
to be on the ice,'' Heinze said. ``You want to start the game,
finish the game, play on power plays, play late in the game as well
as win the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things are going right, it tends to build on itself and
the puck goes in, so you shoot it rather than hoping it goes in.
You think another goal. It's a confidence thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty goals may not seem like an extraordinary accomplishment,
but considering the way defensive play is stressed in today's NHL,
it's impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty goals is 20 goals,'' Heinze said. ``Twenty goals is now
a pretty big number, especially looking at the stats. There may not
be a guy who hits 50 goals this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
