<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUMBLING-INTO-WAR-EC     03-26 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUMBLING-INTO-WAR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE: BELGRADE ISN'T BAGHDAD, AND SLOBODAN ISN'T SADDAM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent, TIMELY 1,125-word ``separate buy'' article is from
the current (week beginning 27 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The West has stumbled into one of its riskiest ventures since
the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   It may pick itself up, and emerge standing proud and erect,
having been a decisive force for good. Or it may fall flat, with
NATO, its military club, weaker than at any time in its 50 years of
life, and the Balkans ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   To armchair strategists, bombing Serbia may not seem especially
risky. When NATO took to the air to strike the Bosnian Serbs, in
1995, none of the dire consequences predicted by doubters ensued;
in due course a peace treaty was signed, which has worked
remarkably well.
</P>
<P>
   Western aircraft now routinely bomb Iraq; they may not unseat
Saddam Hussein, but they appear to run no great risks.
</P>
<P>
   This latest operation, however, is not quite like those others.
First, it is NATO's first unambiguous attack on a sovereign state
that stands accused of being vile not to its neighbors but only to
its own people.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior, offensive as it is, has long been considered the
prerogative of properly constituted governments. It is widely
practiced, and often without much more than a tut-tut from the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Where was NATO, for instance, when Russia tried to squelch the
Chechens, at a cost of 50,000-100,000 lives?
</P>
<P>
   This week's attack on Serbia may be the start of an admirable
new trend to restrain thugs and despots, though that does not look
terribly likely. What is undeniable is that the attack is something
new, and it could set an awkward precedent.
</P>
<P>
   How would the West respond if one day China, say, were to carry
out air strikes against an Indian government fighting to prevent
its Muslim-majority province of Jammu and Kashmir from seceding?
</P>
<P>
   Second, Serbia is better armed and militarily more sophisticated
than the Bosnian Serbs and even latter-day Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of this, NATO's political bosses have drawn
exactly the wrong conclusion. Instead of maximizing their military
power, they have forsworn the use of ground troops, except to
uphold a peace agreement that may never come into being.
</P>
<P>
   Beguiled by technology, they may perhaps believe that smart
bombs and Tomahawk missiles can nowadays win military victories
without the help of foot soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Events may prove them correct. But right now, as the operation
begins, many military men say they are wrong, especially in the
terrain of Kosovo, where military targets and civilians are
inextricably mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Iraq, where conditions are much more favorable,
sustained bombing has yet to produce an outcome satisfactory to the
West.
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, if NATO was not prepared to commit itself fully and
wholeheartedly, it might have been better not to threaten to attack
at all, rather than to attack from the relative safety of the sky
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, NATO's 19 members, despite their initial unity, are
deeply uneasy about the operation. Several _ including Italy, whose
proximity makes it valuable as a base from which to stage attacks _
are generally reluctant warriors unless they see some imminent
threat to their national security.
</P>
<P>
   Their hesitations have already encouraged Serbia's president,
Slobodan Milosevic, in his refusal to make concessions at the
negotiating table; they could yet curtail a military campaign that
should go on for weeks if it is to have any chance of achieving its
aims.
</P>
<P>
   And what are those aims? Ostensibly, just to put an end to
Serbia's brutal treatment of the ethnic Albanians who make up
nine-tenths of the population of the province of Kosovo, and to do
so without breaking up the country.
</P>
<P>
   But if the blunt instrument of bombing succeeds in this, it will
owe as much to luck as to precision.
</P>
<P>
   The hope must be that, after a mind-concentrating battery from
the air, discontented members of Serbia's armed forces will
speedily remove Milosevic and replace him with someone more
conciliatory. Or perhaps they might leave him in office, but
persuade him to come to terms with the West.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible, however, that the Serbs will fight on,
possibly with greater determination than ever. If so, the Albanians
of Kosovo may well be killed or driven from their homes in ever
greater numbers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the bombardment were to tip the balance of
power against the Serbs in Kosovo, the guerrillas there might well
exact horrible revenge on the Serb minority in the province.
Without ground troops, NATO would be hard put to stop this.
</P>
<P>
   What can the West do to increase the chances of success, however
defined? For a start, it can and should do its utmost to tell the
Serb people at large that the outside world bears no animus against
them; that in western eyes, and not just those of Russia, Serbia's
declared ally, their country is a pivotal state with an important
role to play in Europe; and that sanctions of all kinds will be
lifted as soon as it shows itself ready to behave decently.
</P>
<P>
   Since this sort of message cannot be conveyed through Serbia's
controlled press and radio, it should be broadcast from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Other means should be used to undermine Milosevic. Montenegro,
Serbia's tiny sister-component in what remains of the Yugoslav
federation, should be encouraged to break free, even though it has
not been spared airborne attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovars, however, should be told that the West is not
intervening to give them their independence, even though events, if
they spin out of control, may well lead ultimately to secession.
</P>
<P>
   In time, NATO may have to declare Kosovo, or at least a large
part of it, an area into which the Serb authorities should not
venture on pain of retribution, much as parts of Iraq have been
declared off-limits to those who do Saddam's bidding.
</P>
<P>
   But first the province will have to be rid of the Serb forces
that are concentrated there, and without, in so doing, turning its
capital Pristina into a slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   None of this will be easy. At every turn lies the possibility
that fighting will spill over into nearby states, most of which are
an unstable cocktail of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in time there can be a general redrawing of Balkan
borders, with Serbia losing Kosovo and gaining a bit of Bosnia. But
that must await a general cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the West has a war to fight. If it makes a mess
of it, NATO's 50th birthday party next month will be a sad affair.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the world's diminished but by no means extinct band of
dictators will judge that they can, after all, treat their own
people as brutally as they like. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,125-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 0208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4860 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUMBLING-INTO-WAR-EC     03-26 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUMBLING-INTO-WAR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE: BELGRADE ISN'T BAGHDAD, AND SLOBODAN ISN'T SADDAM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
