<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAISE-INTEREST-RATES!     03-26 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAISE-INTEREST-RATES!-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED UP, NOT FED DOWN: U.S. INTEREST RATES NEED TO RISE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 27 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monetary policy is often likened to driving with a blacked-out
windshield, a wonky speedometer and a cracked rear-view mirror. But
at least a motorist knows that if he touches the brake or the
accelerator, the car will respond immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates are more complex. A rise in rates seems like a
tightening of policy and a cut like an easing; so keeping rates
constant seems ``neutral'' (i.e., neither stimulating nor reining
in the economy).
</P>
<P>
   This thinking is flawed _ a point America's Federal Reserve
should remember when its policy-making open-market committee meets
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Most commentators argue that the Fed does not need to raise
interest rates now because inflation remains low, making a neutral
monetary policy appropriate. But current policy is not neutral: it
is deliberately loose.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, remember, cut rates three times last autumn, by a total
of three-quarters of a percentage point. Its justification was the
financial-market turmoil in the wake of Russia's default _ and
notably a sharp rise in credit spreads and a plunge in share
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Since last September, fears of a credit crunch have dissipated;
the Dow has risen by some 25 percent; and, rather than being harmed
by global economic slowdown, the American economy has grown even
more briskly than had been predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, merely to return its policy stance to the position of last
summer, the Fed needs to nudge interest rates up again.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that real interest rates in America are above their
30-year average of 2 percent _ but that does not mean that policy
is tight. The appropriate interest rate depends not only on the
level of inflation, but also on the amount of slack in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   With GDP surging by an annual rate of over 6 percent in the
fourth quarter of 1998, and with unemployment unusually low, the
American economy is running well above its sustainable growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   In such circumstances, a small rise in interest rates is
equivalent not to stamping on the brakes, but to easing up slightly
on the accelerator. Keeping rates where they are amounts to driving
at a constant high speed even when the road ahead bends sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, financial conditions are more lax than they seem. A
rise in share prices boosts spending in similar ways to a cut in
interest rates or a cheaper dollar. This is no small matter, given
that the assets of mutual funds overtook those of banks last year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, taking account of the impact on the economy of higher
share prices, as well as last year's cuts in interest rates,
financial conditions in America are now at their most accommodating
since 1993, when the economy was crawling out of recession. Rapid
growth in America's broad money supply bears this out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet why worry when inflation remains low? Increased competition
and technological advances may have helped America's economy to
grow faster without pushing up inflation, but the drop in inflation
has also owed a lot to falling oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the recent rise in oil prices is not sustained, that
windfall is likely to disappear over the next year; so inflation
could well creep up.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even if inflation in the prices of goods and services
remains subdued, lax financial conditions carry risks of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Asset-price inflation can harm the economy as much as
consumer-price inflation. It can distort the allocation of
resources by encouraging reckless spending, for example. The
combined saving rate of households and firms in America has already
fallen to its lowest level ever.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a risk that a rise in rates might instantly
trigger a sharp fall on Wall Street, bringing America's economy to
a grinding halt and thus harming the world too.
</P>
<P>
   But American policy should not be seen in isolation: while the
Fed should be raising rates, the European Central Bank should be
cutting them, and Japan needs reflation too.
</P>
<P>
   For the Fed, in the longer run doing nothing is riskier still.
It is not the central bank's job to prop up an overvalued stock
market. &QL; 
