<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS EYEING BERG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A missing piece to the Kings' puzzle this season was
21-year-old defenseman Aki Berg.
</P>
<P>
   One of the team's top prospects, Berg opted before the season to
play in his native Finland when he couldn't reach contract terms
with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, Berg and Kings general manager Dave
Taylor met briefly while Taylor was on a scouting trip in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went to talk to him after a game,'' Taylor said
Thursday night following the Kings' 2-1 loss to Dallas. ``I invited
him to dinner. He didn't want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, Berg spoke with a reporter for a Finnish sports
newspaper. According to a translator, Berg said: ``I just briefly
met Taylor. We just said, `Hi.' I never told him that I'm coming
back to L.A. Everything is still open. But if the negotiations are
like last time, I'm never coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he wants Berg back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's appropriate to talk while he's still
playing there,'' Taylor said. ``As soon as the season is over,
we'll talk to his agent (Larry Kelly of Ottawa). We'd like to bring
him back. We're not going to trade him. We'll negotiate with him,
but we're not going to overpay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish playoffs end in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Babych arrives: The newest King was not in the lineup Thursday
night, but he said he's ready to contribute when he gets the
chance, an opportunity that may come Sunday in Colorado when the
Kings begin a five-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Babych arrived in town Wednesday, and practiced with his
new team for the first time Thursday morning. Drafted in 1980 and
approaching his 38th birthday, Babych said he's planning on playing
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing for sure,'' said Babych, acquired Tuesday in the
trade that sent Steve Duchesne to Philadelphia. ``I'm not ready to
stop. I've got no doubt about it. I feel too good to stop. I think
I'd be cheating myself if I didn't want to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Babych's contract expires after the season, but he said he'd
like to remain with the Kings next season. He also said he believes
he can help the team immediately, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got seven defensemen here,'' he said. ``They know they
can count on me to step in and not hurt the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Babych, Kings coach Larry Robinson said: ``I think he's very
similar to Dougie Bodger, a real smart player, a big strong kid who
can move the puck. He played on the power play in Philadelphia.
He's a cagey veteran, is what he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
