<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW QUESTIONS ABOUT NYC POLICE CHIEF'S OSCAR JAUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The company that controls Revlon Inc. hires off-duty
New York City police officers, in uniform, to guard its offices at
night under a city-sponsored arrangement that may complicate the
ethics inquiry into Police Commissioner Howard Safir's free trip to
the Academy Awards with the president of Revlon.
</P>
<P>
   Safir has said he does not believe the trip last weekend with
his friend, Revlon president George Fellows, is an ethical
violation because, although officials are barred from accepting
gifts from companies that do business with the city, Revlon does
not hold any such contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the definition of ``business dealings'' in the city ethics
code is a broad one that encompasses much more than simple
contractual relationships and includes such matters as real estate
purchases and license applications. And City Councilman Sheldon
Leffler, chairman of the Public Safety Committee, which oversees
the Police Department, said the use of off-duty officers at a
company affiliated with Revlon may constitute a business dealing as
defined by the code.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not good judgment for the commissioner to accept the
trip in a jet and the hotel and whatever else that goes with it
while at the same time the department is allowing these people to
participate in the program,'' Leffler said.
</P>
<P>
   The affiliate of Revlon, Mac Andrews &AMP; Forbes, which holds 83
percent of Revlon stock, is one of about 100 companies that take
part in the Paid Detail program, in which companies register with
the Police Department and hire off-duty officers in uniform to
guard their premises.
</P>
<P>
   Safir started the program two years ago to increase police
presence on the streets without additional expense. The companies
pay the officers $27 an hour and the city a $2.70-an-hour
administrative fee.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mac Andrews &AMP; Forbes said that, since April
1998, the company has employed an off-duty officer six nights a
week to patrol outside its headquarters on East 63rd Street, the
same block where Ronald Perelman, the company's owner, lives.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, James Conroy, said it was inaccurate to describe
the use of the off-duty officers as a business relationship and
said the arrangement was ``utterly unrelated to the friendship
between Howard Safir and George Fellows.'' He said Fellows was not
affiliated with Mac Andrews &AMP; Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The city Law Department, at Safir's request, is reviewing the
propriety of his trip with Fellows, a friend who invited the
Commissioner and his wife on the trip last weekend and paid for
their $700-a-night hotel suite in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Safir's spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, agreed that employing the
police officers could not be construed as a business relationship
between Revlon and the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the nexus at all,'' Ms. Mode said. Although
companies must apply and be approved to be part of the program, she
said, she did not think that any company had ever been rejected.
``We administer this as a courtesy to the officers and to maintain
the integrity,'' she said. ``We don't make money off of this. We
just cover our costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Davies, executive director of the Conflict of Interest
Board, which interprets the city's ethics code, said the city code
defines business dealings in a broad fashion. ``The board takes the
position that a business dealing is some pending matter,'' he said.
``It could be a contract with the city. It could be the sale or
exchange of services or a license or permit application.''
</P>
</TEXT>
