<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JESUS-BILLBOARDS-ECON     03-26 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-BILLBOARDS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD-FEARING MESSAGES ON THE HIGHWAY TO HEAVEN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Dallas, Florida _ and Religion Editors)   (This quirky 450-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 27 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general/religion news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Along the busiest street in downtown Dallas, opposite a
billboard reading ``Who's the Father? Call 1-800-DNA-TYPE,'' there
is a message from a father of a different sort, one without a
genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   The sign reads ``What part of `Thou Shalt Not' didn't you
understand? _ God.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the road, another billboard carries a second
message attributed to the Almighty: ``You think it's hot here?''
</P>
<P>
   Since last month, similar black billboards with stark white
lettering have sprung up in more than 100 places about the city,
generally along Dallas's busiest roads. Drivers stuck in rush-hour
traffic may think twice before cursing the heavens in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in south Florida last September, the ``God Speaks''
advertising campaign was at first financed by a wealthy individual
(insisting on anonymity) who believes the American ship has tossed
its moral compass overboard.
</P>
<P>
   According to Andy Smith, whose advertising agency created the
messages, ``Our society these days is a mess of murder, rape and
adultery. God gave us rules, and it is His rules we need to live
by.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs are meant to be a lighthearted way to get people to
think about God as the day rolls by.
</P>
<P>
   The response from Florida and Dallas has been so positive that
billboard companies around the country have agreed to donate
millions of dollars' worth of space.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference on March 16, the campaign's organizers
said their goal was to have 10,000 billboards in more than 200
American markets by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it may be that these messages from God are, as they say,
``preaching to the choir.'' According to Gallup, which tracks
worldwide trends in religious beliefs, the United States is among
the most devout nations of the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Gallup poll, 63 percent of Americans said they
believe that religion can solve the vast majority of today's social
problems, a percentage which has remained stable for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Over 70 percent of Americans are members of a church or
synagogue, and 40 percent attend regularly, compared with only 12
percent in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is a good thing, then, that the God Speaks campaign
will soon go international. Advertising agencies around the world
have expressed interest in bringing the billboards to other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, drivers in Europe, South America and Africa may be
starting their day with one-liners from the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of the campaign point out that the messages are
strictly non-denominational, and should have meaning to anyone who
believes in a Supreme Being. Among these people, at least, there is
at last hope for a worldwide decline in road rage. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can
also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 0224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
