<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     03-26 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' PLAYOFF HOPES GROW DIMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It was a night when the Kings desperately needed to
alter history and desperately needed to upend an unflappable
nemesis that calmly goes about its business.
</P>
<P>
   But some things obviously aren't meant to be for the Kings this
season. And some things don't seem meant to be for this team in any
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings almost definitely will not make the playoffs. And a
winless streak against the Dallas Stars _ which reached 17 games
with a 2-1 loss Thursday night before a Forum crowd of 14,888 _
seems as if it might never end.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for lack of effort Thursday, however, as the Kings
outshot the Stars 32-26 but dropped to an astonishing 0-11-6
against Dallas, dating back to since Barry Melrose was coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk out of a game like that and say, `What else could we
do?''' Kings coach Larry Robinson said following Thursday's loss,
which dropped his team eight points out of a playoff berth with 11
games remaining, eight on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held the best team in the league to a minimum amount of
chances, we hit posts, we had guys in front. We just didn't put the
puck in the net. But everybody, to a man, played their hearts out.
I don't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sean O'Donnell added: ``It's tough, but that's what's
tough about sports. We needed two points, we wanted two points, but
what else could we have done? It's better than being outshot 40-20.
At least the effort was there and we can look at ourselves in the
mirror afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably preferable to glancing at the standings, which
reveal that the Kings (27-39-5) fell eight points behind Calgary
for the final Western Conference playoff berth. The Flames defeated
Montreal on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are 0-5 against Dallas this season, all one-goal
losses, with one meeting remaining. The Stars (45-14-12) didn't
dominate and didn't outplay the Kings but displayed a composure
that explained as well as anything else why they will finish the
regular season with the best record in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings opened the game with a strong shift by the line of
Olli Jokinen, Craig Johnson and Donald Audette, a shift that set
the tone for how the Kings would play but also for the strong
effort by Dallas goalie Roman Turek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we came out and did exactly what we wanted to do,''
defenseman Garry Galley said. ``We wanted to play in their end and
get the puck deep in their end and get our forecheck going and get
some chances at the net, which we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all the scoring coming in the first two periods, the
Stars sandwiched goals by Benoit Hogue and Brett Hull around one by
Luc Robitaille for the victory. In the third period, the Kings
battled to tie the score, but a shot by Rob Blake hit the crossbar
and one by Sandy Moger hit the right post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't hit the post and go in,'' Robinson said. ``No, no. It
doesn't want to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson refused to concede that a playoff berth is impossible,
even with his team facing a difficult five-game trip that begins
Sunday at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do keep working hard, the results are going to come,''
he said. ``We can't have this much bad luck all year. At some
point, it's got to turn around for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the trip, he said: ``It's a lot easier going on a big
trip after a huge win. But there's nothing we can do about that. We
have to build on our momentum, and that momentum is we played a
strong game against a great team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
