<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4898 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARBURST-PUZZLE-SFCH     03-26 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARBURST-PUZZLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASTRONOMERS BAFFLED BY COSMIC MEGABLAST  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most brilliant and powerful cosmic explosion ever detected
by earthbound astronomers is puzzling scientists around the world,
and many believe its stupendous burst of energy was beamed toward
the Earth in a jet of radiation traveling at nearly the speed of
light.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary blast near the outer edges of the universe was
first detected by two scientific satellites January 23. Its flash
of light was so bright that even a pair of binoculars could have
picked it up faintly for a few fleeting moments, the astronomers
said.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, an automated telescope at Los Alamos, cobbled
together from recycled lenses and used camera components, captured
the first images of the explosion within 22 seconds after the
satellites picked up its signal and transmitted its location
instantaneously over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, both the Hubble space telescope and the giant
Keck instrument atop Mauna Kea in Hawaii were able to photograph
its brilliant afterglow as radiant debris from the blast faded
away.
</P>
<P>
   The blast event, called a gamma ray burster, occurred some 9
billion light-years away, which means that its huge energy took 9
billion years to reach Earth's neighborhood. It appeared to be some
6 million times brighter than a typical exploding star known as a
supernova, but just what caused it remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been a truly monstrous explosion marking the death
of an unusually huge giant star, or a collision between two neutron
stars, or perhaps a single neutron star that emitted tremendous
quantities of energy as the inexorable gravity of a single
super-dense black hole sucked it in. But at this point, such
explanations are only speculations at best, said Alexei Filippenko,
an astronomer at the University of California in Berkeley who has
analyzed many smaller such blasts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 gamma ray bursters have been reported since the
first one mystified the world's astronomers in 1967, when it was
detected by a fleet of American satellites called Vela Hotel, which
had been flying in orbit over the poles since 1963 to make sure the
Soviets were not conducting illegal secret treaty-busting nuclear
weapons tests in outer space.
</P>
<P>
   But the one detected in January, in the direction of the
well-known constellation Bootes, was by far the most powerful
burster of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It emitted a truly stupendous amount of energy _ millions of
times brighter than a supernova, '' Filippenko said. ``It was a
bright beacon near the edge of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion has already generated six scientific reports on
the event, and all were released Thursday by astronomy teams from
15 nations. Three of the reports are being published in the
American journal Science Friday, and three more will appear next
week in the British journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The principal team investigating the fireball event, now dubbed
GRB 990123, is led by Caltech astronomers Shrinivas Kulkarni and S.
George Djorgovski. Carl Akerlof, a physicist at the University of
Michigan, headed the group that captured the first images of the
blast with their improvised telescope at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burst appeared to be more luminous than the whole rest of
the universe, and that would be very hard to explain by most
current theories,'' Kulkarni said Thursday. And if the explosion
spewed its gamma rays out in all directions, Djorgovski added,
``their energy would correspond to 10,000 times the energy emitted
by our sun over its entire lifetime so far.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a commentary on the discovery that will appear next week
in the journal Nature, astrophysicist Peter Meszaros of
Pennsylvania State University said there is ``reasonable evidence''
that the explosion had beamed its energy only in Earth's direction,
which would mean that the blast was less powerful than the Caltech
scientists estimated _ although it was still most probably stronger
than any cosmic event yet known since the Big Bang gave birth to
the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Djorgovski, however, insisted in an interview that there is no
real evidence yet for any ``beaming'' of the explosion's energy,
nor for a beam from the quickly dying but still brilliant afterglow
melange of gamma rays, X-rays and radio waves that followed the
first blast.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliance of the afterglow, he said, might possibly have
been boosted in all directions by a jet of incandescent gases
thrusting outward from the blast at nearly the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any event,'' he said, ``we have no theory to account for
it, but if we don't know how it's done, then it's obvious that
nature does know how because our telescopes saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only last May that a similar brilliant gamma ray burster
was detected by instruments aboard the same two satellites that
found the January one, and the May event was considered the most
powerful burst ever detected.
</P>
<P>
   This one was even stronger, and the Italian-Dutch satellite
called BeppoSax located its first burst, while America's orbiting
Compton Gamma-Ray Observatory caught caught the radiation at almost
the same time. The two satellites pinpointed the blast's direction
and relayed their signals instantly via the Internet to the
automated telescope at Los Alamos. That instrument then swivelled
its optics without a human hand to guide it and locked onto the
light of the explosion within 10 seconds, just as the blast's
brilliance was peaking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
