 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2530 - March 26, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2530 -- March 26, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. PRUDENCE MURDOCH MacLEOD INTERVIEW A lifetime of having
refused publicity probably explains the frankness with which Rupert
Murdoch's eldest child, Prudence, now talks about herself, her life
and the family business in this interview. By Penelope Debelle.
From The Melbourne Age. (N/A Australia and U.K.) 4,500 words +
photos. ________________________________________________________ 2.
WHY BOMB THE SERBS? WHY NOT? To win over the public, Clinton is
trying to turn three issues upside down. By William Saletan. From
Slate online magazine. 900 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
NATO IS SETTING A PRECEDENT IN KOSOVO Talking about Kosovo, an
unnamed foreign policy adviser to Clinton pointed out, ``There are
massive bloodbaths all over the world and we're not intervening in
them ... (But) this one's in the heart of Europe.'' By Flora Lewis.
1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
KICKERS WITHOUT CARTILAGE : SOCCER'S WALKING WOUNDED The legions of
soccer invalids -- soccer players who have suffered career-ending
injuries -- are growing rapidly. Profit-oriented teams are under
intense pressure to keep their good players, regardless of their
injuries. Team doctors are encouraged to do whatever they can to
keep injured players on the field, even at the risk of longer-term
injury and if they do not, the doctors are fired. Making matters
worse, the number of matches played each year seems to be
constantly rising. By Veronika Hackenbroch. From Der Spiegel. 1,000
words. (English translation available.) 5. FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES
SCIENCE TIMES :
</P>
<P>
   A. LIVING WITH LOSS THAT IS UNRESOLVED Researchers are now
exploring the concept they call ambiguous loss, in which a ``lost''
person is still physically present but emotionally absent or a lost
person is physically absent but still emotionally present.
Research, outlined in a new book, contends that in such
circumstances it is often very difficult for people to resolve
their grief and get on with their lives. By Jane E. Brody. 1,500
words.
</P>
<P>
   B. FOLLOW-UP CONFIRMS THE BENEFITS OF A DIET A generation ago,
researchers examined the relationship between diet and heart
disease rates and found that people who lived along the
Mediterranean suffered only a tiny fraction of the heart attacks
and coronary deaths experienced by people in other Western
industrialized countries. The latest study is a four-year follow-up
of more than 400 men and women in France. By Jane E. Brody. 1,300
words + graphic.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
SPECIAL REPORT : CZECHS, POLES, TEN YEARS ON Poland and the Czech
Republic were isolated for 40 years by communism and have been
separated since 1989 by old stereotypes. They may only come to
regard each other as equals when they are both safely inside the
E.U. By Tim Snyder. Prospect magazine. 2,000 words. (N/A U.K.)
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   A. HUE AND CRY : If you thought colour perception was universal,
think again. The language you speak may affect the way you describe
colours. By Alison Motluk. 500 words. B. NOT A SOUND IDEA :
Attempts to build weapons that incapacitate people by harnessing
the power of very low-frequency sound waves are destined to fail,
says a German physicist. By Jeff Hecht. 350 words. C. THE HEART
THAT JUST WON'T DIE : You can give it a heart attack then make it
better, pump it full of drugs - and still it comes back for more.
By Mark Buchanan. 2,500 words. D. STATES OF MIND : Learning a task
takes far more brain power than repeating it once it's become a
habit. Could the difference show us where consciousness lies? By
John McCrone. 1,500 words. E. TEN, NINE, EIGHT ... YOU'RE UNDER :
Surgeons have been knocking patients out with general anaesthesia
for 150 years, but no-one actually knows how it works.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
SPACE : BLASTS FROM BEYOND The biggest bang since the Big Bang
itself has sparked a frenzy of space research across the globe as
astronomers reap a rich harvest of information on one of science's
most mysterious secrets -- the nature of the elusive phenomena
called 'gamma-ray bursts.' By Henry Gee. From Nature News Service.
1,000 words. (N/A France and Spain.) Embargo 20h00 GMT Thursday
March 25.
