<HEADER>
A5020 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-RIVER-NYTSF     03-26 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-RIVER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE RIVER MIDNIGHT
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Lilian Nattel.
</P>
<P>
   414 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Scribner. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE WILD ONES
</P>
<P>
   BY ROY HOFFMAN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AS enchanting at times as a Chagall mural, at others as
overdrawn as an old Yiddish melodrama, ``The River Midnight''
conjures up Blaszka, a fictional Polish shtetl of the 1890's, and
the interwoven stories of four of its women. In their youth, they
were known as the vilda hayas, ``the wild creatures.'' Now
approaching middle age, they still confound their village -- and
especially their men -- with a little craziness.
</P>
<P>
   Childless Hanna-Leah, long married to the hapless butcher,
Hershel, is tempted early in the novel by a ghostly refugee she
meets in the woods, a self-described ``traveler'' fleeing the
draft. Her best friend, Faygela, has traded her hopes for a bookish
life to marry well-meaning Shmuel, the baker, and bear him six
children. But after going to Warsaw to care for an ailing relative,
Faygela is inspired by the city's intellectual life and returns
home to publish stories about the shtetl sisterhood. ``A real
writer tells the truth,'' she declares, dismissing a man who churns
out popular Yiddish romances, ``and that's how he changes the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   A fondly remembered friend, Zisa-Sara, has died with her husband
in a garment factory fire in New York, but her daughter, Emma,
returns to the village, radicalized by this tragedy. Coming of age
in Blaszka, she strikes up a friendship with Faygela's oldest
daughter, Ruthie.
</P>
<P>
   The most engaging of the vilda hayas, Misha, the midwife, is
defiantly nobody's wife. She is divorced from Hayim, the water
carrier, and is now expecting a child, fathered either by the
lovelorn rabbi, Berekh, or by the violently drunken peddler,
Yarush.
</P>
<P>
   Dynamic women, feckless men -- this fin de sicle novel often
sounds as if it were set in the 1990's, not the 1890's: '' 'I'm
going to be independent like Misha was before she got herself into
trouble. And who brought her down?' Ruthie asked agitatedly.
'Nobody knows for sure, but it wasn't an angel, I can tell you. It
was some man.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lilian Nattel, the Montreal-born daughter of emigres from
Poland, says in an author's note that her family's stories,
bolstered by her own research, formed the basis for the novel. She
even provides a welcome bibliography for further reading. Not
surprisingly, ``The River Midnight'' has the ring of authenticity,
from its vibrant depiction of the shtetl to its elaboration of
Misha's role as midwife. But, unfortunately, persuasive fiction
does not live by authenticity alone.
</P>
<P>
   NATTEL writes with refreshing bawdiness about the vilda hayas,
but she shies away from delving into the complex relationship
between Emma and Ruthie, veiling its eroticism in somewhat tangled
language: ``Ruthie laughed and Emma wasn't quite sure if she fell
accidentally or on purpose, pulling Emma with her, but soon the
girls were drenched, braids undone, their shifts transparent, water
dripping like a fountain from their chins, and when Ruthie drank
from Emma's fountain, she had to laugh and scream and push Ruthie
away, her hands tingling strangely where they had touched Ruthie's
chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Although her characters are meant to be speaking Yiddish,
Nattel's dialogue includes little that is distinctive, rhythmically
or syntactically. Instead, it favors the generic vernacular of too
many historical novels; while informative, it lacks the true flavor
of a particular place. Because Nattel often uses imagery to lush
effect -- invoking, say, ``the fruity perfume of summer darkness''
-- it is especially disappointing that she also leans on cliches. A
jerry-built sentence, a leached metaphor, an overwrought gesture --
to point out such flaws in light of Nattel's larger accomplishment
may seem like quibbling, but their effect is to yank the reader out
of the fictional dream.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, perhaps through Nattel's sheer love for these
characters, that dream holds on. As an artist, she is like Hayim,
who is scolded by his adoptive father, Asher: ``I'm telling you
plain, everything is God. Are you looking, Hayim? Are you using
your eyes? The Baal Shem Tov, of blessed memory, spent days in the
fields and the woods, and there he saw the Holy One arising from
every living thing and also the stones.''
</P>
<P>
   When Asher goes blind, Hayim dutifully tells him about his daily
rounds: ``Do you think, Hayim asked hesitantly, I saw the Holy
Presence? 'Don't stop looking, Hayim,' Asher said.''
</P>
<P>
   With fervor, and intermittent moments of revelation, Hayim
persists. And so does Lilian Nattel.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Roy Hoffman is writer in residence at The Mobile (Ala.)
Register.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
