<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5021 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CITY-NYTSF     03-26 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SINGING THE CITY
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bonds of Home in an Industrial Landscape.
</P>
<P>
   By Laurie Graham.
</P>
<P>
   University of Pittsburgh Press. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; STEELER
</P>
<P>
   BY HOLLY BRUBACH
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The particular landscape that serves as the backdrop for our
childhood -- the topography, the buildings, the trees, the light --
imprints itself forever on our memory: it is the norm with which we
will compare every landscape we encounter for the rest of our
lives. Laurie Graham goes so far as to contend that a landscape can
work its way into our DNA. Hence, she claims in ``Singing the
City,'' her sense of coming home when she moved to Pittsburgh,
where previous generations of her family had lived -- though she
herself had grown up in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   With the death of her husband in 1989 when she was not quite 50,
Graham vowed to make a fresh start. Leaving New York and her job as
an editor at Scribner, she moved to Pittsburgh, where she fell in
love -- first with the industrial culture that she found there and
soon after with a former steelworker. Her chronicle of the early,
halting stages of their courtship is intertwined with an account of
the demise of Big Steel and its profound effect on the lives of
people for whom the mills provided the foundations of community.
Graham is evenhanded in distributing the blame. The devastation,
she argues, is not only economic but moral, and it extends to other
American cities -- Buffalo, Youngstown, Cleveland, Baltimore,
Chicago -- that are likewise faced with the decline of heavy
industry.
</P>
<P>
   This book is perhaps best appreciated in the context of two
others about Pittsburgh: ``An American Childhood,'' Annie Dillard's
superb memoir of her early years in Squirrel Hill, a prosperous
neighborhood within the city limits, and ``American Elegy,''
Jeffrey Simpson's eloquent investigation into his family's life in
Parnassus, a small town in Pittsburgh's shadow. Both Dillard and
Simpson chronicle the peculiarities of the relentless Calvinism
that held sway among descendants of the city's early settlers,
Scotch-Irish immigrants who established a Presbyterian stronghold
and emerged as the ruling class. Graham rounds out the picture by
delineating the work ethic of the city's minorities, mostly Eastern
European and Roman Catholic. While Dillard's and Simpson's
reminiscences are rooted in the sediment of personal memory,
Graham's portrayal relies for its depth on other people's
recollections.
</P>
<P>
   As a newcomer to the city, she interviews longtime residents of
neighborhoods like Polish Hill and Homestead, in which the bonds of
church and family are inextricably tied to the virtues of manual
labor. ``Blue-collar people think that if you don't want to work
you get a desk job,'' Graham's new husband, Bob, explains. She
champions those who have stayed where they were born and
perpetuated the values they inherited, among them Sharon Wolkiewicz
and her mother, Helen. ``Helen says she is 'embedded here,' ''
Graham reports. Sharon asks, ``How could you just move away and
call another place home?''
</P>
<P>
   Graham introduces the reader to Diane Novosel, the granddaughter
of Croatian and Romanian immigrants, who ``dropped out'' in her
early 20's; she ``tried popular culture and it wasn't enough.''
Novosel is now the head of the Society for the Preservation of the
Murals of St. Nicholas, a church in Millvale whose interior is
painted with scenes that conflate peasant life in rural Croatia,
Bible stories and the Homestead strike of 1892, coming to the
rescue of a local past that many natives -- myself included -- have
taken for granted if not dismissed altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh I grew up in -- a Pittsburgh that predates
Graham's arrival by some 30 years -- was the proud capital of vast
business empires, the headquarters for United States Steel, Alcoa,
Westinghouse, Gulf Oil and Pittsburgh Plate Glass. All its
prominent features -- the smokestacks, the skyscrapers and trestle
bridges, the highways cut into the rock face, the strip-mined
cliffs, the row houses that climb the mountainsides like stairs --
attested to hard work. The peculiar gray cast of the light served
only to intensify the lingering impression of dinginess,
attributable not to neglect but to the climate of diligence and
moral austerity.
</P>
<P>
   Beauty resided elsewhere -- in Ligonier's rolling countryside 50
miles to the east or in New York's glittering skyline or in
pastoral France, which had supplied the raw material for
masterpieces by Monet and Cezanne. Pittsburgh had been immortalized
by its own painter, John Kane, and as a young art student I
remember thinking what a shame it was that he had squandered his
obvious talents on a place where there was nothing to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past 20 years, in Pittsburgh and elsewhere, train
stations have been converted to shopping malls and factories to
residential lofts. The industrial esthetic now reigns supreme in
everything from museum architecture to bathroom fixtures;
Pittsburgh's brand of beauty, resplendent in things whose forms
have been entirely dictated by their functions, has come into its
own -- just as those things are being rendered obsolete. On
occasion, Graham's appreciation for Pittsburgh's history is
subsumed by acute nostalgia for a time before the layoffs and the
closings, when the ``bonds of home'' referred to in the subtitle
were still intact.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to go backward, rowing against the currents of
change, the longing for an enclave in which the old order still
prevails, seem benign enough until this tribute to manual labor
strays into the realm of men's supremacy and their entitlement.
Graham quotes the ``poet and steelworker'' Tim Russell: ``There is
something great about sitting in an easy chair, next to your father
in his easy chair, eating a plate of food, watching a bowl game on
TV. It isn't the food or the game that matters but the extreme bond
of family. . . . Men are in front of the firelight of the TV, women
are in the kitchen comparing notes about kids. It's a good thing
knowing you have that place.'' I guess it must be. I wouldn't know.
I was washing the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer physicality of the labor that Graham extols culminates
in the image of surging molten steel as a metaphor for sexual
potency. Indeed, ``Singing the City'' is a veritable anthem to
virility. The Pittsburgh it portrays is a mythic town, the furnace
of the gods stoked by plain-spoken blue-collar guys with good
hearts. The furnace is cold now, the guys at a loss. To cure what
ails us, Graham would rekindle those fires.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Holly Brubach's new book, ``Girlfriend: Men, Women and Drag,''
will be published next month.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
