<HEADER>
A5022 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SURVIVAL-NYTS     03-26 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SURVIVAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SURVIVAL RATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; IT'S NO FUN BEING NORMAL
</P>
<P>
   BY KAREN KARBO
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALL nine of the potent stories in ``Survival Rates'' share a
setting: the desert Southwest and parts of California so far south
that the freeway signs announce the approach of the Mexican border.
The desert, as Mary Clyde well knows, looks vast and boring, but
it's an unpredictable and perilous place, alive with bats,
thunderstorms, alien-looking cactuses, ornery wild pigs that can
eat a sapling straight down to the ground. Clyde's characters are
similarly deceptive. Ordinary folk, the calm center of other
people's storms, they are the staid citizens of melodramatic times,
for whom doing the right thing is a foregone conclusion, even
though they ache for behavior splashy enough to make their lives
seem worthwhile. Clyde's singular world is one where candor is
dangerous but reticence is a curse, and being called decent is
almost an insult.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pruitt Love,'' Neil Pruitt frets because he imagines he is
too sedate for his girlfriend's frenetic and determinedly zany
family. ``They wreck cars. They turn over furniture. They throw
whatever's in their hands: books -- I've seen a biography of Samuel
Johnson knock six lit candles out of a candelabra.'' Neil comes
from a family of worriers ``orderly as the alphabet, befuddled by
clock radios and answering machines.'' In one hilariously horrific
scene, he tries to live up to his girlfriend's family's
expectations by trotting out the only bit of his history that's
remotely exotic: his mother was killed. Unfortunately, the cause
was an exploding hot-water heater. ``He saw disappointment slip
from their eyes, coming to rest at the corners of their mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the inestimable Lorrie Moore, whose work ``Survival Rates''
resembles, Clyde, winner of the Flannery O'Connor Award for Short
Fiction, has an exquisite sense of humor: sly, heart-battering and
a little tetchy. In ``Howard Johnson's House,'' Cecil, a wealthy
Phoenix plastic surgeon, gives a young girl whose ugly nose (``like
a golf club -- a 1-wood'') was bitten off by a dog a pretty new
one, and is sued by her jealous mother for the improvement.
</P>
<P>
   In the title story, Wilson, a landscape architect, feels vaguely
ashamed for contracting a lowly, inferior form of cancer instead of
something more theatrical that would better satisfy the emotional
needs of his pessimistic wife. ``Dr. Rodgers, insisting that
cancers have personalities, has told them thyroid cancer lacks any
real oncological ambition. He's called it shiftless, an
embarrassment to the whole cancer community.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the stories here are all strong, a few are splendid.
``Krista Had a Treble Clef Rose'' deserves a place in the pantheon
of harrowing stories about seriously ill children, alongside ``A
Small, Good Thing,'' by Raymond Carver, and ``People Like That Are
the Only People Here,'' by Lorrie Moore. Clyde has chosen the
tritest setting imaginable, a mall, where two seemingly average
teen-age girls -- narcissistic and misguided -- are making the
rounds of cosmetics counters and ear-piercing shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicole says, 'The anesthesia made my hair fall out. I've got
three hairs left. I'm playing up my eyes.' ``Quickly we realize
that Anne and Nicole are hardly average; they are survivors of
colon cancer, and know more than any child should about restricted
diets (no more popcorn, ever), ostomy bags -- Nicole wore clear
bags. Anne wore flesh-colored bags. She said she thought they were
more feminine'' -- and the adaptive gallows humor of the ravaged.
The power of the story is unshakable: by the end, we're desperate
for them to be run-of-the-mill, insufferable teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde's writing has many strengths, but the greatest one is her
ability to transform a shallow experience into something resembling
hope. That she does so with intelligence and wit makes this
collection as good as they get.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Karen Karbo is the author of two novels. Her latest nonfiction
book, ``Notes From Ex Isle,'' will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
