<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MORGAN-1000&AMP;A     03-26 1969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MORGAN-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MORGAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Financier.
</P>
<P>
   By Jean Strouse.
</P>
<P>
   Random House. $34.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; FIRST MASTER OF THE UNIVERSE
</P>
<P>
   BY RICHARD LINGEMAN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After reading Jean Strouse's voluminous biography of J. Pierpont
Morgan, with its thoroughgoing accounts of his business ventures in
the crucible stage of American capitalism, the era between the
Civil War and World War I, one is left with a multitude of rounded
impressions of this powerful but enigmatic figure. There is the
great consolidator of wastefully competing railroad lines and
industries, the ``apostle of order,''who believed, as the business
historian Edward Kirkland wrote, that ``the incalculable must give
way to the rational, strife to cooperation.'' Then there is the
consummate international financier, organizing syndicates to float
immense bond and stock issues that gave birth to companies like
A.T.&AMP; T., General Electric and United States Steel. And the
prodigious collector who spent some $60 million (approximately $900
million in today's dollars) on paintings, sculptures, rare books
and manuscripts and all manner of precious objets d'art. And the
benefactor of St. George's Episcopal Church (where he had a radical
minister installed), New York Lying-In Hospital (which he
reportedly subsidized to care for pregnant mistresses -- Strouse
scoffs at this rumor), the Metropolitan Museum of Art (to which he
did not leave his fabulous collection because the museum failed to
authorize a special wing for it in his lifetime), Harvard Law
School and the Morgan Library.
</P>
<P>
   Strouse's solidly researched biography draws, she informs us, on
an enormous archive of Morganalia that previous biographers hadn't
the temerity to crack. She debunks many of the errors propagated by
both hagiographers and muckrakers and elucidates in ample detail
Morgan's financial maneuverings (readers without an interest in
business and financial history may find some of this material
wearisome). The House of Morgan erected the financial
superstructure of the most prominent American industries in the
Gilded Age, beginning with the railroads. In the press Morgan was
garlanded with grandiose sobriquets -- the field marshal of
industry,'' the ``financial Moses of the New World,'' the
``railroad Bismarck.'' But to populists and radicals who spoke for
the struggling farmers in the West and the South, and to the
laboring men and women in factories and sweatshops, he was the
``great Financial Gorgon'' who personified the oppressive power of
Wall Street that would crucify mankind on a cross of gold.
</P>
<P>
   That image was serendipitously caught in a photograph by Edward
Steichen in which the financier, asked to change his position,
glares at the camera with intense ferocity, ``As his body
disappears in the blackness,'' Strouse writes, ``the light catches
only his head, the watch chain, and his hand on the gleaming metal
arm of his chair: this last detail looks like the blade of a
dagger, and Morgan appears about to stride out of the frame
slashing -- the ruthless capitalist pirate of popular myth.'' Not
entirely mythical in my view.
</P>
<P>
   Steichen's portrait conveys an idea of the smoldering power of
the man -- an imperious, domineering figure in richly cut clothes,
with massive body and Jovian head, baleful eyes and a chronically
diseased nose, like some purplish fleshy fungus. He was blessed
with considerable physical stamina; he lived to the age of 75, and
despite his sybaritic life style he rode his younger partners into
the ground -- and sometimes under it. He imperiously ordered bank
presidents to do what he thought was necessary to quell a financial
panic, and they usually fell in line like reluctant schoolboys.
</P>
<P>
   During the financial panic of 1907, when the nation's chronic
gold shortage triggered a run on the undercapitalized trust banks,
Morgan took charge. The challenge was to prop up the trust banks
before they toppled like a row of dominoes. To this end, he
assembled the leading bank presidents in his library and at some
point locked the door. At 4 A.M. his lawyer read them an agreement
stipulating how much each must pledge to the bailout package.
Morgan laid it on his desk and told Edward King of the Union Trust:
``There's the place, King, and here's the pen.'' King signed, as
did the others.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan transacted great schemes from Olympian heights. When he
decided to buy the Carnegie Steel company on the way to forming
United States Steel -- in 1901 the largest corporation in the world
-- he told Andrew Carnegie to name his price. Carnegie wrote down
$480 million on a single sheet of paper. Morgan glanced at the
paper and said, ``I accept this price.'' ``Pierpont Morgan is
apparently trying to swallow the sun,'' marveled Henry Adams.
</P>
<P>
   What really drove him, psychologically, Strouse can only infer
from the testimony of others. Morgan's was a secretive personality,
partly out of shyness, though he was not shy about taking credit
for saving the country on several occasions. He had the banker's
traditional reticence, part of the mystique of the priesthood.
Once, under grilling by a Congressional committee, he was asked why
he had become involved in the purchase of the Equitable Life
Assurance Society, in which the House of Morgan acquired securities
yielding only one-eighth of 1 percent. ``For the very reason that I
thought it was the thing to do,'' Morgan said, and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was an inarticulate man with no interest in explanations
or introspection. Strouse comments: ``His authority -- in his
office, over railroads, in the world's capital markets -- came not
from what he said but from what he did.'' He took responsibility
but demanded complete authority. He insulated himself from people
who thought differently and was deaf to the agrarian protest
movements that flared up during the 1880's and 1900's.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Morgan's traits are strongly reminiscent of those the
sociologist David Riesman ascribed to the inner-directed character,
who is guided by an internal compass and a strong superego. The
chief influence on him was undoubtedly his father, Junius S.
Morgan, head of J. S. Morgan &AMP; Company in London. Morgan pre
groomed Pierpont from boyhood to take over the business. He
tirelessly drilled home the lesson that a banker's most important
business asset among his peers was ``character'' -- a reputation
for honesty and square dealing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-MORGAN-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: square dealing.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pierpont never ceased to honor his father, Strouse makes clear.
One wonders if a chronic fear of failing to live up to paternal
demands could account for the fits of depression he was subject to
throughout his life. In the throes of melancholia, he would moan
that ``the best thing would be for me to give up myself -- I don't
feel good for much anyway.'' In addition, he had been sickly as a
child, suffering mysterious ailments that gave him ``a
hypochondriacal sense of frailty all his life.'' Strouse theorizes
that the reason he never had his disfigured nose -- the result of a
skin disease called rhinophyma -- surgically modified was that he
harbored an obscure fear that if he did so he would somehow be
subject to the seizures he had experienced in childhood. The many
women in his life didn't seem put off by it, though his money
surely helped ease their qualms. He was married twice. His first
wife died young; his second wife, Fanny, bore him four children,
including the heir apparent, J. P. Morgan Jr. But Pierpont tired of
her and sought consolation elsewhere, as was the way of men of his
class. Strouse focuses on only two main mistresses, women of
sophistication and means, while admitting he was an ``indefatigable
Don Juan.'' His librarian, the spunky Belle Greene (one of the
livelier characters in a book populated by bankers; of
African-American parentage, she passed as white and presided over
his library), complained that ``every woman who comes within a mile
of J. P. immediately loses her head. . . . They flock to him all
day long in rapid and sickening succession. Each one pluming her
feathers and thinking she is the hen pheasant, when in reality she
is forgotten before her successor appears.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was also a voracious collector of art, statues, rare
books and manuscripts. Strouse quotes the French critic Jean
Baudrillard, who wrote of the kind of collector who wishes to
``stand alone surrounded by exquisite objects like the 'sultan of a
secret seraglio.' ``Morgan's artistic and financial drives may have
been rooted in the same sexual dynamic, like Theodore Dreiser's
fictional hero Frank Cowperwood in ``The Financier.''
</P>
<P>
   If the mysteries of Morgan's inner psyche remain dark, Strouse
has clarified the public career and swept away some of the mud
slung at him by previous biographers who drew their information
from hostile contemporaries. The cool dispassion of her elegantly
modulated prose, the evenhandedness of her sources, tends to muffle
the hostile, populist roar against Morgan. Yet she does not seek to
exculpate her subject; in the end the moral she seems to draw from
his career is that ``the country's economic welfare could no longer
be left to private bankers. . . . Morgan's extraordinary authority
endangered the public welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's marriage and his personal religion, which assured him
that Christ had obligingly atoned for his sins, provided a sanction
that left him feeling ``perfectly justified in whatever he chose to
do'' in his private life, as one descendant of a Morgan intimate
tells Strouse; similarly, the prevailing social Darwinian ethos
justified his belief that whatever was good for Pierpont Morgan was
good for the country. When he intervened to damp down a financial
panic, it was always in the higher interest of economic stability
and saving the jobs of millions. But his enemies charged him with
manipulating the market for his own ends; even Teddy Roosevelt
blamed the ``malefactors of great wealth'' for the panic of 1907.
</P>
<P>
   Strouse shows that this, like many of the charges flung at
Morgan in the heat of controversy, was overstated, though it was
not entirely untrue either. Morgan's fingers were constantly in the
financial pie. She amends the record to show that Morgan's
syndicate, which handled the 1895 bond issue that brought European
gold flowing back into the Treasury's near-empty coffers, collected
nowhere near the $5 to $18 million in fees that the press reported.
But the point that should be stressed is not so much the inaccuracy
of the figure; it is that the financial rescue package Morgan
devised was totally in the service of his financial interest in
tight money policies. That is, the rescue profited the House of
Morgan and the foreign investors it serviced. During the gold
crisis, he telegraphed colleagues who had gone to Washington ahead
of him: ``We consider situation critical, politicians appear to
have absolute control.'' He meant Congress, which favored easing
the money supply and selling bonds in a public offering. To Morgan,
the representatives of the people were annoying obstacles, and the
interests of the financial class ranked far above those of the mass
of working people. When Morgan died, there was no one to replace
him; his time had passed. The United States went off the gold
standard and the Federal Reserve took control of the money supply.
But although control in Wall Street is more diffuse, the interests
of the financial class Morgan so assiduously served remain
paramount today.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lingeman, a senior editor of The Nation, is the author
of ``Theodore Dreiser: An American Journey,'' and is writing a
biography of Sinclair Lewis.
</P>
</TEXT>
