<HEADER>
A5025 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TRUMPETS-NYTS     03-26 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TRUMPETS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE SOUND OF TRUMPETS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By John Mortimer.
</P>
<P>
   273 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Viking. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; TANTANTARA!
</P>
<P>
   BY ALISON LURIE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IT is not unusual for a well-known author to write a series of
novels in which the hero is a version of himself, with a few
essential characteristics altered. Philip Roth has chronicled the
lives of several alter egos. John Updike's Rabbit Angstrom has the
life Updike might have had with a much lower I.Q.; Henry Bech has
the life Updike might have had if he were Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   In England, the best-known practitioner of this genre is John
Mortimer. His many successful crime novels feature a barrister
called Horace Rumpole who, like Mortimer, is large and brilliant
and well trained in the law, but lacks Mortimer's literary
sophistication and strong will. And in the Rapstone Chronicles, of
which ``The Sound of Trumpets'' is the third and last volume, the
dominant character, Leslie Titmuss, is a kind of antiself. He has
Mortimer's shrewd intelligence and subtle understanding of English
society; but unlike Mortimer, who is a genial and relatively modest
Labor voter of upper-class origins and education, Titmuss is a
cold, dangerously ambitious Tory politician born into poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The two earlier novels in the series, ``Paradise Postponed'' and
``Titmuss Regained,'' chronicled Leslie Titmuss's rise from
obscurity to prominence in the Thatcher Government. He is now
retired and a member of the House of Lords. But back home at
Rapstone Manor, Lord Titmuss is still a powerful and even a
sinister figure. When the local M.P. is found dead in a swimming
pool, Titmuss seizes his chance to influence the coming
by-election. He despises the new Tory candidate and begins secretly
to work against him.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor candidate, Terry Flitton, the hero of this novel, is a
likable, ambitious young man, somewhat navely committed to liberal
causes. Lord Titmuss sees him as a younger version of himself: an
ambitious working-class boy who will advance ``the great cause to
which he had devoted his youth, getting up the noses of the
toffs.'' At first, Terry resists Titmuss's advice. But gradually he
starts to listen, excusing the lies he begins to tell as necessary
means to a noble end -- his election.
</P>
<P>
   Terry has a beautiful young wife named Kate, who believes in him
absolutely. She is also a New Age Puritan who believes that eating
meat is disgusting and that sex is too serious for jokes. It is not
long before Terry falls passionately in love with an older woman,
Agnes Simcox, who runs a local bookstore. When he is with her, it
is ``as though he had been given a glimpse of another country,
unexpected, extraordinary, anarchic and sometimes beautiful.''
Agnes is also an idealistic liberal, but she is far more tolerant
and knows a lot more about love than Kate.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to balance love and politics lands Terry in some wildly
comic situations. In order to please Agnes, he goes riding with
her, though he has only been on a horse once in his life. He is
given an animal called Balaclava, who has ``a mad appearance, with
a rolling eye and strong yellow teeth exposed in a sneer.'' On
their second outing, they run into a local fox hunt and Terry's
horse bolts, joining the chase. As a result, Terry, who has been
trying to avoid taking a position on the issue, earns the hatred of
animal liberationists and the support of local hunters.
</P>
<P>
   John Mortimer has always been a subtle observer of the ironies
of the British class system. ``The Sound of Trumpets'' has a
Dickensian range, and it is full of characters with Dickensian
names, from the skilled teen-age burglar, Slippy, to the
domineering -- almost dominatrix -- Home Secretary, Hannah
Mortlock, who finally determines Terry's political career. Some of
these characters have appeared in earlier volumes of the Rapstone
Chronicles, but it is not necessary to have read those novels to
enjoy this one.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mortimer is a lifelong Labor supporter, in many ways
``The Sound of Trumpets'' suggests the work of right-wing authors
like Evelyn Waugh and Kingsley Amis. Like them, Mortimer admires
practical know-how, irony and detachment. He looks with tolerance
on smoking, hunting and established religion. He loves the
countryside and hates developers and strip malls. Politically,
Mortimer seems to disapprove equally of Mrs. Thatcher and of both
her successors. He ridicules vegetarianism, atheism, astrology and
the animal rights movement. He describes the hunt saboteurs, for
instance, as ``sometimes leaving their vans to shout 'Murderers!'
at the girls from the pony club or, more daringly, to stub out
their cigarettes on the rumps of horses who had, presumably,
defected from the animal world and gone over to the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sound of Trumpets'' is a wonderful comic novel, but
underneath its humor runs a black shadow of pessimism. Politics, it
proposes, is always a dirty business. Power belongs to
Machiavellian plotters or to pushy pragmatists. Terry Flitton's
belief in liberal causes and his romantic passion are both in
conflict with his wish for power. When he is accused of being soft
on crime, and victory seems to be slipping away, he follows Lord
Titmuss's advice and attacks Agnes's best friend, a kindly gay man
who runs the local home for delinquent boys. Terry wins the
election, but loses Agnes's love.
</P>
<P>
   American readers will recognize Terry Flitton as a type common
on this side of the Atlantic as well. Indeed, his combination of
attractive rhetoric, increasingly compromised ideals and sexual
indiscretion is perhaps even more familiar here. Readers will also
recognize Lord Titmuss. Like all successful political villains, he
is fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Titmuss manipulates everyone around him, just as an author
manipulates his characters. Like Mortimer, Titmuss has always
chosen his opponents shrewdly and defeated them successfully. Now,
though, as we learn in the last chapter, he has a more powerful
enemy: death. Titmuss faces it alone, silently and stoically,
``looking, not for the first time, towards a conclusion that even
he would find it difficult to outmaneuver.'' At this final moment,
after following his antiself through three fine novels, John
Mortimer seems to sympathize with, almost to admire, his most
remarkable creation.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Alison Lurie's most recent novel is ``The Last Resort.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
