<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BARNYARD-NYTS     03-26 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BARNYARD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 LORD OF THE BARNYARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Tristan Egolf.
</P>
<P>
   410 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Grove Press. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; DOWN ON THE FARM
</P>
<P>
   BY LAURA MILLER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT a rough beast is Tristan Egolf's first novel, a book that's
both interesting and exciting without quite managing to be good. It
comes accompanied by a mediagenic history: the 27-year-old American
author, something of an autodidact, collected over 50 rejection
slips from publishers here before being befriended by the daughter
of the French novelist Patrick Modiano. She found him busking on
the streets of Paris and introduced his manuscript to her father.
And, sure enough, ``Lord of the Barnyard: Killing the Fatted Calf
and Arming the Aware in the Corn Belt'' is exactly the sort of
fauvist extravaganza Europeans welcome as quintessentially
American: brash, vigorous, violent and crude.
</P>
<P>
   The novel tells the story of John Kaltenbrunner, the only son of
a much-admired East Kentucky coal mine overseer killed in a methane
gas explosion three months before John's birth. An agricultural
prodigy, young John whips the family's neglected farm into shape
almost before he's out of short pants. However, his antisocial,
single-minded devotion to poultry husbandry and sheep raising
alarms his mother, provokes his classmates and causes him to
neglect his schoolwork, drawing the ire of the high school
principal. The irritated parties join forces with a tornado and a
gang of scheming church ladies referred to as the ``Methodist
crones'' to ruin John's farm and visit upon him ``an inconceivably
bad losing streak.'' He winds up stripped of his patrimony and
sentenced to three years' work release on a river barge.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets out, John returns to Baker, the Godforsaken town
that has done him so much wrong, with vague intentions of settling
the score. After stints at the nightmarish Sodderbrook poultry
plant, a convenience store and various other scut jobs, where his
preternatural competence is equaled only by his bad attitude, John
goes to work as a garbage collector for the local landfill. There,
among the despised ``hill scrubs'' who haul the community's refuse,
he finds the ideal opportunity in a crew of downtrodden but eager
followers. He organizes a garbage strike that precipitates a
municipal crisis culminating in a devastating riot during a
basketball playoff against a rival town. Afterward, local rumor
remembers him as ``the freak on the tractor, the corncrib fascist,
the troglodytic goatroper from just north of the river -- the one
who rarely spoke a word to anyone but who, nevertheless,
unfailingly succeeded in alienating, revolting and terrifying just
about every living being he came in contact with.'' His outraged
comrades resolve to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out with a scenario that promises so much --
retribution, fate, history, class warfare and a malevolent sense of
place -- Egolf, unfortunately, mostly just goes around in circles.
The shortcomings of ``Lord of the Barnyard'' might well be
attributed to the inexperience (or perhaps the arrogance) of youth
and to a lack of guidance. For, refreshing as it is to read a new
novelist whose prose hasn't been manicured to lifeless perfection
by too many fiction-writing workshops, Egolf still needs someone to
tell him that he can't pull off this kind of novel without a single
line of dialogue. A good editor would also have suggested
alternatives to tortuously awkward sentences like this: ``He'd seen
one too many wetbacks hauled off in stretchers after crippling
falls from the tiers not to begin to realize that their never being
seen or heard from again indicated Sodderbrook's refusal, on
grounds of one vague technicality or another, to foot the required
medical bills.'' And a teacher might point out that even the dense,
cascading prose of Thomas Pynchon (an obvious inspiration) uses
language like a precision instrument. The author of ``Gravity's
Rainbow'' would never call a priest's phony, unctuous eulogy a
``jeremiad'' or describe a town as a ``police state'' in one
sentence and ``mob ruled'' in the next.
</P>
<P>
   There's a callowness, too, in Egolf's penchant for hyperbole.
Everything bad in Baker (which is everything in Baker) is the worst
possible specimen of its kind. The German forebears of the
townsfolk are ``the poverty-ridden, uneducated, woebegotten dregs
of the peasantry. . . . A combative, vulgar, ignorant and
hopelessly superstitious people.'' The secretaries at City Hall are
``intellectually on a par with a school of mill pond guppies.'' The
scene after a few weeks of the strike is ``heinous beyond
description.'' The words ``hideous,'' ``repulsive'' and
``abominable'' are deployed with a frequency unparalleled since the
heyday of H. P. Lovecraft. The nameless, faceless, historyless
narrator (one of the striking hill scrubs) assures us so often that
a situation or person is infinitely, inconceivably or unbelievably
awful that eventually a certain amount of disbelief does set in.
It's hard to lend credence to someone who never stops shrieking.
</P>
<P>
   Invective is a cornerstone of Egolf's characterization as well.
Pretty much everyone in ``Lord of the Barnyard'' is angry pretty
much all of the time, and nearly all of them are described as
contemptible. Of the whole scurvy lot, only John (who expresses his
nobility in his desire to be left alone) amounts to more than a
flimsy construction. Considering that the only significant female
character besides John's mother is the fiendish Hortense Allenbach
-- a middle-aged Methodist who, in the book's most ludicrous scene,
cements her triumph by taunting and sexually assaulting the
15-year-old John beside a campfire -- perhaps it's best that Egolf
doesn't try his readers' credulity further by depicting more women.
Still, for such a broad, brawling novel, ``Lord of the Barnyard''
is strangely sexless. John's seeming lack of erotic inclinations of
any kind makes him a particularly implausible teen-age boy and
suggests that Egolf can't manage to render an emotional state
softer than high dudgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Egolf's novel gave publishers plenty of reasons for
turning it down, it's also not hard to see why it won over Modiano
and finally found its way to print -- and acclaim in The Times
Literary Supplement. For all its clumsiness, ``Lord of the
Barnyard'' has the whiff of real talent -- that rare and maddening
thing -- about it. First and foremost, Egolf has a terrific story
under all that guff, one charged with dramatic conflict and built
on a scale that can encompass both individual passions and the
inchoate mind of a community. He can pile a whole atticful of
grudges and personal agendas onto it, and it still keeps chugging
along, dragging his (sometimes unwilling) reader with it. Then
there's the tremendous energy fueling Egolf's prose -- part of it
rage, yes, but also an infectious exuberance for words and the
telling of tales. Thousands of young writers produce pages of
lambent, flawless sentences without anywhere near this much life in
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord of the Barnyard'' is the book a shrewder novelist would
have stashed in a drawer, chalking it up to various lessons learned
and letting a second, more polished work serve as his debut. The
question is: Can Egolf learn to write dialogue, to fully imagine
characters and to get over his adolescent misanthropy without
refining the fire right out of his work? If he does, that second
novel will be a book to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Laura Miller is a senior editor at Salon, an Internet magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
