<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-RUSSIA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 KAPITALIZM
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russia's Struggle to Free Its Economy.
</P>
<P>
   By Rose Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Press. $30.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; MARKET MAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   BY FEN MONTAIGNE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Press. $30.
</P>
<P>
   In little more than a decade, Russia has been transformed in the
minds of most Americans from menace to muddle. No realm seems
hazier than the effort by Boris N. Yeltsin and company to
metamorphose the Communist economy into a capitalist proving
ground, an exercise some liken to putting a scrambled egg back in
its shell. The 1990's present a swirl of images: bundled-up
babushkas taking to the streets to peddle their possessions as free
prices and inflation hit, buzz-cut mobsters rubbing one another out
with Capone-like gusto, the trappings of the West's good life --
from the Golden Arches to Mercedes sedans -- flooding the country.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though we may not have grasped it, one of the most
daring social experiments in history has unfolded before our eyes.
And in ``Kapitalizm,'' Rose Brady admirably chronicles, step by
step, how Yeltsin's young reformers fought to dismantle the
insanely complex Soviet economy and construct a free-market society
in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Often it is not a pretty story, but Brady is able to see past
the blundering and corruption and appreciate the achievement that
has taken place: Eight years after the demise of the Soviet Union,
private enterprise accounts for 70 percent of Russia's economic
production, and -- most important -- the psychology of many
Russians has irretrievably changed. ``The task, then, was to
dismantle the machine,'' she writes of Anatoly Chubais, who led
Yeltsin's privatization drive. ``He had come up against fierce
opponents of reform, and in the political-economic game that ensued
he had not always played clean. But he had kept his eye on the
prize. The prize was a non-Communist Russia in which private
property dominated the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of Russia's economy is a sprawling and
byzantine tale, and Brady, a former Moscow correspondent for
Business Week, is well qualified to tell it. As could be expected,
the reform process has been a constant round of two steps forward,
one step back, with Communist die-hards in Parliament and the
so-called Red Directors of state factories resisting the march to
capitalism. Brady skillfully relates the missteps and compromises
that Yeltsin's team made along the way. Nowhere was the maneuvering
trickier than in the privatization of state-owned business and
industry, the cornerstone of the market makeover.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Chubais permitted several major banks, which had
provided the Government with much-needed loans, to acquire large
blocks of shares in industrial giants, like Norilsk Nickel, through
shady auctions. Such insider deals enabled a handful of financial
institutions to gain control over large segments of the economy at
bargain-basement prices. But Chubais, fearful that a Communist
victory in 1995 parliamentary elections might derail privatization,
wanted to make the process irreversible. Unloading factories and
oil companies to private investors, however improperly, did just
that. The year after, Brady explains, the oligarchs showed their
gratitude, plowing by some estimates $140 million into Yeltsin's
victorious re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kapitalizm'' is at its best when Brady takes readers behind
the scenes of machinations like these, or when she recounts the
rise of Russia's new magnates. Her story falls short, however, in
describing the effects of the reforms on average Russians. To be
sure, the book is replete with man-on-the-street interviews, but
closely following one or two families over the past eight years
would have been more effective.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Kapitalizm'' is one of the most coherent accounts to
date of the disassembly of the economy of the Evil Empire. Now,
with Russia mired in its worst crisis to date, all involved
acknowledge that the task has been far more daunting than they ever
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We . . . did not comprehend the enormity of the process we
were dealing with,'' Chubais says. ``We thought it was a difficult
transition that would last three years, five years, seven years.
Now it's clear that the transition will last decades.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Fen Montaigne, a former Moscow correspondent for The
Philadelphia Inquirer, is the author of ``Reeling In Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
