<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DOG-NYTSF     03-26 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DOG-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TEETH OF THE DOG
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Jill Ciment.
</P>
<P>
   216 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Crown Publishers. $22.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; VACATION GETAWAY
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVID SACKS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UH-oh. Americans abroad in a ``developing'' country. They mean
well, but they foist themselves on a fragile culture that is
dependent and hostile, that views them as both predator and prey.
In the fiction of writers like Graham Greene and Robert Stone, this
familiar scenario can combine crackerjack suspense with political
comment. Jill Ciment, in her fast-paced and handsomely written
second novel, ``Teeth of the Dog,'' adds a 1990's-style ingredient:
a woman's progress toward self-reliance. The result is
thought-provoking and very entertaining, if a bit unevenly plotted.
</P>
<P>
   Helene is a New York City redhead in her mid-30's with a
``negligent beauty'' and a core of sadness. For 12 years, she has
been the pampered third wife of Thomas Strauss, an eminent
anthropologist more than 30 years her senior. When their vacation
in the remote South Pacific goes tragically awry, Helene is swept
up in monstrous events. With no help available from her husband or
Uncle Sam, she faces the old challenge: adapt or die.
</P>
<P>
   The action unfolds on the fictional Melanesian island of Vanduu
-- a new and very poor country,'' one inhabitant primly explains,
``still making adjustments.'' Symbolically, Vanduu encapsulates the
ex-colonial world. A ``hodgepodge of cultures, a modern Tower of
Babel,'' it harbors a Christianized native tradition, a Muslim
minority and resident aliens from India and the entire Far East.
Tensions of race and class smolder. So do resentments over United
States foreign policy pressures and Vanduu's own ``ceaseless
dependence on tourist dollars.'' This is no place for Westerners'
fantasies of paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Ciment writes tight prose with carefully selected details, often
quirky or comical. Island life is sympathetically rendered, yet we
feel Thomas and Helene's nausea amid bad food (``Spam sushi'') and
intense heat and light.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts as a love triangle. The elderly Thomas is
battling prostate cancer, and Helene has organized this trip in the
hope that ``the sheer newness, the unrelenting beauty, the intrigue
of an unprobed culture, the mere fact of their traveling together
again, would make him, if not exactly well, at least himself.''
Instead, Vanduu's discomforts soon leave Thomas exhausted and
withdrawn, Helene bitter and defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's Finster, a raffish, expatriate Californian
with ``surfer boy good looks,'' a local salesman of sorts. Finster
(the name suggests ``window'' in Latin) is genuinely smitten with
Helene; his attention offers momentary escape and reassurance.
``She needed to be so shamelessly desired.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the plot steers close to trashy cliche: tropical
nights; a restless, sexy wife; a stranger with ``cobalt blue''
eyes. Fortunately, the author has bigger plans: Finster is too
oafish and possessive, Vanduu too ominous. The capital city ignites
in hysteria, and Helene is reduced to a lone fugitive, hunted by
the police. Desperate, she finds ways to hide out and alter her
appearance. If she can get across the island to Finster's village,
will he help her escape? The climax is exciting and fairly
plausible.
</P>
<P>
   The storytelling does show a seam or two. Both male characters
prove oddly ineffectual in adversity, given their backgrounds.
Thomas actually disappoints: sure, he's sick, but where's the
worldly, amused, manipulative mind of a renowned traveler and
writer? And Finster never quite emerges as the dangerous
entanglement we expect.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Teeth of the Dog'' delivers, on several levels. Beneath
the drama, Helene's journey toward independence suggests a metaphor
for a woman's passage toward middle age; throughout, the book
broods on the inevitability of change.
</P>
<P>
   Watching an incoming ferryboat, Finster notes the prow ``carving
a wedge of foam through the glassy swells. In Vanduuan lore, a boat
tugs a whole new ocean behind it. Ocean eats ocean. New world
devours old. The foam is the mark of its voracious appetite. Teeth
of the dog, the natives call it.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Sacks is the author of the Encyclopedia of the Ancient
Greek World.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
