<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SCIFI-NYTSF     03-26 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SCIFI-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SCIENCE FICTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY GERALD JONAS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The hero of John Barnes' 1995 novel ``Kaleidoscope Century'' was
a coldhearted hit man with one redeeming quality: he was marginally
less nasty than a sadistic comrade in arms who took pleasure in
``serbing'' his female victims before dispatching them. Since
Barnes has an undeniable knack for getting under the skin of his
characters, it was perhaps inevitable that some readers had trouble
distinguishing the author from his disturbing creations. My
grudgingly positive review of ``Kaleidoscope Century'' ended with
the hope that there would be no sequels. I am happy to report that
FINITY (Tor/Tom Doherty, $22.95) is an altogether different kind of
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finity'' starts from a premise as edgy as anything conjured by
Philip K. Dick. Quantum theory -- the set of assumptions and
equations that allows us to get a grip, however slippery, on the
behavior of the smallest of things -- poses severe challenges to
the conventional view of reality. To explain the odd behavior of
subatomic particles, which are literally neither here nor there
until you look for them, some physicists posit the existence of an
ever-expanding number of realities in which everything that is
possible actually happens somewhere. For example, if you observe a
particular particle jump to the left, there is another reality in
which that particle jumps to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its value to modern physics, the so-called Many Worlds
hypothesis has proved useful to science fiction writers, because it
affords scientifically respectable cover to the wildest
speculations about alternative histories: what kind of world would
result if, say, Nazi Germany won World War II or Lyndon Johnson
became president of a latter-day Republic of Texas? But Barnes goes
far beyond such conjectures to question the nature of reality
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Peripart, an American expatriate who teaches astronomy in
21st-century New Zealand, takes for granted that his world was
shaped by the triumph of Hitler's nuclear-armed forces over Allied
resistance in the 1940s. Then he learns from a Delphic billionaire
named Geoffrey Iphwin that widespread use of quantum-based computer
chips is breaking down the barriers between the Many Worlds, so
that calling on a cell phone or taking a ride in an automated taxi
can catapult you into a reality with a radically different past.
</P>
<P>
   Peripart joins a group of adventurers out to discover why, in
all the worlds they visit, there is no sign of life from the North
American territory of the former United States. The cast of
characters, who change in subtle and not so subtle ways as their
pasts mutate, are engaging enough to hold our attention; along with
the pathos and puzzlement inherent in their situation, they manage
to find humor and several varieties of love before the narrative
reaches as much of a conclusion as is possible in the endlessly
malleable universe they inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   John Barnes' recent collection of short stories, APOSTROPHES AND
APOCALYPSES (Tor/Tom Doherty, $24.95), offers additional reason to
welcome this writer to the front ranks of contemporary science
fiction. At least four of the stories have never been published
before, including the best of the lot, ``Gentleman Pervert, Off on
a Spree,'' which bares the thoughts and feelings of a sex addict at
a time when virtual reality has made possible the easy
gratification of all itches except one.
</P>
<P>
   Because he writes so well about unrepentantly macho men, Barnes
has been identified with what might be called science fiction's
right wing -- a school of writing exemplified by Robert A.
Heinlein, in which fierce independence and military discipline are
passionately (if paradoxically) held up as saving virtues for
future societies. But Barnes seems less eager to sell a point of
view than to explore it: his gentleman pervert is agonizingly
honest about his fear of impotence and the other self-doubts that
drive him to sexual excess.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered among the stories, which play agreeable and
stimulating variations on many of the genre's longest-standing
themes, are little essays that give Barnes the opportunity to vent
his strongly held opinions on almost everything. A self-proclaimed
atheist who constructs imaginary futures with the aid of computer
spreadsheets believes that science fiction, having lost its onetime
central metaphor of space travel to the bean counters at NASA, is
now in danger of losing its franchise as an ``escape hatch'' for
teen-agers. While some might applaud this as a sign of progress,
Barnes argues that a genre can do a lot worse than function as a
dream machine for adolescents; he likens their efforts to figure
out the adult world to the work that readers must do to comprehend
any fiction set in a possible future.
</P>
<P>
   One of the revelations of ``Apostrophes and Apocalypses'' is how
Barnes's freewheeling imagination thrives at shorter lengths; his
novels tend toward repetition of narrative elements rather than
development of theme or character. Vernor Vinge, who wrote the Hugo
Award-winning novel ``A Fire Upon the Deep'' (1992), returns to the
same far-future universe in A DEEPNESS IN THE SKY (Tor/Tom Doherty,
$27.95). Despite its many virtues, a comparison of his new novel
with ``A Fire Upon the Deep'' demonstrates the critical importance
of scale in science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Fire Upon the Deep'' ranged the Milky Way, encompassing a
galaxy of diverse humans and nonhumans and dealing with literally
cosmic issues. It never seemed padded; indeed, I finished it hungry
for more. ``A Deepness in the Sky'' is set 30,000 years earlier.
Although humanity has already spread through the galaxy, the story
concentrates on events in a single star-system. Representatives of
the Qeng Ho, a galactic trading consortium, and the Emergents, a
group of long-isolated humans with strange powers, vie for control
of one another and for the opportunity to exploit a planet of
intelligent nonhumans, called Spiders, who are just reaching their
technological maturity.
</P>
<P>
   The novel's 606 pages offer ample scope for Vinge to elaborate
on his themes -- the allure of power, the power of knowledge, the
necessity of freedom. The point of view shifts back and forth among
the Traders, the Emergents and the nonhumans. While the latter
physically resemble spiders, their social organization is
reminiscent of 19th-century England; unlike the truly alien
nonhumans in ``A Fire Upon the Deep,'' the Spiders interact with
one another and with the encroaching humans in mostly predictable
ways.
</P>
<P>
   While disappointing, this is hardly a fatal flaw; the three-way
struggle for dominance provides sustained suspense as well as
carefully calibrated fireworks at well-timed intervals. But the
book is simply too long for its subject. Instead of feeding our
curiosity about the boundless expanse of space-time, as he did in
``A Fire Upon the Deep,'' Vinge weighs down this much more compact
tale with gratuitous detail and dispensable background information.
A more economical telling would have focused attention where it
belongs, on the shrewdly interlocking plot lines with their
surprising yet satisfying resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
