<HEADER>
A5030 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CLASS-NYTSF     03-26 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CLASS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE RISE AND FALL OF CLASS IN BRITAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   By David Cannadine.
</P>
<P>
   293 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University Press. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; POWER RANKINGS
</P>
<P>
   BY PAUL S. SEAVER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1940 George Orwell accepted as a fact that England was ``the
most class-ridden country under the sun.'' Although in more recent
times Margaret Thatcher complained that class was ``a Communist
concept,'' John Major, in his expressed intention to create a
classless society, testified to its ubiquity. A minor pleasure
experienced by North American visitors is that our accent
immediately betrays us as foreigners, thus not subject to the
complex rules and resentments that still seem to govern class
relations in England. For the English truly seem obsessed with
class to a degree that startles a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Although David Cannadine is a native of Britain, it may be his
experience as a professor of modern British history in America
(``The Rise and Fall of Class in Britain'' originated as the
Leonard Hastings Schoff Memorial Lectures at Columbia University)
that suggested the subject of his new book: certainly class has a
different history here than in Britain. In any event, this richly
documented study is concerned not so much with class today as with
the emergence of class as a social category, as the dominant way of
viewing social distinctions in England during the past three
centuries (the rest of Britain is not entirely neglected, and
Cannadine is sensitive to the role played by the North American
colonies and later by the British in India).
</P>
<P>
   As Cannadine notes, class analysis has gone out of fashion as
the motor of history since the 1970's, not only because of the
decline of Marxism but also because of the rise of feminist and
post-modernist critiques. His intention is not to buck this trend
by resurrecting class as a historical force, but rather to trace
the complex history of its use as an analytical category and to
steer a middle course between ``the overdetermined reductionism of
Marxist analysis and the free-floating subjectivities of the
historians of language.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally the English have been understood to view their
society as an aspect of the Great Chain of Being, as a graded
hierarchy of ranks, degrees and orders from the peasant laborer at
the bottom to the duke and prince at the top, a view inherited from
the Middle Ages but still current in the 16th and 17th centuries.
While this was the dominant view of society, some observers talked
at times in terms of ``better sorts'' and ``meaner sorts'' of
people, dichotomous terms particularly in vogue in times of acute
social tension. By the 17th century, in the light of the
spectacular growth of London, many described urban artisans and
merchants as ``middling sorts,'' lying roughly between the landed
classes and the rural peasantry.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Revolution was seen as transforming this
traditional society into the class-dominated society of modern
times, a development leading to the rise of modern parties and in
turn to the identification of party with class, to the decline of
the Liberal Party and the rise of Labor, the party of the working
class, arrayed against the Tories, the party of business, privilege
and property that has dominated British politics since 1945. What
Cannadine demonstrates with an array of apt quotations is that at
least from the late 17th century to the present, social analysts of
various stripes described English society in hierarchical, triadic
or dichotomous terms, depending in part on ideological need.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Johnson, a Tory, preferred to visualize English society as a
graded hierarchy in which every subject had a God-given place, and
in which deference to those above and the right to command those
below naturally followed from one's location in the hierarchy. Such
a vision does not vanish with the Industrial Revolution but
reappears both early in the 19th century in Robert Southey, who
invokes ``That appointed chain, /
</P>
<P>
   Which when in cohesion it unites /
</P>
<P>
   Order to order, rank to rank, /
</P>
<P>
   In mutual benefit,'' and in a different register in
late-19th-century social Darwinists, who, if they did not
necessarily see a hierarchical order as God-given, nevertheless saw
inequality as built into the natural order.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, revolutionaries like Tom Paine saw society in
dichotomous terms, us against them. Paine wrote, ``There are two
classes of men in the nation, those who pay taxes and those who
receive and live upon taxes.'' A triadic vision, one in which a
middle class was thought to play a particularly enticing role, is
found in Lord John Russell's argument for the 1832 Reform Bill; he
felt that enfranchising part of the middle classes would enable
them to ``bind firmly and kindly the different classes of society
together.''
</P>
<P>
   ON the whole, the evidence convinces Cannadine that society is
too complex for any form of class analysis to have more than a
rhetorical resonance. Nonetheless, he points out that while Labor
claimed to speak for the working class, Labor between the wars
never received as much as 50 percent of the working-class vote -- a
statement that makes sense only if indeed there was a working
class. Later he notes that ``although the Tories delighted in
working-class embourgeoisement, and although Labor feared it, this
turned out to be no more than another ideological stereotype: there
was very little evidence that prosperous members of the working
class crossed a great social (and political) divide and became
middle-class Tories'' -- a statement that implies both a working
class and a middle class, separated by a virtually unbridgeable
gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Even if class categories are at best social approximations,
Cannadine, like the rest of us, cannot do without them: in certain
contexts modern societies seem not to behave simply as congeries of
atomistic individuals, no matter how much they escape our simple
categories in other circumstances. At the end of this important and
provocative study Cannadine asks whether a classless England is
conceivable, at least in the sense that he sees the United States
as classless -- a society in which vast income disparities and
inequalities ``do not translate into corresponding inequalities of
social prestige or social perceptions'' (a characterization of our
society that may not be beyond dispute). Nevertheless, he does
point out reasonably enough that if such a society is what Tony
Blair aims to create, the minimum requirements are the elimination
of titles and honors along with an educational system that
reinforces class perceptions. ``But,'' he asks rather sadly at the
end, ``is such a 'classless society' something the British actually
want?''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Paul S. Seaver, a professor of history at Stanford University,
is the author of ``Wallington's World: A Puritan Artisan in
Seventeenth-Century London.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
