<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BLAM-NYTSF     03-26 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BLAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE BOOK OF BLAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Aleksandar Tisma.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Michael Henry Heim.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt Brace &AMP; Company. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; GHOST TOWN
</P>
<P>
   BY LARRY WOLFF
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the opening pages of Aleksandar Tisma's ``Book of Blam,'' the
eponymous protagonist, Miroslav Blam, sets out for a stroll through
the city of Novi Sad in Tito's Yugoslavia. He finds himself drawn
to what was once the street of the Jews, before the war, now ``the
destination of many idle strollers like Blam.'' He is not, however,
just any idle stroller, for Blam is one of the few Jewish survivors
in Novi Sad, and he can remember the street when it was inhabited
by the now annihilated Jewish population of the city. Following in
Blam's footsteps, in a stunning literary excursion, Tisma conjures
the names and fates of the former inhabitants. He recounts what
occurred at each address after Hitler defeated Yugoslavia in 1941
and Hungary, Germany's ally, occupied the city of Novi Sad:
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 13 housed Arthur Spitzer's grocery and delicatessen.
Spitzer played amateur soccer and had non-Jewish friends. Having
married a Hungarian and converted before the war, he was spared
persecution. He had no children of his own, but his sister sent him
her 6-year-old daughter from the Independent State of Croatia,
where Jews had an even harder time of it. . . . For a while his
baptismal certificate, Christian wife and soccer friends protected
him. On the day his young Jewish niece was to be deported, Spitzer
and his wife went to the station with her, hoping to save her with
their papers and connections. They were all crammed into a train
for Auschwitz.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisma builds his novel around the fictional figure of Blam, who
does escape deportation, in part because he, like Arthur Spitzer,
has a non-Jewish wife. Blam becomes the focus for the literary
reconstruction of a demolished urban landscape and society,
represented according to the intricate historical circumstances of
Eastern Europe during World War II. First published in Yugoslavia
in 1972, now powerfully translated by Michael Henry Heim from the
language that used to be called Serbo-Croatian, ``The Book of
Blam'' offers a literary memorial to the former Jews of the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Novi Sad is a name perhaps best known to the American public as
the hometown of the tennis superstar Monica Seles -- cited in
sports stories as a place where the scarcity of acceptable tennis
courts for training inevitably compelled Seles to migrate to
America at 12. Novi Sad played a considerably more complicated part
in European history, its urban development dating to the 18th
century, when the city grew up alongside the Danube, facing the
great Hapsburg fortress of Petrovaradin. In the 19th century Novi
Sad became a center of Serbian literary culture, though the city
had a heterogeneous population of Serbs, Hungarians, Germans and
Jews. It was the principal city of the Vojvodina province, itself a
geographical crossroads of even greater ethnographic diversity,
including large communities of Croatians and Romanians. Thus Novi
Sad reflected the multinational character of the Hapsburg monarchy,
before being assigned to Yugoslavia in the peace settlement
following World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Tisma traces a fictional family history of migrating Hapsburg
Jews through the whole 19th century and across the map of Eastern
Europe, showing how the parents of Miroslav Blam happened to settle
in Novi Sad. The most remarkable of Tisma's literary historical
accounts, however, is that of the massacre of 1942 in Novi Sad,
perpetrated by the Hungarian military. The Hungarian population of
Novi Sad lived under Yugoslav sovereignty after World War I; the
Serbian population was handed over by Hitler to Hungarian rule
during World War II. Tisma begins with an urban map: ``Look at the
map of Novi Sad, and you will see a kind of spider's web
intersecting on one side with a broad ribbon in the form of a half
circle but extending evenly in all other directions. The ribbon,
usually colored blue, is the Danube.'' He then imagines the
Hungarian officers plotting their murderous raid from that same map
-- they divided the spiderweb of the city's streets into several
hundred smaller webs, assigning patrols to each'' -- and follows
the patrols as they check documents and order executions. Thousands
of Jews and Serbs were killed in the massacre, and Tisma attempts
to convey the atrocity of the historical moment by describing what
happened in a sampling of houses and neighborhoods. One of the
patrols comes to the house of Blam's parents, who are promptly
taken outside and shot.
</P>
<P>
   Other works by Tisma also explore the experience of World War II
in Novi Sad, including ``The Use of Man,'' which has been
translated into English. Some of the same regional terrain also
appears in the fiction of Danilo Kis, who, like Tisma, came from
Vojvodina and wrote about the situation of Yugoslav Jews during the
war. Tisma himself was associated with Tito's Partisans during the
war and afterward played a prominent role in Yugoslav literary life
during the decades of Communism. ``The Book of Blam'' has a young
Communist heroine -- Blam's sister Estera, who is killed in the
Resistance as she throws her last grenade. Hers is one of the
ghosts that haunts Blam after the war. Another is that of the
novel's political villain, Predrag Popadic, a handsome young rake
who collaborates with the Hungarian occupation by editing a Serbian
newspaper in Novi Sad. He seduces Blam's mother and, later, Blam's
wife as well (though not, of course, Estera) but attempts to use
his influence to protect the Blam family under the Hungarian
occupation. After the liberation of Novi Sad the victorious
Communist Partisans arrest Popadic and summarily execute him beside
the Danube, blowing his brains out with a dumdum bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Tito's Yugoslavia was politically constructed as the federal
union of six separate republics: Serbia, Croatia, Slovenia, Bosnia,
Macedonia and Montenegro. The republic of Serbia included two
autonomous provinces: one was Kosovo, with its large Albanian
majority, and the other was Vojvodina, with its large Hungarian
minority. Novi Sad was the provincial capital of the multinational
Vojvodina, and the name of the city was also associated with the
affirmation of cultural unity in Yugoslavia, for it was the Novi
Sad linguistic agreement of 1954 that declared Serbo-Croatian to be
a single language, spoken in two dialects and written in two
scripts. Tisma wrote his novel in Serbo-Croatian, but today both
Serbs and Croats insist on the distinction between Serbian and
Croatian.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian nationalists demonstrated in Novi Sad in 1988, toppling
the provincial government and paving the way for Slobodan Milosevic
to abolish autonomy in both Vojvodina and Kosovo. The overturning
of the intricate Titoist constitution, with its calculated
structure of checks and balances among the nationalities, has
severely reduced the cultural protections and prerogatives of the
Hungarians, as well as the several other minorities, in Vojvodina.
Tisma, living in France, has bitterly condemned the brutal warfare
that continues to accompany the disintegration of Yugoslavia, and
``The Book of Blam,'' looking back to Novi Sad in World War II,
explores the political pressures by which a multinational urban
community became the site of murderous internecine enmity. Indeed,
the various remembered and misremembered versions of what happened
during World War II in Yugoslavia have certainly contributed to the
violence of national conflict in the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   Tisma describes the assembling of the Jews of Novi Sad in the
city's synagogue in 1944, as they awaited deportation to the
concentration camps: ``The Jews sat patiently within the confines
of the synagogue; the guards did their duty meticulously, showing
anger only in the street, when they had to disperse curious
onlookers -- one group of which included a dejected-looking Blam,
exempt because of his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only discordant note in this otherwise harmonious waiting
period came from the animal world rather than the human world; it
came in the form of the dogs that had trotted alongside their
masters to the synagogue and that remained outside when the guards
refused to let them through the gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisma thus follows the deportation from the perspective of the
confused dogs, who cannot figure out the unfathomable human logic
of the Holocaust. The novel returns to the synagogue for the final
chapter, in which Blam attends a concert of the Novi Sad Chamber
Orchestra, performed in the former temple, now best appreciated for
its excellent acoustics. In the synagogue, with its handsomely
surviving cupolas, pillars, chandeliers and mosaics, Blam's inner
acoustical sensitivity focuses his memory with excruciating clarity
on his family and their community, which did not survive the
terrible course of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wolff teaches European history at Boston College. He is
the author of ``Inventing Eastern Europe: The Map of Civilization
on the Mind of the Enlightenment.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
