<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-VALENTE-NYTSF     03-26 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-VALENTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ME, BY JIMMY (BIG BOY) VALENTE, GOVERNOR OF MINNESOTA.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As told to Garrison Keillor.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 152 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Viking. $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; NO, NOT THAT GOVERNOR OF MINNESOTA
</P>
<P>
   BY PETER APPLEBOME
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   They are all there at the Professional Wrestling Online Museum.
Stanislaus Zbyszco, the Viennese intellectual and pioneer grappler
from the first decade of the 20th century, is there facing off with
the Great Gama of India. So are Nature Boy Ric Flair and Superstar
Billy Graham. There are the legendary international tag-teams --
the Fabulous Kangaroos, the ferocious Wild Samoans, the Kalmikoffs
(evil Russians from the 1960's) and Krusher Kruschev and Ivan
Koloff, a more pumped-up, contemporary variation on the theme.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, the only governor in the
nation who used to make a living running around in glitter tights
and a feathered boa, didn't make the cut. So maybe it was to
redress a wrong that the humorist Garrison Keillor decided to give
us this odd little hiccup of political satire telling Ventura's
story, more or less, in the fictional form of Jimmy (Big Boy)
Valente's rise from the ring to the Minnesota Governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to think of a fatter target for satire than
Ventura, which is exactly the problem with this mildly amusing,
mildly irritating quickie book. It is hard enough to parody
professional wrestling, which is a parody in itself. It is harder
still to take a subject treated with amusement by political writers
from International Falls to Washington and make it fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me'' has the feel of promising material for ``A Prairie Home
Companion,'' where Keillor has been doing Ventura takeoffs for
months. Indeed, it reads best if you can summon up Keillor's droll,
deadpan voice while reading it. But as a book, it feels more like a
smart marketing concept than inspired satire.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even make it to Page 1 before you get the idea that
perhaps this book was knocked out a bit too hastily. Across from
the title page is a funny made-up listing of Keillor's other books,
like ``Lentils and You,'' ``10 Steps to More Sensitive Writing''
and ``Dear Heart: The Correspondence of Eudora Welty and Weeb
Eubanks.'' It is a nice joke, but the former Jets coach was Weeb
Eubank, not Eubanks. Even a slender book like ``Me'' probably takes
more than two months to get right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me'' takes the form of a memoir as told to Keillor by a
cantankerous Valente. Augmented by stylized drawings and written in
muscular, weasels-ripped-my-flesh prose, it takes its hero from his
birth in Minneapolis to Vietnam to a fabulous wrestling career and
to his election as Minnesota's Governor.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of quirky touches Keillor's fans will
appreciate, like the father who died while duck hunting when his
waders filled with water. And Keillor certainly captures the
over-the-top nuttiness of wrestling in the form of characters like
Vicious Eddie the Mohawk Kid, who has a zipper implanted in his
cheek that he unzips so people can see the food in his mouth; the
Widowmaker, who runs around in a black hangman's mask whacking guys
with two-by-fours and lead pipes; and a yuppie bad boy named Brent
Beige, who wears white Calvin Klein briefs, brings his cell phone
into the ring and whines about his hair while the crowd begs his
opponent to destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Valente's own wrestling persona as the first
modern existential wrestler, a mixture of the best qualities of
James Arness, Larry of the Three Stooges, Spiro Agnew, the Grand
Exalted Potentate of the Zuhrah Shrine and Bo Diddley.
</P>
<P>
   It has its moments, but even this little goes a long way, absent
a more ambitious satiric premise than Keillor came up with. And
don't even ask about the dubious gag in which Valente is pursued by
a Vietnamese nemesis who turns up repeatedly hollering things like,
``One day I wirr clush you rike a pop can, Big Boy!''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the book is a sendup of the celebrity culture in
which every bozo of the moment uses his 15 minutes of fame to tell
his story. But it may say as much about the current culture of
celebrity writers and the endless appetite of the big bookstore
chains for new product by brand-name authors.
</P>
<P>
   And, as with much of Keillor's work, it's hard to be sure
whether the book reflects a keen instinct for life in Lake Wobegon
country or a snotty condescension toward it. Ventura may turn out
to be a total geek, but the last American politician so easy to
ridicule was probably the one who starred in ``Bedtime for Bonzo.''
He did fine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is one thing that is haunting about the Ventura
saga. Take a look at Ventura's shaved head, rippling muscles and
modest mustache. Go to the on-line wrestling museum and check out
the almost identical pictures of Stanislaus Zbyszco, described as a
noted intellectual who studied music, philosophy and law in his
native Austria. Could Jesse Ventura, existential wrestling
politician, and Stanislaus Zbyszco, existential wrestling pioneer
-- dead since 1967! -- be the same person? As the post-Monica world
waits for the next story of the century, you might stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Peter Applebome, who reports on the arts for The New York Times,
is the author of ``Dixie Rising: How the South Is Shaping American
Values, Politics and Culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
