<HEADER>
A5036 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     03-26 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 Books in Brief: Fiction
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In MORE BREAD OR I'LL APPEAR (Houghton Mifflin, $23), her
sharp-witted novel about an Irish family struggling to stay
connected despite geographical and emotional distance, Emer Martin
traces a young woman's globe-trotting quest to find her long-lost
older sister. Fourteen years earlier, Aisling, the favored eldest
daughter, fled her clinging mother, her institutionalized father (a
man stricken with ``the doubting disease,'' obsessive-compulsive
disorder) and the four siblings she virtually raised to travel the
world, never to return home. The mother, now ailing, asks Keelin,
her youngest and most dutiful child, to leave a promising teaching
job and search for Aisling. So Keelin flies to Japan, Aisling's
last known residence, and follows her sister's circuitous trail
through Hiroshima's transvestite subculture, Tokyo hostess bars and
finally to Central America, all the while grappling with
acquaintances' tales of Aisling as an idealistic hippie, a lesbian
obsessed with an African artist, a call girl. Keelin occasionally
travels with her likable but troubled siblings -- Orla, an earthy
Bronx baker who mourns the son she gave up for adoption; Siobhan, a
London fashion maven who battles anorexia; and Patrick, whose
compulsive habits have shaped his aimless existence -- and with her
uncle, a wealthy, rather debauched Jesuit priest with secrets of
his own. While the peripatetic narrative sometimes wanders astray,
Martin's wry, trenchant prose keeps things animated. What is more
impressive, Aisling becomes a nuanced symbol for the family's lost
ideal -- one startlingly refuted by her actual appearance. Keelin's
odyssey movingly reveals the harm of clinging to the past, even in
the name of family. _ MEGAN HARLAN
</P>
<P>
   THE MOTHER-IN-LAW DIARIES
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   Algonquin, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   When Lulu Penfield hears that her 19-year-old son, Treatie, has
eloped, she takes the news badly. To her way of thinking, he has
done the unspeakable: he's turned her into a mother-in-law, and she
knows mothers-in-law. She's had four of them. Written in the form
of a letter to Treatie, ``The Mother-in-Law Diaries'' is Lulu's
attempt to explain to her son what a crummy thing he's done to her.
Thus she recounts her entire romantic history. She fell just as
hard for her first boyfriend's mother as she did for him; but
quickly, that relationship is history, and it's on to the next,
this time with the sanction of matrimony. All four of Lulu's
husbands are bores or knuckleheads; worse for the reader, they are
cardboard cutouts of bores and knuckleheads. The reader might
overlook that if only the mothers-in-law were fully realized
characters -- they are, after all, the ostensible stars of this
story -- but these matriarchs are just as incidental as everything
else here. Even poor Treatie is no more than a prop. Carol Dawson's
prose can seem boring and knuckleheaded, too. When a would-be
mother-in-law watches Lulu, ``a reflective look floated deep down
behind her eyes.'' One husband, she says, had the ability to ``drop
me into a trough of despondency.'' Dawson does have a knack for
conjuring wacky resumes for her characters -- one mother-in-law is
both a practicing witch and a lush -- but such bright moments
aren't enough of a reward for slogging through this tired,
formulaic book. _ LAURA JAMISON
</P>
<P>
   VITTORIO, THE VAMPIRE
</P>
<P>
   New Tales of the Vampires.
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Vittorio is a 16-year-old ``beautiful boy,'' born and reared in
the splendor that was 15th-century Tuscany. His father was a
``rampant stallion'' of a man whose ``only modern affectation was
that he liked to drink from fine goblets of glass''; his mother was
a ``spirited and beautiful'' woman with ``very green eyes.'' His
sister and brother -- the most lovely and interesting people in the
world'' -- are, like his stallion of a father and his very
green-eyed mother, lost to the world of mortals in a most unlovely
and uninteresting way. Understandably upset, Vittorio takes up his
sword in vengeance. Another of Anne Rice's loquacious vampires,
Vittorio does prattle on. One minute he's whining about the
``things of the night'' who are ravaging villages and the next he's
complaining about being tricked by the one he falls in love with.
The relationship Rice claims to have with this undead Chatty Cathy
is off-putting, too. I may not have been born five centuries ago,
but I wasn't born yesterday, and I know that Vittorio did not hand
Rice this manuscript in Florence, as she claims in the novel's
``Selected and Annotated Bibliography,'' which she signs, too
familiarly, ``Anne.'' Well, Anne, you can believe in the infernal
ones all you wish, but here you and I must part ways, forever and
always. _ ANDREA HIGBIE
</P>
<P>
   DOG EAT DOG
</P>
<P>
   By Jerry Jay Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Ace, paper, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jay Carroll's sequel to his clever debut novel, ``Top
Dog,'' leaves the door open to yet a third book in the series; the
ending alone will leave readers begging for more. Unfortunately,
the same might be said for the rest of the book. As ``Dog Eat Dog''
opens, William (Bogey) Ingersol, once an unapologetic corporate
raider (his personal stationery bore a skull and crossbones), is
mellowing out in California, a changed man. In the previous novel,
Bogey was literally changed -- into a dog -- and transported to an
alternate universe where he disrupted some of the devil's carefully
laid plans. In ``Dog Eat Dog,'' the reformed raider is busily
donating his wealth to charity when old demons reappear. The devil,
represented by a ``Mr. Dark,'' puts up a puppet Presidential
candidate, whom he hopes to use to destroy the world. If Bogey can
be torn to fleshy bits along the way, so much the better. The
novel's best passages -- which should not be read late at night --
come when Bogey is stalked by rapacious pig-faced assassins.
Equally entertaining (at any time of day) is Carroll's giddy,
cynical take on political campaigns. But somehow this novel never
quite manages to claim its own identity; too often, Carroll pauses
to brief new readers on relevant material from the first book.
``Dog Eat Dog'' is as clever as its predecessor, but it seems
smaller and less biting. Carroll seems to be aware of this -- in
``Top Dog,'' Bogey was transformed into a giant beast of a canine.
In ``Dog Eat Dog,'' he's zapped into a Chihuahua. _ LIAM CALLANAN
</P>
<P>
   UNDER HOUSE ARREST
</P>
<P>
   By Yevgeny Kharitonov.
</P>
<P>
   Serpent's Tail, $13.99.
</P>
<P>
   When the openly homosexual writer and Soviet dissident Yevgeny
Kharitonov died in Moscow in 1981 at the age of 40, his work had
been circulated in samizdat but never officially published. ``Under
House Arrest,'' a collection of autobiographical fiction and poetry
about gay life amid the Kafkaesque Soviet bureaucracy, is his first
book to be released in English. Kharitonov's narrator, a writer,
remains unnamed in these stories, and we learn little about the
particulars of his existence -- facts that reinforce the sense of a
man leading a hidden life. (Other characters, mostly gay men, are
refered to only by first names, or by initials.) For Kharitonov's
narrator, self-confidence and indifference are the only things that
protect him from the humiliation and indignity he faces as a Soviet
citizen with a suspect sexual life. In often moving passages that
frequently blend prose with poetry, he embraces his loneliness: ``I
shall never find happiness: of course not. I am incapable of
feeling it. For some reason I can always see its down side, an
insight I could do without.'' He seeks solace, and a kind of
redemption, in his writing, but readers of ``Under House Arrest,''
translated from the Russian by Arch Tait, will rarely find solace
in Kharitonov's own prose. Too often he is repetitive and overly
philosophical, and the lack of specificity and gritty detail here
makes these stories difficult to follow. When Kharitonov sticks to
the emotional nuances of men obsessed with love, however, the
stories have a tortured, captivating sadness and beauty. Vesna
Neskow
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
