<HEADER>
A5037 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     03-26 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY SCOTT VEALE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ECHOES OF A NATIVE LAND:
</P>
<P>
   Two Centuries of a Russian Village
</P>
<P>
   By Serge Schmemann. Vintage, $15.
</P>
<P>
   A former Moscow bureau chief for The New York Times visits his
ancestral village, creating -- with the help of the recollections
of its long-suffering inhabitants -- a miniature history of Russia
in the 20th century. '' 'Echoes of a Native Land' is that rare
achievement: a Russian memoir that subverts the conventions of the
genre and tells us, in clear, elegant and understated prose, that
you can't go home again,'' Michael Ignatieff wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN THERE ON A VISIT
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher Isherwood.
</P>
<P>
   University of Minnesota, $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   In four tales set in Berlin, Greece, London and California, the
author of ``Berlin Stories'' explores the sexuality and inner
turmoil of four vastly different protagonists, from a male
prostitute to a German worker taken with the bohemian life. ``This
excellent novel . . . may be the best Christopher Isherwood has
written,'' Gerald Sykes wrote in the Book Review in 1962. ``Out of
his literary detachment, strengthened by mystical studies, has come
a deeply intelligent and quietly compelling story.'' The same
publisher has reissued The Memorial ($15.95), which tracks the
falling apart of a British family after World War I. Isherwood's
``concern is with a mood, a collective state of mind, one which is
perhaps more accurately named a state of nerves,'' Edith R.
Mirrielees wrote here in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   THE FOOTNOTE: A CURIOUS HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Grafton. Harvard University, $14.
</P>
<P>
   A history professor digs up some surprising lore as he traces
the development of the footnote from ancient Greece to Gibbon (a
master of the genre) to its modern practitioners. The result is ``a
witty and characteristically erudite book,'' David McKitterick said
here in 1997. ``The pages of 'The Footnote' are peppered with human
folly.'' A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the
Eternal Passion for Books, by Nicholas A. Basbanes (Owl/Holt,
$18.95), explores book collecting and those driven to pursue it,
and features a sweeping Who's Who of collectors, living and dead,
visionary and loony. '' 'A Gentle Madness' is an impressive
achievement in its compilation of vast information, as well as
instructive and interesting,'' Philip Kopper wrote here in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ENDURING LOVE
</P>
<P>
   By Ian McEwan. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   A chance encounter radically changes the lives of a married
science writer and a young man who develops an erotic religious
fixation on him. In 1998 our reviewer, Sven Birkerts, called this
``a vibrant and unsettling'' novel that ``reminds us that normal
behavior conceals but does not banish unsavory truths.''
</P>
<P>
   THE RAPE OF NANKING:
</P>
<P>
   The Forgotten Holocaust of World War II
</P>
<P>
   By Iris Chang. Penguin, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Japanese troops slaughtered hundreds of thousands of
citizens in Nanking, an act of barbarism rarely spoken of (for
different reasons) in both Japan and China. ``Iris Chang, whose own
grandparents were survivors, recounts the grisly massacre with
understandable outrage,'' Orville Schell wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   BARNEY POLAN'S GAME:
</P>
<P>
   A Novel of the 1951 College Basketball Scandals
</P>
<P>
   By Charley Rosen. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In this fictional account of basketball's equivalent of the 1919
Black Sox scandal, an idealistic sports columnist bears witness to
the corruption of the sport by gamblers and players who conspired
to fix games. ``Rosen's novel is a particularly American form of
tragedy, in which the characters do not have to fall from great
heights to fall from grace,'' Allen Barra said here in 1998. The
City Game: From the Garden to the Playgrounds, by Pete Axthelm
(University of Nebraska, $12), is both a chronicle of the New York
Knicks 1969-70 championship season and a study of the era's
playground basketball culture, focusing on asphalt legends like
Herman (Helicopter) Knowings and Earl Manigault. ``The book offers
absorbing insights into the most unique and gripping of all city
sports,'' Rex Lardner wrote in these pages in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   CAESAR: LET THE DICE FLY
</P>
<P>
   By Colleen McCullough. Avon, $16.50.
</P>
<P>
   The author's fifth novel in her series on the fall of the Roman
Republic features the uprising of Gaul and Caesar's crossing of the
Rubicon, among other episodes. ``Such important events . . . unfold
as excitingly as if the history were not yet written,'' Allen
Lincoln wrote here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   UNFINISHED JOURNEY: TWENTY YEARS LATER
</P>
<P>
   By Yehudi Menuhin. Fromm, $19.
</P>
<P>
   In this revamped edition of his 1976 autobiography, the renowned
violinist, who died this month at the age of 82, holds forth on his
precocious musical education (he made his debut at 7) and his long,
eventful career. ``Menuhin is . . . a giant above us all when he
talks about music,'' Peggy Constantine wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING: A UTOPIAN DIVERTIMENTO
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Gordon. Scribner, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In this modern fairy tale, a middle-aged painter adopts a
sexually dynamic futures trader as her muse, prompting a struggle
between her artistic purity and the pleasures of the flesh (and the
wallet). ``Gordon is an honest and perceptive writer,'' Hilary
Mantel wrote in these pages last year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
