<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     03-26 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garry Winogrand prowled the public spaces of the United States
with his camera from 1959 to 1976 and stole glimpses of the
transitory lives around him. THE MAN IN THE CROWD: The Uneasy
Streets of Garry Winogrand (Fraenkel Gallery/
</P>
<P>
   Distributed Art Publishers, $45), with 107 black-and-white
photographs, is a retrospective of Winogrand's street photography.
Each image is filled with detail, rich gestures and complex motifs.
The best have a certain mystery and evocative power. Winogrand's
snapshot style captures the widening gyre of public life:
square-jawed businessmen give way to dazed and naked hippies. But
this is not a documentary project. Winogrand did not always note
the location or even the year of his pictures (one is labeled
``1968 or 1972''), and his voyeuristic, anonymous approach leaves
unanswered (and unanswerable) questions: Why is that pretty young
woman laughing? Is that dyspeptic man scowling because his life
tastes sour or because he didn't want his picture taken? Sometimes
an image resists reconstitution; for the viewer, poetry and mystery
can become alienation and frustration. Winogrand famously said that
he photographed to see what things look like as photographs.
Perhaps not surprisingly, when he died in 1984 he left behind
thousands of undeveloped negatives, thousands of unexamined lives.
_ JAKE MILLER
</P>
<P>
   AY CUBA!
</P>
<P>
   A Socio-Erotic Journey.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrei Codrescu.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's, $25.
</P>
<P>
   A likable romp -- and welcome light relief from too much
ponderous commentary on Cuba -- ``Ay Cuba!'' stands or falls on its
ability not so much to make you laugh as make you smile. The book's
charm is Andrei Codrescu's quirky insider's take on Communism (he
grew up in Romania until he was 19). An expert at reading between
the lines, whether of street hustlers or of Granma, the official
newspaper, Codrescu, a professor of literature at Louisiana State
University and commentator on the National Public Radio program
``All Things Considered,'' sees politics in human terms. However,
the early part of the book is rather a slog to get through, and the
writing -- a potpourri of commentary, observation and wisecracking
-- falls somewhere between travelogue and humor writing without
quite being either. Scenes tend to be too short; the longer ones,
such as Codrescu's hilarious and harrowing Santeria exorcism by
means of flapping cockerel, are noticeably the best. But the
picaresque cast is well drawn, from the cash-strapped urban planner
presiding over his scale model of old Havana to the many sirens of
the streets, and in the end it is refreshing to read a Cuban
account where the human takes such firm precedence over the
political. _ HENRY SHUKMAN
</P>
<P>
   IN PLATO'S CAVE
</P>
<P>
   By Alvin Kernan.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University, $25.
</P>
<P>
   As an administrator and professor of English at both Yale and
Princeton, Alvin Kernan has had as triumphant an academic career as
any scholar could hope for. Despite his numerous laurels, Kernan
refrains from looking back in triumph in this blend of
autobiography and commentary. Its very title signals this modesty
by alluding to the image with which Plato illustrated universal
human ignorance. Though Kernan concedes that his heart remains
devoted to the passing ``order in which I was trained,'' he refuses
to call its obsolescence a catastrophe. He occasionally swerves
toward censure, sagely refraining from pompous outrage and Golden
Age mythmaking; Kernan recalls that when Congress passed the G.I.
Bill, the president of the University of Chicago, Robert M.
Hutchins, warned that our universities might become ``educational
hobo jungles.'' He also remembers encountering ``sullen unread
students'' at Yale in the 1950's and deadening rote learning when
he was a student at Williams in the 1940's, where what counted was
``family, money, looks, athletic ability, personality. . . . Very
rarely intellect. . . . Never virtue.'' _ JAMES D. BLOOM
</P>
<P>
   CONTROVERSIES AND COMMANDERS
</P>
<P>
   Dispatches From the Army of the Potomac.
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen W. Sears.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $26.
</P>
<P>
   These lucid, rather jaunty essays on some of the persistent
mysteries, odd characters and hotly debated incidents of the Civil
War demonstrate why Stephen W. Sears has become one of the most
eminent historians of that conflict: he combines a wonderful
command of primary sources with a contagious enthusiasm. Those
qualities turn what might otherwise seem rather esoteric questions
involving the Union's main fighting force, the Army of the Potomac,
into lively forays in historical detection. There is, for instance,
Sears's excavation of the long unsettled question of just how the
famous ``Lost Order'' (Lee's plan for his 1862 campaign to smash
the Union forces) fell into Union hands. The intercepted document
spurred the notoriously timid commander of the Army of the Potomac,
George McClellan, into action, leading to the bloody battle of
Antietam. Sears offers frank appraisals of most of the
personalities involved, a convincing sketch of the chaotic Northern
and Southern command structures and communications, and a fresh,
persuasive explanation of what most likely happened. His command of
sources is on display in the masterly essay ``In Defense of
Fighting Joe,'' a careful exploration of the reasons the capable
Joseph Hooker, commanding the Army of the Potomac, failed to defeat
Lee's army at the battle of Chancellorsville when victory seemed
likely. Dismissing many of the myths that have grown up around the
battle, Sears employs a variety of documentary materials to come to
a simpler and more persuasive solution. Other essays -- on the
ill-conceived attempt by Union forces to raid Richmond and capture
Jefferson Davis; on the career of the bumptious Dan Sickles, who
almost cost the Union the battle of Gettysburg; and on the
court-martial of Maj. Gen. Fitz John Porter, an event that had
profound repercussions for the Army and the war -- offer a pleasing
blend of narrative color and scholarly precision. _ RICHARD E.
NICHOLLS
</P>
<P>
   LETTERS OF INTENT
</P>
<P>
   Women Cross Generations to Talk About Family, Work, Sex, Love
and the Future of Feminism.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Anna Bondoc and Meg Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Free Press, $23.
</P>
<P>
   This collection of epistolary exchanges between young feminists
and their ``foremothers'' may not have turned out exactly as
planned. The editors, Anna Bondoc and Meg Daly, acknowledge that
the older women took advantage of the format (the 20- and
30-somethings fired the initial salvos; the veterans responded) to
get in ``the last word.'' And how. When the freelance journalist
Liza Featherstone asks the psychologist Phyllis Chesler, her former
employer, why feminists make such harsh taskmasters, Chesler shoots
back that ``a feminist boss who occasionally yells or criticizes
real errors is not breaking your spirit. Women tend to experience
everything 'personally.' '' In a similar vein, the poet and
essayist Katha Pollitt reacts to the magazine editor Emily Gordon's
notion that established women writers should help their younger
counterparts with ``When did sisterhood become
mother-daughterhood?'' Happily, many of the young correspondents
pose larger questions. The journalist Sara Hammel asks Arie Taylor,
the first black noncommissioned officer in charge of women's Air
Force training, why women would choose to be in combat anyway. The
reply is straightforward: ``When men restrict who can fight and die
for America, they restrict who can run America.'' In the end,
despite Daly's claim that letters have brought together an
``interconnected web'' of women, the reader has a sense of having
encountered a host of independent spirits -- committed to feminist
ideals, but determined to tread their own paths. _ POLLY MORRICE
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
