<HEADER>
A5049 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX     03-26 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albanians hoping for peace, the second time around
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Recognize Kosovo, USA!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Free Kosovo! Down with Milosevic!''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who attended the Bosnian peace talks in November
1995, these chants _ and the image of 250 Albanian-Americans waving
a sea of red flags _ are indelibly etched in the memory. The
protesters demanded a place at the negotiating table for ethnic
Albanians from the Republic of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time many Daytonians learned of the plight of
Kosovo. The protesters may have seemed a boisterous side show to
the real work taking place somewhere beyond Gate 12A at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base. But their message _ there can be
no lasting peace in the Balkans without Kosovo _ turned out to be
prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of that protest, contacted Thursday at the offices of
the Democratic League of Kosovo in New York City, appear unswerving
in their support of NATO air strikes, despite the danger to their
loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   It's a danger that can't be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   When Agim Rexhaj called his father Wednesday night, the sound of
exploding bombs provided the static on the line. His father said,
``If something happened to us, then God bless America. This is the
moment we are waiting for. This is the only way for us to have a
free country, for the next generation to live in peace.'' The
family, who live in Peje _ some 45 miles northwest of the capital,
Pristina _ planned to flee to the mountains that night.
</P>
<P>
   Rexhaj is concerned about reports of thousands of Albanians
being detained, and of possible retaliation by the army of Serbian
President Slobodon Milosevic. He said he called his brother, a
judge in Peje, Thursday and a man speaking in Serbian answered the
phone. ``At first I thought I had the wrong number, but the man
said, `You have the right number. This is your brother's house, and
we killed him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a lie, but it could be the truth. I'm very worried
about this. What is going on?''
</P>
<P>
   Another of the protesters in 1995, Musa Dakaj, said Thursday
that the military action against Milosevic _ whom he called the
``Hitler of the Balkans'' _ is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Dakaj told the Dayton Daily News , ``Since 1990,
everything but the air we breathe is occupied.''
</P>
<P>
   He wishes the international community had listened back then.
``We are praying for our people there, and also for our troops who
are taking on this dangerous but noble mission,'' he said. ``After
Dayton, we lost faith in the international community. We decided
that, if any country can do it, it's the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   They may not get news of their families for weeks, months. But
the danger is nothing new. ``They have been in danger for the last
10 years,'' Dakaj said. ``Milosevic has been butchering people for
the last 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   What would have happened had their voices been heard in Dayton,
if Albanians had been included in the peace talks?
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back empty-handed from Dayton,'' Dakaj said. ``It was
unjust to us. It would have been a completely different situation
if the Albanians had been included. It would have finished the war
in the Balkans. They could have resolved the problem in Kosovo at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too late for that now. The Democratic League of Kosovo
believes NATO is their next best hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot wait for Milosevic to stop the killing of the
innocents,'' Rexhaj said. ``We cannot wait until he destroys
everything around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud I'm in the United States, and that we took the right
action. We pray for the women and men in the Army that God bless
them. They are heroes for the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Few paid much attention in Dayton in 1995, but today the world
is learning what the protesters prophesized: There can be no
lasting peace in the Balkans without peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
