<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN27-COX     03-26 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Immigrants teach us to appreciate what we have
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _
</P>
<P>
   The following is an excerpt from Jim Minter's book, ``Some
Things I Wish We Wouldn't Forget.''
</P>
<P>
   I pledge allegiance to the flag
</P>
<P>
   Of the United States of America,
</P>
<P>
   And to the Republic for which it stands,
</P>
<P>
   One nation under God, indivisible,
</P>
<P>
   With liberty and justice of all.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have we repeated the words, hand over heart, in
grade-school ceremonies, at civic club functions and the like,
saying but not really hearing?
</P>
<P>
   I heard them one afternoon from 98 adults and 13 children from
30 countries in Judge Robert Hall's courtroom in the Russell
Building in downtown Atlanta. Many of the new citizens had tears in
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They swore to defend their new country against all foreign
powers, to bear arms if called to do so. They pledged their
allegiance. Perhaps all Americans should stand in a courtroom and
do likewise from time to time, like a long-wedded couple renewing
marriage vows.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Henry Rodriguez is an immigrant. I had not seen him
for many months when he dropped in for a visit, bringing with him
his friend Medardo, who runs a plumbing business in Clayton County.
</P>
<P>
   Henry and Medardo have been acquainted since April 17, 1961.
They met on that day when Henry parachuted onto the beach at the
Bay of Pigs. Medardo, who was 17 years old, lived nearby. He joined
Henry's battalion in the fighting to free their homeland from Fidel
Castro's communist government.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, wearing his lieutenant's gold bars, was captured after
American naval forces lying offshore, following the orders of newly
elected President John Kennedy in Washington, declined to provide
promised supporting fire from the Navy's big guns.
</P>
<P>
   He spent nearly two years in a Castro prison, enduring torture
and hunger, losing from 200 pounds to under 150, so that when he
eventually got home, his wife could easily count his ribs. Medardo
escaped to the Italian Embassy in Havana, but not without seeing
friends and neighbors executed before Castro's firing squads. He
spent three years in hiding before being smuggled out of Cuba with
help from the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Although they no longer carry guns, Henry and Medardo are
freedom fighters, the term President Reagan used for patriots who
fought to overthrow the communist Sandinista regime in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Henry, who had become a prosperous contractor,
several times left Atlanta to make dangerous trips into the jungle,
delivering rice, boots, medicine and clothing to the Freedom
Fighters.
</P>
<P>
   His is a compelling story of one who has learned, painfully, a
deep appreciation of life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness,
the great promises of our Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Son of a substantial Cuban family, he was arrested for plotting
against the Batista regime during his student days at Cuba's
military academy. Briefly tempted by Castro after a personal
meeting with the charismatic revolutionary, he was firmly on the
opposite side by the time of the Bay of Pigs.
</P>
<P>
   After his release from prison he came to Atlanta, where he
earned a degree from Oglethorpe University. I met him in 1978, when
he was circulation director of The Atlanta Journal.
</P>
<P>
   He is in love with his adopted country, although baffled and
sometimes disappointed by the way we take things for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you a wonderful story,'' he said to me when he and
Medardo came to visit. ``You have been to my house in Atlanta. I
have a large back yard, enclosed by a 6-foot chain-link fence,
where I keep a duck, a goat, and a small pony for the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large German shepherd somehow broke into my yard,'' he
continued. ``He killed the duck, attacked the pony, and was maiming
the goat. I ran into the house and got a .22 rifle. I shot the
German shepherd. I killed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry knows it is illegal to discharge a firearm within the city
limits of Atlanta. He immediately notified the police of his deed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get a lawyer,'' he said. ``I went to court three
times. Although I knew the judge, I was afraid I would go to jail.
I was fined $75. Isn't that wonderful?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to hire a lawyer, you had to go to court three times,
you feared you might go to jail, and you had to pay a $75 fine, all
for defending your children's pets,'' I said. ``What's so wonderful
about that?
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of life,'' he replied. ``Here you get in trouble for
killing a dog. Where I have been, killing a human being is
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Medardo, smiling. ``It is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
