<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX     03-26 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Claims of police brutality need to be more scrupulously checked
 &HT;    By Roland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ One of the networks' Thursday morning infotainment
programs played grainy footage of a black man being abused by two
white plainclothes cops in Jonesboro, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't catch all the details, but it was evident that the
black man was standing perfectly still. His hands were handcuffed
behind his back when one of the Jonesboro officers hauled off and
knocked the man flat on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 1991 videotaped police beating of Rodney King in Los
Angeles, the Jonesboro police could not claim they feared for their
safety.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officers grabbed the black man by the neck and yanked
him back to his feet. It appeared that the officer continued to
choke the handcuffed man. At another point, an officer is shown
firing his handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the officers stopped the man as a suspected drug
dealer. Now the man has a lawyer. The Jonesboro police chief has
promised to investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, President Clinton said he was ``deeply disturbed''
about police violence. Perhaps he just said that to boost his
wife's chances to win a U.S. Senate seat in New York where police
violence directed at minorities has become a hot political issue.
Or perhaps he meant what he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton really is deeply disturbed about nationwide reports
of police violence and civil rights abuses, he should show some
leadership by ordering Attorney General Janet Reno to conduct a
full-scale investigation beginning in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the FBI investigates few of the police-abuse
allegations. Of those, less than 1 percent were pursued by federal
prosecutors in 1998, according to Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to minority Americans, polls show that white Americans
have a vastly different attitude about the fair enforcement of the
law by the nation's police forces.
</P>
<P>
   After several white New York police officers pumped a hail of
bullets into an unarmed black man with no criminal record, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani called for an investigation. He appears incapable
of understanding why minority citizens continue to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Hispanic Americans across the nation tell pollsters
that they believe they are stopped, searched and often abused for
no other reason than the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman has been forced to
backpedal from her denials that state troopers target minorities
for traffic stops and drug searches after the head of the state
police appeared to justify the practice.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey grand jury is considering criminal charges against
state troopers who literally went ballistic firing at unarmed
minority men on their way to a basketball game on the New Jersey
Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   A class action suit to stop racial profiling has been lodged
against the state of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities have lodged complaints for years against Louisiana
police officers for traffic stops based on DWH or DWB _ Driving
While Hispanic or Driving While Black.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, racial profiling, police violence and civil
rights abuses by can be traced to the escalating demands to win the
``war on drugs'' with arrests. Lock them them up, confiscate their
property for police use and throw away the key.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights and the Constitution have taken a severe beating
while the nation's jails and prisons have become packed from sea to
shining sea.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs should be combated by concentrating on prevention, not
incarceration. Politicians must swing the pendulum back toward the
constitutional protection of civil rights, as intended by the
nation's founders.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton should order the pursuit of all allegations of
unconstitutional police violence.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His columns appear Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail:
RNethaway(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
