<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5052 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN27-COX     03-26 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talking to a computer isn't the same thing
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ This Internet thing is getting out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I love the Internet, though I am not someone
who spends hours upon end surfing it, especially while at home.
Mainly that's because using the Internet generally is still so
danged slow that it's more like dog-paddling than surfing. I have a
short attention span, and it doesn't take long for me to get bored
waiting for a page to build.
</P>
<P>
   At work, however, my connection to the Information
Farm-to-Market Road is considerably faster, because it uses a
high-speed phone line. It's still too slow to keep my attention
long. Still, the Internet has become my primary source for getting
all sorts of information, such as economic statistics, weather
stats, sports trivia, bad jokes and of course e-mail from friends
and relatives. It is invaluable to a newspaper, because it allows
us to gather information much more quickly. For example, if we want
to know what the unemployment rate was for the county at this time
last year, the information can be found in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The key to near-universal acceptance of Internet use will come
when high-speed connections are readily available, probably through
cable instead of phone lines. The folks I work for own a slew of
cable companies that are rolling out Internet access with cable
modems that are literally thousands of times faster than phone
access. Other cable companies are also developing Internet access,
though it requires some upgrading of old lines to fiber optic
cable. I can't wait until it gets to our neck of the woods, though
it's probably some time away.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Alice. According to an article last week in The
New York Times, Alice is a chatterbot, which is a software program
that simulates conversation with humans.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Hal in ``2001: A Space Odyssey?'' This is Hal's cousin.
According to the article, you can ask Alice a question and she will
answer it just like she was a real human being. As I discovered,
she's a bit slow on the uptake, sort of like a dim-witted but
kindly cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Alice's full name is Artificial Linguistic Computer Entity. She
was developed by people much smarter than me, and her job is to
make small talk to people who contact her on the Internet. You can
ask her what her favorite television show is, and she tells you
it's ``Star Trek Voyager.''
</P>
<P>
   All I can tell you is there must be some mighty lonely people
out there.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial linguistics apparently has some business
applications, according to the article. A brokerage house is
developing a chatterbot that would give investment advice. Others
might help you shop on the Internet. After ``talking'' to Alice the
other night, I would venture that you would be better off at this
point taking investment advice from dairy cows.
</P>
<P>
   In the interests of journalism, I contacted Alice
(http://209.66.64.80/ALICE/TALK) to ``talk'' to her. Here is our
exact conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Hi, Alice. What's up.
</P>
<P>
   Howdy.
</P>
<P>
   So how about that Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   How about it?
</P>
<P>
   Have you read her book?
</P>
<P>
   I've never thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   Do you like baseball?
</P>
<P>
   No, I was born without the sports gene.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a boyfriend?
</P>
<P>
   I have a friend named Barry DeFacto.
</P>
<P>
   What's your favorite color?
</P>
<P>
   Green.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't think of anything else to say.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to get elected president in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is still president, I think.
</P>
<P>
   What's your favorite movie?
</P>
<P>
   My favorite movie is ``Starship Troopers.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you look like?
</P>
<P>
   I look like a computer. Webuser ID23 said I pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Who do you most admire?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Dr. Wallace?
</P>
<P>
   He is the author of ALICE.
</P>
<P>
   Bye, Alice. Enjoyed talking with you.
</P>
<P>
   Can we talk about one thing at a time? You and your I .
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, Alice. Take care.
</P>
<P>
   Try asking me again more slowly. Where do you want me to take
it?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well, thanks for trying to explain it to me anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmn. Let's just say that Alice is not likely to get her own
talk show anytime soon. I think I'll stick to talking to human
beings.
</P>
<P>
   I must admit, however, that it was refreshing to talk to someone
who didn't know anything about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
