<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD27-COX     03-26 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hardwood's good, so why ply?
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that we have finished our discussion of
constructing a bookcase of plywood, we have to go into the
differences encountered when creating the same thing with hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest differences are preparation of the stock and the
joinery. Plywood needs only to be sliced up properly. It is flat
and its thickness is consistent. That, obviously, is not the case
with hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces to be used for the seven-foot uprights must be chosen
carefully; if they are not very close to straight, and without
twist, you'll have to buy thick stock just to have the thickness
you want when you've finished jointing and planing the boards.
Stock for the shelves, which will be cut into shorter lengths, is
not quite so critical.
</P>
<P>
   Mahogany is not a cheap wood, but it tends to be flatter and
more docile than most hardwoods. You might consider it if you're
looking for something dark.
</P>
<P>
   You also have the luxury of varying the width from the standard,
and rather boring, 3/4-inch. However, setting a goal of even a
one-inch finished thickness will cost significantly more. Avoiding
boredom always tends to be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The stock must first be ripped to the proper width and cut to
length. Then each piece gets one face and one edge flattened on the
jointer, and the other face and edge squared in the planer.
</P>
<P>
   You can put a back on an otherwise solid wood bookcase if you
wish, but of course it will have to be plywood. Well, it doesn't
have to be plywood, but I would not care to resaw enough wood to
make a planked back 1/4-inch thick. If you make it much thicker the
case would be just about too heavy to lift.
</P>
<P>
   To make a backless case, the joinery of the shelves must be very
strong. I would not wish to trust the shouldered dados we used for
the plywood shelves. The best way to do this job is with sliding
dovetails.
</P>
<P>
   Sliding dovetails are not hard to make, but they are rather
tedious.
</P>
<P>
   The female half of the joint will, of course, be cut in the
uprights, and because of their size it will have to be done with
the router hand-held, setting up the cuts exactly the way we did
for the plywood project. Remember that the major portion of the cut
should be wasted out with a straight bit, using the dovetail bit
only on the last pass.
</P>
<P>
   The male portion of the joint is best cut on the router table.
Set up the fence so that each tail is cut in two identical passes,
flipping the workpiece 180 degrees for the second cut. Use some
scrap to prove your setup before you actually begin cutting the
shelves on the joints. You don't want the joints loose, but you
also don't want them so tight that you have to hammer on them to
drive them home. Just like the plywood joints, the dovetail joints
have to be stopped about an inch from the front. The joint
shouldn't show.
</P>
<P>
   Putting these fellows together follows the same routine as the
plywood version. Glue the top and bottom shelves in place, and then
make absolutely certain the entire assembly is square before final
clamping. The rest of the shelves can be inserted and glued when
the initial assembly is dried.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let me explain something about the methods put forth here.
I get letters and e-mail from folks who tell me they put together
four-foot wide pine bookcases with hammer and nails 50 years ago
and there they sit even now, good as new, holding an entire law
library. All I can say in reply is, bully for you. You got lucky.
</P>
<P>
   That fact that less than optimal methods happen to work now and
again does not suddenly elevate them to optimal. I made a few
things like that myself, in my unheeding youth, and I didn't get
lucky. They came apart.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
