<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0326 _ It's a phenomenon of nature that's older
than modern humans. Yet within our lifetime, we may destroy it. The
miraculous journey of the Monarch butterflies from Canada, through
the United States and into Mexico and back is one of the world's
greatest natural events. (Ferriss, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEART MACHINE _ A new, easy-to-use device that jump-starts
a stopped heart could save up to 100,000 lives a year, if it goes
into widespread use. (Lee Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS _ (Staff, Cox News Service)(EDS: This is the
CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week. This layout will be
available Friday by 5 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   INFANT-MASSAGE _ You rub their tiny little bodies and something
magical happens. They relax and so do you. Infant massage, a
technique developed to help calm drug-addicted babies, has gone
mainstream, with classes all over Atlanta teaching moms how to
better interact with their babes. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE CABINET _ A look at what should be in your medicine
cabinet. (Santos, Austin American-Statesman). WITH
PHOTO/ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BUTTERFLIES _ EL ROSARIO, Mexico _ It's a phenomenon of
nature that's older than modern humans. Yet within our lifetime, we
may destroy it. The miraculous journey of the Monarch butterflies
from Canada, through the United States and into Mexico and back is
one of the world's greatest natural events. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (l) Lifestyle and (i) International
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS: Migration route of Monarch butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Now that we have finished our
discussion of constructing a bookcase of plywood, we have to go
into the differences encountered when creating the same thing with
hardwood. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FLANNERY-LETTERS _ Flannery O'Connor explained herself to the
rest of the world in 250 letters she exchanged with an Atlanta
woman who for 76 years lived such an unassuming life that she was
seemingly invisible. (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
ILLUSTRATIONS. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   PASSOVER _ Freedom is the message of this annual holiday that
focuses on the story of Exodus and the journey of the Children of
Israel from slaves in Egypt to contact with God at Mt. Sinai. The
spiritual stuff aside, this is the most observed Jewish holiday and
a celebration that takes weeks of preparation. We explore both the
spiritual dimension of Passover and the nitty-gritty details of
preparing for the eight-day event. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDENEASTER-TABLETOPS _ If you want to create that party
perfect table for Easter, turn it into a pastel fantasy. Use the
pretty shades of traditionally dyed eggs _ lemon yellow, lavender,
pale green and apricot _ to create a fashionable, tasteful look.
Easter, for Atlanta interior designer Bill Cook, has always been
his favorite holiday. ``It celebrates spring,'' he says. ``And you
have all the wonderful shades of the new season with which to
work.'' As a challenge, we asked Cook to set two contemporary
Easter tables _ an inexpensive look and a pricier version. Although
we used everything new for our settings, you might want to include
nostalgic family favorites on your table. (MJohnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-EXPENSIVE-HOMES _ MANALAPAN, Fla. _ Frank McKinney insists
he's not a gambler, just a developer in tune with what the
mega-wealthy want. The $12 million castle he built in Delray Beach,
Fla. three years ago was one of the country's most expensive houses
built without a buyer lined up. Now, McKinney is set to build his
fourth house so-called spec house: Priced at $39 million, it could
be the most expensive in the world. With a glass-domed rotunda big
enough to seat 150 for dinner, a game room as big as the average
house and a 5,000-square-foot master bedroom suite, McKinney says
this is no wild dream. ``It's a business decision. I think God gave
me a gift to determine what these people want,'' he said. A $12
million spec house is one thing _ but $39 million? (Van de Water,
Palm Beach Post). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
