<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ If Clinton really is deeply
disturbed about nationwide reports of police violence and civil
rights abuses, he should show some leadership by ordering Attorney
General Janet Reno to conduct a full-scale investigation. (Rowland
Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Immigrants teach us to
appreciate what we have. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Few paid much attention in
Dayton in 1995, but today the world is learning what the protesters
prophesized: There can be no lasting peace in the Balkans without
peace in Kosovo. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Remember Hal in ``2001: A
Space Odyssey?'' This is Hal's cousin, and her name is ALICE. This
Internet thing is getting out of hand. (Gary Borders is editor and
publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The United States is taking a bad rap for its
refusal to sign the land-mine ban, sometimes from friends _ Canada
is appalled _ but more often from nations to which the issue offers
easy posturing and even from nations so blithely evil they'll sign
anything virtuous-sounding without the slightest intention of
honoring the deal. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Were I Bill Clinton (and I'm delighted that
I'm not) here's what I would have done. I would have picked up the
phone and placed a call to Boris Yeltsin in the Kremlin. ``Boris,''
I would begin, ``this guy Milosevic, with whom we've had trouble in
the past, is murdering a lot of ethnic Albanians and we need to put
a stop to it.'' (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ The United States declared a state
of war today as waves of Mexican warplanes pounded U.S. military
targets in a campaign to force Washington to accept an
international peace plan for Texas. (Andy Glass is a columnist for
Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SUNDAY
