<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, March 26, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday, Sunday and Monday. If you have questions, please call Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MISSING (San Francisco) _ With the discovery of a female
body in the mining country west of Yosemite National Park, the
search for a missing teenage sightseer may come to a final, tragic
end. The FBI was trying to determine if the body is one of two
teenage girls who disappeared in mid-February during an outing to
Yosemite. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN and ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-DELAYS (Albany, N.Y.) _ As airports get increasingly
congested, travelers are spending more time packed tightly into
airline seats, leading to stress and frustration. More than 3,600
planes sat on the ground for more than two hours last year,
according to the Transportation Department. The situation is likely
to get much worse before it gets better. By CELINA OTTAWAY. (For
release Sunday, March 28.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUNANAN-BOOK (San Francisco) _ Maureen Orth'S first book is
called ``Vulgar Favors: Andrew Cunanan, Gianni Versace and the
Largest Failed Manhunt in U.S. History'' (Delacorte Press).
Cunanan, says Orth, ``never lived in reality. He was spoiled and so
materialistic that he realized the only way he could get everything
he wanted was to sell himself.'' By CYNTHIA ROBINS. (For release
Monday, March 29.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WAR-COVERAGE (Undated) _ We're not in Monicaland anymore. And
it's clear after watching two days of coverage on the nation's
biggest story _ a NATO strike against Yugoslavia _ that many
broadcast news organizations are rusty at real news, their
instincts and ability to mobilize slackened and atrophied by more
than a year of nonstop yakking about oral sex. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ED (Undated) _ One of Hollywood's more inscrutable
mysteries is its tendency to make two movies with the same premise
at about the same time. Ten months after the release of ``The
Truman Show,'' Peter Weir's breathtaking light-dark fantasy about a
man whose life is a television show, we have ``EDtv,'' about a man
whose life is a television show. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-FUTURAMA (Undated) _ It's almost unfair to judge Matt
Groening's latest work, ``Futurama.'' This is the guy who created
``The Simpsons,'' which with each season moves farther away from
just being the best animated series ever toward being the best
comedy ever. The new show isn't bad; it's not bad at all. Just not
all that great yet. Maybe we are all just spoiled. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MOD (Undated) _ Remaking ``The Mod Squad'' is like
cheating off one of the dumber kids in class: Shame! Still, before
director Scott Silver is banished to the principal's office for
copying, he gets a few props for staying within the lines of the
original show. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-20-DATES (Undated) _ ``20 Dates'' is about a moron _
oxy and otherwise. A neurotic jerk of a struggling actor looking
for true love in Hollywood. It's a documentary (snicker, snicker),
meant to be the personal journey soul-searching kind, akin to Ross
McEwee's ``Sherman's March.'' Only Myles Berkowitz doesn't appear
to have a soul, just an ego that fails to grasp why women don't
love him. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLADE-SKIING (Stowe, Vt.) _ Out on Stowe Mountain Resort's many
trails, the slopes were icy and hard. But here in the trees, there
was ample soft powder and no people. And even though I often
descend at a bumbling pace, I'd still rather ski in here than out
on the trails. For those who don't mind the risk, glade or tree
skiing is one of the most exciting ways to schuss down a mountain.
By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-RACING (Albany, Calif.) _ We're certainly living in a
world different from that of 1947, when 30,000 or more people would
show up at Golden Gate Fields for a day of racing. Average daily
attendance over approximately 100 days of racing is not much more
than 3,000 now, for a host of reasons. By GEORGE RAINE. (Also filed
in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAME-EATING (Tucson, Ariz.) _ While eating healthy and losing
weight may seem nearly impossible-to-keep resolutions, the answer
for many is easier than you might think. Most game meats have fewer
calories and contain less fat than conventional meats sold at the
supermarket. While 100 grams of uncooked lean hamburger contain 272
calories and 18 grams of fat, the same amount of deer meat has only
120 calories and 2 grams of fat. A person can consume 56 percent
fewer calories by simply substituting ground venison for hamburger.
By G.J. SAGI.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Here was President Clinton on TV,
pointing to a map of Europe, showing Americans where Serbia and
Kosovo are. It reminded me of a rule of war many of us have learned
over the last half-century: Never go to war with a country you
can't find on a map. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
