<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-UNDER-STRESS-AND-MORE--ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRESS AND YOUR SHRINKING BRAIN
</P>
<P>
   THE PHYSICS OF TRAFFIC
</P>
<P>
   These are stories that clients of DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE recently
received.
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE, which is available through The New York
Times Syndicate, captures all the wonders of discovery in the
environment, medicine, prehistory, space and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, Discover News Service delivers fascinating,
trustworthy coverage in two tightly edited features (available in
Spanish, too). Plus superb color art brings all the discoveries to
life.
</P>
<P>
   The features described below are available for ONE-SHOT PURCHASE
by calling Debra Weydert at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   -------- ALL THE ART IS FREE OF CHARGE! --------
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRESS AND YOUR SHRINKING BRAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TWO B&AMP;W PHOTOS AND ONE COLOR SLIDE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words plus a 200-word sidebar) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT SAPOLSKY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Stress hormones can help us escape a leopard. But in excess,
they may do a lot of damage to the brain. For example, take an
18-year-old, stick him in a uniform, ship him off to a war and
expose him to something horrific _ say, a battle in which he's the
only soldier in his unit to survive. Chances are that some day he
may suffer from post-traumatic stress disorder. By studying
magnetic resonance images of the hippocampus of patients with PTSD,
scientists are detecting new clues about the relationship between
stress and the brain. Robert Sapolsky is a professor of
neuroscience at Stanford who studies stress-induced diseases. He is
the author of ``Why Zebras Don't Get Ulcers.''
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-STRESS-AND-BRAIN-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PHYSICS OF TRAFFIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT KUNZIG &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Two theoretical physicists ponder the snarly equation of highway
traffic and come up with possible cures for congestion. Using
computer models that treat cars on highways like molecules in a
gas, a team of American and German physicists offers more than a
road paved with good intentions. Robert Kunzig is the European
Editor at Discover magazine.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-TREATING-TRAFFIC-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
