<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-HILLS-$ADV28-     03-26 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-HILLS-$ADV28-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-COUNTRY INTERLUDE AND RECONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVON, Colo. _ The house is empty this morning, save for me and
the dog. And she's asleep. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My wife (who, in another life, used to teach skiing) and our
friends have headed over to nearby Vail to take a few runs down the
mountain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't ski. Except for going down a small hill a few times in
my great aunt's backyard in Stockholm, Sweden, in 1958, I've never
been on skis. I have other athletic vices. Besides, I figure if I
want to have my leg broken I know several people who'd be willing
to oblige _ and at considerably less than the cost of a ski-lift
ticket, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what I am doing this morning is what, in my experience,
almost none of us does enough. I am being alone with myself with no
mandatory agenda. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am giving myself this gift of time to become reacquainted with
myself, to listen to places in my soul that often get ignored
because my life is so busy, noisy, spoken for. This is no
complaint. I love my life. I have made choices _ most of them good.
And I am able, much of the time, to live a life reasonably well
centered on the eternal values that give it meaning and purpose. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But now and then I realize that the core of me has simply been
along for the ride for too long. I need to acknowledge my central
essence and try to listen to how it is doing and what it would tell
me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So in this morning mountain chill, on a bright, azure day, I am
sitting on the deck of the house in which we're staying and am
trying simply to be, trying just to be mindful, as the Buddhists
say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across a crooked valley of homes the mountains are dappled with
snow and tiny skiers that I have to squint at to see moving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mountains always humble me. They tell me I am dust and to dust I
will return. They tell me I am a small, dim flash on history's
radar screen, and yet even one so insignificant is given the
common-grace gift of mountains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mountains tell me, too, of the human capacity for grandeur. On
the way up here last night, we drove through the Eisenhower tunnel,
a mile-plus, four-lane part of Interstate 70 lasered through the
belly of a mountain. I remarked then to my wife on the astonishing
engineering required to carry out so bold and seemingly reckless an
idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And isn't that the human condition? We are at once transient
renters on this planet _ ``aliens and strangers,'' I Peter 2:11
calls us in the New International Version of the Bible. And yet
while we are here we imagine and create electrifying things, from
mountain tunnels to skyscrapers, from poetry to sculpture, from
airplanes to space telescopes to, well, Y2K computer bugs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the evidence of ageless mountains and stars, somehow we
are convinced that a human life's normal span _ now 75 or 80 years
in this country _ is a long time, certainly enough to create
something lasting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After dinner last night I stepped out onto the deck to look at
the stunning night sky. In crystal air, more than a mile and a half
above sea level, the stars _ not hidden by the light pollution of
the metropolis in which I live _ took my breath away. This was, in
modern electronic culture terms, the high-definition television
version of a nightly show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And I was reminded of a thought from a book I just read,
``Amazing Grace: A Vocabulary of Faith.'' Author Kathleen Norris
reminds us there that all the atoms that make up human beings once
were part of distant stars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This morning, alone, listening in silence, I'm grateful to be so
physically connected to the cosmos. I'm also glad to be reconnected
to the uniqueness of my being and to celebrate the truth that
although the soulless mountains and stars cannot think about me, I
can think about both them and me. And so I do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, March 28, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5157 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAE-BO-DIARY-AZR &LR;      03-26 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAE-BO-DIARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30 DAYS TO TAE-BO MASTERY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
By THOMAS ROPP  
c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I don't usually pay attention to infomercials, but
this one grabs me. Everyone is kung-fu fighting.
</P>
<P>
   With oneself.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's more like aerobics with bite, or rather, kick.
There's one lead instructor with a dozen or so backups behind him.
I'm especially riveted by the frenzy of kicking, punching and leg
lifts, all synched and choreographed to a driving, hypnotic
soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The voiceover calls it Tae-Bo, the future of fitness. Featured
is a lean, charismatic man with soulful eyes who kicks and jabs
with machinelike precision. His name is Billy Blanks, seven-time
world martial arts champion and Tae-Bo's inventor. He, like the
workout, speaks directly to me.
</P>
<P>
   He's saying, ``That will be $69.95, please.''  &QL; 
Day 1
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, the four videotapes arrive. Considerably less
inspired since getting hooked on the infomercial, I'm feeling a
little foolish for spending so much money on something that may be
an out-and-out scam. In fact, I still don't understand what Tae-Bo
is exactly. Friends tell me it's a funky hybrid of kick boxing,
martial arts and aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes after the tapes arrive, I begin my own Tae-Bo
adventure. There are no written instructions, so I don't know what
tape to watch first, but I pop in the Instructional video, figuring
that makes more sense than the other three: Basic, Advanced and
8-Minute Workout.
</P>
<P>
   The running time of the Instructional tape is about 40 minutes.
It starts with a warmup and slides into how to execute various
types of punches, kicks and leg raises.
</P>
<P>
   I spend nearly 90 minutes, stopping and starting the video to
practice one move before going on to the next. I'm doing pretty
well until the roundhouse kick. Billy says to hold your leg out to
your side, level enough to balance a glass of water on it. Funny
guy. I'm looking at a whole lot of water in my sock.  &QL; 
Day 2
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continue with learning the Instructional tape. It's like
learning the steps to a fast dance. I stop and start the tape,
learning each move before going to the next. I find myself breaking
out into these moves unexpectedly during the day. No one seems to
appreciate my new talents. I think I'm being observed. &QL; 
Day 3
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Begin Basic video.
</P>
<P>
   Am really glad I took the time to learn the moves in the
Instructional video. Footwork on jabs shaky, and roundhouse kicks
still pathetic, but I'm keeping up, even when the workout shifts
into double time.
</P>
<P>
   Some moves, such as punching at an invisible ``speed bag,'' are
not covered in the Instructional tape but are easy to learn. At
least they appear easy. Doing them correctly is another matter. To
get maximum benefit, the speed bag exercise requires keeping upper
and lower arm muscles taut. Stomach muscles are always taut. Blanks
isn't bashful about reminding to keep abs tight, ribs high.
Overall, he speaks softly, carries a big kick.
</P>
<P>
   The full Basic workout runs about 20 minutes, culminating in a
leg-burning set of double-time roundhouse kicks shifting between
left and right sides.
</P>
<P>
   I'm impressed. Sweating profusely, I feel better about my Tae-Bo
investment. It's a good, honest workout. I expected something
harder. I'm a runner, which probably helps my endurance at Tae-Bo.
But I think anyone who is in good health could complete this
workout.
</P>
<P>
   A tae-chi type cool-down follows the workout. Shifting from
frenzy to ballet, Billy leads me through a slow, mysterious
exercise that requires scooping up air and pushing it from side to
side. Strange as it seems, I can actually feel the energy move
around me.
</P>
<P>
   It's a calming sensation. I feel in balance. &QL; 
Day 4
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No longer in balance. Sore as hell. Especially the backs of the
legs, abs and shoulders. I guess this is a barometer of benefits.
But there's also a sharp pain in my neck that can't be good. Feels
like I've thrown something out of whack. I'm not sure how it
happened. I may have put myself in an awkward position while trying
to watch the tape and do the workout at the same time. &QL; 
Days 5-16
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continue with the Basic workout. The pain in the neck has not
gone away. A trip to the chiropractor may not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected side effect has developed: I'm told that I've
become unusually punchy, a 5-year-old with a stick. It's true. I
suddenly have urges to kick and punch no matter where I am or what
I'm doing.
</P>
<P>
   People are standing back when they talk to me.
</P>
<P>
   A not-so-subtle friend suggests Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   While out running, I encounter two dogs approaching my flank
aggressively. Without breaking stride, I turn my head sharply and
tell the lead mutt, ``No!'' Surprised, he falls; the dog behind him
falls, too. My neck pain disappears. &QL; 
Day 17
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I try my hand (and foot) at the Advanced workout.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Madre de dios! (end ital) Now I understand the term
``hellbent.'' It's diabolical to bend a person's body like this for
so long. Billy does have a cruel side. The soft-spoken apostle of
fitness from the Basic workout has morphed into Godzilla in
leotards as he roars fiery commands and pushes his troops toward
Tae-Bo oblivion in the Advanced workout.
</P>
<P>
   This one is three times longer (60 minutes) but 10 times more
difficult. There are many new, intricate moves performed at
supersonic speeds.
</P>
<P>
   I can't keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the tape, Billy delivers the coup de grace when
the workout drops to the floor for 20 minutes of grueling leg
extensions. Even his perfectly chiseled, fat-free backups do some
serious moaning during the stretch run of this workout.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as hard to watch as it is to do. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Days 18-28
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pain of the Advanced workout grows on me.
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe what a sniveling wimp I was the first time I
tried the Advanced tape. However, the floor exercises are still a
bit much. I'm dividing the Advanced workout into two sessions: 30
minutes of the stand-up workout one day, followed by the 20-minute
down-on-the-floor exercises the next day.
</P>
<P>
   As God is my witness, someday I will complete the entire
Advanced workout as Billy intended. &QL; 
Day 29
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remembered I had another video. Popped in the 8-Minute Workout,
and eight minutes later, popped it back out.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't even work up a sweat. Come on, Billy, admit it, this
video is padding.
</P>
<P>
   Truncated Tae-Bo is like jumping rope with one hand. If I really
wanted a workout shortened that dramatically, I'd just do the Basic
20-minute workout for eight minutes and move on to my next meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Scale check. After four weeks of Tae-Boing, I have lost exactly
. . . 2 pounds?
</P>
<P>
   Good thing I didn't do this to lose weight. &QL; 
Day 30
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I thought I was making some real progress until a black-belt
friend of mine pointed out that my stationary foot was not pivoted
properly for side-kick action. My kicking technique was learned by
what I could see on the video, which obviously wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   My major criticism of the Tae-Bo tapes is that they could use
more detailed instruction, especially on footwork.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not stopping the tapes from selling. According to
``Time,'' the Tae-Bo videos have grossed $75 million in less than
six months since their release. And 43-year-old Blanks has signed a
$1.5 million advance with Bantam to write an exercise book.
</P>
<P>
   Blanks is also gearing up to release 24 more Tae-Bo tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Target stores are now selling just the Instructional and Basic
tapes as a package for $34.99.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to do it all over again, I'd just buy the first two
tapes, then maybe another tape or two as they came out.
</P>
<P>
   Taking real classes with a real interactive instructor would be
even better.
</P>
<P>
   The four-tape set, selling for $59.85, can be purchased by
calling 1-800-637-6632. Learn more about Billy Blanks and Tae-Bo at
www.taebo.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
