<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-BASEBALL27-COX     03-26 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BASEBALL27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE U.S. PLAYS BALL AND MAKES MUSIC WITH CUBA, DRAWING CRITICISM
 &HT;    730&AMP;add. Moving in both the (i) international and (s) sports
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Anticipation's been building in Cuba all week: the
Yankees are coming.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not the Yankees exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the Baltimore Orioles will become the first Major League
Baseball team to stand on a Havana diamond in 40 years when they
face off at noon EST Sunday against a 27-man squad of Cuban
all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, hours later, dozens of U.S. musicians, including
Jimmy Buffett and the Atlanta-based Indigo Girls, will stage a free
invitation-only concert at the Karl Marx theater, also in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball diplomacy. Pop music diplomacy. There seems to be all
kinds of diplomacy going on this weekend between the United States
and its communist archenemy just 90 miles from South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone's in a festive mood.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-line Cuban exiles are outraged, warning that this weekend's
events will do little but provide cheap publicity for Cuba's
repressive leader, Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that these people can still be playing baseball while
the Cuban people are experiencing a new wave of repression is
patently offensive,'' said Alberto M. Hernandez, chairman of the
Cuban American National Foundation, the nation's most powerful
anti-Castro group.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, the Cuban government handed down harsh
prison sentences for four well-known Cuban dissidents who openly
criticized the Communist Party, drawing condemnations from even
Canada and the European Union, countries that want normal trade
with the island to resume.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba also approved a law that imposes severe penalties against
political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say the events are largely symbolic and don't go
far enough to engage Cuba and end decades of hostility with the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe more engagement would give us more leverage in
Cuba's affairs,'' said Damian Fernandez, an expert on Cuba at
Florida International University.
</P>
<P>
   But will these star-studded events lead to an overall warming of
U.S.-Cuba relations? Will Castro _ a former baseball pitcher who
will attend Sunday's game _ provide a symbol of this thaw by
throwing out the first ball?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the answers.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the events have aroused great interest in baseball-mad
Havana, where the rustic Estadio Latinoamericano _ which seats
50,000 and serves coffee and ham sandwiches _ is expected to be
packed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The last time major league teams played ball in Cuba was in
March 1959, when the Los Angeles Dodgers went to bat against the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here really like Americans, so we're happy to have
so many Americans here,'' said Amado Alvarez, a painter and
baseball fanatic. ``Cuban players are very good, so we are sure
they'll perform well against the Orioles.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Alvarez, tickets for the game won't be made
available to the general public. Rather, they'll be set aside by
the Cuban government for selected groups, such as foreign reporters
and school organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Cable sports network ESPN plans to broadcast the game.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Clinton administration says the cultural
exchanges are an attempt to boost people-to-people contacts, part
of an overall strategy to isolate Castro and foster openness on the
island. Washington authorized the events on Jan. 5 as exceptions to
an economic embargo imposed against Cuba in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans are scheduled to play a return game at Camden Yards
in Baltimore on May 3.
</P>
<P>
   The contacts ``expose the Cuban people to the values of a free
society ... and help them prepare for a better tomorrow,'' said
Michael Ranneberger, the Clinton administration's coordinator of
Cuban affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He said the events shouldn't be seen as moves toward closer ties
with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Any proceeds from the game will go not to the Castro government,
but to fund sports activities, mostly among Cuban youth.
</P>
<P>
   But even U.S. officials agree that the timing of the events is
ticklish.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Clinton administration's promotion of
people-to-people contacts has made the Cuban government a bit wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people-to-people contacts are carried out in a
non-political way, then that will be good,'' said Roberto de Armas,
a Cuban government spokesman. ``But if they're used in a political
way, the future of these kinds of contacts could be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Those participating in this weekend's events say politics isn't
even on their radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carter, who manages the Indigo Girls, say Amy Ray and
Emily Saliers are doing what they love best: collaborating with
other musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy and Emily have music on their minds, not politics,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Cuba hosted a major American concert was in 1979,
when Billy Joel and Kris Kristofferson performed at an event titled
``Havana Jams.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, more than 40 performers, including Burt Bacharach,
James Taylor, and Gladys Knight, began arriving in Havana for a
week of songwriting and jam sessions with their Cuban counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Roy Scott, the California songwriter behind the exchange
known as ``Music Bridges Over Troubled Waters,'' said Sunday's
concert carries no political overtones.
</P>
<P>
   And neither does the baseball game, said Joe Foss, the Orioles'
vice chairman for business and finance. He said the team hopes the
games ``can help people in the two countries come together.''
</P>
<P>
   But not since the visit to Cuba by Pope John Paul II in January
1998 has such a debate erupted over the future of an ideological
divide that dates back to the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the U.S. Senate approved a resolution 98-0 urging
the Clinton administration to mobilize international pressure for
political change on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed a similar resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-American members of Congress have chastised the
administration for allowing baseball players and musicians to
travel to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the wrong signal: if the United States can play ball with
Castro, then there can't be any serious problems there,'' said Rep.
Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Some liken this weekend's events to the famous ``ping-pong''
diplomacy between the United States and China in the early 1970s,
when a visit by the U.S. national table tennis team helped pave the
way for President Nixon's official talks with China's communist
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers predict the events in Cuba will have little
overall impact on U.S.-Cuba relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect relations to get better any time soon,''
said Wayne Smith, who headed the U.S. Interests Section in Havana
during the Carter administration. ``In fact, official relations
could hardly grow any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, relations have deteriorated as Washington
condemned the harsh sentences imposed on the dissidents, and Cuba
cut off most U.S. telephone links due to unpaid bills by American
phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   But if nothing else, Kirby Jones, a Washington consultant, said
this weekend's events have spurred more interest among U.S.
businesspeople in Cuba. He said dozens of U.S. companies have
signed up for a U.S.-Cuba Business Summit scheduled for May 19 in
Cancun, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it is baseball fever, but there appears to be more
interest in Cuba now than there was last year,'' said Jones, who
has already led two business delegations to Cuba. ``The game has
symbolic importance, and it seems to be captivating people even
more than the pope's visit.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
