<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-DELAYS-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING THE BUSY SKIES MAY GET MORE STRESSFUL IN YEARS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As airports get more congested and flights fill
up, travelers are spending more time packed tightly into airline
seats. Some are waiting on tarmacs for hours as planes line up for
takeoff. Others are hovering in holding patterns, waiting to land
or diverting to other airports.
</P>
<P>
   Spending extra time in a plane, even in the best of conditions,
means stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sat (on the tarmac) for two, three hours sometimes. You
feel the temperature go up in the plane,'' said Ralph Sargent, who
recently endured a four-hour stress fest of holding patterns and
then a fuel shortage that landed him and his family at the Albany
International Airport. ``People get tense.''
</P>
<P>
   When the waiting follows a stressful ride, the confinement of an
airplane seat can seem unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perspiration began and the plane turned into a steam
bath,'' said Ralph, who had been on what should have been a
relatively short hop from Atlanta to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In one extreme case, thousands of Northwest Airlines passengers
in Detroit had to sit in planes on the tarmac for up to 11 hours
during a January snowstorm. Toilets overflowed. Many had no food or
water.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is discussing a ``passenger bill of rights'' that would
force airlines to pay compensation to passengers kept waiting on a
runway for more than two hours, require explanation for delays and
cancellations and provide food and restroom facilities during
delays, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,600 planes sat on the ground for more than two hours
last year, according to the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The future looks worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration predicts that unless airport
capacity increases, congestion and delays at the major hubs will
grow in the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Good news for authors John Grisham and Danielle Steel. Bummer
for the rest of us who are trying to stake out some elbow room. Or
battling feelings of claustrophobia.
</P>
<P>
   Regular travelers and psychologists say a simple diversion like
a good book, soothing music or interesting conversation can do a
lot to help.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Chris Saunders of Whitesboro, N.Y., spent an
hour of serious get-to-know-you time on the ground in Syracuse
waiting for his flight for Las Vegas to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just bonding, bonding, everyone bonded,'' he said.
``The longer the time we had to wait, the louder it got on the
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking to people (if they are friendly) can be one of the best
ways to calm anxieties and use extra time on an airplane, said
Joyce Tanzer, a psychologist with Hillside Hospital in Queens, N.Y.
Tanzer works in the hospital's anxiety and phobia clinic. She uses
a virtual-reality machine to help people with their fear of flying.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in plans and unexpected delays can trigger fearful
thoughts in people who aren't normally afraid of planes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think something must be wrong, if not this plane, then
someone else's, which casts doubts on flying in general,'' Tanzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the pilot on the Sargents' plane announced another
change, the stress on the plane increased, said Ralph Sargent, who
is from Newbury, Mass. The plane bounced its way to Philadelphia,
then circled the airport for 40 minutes. Finally, the captain
announced that the plane was running low on fuel and they were
going to fly to Albany to land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for the next announcement to go _ `the
parachutes are under your seats,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Changes and delays reinforce people's feelings of helplessness,
said Robert A. Greendale, chairman of the department of psychiatry
at Highland Park Hospital in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the stress comes from figuring out how you are going
to cook your kids dinner if you are stranded across the country. Or
worrying that the sales meeting will start without you. For others,
it is a moment of truth to have a little talk with God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying not to lose control,'' Ralph Sargent's wife,
Andrea, said of their rocky flight. ``My son looked at me, and I
said if I start crying what is he going to do? I just stretched my
arm back and grabbed my husband's hand.'' The tears came anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
