<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WAR-COVERAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA MANIA LEAVES TV NEWS WITH LITTLE ENERGY FOR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We're not in Monicaland anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And it's clear after watching the coverage of the NATO attacks
on Yugoslavia that many broadcast news organizations are rusty at
real news, their instincts and ability to mobilize slackened and
atrophied by more than a year of nonstop yakking about President
Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to sit back and rake in revenue generated from
moralists paid to show up, preach, back their political party, then
do it again the next day _ a programming chess game of infinite
boredom that nevertheless captured the attention of the American
public. It's quite another to prove that your news organization
hasn't suffered so many cuts that you can do little more than mimic
a news conference at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   And so it wasn't surprising that CNN, the most determined
television news organization, had the first pictures among American
news operations of the night bombing in Yugoslavia and, more
importantly, had actual reporters near the action. From the initial
attack, CNN has provided the best coverage but, with President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia kicking out journalists from NATO
countries, the game could revert _ painfully _ back to the studios,
where much of the Lewinsky-Clinton nonsense first took place.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Milosevic lets those journalists back in could be the
key element to what is a major news story. Without proper access,
we're reduced to MSNBC ``news chats'' with blow-dried John Gibson
changing from talk about cigars to talk about collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived the titillating revelations about Clinton's
sexual escapades, viewers who define themselves as news junkies
(thus keeping these 24-hour news channels in business) may be
longing for a change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the NATO bombings and ethnic fighting
in Yugoslavia could go on for some time. What remains to be seen is
whether the TV news can properly shift gears and report a real
story _ a war.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's clear early on that this will be no Persian Gulf War,
in terms of riveting footage. That was the first time since Vietnam
that TV news dominated with significant war coverage. And even
then, critics complained that the coverage was being manipulated by
the White House and Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Access was even more controlled in post-Gulf War attacks on
Baghdad. At least then Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein let the news
media close to the action. Milosevic's decision, if not reversed,
could lead to the media reporting from further back on the
sidelines than they have been in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   And that means only one thing: the so-called experts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pretty safe assumption that prolonged exposure to yet
more experts will not rivet viewers. And these are military
experts, often the worst kind because they have a predictable frame
of reference and not the same kind of giddily vicious verbiage that
politically motivated experts used in the Clinton scandal.
</P>
<P>
   One expert, Michael O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution, said
this on MSNBC: ``We need to offer a carrot, not just a stick.
Though we may need a bigger stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Any more of that, and we're all in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   CNN was able to avoid much of the in-studio babble because it
was still working the angle of Christiane Amanpour and Brent Sadler
being booted out of the country, the former by the government, the
latter by ``uncontrolled armed elements harassing journalists,'' in
his words.
</P>
<P>
   Amanpour, probably the most watched foreign correspondent, went
back to Brussels, while Sadler thought he was heading back to the
calm confines of Macedonia, only to find a stream of rock-throwing
protesters heading for anybody with a camera.
</P>
<P>
   Very little footage of the conflict in Yugoslavia was available.
We saw some smoldering homes in Kosovo, allegedly burned as the
Serbs advanced. We saw state-run television pictures in Yugoslavia
shot from a distance, showing burned buildings while the experts
back in the United States tried to say just exactly what those
targets were.
</P>
<P>
   And we saw news conferences, where the answers were short and
the information nonexistent. Again, that leaves a lot of explaining
in the studios, and many networks are opting for the same tactic:
Go to the map.
</P>
<P>
   As Chip Reid said on MSNBC: ``A week ago people didn't know what
Kosovo was.'' Or where it was, for that matter. News channels are
discovering that just like in the Middle East, relentless
explaining is necessary to hook the American viewing public, or it
all just seems like something happening ``over there.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is where we are in the early days of the latest TV war:
Get a map (no one has done this better than Clinton during his
speech to the nation, by the way), point at the highlighted Kosovo
region, have your anchor talk in general terms about how Yugoslavia
has been a bit of a historic hot spot, then smother the rest of the
hour with experts and redundant news footage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is where the network news from CBS, ABC and NBC can
actually excel. There are so few video elements to show people, and
so little White House or Pentagon information, that the tiny
half-hour allotment of network news may be just right.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the country immediately flips to the 24-hour channels
for thorough coverage, and the networks seem more and more like
news dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   Unless access is widened, however, we'll be left to witness a
talking heads party across the dial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
