<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-FUTURAMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY `THE SIMPSONS,' TOMORROW `FUTURAMA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's almost unfair to judge Matt Groening's latest work. This is
the guy who created ``The Simpsons,'' which with each season moves
farther away from just being the best animated series ever toward
being the best comedy ever.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe if we had never heard of ``The Simpsons,'' we would
have liked ``Futurama'' that much more. Not that it's bad; it's not
bad at all, in fact. Just not all that great yet. Maybe we are all
just spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, after seeing only one episode, I am willing to give
Groening the benefit of the doubt. He is high on ``Futurama,''
which, with his track record, is enough to make one believe it's
going to be good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' will start out twinned with ``The Simpsons,''
airing at 8:30 p.m. EST Sunday and next Sunday on Fox (check local
listings). The show will then move to 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays, creating
an animated block of programming for Fox that night along with
``King of the Hill'' and ``The PJ's.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the distinctions, the comparisons are inevitable.
Sure, ``Futurama'' takes place 1,000 years into the future, but you
swear you are seeing and hearing various folks from around the
Springfield of ``The Simpsons'' (while only ``Futurama'' has a
one-eyed alien, both shows have three-eyed fish).
</P>
<P>
   There are the same no chins and extended upper mouths, the
oversize eyes and the rolling lips and tongues during shrieks of
terror. Why the similarities? Groening says repeatedly it's because
it's the only way he knows how to draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' is the story of Fry, a late-20th-century loser.
It's New Year's Eve 1999, and he is delivering pizza in Manhattan.
After getting dumped by his girlfriend in the quickest brush-off on
record, he realizes the delivery call he is on to the cryogenics
lab is a prank. Accidentally he falls into a cryogenics tube,
which, according to the egg timer on front, is set for 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   While suspended in frozen animated animation, he misses a pair
of alien invasions, both of which destroy New York City. He finally
wakes up on Dec. 31, 2999, to a world that is part ``Jetsons,''
part ``Blade Runner'' and all Groening, from the dogs with jet
packs to walk-in suicide booths.
</P>
<P>
   Free of his miserable job, relationship and life in general, Fry
welcomes the chance to start over in the world. That is, until
Leela (the only one-eyed alien on the planet), who is in charge of
giving the unfrozen their ``permanent job assignments,'' gives Fry
his: Delivery Boy.
</P>
<P>
   There is one drop-dead Simpsonian laugh in the pilot, a riff
which takes place in a museum with preserved and talking heads from
the 20th century, led by Leonard Nimoy. While there are other
strong moments _ one commuter of the future sets off for JFK Jr.
Airport _ you find yourself waiting for a roll-off-the-couch moment
that never comes.
</P>
<P>
   So the inevitable, unwanted but totally relevant question: Is
``Futurama'' as good as ``The Simpsons?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, with no aspersions toward the stepchild, is ``What
is?''
</P>
<P>
   Given time, and Groening, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
