u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTAL-TRACKING27-COX     03-26 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-TRACKING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRIVATE FIRMS SEE NO THREAT IN POST OFFICE'S DELIVERY TRACKING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Postal Service's new delivery confirmation
system is off to a fast start, with officials predicting that more
than 1 million customers will use it during its first month of
service.
</P>
<P>
   But the major private delivery firms said the system poses no
threat to their business.
</P>
<P>
   On March 14, the Postal Service introduced a system that lets
customers verify the delivery of their packages by calling a
toll-free telephone number (800-222-1811) or checking the Postal
Service's Web site (http://www.usps.gov/cttgate/).
</P>
<P>
   The service costs 35 cents for priority mail or 60 cents for
parcel post packages. For customers who send and receive their
shipping information electronically, the service is free for
priority mail costs 25 cents for parcel select and post packages.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry McKiernan, manager of expedited and package services for
the Postal Service, said up to 50,000 customers a day are using the
confirmation system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finally offering a long overdue service,'' McKiernan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service had discussed the possibility of offering the
service for 10 years, he said, but was not able to initiate it
until the Postal Board of Governors approved a $700 million
allocation last year.
</P>
<P>
   Private delivery firms said the new service would have no effect
on their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our prospective, this is a non-event,'' said David
Shoenfeld, senior vice president of marketing, customer service and
corporate relations for FedEx. ``It isn't relevant to what our
customers tell us they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoenfeld said the Postal Service can't compete with private
companies because they can't tell the customer when the package was
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Postal Service's new delivery confirmation system only
tells the customer that their package arrived,'' agreed Tad Segal,
spokesman for United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   Segal said that Atlanta-based UPS, which delivers more than 3
billion packages and documents a year, has the ability to track
packages from the moment they are picked up through several
intermediate points to the final destination.
</P>
<P>
   Segal said the fee for the UPS tracking system is included in
the overall price of the shipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that the Postal Service's new system is a
competitive threat to UPS and other shipping companies right now,''
Segal said.
</P>
<P>
   Shoenfeld agreed, adding, ``what the Postal Service has done is
reinforced the gap between what they are able to do and what
customers expect and can get from private express companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not competing with UPS,'' McKiernan said. ``We are just
offering our customers a reasonably priced product.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
