<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      03-26 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTEGE IS COMING OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Gas is cheap, and great big trucks are popular, even
among people who have no use for great big trucks.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems terribly interested in small, fuel-efficient cars
anymore, even though there are some real bargains in this segment
and little cars are more fun to drive than sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As the revamped Mazda Protege shows, entry-level sedans also
have improved greatly, looking good, driving well and offering a
greater level of refinement than ever before. Protege replaced the
323 as Mazda's base car in 1990. But I never really cared for the
previous Protege, which felt tinny and didn't drive all that well.
</P>
<P>
   The new Protege is a significant upgrade. Its construction is
lightweight, but it seems tight and sturdy. Though the ride is
quiet, the engine does get boomy under acceleration or working hard
up grades.
</P>
<P>
   My only solid gripe about the Protege is its generic styling.
Really, if you wanted to design a stealth vehicle to come in under
enemy radar, this is it. It looks strikingly like a Civic clone
from the sides or rear, and if not for the distinctive chrome
mustache above the grille, you'd have no idea what it was when
viewed from the front.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda needs to look across the hall at its U.S. partner, Ford,
to see how to style a small car that catches people's interest. And
that's the new Ford Focus. The New Edge styling of the Focus is
interesting and forward-looking, maybe not to everybody's taste but
at least it won't get lost in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At least you won't accidentally climb into your neighbor's Civic
one morning instead of your Protege.
</P>
<P>
   Our test Protege was the top-end ES model, with a boatload of
amenities, an automatic transmission and a larger engine than the
base model. And the price just tops $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   For that, you get a decent-looking vehicle that's reasonably
roomy inside, and that drives comparably with Honda Civic, the
undisputed leader of this subcompact group. But the Protege is
several thousands cheaper than the Civic or its other major
competition, Toyota Corolla and Nissan Sentra.
</P>
<P>
   Base-model Proteges, which come only as four-door sedans, list
at $12,000; a middle-grade LX model goes for a bit more. The lesser
models are saddled with a wimpy 1.6-liter, 105-horse engine instead
of the beefier double-overhead-cam four in our ES.
</P>
<P>
   The tester would have been more fun and interesting with a
five-speed stick shift, which is standard, but the automatic worked
pretty well, not sapping too much power from the small engine. I
don't think it would work all that well with the 1.6, however.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I'm pretty impressed with the driveability of the
Protege, its secure cornering and exact steering. The ride is soft
enough to absorb bumps, including speed bumps, but it's not in the
least bit wallowing or vague. Mazda touts Protege's stiff
platform/soft springing layout, a formula that has worked well for
European automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Protege is surprisingly roomy inside, with lots of legroom up
front and plenty of space for regulation-size humans in the back.
The trunk is reasonably big, too. Even with the ES model, the
interior is still fairly simple, nowhere near what you'd call
plush. The upgraded stereo system was pretty good, though the rear
speakers were kind of weak.
</P>
<P>
   The Protege represents good value, offering decent refinement
and equipment, especially in the ES version. And you can run rings
around your neighbor's sport-utility vehicle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mazda Protege ES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
- Vehicle type: Five-passenger, four-door sedan, front-wheel
drive. &QL; 
- Base price: S14,925. &QL; 
- Price as tested: $16,355. &QL; 
- Engine: 1.8-liter in-line four, 122 horsepower at 6,000 rpm, 120
pound-feet of torque at 4,000 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: Four-speed automatic. &QL; 
- Curb weight: 2,577 pounds. &QL; 
- Wheelbase: 102.8 inches. &QL; 
- EPA fuel economy: 24 city, 29 highway. &QL; 
- Highs: Good value. Refinement. Roominess.- Lows: Generic styling.
Engine roar.Weak speakers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
