   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FARM-AUCTION _ GIBSONVILLE, N.C. _ In another sign of hard times
along Tobacco Road, a growing number of farmers are selling their
equipment at auctions. A big sale is planned Saturday in
Gibsonville, a community near Greensboro where farmers are
grappling with decreasing demand for cigarettes. (A sale preview is
on Friday.) Over the past two years, the U.S. government has
reduced by 35 percent the amount of tobacco that farmers can grow.
That has created a surplus of equipment and, in some cases, has
forced some farmers out of business. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ADAMS-BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush says he didn't grow
up wanting to be president. Neither did the only son of a president
who grew up to be president. Hell, the job didn't even exist until
John Quincy Adams was 22 years old. A look at the life and failed
presidency of J.Q. Adams, a man whose accomplishment G.W. Bush is
trying to match. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GA-Y2K _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes will sign a
proclamation today declaring next week OKY2K week. He will be
accompanied by a rep from the Small Business Administration and
from the Southeast Regional Y2K solution center. He also will be
touting a workshop next week at GPTV on Y2K compliance. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERSTATE-BIRTH - WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here's Margaret
Rivera weaving her Chevy Cavalier through IInterstate- 95 traffic,
honking, steering with one hand, sobbing, praying, and with her
right hand trying desperately to deliver Rita Namur's baby, who is
keeping an urgent appointment with the world right now! That's a
lot of imagery for this early in the morning. Let's go back a few
ticks and set the stage for what became Mrs. Namur's wild ride.
(Wiggins, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ ATLANTA _ The first of 13 custom Boeing 777s from an
order valued at more than $1.4 billion arrives at Hartsfield from
Seattle at 4 p.m. For more than a year, Delta has worked with the
manufacturer to develop the new wide-body flagship, which has been
designed exclusively with the airline's long-haul passengers in
mind. Delta Ship7001 is the first 777 with the BusinessElite cabin
with 52 seats for premium passengers. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/DELTA-ONBOARD _ Staff Writer Scott Thurston talks about the
experience flying on Delta's latest flagship enroute from Seattle.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-FESTIVAL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Last year, the South by
Southwest Interactive festival focused on expanding the Internet
and multimedia as revolutionary forms of communication and artistic
expression. This year, the festival was about page views,
partnerships and IPOs. The festival shows that as e-commerce takes
off, the Internet has transformed from a printing press for the
masses to a money mint for companies. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-INVEST _ ATLANTA _ The Coalition of Black Investors, an
economic network organization, begins two-day kickoff of its Road
to Prosperity Tour. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-Y2K _ ATLANTA _ The largest Y2K conference in the South is
Tuesday in Atlanta. 250 small business owners expected.
Ahnuts-and-bolts guide for entrepreneurs, hospitals and anybody
else who needs help getting ready for the big computer meltdown.
(Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
