<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-FOR-SENATE?-N     03-26 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-FOR-SENATE?-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WOULD HILLARY WANT TO DO IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's supporters point to Robert F. Kennedy as
shining proof that an outsider with a household name can move to
New York state on a moment's notice and still be elected to the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It's too easy, but I'll say it anyway: Hillary, you're no Bobby
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   (Ah, that felt good.)
</P>
<P>
   Until now I've resisted jumping into the will-she-or-won't-she
debate about Mrs. Clinton's political ambitions, mainly because I
figured the frenzy was largely the creation of a Washington press
corps suffering from Monica withdrawal syndrome and desperately
seeking another big story.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary for senator? Sounded more like wishful thinking _ fodder
for the topic-starved cable shows _ than a solid possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But the first lady is refusing to issue the outright denial that
would make the story go away. This week Mrs. Clinton acknowledged
making ``lots of calls'' to friends and associates to get their
input, and she was quoted in USA Today as saying she will
``continue speaking out on behalf of the issues that I've spent
more than 25 years working on. Any way I can continue to do that, I
intend to. But the form that will take I really can't predict at
this time.'' So apparently she really is flirting with the idea of
running for the senate, presumably against Rudy Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   How stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Forget, at least for now, about whether Mrs. Clinton would make
a good senator. I'm sure she'd be all right _ better than some, not
as effective as others, certainly not the worst we've ever seen.
(What, she couldn't top Carol Moseley-Braun's legacy?) It just
seems like it would be an incredible blunder, from a political,
personal and practical point of view.
</P>
<P>
   First there's the matter of the campaign itself, which would
have the New York City tabloids salivating like Rottweilers eyeing
a pork chop. The media-loathing Mrs. Clinton would be subjected to
daily headlines and stories about her husband, her daughter, her
friends, her hair, her clothes, her calves, her campaign finances,
her health-care debacle, her own sexual history, you name it. You
think the New York Post would be gentle with her? Puh-lease. If
they've got a photo of Hillary chomping a hot dog with her mouth
open on a bad hair day, it gets played on the front page. Big.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one element of the media factor. In order to get her
message out and compete with the camera-loving Guiliani, the often
snippy first lady would have to submit to interviews with TV
stations from Syracuse to Albany to Buffalo, and she'd have to do
radio segments with the inexplicably powerful Don Imus and the
deservedly influential Howard Stern. If she didn't, she'd get
buried. Hillary could barely maintain a cheery facade with Matt
Lauer and Steve Kroft; how's she going to grit her way through the
local stuff and the radio goofing she no doubt believes is beneath
her dignity?
</P>
<P>
   Running for senator also means Mrs. Clinton wouldn't have time
to write the book that could erode a hefty portion of the family's
legal bills. Even if she did find the time and the ghostwriter to
churn out an autobiography, how forthcoming is she going to be if
she's eyeing the senate? And if it's not going to be a revealing,
intimate work, the advance will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign also means Hillary will have to at least temporarily
eschew the $100,000 speaking fees, the lucrative corporate board
memberships, the law firm partnership and the many other financial
opportunities that would undoubtedly be awaiting the most
fascinating first lady since Jacqueline Kennedy. You can't fly to
Japan and accept a $1 million speaking fee _ not if you're in the
middle of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As for the race itself, the risk isn't worth the reward. Right
now, Mrs. Clinton is enjoying unprecedented public favor, and as a
former first lady her stock would only rise.
</P>
<P>
   That would all change with a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary wins, she's the junior senator from New York. She
gets a windowless office and a smallish staff, and she'll have to
suck up to veterans who barely got the time of day from her when
she lived in the White House. When she visits her former residence,
she'll have to wait in reception lines to say hello to the new
first lady, be it Mrs. Gore or Mrs. Bush or Mrs. Underdog. That'll
kill her.
</P>
<P>
   If she loses _ and I think she would _ her social, professional
and financial clout would be diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The media want to see a Clinton-Giuliani race because it would
make for great copy. Democrats want to see Mrs. Clinton run because
they think she's the best hope of keeping that senate seat. Bubba
probably would favor it because he owes Hillary big-time and this
will be a chance for him to blabber about how his wife is the
greatest thing since the invention of the intern.
</P>
<P>
   My question is, why in the world would Hillary want to do it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
