<HEADLINE>
IS MICROSOFT MOVING TO SETTLE? U.S. SAYS NO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (lh) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The way the Justice Department sees it, if
Microsoft Corp. and the government are to begin talks to settle the
antitrust suit now at issue in federal court here, Microsoft will
have to make the first move. So far, that has not happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not received any settlement proposal from Microsoft,''
Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein, head of the Justice
Department's antitrust division, said Monday in response to a
report in The Wall Street Journal that Microsoft had indicated an
interest in settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is presiding at the antitrust
trial, has indirectly urged both sides to reach for a settlement
during the recess that began at the end of February. The trial is
scheduled to resume in April.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say they are open to such discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it is willing to show flexibility on some issues
but not others, noting, as one executive put it, that ``settling
this case without the need for more protracted litigation would be
good for everyone concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Monday, Klein said, ``The Justice Department
has always been and remains open to a settlement that fully
protects consumers and assures that similar antitrust violations do
not occur in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues on which Microsoft is expressing a willingness to
negotiate are generally those on which the company has already
shown flexibility in the market. Over the last year, it has
loosened some of its restrictive contracts with Internet companies
and has allowed computer manufacturers to customize the opening
screen of the Windows operating system to a degree. But the company
says it is not willing to negotiate in the areas that seem most
important to the Justice Department and the 19 states that are
pressing the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any settlement must preserve Microsoft's ability to add new
features to our operating system as technology advances,'' a
company executive who demanded anonymity said Monday. With that,
Microsoft is signaling its unwillingness to give up the ability to
bundle other software products with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of the Microsoft Web browser with Windows set off
the antitrust suit. A three-judge appeals court panel ruled in a
related case last June that Microsoft had the right to add new
features to Windows, if the addition benefited consumers. Based on
comments and questions he has posed in court, however, it is not at
all clear that Jackson believes that the inclusion of a Web browser
with Windows has significantly benefited consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department wants Microsoft to make the first move
toward settlement talks because government lawyers think they have
the upper hand after more than four months in court in which they
threw the credibility of many Microsoft witnesses into doubt. But
Microsoft's lawyers also believe they have presented a strong case.
So even if settlement talks begin before the trial resumes, lawyers
on both sides say the odds of success are long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-22-99 2229EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
