A5278 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-PIZZA-NAT     03-26 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-PIZZA-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        CLINTON ORDERS AIR ATTACK, GOVERNMENT STAFFERS ORDER PIZZA
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;      By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 25 -- Local pizza delivery folks know if
there's a crisis consuming the nation's capital, government
staffers will be consuming pizza.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton Wednesday night ordered air attacks in
Yugoslavia to halt a Serbian offensive in Kosovo, Domino's pizza
stores delivered a record high number of pizzas to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a case of war and pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Domino's stayed open an hour later Wednesday to accommodate the
800 pizzas ordered by Pentagon staffers. On a typical day, the
Pentagon will order about 75 pizzas, said Frank Meeks, owner of 59
area Domino's stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's previous record was 750 pizzas ordered during the
Persian Gulf crisis, Meeks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pentagon workers didn't seem as confident during this Kosovo
crisis as they did during the Persian Gulf War,'' Meeks said his
delivery staff observed. ``I think they are a little more worried
about this one. It's tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks said Washington's appetite for power and scandal seems to
correlate with its hunger for pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to miss Monica Lewinsky and impeachment, which
we called 'impizzament,''' Meeks said. ``But something always
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had just under 500 Domino's pizzas delivered
Wednesday night, nowhere near its record of 1,000 delivered when
the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke in January of last year, Meeks
said. The White House typically orders about 50 a day from
Domino's.
</P>
<P>
   Since last weekend, about 100 pizzas a day have been delivered
to the State Department. There are usually only 10 pizzas delivered
a day, according to Meeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must have been considering the Kosovo issue for a while,
trying to work it out because they've been ordering pizzas since
last week,'' Meeks said. ``They are a bunch of intellectuals who
typically don't eat much pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   This week offices on Capitol Hill ordered about 500 pizzas a
day, which is more than its usual 200. It doesn't come close to
Domino's record for the Hill, when it delivered 1500 pizzas the day
the House of Representatives voted to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks said government staffers favor pepperoni as a topping, but
tend to order a larger amount of toppings, depending on the
severity of a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are stuck in their offices so they want pizza to deliver
more food groups to them,'' Meeks said. ``They want it to sustain
them for as long as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
