<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-TRUCK-NAT     03-26 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-TRUCK-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TRUCK SAFETY ADVOCATES WANT FEDERAL OVERSIGHT ``SHAKEN UP''
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 26 -- Highway safety advocates criticized the
federal agency that oversees large trucks because they say it is
too close to the industry it regulates to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Calling for a shake-up of the Office of Motor Carriers, safety
advocates urged a congressional panel Thursday to rethink oversight
of the trucking industry. ``What we have with the Office of Motor
Carriers is a cultural problem of avoiding action and working
closely with the industry,'' said Joan Claybrook, of the Advocates
for Highway and Auto Safety. ``It needs a major cultural change.''
</P>
<P>
   Both highway safety advocates and trucking industry officials
testified at the third and final hearing planned in a series that
examined the OMC's role in truck safety.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representatives Ground Transportation
Subcommittee may decide to hold more hearings or make
recommendations to the House Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Mooney Tierney, of Citizens for Reliable and Safe
Highways, said the OMC uses biased research when forming safety
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney said she thinks there was a conflict of interest when
the OMC hired an arm of the American Trucking Association to
conduct the $4.5 million study on driver fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation dismissed the study,
criticizing its design and methodology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be angrier at the lack of movement by OMC,''
Tierney said. ``It is staggering how the number of deaths increase
and the industry and government continue to work together on the
spin that it's because there are more trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing a rise in truck related deaths, and recent reports that
showed the OMC had insufficient data on crashes and is too slow to
implement safety programs, safety advocates say the agency should
be restructured.
</P>
<P>
   Claybrook and several other safety advocates suggest the OMC
should no longer be a part of the Federal Highway Administration,
which has a primary focus on infrastructure and development. They
say the OMC should instead be moved under the authority of the
National Highway Transportation Safety Board, which has a focus on
safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motor Carrier safety will be put first and safety regulations
and enforcement policy will not be initially filtered through
layers of freight productivity goals, safety standards
exemptions,'' Claybrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government oversees more than 490,000 trucking
businesses and 6 million drivers.
</P>
<P>
   While the rate of fatalities per 100 miles traveled by large
trucks has stayed steady in the last few years, the number of
actual deaths has increased. Deaths have jumped 20 percent from
4,462 in 1992 to 5,355 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But truck industry officials say there is a rise in
truck-related deaths, because of an increase in trucks on the roads
and more miles traveled. Walter B. McCormick, Jr., president of the
American Trucking Associations, Inc., said there should be a
separate Motor Carrier Administration created to oversee the OMC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trucking industry and motoring public deserve a federal
agency that has trucking and truck safety as its core mission,''
McCormick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
