<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'90S' `MOD SQUAD' IS OLD HAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remaking ``The Mod Squad'' is like cheating off one of the
dumber kids in class: Shame! Still, before director Scott Silver is
banished to the principal's office for copying, he gets a few props
for staying within the lines of the original show.
</P>
<P>
   It's glossy, stylish and uniquely disembodied from any
recognizable social universe _ a long-form visual brochure for a
minimalist, get-up-and-go-go lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is as simple as the title: Three hyper-styled
young-buck derelicts have been ostracized from quotidian Los
Angeles life. As retribution for past sins, which include drug
addiction, petty theft and, in one case, just being an angry
brother, Linc (Omar Epps), Julie (Claire Danes) and Pete (Giovanni
Ribisi) have to wear second-skin leathers and denims, be badgeless
cops and look mad, as if they haven't eaten in days or somebody
just scuffed their Kenneth Coles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mod Squad'': a television show so desperate to become a
movie that Aaron Spelling, its original producer, gave his wrinkled
thumbs up and worked as co-executive producer of the movie. The
film is a cooly synthetic pleasure more enjoyable as a mellow
swatch of kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   While all the original ideas in Hollywood are drying up, what we
have here is an experience similar to watching a flip-book of the
ads that outweigh the articles in XL coffee-table mags like Vibe
and The Face.
</P>
<P>
   Linc's idea of effective crime-fighting and ending foot chases
is still leaping onto the chasee, though Epps is built more Richard
Roundtree's Shaft than the Linc Clarence Williams III created.
</P>
<P>
   Julie remains a glamour puss, though Danes' version, with a
supporting performance by her midriff, is a reformed drug abuser
and recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   It's Pete who undergoes the drastic make-over from Michael
Cole's smarmy matinee idol to Ribisi's bumbling shout-out to rich
white boys who turn to crime and vintage clothing when their
parents are too busy to love them.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the film apes the original's 1968-'72 era, from
the horns, Moogs and wah-wah guitars of BC Smith's score to the way
Ellen Krause's photography nails those super-quick, super-tight,
panned close-ups of exit doors and clenched jaws in motion.
</P>
<P>
   The Mod Squad is also a peculiar vanishing point where the '70s
become indistinguishable from the '90s. When a new Curtis Mayfield
tune pours over the soundtrack with Lauryn Hill singing in the
background, what decade it is becomes even more vague.
</P>
<P>
   But where the show's rescue the troubled youth agenda was a sign
of the Vietnam- and the civil rights-era's most volatile years, the
film feels like mere late-'90s product when it could have been a
brilliant reconsideration of the times. Working from a script he
co-wrote with Steven Kaye and Kate Lanier, Silver never allows the
movie to breathe contemporary air and get gang-related, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's ``Mod Squad'' could use a bit of the sordid. As if the
very fact that it's a rip-off weren't enough, it's virtually
suspenseless and too antiseptic for its R rating. These kids don't
really drink, they don't do drugs, they're not very kinky, and Linc
only gets to look virile. Don't they have any vices?
</P>
<P>
   The film never stoops to posturing, even when its most appealing
features are empty. But you can't help suspecting that if ``The Mod
Squad'' were a T-shirt, it would be made of some processed fabric
like lycra or polyester, and it would read: ``I went to see the Mod
Squad and all I got was this jive turkey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
