<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 `EDtv' PACKS LAUGHS AS SMALL SCREEN HITS SILVER SCREEN  
 (EDs: SUBS head, story stands.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of Hollywood's more inscrutable mysteries (beyond Keanu
Reeves' career) is its tendency to make two movies with the same
premise at about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Two movies about computer-somatic bugs. Two movies about large
cosmic objects screaming Earthward. Two movies about the
dehumanizing agonies of American soldiers in World War II. Two
movies about randy Elizabethans (among them Joseph Fiennes) in
tights and ruffled collars.
</P>
<P>
   And now, two more: Ten months after the release of ``The Truman
Show,'' Peter Weir's breathtaking light-dark fantasy about a man
whose life is a television show, we have ``EDtv,'' a felicitously
wacked-out comedy about ... a man whose life is a television show.
</P>
<P>
   His name is, you guessed it, Ed, and he's a nobody who becomes a
somebody when he allows a camera crew to film his every move. Just
imagine the high jinks.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ron Howard with ample fizz and sharply acted by a
delightful cast, the film is, in fact, so unlike ``The Truman
Show'' in tone and intent that it mostly stands on its own without
comparison. ``EDtv'' isn't profound, and it doesn't bang around the
brainpan with any particular resonance, but it does pack a lot of
big laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, quite a few are generated by Matthew
McConaughey he of the It Boy credentials, sputtering career and
borderline-unspellable name. McConaughey was fresh in ``Dazed and
Confused,'' sleek in ``A Time to Kill,'' presentable in
``Contact,'' appalling in ``Amistad'' and not all bad in ``The
Newton Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``EDtv'' he's an explosion of slacker charm, an also-ran so
uncomplicated by ambition or cunning that he wins audience sympathy
just by cracking his grin. McConaughey has never been this
watchable; he's never been this much fun (although, as the
loser-lothario in ``Dazed,'' he came close).
</P>
<P>
   When we meet Ed, he's playing pool with his big-dreams brother,
Ray (Woody Harrelson, doing a mean twist on his old ``Cheers''
lunk), and sullen pal, John (Adam Goldberg). Ed's a 31-year-old
video store clerk whose metier is lugging beer in a cup-holder
strung around his neck. ``He's gonna spend the rest of his life
rearranging `Ernest' movies,'' gripes his brother.
</P>
<P>
   But when a cable network starts auditioning average joes for a
new, 16-hour-a-day, reality-based show, Ed catches a programmer's
eye he's cute enough to be telegenic, dense enough to act like an
idiot on national television. So they bring him into the network
offices, where a politburo of prickly executives grill him on
sundry topics. (What did he study in college? ``Study?'' he says.
``Jeeeeez, that would've been a big help.'')
</P>
<P>
   Included in this group are Rob Reiner as a pompous mogul and
Ellen Degeneres in distracted-non sequitur mode, wherein she
delivers some of the movie's more bizarro punch lines (``We don't
even have money in the budget for coffee filters. We use
yarmulkes''). Both put cheery bite into their dialogue, penned by
the same team of screenwriters (Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel) who
wrote Ron Howard's ``Parenthood'' and ``Splash.''
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the film is McConaughey's sweet, dim Ed, a man
so eager to give up his privacy that he clips his toenails for the
camera. The wake-up scene on Day 1 is a vulgar beaut, and the bits
that follow are both smartly staged and stupidly funny; when Ed
drops a hot Pop-Tart (``Whoooo action sequence,'' says Reiner) and
bends to retrieve it, he checks out his rump on television. Dumb?
Sure. But you'll laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Ed sees the downside to this arrangement: It
alienates his brother, embarrasses his mom (Sally Kirkland),
confuses his ailing stepdad (Martin Landau, making great comic hay
of a weak heart), exposes him to fanatical hordes and gums up his
budding romance with Shari (touchingly played by Jenna Elfman of
``Dharma &AMP; Greg''). And as his celebrity grows, he begins to regret
it.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Truman Show,'' ``EDtv'' breaks up the narrative with
quick shots of television viewers gathered around the hearth. We
get the frat boys, the co-eds, the yuppie straight couple, the
yuppie gay couple, even ``the president'' all of them glued to Ed's
every soap-operatic development. This is cute for 15 minutes. By
minute 122 it gets to be a drag.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it the only thing that drags. Howard is a bright, kinetic
filmmaker, but he doesn't always know how to wrap things up; his
movies are just about equally divided between good stories with
obvious endings (``Apollo 13'') and good stories with lousy ones
(``Ransom''). ``EDtv'' is the latter sort.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, it brings Dennis Hopper into the plot, then shunts
him into oblivion after two criminally brief scenes. And the film
is packed to the eyebrows with so many talking-head cameos (Jay
Leno, Ru Paul, George Plimpton, Bill Maher) that the natural
impulse is to grab the remote and fling it at them. Unfortunately,
there is no remote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
