<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP! WE'RE ACCUSED OF A HACK ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Recently our server kicked us off, accusing us
of ``hacking activities of a serious nature.'' My son told us about
Back Orifice and how this was the cause of our problem. I was
wondering if: (A) this was possible, (B) this was probable, (C) I
can let my son out of the closet now, and (D) I should enlarge the
closet to accommodate his geeky friend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleepless in New Hampshire
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SLEEPLESS: At least you didn't opt for summary execution,
which probably would have been my first choice. Back Orifice is
nothing for a kid to be playing with, so naturally your kid has
been playing with it.
</P>
<P>
   There are some nimrods calling themselves ``The Cult of the Dead
Cow'' who have developed a ``remote-administration'' tool, called
``Back Orifice.'' Please don't confuse them with some nimrods
calling themselves ``Microsoft'' who have developed ``Web
site-administration'' tools called ``BackOffice.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in this instance, ``remote administration'' means
rummaging around your computer, messing with your files and finding
all your pictures of Nikki Cox. Sure, it may be a fine line between
teen pornography and art, but do you really want somebody making
that decision for you?
</P>
<P>
   BO has to be installed covertly on your computer first, but
that's no problem. It can be sent to you as an e-mail attachment.
You know all those cute videos and sound clips that wind up in your
mailbox? Each is a potential BO carrier. You should never click on
them if you don't know what they are, but who remembers caution
when you get something named Nakedpix.exe?
</P>
<P>
   BO is sneaky. You can't normally tell if it's running. Go to
www.bardon.com/boelimdl.htm and get a free BO-removal utility. If
you don't trust that download, there are instructions for getting
rid of BO manually.
</P>
<P>
   And don't leave your kid in the closet with that geek too long.
I guess you've seen enough prison movies to know what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have a Power Macintosh with the good old
serial port, and I am thinking of getting a universal serial bus
card so I can use iMac accessories. Is it true that PCs will
someday be USB-compatible?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ports of Call
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CALL: Where have you been? Didn't you see Bill Gates make a
jerk out of himself at a Win98 demo when he plugged a USB scanner
into his PC and crashed it? I wonder where the guy who set up the
demo is working these days. Taco Bell? Jack-in-the-Box? There are
just so many opportunities for somebody with his background.
</P>
<P>
   USB is the latest ``standard'' port for hooking up your
peripherals. You plug something into a USB connector, the operating
system will recognize it and you'll be back to work in no time,
unless you're Bill Gates standing in front of hundreds of people
laughing themselves silly.
</P>
<P>
   PCs have supported USB since the waning days of Win95. You had
to download the drivers and probably add hardware to your PC, but
with enough patience and cocktails, you could get it to work as
advertised. Win98 has the support built in. It should make hooking
up new peripherals fairly painless, at least until the next
standard comes along. I hear Bill's looking for volunteers to set
up the demo. Any takers?
</P>
<P>
   (When noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay plugs something
in, it works, except for that time his house burned down. He can be
reached at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101, or fax: (817)
390-7257. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
