<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOMEZ-COL-3-AZR &LR;      03-26 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOMEZ-COL-3-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVANA NEIGHBORHOOD OFFERS INSIGHTS ON FATHER
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
Editor's note: Baseball columnist Pedro Gomez, a first-generation
Cu ban-American, describes his impres sions of his parents'
homeland. He is in Havana for Sunday's historic exhibition game
between the Balti more Orioles and the Cuban Na tional Team. &HT;     By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
HAVANA _ The same man who pleaded with my parents to stay in Cuba
has lost his hair and his two-day old beard is white. His mind and
body, however, are sur prisingly strong and he looks no where near
his 84 years.
<P>
   For so many years, Rodolfo Fernandez-Guzman has been a face less
person to me. All I knew of the ``old man'' was that he tried in
vain to keep my parents from fleeing Cuba in 1962, shortly after
commu nism was sweeping through the island.
</P>
<P>
   This is the man my mother and paternal grandmother, Trinidad, ar
gued with almost daily. This is the man who told my mother that by
the time I reached kindergarten the world would be dominated by com
munists.
</P>
<P>
   I met Guzman on Thursday when I made my way to the El Vedado
neighborhood of Havana where my father lived until the day he and
my mother left for the United States in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely I remember going back and forth with your mother
and Trini,'' Guzman said. ``All I said was that the child inside
your mother might grow up to be a great scientist, a ballplayer, a
good com munist, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that the child should be able to decide for itself. Now
look at you, you're a grown man with a family of your own. I can't
believe you were the one inside her belly. The world gives us so
many differ ent turns, sometimes it works for some and not for
others. For you, it seems to have worked fine. But who knows where
you would be if you had been born here?''
</P>
<P>
   Like every Cuban I have encoun tered during my first visit to my
parents' homeland, Guzman went out of his way to be gracious and
generous. He was open, with his ideology and his home, offering
food and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The map my father drew for me two weeks ago served as a perfect
guide to reach his old home, which looked identical to what he
remem bered from 36 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the jam-packed M6 bus line south on Avenue 23
toward El Vedado, I exited at 24th Street and set off on a short
walk filled with intrigue and mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Just before reaching the Almen dares River, there was 32nd
Street. One block to the right was Pasaje A. And then I was there,
at the only home my father knew until he fled to Miami with my
mother, who delivered me three weeks later in the U.S. The current
tenant, Vilma Varela-Alfonso, has lived in the same home for 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   The home is 65 years old and has housed exactly two families: My
father's and now Alfonso's. Consid ering how transient Americans
are, it's mind-boggling to consider that only two families have
lived in the same home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this home,'' Alfonso said. ``I've spent my entire life
here. I will never leave here. It's a very comfortable home. It's
very private and quiet. This is where I want to finish my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso is 32. She was kind enough to offer a tour of my
father's boyhood home. Once inside I saw the exact bed where my
father slept and, as Guzman pointed out, where I was
``fabricated,'' the room where my parents lived during their final
year in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there, they made you,'' Guzman said. ``So in a way,
you've actually been here before.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking up to No. 13 on Pasaje A, I felt a strong sense of
pride. Meeting the people of the neighbor hood, at least the ones
who were here when my father still lived here, was like an
out-of-body experience.
</P>
<P>
   First there was Asuncion de la Cruz and her son, Abilio
Valdez-de la Cruz, who vividly recalled playing chess with my
father while growing up. Asuncion informed me of a crush my father
had on her daughter, Magalis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooph,'' de la Cruz said, ``Your father used to chase my
daughter around the neighborhood all the time. I know he had a
thing for her.''
</P>
<P>
   From there I met Ofelia Gonza lez-Pargo, whose husband owned a
grocery store on the same block before it was nationalized by the
government in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   She nearly started crying when she discovered I was Trini's
grand son.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an amazing coinci dence,'' she said. ``I swear on my
mother's grave I was talking about Trini (Wednesday) night. I was
talking about my son's baptism and how we had a little party. I
started talking about all the guests we had and I brought up
Trini's name. I can't believe this. They are sad memories of
glorious times.''
</P>
<P>
   Trini was born in Madrid. At 4-foot-8 and stocky, she resembled
a tough little sparkplug, unwilling to take anything from anyone.
She was known as La Gallega, a common name Cubans have for all
Spaniards. Her reputation in the neighborhood was well known.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel de la Cruz was then a rambunctious 7-year-old and used to
play doorbell ditch at my grand mother's home, the game where you
ring a doorbell and run away before the occupant opens the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew she had a short temper,'' de la Cruz said. ``We
all knew we could get her going. Then she would stand on the porch
cursing at all of us. They were just things children do.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood remains tight-knit. All are friendly and all
take care of one another. The core of the neighborhood is exactly
as my father described it, strong and friendly.
</P>
<P>
   I now have a little better sense of my father and everything
that shaped his life. Not surprisingly, I see the same qualities in
him to this day. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 444-2364 or pedro.gomez &LR; pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
