A5354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-ROBBER-BOS &LR;      03-26 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-ROBBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK ROBBERS ARE AMONG THE DUMBEST OF CRIMINALS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the Hollywood images of robbers like ``Baby Face'' Nelson
or John Dillinger fleeing banks with sacks of easy cash. Police
call it one of the stupidest crimes, something even some criminals
admit.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the crime must be pulled off in broad daylight, on
banker's hours. There are cameras to avoid, as well as bait money,
dye packs, silent alarms, and the strong possiblity a police
officer will arrive soon. In fact, in Boston, police usually
respond to a bank alarm in less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy crime to pull off, but nearly impossible to get
away with,'' said a local detective who specializes in
investigating bank robberies. ``Think about it. How many crimes
leave police with a photograph of the criminal? Even if you wear a
mask, you're leaving behind physical evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But still banks get robbed: at least once a week in Boston,
police say. In fact, in the last four weeks, female robbers _ an
unusual breed _ have struck eight banks in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many bank robbers are druggies who are desperate and looking
for fast money,'' said Harvey Burstein, a former FBI agent who is
now a professor at Northeastern University. ``Then you have the
gamblers, folks who think they can beat the system. There is always
the hope for a big score.''
</P>
<P>
   The average haul, $1,500 in Boston, is not enough to buy a good
used car. And seven of 10 bank robbers get caught, facing at least
six to 10 years in prison, one investigator estimated.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, police arraigned a woman who authorities believe to
be the mastermind of seven of the armed bank robberies in the past
month. Beverly DeAngelo, 33, of Peabody, was arrested on unrelated
drug charges but allegedly was tracked by FBI agents working from
bank surveillance photos and anonymous tips.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a woman who police believe is a copycat bandit
robbed a bank in the North End, the same branch hit by the original
female robber.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some bank robbers were legends, like Willie Sutton,
who once said he robbed banks because ``that's where the money
is.'' Before deposits in banks were insured, a stickup at a bank
could wipe out a small community.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities say that most bank robbers today are low-tech
criminals. The organized bank robber _ one who uses multiple
partners, police scanners, walkie-talkies, masks with fake wigs,
high-powered weaponry, and several getaway cars _ is rare, but a
concern for police.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts alone, there have been a number of bank
robberies in which thieves have walked out with between $100,000
and $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But crime history books are filled with attempted bank robberies
gone horribly awry.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 23, 1970, was one of Boston's darkest days. Walter A.
Schroeder, a 42-year-old Boston officer, was shot and killed when
he responded to a silent bank alarm at the State Street Bank and
Trust in Brighton. All the bandits who pulled off the $26,000
robbery have been brought to justice, including Katherine Ann
Power, who was a fugitive for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to bank robberies, we will always remember
Walter Schroeder,'' said Sergeant Detective Margot Hill, Boston
police spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``His death proves a bank robbery call is always dangerous,''
Hill said. ``We get a lot of false alarms, but we train officers to
assume every one is real and dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say that is why the gamble is so risky for bank robbers,
whether they carry a weapon or not. Officers are trained to respond
quickly and silently, using deadly force when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 7, 1983, for example, two gunmen ordered 15 customers to
the floor of a Back Bay bank, robbed tellers of $14,000 in cash,
and were about to escape when they encountered Officers Daniel
Haggerty and Steven Chin.
</P>
<P>
   One of the gunmen opened fire, the other tried to shoot but his
gun jammed. When it was over, a robber was dead, and the other was
in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Boston's FBI task force, who spoke last week, said
the female bandit who robbed Boston area banks was getting between
$2,000 and $4,000 per job. Her success made her unusual, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But after her last robbery on March 17, one investigator made a
prediction: ``She'll mess up soon.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelo was arrested a few days later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
