<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO GOOD REASON MRS. CLINTON WOULD WANT TO BE SENATOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This week's status report on the New York Senate
race:
</P>
<P>
   Hillary was in Egypt; Rudy was on the ropes. While the first
lady who's thinking of becoming second senator in New York took
Chelsea to look at pyramids, Mayor Rudy Giuliani was looking for a
way out of the escalating political crisis over the police.
</P>
<P>
   The hands-on hard-guy approach that made the onetime prosecutor
the darling of voters has become a liability. Hizzonah is fumbling
for the reins after losing control of the issue. Suddenly the
800-pound gorilla of New York City looks like just another monkey
in the urban political zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats beg her to run, citing favorable polls, a
bottomless war chest, promises to make nice, all the blandishments
for which lesser candidates would kill. My hunch? She won't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Not out of fear of losing. No one married to Bill Clinton,
having survived impeachment, possible indictment, the massed armies
of big tobacco, big pharmaceuticals, big insurance, and the big
wind of the Republican Congress, who has outlasted Ken Starr,
Monica Lewinsky, and the collective hostility of the news media, is
going to be frightened of losing a lousy Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does she get if she wins?'' posed a New York Democratic
activist who's helped wage two statewide campaigns. ``Six years of
doing constituent service?'' Erie County needs more snowplows,
ma'am. The Long Island Expressway needs 85 new bridges. We need to
dredge the Hudson all the way to Canada. Oh, and there are 300
angry black people sitting in at the office, and the Yankees are
threatening to move to Ontario if you don't get Steinbrenner a tax
break.
</P>
<P>
   This is winning? Plus having Rupert Murdoch's New York Post
serve you up a bucket of insult every morning with your bagel? Six
years of tabloid ordeal-by-ordure? Yes, the idea of getting to zing
Trent Lott every weekday afternoon is sorely tempting. But why
settle down to plowing the same furrows year after year when the
whole world beckons?
</P>
<P>
   My suspicions about the attractiveness of the Senate to a woman
like Mrs. Clinton were only reinforced by a dinner Wednesday night
at Harvard's Kennedy School. Former Republican Senator Al Simpson
of Wyoming pointed out that he and a fellow guest, former
Democratic Senator David Pryor of Arkansas, had arrived and left
the Senate at the same time and during 18 years had managed to have
some fun. That made me think of all the senators who have quit the
World's Greatest Deliberative Body:
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell and Bill Cohen of Maine, Warren Rudman of New
Hampshire, Bill Bradley of New Jersey, John Danforth of Missouri,
and Howard Baker of Tennessee and Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas, who
got married to each other instead of the job. Twelve of the 100
quit in '95 alone, indicating that being in the Senate is not the
dream job outsiders think. C-Span and cable network chat shops make
us more familiar with senators remote from our home states _ and
it's scary to see some of these goofs in action, let's be frank.
</P>
<P>
   So my bet is that Hillary thinks twice: decides that the race is
winnable, that the money and support are there, that Giuliani is
beatable _ but that at the end of the day, she just doesn't want to
be nailed to a Senate seat for six years answering roll calls on
inane measures. Every vote she missed, the New York Post would fang
her. Bottom line? Not worth winning.
</P>
<P>
   Win she would, in my view. Giuliani, who's taking his Big Apple
polishing act on the road as a vice presidential auditionee, is now
facing a mandatory 180 on police brutality, veering off his
cops-can-do-no-wrong stance to something softer and gentler. The 41
police bullets aimed at an unarmed black man by overeager cops left
him dead but Giuliani wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Even pro-cop Cardinal John O'Connor spoke out boldly Sunday in
his homily to 1,000 police officers attending Mass at St. Patrick's
Cathedral. ``If there have been insensitive injustices against
black people, against Latin and against Asian people, it would do
no good to deny these injustices.''
</P>
<P>
   Said the state's top prelate: ``As long as the perceptions are
there, they must be dealt with. It is rare that perceptions have no
foundation.'' Confession must precede absolution, said O'Connor.
``If there have been injustices, we must take appropriate steps to
resolve these injustices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulletin to the mayor: Notice that the cardinal told the cops
``we,'' not ``you.'' That's the part Giuliani doesn't get. Governor
George Pataki says the mayor should try listening more. Ed Koch,
the former mayor, says Rudy doesn't get it yet. The blacks,
Hispanics, civil libertarians, and editorial writers tried, too.
But Mr. Tough Guy, the prosecutor-turned-pol, has a tin ear. In a
Keystone Kops move, Police Commissioner Howard Safir planned to
blow off a City Council hearing on police conduct, to fly to
Hollywood for the Oscars. Hammered in the tabloids as ``Hollywood
Howard,'' Safir rushed home for a public flogging before hostile
city councilors.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary looks through the New York papers to bone up on
Rudy's troubles, she might just conclude, like thousands of others
nixing a career move to New York: ``Who needs this?''
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
