<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CD STOOD FOR CIVIL DEFENSE, STAR WARS MADE MORE SENSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you thought CD was shorthand for savings, Sinatra, or
software. It feels more like the days when ``CD'' was that Civil
Defense sign in the school basement and that ominous storage room
with barrels of water and crackers. You wonder if President Clinton
is about to resume air raid drills, with children being ordered to
the basement to get on their knees, tuck their heads, and cover the
backs of their necks (as if that really stops falling bricks).
</P>
<P>
   Such is the wailing in Washington, where Clinton and Congress
are about to spend at least another $10.5 billion over the next six
years to produce a missile defense system that would destroy enemy
projectiles only seconds after they left the ground. Despite our
unrivaled nuclear stockpile, we have scared ourselves back into
yesteryear over so-called ``rogue'' states in Asia and the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are affirming that there is a threat, and the threat is
growing, and that it will pose a danger not only to our troops
overseas but also to Americans here at home,'' said Defense
Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska said, ``There's a real danger of
proliferation that produces either an accidental launching or an
attack by a rogue nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Porter Goss of Florida, the chairman of the House
Intelligence Committee, said: ``The threat is real. It is growing
and more immediate than many have thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Congress have already shown their hand that they
have given the new version of ``Star Wars'' no real thought.
Clinton is so bent on keeping the Republicans from hammering the
Democrats on defense during the upcoming presidential campaign that
he has pledged to announce a decision on deploying a missile
defense in June 2000 _ four months before the election _ even
though it will be impossible to know by then if it can work.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no one in the Pentagon itself is betting that such a
system will be available anytime soon. They are happy to have the
money, but they must be taking it like someone who counts the
change at the grocery store and sees that the cashier has handed
them a $10 bill instead of a one.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Henry Shelton, said
last month in Sea Power magazine that he and the Joint Chiefs have
been so skeptical about ``Star Wars'' that ``we have been portrayed
on occasion as being anti-national missile defense. We are not! The
simple fact is that we do not yet have the technology to field a
national missile defense. We have, in fact, put some $40 billion
into the program over the last 10 years. But  &UR; today &LR;  we do not
technologically have a bullet that can hit a bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said that when such a system becomes feasible he will be
happy to deploy it, but until then, the United States has to show
patience. ``There are other serious threats out there in addition
to that posed by ballistic missiles,'' he said. ``We know, for
example, that there are many adversaries with chemical and
biological weapons that can attack the United States  &UR; today &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``They could do it with a briefcase _ by infiltrating our
territory across our shores and through our airports. So the chiefs
question putting additional billions of taxpayers' dollars into
fielding a system that does not work or has not proven itself _ and
we do not think that one round hitting one missile is proof
positive that we should start fielding.''
</P>
<P>
   For a Capitol Hill that puts politics before patience and for
the sectors of the military that will delight in the dollars,
hitting one missile is a cause for delirium. Two days before the
Senate's 97-3 vote to field a missile defense system, the Army
successfully hit a test target over New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Saying there was a lot of hugging and cheering, the Army's chief
of missile defense programs, Brigadier General Daniel Montgomery,
said: ``The significance of this success can't be overstated. This
certainly moves us well down the road of saying we can make these
systems work.''
</P>
<P>
   Well down the road? This sounds more like low standards.
Depending on who you believe, the military has hit a grand total of
two targets in 15 tries or four targets in 18 tries since ``Star
Wars'' was conceived by President Reagan in 1983. Put another way,
this means that this program, which has cost taxpayers between $55
billion and $68 billion, is still likely to miss eight or nine
times out of every 10 attacks.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a boondoggle that other members of the Joint Chiefs
have echoed Shelton. Testifying about a missile defense system last
fall before the Senate Armed Services Committee, the Army chief of
staff, Dennisa Reimer, said: ``I think we need to have something
that's practical, that has a degree of success. I think it has to
be balanced against the other priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill there is no balance, no patience. Missile
defense is nothing but a political bomb lobbed by the Republicans
at the Democrats. The Democrats, instead of calling for an air raid
drill for all of us to hear, are on their knees with their heads
tucked down, writing blank checks for clueless programs. Lockheed
Martin, Boeing, Raytheon, and the like are popping the champagne.
They know that after the billions are spent, they will be lucky if
they produce anything worth any more than a Civil Defense barrel of
water and crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
