<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPORTANT LESSON IN LOVING THY NEIGHBOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, I introduced my daughters to racism.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the sort of thing you hope your children will
encounter, but as African-Americans, they are likely to experience
it sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   And so I wanted them to see the kind of up-close and personal
discrimination that patrons are exposed to at the new ``Face to
Face'' exhibit, which opened last month at The Science Place in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at children ages 7 to 12, the exhibit explores
stereotyping, name-calling and exclusion through interactive videos
and role-playing exercises.
</P>
<P>
   As Jamila and Asha scurried through the various stations, I took
particular note of the ``Talk Back Board,'' filled with handwritten
testimonials from visitors.
</P>
<P>
   There were literally hundreds of responses, mostly from
school-age kids. They had one overriding theme: ``Treat others the
way you want to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading those comments and listening to my daughters' reactions,
I was reminded of a conversation about racism and growing up in
Mississippi that I had with the Rev. Laurie Feille recently at
University Christian Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of our talk, a woman in the audience asked me how we
might overcome the race issue. I told her that I believed the only
way we will ever get past it is for all of us to love our neighbors
as ourselves. I told her that if we can't find it in ourselves to
do that, we're are in for a rude awakening. All the time we spend
in church pews and doing ``good'' things will have been for naught.
</P>
<P>
   At the ``Face to Face'' exhibit, I wondered whether this might
be an affirmation of my comments. I wondered how in the world we
could still be wrestling with such a question when the answer seems
so clear, even to little children.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to this, from a child named Rachel: ``It's horrible to
see the judgment people show toward each other. What you must do is
love your neighbor as yourself no matter how hard it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   And this, scribbled by Alexis Perez: ``I am a popular girl
sometimes, but there is a girl that does not like me. But even
though she doesn't like me I try to be sweet to her. I hope you do
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Face to Face'' opened last month and will run through May 30
before moving on to nine other cities this year. No one who is
still trying to come to terms with race and other differences, or
who has been hurt by discrimination, should miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it expose prejudice for what it is, it offers
tools to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   But as one student wrote, ``Many people live in denial of their
racist attitudes. This is why we still have SO many problems in
this country. This is no illusion. It is real!! Wake up, America,
before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   I was deeply moved by these notes _ moved by the wisdom found in
such a simple truth: Treat others the way you want to be treated.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this seems idealistic and unobtainable. But it is
no more idealistic than it is to believe that attitudes about race
have changed along with laws.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't. Not all of them.
</P>
<P>
   And so I was moved by the wisdom in our children's words because
I believe, like them, that when we exercise love and forgiveness,
we promote healing.
</P>
<P>
   When asked which is the first commandment of all, Jesus said:
``And thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with
all thy soul, and with all thy mind, and with all thy strength:
this is the first commandment. And the second is like unto, namely
this: Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that no facet of human personality _ affection,
intellect or will _ is left untouched by love?
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
