<SLUG> BC-EASTER-TABLETOPS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Easter table settings can be high-end or budget savvy
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Martha Stewart wannabes, the table setting is
almost as important as the food.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers, china and stemware set the mood and style of the
occasion _ transforming even the most ordinary dinner into an
unforgettable experience for guests.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to create that party perfect table for Easter, which
is April 4, turn it into a pastel fantasy. Use the pretty shades of
traditionally dyed eggs _ lemon yellow, lavender, pale green and
apricot _ to create a fashionable, tasteful look.
</P>
<P>
   Easter has always been Atlanta interior designer Bill Cook's
favorite holiday. ``It celebrates spring,'' he says. ``And you have
all the wonderful shades of the new season with which to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect to see rabbits hopping around his table.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to get too thematic with the bunny thing,'' says
Cook. ``I prefer to decorate with the egg, the ancient symbol of
new life. Jelly beans or chocolate eggs are whimsical and witty and
can be used with traditional or contemporary china.''
</P>
<P>
   As a challenge, we asked Cook to set two contemporary Easter
tables _ an inexpensive look and a pricier version. Although we
used everything new for our settings, you might want to include
nostalgic family favorites on your table.
</P>
<P>
   TARGET:
</P>
<P>
   ELEGANTLY INEXPENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   For this setting, Cook found sleek plastic dinnerware at Target,
which included oval plates, square platters and oversize latte
cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid of mixing colors,'' he says, as he happily
combined shades of lemon, pale green, apricot and lavender in a
place setting. Clear tumblers, accented with stripes, flowers and
dots in the same colors, carried through the theme, as did the
place mats. Other touches: colorful cloth napkins, look-alike ivory
flatware, jelly beans and a wheat grass centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Cook also chose architect Michael Graves' stainless steel napkin
holder (below) with egg-shaped salt and pepper shakers as well as
his streamlined ice bucket, with oval handles (above).
</P>
<P>
   COST BREAKDOWN
</P>
<P>
   From Target stores: Soup bowl, $2.69; small bowl, $1.99; oval
salad plate, $2.49; dinner plate, $2.69; large striped or polka-dot
tumbler, $2.69; small tumbler, $2.49; latte cup, $2.49; 12-piece
casual flatwCOX 03-26  &UR; BC-PASSOVER27-COX
</P>
<P>
   Getting ready for passover can be a daunting task, but the
annual spring festival is a joyous celebration of freedom
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Hendrick
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Oy vey! Passover is coming, and time is short for
Debbie Deutsch, who works by day running a preschool and by night
chasing kids and cooking. And Tuesday she'll have to find time _
somehow _ to scour her house to rid it of every single crumb and
kernel of hametz.
</P>
<P>
   What's hametz?
</P>
<P>
   Anything made with grain _ such as wheat, rye, barley, oats,
beer, liquor, pasta, cookies, cakes, rice, dried peas and beans _
all forbidden to Jews during Passover, which begins with an
hours-long feast called a Seder on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she'll clean the oven, run the dishwasher _ empty _
a few times to make it kosher for Passover, remove everyday dishes,
put down new shelf paper, replace the plates and silverware
normally used with ones reserved for Passover, and draft her whole
family into the ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The forbidden foods contain leaven, the stuff that makes bread
rise, and during Passover is seen as a symbol of slavery, a
reminder of the Exodus from Egypt some 3,400 years ago. According
to the Torah, the Jewish name for the first five books of what
Christians call the Old Testament, the Israelites fled in such
haste they had no time to bake bread. So they took the dough and
baked it in the hot desert sun into hard, flat crackers called
matzo.
</P>
<P>
   For at least 1,800 years, matzo has been seen not only as a
reminder of oppression, but also of redemption, freedo a feeling of
control, and they can be very comforting. People find it reassuring
to be able to return to the same kinds of rituals, time after time.
It helps bring people and communities closer together. ``
</P>
<P>
   And this, says Dr. Stuart Vyse of Connecticut College, reduces
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``These rituals create a tie to the past and to the religious
group,'' he say. ``They create a sense of belonging that everyone
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin says leaven also symbolizes ``inflated ego,'' so getting
rid of hametz is like cleansing the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a choice we make,'' she says. ``It makes us feel whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
