<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROENING-FUTURAMA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIMPSONS' CREATOR GROENING FORWARDS TO `FUTURAMA'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Sunday, March 28 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The future looks familiar in ``Futurama,'' the new
animated series debuting tonight on Fox. No doubt, that's because
it's from Matt Groening, the man behind ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' begins on Dec. 31, 1999, when Fry (Billy West), a
down-and-out pizza delivery boy, accidentally falls into a
cryochamber and freezes while making a delivery to Applied
Cryogenics (``No power failures since 1997'').
</P>
<P>
   Fry stays frozen for 1,000 years while we watch out a window as
civilization is destroyed twice and then rebuilt. Awakened on Dec.
31, 2999, Fry is thrilled, seeing it as a chance to escape his
loser life, but a one-eyed alien woman, Leela (Katey Sagal), who is
the Fate Assignment Officer, tells him that the only job he is
suitable for is delivery boy. Since his new fate is looking a lot
like his former life, Fry flees when Leela tries to imprint him
with a permanent career chip.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly loses himself in 30th-century New York City, where
the motto is ``You gotta do what you gotta do.'' Throughout the
city are odd remnants of the past such as an Angelyne billboard
(isn't that an L.A. thing?). He then hooks up with a suicidal robot
named Bender (John DiMaggio) before ducking into the Head Museum to
hide from Leela and the authorities. There he is greeted by the
head of Leonard Nimoy, who can't do the Vulcan thing anymore since
he doesn't have hands. If you're quick, you'll see heads of Gillian
Anderson, David Duchovny, Dennis Rodman, Liz Taylor, Ms. Streisand
with Barbra misspelled as Barbara and Mr. Groening himself. Later
New Year's Rockin' Eve 3000 is introduced by the head of Dick
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, Bender and Leela eventually find themselves on the same
side and join craggy Professor Hubert Farnsworth, Fry's lone living
relative, on a voyage into space, where they will, presumably,
encounter weirder aliens than the ones here on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The animation on ``Futurama'' is a bit jazzier than ``The
Simpsons,'' but with the same bug-eyed faces. Judging by the first
episode, the writing isn't as sharp, though. Apart from the concept
of being trapped in the same future you were trapped in 1,000 years
before, most of the satirical targets are fairly obvious. Given
Groening's successful track record, you would have expected that he
try for something bolder _ both in animation and in concept.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, ``Futurama'' shares Fry's dilemma: It's caught in the
same old rut. But Groening has built up enough cachet that viewers
might want to stick around in ``Futurama'' long enough to give it a
chance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1511EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USDA-BEEF-$ADV0328-CO     03-26 1617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USDA-BEEF-$ADV0328-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUESTIONS RAISED ABOUT MEAT-FOR-SCHOOLS PROGRAM
 &HT;    For use Sunday, March 28, or thereafter
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    with COX-USDA-BOX-$ADV28
 &HT;    with photo of Almquist family
 &HT;    By Elliot Jaspin and Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FINLEY, Wash. - As battles go in the deadly war with the E. coli
bacteria, what happened last October in this dusty little town
would seem a minor skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve children got sick but no one died. Although state
officials are convinced meat in a school lunch caused the outbreak,
the source was never conclusively determined, and the supplier
denies any fault. Today, five months later, the E. coli 0157:H7
outbreak is remembered much like a bad summer storm that briefly
threatened and then passed on.
</P>
<P>
   But a Cox Newspapers investigation found that Finley's toxic
lunch reveals the risk children face because of the way the U.S.
Department of Agriculture runs the country's school lunch program.
The USDA, which donated the ground beef for Finley's tacos, bought
the meat from a plant with a history of E. coli contamination and
repeated serious food safety violations because it was the low
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's outrageous. Safety violators shouldn't be allowed to
participate in the lunch program,'' said Nancy Donley, president of
Safe Tables Our Priority (S.T.O.P.), a citizen's group long
concerned with E. coli issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The USDA should be putting them out of business, `` said
Donley, whose six-year-old son died in 1993 of E. coli poisoning,
``not helping them stay in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's problems began on Oct. 6, 1998, when the school served
a taco lunch to the children at Finley Elementary school. Within
days at least 12 children became violently ill from E. coli. When
the condition of four of the children worsened, they were
transferred to Seattle's Children's Hospital for blood transfusions
and, in one case, kidney dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   As doctors worked to save the lives of the 12 children,
investigators tried to track down the source of the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic testing showed that all the children were infected when
they ate the same food. The most likely source of the infection was
the ground beef in the tacos, even though health officials said
they did not find E. coli in the leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Northern States Beef Co., which produced the ground beef, cites
the negative tests as proof it was not the source of the outbreak.
But health officials say such seemingly contradictory findings are
not unusual because E. coli contamination is often restricted to
one small portion of ground beef. Where and how much of a sample
one takes can determine if the pathogen is found.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said it was more significant that, when they
examined the leftover taco meat, they found that some of the ground
beef was undercooked. Heat-sensitive E. coli bacteria would only be
able to survive and infect the children if the meat were improperly
cooked. They also said that, with one exception, the illness was
restricted to children who ate the school lunch. The exception, a
two-year-old who lives in the neighborhood, is thought to have been
infected through contact with one of the school children.
</P>
<P>
   What the townspeople in Finley never knew _ because federal
officials never told them _ was that in the 18 months prior to the
government purchase the Agriculture Department's own inspectors
found 171 ``critical'' violations of U.S. food safety regulations
at the Northern States Beef plant.
</P>
<P>
   A ``critical'' violation is defined by the Agriculture
Department as a plant condition that is ``certain'' to cause
contamination of food, which is ``certain'' to reach consumers, and
is ``certain to have a detrimental effect upon the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal records show inspectors cited the plant repeatedly for
the same kinds of violations. For example, the plant amassed 64
critical violations in 1996 for the failure of its pre-operational
sanitation procedures such as properly cleaning equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to food safety violations, federal officials linked
the Northern State's plant to an April 1994 E. coli outbreak that
sickened at least 18 people in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern States Beef plant had more violations than most
other plants of its size in 1996, the last year for which complete
records are available. By comparison, a plant in Nebraska operated
by Hudson Foods _ with 90 critical violations in 1996 _ was forced
to halt production in 1997 after it had the largest recall of E.
coli tainted ground beef in the history of the meat inspection
program.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Northern States' track record, government records show
the Agriculture Department purchased over 20 million pounds of beef
from the plant as part of its commodities program.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal law, the track record for Northern States
Beef should have been taken into account before the government
purchased meat from the plant. The law establishing the School
Lunch Program orders the Agriculture Secretary to ``establish
procedures'' to ensure the wholesomeness of food bought for school
lunches.
</P>
<P>
   The law goes on to say that ``...contracts for the purchase of
commodities shall not be entered into unless previous history and
current patterns of the contracting party with respect to
compliance with applicable meat inspection laws... are taken into
account.''
</P>
<P>
   USDA spokesman Andy Solomon said that food graders are in each
plant as meat is being prepared for the school lunch program.
Although he said these officials do not test for E. coli, they do
test for spoilage, which Solomon said indicates in a general way
the cleanliness of a plant.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon added that the government did take one sample for E.
coli at the Northern States plant in 1997, 1998, and 1999 and all
three samples were negative. By contrast, the Jack-In-The-Box
hamburger chain does E. coli testing every 15 minutes at plants
that supply it.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Shanholtzer, a spokesman for the USDA's Food and
Nutrition Service, which distributes the commodities, said his
agency does not check the safety of meat used in the school lunch
programs. ``FSIS (Food Safety and Inspection Service) is USDA's
meat and poultry safety agency. They work for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was FSIS inspectors who detailed the problems at the Northern
States Beef plant in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Phares, a spokesperson for ConAgra, which owns Northern
States Beef, said there is no proof that meat from that plant
played any role in the Finley outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Government) tests were negative,'' said Phares, ``So it's
perplexing to us that they (Washington State health officials)
would say this.''
</P>
<P>
   She also termed her company's role in the 1994 E. coli outbreak
as ``inconclusive.'' While she acknowledged the tainted ground beef
came from the Northern States plant, she said some of the meat used
to make the ground beef came from other plants.
</P>
<P>
   Local health officials in Washington state are unanimous that
the school lunch caused the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rational thought leads you to the taco meat,'' said Dr. Larry
D. Jecha, the district health officer for the Benton-Franklin
Health District. He said county health officials found evidence of
undercooked ground beef _ a common source of infection _ in the
taco meat, all but one of the children ate the meal, and the
genetic signature of the pathogen that infected everyone was
identical.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials like David Gifford agree. ``The logical
conclusion was that it was the meat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Phillip Tarr, a Seattle-based expert in E. coli outbreaks,
summed up the Finley evidence, saying, ``Absence of proof does not
mean proof of absence.''
</P>
<P>
   While health officials in Washington state said all meat should
be considered dangerous and cooked thoroughly, they said that does
not excuse federal officials from trying to provide meat that is
wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher the risk the more care should be taken,'' argues
Bruce Perkins, a county health official. ``Maybe the better way (to
provide meat for school lunch programs) is to see who has the best
inspection records and buy from those people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department buys large quantities of beef and
pork through its commodities program for two reasons. One goal is
to support food prices when the market has gone soft, and the
second is to supply schools, soup kitchens and other social service
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the USDA spent more than $219 million buying more than
209 million pounds of frozen and canned meats. Most of the meat is
given to schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked,'' said Alan Almquist, father of one of the
children sickened in the outbreak, when told about the USDA role.
``It's like the government is approving of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize I was sending my child into a danger zone,'''
added Almquist's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Almquist's son was one of four children who had to be
transferred to Seattle Children's Hospital over 200 miles away as
their condition worsened. ``I can't tell you how close my son came
to dying,'' Almquist said.
</P>
<P>
   The parents' dismay was echoed by Robert Van Slyke, the
superintendent of the Finley schools. He said he was ``outraged''
by the USDA's silence.
</P>
<P>
   Van Slyke said federal officials had a responsibility to tell
him about the source of the beef before the school cafeteria
workers used it and, after the outbreak, to disclose what they
knew. ``It was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they knew (about the violations) and didn't say, how far
can we go in trusting what they say now. ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
