<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUNANAN-BOOK-$ADV29-H     03-26 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNANAN-BOOK-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER EXPLORES THE STORY OF THE ANDREW CUNANAN MANHUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Vanity Fair story that Maureen Orth had
researched for two months about Andrew Cunanan's cross-country
killing spree was ready for typesetting when word came that Cunanan
was the chief suspect in the July 1997 killing of international
designer Gianni Versace on the steps of his South Beach mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Orth hurried to Florida for additional reporting and added the
necessary coda. At that point, Cunanan was still at large, and the
mystery of whom he was and why he killed was growing along with one
of the largest manhunts in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Cunanan had killed four people in three states over the course
of 13 days. ``We were in the final fact-checking process,'' says
Orth, an intense brunette with a brilliant smile and a steel-trap
mind. ``We were juggling and cutting and adding, and then we had to
open the story up a third time when they found Cunanan's body. That
issue went to press later than any in Vanity Fair history.''
</P>
<P>
   The story has become a book, Orth's first, called ``Vulgar
Favors: Andrew Cunanan, Gianni Versace and the Largest Failed
Manhunt in U.S. History'' (Delacorte Press). The book and film
rights were sold by hotshot literary agent Amanda ``Binky'' Urban
even before the magazine hit the newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of nine months, Orth interviewed as many as 500
people, some of them twice. One of them was San Francisco socialite
Harry de Wildt. Six of Orth's sources went on record to say they
had seen de Wildt in a limousine with Versace and Cunanan when the
designer was in San Francisco, preparing the costumes for the San
Francisco Opera's production of ``Capriccio.''
</P>
<P>
   De Wildt has always denied that he knew Cunanan. ``Andrew was a
great aspirer,'' says Orth, ``and he was fascinated with de Wildt,
whom I called for my Vanity Fair article. He told me that Andrew
was a `nobody' who was probably fascinated with the idea of him and
Gordon Getty.''
</P>
<P>
   Why then, if people saw them together with Versace after meeting
at Colossus, a massive weekend gay dance party, did de Wildt deny
meeting Cunanan? Orth can only surmise that ``he didn't want to be
the conduit for this connection.''
</P>
<P>
   For 19 months, Orth immersed herself in the sad, sordid life of
the half-Sicilian, half-Filipino man. Cunanan, says Orth, ``never
lived in reality. He was spoiled and so materialistic that he
realized the only way he could get everything he wanted was to sell
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cunanan, who never told the same story about himself twice,
``the center didn't hold,'' Orth continues. ``He was a pastiche and
a narcissist and in the end, the only thing that counted was image.
He became so frustrated and enraged; he wanted to be famous so
badly. Finally, he would have to kill to be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Orth's first book _ as she puts it, at the age of
``50ish,'' she has finally written the big book. ``My mother said
to me after reading something written by some rock star, `Maureen,
what's the matter with you? Any damn fool can write a book.'''
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody sinks their teeth into their subject matter
like Maureen Orth, who worries her subjects to death with extensive
research.
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter for Newsweek, Orth had eight cover stories in five
years, including Bob Dylan's comeback, Bruce Springsteen and
Francis Ford Coppola. Her work has always been edgy and fluent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She didn't start out to be a writer. Orth graduated from the
television documentary program at the University of California at
Los Angeles. A political science major who had spent two years in
the Peace Corps in Colombia, she was hired by the CBS affiliate in
Sacramento and then promptly fired when management decided it
couldn't have more than one woman on the anchor team.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1970. To keep body and soul together, she moved back to
the San Francisco area and wrote public relations releases for
friends, including a group of lawyers who had just bought a
warehouse full of MGM effluvia.
</P>
<P>
   The memorabilia had come to the attention of Hal Silverman,
editor of the San Francisco Examiner's former Sunday magazine,
California Living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hal wanted to know who these people were,'' Orth says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were dope lawyers _ Hal asked me to write about them,
about the counterculture. I'd never written anything in my life. I
met this man at a party who was carrying a briefcase. In it, he
said, was the sixth draft of his book. He asked to see the notes
for my story, and he underlined everything that should be used as a
quote, and together we cut and pasted the article together.''
</P>
<P>
   The helpful Samaritan? Alex Haley, who was carrying around the
final draft of ``Roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Her second story for Silverman was about Jesus freaks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the dope lawyer story had been picked up by New York
magazine writer Nick Pileggi. ``He felt so bad about stealing my
story that he turned the Village Voice onto me.'' In less than
three years, Orth was working for Newsweek in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she married a consultant for NBC named Tim Russert
who is now moderator for ``Meet the Press.'' They have a son named
Luke who is 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1522EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STOP-BOMBING-N     03-26 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STOP-BOMBING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 NATO AIR STRIKES: DANGEROUS and COUNTERPRODUCTIVE  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world affairs. To publish it as a ``separate
buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _
from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The decision of the United States and its NATO allies to strike
Yugoslavia is a very dangerous step fraught with unpredictable
consequences not only for Europe but for the whole world. Let us
call a spade a spade; it's an aggression.
 &HT;    War has effectively been declared on a sovereign state going
through an internal conflict. The behavior of the Yugoslav
government in the conflict and in the talks aimed at settling it
deserves, at the very least, severe criticism.
 &HT;    But the fact remains: NATO's military action is a blatant
violation of international law. The U.N. Charter permits such
action only in self-defense or with authority from the U.N.
Security Council. Neither was present.
 &HT;    What the Western alliance led by the United States is in effect
saying is that might is right and it wants a monopoly position in
the world power system. Clearly, a ``victory complex'' is at work
here, born of the heady conviction that the West won the Cold War.
But in international affairs, superiority complexes can be at least
as dangerous as inferiority complexes. ``Acting with resolve''
should imply a great sense of responsibility and vision.
 &HT;    Western negotiators in the talks on Kosovo settlement told us
again and again that without the threat of force the talks would go
nowhere. It is now clear that the threat was counterproductive.
Instead of recognizing the failure of that course and persevering
in a search for compromise, NATO is compounding the mistake. We are
now being told that bombs and cruise missiles will help to
``prevent a humanitarian catastrophe in Kosovo'' _ an argument that
is nothing but thinly veiled hypocrisy.
 &HT;    The use of force always points to a fiasco of policy and
policy-makers. Even when, in early 1991, there was legal
justification for the use of force against Iraq, I insisted on the
use of all political means and stressed that the military operation
could be avoided. Today, we see that Western politicians are making
a habit of using force. But is it not clear that this has not made
the world more secure?
 &HT;    It is amazing how quickly the United States and NATO have fallen
into a double standard in assessing internal conflicts and ways of
solving them. I won't cite the all-too-familiar examples where such
conflicts _ and even some governments' waging war on their own
people _ caused but a mild rebuke from the United States. Was it
alliance ties that influenced the response, or perhaps fear of
becoming involved in a conflict fraught with the risk of major
American casualties?
 &HT;    There are dozens of conflicts and crises, raging or latent, in
the world today. Should air strikes and military operations be used
to deal with all those conflicts? What would be the outcome of
that? Could it be another Cold War?
 &HT;    I urge Western policy-makers to give thought to these questions.
I endorse Russia's firm stand against the use of force. True,
Russia is no longer a superpower, but that kind of strength is not
the only factor that makes for strong policies.
 &HT;    Yevgeni Primakov's decision to cancel his visit to Washington
was dramatic and probably difficult to take, but I believe it was
right under the circumstances. For the West, it would be another
mistake to try to ``punish'' Russia for this position of principle.
I think that acting in this way, Russia is defending not just its
own interests.
 &HT;    There is still room for a political solution to the conflict.
Every opportunity should be used. A way has to be found out of a
situation brought about by wrongheaded policies. The problem must
be examined by the U.N. Security Council, and a negotiating
mechanism should be recreated.
 &HT;    I call upon the Yugoslav government to accept the political part
of the agreement worked out in Paris and to discuss a mechanism for
its implementation that would involve the participation of the
international community. Russia could play a major constructive
role in this process, whose resumption is indispensable if we are
not to slip into another Cold War.
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
