<HEADER>
A5392 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEALER-AUTO-BOS &LR;      03-26 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEALER-AUTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKEUP IN AUTO DEALERSHIPS HITS MASSACHUSETTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWOOD, Mass. _ Ernie Boch, whose ``Come on down'' tagline
helped make him a legend on the Route 1 auto mile, is very clear
about what is at the core of his car-selling philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll beat anyone on the showroom floor,'' says the 72-year-old
salesman. ``I believe 100 percent in free trade. You survive on
your own. You don't need any protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an industry where car manufacturers and giant chains are
putting the squeeze on independent dealers, most of Boch's
colleagues in Massachusetts don't agree with him. They say they
need more protection in dealing with the likes of Ford, General
Motors, and Toyota, not to mention big regional players like Boch,
who in addition to owning four dealerships is the exclusive New
England distributor for Subaru.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of dealer discontent are everywhere, and Boch is a
prime target. Seven current and former Subaru dealers have sued
Boch in federal court, alleging a pattern of harassment designed to
force them to take cars with expensive unwanted accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Clair Honda in West Roxbury is in court trying to stop Boch from
opening a new Honda dealership 4 miles away in Norwood. And the
state association of auto dealers is pushing legislation that not
only would give them more leverage in their dealings with
manufacturers but also force Boch to divest either his Subaru
distributorship or his Toyota, Oldsmobile, Mitsubishi, and Kia
dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Given that both sides of this issue are populated with
salespeople, it's not surprising that all the players claim to have
the interests of the car-buying public at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Boch, who has hired a lobbyist and is attacking the dealer
campaign head-on, says the lawsuits and the legislation seek to
stifle him and competition, which will result in higher prices for
car buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition works. It flushes everything out,'' said Boch, who
says he outsold all other Toyota, Mitsubishi, and Oldsmobile
dealers in the region last year. Adding in the Subarus he sold to
dealers, he moved 31,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's legislative sponsor, Senator Stephen F. Lynch, a
South Boston Democrat, says car manufacturers and ``chosen
dealers'' like Boch want to do to the automobile business what Home
Depot has done to the hardware store business _ eliminate mom and
pop stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smacks of anticompetitiveness,'' Lynch said. ``It's better
for the people I represent to have this competiton and have these
dealers out in the neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate in Massachusetts is just starting to heat up, but
it's already boiling in other parts of the country. After years of
taking a hands-off attitude toward dealers, manufacturers over the
last four years have tried to gain more control over how dealers
operate.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is buying stakes in dealerships in Oklahoma, Texas, and a
handful of other states. GM is taking control of advertising funds
it once allotted to local dealerships. And chains such as CarMax
and AutoNation are gobbling up dealerships. Industry analysts say
the goal is to reduce costs and increase profits by operating
fewer, larger dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is unmistakable. Last year, the National Automobile
Dealers Association said Americans bought 15.5 million cars from
22,400 dealers, 200 less than the year before. Forty percent of the
sales were made by dealers with multiple facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real upheaval going on in the retail landscape
right now,'' said Jack Madden, owner of Jack Madden Ford in Norwood
and the president of the Massachusetts Auto Dealers Association.
``A lot of dealers who have been in the business for years are
feeling threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill being pushed by Madden's organization would update
dealer protections in three major ways:
</P>
<P>
   --Protected areas. If a manufacturer decides to open or relocate
a dealership, a dealer selling the same brand within a 15-mile
radius of the proposed location would have standing to try to block
it. The actual area is larger, since it includes any town touched
by the 15-mile circle. Protests are more restricted under existing
law.
</P>
<P>
   --Automatic stays. Any dealer challenging a manufacturer's
decision to cancel his franchise, move it, or place a competing
dealership nearby could automatically stay the action by filing a
protest with a seven-member state board, of which three members
would be auto dealers. The onus of proving the action was warranted
would be on the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   --Dealer discipline. Manufacturers would have far less
flexibility in disciplining dealers for sales and service
violations or fraud on warranty work. Warranty work reviews would
be limited to one year, instead of the three years allowed under
current law. Any dealer accused of warranty fraud could stay any
disciplinary action by appealing to the state board.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the provisions in the bill address complaints made in
the Subaru suit against Boch. A common denominator of the bill and
the lawsuit is Richard Kalika, the owner of Wakefield Subaru.
Kalika, a plaintiff in the lawsuit and the head of the dealer
committee that drafted the legislation, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   One provision in the legislation would bar manufacturers or
distributors like Boch from owning any dealerships in the state.
Some people familiar with the drafting say Boch was targeted, but
Lynch says that is not the intent of his bill.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Curhan, legal counsel to the state dealers association, is
emphatic that the bill is not an attack on Boch. He says consumers
will be well-served if the bill passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately,'' he said, ``it means the forces of the market
determine who stays in business, not a marketing committee in
Detroit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
