<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5399 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICAN-COMPUTER-WHIZ     03-26 1889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-COMPUTER-WHIZ-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVENGE OF THE NERDS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By BRENDAN M. CASE, with additional reporting by Latin Trade staff 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Scooting about his office among three computers, typing at a
speed faster than most people are capable of thinking, Miguel de
Icaza is nearly oblivious to anything but his bold plan to reclaim
the software industry from corporate giants. At his day job, the
25-year-old oversees the computer network at a Mexico City research
institute. But by night, De Icaza coordinates a small band of
guerrilla programmers over the Internet in a global struggle
against Microsoft's dominance of the products that make computers
run.
 &HT;    Using a powerful computer system favored by the technically
savvy, De Icaza and his team have created rivals to the popular
Microsoft Windows and Office programs. They are volunteers, in the
spirit of collaboration that ruled the Internet in its early days.
Their product, called Gnome (pronounced guh-NOME), is free to
anyone who wants to download the software.
 &HT;    What sounds like a Lilliputian effort has come to be recognized
as the biggest threat to the profits of the mighty software
industry, including its largest, wealthiest member, Microsoft.
Working together worldwide via the Internet, software aficionados
have long created products for fun and charity as well as to solve
important problems. Whether born from a hatred of one corporation's
control of the desktop or an esthetic urge to write beautiful code,
De Icaza's hobby is now putting him at the front of a growing band
of Internet-connected techies that aim to kill the giant.
 &HT;    De Icaza has already won his first battle: Authorities at
Mexico's Public Education Ministry have chosen Gnome software over
the standard Microsoft package for the landmark Scholar Net program
to bring 1 million Internet-connected computers into schools.
Microsoft executives feel the heat: ``We have meetings every week
with the top management of Scholar Net,'' says Microsoft's
Alejandro Flores, who claims that his company has an agreement to
provide the ministry with Windows software. ``If they want to
negotiate price, we're willing to do so to get our product in,'' he
says, at any price. ``Maybe even for free.''
 &HT;    Even for free, De Icaza can compete. The main weapon in his
Gnome arsenal is Linux (rhymes with `cynics'), a program that
controls the basic functions of a computer. The collaborative
achievement of the renowned MIT programmer Richard Stallman, a
Finnish programmer named Linus Torvalds and thousands of others
around the world, the complex software is a prime example of what
is known as open-source software. Such programs carry no
copyrights. In fact, they carry ``copylefts,'' an industry term
meaning anyone with a hankering to tinker withand perhaps
improvetheir underlying command codes may do so. The only condition
is that users must pass along their improvements to others.
 &HT;    Proponents of the open-source movement say that as a result of
massive collaboration, their programs are more stable and just
plain better than similar proprietary software. For cash-strapped
organizations, open-source products have another major perk: They
are free.
 &HT;    The Windows serfs are most concerned about the Linux brand of
free software. ``Linux is growing very fast, much faster than other
open-source products,'' says Microsoft's Flores. ``Microsoft is
working to develop a strategy against that.''
 &HT;    While largely unknown outside of computing circles, Linux
already has millions of high-tech users and powers huge corporate
networks and Internet servers around the globe. Computer geeks and
network administrators admire the software for its power and the
fact that they can tinker with the source code to tweak the system
to their individual needs. Internet service providers favor the
operating system for all that, but they especially love it because
anything that comes for free is a godsend in that tight-margin
business. Strong ties to the Internet technical crowd have also
guaranteed that Linux programs are widely available for downloading
around the world, a major distribution advantage.
 &HT;    But what Linux had long lacked were useful programs for ordinary
people. Not so long ago, all personal computer users faced the same
problem. Then in the mid-1980s, first Apple's Macintosh, and then
Microsoft Windows revolutionized desktop computing with easy-to-use
applications that did not require the use of special command
language. The point-and-click method allowed users to operate a
computer without having to understand what went on inside the
machine. ``Most people just want a computer to do something useful
for them,'' says Dan Kusnetzky, an analyst at International Data
Corp.
 &HT;    De Icaza began using Linux as an 18-year-old computer-science
student at the National Autonomous University of Mexico. He came
across a German project called KDE, which attempted to create a
Linux system that worked similar to Windows. But after trying it,
De Icaza came away frustrated. He complained to friends about its
shortcomings. Instead of sharing his sorrow, they goaded him on,
saying why don't you do something about it'
 &HT;    So he did.
 &HT;    Within a few days, he had arranged a small team of programmers
to develop their own group of useful tools for Linux. A week later,
they had posted their first lines of source code on the Internet
and tagged their project as Gnome, which stands for GNU Network
Object Model Environment. ``The first programs didn't do anything,'
De Icaza says, ``but they showed people we were serious and that
generated a lot of interest.''
 &HT;    The state of controlled chaos gained momentum as programmers
from around the world joined nto the project, communicating and
delivering their work through the Internet. De Icaza and the other
programmers involved had to agree to use one single version of the
base program. They decided on one and began to write Gnome's
programs on top of it.
 &HT;    Now, less than two years later, De Icaza and his team are set to
post Gnome 1.0 on the Internet (www.gnome. org) though the first
version may be somewhat of a rough draft. It will include a word
processing program, spreadsheet and other features built to look
and feel like Microsoft Office, with two exceptions. First, they
are free, whereas Office costs about US$200 in Mexico. Second,
since the source codes are available to the public, any programmer
can fix bugs and make customized adjustments that adapt the
programs to the needs of a particular person or organization. 'I
don't want to live in a world where I'm dependent on what Microsoft
does and where I'm tied down to Microsoft's mistakes,' says De
Icaza.
 &HT;    Among its followers, which tend to be professional computer
scientists or devoted amateurs, this is the charm of Linux. As
individual improvements are made, word spreads rapidly by Internet
within the global community of software programmers, who then
download the updates. Many Linux programmers are motivated by an
esthetic impulse to create good software; others simply dislike
Microsoft and its stranglehold on the software industry. But most
computer users are not charmed by the idea of tweaking obscure
software codes. Tapping that realization was key to turning Bill
Gates'' dynamo into the mega wealth creator of the 1990s.
 &HT;    Despite its communal roots, there is money to be made in
open-source software, too. At least two U.S. companies, Red Hat and
Caldera Systems, put the best open-source software they can find on
compact disks and sell them for a small fee. The firms also charge
for technical support and service. Companies in Latin America are
catching on. Conectiva Informatica, a Brazilian software firm,
distributes a CD and user's manual of Linux programs. ``We estimate
there are about 100,000 Linux installations in Brazil, including
more than 50 percent of Internet service providers, a large private
bank and public hospitals, to name a few,'' says Sandro Henrique, a
company executive. ``We're always looking for ways to find new
customers.''
 &HT;    Neither Linux nor Gnome will spark a conversion of the masses
from Microsoft, but numerous potential customers do exist.
Organizations that have their own technology staff and that would
rather spend time than money on computing solutions are prime
targets. These institutions could provide the spark for wider
recognition and usage.
 &HT;    Indeed, Gnome had already begun catching on even before the
first official version hit the Internet.
 &HT;    Last year, Mexico's Public Education Ministry began buying
thousands of computers to outfit Scholar Net, a program to spread
computer literacy in the schools. Within five years, offidials aim
to install 140,000 computer labs with an average of seven computers
per lab, nearly a million machines.
 &HT;    Project leader Arturo Espinosa faced a choice. He could have
paid licensing fees to Microsoft on hundreds of thousands of copies
of Wows 98 and Microsoft Office at a cost of $55 a pop, plus $500
licensing fees on Windows NT for each of the project's servers. The
alternative to paying tens of millions of dollars was to take a
risk on a preliminary version of Gnome and pay nothing. ``In the
case of an educational system, where users don't have to worry
about a lot of packaged software'' says IDC's Kusnetzky, ``Linux
would make a lot of sense.''
 &HT;    Not so, argues Microsoft's Flores, who repeats what he told
Mexico's Education Ministry: ``The problem they face in the future
is who will give them support'' There are not enough people in
Mexico to travel around the country to fix a Linux server. All the
people who know Linux are in Mexico City.''
 &HT;    But Kusnetzky says that support for the two options is hard to
compare. ``Microsoft has a good track record of fixing high-profile
problems quickly, but when dealing with lower visibility issues,
Microsoft's track record isn't quite as good,'' he says. ``Linux is
really working with a different model. It is a group collaboration
rather than a supplier/purchaser model. Linux folks help one
another.''
 &HT;    Espinosa? He chose the freebie.
 &HT;    So far, he reports smooth operations and low cost. To keep the
system current, satellites will beam versions of Gnome as upgrades
are released. Says Espinosa, ``At an average of 20 users per
computer, all of them school children and teachers, these programs
will become a major influence in Mexico.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
