<HEADER>
A5406 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NESHOBA-RIGHTS-BOS &LR;      03-26 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NESHOBA-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE GROWS TO REOPEN PROBE OF MURDERS OF CIVIL RIGHTS WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA, Miss. _ The 1964 murder of three civil rights
workers has cast a shadow over Neshoba County for more than a
generation, and memories are being stirred again by the possibility
of new prosecutions in the infamous case.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since a federal trial against 18 defendants ended
with mixed results, many of the suspects in the original
investigation have lived quietly in this rural, east Mississippi
community. But pressure to reopen the case intensified after state
prosecutors won a murder conviction last August against former Ku
Klux Klan leader Sam Bowers for his role in another 1960s civil
rights slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The new investigation is said to focus on an aging
fundamentalist minister, Edgar Ray ``Preacher'' Killen, according
to people familiar with the case. Several others who stood trial on
federal conspiracy charges more than three decades ago also could
face state charges.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney for Neshoba County, Ken Turner, asked the
FBI in January to turn over its files on the Neshoba investigation.
Because the state never filed murder charges, the prosecutor still
has an option to do so, though Turner has not decided whether to
seek indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Although a massive casino opened near here by a Choctaw tribe
has changed the complexion of the countryside, the county seat of
Philadelphia, with a population of 7,000 and a courthouse square
surrounded by storefronts, has never shaken its association with
the murders. That link was cemented in the public's mind a decade
ago with the film ``Mississippi Burning.''
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of James Chaney, a young black man from nearby
Meridian, and two white companions from New York, Michael Schwerner
and Andrew Goodman, represented one of the most chilling chapters
in the history of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   In June, 1964, at the beginning of a ``Freedom Summer''
operation in Mississippi, the three activists were arrested here on
a traffic violation. According to testimony, a death warrant for
Schwerner had been ordered by Bowers, who was the imperial wizard
of the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan. While the civil rights
workers were detained, a posse composed of Neshoba County Deputy
Sheriff Cecil Price and several Klansmen assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after their release from jail, the three men were
intercepted on a lonely road four miles outside Philadelphia,
executed, and buried under a red clay dam.
</P>
<P>
   President Lyndon B. Johnson dispatched dozens of FBI agents to
the state to look for the missing civil rights workers, even as
local authorities suggested their disappearance was a hoax. Six
weeks later, the bodies were discovered when an informant led the
FBI to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The state never sought indictments, but federal prosecutors
charged 18 men with conspiracy to violate the civil rights of the
three victims and brought the defendants to trial in Meridian in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, regarded as the mastermind behind the killing, was
convicted and served six years. After his release from prison,
Bowers lived as a free man for more than two decades in Laurel, 80
miles south of here, until a state jury found him guilty last year
of ordering the murder of Vernon Dahmer, an NAACP leader, in 1966.
He is serving a life sentence at the Mississippi state
pentitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Sheriff Price and five others were also convicted in the
1967 trial. Price served four years in federal prison, then
returned to his family here. He worked for a trucking firm owned by
Olen Burrage, a wealthy Philadelphia landowner who was acquitted in
the case. (The bodies of Chaney, Schwerner, and Goodman were found
on Burrage's property.) Price joined the local Shriners
organization, and later became a drivers license tester for the
state until he was recently indicted in federal court for
falsifying test results.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Lawrence Rainey and seven others were acquitted in 1967.
Rainey went on to work as a security guard in Meridian, and several
of his codefendants still live in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The cases against ``Preacher'' Killen and two others were
declared a mistrial when the jury failed to reach a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe the jury had a tough time because not enough
was brought out'' on Killen, said former FBI agent Jim Ingram.
Ingram headed the agency's civil rights desk in Mississippi in 1964
and currently is the state public safety commissioner. Killen
appears to be the key target in the current investigation, said
Ingram, who testified against Bowers in last year's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Although Killen was implicated in two confessions given to the
FBI, the statements were not used in the 1967 trial.
</P>
<P>
   According to transcripts of the confessions published recently
by a Jackson newspaper, the Clarion-Ledger, James Jordan, a Neshoba
County Klansman, said Killen told him that ``they had three civil
rights workers in jail in Philadelphia and that they needed their
`asses tore up.' '' Jordan admitted his guilt in a plea-bargain
arrangement with federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   After FBI agents tracked down another Klansman, Horace Doyle
Barnette, in Louisiana five months after the murders, they obtained
a second confession in which Barnette said Killen had told a group
of Klansmen, ``We have a place to bury them and a man to run the
'dozer to cover them up.'' Barnette later renounced the confession,
but he was convicted in the 1967 trial and sentenced to three years
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jack Rucker, a retired FBI agent who worked on the
case 35 years ago, ``Killen was right in the middle of planning to
get the group together'' to carry out the murders. In a telephone
interview from his home in Alabama, Rucker said Killen escaped with
a mistrial because the jury concentrated ``on the ones there at the
shooting and let the ones who planned it get off.''
</P>
<P>
   Killen professed innocence and lashed back at the FBI in a brief
interview last week. He said his accusers ``were told what to say
by the FBI.'' Killen said the agency tried to pit suspects against
each other during the original investigation. Rucker, Killen said,
``was the one carrying the money around to pay them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Killen, 74, denied any Klan affiliations and said no authorities
have questioned him lately. He is a Baptist minister with relatives
in Neshoba County and lives on a farm near Philadelphia, but no
longer has a church.
</P>
<P>
   The case has stirred passions long after the first
investigations were closed. About a decade ago, Dick Molpus, a
member of one of Neshoba County's leading families, publicly
expressed regret at a black church built on the ashes of a
sanctuary burned here in 1964. Molpus was secretary of state at the
time. Four years ago, as the Democratic nominee for governor,
Molpus was ridiculed for the apology by his victorious opponent,
Republican Governor Kirk Fordice.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the other day about the prospect of reopening the case,
Molpus said: ``I don't think murder can be forgiven. There's no
statute of limitation. If the evidence is pulled together, I
believe the attorney general and the district attorney should act
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of the victims never let the case die. Ben Chaney, a
brother of the slain Mississippian, pushed for years to reopen the
case. Earlier this year, Schwerner's widow, Rita, called upon state
Attorney General Mike Moore to ``bring closure to these events by
the vigorous pursuit of justice.'' Moore lent state investigators
to local prosecutors in the Bowers case last year, but has made no
moves yet in the Neshoba affair.
</P>
<P>
   Obie Clark, president of the NAACP chapter in Chaney's hometown
of Meridian, said he was encouraged by developments. ``The level of
interest in the case is still high'' in black circles in
Mississippi, he said, because of the successful prosecution of
Bowers and Byron De La Beckwith, who was convicted five years ago
for the 1963 murder of NAACP leader Medgar Evers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're optimistic,'' Clark said. ``At least the district
attorney's looking at it. That's something we never had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of District Attorney Turner say he is in an awkward
position. He will be condemned by some if he chooses not to
prosecute, said Don Kilgore, a local attorney. Yet if he seeks
indictments, ``it could kill him politically'' by antagonizing
those who do not want the old wounds reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgore and Fent Deweese, another lawyer who was a teenager at
Philadelphia High School when the murders took place, discussed the
town's dilemma over lunch here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went into the service and would be asked where I was
from, people would say `That's where they killed the civil rights
workers.' It stigmatized me,'' Kilgore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got really good people who live here,'' Deweese said,
and the infamy is ``a hell of a burden.'' Reviving the case ``will
bring closure for the families'' of the victims ``and cause serious
problems here.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of its painful history, both men said Philadelphia
is prepared for a new ordeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
