<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-26 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS BIG BANK'S BIG BOSS GOING TO DO FOR BOSTON?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parochial thinkers want to know. What is the king of the hill
going to do for the city on a hill?
</P>
<P>
   Terry Murray, chief executive of Fleet Financial Group Inc., is
being touted as a visionary and dealmaker extraordinaire for
putting together Fleet's proposed merger with BankBoston Corp. If a
few thousand people lose their jobs and consumers lose a banking
choice, so what? As the '90s draw to a close, this much is clear:
The big picture counts, not the little one, and certainly not the
little people.
</P>
<P>
   And Murray is truly master of the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   He sketched out a career of power and success from humble
beginnings in Woonsocket, R.I., and a job at a tiny Providence
bank. First he built that tiny bank into the nation's
ninth-largest. And now the merger of Fleet and BankBoston will
produce a superregional institution, Fleet Boston Corp. Its
combined $178 billion in assets stand to make it the country's
eighth-largest bank and a strong national and international
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question remains: Can a big thinker like Murray think
small _ as in Boston?
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry played the Boston card,'' an ever-anonymous BankBoston
executive confided to the Globe. He was explaining how Murray
sealed the deal with Chad Gifford, BankBoston's chief executive, by
playing to his rival's loyalty to this city, not to mention a
propensity for high-profile do-gooder acts like carving turkeys at
the Pine Street Inn.
</P>
<P>
   After playing the Boston card to make the deal, what will Murray
do with the entire deck?
</P>
<P>
   He flashed in and out of the Hub when he acquired the failed
Bank of New England in 1991. It was clear then that his heart,
soul, and home remained in Rhode Island. After taking over Shawmut
in 1995, Boston became Fleet's official headquarters, and Murray
purchased the obligatory antique-filled condo in the Four Seasons.
His heart, soul, and home still remained in Rhode Island. Since
then, however, he has taken steps that show some promising
commitment to this city and state.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Fleet donated $13.5 million to charitable causes in
the Northeast, according to bank spokesman Jim Mahoney.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Fleet stepped up in a big way in 1998 to sponsor
``Monet in the 20th Century,'' a blockbuster show at the Museum of
Fine Arts. The bank contributed $1.2 million to the museum and
spent a million dollars more to make the exhibit available to the
broadest possible audience.
</P>
<P>
   The scale, says Mahoney, ``reflected Fleet's coming of age as a
corporate citizen in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Fleet also contributed $1 million to the Boston public
schools. It was targeted to fund an effort by the Harvard School of
Education to provide professional development.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will make more Monet-like contributions, says Mahoney.
But beyond outright corporate giving, what role will Murray play in
ongoing civic debates?
</P>
<P>
   This week, Fleet Financial announced that it is negotiating a
groundbreaking, multimillion sponsorship deal with Major League
Baseball that would create a national presence for the bank. The
deal would make Fleet the first bank to become a national sponsor
of any of the four major sports leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Such interest in national sports lending raises another obvious
local question: What about the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft, a longtime BankBoston
customer, just happens to be a potential new Fleet Boston customer
just as Kraft's plan to move the team to Hartford could be falling
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there is one last opportunity to come up with a
Massachusetts solution. And perhaps Murray can be the one to seize
it. Not much money _ just a lot of ego _ stood between the House
and Senate versions of a plan to renovate Foxboro Stadium. Could
Murray help lead the respective egos to a comfortable middle
ground?
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's Mahoney says Murray would not intervene if Kraft goes
forward with a Hartford move. But if Kraft is contemplating a move
to another region of the country, Mahoney says, ``Terry would
absolutely do whatever he could to try to prevent that from
happening. He does think that having the Patriots in the region is
an important element of the local regional economy. He would
certainly participate actively in any efforts to keep the team from
leaving the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Irish-American roots, Harvard degree, and front-row
Fenway box seat, Murray is an outsider here. That's not necessarily
bad; he is less encumbered by petty political and personality
issues that inevitably undercut local policy.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects him to relinquish his Narragansett homestead or
hand out Thanksgiving turkeys. Sure, he has a banking empire to
run. But since he is supposedly running it out of this city, it
would be nice to see him play the role of Boston business leader on
issues that go beyond a bank's asset base.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
