<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW FAR WILL GAY CHARACTER GO ON THE WB?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Williamson talks rather proudly of the muted reaction to
his shrewdly introduced gay character on his shrewdly deceptive
drama ``Dawson's Creek,'' but the producer is bound to face the
same content constraints that made Doug Savant a sexless, pitiful
bore on ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Once that sweet-faced Jack (Kerr Smith) irons out the wrinkles
of his hormonal angst, isn't the exploration of sexual territory
next? After all, ``Dawson's Creek'' remains a sweaty, hormonal
playground. And that would be the true test of how much America has
changed and grown and become accepting of gay and lesbian
relationships, as Williamson suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Savant now, and he'll gladly share his lingering
disappointment over the 1994 scene in which his character, Matt,
was all set to lock lips with a handsome suitor, only to see the
camera go elsewhere when the Fox censors came down with a case of
wobbly knees.
</P>
<P>
   The same scenario played out later that season on ``Northern
Exposure,'' when Don McCanus (Erick) and Doug Ballard (Ron)
``married,'' only to have the camera pan away from their nuptial
smooch.
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed since then.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian characters in broadcast network series are said
to have graduated from rare exception, but to what _ comedic
novelty? Besides, take a close look at the 20 or so gay characters
(most played by straight actors) on weekly series. Few are on
dramas, fewer are sexual and none, if they're men, affectionately
embrace.
</P>
<P>
   What a tricky creative challenge for writers, this whole gay
thing. How clear that as the kiss-avoidance pattern suggests, TV is
still very wary of offending not so much the day-to-day viewer but
the noisy homophobes making up the often-powerful fringe groups
that keep advertisers' numbers on their speed dials.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard I've tried, I can't explain how ``Dawson's
Creek'' has managed to remain under the radar with this story line.
Is it because you could conduct a live execution on the
little-watched WB network without anyone noticing? Or is it that
today's teens really do see the world through a more accepting
lens?
</P>
<P>
   The only organized mass protest has come from Mike Gabbard,
president of Hawaii-based Stop Promoting Homosexuality
International, an interfaith organization preaching that gay
relationships are unnatural, abnormal and morally disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   Gabbard, a soft-spoken, smart, extraordinarily polite man who
led the charge against legislation legalizing gay marriages in
Hawaii, just happened to be in the ``Dawson's Creek'' stamping
grounds of Wilmington, N.C., when the story line was first
introduced. He challenged the teen audience to which he was
lecturing to ``do something'' proactive, and within days, the teens
were pacing outside the ``Dawson's Creek'' set with banners and
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read some newspaper accounts which said there has been no
protest, and that kind of amazes me,'' Gabbard says. ``We were
right there at the start. My only theory is that people write not
what's really there but what makes their point.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabbard won't say ``liberal conspiracy,'' but what most concerns
him is that Williamson, who is gay, and the WB, which loves
controversy and the ratings it may bring, plan to make Jack a
likable fellow. Next season, he'll be given enough athletic skills
to quarterback the football team. He'll certainly have enough
enemies to infuse his story lines with drama, but his character
will possess just enough charm to keep the audience returning.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Williamson is using the program to show
``positive'' aspects of homosexual life in much the same way the
producers are trying to level the playing field on the NBC comedy
``Will &AMP; Grace,'' in which there's both the strait-laced gay guy
and the animated queen.
</P>
<P>
   Gabbard thinks that's another series worthy of a cancellation
slip. ``It's almost as if they (networks) think being gay is a
selling point,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's Hollywood. Thing is, the mere fact that a character is
gay is no longer interesting in and of itself.
</P>
<P>
   That the media quickly questioned whether the furor over
``Ellen'' was a ploy to revitalize a dying comedy suggested that
we'd already absorbed the premise of having gay characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek'' has pushed the envelope in its mature subject
matter as it relates to high schoolers. It will be interesting to
see whether Williamson actually creates what would be a
multifaceted dramatic gay character, libido and all.
</P>
<P>
   Or will the WB be stricken with wobbly knees?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
