A5426 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     03-26 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY SEDAN NO LONGER HAS TO BE HUGE, SEDATE AND UGLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's just amazing what automakers can do with a sedan these
days.
</P>
<P>
   No more does a five-passenger car have to be a huge, sedate,
ugly family-hauler; thanks to Lexus and a few other automakers who
have decided that fun, performance and even excitement mix well
with a family car.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lexus introduced two exciting new sedans, the
six-cylinder GS 300 and the V-8 GS 400.
</P>
<P>
   The two cars are almost identical except for their drivetrains:
the GS 300, already powerful and decidedly fun to drive with its
3.0-liter inline-six engine with 225 horsepower; and our test car
for the week, the hot-rod 1999 GS 400, with a 4.0-liter, 32-valve,
300-horsepower V-8.
</P>
<P>
   Both have rear-wheel drive like traditional performance cars,
and are designed specifically to provide a pleasurable driving
experience, not just a comfy ride.
</P>
<P>
   If you have never driven the GS 400, you'd probably be perfectly
happy with the GS 300. But once you get a taste of the V-8 in the
GS 400, you won't want to go back to a V-6.
</P>
<P>
   The only automatic-transmission sedan I've driven that was
faster than the GS 400 was the 1999 Mercedes-Benz E55, a speedster
with a 350-horsepower engine, but a price tag that is $20,000
higher than that of the GS 400 that I tested.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexus is a better value, with a sticker price of $49,279
(including $495 transportation).
</P>
<P>
   Lexus, which burst onto the luxury-car scene in 1990 with the ES
250 and LS 400 sedans, has built such an impressive model lineup
during the past nine years that these cars have become the standard
by which other luxury cars are judged, even the Mercedes-Benzes and
BMWs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lexus has overtaken all others to become the
best-selling luxury brand in the United States so far this year
(through February), with help from such models as the GS 400 and
the brand's two sport-utilities, the RX 300 and LX 470. The
sport-utilities alone have accounted for 45 percent of Lexus sales
this year.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to buy a sedan for family or business purposes, and
you can afford to spend 50 grand, the GS 400 is worth a look. One
reason Lexus is so popular among baby boomers who buy luxury cars
is Toyota's commitment to quality and perfection in its upscale
brand.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexus slogan, ``The Relentless Pursuit of Perfection,'' is
part of a firmly ingrained corporate culture at Toyota; it's not
just a catchy phrase dreamed up by some advertising agency. One
merely has to touch any part of a Lexus, inside or out, and then
look closely at that part to see that nothing _ absolutely nothing
_ has been left to chance. There is careful thought behind every
square inch of a Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   One reason I like the GS 400 so much is that it has no
gratuitous trappings of luxury like so many other luxury autos
(particularly some of the U.S.-built models). Instead, it is a
practical, well-built car with modern amenities and an
extraordinary investment in the heart of the vehicle: its
drivetrain.
</P>
<P>
   The GS 400 is positioned in price between the entry-level ES 300
sedan and the prestige luxury LS 400 model, both of which have
their own strong selling points. What the GS 400 gives up in luxury
trappings found in the more expensive LS 400, it more than makes up
for in performance. I would trade some luxury for performance any
time.
</P>
<P>
   With the V-8 engine and this year's new five-speed automatic
transmission with manual-shift feature, the GS 400 can zip from
zero to 60 mph in less than six seconds. That might not be quite as
fast as the E55's 5.4-second zero-to-60 mph performance, but it's
still doggone fast for a practical family sedan that holds five
passengers and a truck that holds nearly 15 cubic feet of luggage.
</P>
<P>
   All of that power comes with some pretty nifty safety features
built into the GS 400, too, starting with side air bags for the
driver and front passenger. Included are the standard Vehicle Skid
Control or VSC system, an integration of the car's electronic
traction control and antilock braking system.
</P>
<P>
   The VSC uses a computer brain to compare the vehicle's turning
direction with the driver's steering, braking and throttle inputs
to think ahead and avoid letting the vehicle go into a skid. It
accomplishes this automatically and seamlessly by applying brakes
to the proper wheels and/or modulating the throttle as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Although the GS 400 might not look quite as luxurious as an LS
400, this still is one truly comfortable and well-laid-out vehicle.
The cabin is spacious enough for five full-size adults to sit in
comfort for a short drive around town or a trip across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The GS 400's $45,465 base price (not including shipping)
includes a whole list of standard amenities such as leather
interior with walnut trim, dual-zone automatic climate control,
power-adjustable front seats, power windows/mirrors/door locks,
tilt steering wheel, steering-wheel-mounted transmission shift
buttons, gas-pressurized shock absorbers, 215-watt AM/FM/cassette
audio system, a theft-deterrent system with engine immobilizer,
remote keyless entry and much more.
</P>
<P>
   Our test model came with Z-rated tires (a $215 option, designed
to handle speeds above 100 mph _ as if there were any place in the
United States where you could legally drive that fast), a $49 trunk
mat, and a $3,055 premium package that added an in-dash six-disc CD
changer, one-touch open/close moon roof, heated front seats and
high-intensity headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is impressive for a vehicle that is both practical
and really fast: 17 miles per gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Lexus GS 400 sedan
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Midsize, four-door, five-passenger, V-8 powered,
rear-drive, luxury-performance sedan.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW: For 1999, a new five-speed automatic transmission
offers optional manual shifting for more driver control, with shift
buttons on the steering-wheel spokes.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: With its 300-horsepower V-8, this is one of the
fastest sedans on the road. Combined with Lexus quality and luxury,
that power makes this an impressive driver's machine that also is a
practical family car.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: It's a bit pricey for most buyers.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Mercedes-Benz E430, BMW 540i, Cadillac
Seville STS, Infiniti Q45, Audi A8 4.2 Quattro.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 17 miles per gallon city, 24 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $45,465 plus $495 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $49,279, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
