<HEADER>
A5428 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     03-26 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVEL IS A TESTAMENT TO GRISHAM'S SPIRITUAL INTERESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene is deep in the jungles of Brazil. Rachel, a missionary
who refuses to accept a billion-dollar inheritance, is asking Nate,
a hardened, twice-divorced and alcoholic American lawyer, to pray
with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear God, forgive me of my sins, and help me to forgive those
who have sinned against me,'' Nate prays, repeating words given to
him by Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   Then Nate had ``an odd sensation as his burdens seemed to be
lifted; his shoulders felt lighter, his head clearer, his soul was
less troubled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your sins are forgiven, Nate,'' Rachel tells him.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a passage from the latest Christian novel? Not at all.
It comes from John Grisham's newest bestseller, ``The Testament.''
</P>
<P>
   Grisham has another gripping plot about a lawyer trying to track
down the missionary in Brazil to persuade her to accept her
inheritance. The story is his most unabashed effort yet to tell
about his own Christian faith in one of his legal thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, like his others, including ``A Time to Kill,'' ``The
Firm,'' and ``The Client,'' is being snapped up by readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Grisham's best novel in years,'' writes Deirdre Donahue
in USA Today. Malcolm Jones in Newsweek describes the book as ``a
compulsory page turner.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel has plenty of action _ storms, a plane crash, a
terminally ill billionaire leaping to his death from a building.
</P>
<P>
   But the spiritual emphasis is pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   During an almost fatal bout with dengue fever, Nate finds the
missionary mysteriously at his side, holding his hand and telling
him, ``I'm here, Nate. God sent me to protect you. ... You are not
going to die. ... God has plans for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The fever fades and Nate sleeps, dreaming of ``angels _
white-robed young maidens floating above the clouds above him,
humming hymns he'd never heard but that somehow seemed familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   One reader didn't like the God talk, though.
</P>
<P>
   He complained on the Barnes &AMP; Noble Web site that Grisham has
become ``a Bible-thumpin' preacher trying to save my ... and your
... poor, blackened soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering that view on the same Web site is a retired professor
of English, who referred to Grisham as ``John the Apostle.''
</P>
<P>
   He refers to one episode in the novel in which Nate, looking for
Rachel, walks into a small Brazilian church where he faces a mural
of Christ on the cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``He studied the crucifixion, the nails through His hands, the
sword in His side, the agony in His face. Did they really kill Him
in such a dreadful manner?'' Grisham writes.
</P>
<P>
   The English professor said the words epitomize what Holy Week is
all about. And he compares Grisham to American novelist Flannery
O'Connor, a Roman Catholic, in proclaiming redemptive Christian
orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the story, Nate's addiction to power, money and
booze has faded as he turns to God.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Grisham well aren't surprised by the religious
subject matter in ``The Testament.'' Write about what you know,
teachers of creative writing always advise.
</P>
<P>
   And Grisham knows about Brazil and missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   While a member of First Baptist Church in Oxford, Miss.,
Grisham, 44, went on several volunteer mission trips to Brazil. He
helped build churches.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham told USA Today that he liked the experience so much that
he plans to volunteer for more mission trips in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If he does, don't be surprised if you see more Grisham novels
telling intriguing tales about sin, faith and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707 or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
