<HEADLINE>
TREES MEAN ADVENTURE ON THESE SKI TRAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOWE, Vt. _ Tim Kelly stood on his skis, poised deep in the
snow-covered woods on the side of Mount Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love glade skiing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And then he took off, expertly following a straight downhill
line between trees, at a speed I could never hope to match.
</P>
<P>
   Out on Stowe Mountain Resort's many trails, the slopes were icy
and hard. But here in the trees, there was ample soft powder and no
people. And even though I often descend at a bumbling pace, I'd
still rather ski in here than out on the trails.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't mind the risk, glade or tree skiing is one
of the most exciting ways to schuss down a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, many resorts prohibited people from heading into
the trees, or at least frowned upon it. Not any more. In the past
five years, New England's best ski areas have been clearing small
trees and branches from wooded areas to encourage expert skiers to
head into the forests. Many glade areas are even marked on ski
maps.
</P>
<P>
   At Stowe, tree skiing always has been allowed. And, with a
70-year ski history, Stowe likely contains more gladed ski runs
than any other mountain on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, I hooked up with Kelly, a volunteer ski
patroller, for an afternoon of skiing. It would not be an easy
time: most of Stowe's tree routes were cut by local skiers, not by
the mountain. And be assured, they know how to ski. Steep, narrow
routes are the norm, so if you're like me and like to traverse the
slope when it gets too steep, you're going to find yourself
smashing through branches very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Most routes are not official trails. Most, in fact, were made by
locals who climb the slopes in the summer to carve their niche in
the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   For skiers just beginning to explore the woods, Stowe has a huge
area to the left of the trail ``Chinclip.'' Slightly easier is the
place called ``Tres Amigos,'' located off the black diamond trail
``Hayride.''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is accessed off the Perry Merrill trail, just below
the top of the gondola. A narrow trail leads into a thick forest of
spruce. After some spine-tingling switchbacks, the trail spits you
out on a narrow catwalk of snow below a 100-foot cliff covered in
icicles. You traverse below this incredible spot for what seems
like forever before you reach the end.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's time to dive downhill into more thick woods, following
dozens of lines that twist and curve at a pitch gentle enough for
any reasonable skier to follow without getting hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only the beginning. Kelly says Stowe has trails that
extend way beyond the ski-area boundaries. If you know what you're
doing and where you're going, you can hike to the bottom of a broad
escarpment called ``The Chin.'' From there, a number of lines head
down to the closed highway at the bottom of Smugglers' Notch _ and
a 20-minute walk back to the resort.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you can hike to the top of 4,395-foot Mount Mansfield and
ski down the other side. Such a journey can take several hours or
more. And it's a long way back to the parking lot once you finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals take pride in what they cut,'' Kelly said.
``There's a lot of secret stashes around the mountain. And if
someone skis them before the person who cut them, they can get
pretty upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The ice storm that rocked the Northeast last year ruined some of
the trails, but plenty remain, if you know where to look.
</P>
<P>
   It's essential, however, to keep in mind the risk. The ski
patrol does not monitor the glades. And once you're outside
ski-area boundaries, the resort has no obligation to search for
you, or rescue you if you get hurt (though rescue workers most
likely will come and get you if they know where you are).
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a group had to build a snowcave up on The Chin after
getting lost. A helicopter was needed to search for another lost
party.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Bono's skiing death last year illustrates another danger
of tree skiing. You have to know what you're doing, and be
constantly alert.
</P>
<P>
   I find skiing in the woods is generally safe as long as you
maintain a comfortable speed.
</P>
<P>
   There's little grace in glade skiing. You do what you can to ski
safely, and that means falling sometimes to avoid danger or blind
curves. Even Kelly takes a spill now and again.
</P>
<P>
   Stowe is by no means the only mountain with glade skiing.
Killington has several popular areas, including Big Dipper for the
experts and Echo Woods for the intermediate skiers. For beginners,
the easy glades off the Falls Brook Road trail are an excellent
introduction to skiing the trees. Many other glade areas are marked
``fusion zones'' on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Bromley and Mount Snow also have excellent glade areas, as
marked on the trail map. Sugarbush has taken it one step further,
opening a wooded section of the mountain between the south and
north sections of the resort called Slide Brook. When the snow is
deep enough, skiers who pay an extra $30 are taken by a guide from
the top of the mountain to the base, avoiding trails the entire
time. The tour takes several hours, and the skiers are met by a bus
that brings them back to the base lodge.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Gore Mountain is a latecomer to the glade game, but
has made up for that by creating some of the best glades for
intermediate skiers I've ever seen. I'm referring to the Twister
Glade, accessed off the trail by the same name.
</P>
<P>
   The route is wide enough that, on good powder days, you can be
making new tracks all day long. It takes you past cliffs and huge
boulders, going on and on until you wonder if you're still in the
same state. Finally, it drops you off right behind the Adirondack
Express chairlift entrance. You're exhausted, and hungry for more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
