<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-NASD-BROKERS-A     03-26 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-NASD-BROKERS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCLOSING A BROKER'S PAST CRIME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: La., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By GEANNE ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1971, a 17-year-old New Orleans high school student made the
mistake of his life. A young man he met asked to be introduced to a
drug dealer, and he complied. The acquaintance, who bought a single
orange mescaline pill, turned out to be a narcotics agent, and in
1973, the student, by then in college, was convicted of felony drug
possession in connection with the incident.
</P>
<P>
   His sentence of a year in prison was suspended, and his long
locks of hair were swept off the barbershop floor decades ago.
Today, still in Louisiana, he is a stockbroker agitated by the fear
that his criminal past will be posted on the Internet by the
national organization that registers and regulates securities
brokers _ NASD Regulation Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The broker has made his concern clear to the officer in his firm
who is responsible for adherence to regulations. ``I told my
compliance officer that if this is on the Internet, I'm going to
consider giving up my registration,'' said the broker, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage industry may be the only major profession in the
country that is planning to systematically disclose negative
information about its members on line. But the ease of Internet
access has prompted a debate within NASD Regulation _ a subsidiary
of the National Association of Securities Dealers _ over whether to
disclose all the information in its brokers' records or to omit
data on felonies committed more than 10 years ago and unrelated to
investing.
</P>
<P>
   The full records, including details of past felony convictions,
work-related disciplinary actions and unsubstantiated customer
complaints, have long been available by mail to anyone who requests
them. But many people familiar with the brokerage business contend
that because the Internet provides instantaneous and anonymous
global access, it constitutes a far more powerful vehicle for
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   NASD regulators are committed to the general principle of
Internet disclosure. But as they try to reconcile investors' rights
to information with brokers' rights to privacy, they are deadlocked
on the specific question of whether to disclose old felonies not
related to investing.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 600,000 registered brokers nationwide, and
scant few of them have felony records, according to NASD
Regulation. However, when NASD Regulation announced its intention
to place broker disclosure information on the Internet, that group
became an extremely vocal minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say they were concerned is putting it mildly,'' said Clark
Hooper, executive vice president at NASD Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Since the organization put out its request for comments, it has
received scores of e-mail messages, phone calls and letters. Many
have been protests about the proposed felony disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD has what is called ``statutory immunity'' under
securities law, a status that allows it to publish negative
information about brokers with protection against liability. But
because the relevant provision in the Securities Exchange Act of
1934 makes no reference to the Internet, the NASD and the
Securities and Exchange Commission are working to amend the law,
specifically extending that immunity to on-line disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always indicated that we felt disclosure was the way to
go here, and we're working with Congress and the NASD to resolve
the issues involved,'' said an SEC spokesman, John D. Heine,
adding, ``the sooner the better.''
</P>
<P>
   But others question whether the raw power of the Internet as a
communications tool may change the nature of the disclosures
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody releasing information on the Internet needs to think
not only in terms of the specific use in question, but other ways
it can be used that are totally unrelated,'' said Sheldon Krantz,
chairman of the American Bar Association's task force on law
enforcement and new technology and a partner at Piper &AMP; Marbury in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana broker said he was concerned that Internet
disclosure would harm not only his business reputation, but also
his standing in his church and his community.
</P>
<P>
   From where Ira Lee Sorkin sits, NASD disclosure already goes too
far, even without the Internet. ``It's a terrible, terrible
system,'' said Sorkin, a former federal prosecutor and SEC official
who is now a partner at Squadron Ellenoff Plesent &AMP; Sheinfeld, a
law firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He sees publishing old felonies unrelated to the investment
business as unjustified, but he expressed greater concern about the
publication of unsubstantiated complaints about brokers. Such
complaints remain in public disclosure records for two years, even
if a broker is found by an adjudicator to have done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a bare allegation out there because a disgruntled
customer is blaming the broker can cause irreversible damage to a
broker even if it is determined after a hearing that he did nothing
improper,'' Sorkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD requested public comment about felony disclosures last
fall and has yet to adopt a policy. ``It's been an absolute split
down the middle,'' Ms. Hooper said. ``There's been no clear-cut
mandate over what should be done.'' But the emotional maelstrom
whirling around the issue is reflected in many of the 97 written
comments the agency has received from consumer advocates,
investors, regulatory agencies, brokerage firms, brokers and
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The AARP, formerly the American Association of Retired People,
has advocated full disclosure, stating in its public comment letter
last September that ``it must be an investor's decision'' to
determine whether a felony conviction is relevant. The AARP
provided the example of ``an investor who had been a victim of
domestic violence'' and who might want to know if a broker had been
convicted of a similar crime and take the business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is it should be up to the investor,'' said Laura
Polacheck, a policy analyst at the AARP. ``If the investor sees
they had some conviction that occurred decades ago that doesn't
seem to compromise their integrity, that's up to the investor to
make that determination. We are putting trust in the investor to
make his or her decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana broker, hoping to clear his name once and for all,
hired a lawyer who successfully argued to have the old felony
expunged from his court records. Now he waits for the information
to make its way to the NASD, so that his record there will be
cleared of the felony soon enough to avoid Internet posting.
</P>
<P>
   For him, the fear of humiliation that might result from Internet
publication of his past felony is almost tangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a guy walking around with a marble in his pocket,''
he said. ``You feel it. It's sometimes uncomfortable when you sit
but no one else can see it. Now it's a baseball in your pocket;
people can see it. It really takes the person down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
