<HEADER>
A5443 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LIMITS-HNS &LR;      03-26 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LIMITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR POWER IN YUGOSLAVIA HAS LIMITATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As NATO warplanes continue to pound Yugoslavia,
U.S. strategists say past military operations show that aerial
assaults alone won't compel an adversary to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the recent conflict in Bosnia, the Persian Gulf War,
Vietnam and World War II, these experts say that without a
coordinated campaign involving ground troops, victory often remains
elusive or at least inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the nation's most respected military experts,
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., says the level of force required to
drive Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic, into accepting a
peace agreement has become so great ``that no one is entirely
confident that Serbia can be coerced by the use of air power
alone.'' McCain is a member of the Senate Armed Service Committee
and a former fighter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Col. James Hunt, an instructor at the National War
College in Washington D.C., notes that the public's distaste for
casualties has forced U.S. leaders to rely on air strikes in
Kosovo, Serbia's rebellious southern province.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, air power used in conjunction with land
power is the way to go,'' says Hunt, who teaches a course on air
power in modern war to military officers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-led NATO force is trying to use bombs and missiles
alone to compel Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to pull back
his troops from Kosovo, grant self-rule to its ethnic Albanian
citizens and accept 28,000 NATO ground troops as peacekeepers.
Milosevic, whose troops have been pummeling the Kosovar Albanians
for a year _ killing civilians, burning villages and dispersing
hundreds of thousands of refugees _ has refused.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pape, a Dartmouth College professor of national security
studies, makes this argument for the use of ground troops:
</P>
<P>
   ``History tells us that air power alone never has won a major
war. There isn't a single case. ... We will need a ground force and
could do this by arming the Kosovo Liberation Army,'' the
province's guerrilla fighters. Pape is the author of ``Bombing To
Win: Airpower and Coercion in War.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Navy Adm. Leighton Smith, who commanded NATO air attacks
against Bosnian Serbs in 1995, agrees. ``People should not delude
themselves into thinking that this thing in Kosovo is going to go
away with the application of air power,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that NATO launched its air attacks to force the
Bosnian Serbs, who were supported by Milosevic, to sign a peace
treaty with other warring factions. The attacks destroyed key
Bosnian Serb targets, but it wasn't until the Croatians had mounted
a sweeping ground offensive that the Bosnian Serbs agreed to the
settlement, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kosovo might be different, according to Joseph Collins, a
retired Army colonel and former special assistant to the Joint
Chiefs of Staff. Collins notes that in the Kosovo conflict NATO is
using more radar-evading stealth aircraft and more satellite-guided
``smart weapons'' that can hit their targets with precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll probably revoke my Army union card for saying this,
but my take is that (such) air power, used in great quantities, is
in fact useful for coercion,'' insists Collins.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed this week by retired Air Force Lt.
Gen. Buster Glosson, the architect of the 1991 Gulf War's air
assault against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only question is: Do we have the political will and
patience to let that campaign continue long enough to accomplish
that knockout blow,'' Glosson said. ``If we do, we will not see
American men and women fighting a ground war in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over whether air power alone can coerce a foe is a
key issue now because of President Clinton's promise this week not
to dispatch ground troops to fight Yugoslav forces. Clinton said he
would send U.S. troops only to act as peacekeepers once a treaty is
signed between Milosevic and the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Clinton's strategy insist that air power had its
limits in the Gulf War, in which the United States and its allies
pounded Iraqi positions from the skies for 43 days.
</P>
<P>
   While the massive attacks destroyed equipment and killed enemy
troops, Iraq relinquished its grip on Kuwait only when thousands of
allied troops swept through the region.
</P>
<P>
   A House Armed Services Committee report after the war said,
``The air campaign did not force Saddam (Hussein) to withdraw, and
despite its military effectiveness, did not lead to his overthrow.
Consequently, valid questions remain about the limits of air power
to achieve largely political goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's official report to Congress on the Gulf War
concluded that ``air power alone could not have brought the war to
so sharp and decisive a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   It added, ``Without the credible threat of ground and amphibious
attacks, the Iraqi defenders might have dispersed, dug in more
deeply, concentrated in civilian areas or otherwise adopted a
strategy of outlasting the bombing from the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam War also shows that years of strategic bombing
against Vietcong targets failed to assure victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``American civilian and military leaders entered Vietnam
convinced that bombing's lethality assured political results,''
wrote Air Force scholar Mark Clodfelter in ``The Limits of Air
Power.''
</P>
<P>
   What they learned was that ``air power is unlikely to provide
... `victory' in a guerrilla war,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the U.S. military after World War II said allied
bombing of German targets succeeded in terrorizing Nazi officials.
But it noted that the attacks by 12,000 B-17s and more than 10,000
RAF bombers were not accurate enough to destroy Germany's
production capability or the morale of its citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1610EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-ART-$     03-26 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRENGTH IN DIVERSITY, AND IN UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 By PAUL SWEENEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not unusual for businesspeople with a common background to
join together to promote economic development and entrepreneurship
in their community, forming groups like the Asian American Business
Development Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now these groups are finding that they can magnify their
effectiveness by banding together into minority-group coalitions, a
move encouraged by the Minority Business Development Agency of the
Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Courtland Cox, the director of the agency, was in New York last
week for the release of a research report by the Asian center. The
report calls for greater economic collaboration among Asian,
Hispanic, African-American and other minority groups, who together
command $1.1 trillion in consumer purchasing power, according to
John Wang, the center's president.
</P>
<P>
   Cox discussed the report's findings and the challenges of
minority business development. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you see small-business development and entrepreneurship as
the best route out of poverty? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. The real issues minorities face are economic rather than
social. People try to deal with illegitimacy and crime and drug
addiction, but these are the effects, not the root causes, of
problems. It is important to develop a business and economic
infrastructure that can deal with the real issues of jobs, economic
development and the creation of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   When I look at a map of where murders take place in Washington,
basically it is east of 16th Street Northwest, where there is more
poverty and higher unemployment. There are almost no murders west
of 16th Street, where the wealth is. Where you have access to
opportunity, you have less crime.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a minority businessperson, it's an exciting time,
because you're in a dynamic growth area. The United States
population is expected to grow by 120 million people over the next
50 years, and 90 percent of that growth will be in the minority
community. If you look at where the markets for the future are,
it's clear that's where they will be. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does minority entrepreneurship translate directly into more
jobs for minority workers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, the numbers will show you that. Recently I went up to
Detroit to see Bing Manufacturing. Dave Bing, the former basketball
player, has an automotive assembly operation that included 15
percent of employees who were ex-offenders, predominantly nonwhite.
Detroit also has Mexican Industries, a $300 million company that
has hired about 2,000 people, most of them Hispanic, who make parts
and do assembly work for GM, Ford Motor and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   These are private-sector initiatives. A lot of big companies
realize that markets change and they have to include minorities,
not because it's nice or legal, but so that they can sell into the
market. IBM just created its first minority distributorship. These
guys aren't stupid. They want to be where markets are. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Researchers say lack of access to financing is a roadblock to
minority business creation, and the administration has responded
this year by proposing tax credits and government loan programs for
struggling inner-city areas. What should the private sector be
doing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We need a mechanism for banks and other financial
institutions to sell off their loans to minority enterprises,
instead of waiting for them to mature before they can lend more
money. This was an important finding of the task force. There is
now much more mortgage money because banks are selling off
mortgages and securitizing them. We need to apply the same
principle to business loans. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your agency is encouraging coalitions among different
minority groups, like the Minority Business Coordinating Council in
Washington. How far has this cooperation advanced? Will it be
hampered by past tensions between some groups? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a new concept, and it's just in the discussion
stages. We still have a ghetto mentality, where people fight over
crumbs. Many people still think the world is their block and don't
see the possibilities in the larger world. But I don't think groups
will be that far apart once they understand the opportunities that
exist. People are crossing all sorts of ethnic and national
boundaries, and business is more important than ethnic prejudices. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you agree with John Wang that in a global economy,
American entrepreneurs of Asian or Hispanic background may have an
advantage in dealing internationally? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. America has the diverse population to position itself
internationally. I have people in my office who have the feel for
different countries. In an international economy, we need people
who understand different languages and different cultures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
