 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, March 28, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARLEM-RENAISSANCE-II (New York) _ Those who live in the 50 or
so blocks above Central Park like to term what's happening in the
area today Harlem's Second Renaissance, with the return of black
professionals, new businesses, increased tourism and a rebirth of
night life. While the term may be strained, it is not far from the
truth. Economic development, historical preservation and plummeting
crime rates in the area have contributed to a kind of boom. By Nina
Siegel. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AERIN-LAUDER-PROFILE (New York) _ Ms. Aerin Lauder, 28, is that
rarest of Park Avenue princesses: a hyperactive member of junior
society by night, and by day, a working woman who is being groomed
for the executive suite of one of the country's largest companies:
Estee Lauder. By Ruth La Ferla. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STYLISH-AIR-TRAVEL (Undated) _ There is no greater indignity
than commercial air travel. Multi-hour delays are imposed without
apology or extra peanuts. Flight attendants have all the charm of
hall monitors. The term ``jet set'' now means a matching sweat-suit
ensemble. The plummeting dress code on your average 737 may sound
like a superficial gripe in the larger context of crippling pilot
strikes and $4 headsets. But I would argue that the relentless
unstylishness of the in-flight experience is the problem, from
barefoot passengers to the cabin crew's Salvation Army-drab
uniforms to the goats and chickens roaming around the back of the
plane. By Rick Marin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLERGY-WOMEN-FASHION (New York) _ Women who are spiritual
leaders, one might imagine, would be too preoccupied with crises of
faith to concern themselves with crises of fashion. But many of
those who are rabbis and ministers are careful not to overlook
matters like nail polish, hem lengths, heel heights and hair color.
By Elizabeth Hayt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Although cherry tomatoes existed in
Europe as long ago as 1623, they have always been relatively
unimportant, grown mostly for curiosity or for pickles and
preserves. Nowadays, most of the crop turns up in salad bars, and
then because they do not need slicing. By Lee Reich. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
