<HEADLINE>
YOU SHOULD SERVE THEM TO YOUR GUEST, FOR EASTER AT ITS BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I do not like them Sam-I-am
</P>
<P>
   I do not like spring eggs and ham.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would you like them in a house? Would you like them with a
spouse? Would you like them with some grits? Would you like them
just a bit?
</P>
<P>
   I would not like them in a house
</P>
<P>
   I would not like them with a spouse
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would you like them in some toast? Would you like them from your
host?
</P>
<P>
   Would you like them with some sauce?
</P>
<P>
   Would you like them with a toss?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would you like them with some cheese?
</P>
<P>
   Would you like them as you please?
</P>
<P>
   Sam!
</P>
<P>
   If you will let me be,
</P>
<P>
   I will try them.
</P>
<P>
   You will see.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Say!
</P>
<P>
   I like spring eggs and ham!
</P>
<P>
   I do! I like them, Sam-I-am!
</P>
<P>
   So I will eat them in some toast.
</P>
<P>
   And I will eat them from my host.
</P>
<P>
   And I would eat them with some cheese.
</P>
<P>
   And I would eat them as I please.
</P>
<P>
   I do so like spring eggs and ham!
</P>
<P>
   Thank you! Thank you! Sam-I-am!
</P>
<P>
   _ With apologies to Dr. Seuss
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   POACHED EGGS AND FRIED TOMATOES WITH CREAMY HAM SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarse yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound well-trimmed firm, smoky ham, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh thyme, plus thyme sprigs for garnish,
optional
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large, firm ripe tomatoes, cut into 8 thick slices
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   8 eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 thick English muffins, split and lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   On a plate, stir together cornmeal and 1/2 teaspoon of the
pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In small, heavy saucepan over medium heat, combine cream, ham
and minced thyme. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and simmer
uncovered, stirring once or twice, until reduced to 1 cup, about 20
minutes. Remove from heat and stir in lemon juice and remaining 1/2
teaspoon pepper. Cover and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   In large skillet over medium heat, melt butter. Dredge tomatoes
in prepared cornmeal and fry in the skillet, turning once, until
lightly browned and crisp, about 4 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to a deep skillet, add water to a depth of 2 inches.
Set over medium heat and bring just to a simmer. Stir in salt. One
at a time, break eggs into small dish and then slide them into
water. Adjust heat to keep water from exceeding a simmer and cook
the eggs, gently shaping them into ovals with a spoon, to the
desired doneness, about 3 minutes for medium-firm.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange 2 muffin halves on each of 4 plates. Top each half with
1 fried tomato slice. With slotted spoon, remove eggs from water,
blot briefly on paper towels and set an egg atop each tomato slice.
Spoon cream sauce over and around eggs and muffins, garnish each
serving with a sprig of thyme if desired and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Good Mornings'' by Michael McLaughlin (Chronicle, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HONEYED FRENCH TOAST SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lowfat milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   4 slices firm-textured white or egg bread
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon safflower oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 ounces of thinly sliced ham
</P>
<P>
   Maple syrup, optional
</P>
<P>
   In shallow dish, whisk together eggs, milk, honey, flour and
baking powder. Press each piece of bread into mixture and allow to
soak for several minutes. Using a spatula, turn and allow other
side to soak.
</P>
<P>
   In 12-inch skillet over medium-high heat, heat oil and butter.
Using a spatula, lift bread from batter into pan and brown on both
sides. Spread mustard on all the bread slices, top 2 of them with
ham and top with remaining toast. Serve hot, with maple syrup, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Breakfast All Day'' by Edon Waycott (Hearst, $22)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HAM AND EGGS DIDGERIDOO
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups diced cooked ham
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   8 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped chives or fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   In medium-size frying pan, brown ham lightly in butter.
</P>
<P>
   Mix remaining ingredients with a fork. Pour over ham and cook
over medium heat. As eggs begin to set, gently lift cooked portions
so thin uncooked portion can flow to the bottom of the frying pan.
Cook until eggs are thickened throughout but still moist. Serve
with sliced ripe tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Complete Book of Egg Cookery'' by Ann Seranne
(Macmillan, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HAM AND GRITS LOAF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup quick-cooking grits
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh bread crumbs (2 slices bread)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound cooked ham, ground
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   In heavy 2-quart saucepan, heat 1 1/2 cups water to boiling over
high heat. In a small bowl, combine grits, salt and remaining 1/2
cup water. Stir grits mixture into boiling water. Cook, stirring
constantly, until mixture is thickened and bubbly, about 5 minutes.
Cover and cook over low heat 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. In medium-size bowl, combine milk,
egg, ketchup and pepper. Stir in bread crumbs and let stand 5
minutes. Stir ham, beef, onion and parsley into bread-crumb
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Generously grease a loaf pan. Spoon half the ham mixture into
pan. Top with half the grits mixture, the remaining ham and the
remaining grits.
</P>
<P>
   Bake loaf 50-55 minutes or until center feels firm when gently
touched. Let loaf cool 5 minutes on wire rack, then remove it from
pan. Carefully cut into slices and serve.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Country Living Country Morning Cookbook'' (Hearst, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TWICE-BAKED HAM POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 baking potatoes, scrubbed and patted dry
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cooked ham, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Coat potatoes with nonstick cooking spray and bake in preheated
400-degree oven for 1 hour or until tender. Remove and cool
slightly. Cut each potato in half and gently remove pulp, reserving
shell. In large bowl, mash potatoe pulp with eggs, cheese, milk,
mustard and half of the parsley. Add chopped ham and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   In small skillet, saute onion and garlic in butter for 3
minutes. Add to potato mixture. Divide mixture back into potato
skins and place each half on a baking sheet. Rebake potatoes in
preheated 350-degree oven for 30 minutes until bubbly. Garnish with
remaining parsley.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Honeybaked Ham Co.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
