<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DRUG-TEST TIGHTROPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ariz.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My company is instituting random drug testing, and my fellow
managers and I are trying to decide how strict to be. For safety
reasons, we figure that a factory worker who tests positive should
be severely penalized or dismissed, but that such punishment seems
extreme for secretaries and midlevel managers. How can we be both
fair and effective? And what is the best way to present the new
rules to employees? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you don't know your state's laws on this subject, find
out. Random testing is often perceived as being more invasive and
offensive than other kinds, said Jonathan Segal, a partner in the
employment department of Wolf, Block, Schorr &AMP; Solis-Cohen, a
Philadelphia law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, some states by statute restrict random testing
only to safety-sensitive positions,'' Segal said, ``while others
restrict it by case law.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even if there are no legal restrictions, your
employees may not be thrilled _ and may think that you are morphing
into Big Brother. To avoid a revolt, experts say, sell the policy
as a way to protect employees' safety and financial interests as
well as the company's.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Johnson, a spokesman for SmithKline Beecham Clinical
Laboratories, which is one of the nation's largest providers of
workplace drug tests, suggests talking about how drug use raises a
company's insurance rates, harms productivity and increases
workplace accidents.
</P>
<P>
   To alleviate concerns about possible abuses, invite employees to
ask questions about who will conduct the test and how _ and who
will have access to results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assure them that it really will be random,'' Segal said,
noting that some workers think supervisors use such policies to
retaliate against underlings they don't like. ``Make it clear that
the goal isn't to `get' people.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Segal said, ``often some companies will defer testing
for 60 or 90 days and tell people, `In the interim, if you think
you have a problem, seek help.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Consistency is the key in enforcement. ``Spell out the
repercussions for anyone using drugs,'' said Susan Jones, director
of Drugs Don't Work in Arizona, a nonprofit organization in Phoenix
that helps area businesses establish antidrug programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although you may not be legally obligated to take identical
disciplinary action against offenders from different divisions,
Segal said, separate rules for manufacturing or engineering on the
one hand and for management or support staff on the other could
undermine employees' faith in the policy. ``You would create a
double standard that could become a morale issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies suspend all first-time offenders automatically.
Then they are required to undergo an assessment by a
substance-abuse specialist and to abide by the specialist's
recommendations as a condition of returning to work. That allows
both a uniform policy and a diversity of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And regardless of whether an employee is a marketing executive
or a truck driver, if he tests positive a second time, you may
decide it's best to send him packing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, NY
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
