<HEADLINE>
THE TIME-KILLING 1040 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mo.)   (af)  
 By JAMES SCHEMBARA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is any time of year that most of us would love to skip,
this is it. Taxes are due in less than three weeks, and only two
weekends remain for us to lock ourselves away and get the chore
done. The pressure is on.
</P>
<P>
   Although the amount of taxes we pay is cause for much debate,
the time required to prepare the forms can be just as vexatious. Of
the estimated 126.2 million individual tax returns that will be
filed this year, almost half will be completed by taxpayers
themselves, not accountants. And even those who use professional
help must spend many hours compiling their records.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it is a big job. And the burden falls hardest on
baby boomers. According to the Tax Foundation, a research
organization in Washington, boomers will pay 70 percent of the
$877.4 billion tax bill for individuals this year.
</P>
<P>
   And, because their finances tend to be complex, the foundation
estimates that they will spend about a third more time preparing
Form 1040 and its many schedules than the average American _ 40
hours instead of 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are at the peak of their earnings and have children and
houses,'' said Patrick Fleenor, a foundation economist. ``Younger
and older people tend to have much simpler filings.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises questions beyond whether the tax system is fair.
Considering that boomers, now into middle age, are at the height of
their earning power, creativity and productivity, there must be a
social cost in forcing them to spend millions of hours a year at
their kitchen tables trying to maneuver through the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity cost of the time they're spending is very
large,'' said James M. Buchanan of George Mason University, winner
of the 1987 Nobel Prize in economics. ``It's a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleenor called it ``brilliance lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the whole reason tax reform proposals have weight,''
he said. ``Tax preparation doesn't add anything to society's worth.
Nothing positive is coming out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no way to measure what could have been;
would boomers really use the extra time more productively, or would
we just lie around listening to old Beatles albums? But we can
measure the opportunity noted by Buchanan. The Tax Foundation
estimates that the time Americans spend doing their taxes robs the
economy of $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A taxpayer in Malibu, Calif., who requested anonymity, said he
spent about 90 hours on his taxes. Throughout the year, he said, he
is meticulous about record-keeping because he runs a business out
of his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have several careers,'' he said. ``One of them is doing my
taxes. It's a tremendous waste of my time. I should be spending it
with my family or out making more money.''
</P>
<P>
   David P. Mulford, a computer programmer and musician in St.
Louis, said he usually puts off doing his taxes until April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread doing them more than I do paying'' the taxes owed, he
said. ``It's such a headache. When I get home from work, I don't
want to spend three or four hours doing my taxes. I want to visit
with friends or work on my music.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he was a recent convert to proposals for a
simple-to-calculate flat tax, with no deductions. Others critics of
the current system are calling for a national sales tax. And the
other day a friend jokingly suggested requiring high-school juniors
to fill out the nation's tax returns, giving the youngsters the
chance to make their math skills relevant while freeing up time for
their elders.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that everyone has an idea for cleaning up the tax mess,
but as Fleenor observed, the history of the tax-overhaul movement
is not reassuring. Within years of any move to simplify the
process, he said, Congress bows to special interests and
complicates it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are just playing around with the tax code, trying
to find ways to avoid paying taxes, they are not engaged in
creating wealth,'' he said. ``People's time could be much better
spent inventing the better mousetrap.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the better tax system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
