<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-NISSAN-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH FOR NISSAN; COUTURE, TOO? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Tenn., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM DIEM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Nissan can certainly use Renault's help to straighten
out its bleak and tangled finances. But it could also stand a nudge
at the drawing board, some auto industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan products are ``obsolete, out of date,'' said Gregoire Van
de Velde, an automotive consultant in Detroit. ``The styling is
much too conservative worldwide.'' Van de Velde, president of
Automotive Strategy, added, ``Renault has the capacity to bring
Nissan what it is missing.'' He spoke as Renault, of France, was
preparing to sign an agreement to buy 35 percent of Nissan, Japan's
No. 2 auto maker, after Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   For almost 20 years, Nissan's strategy was to match Toyota
product for product but to do a better job of execution. It ended
up with the most efficient factories in Europe, at Sunderland,
England, and in the United States, at Smyrna, Tenn. _ along with a
series of me-too cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The symptom is that Nissan doesn't make money,'' said Nigel
Griffith, an analyst for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in London. ``The
cause is that Nissan doesn't have a strong brand image.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's often-bland cars aim to please everyone, so ``any
consumer, in any part of the car market, is going to have another
proposition that's closer to the unique features that he's looking
for,'' Griffith added.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Renault's designs are widely admired, even
though the company no longer sells cars in North America. ``Renault
seems to have taken over the role of design innovation which used
to belong to Citroen,'' said David Browne, manager of the
transportation design program at Coventry University in England.
``Citroen, in its glory days, finished up with products that people
both loved and feared.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That has also been Renault's secret. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to please some people,'' Patrick Le Quement, Renault's
vice president for design and quality, said last month at the
introduction of the striking Avantime concept car. ``Our aim is
(italics) not (end italics) to not displease people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Le Quement sent teams of designers to London,
Barcelona and Milan to observe people and trends. Then the staff
tried to envision what people will need in a few years, and create
it for them if it doesn't yet exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a history of being good at coming up with trend
setters,'' Le Quement said. Renault established new segments with
the European minivan (Espace, 1984), microcar (Twingo, 1992),
compact minivan (Scenic, 1996) and small passenger van (Kangoo,
1997). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands, a spokesman for Nissan Europe, Clyde
Moerlie, defended Nissan's talents. ``We don't agree that our cars
are boring,'' he said. ``The Micra is the only Japanese car to ever
win European Car of the Year, in 1993. The face lift last year had
record sales.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1970-75 Datsun 240Z was the first Japanese sports car to win
a big following, and the Nissan Pathfinder of 1986 was ahead of the
sport utility craze. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nissan was there at the right time, but they didn't follow
through,'' said Philippe Houchois, another Standard and Poor's DRI
analyst in London. He said he thought that Renault's money was more
important than its creativity. ``Nissan themselves, they know what
to do,'' he said. ``They've identified the problems.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in showing off more innovative designs in recent months,
the president of Nissan Design International in San Diego, Jerry
Hirshberg, has said that ``there's nothing like a good jolt of fear
to release the creative juices.'' A clever city car design from
Nissan Design Europe, the Kyxx _ pronounced kicks _ was a highlight
of the Paris auto show in October. In Japan, the compact Cube
wagon-minivan has sold well.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Renault and Nissan may be more in the
execution than in the intention. Some of Renault's design strength,
said Browne of Coventry University, derives from the fact that Le
Quement is a senior executive, and thus ``at the highest levels, he
argues for the importance of innovative design and creative
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   At Nissan, on the other hand, American managers routinely talk
about innovative proposals delayed in Japan, or bold strokes
reduced to staid designs. As a result, the company did not keep up
with American tastes; it is only now bringing out a small sport
utility, the Xterra, years behind Toyota and Honda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
