<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-RANGE WARFARE IS GOOD; LONG-RANGE PLANS ARE BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What a world, what a world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ the Wicked Witch of the West, ``The Wizard of Oz''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   What a world, indeed, and here the United States sits, depending
on an administration that couldn't buy the right vowel to complete
``-xit strat-gy'' even if you spot it the other letters.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is finally bombing the Serbs, trying to force Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to stop the slaughter in Kosovo and to
play nice in a region that has suffered from sporadic ethnic-based
conflicts for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong; I thought President Clinton should have
given the green light last month when the initial deadline passed
while parties on both sides of the battle were vamping for time in
Rambuillet, France. The only thing different between then and
Wednesday afternoon, when the first alliance munitions finally hit
Yugoslav dirt, was the number of ethnic Albanians whom Milosevic
had killed or made into refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But then, as now, I'd have felt a whole lot better about
airstrikes over the Ottoman if the United States and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization had some kind of plan for what happens
if, heaven forbid, the Butcher of Belgrade doesn't back down.
</P>
<P>
   The reason why stability in that region of the world is
important to the United States is a no-brainer _ one look at a map
should be enough to convince even the most ardent isolationist that
it is not in this country's best interest to allow ethnic warfare
to spill beyond Serbia's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Add in our obligations to our 18 NATO allies, some of whom are
nervously watching from close proximity as thousands of refugees
urgently seek a new place to call home, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to know that although the United States is
rushing to the aid of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the underarmed
and undermanned underdog in this conflict, its members aren't
exactly choirboys.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of sordid past and unsavory tactics to go around.
But the leaders of the KLA ultimately accepted a peace agreement
even though it didn't give them the independence they so
desperately want _ a sign that they were willing to consider a
diplomatic solution over continued aggression. Milosevic just dug
in his heels, refusing to accept the provision that would require
NATO troops in his country to enforce the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the original question: What happens
next? So NATO lays down two or three weeks of intensive airstrikes
on Belgrade and Pristina, and Milosevic continues his assault on
Kosovo. In fact, the bombing just ticks him off even more, and he
intensifies his bloody campaign to annihilate the ethnic Albanians.
What's the plan then, Mr. President?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, supreme commander of NATO forces,
said yesterday that ``the operation will be just as long and
difficult as President Milosevic requires it to be.'' Possible
translation: ground troops needed to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the risks of bombing campaigns for the personnel flying
the missions are very real, airstrikes are low-risk military
maneuvers in the minds of the American people. Shoot, we've been
throwing armament at Iraqi targets since December, and the
near-daily exchanges over the no-fly zones barely make news briefs
anymore. Technology has made air combat impersonal _ at least until
the first fresh-faced kid from Kansas comes home in a box. Then
watch Americans take things extremely personally.
</P>
<P>
   Air campaigns historically have not been successful in closing
the deal. Without question, the bombing sorties flown over Iraq
during Operation Desert Storm made a huge impression on Saddam
Hussein _ actually, they made a bigger impression on the Iraqi
Republican Guard as it was being turned to glass _ but it took
troops on the ground to achieve the definitive push out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton keeps saying that he does not intend to put U.S. troops
in Kosovo to fight a war, even when his top military gurus are
making noise otherwise. But then, this wouldn't be the first time
that Clinton's lips did one thing and his actions were something
quite different.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's army is trained and equipped beyond Saddam's wildest
dreams. Don't expect to see photographs of Serbian military men
waving white flags and surrendering in the numbers that the world
witnessed in Iraq. This won't be a lay-down.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has moral, economic, allied and security
reasons for taking action in Yugoslavia. But it would have been
nice, just once, if Clinton had a long-range plan going into this
war instead of doing his typical
``let's-just-wait-to-see-what-happens'' routine.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
