<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORSE-RACING-HNS &LR;      03-26 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-RACING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACETRACK ON THE BAY SEEKS TO REVIVE ITS FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed on the ``f,'' financial, and ``s,'' sports, wires)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Calif. _ We're certainly living in a world different
from that of 1947, when 30,000 or more people would show up at
Golden Gate Fields for a day of racing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some things of value endure through the years: the
cluster of beautiful horses in the paddock, the jockeys in bright
silks, the thrill of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Such images, along with others showing jockeys at familiar San
Francisco settings, are jammed into a 30-second prime-time
television commercial to be shown Tuesday through Friday on network
stations in the San Francisco area. It's a major advertising
investment of more than $1 million for the track that has been
losing customers.
</P>
<P>
   Average daily attendance over approximately 100 days of racing
is not much more than 3,000 now, for a host of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them is the 1985 introduction of off-track betting
in California, making a trip to Albany, on the east side of the San
Francisco Bay, unnecessary. Other reasons include heady competition
for entertainment and gambling dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get the message out that it's affordable; it's fun;
it's safe, clean and exciting. It's traditional,'' said Doug
Nelson, vice president of MGO Marketing Group of Lafayette, serving
as consultants to Golden Gate Fields as it prepares for its season
opener on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And customers have a vested interest in the outcome if they have
placed a bet, said Jill Borden, Golden Gate Fields' director of
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, average daily attendance at the track along the San
Francisco Bay has fallen 40 percent in the past decade. The TV
spot, along with a print ad campaign and a 60-second radio
commercial _ all clearly aimed at people who have a lot of
disposable income and an interest in the swing era _ aim to reverse
that trend.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, there's no reference to gambling in the ads
created by a Newport Beach-based production company, Lyon Studios,
although winning is everything for many people who go to the races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I like to play that down, but for me the thrill
of it all is the racetrack experience,'' said agency owner Curt
Lyon, who also creates advertising for Santa Anita in Arcadia, a
track that can actually claim it has staunched the drain of
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Its attendance went up 1 percent in 1998 after 12 consecutive
years of decline, said Craig Dado, the track's vice president for
marketing. Of course, Santa Anita also invested heavily in
marketing programs in part to identify its customers and people
like them: They're men over 35 with money in their pockets and time
on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track will probably not appeal to you without those
elements,'' Dado said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985, when off-track or satellite betting was introduced in
California, to 1987, there were only two facilities in Northern
California housing the necessary equipment _ Golden Gate Fields and
Bay Meadows in San Mateo. In 1987, though, other off-track sites
opened, and Golden Gate Fields' average daily attendance plummeted
from 12,773 in 1987 to 6,890 the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shows you the need to do something,'' said Sam Spear, the
veteran media relations director at Golden Gate Fields.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are satellite betting facilities, open 108 days a
year, at Anderson, Bakersfield, Bay Meadows, Eureka, Fresno,
Monterey, Pleasanton, Sacramento, San Jose, Santa Rosa, Stockton,
Tulare, Turlock and Vallejo.
</P>
<P>
   Racetracks knew that when they supported off-track betting, they
would lose live customers, said Peter Tunney, Golden Gate Fields'
vice president and general manager. ``But we also knew we had to
make it more convenient for people to keep them as regulars _ to
open up those (satellite facilities) that are closer to where they
might live and work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we suspected that it was going to have some drain,'' Tunney
said. ``I think that about the time we started simulcasting, there
was also a nationwide depletion of attendance at racetracks, so we
got hit with a double whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyon and the management of the 58-year-old track hope to make up
some of the loss with the new campaign, which is centered on the
theme: ``Where the Bay Comes to Play.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad speaks of a ``pageant of power, tradition and
heart-pounding thrills'' and weaves scenes of a horse being
saddled, a nose-to-nose race and postcard-like images of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Gate Fields, owned by British-based Ladbroke Racing, a
major owner of betting shops in Britain, thinks its opening day
program Wednesday will draw a crowd. It's running the richest race
in the country that day, the $125,000 Berkeley Handicap, featuring
Cavonnier, a gelding reared in Sebastopol that lost the 1996
Kentucky Derby by a nose to Grindstone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
