<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO: ANOTHER QUAGMIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When President Clinton bombed suspected terrorist enclaves and
launched military action against Iraq last year, his detractors
accused him of using the nation's armed forces to distract the
public's attention from developments in the presidential sex
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible, said his defenders. The president of the United
States would never do such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   I sided with the defenders, for I was certain that not even a
dishonest, dishonorable, self-serving worm like Clinton would abuse
his power as commander in chief for the sake of crass political
gamesmanship. I likewise reject the current argument _ compelling
though it is _ that Clinton has committed the United States to
airstrikes against Yugoslavia for no reason but to enhance his
eventual standing in the history books.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, if the military adventure in the Balkans is as
risky as most experts say it is, it could doom Clinton to a legacy
of recklessness and failure. The president must know that this
whole deal could blow up in his face.
</P>
<P>
   If it's his legacy he's concerned about, Clinton would be better
off searching for a way to save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   So let's assume that the president of the United States has led
the world's lone remaining superpower into the quicksand of a
European civil war because he believes it's the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The question then becomes: What in the world makes him think
that this terrible misuse of American firepower is right, either as
a matter of principle or as a matter of sensible foreign policy?
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason why Clinton's predecessor George Bush refused
to entangle the United States in the ethnic, religious and
political turmoil that has plagued Bosnia, Kosovo, Serbia, et al.,
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was: The region is a quagmire, a self-destructive
blight on the face of the earth whose problems have nothing to do
with the national security interests of America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton rationalizes U.S. involvement _ as he rationalized our
endless ``peacekeeping'' mission in Bosnia _ by pointing out that
the brutal conflict in Kosovo is hard on the people who live there.
That's not foreign policy, folks; that's bleeding-heart
sentimentalism.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995, Clinton sent troops to Bosnia _ for one year, he
said at the time. The troops are still there, with no prospect of
getting out. The U.S. military is, in effect, an occupying force in
a country that the United States doesn't want, doesn't need and has
no hope of controlling over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clinton bombs Yugoslavia because the United States doesn't
like its evil president, Slobodan Milosevic _ and the only apparent
objective of the bombing is to force Milosevic to allow foreign
troops to occupy his country.
</P>
<P>
   Our president is placing America's armed forces in jeopardy for
the purpose of winning the privilege of placing them in further
jeopardy as part of a NATO ``peacekeeping'' mission in Kosovo. At
this rate, the formerly communist Yugoslavia that had the audacity
to defy the Soviet Union will one day be an occupied colony of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization, with U.S. soldiers as the
backbone of the occupying force.
</P>
<P>
   It's a horrible prospect, and a likely one if foreign policy
experts such as Henry Kissinger are accurately assessing the
probable outcome of the military action that began Wednesday and is
expected to conclude ... when? Nobody seems to know, including the
man who's supposed to be in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Clinton is trying to market his ill-advised policy
to the American people by explaining _ in sometimes condescending,
patronizing fashion, by the way _ the complexities of the
situation. And the more he talks about how complex it is, the more
he inadvertently makes the case for keeping the United States out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Clinton is taking a calculated gamble here. If U.S.
involvement in the Balkans ultimately brings peace and stability to
the region, he will have achieved a remarkable and historic
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the gamble is a long shot, and the stakes are American
lives. It's a lousy bet.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
