<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE WINDOW WELLS DRAIN THE WATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have window wells wih a U-shaped metal wall holding the
earth in position. I dug down three feet and filled the well with
crushed stone. Now the water does not overflow the well, but I am
getting some at the bottom of the foundation, where I think the
water is percolating downward in the well. How can I prevent that
seepage, which is only in the area of the window?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Andover
</P>
<P>
   A. Good point. I think a cure is possible. Install a four-inch
PVC perforated pipe or similar pipe, as long as it is perforated,
below the crushed stone, or at the bottom of the crushed stone,
leading several feet horizontally, with a slight downward pitch,
outward from the well. You could improve things by building a small
dry well at the end of the pipe.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a good idea to put some polyethylene plastic at the
bottom of the crushed stone so the pipe will gather water and
deliver it to the dry well. If the dry well is far enough from the
house, water will percolate downward instead of into the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I tore out the bottom 20 inches of tile on my shower stall,
and installed concrete board, planning to put new tile on with
thin-set mortar. Trouble is, I can't find any tile to match the
old. They are 1 3/4 inches square.
</P>
<P>
   DANA GREEN, Corpus Christie, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are companies that offer old tile; in fact, old
everything, but I don't know of any in Texas. However, you could
call one of these companies that deal in old tile.
</P>
<P>
   General Flooring House of Carpets, of Weymouth, Mass.
781-337-3600, Vermont Salvage in Manchester, N.H., and White River
Junction, Vt. has old tile and metal ceiling tile, marble, and old
mantels and door hardware. Also, Colonial Floors in Framingham,
Mass.,
</P>
<P>
   has old everything.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't work, you have two chocies: 1. Remove the
remaining tile and install a new tile of your choice in the entire
stall. 2. Choose new tiles compatible in size and color with the
existing tile, and fill in with those.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Someone gave me two old, old-fashioned high chairs with
trays. They are wonderful, but the brackets are missing, and I
can't make the trays stay put. Is there a place that sells the
brackets? I'd hate to give up those chairs for the want of a
bracket or two.
</P>
<P>
   SANDY SCAFIDI, Sudbury
</P>
<P>
   A. Try the Woodworkers' Store, now called the Rockler
Woodworkers' Store (800-279-4441.) The catalog carries a lot of
things, including high chair hardware. Such hardware might work for
the high chairs. In fact, Sandy called later to say she called,
ordered, and received the brackets, which she said ``work
prefectly.''
</P>
<P>
   That is always nice to hear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In redoing my basement, I did the walls with Blueboard and
plan to tape the joints and cover them with joint compound, and
also cover nail heads with joint compound, just as one would with
ordinary plasterboard (dry wall). I was told I can't do that. Why
not?
</P>
<P>
   RICK, from Medway
</P>
<P>
   A. He who told you that also should have told you why, but since
there was no reason, he couldn't give you a ``why.'' While
Blueboard is designed to take a skimcoat of plaster, filling joints
filled with a mesh tape, nail heads, and the whole wall with a
plaster skimcoat, there is no reason why you can't do what you plan
to do. The Blueboard has a sort of sandpaper finish to allow the
skimcoat to stick properly; that finish will also allow the joint
compound to stick better. Also, the Blueboard is more water
resistant then ordinary plasterboard.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback might be this: The rough finish of the
Blueboard might contrast with the smooth finish of the joint
compound, making any paint coating uneven. A way around that is to
use a flat, not an eggshell, finish latex wall paint, which is more
likely to even out the finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a rubber roof installed on a shallow dormer roof three
years ago. The roof is great, no leaks or anything else, except
that ice slides down over the roof in great chunks, which I feel is
a hazard when they fall to the ground. How can I prevent that?
</P>
<P>
   LAILA DAMON, Concord
</P>
<P>
   A. Ice, and even snow, often causes hazards by plummeting over
the roof edges. It's the smoothness of the rubber roof that is
losing its grip on the ice (and/or snow). If the roof were rough,
like an asphalt shingle (with tiny stones on top to provide color
and protect the asphalt), there would be no sliding. The same thing
can happen with a slate roof.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why they invented snow hooks, fences or little
pylons on the roof to keep snow (and ice) from sliding off until it
melts. Two companies make them: 1. Vermont Slate &AMP; Copper Services
of Stowe, Vt.; call 802-888-8573 or 888-766-4273. 2. M.J. Mullane
Co. Hudson; call (508) 568-0597. Be careful attaching them to a
rubber roof; make sure the fasteners are well sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Call in your questions on 617-929-2930. Globe Handyman on Call
Peter Hotton is available on Tuesdays from 1 p.m. to 6 p.m. to
answer telephone questions on house repair. Hotton will chat on
line about house matters Thursdays, 1-2 p.m. To participate, point
your Internet browser to http://www.boston.com and use keyword:
chat.
</P>
</TEXT>
