<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SEALAUNCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMENT OF TRUTH COMES TODAY FOR SEA LAUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the equatorial waters of the Pacific Ocean near Christmas
Island, a 208-foot-long Ukrainian-Russian Zenit 3SL rocket is set
to blast off today from a 20-story high North Sea oil rig that has
been converted into a one-of-a-kind space port.
</P>
<P>
   If the historic demonstration launch is successful, it could
give The Boeing Co., principal partner in the venture known as Sea
Launch, a competitive advantage in its goal of being the world's
premier provider of satellite launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of this initial test of the Sea Launch system is
anything but a sure bet. The rocket has had several failures, and
another would be a major setback for Sea Launch, industry experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes of the world's satellite industry will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   The launch can be seen live on the Internet, at Boeing's Web
site, www.boeing.com. It is scheduled for 2:18 p.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of an exciting new era in commercial
space launch activity,'' FAA Administrator Jane Garvey said last
week when the federal regulatory agency announced it had issued a
launch license to the Boeing-led consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications is potentially a $100-billion business, and
the commercial launch business for communication satellites is
exploding. There are many different launch vehicles available to
satellite customers today. More are in development. But there is
stiff competition for the limited number of ground-based launch
sites around the world.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the real significance of Sea Launch and the reason
the program is potentially so important to Boeing, said Marco
Caceres, aerospace analyst with the Teal Group, a market research
firm in Virginia. His speciality is commercial launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This platform in the middle of the ocean is really a
commercial space port,'' Caceres said. ``Boeing will have the
advantage of not having to wait in line to launch commercial
payloads because of backups at ground launch sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it will not say so officially, Boeing reportedly has so
far invested upwards of $500 million in Sea Launch, a 40 percent
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is a partner in Sea Launch with the Norwegian shipbuilder
Kvaerner (20 percent); Russia's RSC-Energia (25 percent); and the
Ukrainian company Yuzhnoye/Yuzhmash (15 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Energia is the company that launched the first Sputnik and
designed the Russian Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some industry speculation in recent months that
Boeing may not be committed, in the long term, to Sea Launch
because it will be years before the program could be expected to
make a profit. Earlier this year, Boeing executives, who are under
fire to make the company more profitable, announced a sweeping
initiative to identify programs that are not of value to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 5 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Boeing said development and administrative losses related to the
Sea Launch program were dragging down returns from the company's
space and defense business, and the losses will continue in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technical failure on the initial launch could substantially
impair the prospect for additional customers' acceptance and could
consequently result in significant reduction to the value of the
Sea Launch program assets,'' Boeing cautioned in its SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing corporate spokesman Larry McCracken would not say if Sea
Launch is one of the programs that will be scrutinized. But because
the program is just getting started, it will take time to assess
its financial success, he said. Only then would it be fair to look
more closely at the program's margins and costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Caceres said he believes Boeing will stay with Sea Launch for
the long haul. But it could be five years or more before the
program shows a profit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how the market develops,'' Caceres said. And
that will determine the all-important number of yearly launches.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch officials have said they hope to initially launch six
to eight rockets a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, any company getting involved in launch services is
not looking to turn a profit quickly,'' Caceres said. ``The
short-term value for Boeing is not that you have another launch
vehicle with Sea Launch, but an independent launch site. That's
something that very few private companies can claim.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Sea Launch is the launch platform known as
Odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   The self-propelled platform is a former North Sea oil drilling
platform, which was refurbished at a shipyard in Norway. It is 436
feet long and 220 feet wide, and can cruise along on pontoons
larger than a Trident submarine at a speedy 13 knots.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Odyssey, the Sea Launch project also includes
the Sea Commander, a 660-foot, specially designed rocket-assembly
and mission control ship.
</P>
<P>
   Home port for both vessels is Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   For the initial launch tomorrow, the total crew for both vessels
is about 320 people, half Russians and Ukrainians. The 70 people on
the Odyssey will be transferred to the command ship before the
rocket blast off.
</P>
<P>
   For launch, the Odyssey will be lowered 65 feet more in the
water to provide more stability.
</P>
<P>
   The site in the middle of the Pacific was picked because it is
on the equator, where the Earth's surface is rotating eastward at
better than 1,000 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   A rocket fired there takes less fuel to reach the 17,500 mph
velocity necessary for orbit because the rocket is able to get the
maximum boost from the Earth's rotation. Less rocket fuel means
less weight, which allows increased payload capacity. What it all
adds up to is that a rocket launched from Odyssey can carry a
heavier satellite at less cost to the customer _ the key selling
point for Sea Launch.
</P>
<P>
   The project was conceived to win contracts from such
California-based satellite companies as Hughes. They can save money
because they don't have to pay the cost of transporting their
satellites to far-away launch sites in Russia, Japan, China or
French Guiana or the U.S. facilities at Cape Canaveral, Fla., and
Vandenberg Air Force Base in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Odyssey may be left at its launch site so it
does not have to return to Long Beach after each firing. Instead
the Sea Commander would carry rocket there. Time saved could allow
a dozen or more commercial launches a year, the same number that
now take place at Cape Canaveral, according to Sea Launch
executives.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Commander can also process two Zenits at a time, so
Odyssey could launch two rockets before the command ship has to
return to Long Beach for another.
</P>
<P>
   The first Sea Launch rocket will carry a dummy payload because
of concerns about past failures of the Zenit booster.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Launch Zenit 3SL is based on the two-stage Zenit 2 built
by the Ukrainians. The third stage is a modified Proton rocket by
Russian's Energia.
</P>
<P>
   The configuration has never been tested before.
</P>
<P>
   Zenit 2 rockets failed in 1990, 1991, 1992 and 1997. The last
resulted in the loss of 12 Globalstar communication satellites. Sea
Launch was to have launched a Galaxy XI satellite on its first
mission, but in the aftermath of of the last Zenit 2 explosion, it
was decided to use a dummy payload.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy satellite was transferred to a French Ariane rocket,
and Sea Launch subsequently lost two of three ICS launches from its
commercial manifest.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hughes and Loral have booked space on Sea Launch for future
launches, but the only certain commercial payload at present is the
third ICO satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Caceres said the success rate of the Zenit 2 is about 80
percent, though that drops to about 75 percent over the last half
dozen years. By comparison, Boeing's Delta 2, a mainstay of the
commercial and government launch business for many years, has a
success rate of about 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only one or two of Zenit 2s are launched a year, Caceres said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to launch more often than that to get a good track
record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One problem Boeing would face if the Zenit 3SL failed is the
highly charged issue of technology transfer by U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. State Department suspended work on Sea
Launch over concerns that Boeing improperly shared sensitive
technology with its Sea Launch partners. Boeing paid a civil
penalty of $7.5 million and Sea Launch was allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is apparently not over. A federal grand jury in
Seattle has been hearing information about the technology transfer
to determine if Boeing broke federal law.
</P>
<P>
   It was the failure of a Chinese Long March rocket carrying a
Hughes satellite that resulted in closer examination of technology
transfers involving U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   After the Chinese rocket exploded, a Hughes team shared
information about the cause with the Chinese. That caused an uproar
in Congress, which found that China was able to use the information
to improve its ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing would have to very careful in helping its partners
determine the cause of any the failure of the Zenit 3SL, and that
could delay the program by a year or more, Caceres said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a significant setback,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
