 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, March 27, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ As NATO forces stepped up their
bombing assault into the daylight hours, President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia maintained fierce resistance both on the
ground and in the air. Two of his MIG-29 fighters shot down on what
NATO claimed was a foray into neighboring Bosnia. The sweep by Serb
troops through the ethnic Albanian villages of Kosovo continued
unabated, NATO said, despite the third straight day of air assaults
that NATO officials emphasized would be unrelenting until Milosevic
accepted peace. By Francis X. Clines and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ The allied military
strategy for stopping Serbian attacks against ethnic Albanian
rebels in Kosovo rests largely on the hope of a specific Serbian
response to the heavy NATO bombing that began on Wednesday,
according to officials here. The hope, allied officers and
diplomats say, is that intense airstrikes will cause so much damage
to Yugoslavia's army and its sophisticated air-defense system that
Serb commanders may soon pressure him to back down and accept
allied terms before they lose everything. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Whispers about a
face-saving Serbian loss to the world's most powerful military
alliance began here long before NATO bombs started to fall.
Surrendering control of Kosovo through peaceful negotiation would
be humiliating. But a hard military loss of Kosovo, after a brave
and hopeless struggle against an overwhelming Western foe, could be
just the ticket that Milosevic needs to survive with his Serbian
manhood and his rule intact. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COUNCIL (United Nations) _ In a resounding victory for
the United States and its NATO alliance, the Security Council
overwhelmingly rejected Friday a Russian-sponsored resolution
demanding an immediate end to NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
The vote on the 15-member Security Council was 12 against the
resolution and three in favor. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-ANALYSIS (Washington) In passing the Republican tax and
spending plan on Thursday, Congress took care of the easy part of
this year's budget battle. By managing to hold their fractious
caucus together and dampen rivalries between the party's leaders in
the House and Senate, Republicans managed to lay out a cohesive
agenda built around a sweeping tax cut, fiscal austerity and
smaller government. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
