<P>
   RENAULT-NISSAN (Frankfurt, Germany) _ A 45-year-old Brazilian
who grew up in Lebanon and was schooled in France is about to lead
40 French executives on a mission to rescue, of all things, Japan's
No. 2 car company. The challenge confronting Carlos Ghosn,
executive vice president of French car maker Renault, would be
enormous enough at any large troubled car manufacturer. But the
potential culture clashes looming as Renault prepares to invest
about $5 billion for a 35-percent stake in Nissan make the
assignment a huge undertaking. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
