<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AVIANO-0327-CO     03-26 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AVIANO-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT AVIANO, THE JETS ROAR AND THE COMMUNITY HOLDS ITS BREATH
 &HT;    EDs: With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0327.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy _ Day Three of the air campaign against
Yugoslavia, and with every roaring jet that leaves this sprawling
NATO air base in northwestern Italy, the tension mounts that one
may not come back.
</P>
<P>
   Aviano is the busiest base involved in the campaign over Kosovo,
a giant staging area for U.S.-led air attacks surrounded by rich
farmland and picturesque villages, the snow-capped Dolomites
looming to the north.
</P>
<P>
   But as the NATO operation grinds on, and the total number of
sorties climbs, concern here grows that so far it has all been a
little too easy for the pilots, who have met little in the way of
resistance from Serbian anti-aircraft fire or attack aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tension, a lot of tension,'' said Marine Lance Cpl.
Dominic Easton, 21, of Miami, Fla., a technician on the EA-6B
Prowler, a radio- and radar-jamming jet aircraft designed to foil
enemy communications.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns grew Friday as NATO officials reported that two
Yugoslav MiG-29 fighters were shot down in action against allied
planes in the skies over Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people who are flying the missions and those on the
ground here at Aviano, you have to know that we worry about them
while they are up there and we worry about them coming back,'' said
Canadian Air Force Capt. Dave Muralt. The Canadians have six F-18
Hornets with 130 pilots and support crew at Aviano. (Citing
security concerns, U.S. officials have not made American pilots
available for interviews).
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, this is a U.S. base. Italy owns it, but
it is dominated by the American 31st Fighter Wing -- two squadrons
of F-16s and dozens of other warplanes and support aircraft. The
fighters carry the wing's motto: ``Return With Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The community of Aviano, just north of the base, is quaintly
Italian, with stucco-walled villas and blossoming fruit trees --
and a dash of America to accommodate the contingent of 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block has an office here, as does the U.S. Automobile
Association. There's a bowling alley, a steak house and, the staple
of nearly every base town, a strip joint. Armed Forces Radio
broadcasts rock-and-roll, country music, Russ Limbaugh and NPR to
the forces. The Aviano Inn offers the classics like chianti and
linguine on its menu, along with cheeseburgers and Cokes.
</P>
<P>
   A tent city sprouted on the base last month to house another
1,000 Air Force and Marine troops brought in as U.S. forces geared
up for the current operation.
</P>
<P>
   American pilots have been filling a combat role over the Balkans
from Aviano since 1994 in Operation: Deny Flight, NATO's air
mission to prevent flights by Bosnian Serb warplanes. In 1995, U.S.
F-16s flew more than 400 combat sorties that helped convince the
Bosnian Serbs to concede to the Dayton Peace Accords being
negotiated at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction is strongly voiced among Americans on- and
off-the base that the United States and NATO are doing the right
thing now by seeking to limit Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's ability to wage war against ethnic Albanians in the
separatist province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to American pilots is just part of the job, they say,
but it doesn't alleviate the tension that has settled over the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want my husband to be a pilot, I'd be a nervous
wreck,'' said the secretary of Aviano's Baptist church, who did not
give her name.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest concern in the American community is that Aviano
could become a target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to send my daughter to school at the base this
morning. You know, terrorism,'' said Erica McNelly, the wife of a
civilian contractor. ``People are worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Military police forces, clad in flak jackets and combat helmets,
have stepped up security measures and canceled events, such as
soccer games and a talent show, that would draw American civilians
to the base's community center. Bomb-sniffing dogs inspect every
car entering the base and Humvee's patrol the base perimeter, their
mounted machine guns manned and ready.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials refuse to discuss security, and whether the
increased security is in response to a specific threat.
</P>
<P>
   But locals believe the security is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said McNelly, an Aviano native who married her
American husband 16 years ago, ``is not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
