<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WIDER-WAR-$ADV     03-26 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WIDER-WAR-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON INVOKES DOMINO THEORY TO JUSTIFY BALKAN INTERVENTION  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 A News Analysis   
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has dusted off the Cold War-era
``domino theory'' _ used to rationalize U.S. intervention in
Vietnam _ to help justify the U.S.-led attack against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argues that the most sustained allied bombing campaign
since the Persian Gulf War is required to crush Yugoslav armed
forces in order to stem the threat of a wider war across the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let a fire burn here in this area and the flames will
spread,'' Clinton warned last week. ``Eventually key U.S. allies
could be drawn into a wider conflict or we would be forced to
confront it later only at far greater risk and greater cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The president did not mention Greece and Turkey by name but his
subordinates did, citing the risk that the exodus of ethnic
Albanian Muslim refugees from the Yugoslav onslaught in Kosovo
could ignite repercussions in neighboring Albania and Macedonia _
prompting Turkey and Greece to enter the conflict to protect their
ethnic and religious allies.
</P>
<P>
   All of these nations have some ethnic or religious linkage to
the rivalries underlying Yugoslavia's attempts to suppress Kosovo's
drive for independence.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said the flood of
refugees out of Kosovo ``threatens peace in the Balkans and the
stability of Europe'' because it could ``exacerbate rivalries
between Greece and Turkey _ two of our NATO allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Greece nor Turkey last week declared any intention to
intervene in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's rationale recalls the explanation
used by President Lyndon Baines Johnson in the 1960s to explain
what became a fruitless 11-year intervention in Vietnam to stem the
southward march by communist North Vietnamese forces.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said U.S. aid was needed to prevent South Vietnam from
falling to the communist onslaught like a ``domino,'' leading to
potential communist takeovers in Laos, Cambodia, Thailand,
Malaysia, and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   But Balkan experts question the Clinton administration's
contention that allied intervention is needed to halt the civil war
in Yugoslavia in order to avert a wider war spreading to Albania
and Macedonia, provoking intervention by Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Bulent Aliriza, a Turkey expert at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies (CSIS) in Washington, D.C., says the ethnic,
historic and religious alliances crisscrossing the Balkans are
unlikely to ignite a wider conflict involving Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between Turkey and Greece has been strained
for a long time,'' said Aliriza. ``Add the wrinkle of Kosovo and it
doesn't make the relationship any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Greece opposes the allied bombing of the Yugoslav Serbs; Turkey
supports the operation, designed in part to halt Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosovic's repression of ethnic Albanian Muslim
separatists in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey and Greece have long had a tense relationship based on
differences over the Mediterranean island of Cyprus, territory in
the Aegean Sea and Greece's protection of fugitive Kurdish rebel
leader Abdullah Ocalan in Kenya, where he was seized by Turkish
commandos on Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, both Turkey and Greece are democratic members of
the 19-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Greece belongs to
the 15-nation European Union; Turkey wants to join.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kane, an expert on Turkey who served with the Central
Intelligence Agency in a variety of overseas posts including
Turkey, Egypt, Iraq, Lebanon and Algeria, also discounts the
possibility of a full blown regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greece and Turkey have a lot to fight about as it is and they
have both shown restraint,'' Kane said. ``The idea that Kosovo
could have triggered a war between Greece and Turkey is kind of
far-fetched. It's nothing to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Montville, a 23-year veteran of State Department posts in
the Middle East and North Africa who now serves as director of a
preventive diplomacy project at CSIS, dubs the risk of war between
Greece and Turkey ``hypothetical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the dogs of war were unleashed and left unchecked in that
part of the world, you could see tensions flare in Albania and
Macedonia,'' Montville said. ``It doesn't take much to get the
Greeks and the Turks geared up to threaten war _ but going to war
is a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Montville and Aliriza caution, however, that events in the
Balkans often prove unpredictable. As Aliriza puts it: ``You start
turning the pages of history and looking at the remnants of
minorities in these countries and a remote possibility always
exists that Turkey and Greece could stumble into war.''
</P>
<P>
   The specialists cite two worst case scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   _ Turkey would come to the aid of besieged fellow Muslims in
Kosovo, Albania or Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian Muslims comprise 90 percent of the population in
Yugoslav-controlled Kosovo; 70 percent of the 3.3 million people in
Albania; and 30 percent of the 2 million people in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Some 450,000 ethnic Albanian refugees have fled their homes in
Kosovo over the past year, with an estimated 260,000 remaining in
Kosovo, 55,000 in neighboring provinces in Yugoslavia, 20,000 in
Macedonia and 18,500 in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   _ Greece, a predominantly Eastern Orthodox Christian nation with
historic and religious ties to the Serbian allies with whom they
fought the Ottoman Turks, would come to the aid of imperiled Greeks
in Albania or Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Greeks account for up to an estimated 12 percent of the
population in Albania and 65 percent of the population in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Friday the allied
campaign has diminished the risk of a wider war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be a greater risk of a wider war if we had done
nothing,'' Lockhart said. ``The war has not spread in a material
way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Balkan tinder box traces its fuse back centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ottoman Turks swept into southeastern Europe in the 1300s,
storming across Greece to triumph over defending Serbs in a
legendary battle in Kosovo in 1389 that opened the door to Turkish
Muslim domination of the Eastern Orthodox Christian region for six
centuries until World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Stubborn antagonisms linger still between Muslim descendants of
the occupying Turks and Christian descendants of conquered Serbs
and Greeks who fought for centuries to rid their homelands of
unwelcome Turkish overlords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
