202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO-CRIME-PUNISHMENT. On a cold December night in 1994,
gang members gunned down 18-year-old Maximino ``Mino'' Galindo in
an alley in east Pueblo, a city torn by gang violence. Galindo's
slaying was the fifth gang-related murder that year. Five years
after Galindo's death, gangs are still active on the streets of
Pueblo, but something of a miracle seems to have taken place. Last
year, there were no gang-related murders. Even more striking has
been the drop in total crime in this city of 100,000: Since the
start of 1995, Pueblo's total crime rate has been cut in half, down
52 percent through the end of last year, according to the FBI's
Uniform Crime Reports. (20 inches.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT-FIRE. Rep. Sam Gejdenson introduced legislation this
week to help volunteer fire departments buy emergency equipment.
(200 to 300 words.) By Laura Maggi
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-CREDIT-LANDRIEU. The Senate passed an amendment by
Sen. Mary Landrieu to provide tax credits in a variety of areas --
health care, child care, businesses. The proposal is similar to
President Clinton's plan for targeted tax relief, and thus looks
likely to be enacted. (300 words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-KOSOVO-REACT. Reactions from members of the Georgia and
South Carolina congressional delegations to the bombing campaign in
Yugoslavia. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-OPEN. A look at competing open-space plans in
Congress. By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-KOSOVO-REAX. Philadelphia lawmakers react to NATO
air strikes in Yugoslavia. (400 words.) Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-GAO. The Government Accounting Office released a
nursing home report that outlines staffing and other difficulties.
A local incident in Johnstown has officials working to make nursing
homes safer. (800 words.) Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-REACT-KOSOVO. Reaction from the Texas delegation to NATO
air strikes in Yugoslavia. Brown
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-KOSOVO-REACT. Hundreds of angry Wyoming residents have
called their senators and congressmen to protest President
Clinton's decision to attack Serb targets within Yugoslavia,
congressional aides said Friday. (400 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-KOSOVO-GRAPHIC. Quotations from Wyoming's three federal
lawmakers on the use of force in Yugoslavia for an infographic. (6
inches.) By Charles Davant
</P>
