<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-PR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors' new oath: Physician, publicize thyself
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dr. Daniel Choy has a flourishing
medical practice on the tony upper East Side of Manhattan. Chances
are you've heard of him.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City surgeon was disappointed a few years ago when
a procedure he devised to treat spine problems wasn't catching on
in the medical community _ or with prospective patients. Articles
had appeared in respected medical journals such as the New England
Journal of Medicine, but an article here or there wasn't cutting
it.
</P>
<P>
   So, Choy took a step many other ambitious doctors are turning to
_ and not without some criticism. He hired a public-relations
expert, a ``flack,'' paying a professional to do what he couldn't.
Amanda-Beth Uhry, a specialist in New York City, would get the word
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``She worked for me for about a year and in that time got me
into some newspapers, and CBS did a news program on me. And God, it
was incredible. My phone rang off the hook for months after.''
</P>
<P>
   As more doctors strive to maintain their financial health during
times of changing insurance practices, they're increasingly
employing promotional experts.
</P>
<P>
   But self-promotion can still carry an odor _ even among those
who play the PR game themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Ellenbogen, a Los Angeles plastic surgeon, says he
needs the help because his speciality is so competitive. But he
doesn't approve of traditional doctors such as Choy doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm selling something, so I have to create a market,'' he said
in a recent article in American Medical News, a publication of the
American Medical Association. ``But it's reprehensible for a doctor
who takes care of illness to do PR.''
</P>
<P>
   Choy says with his procedure, ``People get off the table usually
free of pain.'' But he adds: ``New technologies take a long time to
diffuse through the medical community and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the medical community frowned on doctors trumpeting
their skills. Today, the American Medical Association has no rules
against it, except guidelines that ban anything misleading. Aside
from that, anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   That means telephone calls and faxes from agents to reporters,
editors and producers, and glossy photos and press releases
overnighted and hand-delivered _ all carefully planned to score
some attention for clients and their medical ``breakthroughs.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest stunt Boca Raton, Fla., publicist Barry Epstein ever
pulled for a medical client was for Dr. Richard Staller, a dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Staller is a baseball fanatic, so Epstein sent out photos of the
dentist in a baseball uniform, one with a bat over his shoulder,
posed by his dental chair. Staller had practiced with the
Philadelphia Phillies in a ``dream team'' program during spring
training _ that was the news hook. But stories also mentioned
Staller's ``thriving dental practice with offices in Palm Beach and
Broward counties.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hook, an angle. Spring training and the Marlins were
big, and the newspapers ate it up,'' Epstein says. ``Visibility is
the word. The name of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And that kind of exposure carries far more credibility, PR
experts say, than paid advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a doctor appears on `20/20' and shows their personality,
and can more clearly explain what they need to, it holds more
weight in the mind of the consumer than seeing an ad where doctors
advertise themselves,'' says Kathy Rothman, of Uhry's firm.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Randie Levine-Miller, president of Accent on Broadcasting
in New York City: ``Advertising is too blatant, and a lot of people
get very turned off when they see doctors advertising; they don't
trust them. If they see an article in the newspaper, they think the
printed word is the gospel. It's a virtual endorsement when a
reporter gives a mention to a doctor unless it's a controversial
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   For that very reason, not all doctors want the public to know
they are paying to get into newspapers, magazines and TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of doctors like it kept confidential,'' says Rothman.
``They think that letting the public know defeats the purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Uhry, the Manhattan PR agent, opened her firm seven years ago
when plastic surgeons _ the firm's bread-and-butter clients _
started dropping procedures that required insurance and
reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were looking to take their practices from reconstructive
to cosmetic, because it was more profitable,'' Rothman says.
</P>
<P>
   The fierce competition in that field drove many to seek
professional public relations counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastic surgery, dermatology, it's enormously competitive.
When the economy's good, patients can afford it. But doctors want
their practices to flourish independent of the economic condition.
That's what we do, increase their name recognition, find their
target market,'' Rothman adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, the way people pick elective surgeons, sadly
enough, it's what kind of buzz they heard about it. Like a
restaurant. They equate having heard about it with people being
good.''
</P>
<P>
   But individual doctors aren't the only ones turning to
professional public relations agents.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals and medical centers are also trying to distinguish
themselves from their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the individual doctor necessarily who is doing
this,'' said Kathy Adams, president of MediaReach in West Palm
Beach, which has Duke University Medical Center and Intracoastal
Health Systems (which runs Good Samaritan and St. Mary's medical
centers here) as clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who use PR companies are more cutting edge . . . The
advantage is to inform the public of what's coming out now so the
consumer can better research that.''
</P>
<P>
   And what do these publicity artists say when confronted by
doctors who think promotion is unethical?
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors who think it's horrible,'' said Levine-Miller,
``are the doctors who can't get ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
