<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road rage? Naw, Mom's just having a baby
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here's Margaret Rivera weaving her Chevy
Cavalier through Interstate 95 traffic, honking, steering with one
hand, sobbing, praying and, with her right hand, trying desperately
to deliver Rita Namur's baby, who is keeping an urgent appointment
with the world right now!
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of imagery for this early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back a few ticks and set the stage for what became
Namur's wild ride to Bethesda Memorial Hospital in Boynton Beach,
Fla., at 10 a.m. on Thursday, March 18.
</P>
<P>
   Namur, 23, of suburban Lake Worth, is the wife of Juan Namur,
33, who six months ago suffered an incapacitating neck injury in a
fall on the job. Rivera, 46, is his home caretaker. She had just
stopped by on a scheduled visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you take a look at my wife?'' Juan asked Margaret in
Spanish. ``She is feeling strangely.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months' pregnant, Rita's due date was April 1, and the
mother of a 3-year-old did not think she was going into labor. But
when Margaret called the expectant mother's doctor, she was told to
get Rita to Bethesda.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret drove while, between contractions, Rita gave
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get off at Woolbright going west when we should have been
going east, and I'm weaving around, trying to drive, and I look
down and here's the baby's crown, and I've got to turn around, and
suddenly Rita arches up and cries out my name as long as I've ever
heard it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Margieeeeeeeeeeeee!''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret executes a deft backhand stab, catching the baby on the
short hop off the seat, and manages to flip the baby girl on the
mother's chest and pull into a strip mall simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks I'm road-raging, but this one woman in
traffic can tell that something's up, so she pulls over and says,
`I'm an R.N. Is there a problem?'''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes. Margaret, a study in efficiency, is managing to have a
nervous breakdown and minister to the newborn girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I'm parked, I reach over and swoop the mouth . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Swoop?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, clear the stuff out of the mouth. I gave the baby a
smack on the bottom, and she started crying, but then she stopped,
and I picked her up, the cord still hanging, and give her a couple
of breaths and another spank, and she starts yelling. It was
wonderful!''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nurse _ Margaret believes her name is Rita Tart _
reports that an ambulance is on the way, and now it is time to cut
the umbilical cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned my car upside-down, looking for something to cut it
with. Somebody, I don't know who it was, came up with a spring
clamp for holding papers together, but we still didn't have a
blade.''
</P>
<P>
   And here the mother, who had gone into labor and delivered in 15
minutes, was composed enough to offer a suggestion in Spanish, a
memory of how Mexican midwives cut the umbilical cord. You can see
what's coming, can't you?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Here goes,''' said Margaret, ``and, `chomp,' bit
through the cord. Then we clamped it off. Meanwhile, the EMTs
showed up with oxygen. The baby was wrapped in my old pink
sweatshirt I keep in the car, and she was just precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom and baby proceeded to Bethesda, where both were pronounced
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The story was well told by Margaret, with much help from her
hands, so there could be no mistaking when she finished. And then
the mother, cradling tiny Aolani Namur in her arms, asked something
of Margaret in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants me to tell you that she doesn't know what she would
have done because her husband is injured and cannot drive.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Margaret smiles, starts to say something and then
chokes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't get over it. Especially, since I took an EMT
course and flunked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
