<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-EDTV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY AND TELEVISION SEEN AS SIDES OF THE SAME COIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So OK, we're a celebrity-driven culture, where people are famous
just for being famous. Why does our fascination with fame
crystallize around TV? In less than a year, we've had three
ambitious comedies on the theme of TV worship. TV rules, said ``The
Truman Show,'' and this is bad. Forget your troubles, c'mon get
happy with TV, said ``Pleasantville,'' and its protagonists did. In
its unassuming and even charming way, Ron Howard's ``EDtv'' reminds
us why TV is the devil we feel we have to make a deal with. TV is
today's great validator, the only validator that matters, really.
Today you're a schlep, tomorrow you're golden _ provided TV smiles
upon you. TV is the rubber stamp on your hand that gets you into
the club of People Who Matter. For at least 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Howard is too much the amiable and unpretentious entertainer to
lapse into earnest sermonizing. He casts his take on TV's takeover
as a romantic comedy that disarms us with its zaniness and
sweetness. There's a nice overlay of goofiness on the satire, but
make no mistake, Howard knows exactly where to go with the fertile
subject of reality-based TV, and goes there winningly, from the
moment the film's San Francisco-based cable channel named True TV
finds itself being clobbered by the Gardening Channel and decides
to fight back. Their weapon? Everyslob, a beer-drinking,
going-nowhere guy toward whom audience members can feel
unthreatened and superior.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson's VCR repairman thinks he's the perfect
candidate, and perhaps would be, except that the talent scouts
prefer his kid brother, Matthew McConaughey's videostore clerk
named Ed. Ed's not too crazy about the idea, but his brother
convinces him that round-the-clock TV exposure will make their
lives better. So Ed says yes. In contrast to Jim Carrey's Truman,
who didn't know he was on TV, Ed willingly allows the cameras in.
All Ed all day works fine for the ratings _ and for the
commercials, which ribbon across the bottom of the screen, starting
with local restaurants and amusingly escalating to national brands
as the audience grows.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed soon begins to regard the situation as a sort of
Pandora's box in reverse. As TV films Ed's life, TV becomes Ed's
life, neatly giving form to the central contradiction of so-called
reality-based TV. How can reality become entertainment, when
entertainment becomes reality? Not that Ed sits around pondering
these conundrums. He's too busy trying to keep his life together as
the cameras relentlessly begin to pull it apart. First, his yahoo
older brother sours with resentment that Ed and not he was the
chosen one. His rancor deepens when Ed finds himself getting close
emotionally to the girlfriend his brother ignores.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, inevitably, Ed and the girlfriend kiss. But what
should be a private moment is telecast to millions of homes, and
the romance never really gets the growing room it needs. What it
does get is a delightful performance by Jenna Elfman that's at once
gritty and buoyant. She's got enough backbone to take off when Ed
is told that 71 percent of the show's audience doesn't like her.
This leaves Ed to reluctantly be prodded into a strictly
made-for-TV romance with Elizabeth Hurley's actress on the make. It
also starts pulling his family apart.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey and Harrelson groove on the lowlife brother
interplay and Sally Kirkland is on target as a self-justifying mom
whose rationales crumble when the husband she dumped, played by
Dennis Hopper, resurfaces with a bit of inconvenient revisionist
truth-telling. Funnier still is Martin Landau as the ailing second
hubby, scooting around in a wheelchair, running on the best lines
by the screenwriting team of Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel, in
their best form of the '90s. But it's McConaughey's comic
zigzagging and Elfman's plucky sprite who give ``EDtv'' its vital
center.
</P>
<P>
   Considering all the moving parts in ``EDtv,'' Howard directs it
with remarkable nimbleness, especially when it comes to juggling
film and TV-within-a-film footage. He never hits the material (or
us) over the head. He has fun, too, with the controlling TV execs _
Ellen DeGeneres, who at least arrives at remorse, and Rob Reiner's
archfiend, who keeps fingering his necktie while saying things such
as, ``If it's dirty and it's true, we want it.'' Don't let the fact
that you may have seen ``The Truman Show'' or ``Pleasantville''
keep you away from this one. Those films were brilliantly stylized.
This one is much more down to earth, but just as appealing while
covering as much ground in its deceptively modest way. `EDtv'' is
juicy stuff served with a light touch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
