<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHEIST-CASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WITH LINKS TO O'HAIR FIGURE ARRESTED IN MICHIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A second ex-convict who is a possible figure in the 1995
disappearance of atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair was ordered held
without bond Friday on federal firearms charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gary P. Karr, 50, was arrested Wednesday after the police and
FBI agents searched his apartment in Novi, Mich., and found two
loaded firearms _ an RG Industries .22-caliber revolver and a
.25-caliber Raven Semi-Automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were found at his residence. The search warrant was
executed on Wednesday, the same day a search warrant was served on
Mr. David Waters in Austin,'' Darren Holmes, an FBI spokesman in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Karr appeared Friday afternoon before a federal magistrate in
Detroit who ordered him held without bond.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 52, who was once O'Hair's office manager in Austin, also
is being held without bond in Texas. The police and FBI discovered
119 rounds of ammunition in his Austin apartment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were charged under the federal statute that makes it
illegal for a convicted felon to possess ammunition or firearms.
</P>
<P>
   For eight months in the mid-1980s, the two men were inmates at
the same minimum security prison in Vienna, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Waters and Karr have not been charged in connection with the
O'Hair case. But Waters' court-appointed attorney, Patrick Ganne,
said earlier this week that a federal prosecutor brought up the
disappearance of O'Hair and two of her adult children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said you can get the death penalty for solicitation to
commit murder. He said he better get right with God and tell his
side of the story,'' said Ganne, referring to conversations with
Assistant U.S. Attorney Gerald Carruth in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Ganne also said that Carruth had told him that Waters had been
implicated in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said a bunch of people are rolling over on him and
implicating him in the murder of the O'Hair family,'' Ganne said.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth has declined to discuss his conversations with Ganne.
</P>
<P>
   Karr served more than 20 years in Illinois prisons as a result
of a spree of crimes, including rape, kidnapping and robbery, in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has prior convictions for murder, battery, forgery and
theft. The latter conviction came in 1995 after Waters stole
$54,000 from the O'Hair organizations while working as their office
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Waters was released in 1987. Karr left prison in May 1995, four
months before O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin
Murray O'Hair disappeared in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The three vanished along with $500,000 in gold.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair had long lost the cultural prominence she relished in the
decades following the Supreme Court decisions of the early 1960s
that removed Bible reading and prayer from public schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her disappearance, she was a sick and aging woman
who had become a marginal figure within atheist circles, and was
known to be contemplating retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it will become very clear that my mother, brother
and (Robin) did not take $500,000 and flee the country, that in
fact they were kidnapped and murdered for the money,'' said Bill
Murray, O'Hair's other son, who lives in Fredericksburg, Va. ``I
think this will help to give closure not only to me, but to all the
members of my mother's organizations who were led to believe she
just took their funds and absconded.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Florida man, Danny Fry, vanished at the same time as they
O'Hair family after spending September 1995 in San Antonio on a
mysterious errand. He had gone to Texas to work with Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's family and relatives said Waters was not helpful after Fry
did not return to Florida as promised in early October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   His fate was not known until January of this year when DNA
testing indicated that a nude, headless and handless body found on
Oct. 2, 1995, east of Dallas was that of Fry.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has denied any knowledge of either the Fry or O'Hair
case.
</P>
<P>
   Theories on the O'Hair case have ranged from kidnapping and
murder to a self-imposed foreign exile sustained by funds drained
from her atheist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous bits of circumstantial evidence, however, suggest that
the Fry and O'Hair cases are connected. Additional evidence puts
Karr and Waters in San Antonio at about the same time in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone records also suggest extensive contact between Fry and
Waters earlier in 1995, and show that he stayed at Waters' Austin
apartment a month before O'Hair and her children vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's last telephone call home, on Sept. 30, 1995, was made from
Waters' apartment. Less than 48 hours later, the mutilated body was
discovered 275 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   According to an affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in
Detroit on Thursday, Karr offered no resistance when police
confronted him Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests of Karr and Waters came as federal agents
simultaneously questioned people in Chicago and Fort Worth, Texas.
Only Karr and Waters have been charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
