<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LAWMAKERS-NYTR     03-26 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LAWMAKERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN HAWKS GIVE WING TO DOUBTS ON BOMBING CAMPAIGN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Southern lawmakers are among the most outspoken
boosters of the U.S. military, but they were also the most vocal
critics of President Clinton's decision to bomb Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the air strikes have commenced, most lawmakers,
regardless of political affiliation, have tempered their criticism,
signaling their support for U.S. forces in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   But they are clearly uneasy about the air campaign, part of a
NATO-led effort to end the conflict in Kosovo, a province of
Yugoslavia where Albanians want their independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think we should be choosing sides in what amounts to
a very brutal civil war,'' said Sen. Strom Thurmond, a Republican
and former chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee. The
venerable South Carolinian voted against a resolution supporting
the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed before the bombing runs began. But the
58-41 vote reflected congressional reluctance to intervene in the
Balkans dispute. Even Democrat Fritz Hollings of South Carolina
broke party ranks to vote against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Mack of Florida, Richard Shelby of Alabama and Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky were the only Southern Republicans in the
Senate to support it. But their comments were hardly a ringing
endorsement of Clinton's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby faulted the president for not articulating an ``exit
strategy'' and pursuing policies that put America's credibility at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said the White House should not misinterpret his position.
``My vote in favor of this deployment was not carte blanche for any
future military action the president may seek to undertake,'' said
Mack, who hit Clinton for failing to communicate both with Congress
and the public.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the target at a Senate hearing where Republicans
criticized his record on prosecuting gun offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Subcommittee
on Youth Violence, offered statistics that showed federal
prosecutions of firearms violations involving drug and gang
criminals declined 46 percent between 1992 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``How President Clinton can justify calls for more gun control
laws when his Justice Department doesn't fully prosecute the gun
laws we have now is a mystery to me,'' Sessions, a critic of gun
control, wrote recently.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials said the decline reflected greater
coordination between state, local and federal officials. They said
state and local courts are targeting more of the lower-level
offenders, while federal officials are focusing on the bigger
cases.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton promised in a recent radio address
``to use every available tool to increase the prosecution of gun
criminals and shut down illegal gun markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Are 150 House Democrats firmly on the record in support of
racism? That is what Republicans are claiming in the wake of a
politically tortured vote on a resolution that condemned all forms
of bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the background: House Democrats, trying to embarrass
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and House
impeachment advocate Bob Barr, R-Ga., introduced a resolution
condemning the Council of Conservative Citizens, a white
supremacist group that both Lott and Barr have spoken before.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered with a resolution attacking any and all
racism, saying Democrats fell short in just going after one group.
``We should not use this as a political tool,'' said Rep. J.C.
Watts, R-Okla., a black GOP leader and sponsor of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats rejected the GOP resolution, calling it a meaningless
political gesture. ``It does nothing real,'' said Rep. Robert
Wexler, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans strategists hope to turn the vote against Democrats
next year, but Wexler and others say the party's record on civil
rights will insulate them from GOP attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't accuse Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., of letting bygones be
bygones.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Inglis, his opponent in last year's bitter Senate race, was
an advocate of term limits and stuck to his own vow of serving just
three terms in the House. He then ran for the Senate, arguing that
Hollings had overstayed his welcome. The attack obviously rankled,
judging by Hollings' response to a recent question on term-limit
advocates rethinking their pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, I had to run against all that last year,''
said Hollings, getting wound up as he remembered Inglis. ``He said
that he was going back and live under the laws that he had passed
and everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' declared Hollings, ``he wanted to come and live in
my house. I had to run him out.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
