A5643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-26 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS GEORGE REGAN AND WHY IS HE TAKEN SO SERIOUSLY?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His slicked-back hair is unlike any patchwork of reddish-brown
known to even the best colorists on Newbury Street _ the shade of
tree bark in some spots, what Martha Stewart might call fawn's fur
in others. When he talks in that machine gun, rat-a-tat,
nobody-can-barely-understand-me-but-hey-that's-okay way of his, he
punctuates each sentence with an unintentionally comical raise of
his eyebrows. Why? Who knows.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows. Who knows why George Regan, arguably the most
dominant public relations executive in Boston, chooses to be so
domineering. Who knows why he picks petty fights, savages
reputations, tries to tear down what others have built up.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, who knows why some of Boston's most serious people,
people of character and consequence, kneel so readily at his altar
of promising publicity and embrace him as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the whole of Boston politics, business and media, and that
murky area where the three inevitably and often intertwine, there
may be no more discussed figure than Regan, part huckster, part
old-fashioned press agent to the famous and frantic, part effective
strategist for the corporate elite.
</P>
<P>
   And he's at it all over again, a hurricane in perpetual search
of land, this time taking on the lobbying and public relations
titan Thomas P. O'Neill III, son of the late House speaker. Like a
car crash in the making, it is a collision that is painful to watch
but irresistible to see.
</P>
<P>
   Regan, according to O'Neill, told a potential client he was
about to hire away a prized publicist from O'Neill's company, and
then spread rumors that O'Neill's business was ailing. O'Neill
responded with a stern letter from his lawyer. Regan responded by
delightedly faxing the letter to anyone who asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``My company has to be protected, my clients have to be
protected,'' O'Neill said. ``When I find him doing something
inappropriate, I'm going to handle it professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Regan: ``I wouldn't be surprised if Tommy O'Neill had a
used car lot behind his building.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another day in the life of George Regan. His success is
legend _ 130 active clients by his own count, $5 million in
reported fees last year. His friends are legion, extending down the
corridors of government power to the most prized corporate
boardrooms to the city's major newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Investigative and business reporters graze on his tips. Few are
the city's journalists who've had the pleasure of never meeting
him. Regan, a former spokesman for Kevin White, claims the Herald
as a client, and even has its former editor-in-chief, Alan Eisner,
as his company president.
</P>
<P>
   Within the tightly woven public relations community of Boston,
Regan isn't so much disliked as despised. ``He's deadly,'' says
Dusty Rhodes, a respected publicist. ``He takes down what you try
to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes knows first-hand. Her long-held plan to bring the Tall
Ships to Boston in July 2000 was nearly sunk by Regan, who was
hired by a Connecticut company with a competitive plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was paid $10,000 a month,'' Rhodes says, in a
conversation confirmed by a witness. ``He said he was hired to
destroy Sail Boston, and if he had to, to destroy me.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Regan: ``I don't know what she was drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Regan, rival publicists express fear and scurry for
anonymity. They whisper about his relationship with the Herald,
about his penchant to generate negative news to prolong contracts.
They complain about a 1995 Globe profile of Regan they deemed too
positive, yet only one publicist _ Joe Burnieika _ agreed to be
quoted in that story by name. Burnieika says Regan has battered his
reputation ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Batting practice,'' Regan says of his swings at Burnieika.
Later, he calls to relay a supposed Burnieika transgression.
</P>
<P>
   Smart people sing Regan's praises. He counts as clients
BankBoston, Biogen, the Celtics, Robert Kraft, New Balance. ``You
call and he springs into action,'' says Massachusetts Turnpike
chairman James Kerasiotes. ``He's relentless.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Regan called 12 times  &UR; yesterday &LR;  attempting to
influence these words. Mutual associates telephoned out of the blue
to praise him. At one point, the nice manager of Ciao Bella _ a
Regan haunt _ was on the line with an offer of free dinner. Regan
is, by most accounts, a great friend to the worthy.
</P>
<P>
   All of which provides a lesson of sorts. Good reputations are
hard-earned, and in this era of media saturation, easily lost. So
why does Regan, so protective of his own reputation, so enjoy
tearing others down? The only answer isn't much of one at all. Who
knows.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
