<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MOD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ``MOD SQUAD'' QUICKLY BECOMES A PLOD SQUAD
</HEADLINE>
 SQUAD-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Mod Squad'' brings to the big screen _ but not in a big
way _ the TV series that ran from 1968 to 1973 and was one of the
things that defined the medium's cool. The intended audience for
the new movie version is much too young to have watched the
original, except perhaps in reruns. Not that it's in any way
crucial because, frankly, the film's only point of similarity with
the original is that it, too, stars a black character named Linc
(Omar Epps), a white one named Pete (Giovanni Ribisi), and a blonde
named Julie (Claire Danes). There's something to be said for all
three, although more for Epps and Ribisi than for Danes, who never
seems comfortable enough to fully inhabit her role of an ex-junkie
trying to win her freedom and clear her record by going undercover
for the LA police.
</P>
<P>
   Epps is more than comfortable with his undercover assignment,
which consists mostly of looking, taking everything in, and
reacting a lot, but in internalized ways, never histrionically.
Ribisi is the hotdog who gets off on making it up as he goes along.
He brings a nice scatty energy to his role and curls the ends of
his lips into various expressive smirks. In short, all three show
up more than ready to work, but the case they're working on is
lame, predictable, and drawn out to numbing length. Its take on
dirty cops stealing and selling drugs from the police evidence
locker is the stuff that awns are made of. For an action film,
it's amazingly sluggish, and the club scenes, where the presumably
hip delinquents seem more out of place than on the streets, offers
little relief.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the problems stem from the low level of
inspiration in the screenplay, Scott Silver's choppy, disjointed
direction is another liability. Silver is best in capturing the
atomized atmosphere of the LA streets, where life seems to stand
still while cars go by. The problem is that ``The Mod Squad'' also
seems to stand still, all its back-and-forth notwithstanding.
Dennis Farina, as the cop who takes the trio under his wing,
injects some warmth in the beginning, and Michael Lerner, as a rock
promoter playing drug kingpin, supplies a touch of welcome
eccentricity at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``The Mod Squad'' plays like a very ordinary
half-hour cop show stretched into an hour and a half. It's hard not
to think of it as ``The Plod Squad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
