A5661 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-$AD     03-26 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHOMING THE CHERRY TOMATO, A SEED AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LEE REICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I have seen gardens which were all experiment, given over to
every new thing, and which produced little or nothing for the
owners, except the pleasure of expectation.'' With those
century-old words of wisdom from the essayist and editor Charles
Dudley Warner (``My Summer in a Garden,'' 1888) looming over me, I
still went ahead two years ago to devote 120 square feet of my
property to cherry tomatoes, almost two dozen varieties. I wanted
to see how different one variety was from the next in plant size
and health, and in fruit size, color and _ most important _ flavor.
</P>
<P>
   To most people, a cherry tomato is, well, just a cherry tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who scour garden centers for special varieties of
full-size tomato plants will grow just about any old cherry tomato
offered. And no wonder. Although cherry tomatoes existed in Europe
as long ago as 1623, they have always been relatively unimportant,
grown mostly for curiosity or for pickles and preserves. Nowadays,
most of the crop turns up in salad bars, and then because they do
not need slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry tomatoes are a subspecies of tomato, with round fruits
divided within into two cells. They usually dangle from the plants
in parallel, ropelike clusters, and they are small, generally the
size of a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   My journey into the land of cherry tomatoes began on a winter
evening, while I was studying seed catalogs, in which I found a
good selection of red and yellow varieties. Most of my seeds came
from two specialists, Tomato Growers Supply Co. (P.O. Box 2237,
Fort Myers, Fla. 33902; 888-478-7333; free catalog) and Totally
Tomatoes (P.O. Box 1626, Augusta, Ga. 30903; 803-663-0016; free
catalog).
</P>
<P>
   The site I selected was bathed in sunlight from morning until
midafternoon, with a deep loam soil that had been enriched annually
with horse manure, hay and leaves. In short, perfect.
</P>
<P>
   I started plants indoors in mid-April, and shortly after the
seedlings were transplanted outdoors, warm, sunny weather spurred
growth. The plants had to be pruned to prevent congestion in some
of the tomato cages I used (5-foot-tall cylinders 18 inches in
diameter, made of concrete reinforcement wire with a 6-by-6-inch
mesh). As I pruned, pronounced differences among varieties became
evident. Varieties like Peace Vine, Camp Joy and Red Cherry Large
were reaching out the sides of their cages and eventually spilled
over the tops. Bushy vines of Baxter's Bush and Husky Red rose
neatly and slowly, like green cylinders, within their cages. Red
Robin looked ridiculous, a plant only 8 inches high by 8 inches
wide within a giant cage.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff to my hours of planning, planting and care began in
the middle of July, when the first fruits began to ripen _ on
Cheerio and Chello. The red Cheerio was tart, without any
counterbalancing sweetness, which the yellow Chello did have,
making it a bit better tasting.
</P>
<P>
   That first small wave of ripening was followed in a week or so
by subsequent waves.
</P>
<P>
   Whippersnapper lived up to its name, with insipid taste and
color, and Presto was tart but palatable. Finally, by mid-August,
all the plants were bearing well, and I could start comparing their
fruits. The differences were striking, in size, color and flavor.
And good flavor generally was not a pervasive quality. Most were
just plain acidic, lacking character, richness or sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   As I sampled, the phrase ``Tastes too much like a market or
salad bar cherry tomato'' kept running through my head, summing up
my benchmarks for bad cherry tomatoes. I later learned, in talking
with tomato breeders, that the leading commercial cherry tomato,
making up perhaps 75 percent of all sales, is Cherry Grande. It
looks pretty and ships well, but its mushy texture and acidic
flavor cause most tomato breeders to wince.
</P>
<P>
   A few plants bore delicious fruits. Most of the Sweet Million,
Sun Gold, Sun Cherry and Gardener's Delight fruits never reached
the kitchen. I could not resist the temptation to pop them into my
mouth as I harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed as late summer weather turned cool and moist. The
flavors of Red Cherry Large, Washington and Fox Cherry improved
somewhat from their summer mediocrity. By early fall, the Gold
Nugget, Sweet Million, Red Robin, Whippersnapper, Chello and Early
Cascade plants had collapsed, dead or nearly so, and most others
were yielding only occasional fruits. But Sun Gold and to a lesser
extent Sun Cherry kept ripening great-tasting fruits.
</P>
<P>
   By summer's end, I could hear Charles Dudley Warner's ghost
nagging me, asking whether I thought that my bevy of cherry tomato
plants was a waste of space. OK, yes. Although cherry tomatoes are
fun to eat, lovely to look at and easy to grow, 20 plants were too
many. And most were pretty bad-tasting.
</P>
<P>
   Which would I grow again? For a neat plant, hardly requiring
pruning, with dark green leaves well into fall, it would be Husky
Red, even with its average flavor. Presto was notable for its
productivity. My all-around favorite, though, was Sun Gold. It was
productive and disease-free well into fall, and its beautiful,
persimmon-orange fruits held superb flavor even if not picked
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   If you grow cherry tomatoes, plan on two or three plants a
person, and choose varieties with care. Only the best are worth
growing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
