<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLISH-AIR-TRAVEL-$A     03-26 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLISH-AIR-TRAVEL-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN FLYING TOURIST MEANT GOING IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people made fun of Sean Penn for his widely leaked letter
to 20th Century Fox complaining that the studio wouldn't give him a
private jet for a publicity trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you guys don't remember what the inside of a commercial
airline terminal looks like, but if you send me a picture of your
jets, I'll send you a picture of the door at the Red Carpet Room,''
he wrote, somewhat cryptically. Rather than accept the indignity of
a $2,000 first-class ticket, he canceled the trip. His ``cc'' list
at the bottom of the letter included Rupert Murdoch and ``God
Almighty.'' This from a guy who posed for Vanity Fair in front of
his trailer home.
</P>
<P>
   But he's got a point. There is no greater indignity than
commercial air travel. Multi-hour delays are imposed without
apology or extra peanuts. Flight attendants have all the charm of
hall monitors. The term ``jet set'' now means a matching sweat-suit
ensemble. I've seen more style-savvy passengers on the casino bus
to Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The plummeting dress code on your average 737 may sound like a
superficial gripe in the larger context of crippling pilot strikes
and $4 headsets. But I would argue that the relentless
unstylishness of the in-flight experience is the problem, from
barefoot passengers to the cabin crew's Salvation Army-drab
uniforms to the goats and chickens roaming around the back of the
plane. And Exhibit A is my most recent sartorial nightmare in the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Long story short: Settling into American Airlines flight 662
from San Juan, P.R., to Kennedy airport last week, my traveling
companion smells a smell euphemistically known as ``air sickness.''
Flight attendant says we're ``free to switch seats,'' except plane
is way overbooked. A couple of hours later, companion notices trace
of so-called air sickness on her coat.
</P>
<P>
   Further investigation reveals similarly soiled spot on cabin
wall, just below window seat. Deplaning at JFK, feel wet on leg,
look down, see and smell huge patches of aforementioned substance
on jeans and tennis bag. Bag was in overhead compartment. Complain
to supervisor at the gate. He apologizes, scrawls name and these
words on scrap of paper: ``Please honor cleaning voucher.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you've ever walked off an airplane covered in someone
else's vomit, you know that a cleaning voucher doesn't really cut
it in the compensation department. Maybe this sort of thing happens
all the time, but such appalling behavior didn't use to be
considered the minor inconvenience of a discount fare.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always a vile-high club. Anyone over 30 remembers when
flying was a first-class event, no matter how much the ticket cost.
Men wore jackets and ties. Women decked themselves out in fancy
frocks and and travel suits. Even children were cleaned up and
pressed into their Sunday best. Out of consideration for child-free
travelers, babies were deemed too young to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Craving proof that these halcyon days of civilized airborne
transport really existed, I've been poring over back issues of
Holiday, a defunct travel monthly published from 1946 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   I first came across it last year, while going through my
father's stuff after he died. He had saved an issue from 1965
because of its cover story on Spain, his native country. About a
month ago, I found another copy (also 1965) at a junk arcade in
Cold Spring, N.Y., with a piece by Bruce Jay Friedman (on this
crazy new music called rock-and-roll) and a dyspeptic Mordecai
Richler dispatch from the Catskills illustrated by Arnold Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday had an impressive stable of contributors _ John
Steinbeck, John O'Hara, Alfred Kazin, Kenneth Tynan _ and an
arrestingly modern look: huge color photographs and acres of white
space around the text. But just as eye-catching in the pages of
this oversize glossy are the ads. They are a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Peck and Marlene Dietrich endorse the ``divine'' Air
France. Pan Am stewardesses wear Pucci uniforms. In a joint
advertorial for American Airlines and American Tourister, shot on
location at Kennedy, razor-sharp Rat Pack types clutch glamorous
women in furs.
</P>
<P>
   These chic young ladies are invariably equipped with a
half-dozen pieces of matching luggage that put to shame the boring
black boxes their daughters now wheel around _ the carry-on
equivalent of sensible shoes. As in Holiday's full-page Technicolor
pitches for Cadillac, Chris-Craft and Martini &AMP; Rossi, Madison
Avenue offers up flying the friendly skies as one more piece of the
post-war good life.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the sexiest airline ads tell you how many
frequent-flier miles you get if you take the US Airways shuttle
before April 1. It's all about the miles now, a volume business
where service and style take a backseat, near the bathroom, the one
that always says ``Occupied.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone could afford to fly in those days _ just as not
everyone could afford a television set. Now, anyone can. Having
survived its slump, the airline industry is earning record profits.
Many carriers are squeezing their coach sections to make more room
for rich passengers or lap-topped ``road warriors'' with millions
of miles on their plutonium cards.
</P>
<P>
   A big deal is made out of the widening disparity between coach
and first. You know what the difference is? About 20 lousy inches
between seats, a mug for your bad coffee, and a choice of movies on
hand-held, unwatchably small screens.
</P>
<P>
   Far from becoming more classist, flying, like television, has
been democratized to the lowest common denominator. First and
business classes are coach with warm nuts _ filled with slovenly
adults and ill-mannered children. That's why Sean Penn, and anyone
in his tax bracket, has a horror of flying commercial.
</P>
<P>
   But flipping through Holiday's transporting pages, you have to
believe that if more passengers wore snappy mohair suits and mink
stoles to get on a plane, classless fliers would at least be less
frequent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
