<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STEAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN GETS INTO HOT WATER AT ISTANBUL STEAM BATH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Steam'' rejiggers the familiar story of urban ennui swept away
by emotional authenticity and revitalizing contact with a different
culture. In this case, it's a journey to Istanbul that snaps
Alessandro Gassman's Roman designer, Francesco, out of the
doldrums. He's prosperous but pressured. His marriage to Francesca
d'Aloja's Marta is in a jangly state, too. So when he gets word
that an aunt in Istanbul has died and left him a steam bath, he's
more than ready to take a break to go there and sell it.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrives, though, he's disarmed by the homey warmth of
the hospitable Turkish custodian and his family living in the
building. And he finds his resistance to selling stiffened when he
learns that the prospective buyer is grabbing up the whole
neighborhood and plans to displace its working-class _ which is to
say politically cloutless _ inhabitants. What really makes him want
to stay around, however, is his homoerotic attraction to the
family's languid young son, Mehmet, who leads him into the
otherwise-forbidden pleasures of the male-only baths, accompanied
by dervish music on the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   When Marta arrives to find out what's taking Francesco so long,
and also to tell him she's been having an affair with their
business partner and wants a divorce, she finds she likes the new
version of her husband, who presumbaly has been humanized by
finally getting his sexual preferences, so to speak, straight.
Essentially, it's a banal story made interesting by views of
Istanbul that leave the usual tourist sites and move into the
neighborhoods, and by Francesco's delving into his late aunt's
letter and diaries.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out she was a passionate and venturesome creature who
reveled in her own eroticism, and Francesco feels a kinship with
her. It makes the otherwise-standard angst of both Francesco and
Marta a shade more interesting and makes them seem marginally less
like characters cut from an old Antonioni movie. Halil Ergun and
Serif Sezer are very sympathetic as the parents of the Turkish
family that befriends Francesco. As the latter, Gassman, son of
Vittorio, shows us just enough to make us want to see what else he
can do. But as ``Steam'' goes its predictable way, we can't help
feeling that it's telling the wrong story, that of the nephew and
not the far more interesting dead aunt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
