</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDDA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPTH MISSING FROM BENING'S `HEDDA GABLER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the new Geffen Playhouse production of Henrik
Ibsen's ``Hedda Gabler,'' Annette Bening first appears before us
barefoot in a white nightgown, an ethereal, bewitching presence.
</P>
<P>
   It's night, and Bening's title character glides wordlessly
through her provincial Norwegian home, pausing before a full-length
portrait of her father, whose gray general's uniform makes him look
a bit like a Scandinavian Robert E. Lee. Before drifting off stage,
she stops before a looking glass to examine her own nocturnal
reflection, as if trying to fathom the spiritual kinship between
the rugged old warrior hanging in the hallway and the high-strung,
sexually explosive woman in the darkened mirror.
</P>
<P>
   This haunting prologue, not in Ibsen's original text, is by far
the most poetic and psychologically reverberant interlude in Dan
Sullivan's disappointingly tepid production of Ibsen's robust 1890
tragicomedy. Unfortunately, little that follows in the next 2{
hours comes near that level of dramatic invention or emotional
penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Bening herself, making a welcome return to live theater
after nearly a decade's absence, as mysteriously compelling as she
is in those first spectral moments. Like the production as a whole
_ at least, at Wednesday night's opening _ Bening's performance
feels tentative, more transparent than revealing, unsure of who
exactly that trapped, angry woman in the mirror is supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   And while Jon Robin Baitz's crisp, conversational new
translation gives Ibsen's words a lively contemporary ring, the
production tends to flatten out the play's repressive, 19th-century
dimensions, reducing the characters to humdrum middle-class
suburban neurotics. Like Riccardo Hernandez's set design, blockily
compressed by the Geffen proscenium, the production can't break
free of a constricted conceptual framework.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished and versatile stage actress before taking up
residence in Hollywood, Bening would seem a logical, even inspired
choice to portray Ibsen's doomed, defiant heroine. In films, she
has painted memorable closeups of femme fatales whose fierce
sensuality is equaled by their diamond-hard willpower, whose
ingenue charms are underpinned with lethal cunning.
</P>
<P>
   Similar traits are constantly jostling with each other in Hedda,
the smart, spoiled, headstrong general's daughter _ a 19th-century
army brat, if you will _ who somehow has ended up married to the
wonky academic George Tesman (Byron Jennings). House-bound in the
dull, sub-arctic outback, where she's almost literally dying of
ennui, Hedda has few amusements left save her father's old dueling
pistols, which she enjoys firing over the heads of unsuspecting
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   If she hadn't unwisely sought wealth, social position and a
man's privileges in her conventional marriage, Hedda still might be
keeping company with her old flame, the dashingly debauched Elert
Lovborg (a somewhat subdued Patrick O'Connell). But Lovborg, the
unreconstructed ladies' man, has been heating up a dangerous
liaison of his own with the married Thea Elvsted (Carolyn
McCormick), who has replaced Hedda as his intellectual comrade and
romantic sparring partner.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings' splendidly feeble turn as absent-minded professor
Tesman reminds us that ``Hedda Gabler'' is a comedy, albeit a
comedy that ends with two people dead of gunshot wounds. Few
playwrights have captured smothering domesticity better than the
author of ``A Doll's House,'' and it is on this level that
Sullivan's direction is at its most entertainingly assured.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bening's Hedda is seldom in sync with these rhythms. On
Wednesday the actress's line readings were stiff and dynamically
limited. Her physical mannerisms _ an arm cocked on one hip, her
body weight propped against a settee for support _ were
distracting, making this ordinarily lithesome performer appear
self-conscious, off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   The keen, skeptical intelligence Bening radiates makes it hard
for her to persuade us she really believes Hedda's dotty romantic
delusions about Lovborg being a Dionysiac rebel with ``vine leaves
in his hair.'' Although her performance grew stronger as the night
went on, Bening hasn't yet tapped into the specific nature of
Hedda's insult, the depth of her (partially self-inflicted)
lifelong wound.
</P>
<P>
   Of the strong ensemble, Paul Guilfoyle manages to make the
cynical, manipulative Judge Brack surprisingly funny and human, all
too human. McCormick, who was so effective opposite Frank Langella
in last season's Geffen production of Strindberg's ``The Father,''
is every bit as persuasive here as Hedda's saner romantic rival.
</P>
<P>
   There's a decent chance this production will deliver a much
bigger bang by the time it closes in April. With an actress of
Bening's skill calling the shots, you know there's a terrific
reservoir of firepower in there somewhere. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
