<SLUG> BC-MENDOCINO-WINES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDOCINO WINES: `OUR TIME HAS COME' 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  By MIKE GENIELLA   
 THE PRESS DEMOCRAT OF SANTA ROSA, CALIF.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPLAND, Calif. _ Flush with rising prices and growing
recognition for locally grown wine grapes, Mendocino County growers
are helping underwrite the county's first national promotional
campaign in a bid to garner the kind of attention usually paid to
Napa and Sonoma counties.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 17 wineries have signed up to participate with local
growers in the first ever ``Mendocino Bounty'' tasting outside of
California. It's scheduled for June 10 in Chicago, the first stop
on a planned three-year national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our time has come,'' said John Enquist, new executive director
of the Mendocino Winegrowers Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The national campaign is a collaborative effort of the local
wine industry and a new organization formed by the county's
tourist-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-year planning effort, and aided by a $275,000 grant
from the county Board of Supervisors, the Mendocino effort is seen
as an important step in securing national recognition for the local
wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   John Dickerson, president of Mendocino County Promotional
Alliance, said it may take three years before Mendocino wine and
tourism-related businesses see fruits of the national promotional
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all we have to do is look to Napa and Sonoma, which spend
millions and millions of dollars every year on promotion, to see
what it has meant to growers and the lodging industry there,'' said
Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson said national recognition of Mendocino's wine industry
is bound to help the overall county economy in the face of a
dwindling timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wine and tourist industries are helping replace the lost
jobs,'' said Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson and others see the possibility of even more local jobs
if the county wine industry can succeed in reversing the flow of
grapes to wineries outside Mendocino County. Currently, about 50
percent of the total grape tonnage grown in Mendocino is processed
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could cut that export to 25 percent, and produce more
wines locally, we'd create hundreds of new jobs here instead of in
neighboring counties,'' Dickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
