<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLERGY-WOMEN-FASHION-     03-26 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY-WOMEN-FASHION-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN OF WHICH CLOTH? TWEED? CASHMERE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28.)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before leading services at Central Synagogue in
Manhattan, Rabbi Jill Kreitman, 35, performs a few rituals: she
splashes on Spring Flower perfume by Creed, applies Stila lipstick
and slips on flats by Prada or Gucci. ``When you have to get up to
take out the Torah from the Holy Ark during services, you don't
want to be wobbly,'' Kreitman said. She also irons her hair,
because, she adds, the light on the pulpit ``tends to accentuate
the frizzies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Christine McSpadden, 35, a priest at St. Bartholomew's
Church on Park Avenue, reads Vogue, wears black and has three
piercings in one ear. She jazzes up the traditional Episcopal shirt
and collar with a bugle-beaded cardigan and a rhinestone barrette a
la Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always stood out in Connecticut,'' Ms. McSpadden said of her
home state, where she said priests who are women usually wore
clerical shirts with prim dirndl skirts and Shetland sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   Women who are spiritual leaders, one might imagine, would be too
preoccupied with crises of faith to concern themselves with crises
of fashion. But many of those who are rabbis and ministers are
careful not to overlook matters like nail polish, hem lengths, heel
heights and hair color. They do so at some risk.
</P>
<P>
   When Rabbi Mychal Springer, 33, director of pastoral care and
education at Beth Israel Medical Center, wore an above-the-knee
skirt to work one day, an Orthodox woman recoiled, lambasting her
in front of patients and staff members. ``You're not a rabbi _ your
skirt is too short!'' Springer recalled the woman as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Her reply today: ``So if my skirt was longer, I'd be a rabbi?''
</P>
<P>
   As more and more women have entered the clergy over the last
three decades, a question that leaders of age-old faiths never much
pondered is being asked every day: What will I wear?
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 500 rabbis nationwide who are women and the
Episcopal Church has 1,500 active priests who are women. The issue
of how to present themselves in public, to strike a balance between
decorum and worldliness, is an open-ended one. A clergywoman, many
say, can't look tarty, dowdy, girly or overly ``mannish.'' To break
through what Ms. McSpadden has called ``the stained-glass ceiling''
and rise in a denomination's hierarchy, even a woman's hairstyle
has to be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus wasn't big on style,'' said the Rev. Joanna Adams, 54,
senior pastor of Trinity Presbyterian Church in Atlanta, who has
her nails done every week, always in a pastel. ``But women in the
clergy live in the real world, and a part of who we are is how we
present ourselves. Appearance isn't everything, but at the same
time, loveliness is not a sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressing for services poses the least conflict. Both Christians
and Jews say they feel comfortable wearing the flowing unisex
liturgical robes that allow clergywomen to blend easily with the
men. The plain robes are traditionally worn with other ornate
vestments, which many women use as style statements. An embroidered
prayer shawl or lace? Yarmulkes in white crochet, plaid or gold?
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Berle Ingram, a United Methodist minister and a
doctoral candidate at Union Theological Seminary, said that some
clergywomen drape colorful stoles around their shoulders for a more
feminine effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Lent, the color that the ministry wears in their stoles is
purple,'' she said. ``With more and more women, I have noticed
there are a variety of shades of purple, lavender, gradations of
pink, and stoles with fuchsia highlights. It's a way of making
softer or bolder statements, and looking more individual. Men are
starting to do this, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Feminizing the traditional garb has its share of pitfalls. ``You
don't know how many times I've gotten lipstick on my tallis,'' said
Kreitman, referring to the Jewish prayer shawl. ``It must be so
hard for a woman priest not to get make-up on her collar.''
</P>
<P>
   How to dress off the pulpit is the real problem. ``The issue is
sexuality,'' Springer said. ``Clergy are not supposed to be sexual
beings. Clothing hints at a private sexuality, and that's very
threatening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5676 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLERGY-WOMEN-FASHION-     03-26 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY-WOMEN-FASHION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: very threatening.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women who are rabbis and ministers agree that they cannot look
like sexpots. As role models in their communities who are on duty
all the time, clergywomen cannot run from the gym to the post
office in a tank top and Lycra shorts. The challenge is to look
modern, yet modest.
</P>
<P>
   One misstep and their congregants can be brutal fashion critics.
``I received complaints that a female rabbi was wearing sandals,
and that another one, who was officiating at a wedding, wasn't
wearing stockings,'' said Rabbi Mordechai Liebling, 50, senior
consultant to the Jewish Reconstructionist Federation in
Philadelphia. ``People who are having trouble with women rabbis
will focus on another area to voice their complaints. A woman's
dress is the most socially acceptable way to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Even something so small as a belt can be seen as a problem. When
the Rev. Denise Haines, 59, an Episcopal priest, was being
interviewed as a candidate in an election for bishop 10 years ago,
she wore a black dress with a slight V-neck, allowing her to wear a
clerical shirt and collar underneath. The dress was cinched at the
waist with a narrow belt. Although the outfit was hardly
suggestive, it did reveal the contours of her figure. Ms. Haines
lost the election, and later got word that one of the reasons might
have been her dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``A male priest said to me, `Some of us were not comfortable
with what you wore,''' said Ms. Haines, who is now the director of
community education and outreach at the Healthcare Chaplaincy in
Manhattan. ``I had a dress with a waist, and you could see that I
have breasts. It's hard for people to get past that when they're
trying to rethink roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight sweaters are taboo, Ms. Ingram confirmed. ``Right now,
there is so much sensitivity to appropriate sexual behavior for the
clergy, and dress is a part of that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Provocative, no. Approachable, yes _ which often means being in
style synch with congregants. For Rabbi Sherre Zwelling, 30, a
rabbi at Sinai Temple, the synagogue in West Los Angeles favored by
Hollywood's rich and famous, that means wearing ensembles by
designers like Helmut Lang, Armani and Donna Karan. Clothes become
a point of connection with the congregants. ``A woman will talk to
me about my lipstick and makeup and then confide in me that her
husband abuses her,'' Zwelling said. ``A conversation might open
with a congregant asking me, `Did you get those shoes at Prada?'
and then move on to her telling me about her eating disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Each clergywoman draws her own line between what is appropriate
and what is over the top for a credible servant of God. ``You can't
wear the latest Versace,'' said Kreitman, who serves a well-to-do
Manhattan congregation. She opts for conservative Ralph Lauren
suits. ``Now that skirt lengths are longer and three-quarter
sleeves are in, we look like we've just walked out of the pages of
Vogue,'' she added, smoothing the highlighted bob she has cut and
colored at Bumble &AMP; Bumble.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, where tailored black is always in, clerical garb
can be inadvertently fashionable. Ms. McSpadden went to a party
recently where several young professionals asked her what she did
for a living. When she told them she was a priest, they were
surprised, despite the fact that she was wearing her black shirt
and collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought my clothes were some funky, East Village style,
like a Nehru jacket,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   People not used to seeing priests who are women often mistake
them for nuns. To prevent such errors, some women wear colored
clerical shirts cut for the female figure. But Canon Anne Richards,
48, of the Episcopal Diocese of New York and an assistant to the
bishop, says she sticks to the basic black and white look. ``Jesus
said, `Be like the lilies of the field' _ they don't care what they
wear,'' she remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the canon allows herself one style indulgence.
With her gray Barami suit, she wears purple buttons on her black
vest, to send a message that she is representing the bishop, who
wears purple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wear red,'' she said. ``It sends a Madison Avenue
message, a power suit message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
