<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, March 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Strong winds from the north gusted as high as 60 mph in the
canyons of southern California Friday as potent low pressure aloft
drifted southeast across the Gulf of California toward Mexico. On
Saturday, the lethargic low will head across Mexico toward the
lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms, some with heavy rains, will develop
across parts of south Texas as increasingly moist air from the Gulf
of Mexico is lifted by the approaching system. Lifting will also be
enhanced by the westward sloping terrain. As a result, rainfalls of
one inch or more are possible in some areas of southern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the sluggish low-pressure system that produced snow
in the mountains of North Carolina on Friday will continue to drift
northeast across the Middle Atlantic states. Rain will likely
spread from northeast North Carolina to parts of southern New
Jersey. Whether precipitation penetrates farther inland over the
northern Middle Atlantic states will depend on the somewhat erratic
path of the system. Nonetheless, patchy sleet or wet snow could mix
with rain over some inland locations.
</P>
<P>
   The recent warm spell across the northern Plains will ebb in the
wake of a cool front crossing the Dakotas. Showers will be rather
limited along and ahead of the front because much of the available
moisture will be intercepted by the showers and thunderstorms in
southern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Light to occasionally moderate rains and mountain snows will
speckle the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Brimming Back Bays
</P>
<P>
   Minor tidal flooding is possible Saturday in back bays and
inlets near the Delaware and New Jersey coasts. But any flooding
that occurs will not result from fierce ocean winds pushing water
rapidly onto land. Flooding could occur because moderate but
protracted onshore winds will prevent bays and inlets from draining
at times of low tide. Thus, with water almost brimming in a few
bays and inlets at low tide, rising tides could send water spilling
onto land. Protracted ocean winds will be maintained by high
pressure over the Great Lakes and a modest low moving slowly north
along the coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1751EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BRAKHAGE-BOS &LR;      03-26 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BRAKHAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY GIVE EXPERIMENTAL FILMMAKER HIS DUE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stan Brakhage's filmmaking began during America's great postwar
age of artistic experimentation that gave us John Cage, Allen
Ginsberg, Ornette Coleman, and a host of other American mavericks.
Of them all, Brakhage is still working, wearing lightly his laurels
as America's patriarch of experimental cinema. Not well known to
the public, he cuts a wide swath through academic circles and among
avant-garde filmmakers. He still shows up at festivals, bearded,
strong-profiled, wearing his trademark wide-brimmed hat and
photographer's vest, the kind that looks like a safari jacket with
sleeves cut off and a lot of pockets stuffed with rolls of film and
other gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brakhage,'' Jim Shedden's documentary overview of Brakhage and
his work, is a useful and long-overdue introduction that should
gain Brakhage the wider appreciation he has earned as a major
influence on the aesthetics of cinema. It didn't take him long to
align with such predecessors as Maya Deren and Kenneth Anger as a
filmer of psychodramas. They began with figurative images
transformed into inward-looking abstractions. Later, he moved
toward more primal shapes and colors and rhythms, keyed to the way
the eye and mind perceive. In going abstract, he founded, in the
words of one of his collaborators, Phil Solomon, a radical poetics.
Yet his films always remained personal.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them dealt with the Colorado mountains where he lived.
Many featured his first wife, Jane, and their five children. Later,
one of his grown children comments that far from minding that he
was photographed, he liked it because it was one of the few times
he could count on his father's attention. One of the most
entrancing of Brakhage's more than 300 short films (and a few long
ones) is of his two young daughters in yellow skirts and red
patterened blouses running through a grassy yard, hypnotic in the
play of rhythms involving color and motion. His first controversial
film was ``Window Water Baby Moving'' . It depicted his wife's
natural childbirth and annoyed Deren, who said he should not so
freely have revealed women's secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But Jane says she loved having babies and that the film offered
more information on childbirth than any other film had. Many years
later, Brakhage's second wife, Marilyn, lifted a great weight from
his shoulders, Brakhage says, when she refused to be photographed.
But, in the one soundbite she permits Shedden, she sheds light on
her husband's oeuvre, observing that he extended the Abstract
Expressionist movement by adding light and movement to it. This
became unmistakably apparent in his ``Prelude: Dog Star Man'' of
1961, in which he emblazoned across the screen a personalized
cosmology combining abstract color applications, distorted
naturalistic images of trees, and a new plasticity that involved
altering the film stock itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, his populist imperative of filming on 8mm in order
to raise the level of home movies to art did little to increase
awareness of his work, especially when the camcorder crowded 8mm
out of the picture and Brakhage refused to switch to video. He
persevered, producing a succession of works ranging from ``Song 7''
of 1964, a lyrical evocation of San Francisco, to ``The Art of
Seeing with One's Own Eyes'' (1971), focusing on an autopsy in a
Pittsburgh morgue. The last, he says, was his way of coming to
grips with the Vietnam War. As the black in his hair and beard
turns to gray, he weathers several more crises, including becoming
spooked enough by the mountains to move to the lower and more
benign elevation of Boulder, then surviving an eye operation.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Brakhage becomes more patriarchal, more at ease
in the company of adoring acolytes and collaborators, more at ease
with himself. He gave up hand-painting his films when he suspected
the chemicals in the paints gave him bladder cancer, which he
survived. From that point on, he has simply scratched designs with
etching tools directly onto film leader. Indeed, some of his later
abstract films seem little different from scratched-up leaders that
flash on-screen before films begin. In the end, Brakhage pokes fun
of the process of making pronouncements during interviews. He
doesn't know why he keeps making films, he says, except that he's
compulsively drawn to it, and that it is, in any case, a mystery.
Fair enough. And this documentary, which mimics Brakhage's rhythms,
images, and exposure schemes, is more than fair enough. It's good
to have around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
