<HEADER>
A5688 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARLEM-RENAISSANCE-II     03-26 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-RENAISSANCE-II-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEM AFTER DARK IS COOKING AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28)  
 (af)  
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once, clusters of dapper night owls would zigzag down
the broad, limestone-lined avenues of Harlem, from jazz joint to
rent party to cabaret. In 1929, during the Harlem Renaissance,
Variety reported: ``When it comes to pep, pulchritude, punch and
presentation, the Harlem places have Broadway's nightclubs
distanced. Celebrities in all walks of life `make' the Harlem
joints every night. You'll likely see a Lady Mountbatten on the
ringside of the Cotton Club, a David Belasco at another and a
diplomat in the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who live in the 50 or so blocks above Central Park like to
term what's happening in the area today Harlem's Second
Renaissance, with the return of black professionals, new
businesses, increased tourism and a rebirth of night life. While
the term may be strained, it is not far from the truth. Economic
development, historical preservation and plummeting crime rates in
the area have contributed to a kind of boom.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Harlem's clubs, restaurants and bars now is like
watching a small bud begin to bloom. In a few years, said Berta
Alloway, a music promoter for some of the night spots, Harlem may
come to resemble its old self again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are moving back to Harlem, and they have
money, and they'd rather spend it here,'' she said. ``There's money
coming back up here, and people are coming back out to the clubs
also. They're coming from all over. A lot of Caucasian people are
coming back uptown, and they're not afraid to hang around. I look
around at night and say, `Didn't the tour bus leave?' and they say,
`We're not going anywhere.'''
</P>
<P>
   Al Howard, one of the two owners of Showmans, since 1942 a
staple of Harlem night life, which moved to a new address on 125th
Street in August, said that more than half of his clientele on any
given night are from out of town or from Manhattan below 110th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do get a lot of trade from downtown, a lot more than people
realize,'' he said. ``Once people come here, they see how safe it
is, they come back, and they tell their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, there has been a 77 percent decrease in
homicides in the area surrounding the 28th Precinct in central
Harlem, according to the Police Department. (The citywide murder
rate has decreased 67 percent in the same period.)
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem scene today is part nostalgia, part novelty. Some of
the recognizable places, like the Apollo Theater, the Cotton Club
and even the famous Sylvia's Restaurant, maintain a steady tourist
trade but don't attract local residents in the same numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Other traditional joints, like Showmans, the Lenox Lounge,
Perk's Fine Cuisine and St. Nick's Pub, have found ways to maintain
their popularity through new events, like a gay night at the Lenox
Lounge; with theme evenings, like jazz, rhythm and blues and
calypso at Perk's every Thursday, or by sheer force of will.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, new clubs and cafes like the Sugar Shack, Miss
Mamie's Spoonbread Too, Emily's Restaurant and Bar, Londel's Supper
Club, Cafe Largo, the Gishen Cafe and the Audubon Bar and Grill,
are luring a different crowd, with tap dancing, open-mike poetry
nights, even comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tremendous opportunity up here right now,'' said Marc
Calcano, who opened Cafe Largo on Broadway near 137th Street last
June and just began presenting live jazz on Sunday and Monday
nights. ``The volume of traffic here now is tremendous. Harlem was
vacant for a very long time, and it's about half filled now, and I
believe that in the next two to three years, tops, it's going to be
filled to capacity again.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone is convinced of the inevitability of
Harlem's comeback. A few years ago, Robert De Niro and his
restaurateur partner, Drew Nieporent, announced plans to reopen
Minton's Playhouse, a legendary jazz hall known as the birthplace
of bebop, by late 1997. But today, there is no Minton's. The
project has stalled, Nieporent said, because investors are wary of
signing on to this $3.1 million project.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Minton's, there is no lack of excitement at clubs
operating now. At 2:30 a.m. on a recent Monday, while the musicians
at St. Nick's Pub were gearing up for another set, Ms. Alloway,
dressed in leopard-skin eyeglass frames, a floppy black hat and a
leopard-skin velvet shirt, surveyed the boisterous and packed room,
where the cabaret tables were piled high with full ashtrays, empty
beer bottles and plates of oxtail stew. ``No one should have to
work on Tuesdays,'' she said, pitying those who had to get up in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Harlem's night life begins, like the workweek, on Monday. At
around 8 p.m., those with a taste for gumbo, banana pudding and
Diana Ross gather at Miss Mamie's Spoonbread Too, a restaurant
sprung from a well-known catering company. The decor is a cross
between the Southern kitchen and pop art, with a bold red and
yellow checkered floor and 1950s-style kitchen tables. In front of
the large windows, a pianist playing a small upright leads the
crowd in a sing-along or allows poets to share their craft.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, a more sophisticated crowd is settling in
at Wells Famous Home of Chicken and Waffles, where the 16-piece
Harlem Renaissance Swing Band packs into the main dining room. The
house specialty is fried chicken and waffles, once an after-hours
breakfast treat, now a main course on the evening menu. Dancers
from the New York Swing Society, led by Frank Manning, occupy the
front table and take the floor by turns.
</P>
<P>
   The long tables where everyone sits together are packed with
white and black groups, small clusters of tourists from Japan or
France, as well as an occasional celebrity just off a film shoot.
The dress code ranges from tube tops to floor-length furs, but
within an hour, when the food and drinks start flowing, everyone is
talking to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The dancing picks up around 11:30, when the novice swing dancers
are lubricated enough to brave the floor next to the professionals
and old-timers. But by then, it's time to move on to St. Nick's Pub
on St. Nicholas Avenue and 149th Street, where you can still snag
an empty table before the jam session starts to bubble.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At St. Nick's, a narrow dive a few steps down from the street,
free jazz, accompanied at times by singers and occasional tap
dancers, begins at 11 p.m. and goes on until 3 a.m., and many
notable musicians _ Stevie Wonder, Etta Jones and James Carter
among them _ have been known to drop in for a round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The musicians that play downtown and play abroad, they don't
play our club for the money,'' said Ms. Alloway, who also goes by
the professional name Berta Indeed. ``But they come up because it's
like home. They'll come up and sit in with us.''
</P>
<P>
   By 3 a.m., part of the audience from St. Nick's or Wells has
arrived at the counter at M &AMP; G Diner, 383 West 125th Street, which
advertises itself in hot pink neon as ``Old Fashion' but Good.''
The R-and-B jukebox pumps out Billie Holiday or the Spinners, and a
pat of bright yellow butter shimmers in a plate of grits like the
rising sun.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Tuesday night, which is gay night at the Lenox
Lounge, beginning around midnight. ``You take a nap when you get
home, and you take another nap after you get home from work,'' one
patron, a Brooklynite, 36, explained. He was seated on the
crescent-shaped red leather couches that line the Art Deco bar.
</P>
<P>
   The Lenox Lounge has been a neighborhood mainstay since it was
opened at Harlem's hub, Lenox Avenue and 125th Street, in 1942. But
two years ago, a young promoter calling himself Cris Is Bliss put
together gay night, with live deejays spinning funk and hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   The steamy Zebra Room fills up by 12:30, and sleek black bodies
pack the dance floor until about 4. The lounge is the only club
open to the public that caters to gay men (Emily's has a ladies
night for women), although up to 15 years ago, Harlem had a handful
of gay clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've known about a place like this
in Harlem,'' said the Brooklynite, who did not want to be
identified, adding that as the quality of services improves in the
neighborhood, he expects to see more such places. ``There's better
policing, and there are more companies like Duane Reade up here,
and people feel more comfortable getting off the train and walking
around.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesdays, the Sugar Shack offers an open-mike poetry slam,
where performers in dreadlocks or with shaved heads recite verses
or read raplike meditations to drumbeats, keyboard and flutes.
Odell Holland Fincher, 27, who opened the club in January 1998,
hoped to create a blend of uptown and downtown that was ``spiritual
to a certain extent, but not overbearing,'' he said, adding, ``I
wanted it to be homey, so people could come and feel they were
sitting in their grandmother's living room.''
</P>
<P>
   The large, open, Southern-style kitchen, which prominently
displays boxes of Quaker Oatmeal, serves up candied yams, smothered
chicken and hearty soup. The rest of the club is clearly inspired
by a SoHo look, except for the kente cloth tacked on a couple of
walls.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, the Audubon Bar and Grill, which opened in
1996, lures people uptown to a comedy night, with Angelo Lozada as
host. The roundup presents comedians who have performed on HBO,
Comedy Central and late-night television shows, including Greer
Barnes, Eric Nieves and Patrice O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The large, brightly lighted club serves chicharones, yuca fries,
chicken wings and other bar food, as well as mixed drinks for $3,
but warns ``no hoodies, no hats and no sneakers,'' if you want to
get in.
</P>
<P>
   Thursdays might find a night owl at Perk's, a narrow bar joined
to an equally narrow white-table-cloth restaurant, where a jazz,
rhythm and blues and calypso band performs so close to the front
entrance that it is hard to get in or out. Thursday is also a good
night at Showmans, where tap dancers and jazz musicians perform for
an older crowd dressed in three-piece suits and fedoras.
</P>
<P>
   LeRoy Myels, a former tap dancer, who has spent evenings at
Showmans, on stage and off, since 1942, said he is pleased to see a
new generation venturing to Harlem clubs. In 1949, he said,
Showmans was the unofficial meeting place of the Copacetics tap
dance group. Today, it attracts dancers from the recently closed
long-running Broadway musical ``Bring In da Noise, Bring In da
Funk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids now are a little different, but the tap is still the
same,'' Myels said. ``The crowd has definitely increased since they
moved.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend picks up, with live jazz and blues or deejays
spinning dance mixes at almost every spot, including St. Nick's,
Showmans, Perk's, the Lenox Lounge, Wells, the Cotton Club, the
elegant but spare Londel's Supper Club and a new Ethiopian
restaurant, the Gishen Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the action grinds to a halt. But then, on Monday, it
starts all over again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
