<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5706 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AERIN-LAUDER-PROFILE-     03-26 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AERIN-LAUDER-PROFILE-ART-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AERIN LAUDER, THE GIRL MOST INVITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release Sunday, March 28)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At age 4, Aerin Lauder liked to play dress-up. In a
photograph from that period snapped at the Palm Beach, Fla., house
of her grandmother, the cosmetics empress Estee Lauder, Aerin wears
Mrs. Lauder's straw hat and gold sandals. One arm, saucily perched
on her hip, is sheathed to the elbow in a white satin glove.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a trace of that self-consciously coquettish little
girl the other night, when Ms. Lauder swept into Christie's for a
cocktail party and preview of past Academy Awards fashions to be
auctioned for the benefit of AIDS research. In a room already
blazing with such legendary lights as Pauline Trigere and Lauren
Bacall, Ms. Lauder glowed, serene as a duchess as photographers
swarmed around her like ants on jam.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauder, 28, is that rarest of Park Avenue princesses: a
hyperactive member of junior society by night, and by day, a
working woman who is being groomed for the executive suite of one
of the country's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty, well-mannered and mannequin-tall, the third generation
Lauder is The Girl Most Invited. There she is photographed in Vogue
wearing Oscar de la Renta at a garden party; there, in Women's Wear
Daily, at a dinner at Chow to honor her friend, the designer
Michael Kors. The fashion press, in particular, seems intent on
anointing Ms. Lauder the Upper East Side equivalent of Hollywood
royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society reporters are looking for a young star,'' said Kevin
West, a senior editor at W, who recorded the doings of the gilded
set in his former job on the magazine's Eye page. ``Which of us
isn't drawn to the glamor of taste, wealth and social prominence?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauder is a fixture in a constellation of Young
Establishment stars, the daughters of moneyed and prominent New
Yorkers, many of whom know each other from private schools or
Locust Valley and have found careers in fashion and style fields.
They share uptown aspirations, presiding over high-profile
fund-raisers, and dressing in the hip and luxurious, but
understated, style of their favorite designers: Bill Blass, Michael
Kors, Marc Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Among this pack are Serena Boardman, who works at Sotheby's, and
her sister Samantha, a medical student; Brooke de Ocampo, a former
Vogue editor; Eliza Reed, who works for her stepfather, Oscar de La
Renta, and of course, the ``Miller girls'' _ the sisters Pia Miller
Getty, Alexandra Von Furstenberg and Princess Marie-Chantal of
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Ms. Lauder, who is fronting for her family as she
ascends in junior society, mixing business with pleasure. She
accepts invitations to four or five functions a week, and will tell
you in a heartbeat that she loves to dress up, to go out ``and see
the dresses, see my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   All the intensive partying is part of a strenuous public
performance. ``Now that Mrs. Estee Lauder is getting older,''
Leonard A. Lauder, Aerin's uncle and the chairman and chief
executive of the Estee Lauder Companies, said, ``it's very
important that there be a Lauder who is socially active.'' Ms.
Lauder is the eyes and ears of the company. When she drops in at
glittering affairs, ``she helps us gain an understanding of a very
important segment of the market,'' Lauder said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauder has been mentioned as a possible co-chairwoman of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art's Costume Institute gala in December _ a
social pinnacle that has been occupied by Pat Buckley and
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, but never by a 20-something. The name
being linked with hers as co-chairman is Tommy Hilfiger. His
company would be the primary underwriter of the evening, which the
Met calls the party of the year. Because the Lauder companies are
the licensee for Hilfiger's Tommy fragrances, it would be a match
made in not only society columns, but also boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauder, like her younger sister, Jane, 25, and her cousin
William, 38, is being groomed to take a leadership position in the
$3.4 billion Lauder cosmetics empire, which though publicly owned
is still very much a family operation. (Aerin and Jane's father,
Ronald S. Lauder, is chairman of Clinique Laboratories and Estee
Lauder International.)
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers have speculated that Ms. Lauder eventually
will head her own brand within the company _ a notion that Dan
Brestle, Ms. Lauder's boss and the president of Estee Lauder Inc.,
dismisses. But he does envision Ms. Lauder heading a company
division. ``Developing her career though the creative and marketing
side will give her the credibility to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Ms. Lauder is director of creative product
development for the Lauder brand in the United States and Canada.
She creates the palette for lipsticks and other makeup, colors that
beckon at store counters with titillating names like Exotic, Nude
and Wild. In the last year, she has played an increasingly
influential role in the company's advertising campaigns, weighing
in on decisions from the choice of stylists and photographers to
the mood and ambiance of each image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hers is not a job on the outskirts of the company,'' said Alan
Mottus, publisher of The Informationist, a beauty trade monthly.
``She's a gladiator _ she's in the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   She certainly works with a gladiator's zeal. Within a day of
returning from a trend-spotting mission in Paris and Milan, she sat
in the Lauder conference room in the General Motors building on
Fifth Avenue, briefing her art and copy teams on the lacquered
eyes, bedroom hair and knee-high boots she had spied on Europe's
runways.
</P>
<P>
   The following day would send her speeding from a cluster of
in-house meetings to taping with the Arts and Entertainment
Network, which was filming a biography of her grandmother. The
former Josephine Esther Mentzer of Corona, Queens, founded her
empire on grit and a genius for spreading to the masses the gospel
of glamour-through-artifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved beauty and she was incredibly feminine,'' said Ms.
Lauder, who has inherited not only Estee's taste for cut flowers,
good shoes and luxurious fragrance, but also an instinct for
divining trends.
</P>
<P>
   Not least of Ms. Lauder's activities that day would be a trip to
the obstetrician for a routine checkup. Ms. Lauder, whose husband,
Eric Zinterhofer, works for a private equity firm, is six months
pregnant, but never mind. She sprints between engagements on a pair
of spindly snakeskin heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to give up my jeans, but you won't get me out of my
Manolos,'' Ms. Lauder joked.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks nothing of mixing a demure lilac cardigan with racily
streamlined Prada pants, and she dreams of the days when she'll be
trim enough again to snake into Gucci's new lace-up-the sides
leather pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are women less confident who will dress in one designer
from head to toe,'' said Anna Wintour, Vogue's editor in chief,
whose party pages regularly feature Ms. Lauder and her Manhattan
set. ``But Aerin makes her own look. She never lets the clothes
wear her.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That unerring instinct also tells Ms. Lauder what shade of
mulberry lip stain her contemporaries will want to wear next fall _
an intuitive flair that sets her apart from her more cerebral
sister, Jane, marketing manager for the Clinique brand, and cousin
William, who is president of Clinique.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauder's office looks like a fashion editor's lair. Guests
sit in pink imitation Eames chairs within yards of a bulletin board
paved with pictures and fabric swatches that conjure up winter
scenes. ``For fall we're seeing a cool neutral palette,'' she
pronounced, with an editor's penchant for spinning out forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   But in a business whose lead times are far longer than most
magazines, Ms. Lauder has to functions like a medium, channeling
style signals six months to a year before they appear on the
runways. ``I'm so ahead, it's scary,'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   She draws her leads from a crazy quilt of sources _ travel
features, museum shows, yarn samples, jelly beans. Jelly beans? Why
not? Ms. Lauder learned from Dominque Szabo, the company's color
guru, that nothing is too lowly or farfetched to inspire next
season's hues.
</P>
<P>
   During the post-Milan briefing with the company's senior art
director, Jason Phillips, and a brace of copywriters, Ms. Lauder
issued directives with a blend of firmness and tact. Phillips
informed her that the marketing department planned to emphasize
lips and nails in the fall ads, but she wasn't having it. ``The
eyes were so important in Europe,'' she said. ``We have to focus on
that. We have six different mascaras. Now is a good time to push
them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the conference table, a poster-size photograph of Elizabeth
Hurley, the company's ``face,'' features the actress swathed in a
blanket and not much else. The image is a provocative departure
from traditional Lauder campaigns, which have tended to feature
models engaged in wholesome activities like fly-fishing. ``Aerin
has a cutting edge,'' Brestle, her boss, said. ``She's pushing the
envelope and positioning us in a place that historically we never
have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Her provocativeness is the result of an upbringing that took her
from Vienna, where her father was ambassador to Austria in the
mid-1980s, to a precocious adolescence in Manhattan. ``Since high
school I've been in leather and high boots,'' Ms. Lauder said. ``In
New York you grow up very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashion and society columnist Billy Norwich described her
set as mingling traditional backgrounds with a liberal experience _
open classrooms and the like. ``We're not looking at a generation
of rebels,'' he said. ``These women aren't rejecting the parents'
values; they're interpreting them in their own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauder shares her family's bred-in-the bone propriety almost
to a fault. ``I lose it when people are arrogant,'' she said. She
used to frequent Harry Cipriani, midtown headquarters for society
divas and fashion wags. But no longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there one day, and a woman was pregnant,'' she said.
``They had a table, but they ignored her. That's so obnoxious _ you
can quote me on that.''
</P>
<P>
   She returns phone calls, shows up for appointments on time and
guards her privacy. ``I would never let anyone photograph my
home,'' she said. She's also loath to have her husband interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep things separate,'' she said. ``I want him to have his
own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwich said, ``Her set is loyal.'' So constant in fact, that
not one of her friends will utter an indiscreet word about her.
Intimates tend to describe her in terms of attributes she lacks:
unassuming, unpretentious, nonthreatening. Socially, she is as
well-defended as a fortress, a testament perhaps to the formidable
power of the Lauder name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aerin has no attitude,'' Ms. de Ocampo said.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Mr. Norwich observed, ``In Manhattan you can be a duchess
if you're courteous for just one day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
