<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN THE NEWEST, AND SMALLEST, NATO ALLIES STAND TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Iceland has no military. Luxembourg has no air
force. Greece doesn't want to bomb a neighbor. And the three other
nations not contributing forces to the NATO air war against Serbia
have only been alliance members for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But those six countries, including the new members _ Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic _ bridle at the suggestion that they
are not full partners in the allied attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Greece is doing,'' said Alexander Philon, the Greek
ambassador to the United States, ``and what we decided a long time
ago to do with the full agreement of NATO, is to open all of our
ports, roads and airfields to the mission but not get involved
directly in the actual bombing of our neighbor. We are going to
live in the future with those countries, and we don't want
resentments.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without an air force, Luxembourg has contributed by giving
money to the Belgian Air Force and registering the only planes
common to all NATO members, the AWACS reconnaissance planes, under
the Luxembourg flag. ``We wanted to make the point of our
solidarity with the mission,'' said Carlo J. Krieger, deputy chief
of the Luxembourg Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airspace _ we're providing airspace,'' said Andreas Simonyi,
the Hungarian Ambassador to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hungarian parliament also voted to provide airfields and
bases as well as airspace should NATO countries need them in their
attack on Hungary's southern neighbor. ``That is a very very strong
statement on our behalf, taking into account we are a neighboring
country,'' Simonyi said.
</P>
<P>
   Poland, once one of the major military powers in the Eastern
bloc, went further and offered combat troops should the operation
require them, said Jaroslaw Kurek, the press officer at the Polish
Embassy. ``We have no active combat role now but we are ready to
take part in any ground operation if that is necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he added, a Polish military brigade is guarding
the American who directs the Kosovo Verification Mission, the
unarmed group of monitors who had tried to keep warring Serbs and
ethnic Albanians apart.
</P>
<P>
   The decision for Iceland was simple. ``We have no military, so
we are not involved,'' said Jon Hannibalsson, the ambassador in
Washington. But Iceland has provided a naval base to NATO since
1951.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
