<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARIUCCI-IZZO-NYTR &LR;      03-26 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIUCCI-IZZO-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST FRIENDS IZZO AND MARIUCCI MAKE IRON MOUNTAIN PROUD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LOWELL COHN   
 The (Santa Rosa, Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you may know by now, Steve Mariucci, coach of the San
Francisco 49ers, and Tom Izzo, coach of Final Four entry Michigan
State, grew up together in Iron Mountain, Mich. They were boyhood
friends, although they attended different grammar schools as little
kids. Izzo went to a public school called Central, Mariucci
attended Immaculate Conception. They rode the same school bus,
which Mariucci named the Immaculate Contraption.
</P>
<P>
   When they were teenagers, they both attended Iron Mountain High
School. They were co-captains of the basketball and football teams
as seniors. Mariucci was the quarterback, Izzo the running back.
Izzo was the point guard, Mariucci the shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   They also competed together in the mile relay. ``I always handed
the baton to him with a big lead and he'd usually lose it,''
Mariucci said the other day on a conference call he'd arranged to
talk about his pal.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene about the wall beats everything. In their senior
year at Iron Mountain High, Mariucci and Izzo decided to do
something about the 10-foot-high reinforced concrete wall that runs
around the football stadium. A definite eyesore, it looked like the
leaden gray walls that encircle a penitentiary. They dedicated
their entire summer to painting it on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   There they'd be working, and Izzo's dad, Carl (always called
Carlie), would drive by several times a day to bring the boys Cokes
and to chat. That's how proud he was of them. They painted the wall
black and gold, Iron Mountain High's colors, and when they were
done, they climbed on top of the bleachers and stenciled upon a
20-foot-high background, HOME OF THE MOUNTAINEERS.
</P>
<P>
   That story is such a bit of Americana _ two innocent, devoted,
dedicated boys doing something for their town, population 8,500. It
smacks of malt shops and scuffed Keds and Norman Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the story doesn't end there. Mariucci and Izzo went
off to college together, to Northern Michigan to be precise.
Naturally, they roomed together all four years. According to
Mariucci's dad Ray, Izzo became ``part of the family.'' After that,
when they were young coaches, they shared a house together. That
makes seven years in a row they were roommates. Hey, not even
Koufax and Drysdale were that close.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Ray Mariucci would want to know what was going on with
his son, but he could never ask Steve, because his kid would say
everything was swell no matter what. So Ray went to Tom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would confide in Tom to see how Steve felt and to get an
in-depth answer,'' Ray told me the other day. ``He was gracious
enough to tell me the truth. I admired Tom for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci and Izzo were best men at the other guy's wedding.
Except one time there was a bit of a hitch. Just before Mariucci
got married, Izzo shattered his jaw in a softball game. So he flew
to Mariucci's wedding with his mouth wired, and when it came time
to deliver the toast, he sort of mumbled, and frankly, no one could
hear a word he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Iron Mountain that story has become part of the Iz/Mooch
lore. Also part of the lore is this year's NCAA Tournament.
Mariucci flew to St. Louis to watch Izzo's team beat Oklahoma in
the Midwest Regionals. At the game, he held the hand of Izzo's
wife, Lupe. ``She was really nervous,'' Mariucci said. ``Maybe she
was holding my hand. I was really nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mariucci watched film of Kentucky with Izzo and his
assistants until three in the morning. ``I kept telling them to
blitz and they kept telling me to shut up,'' Mariucci said. He
returned to the Bay Area early the next morning for 49er meetings,
but watched Michigan State beat Kentucky on television. He booked a
redeye to the Final Four Friday night in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   On the conference call, Mariucci tried to define his friendship
with Izzo. ``We went through everything together,'' he said.
``Everything as a kid, adolescent, young adult and marriage. We
know each other's secrets. He's as honest a person as you're ever
going to find. I sound like I have a biased opinion of my best
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   That's OK, Steve. It's allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci also gave his impression of Izzo as a coach: ``He's got
a football coaching demeanor. He could very well coach football at
any level. If you go by the old cliche that a team takes on the
personality of its coach, you'll see that in his kids. They're a
very physical team. They play fast and they play hard, and they're
diving for balls, knocking guys out, getting concussions. It's like
Big Ten football.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Izzo and Mariucci are still painting the wall. Last
year, they inaugurated the Izzo-Mariucci Golf Classic to raise
money for sports facilities at Iron Mountain High. They've already
put together $75,000 for new bleachers. They're also funding a new
sports complex at Northern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, they happened to be in town visiting their
families at the same time. The local newspaper ran a photo of them
together, accompanied by an article. What was the theme of the
article? They're here. Period. In Iron Mountain the hereness of
Izzo and Mariucci was big news.
</P>
<P>
   So you get the picture. The two pals are famous now, but they
haven't outgrown the town or each other.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
