<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ASTHMA DRUG GETS OK FROM FDA, COMPANY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sepracor Inc., a biotechnology company based in Marlborough,
Mass., said Friday that it had received approval from the Food and
Drug Administration to begin marketing a new inhalable drug named
Xopenex for the treatment of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor shares fell $6.6875 to $111.5625 Friday in Nasdaq
trading. Analysts said the approval was anticipated, and that
Sepracor shares were subject to profit-taking after rocketing from
$36.25 to $140.87 in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's approval coming after the company's $90 million
agreement to produce an improved version of Prozac for Eli Lilly &AMP;
Co. in December, the value of Sepracor's strategy is clear, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The generic name for Xopenex is levalbuterol, which the company
says is an improved version of albuterol, the world's leading
asthma treatment, which works by dilating the bronchial tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Albuterol, sold under the trade name Ventolin by Glaxo Wellcome,
and in various generics, will remain on the market as well. It had
estimated worldwide sales of $1.2 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a validation that the FDA can give marketing approval to
an improved chemical version when the original drug remains on the
market,'' said Sergio Traversa, an analyst with Mehta Partners. He
forecast Xopenex sales of about $25 million in its first year,
peaking at $150 million. ``It will never be a blockbuster for
Sepracor, but it's a validation of their strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first approved usage for Xopenex will be for the relief and
prevention of bronchial spasms. The drug will be available in a
solution to be used in a machine called a nebulizer. This is an
electric air compressor with a mouthpiece through which a patient
inhales vaporized asthma medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the prevalence of asthma, especially in children, on the
rise, there is a great need for rescue therapy with minimal side
effects,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Drazen, a professor at Harvard Medical
School. ``Levalbuterol is the first real advance in rescue asthma
therapy in over 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor has indicated that it will price Xopenex comparably to
Glaxo's Ventolin, which sells for about $1.75 a dose; the generics
typically sell for $1.25 a dose. However, patients are expected to
use just three doses of Xopenex a day, compared with four for the
older drug, Traversa said.
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor, founded in 1984, developed a technology to exploit the
century-old discovery that most chemicals are formed in
mirror-image pairs. For most drugs, only one side of the pair,
called an isomer, is active, while the reverse-image side may cause
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   By isolating the active isomer of albuterol, and eliminating the
inactive mirror-image isomer, Sepracor claims to have produced a
more effective drug, with fewer side effects. Sepracor patented the
isomeric forms of many major drugs before their manufacturers
devised ways to copy its technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
