</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATESMANLIKE SCHROEDER PULLS HARMONY FROM EUROPE'S HAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Showing a statesmanship that had seemed to elude him,
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder guided the European Union early Friday
to a landmark agreement to hold down its spending enough to enable
three Central European countries to join.
</P>
<P>
   The union also advocated Palestinian statehood within the next
year in more forthright terms than it had previously used or than
the United States has ever backed, provoking a furious reaction
from Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Through a long night, and despite the overwhelming distraction
of Kosovo, Schroeder cajoled leaders of the 15-member bloc to agree
to the so-called Agenda 2000 reforms, which will cap the group's
budget at $92 billion a year through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   By then Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary should already be
members. Strong growth in the budget could have made membership
difficult for the three formerly Communist countries to afford.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, long the unstable center of a volatile continent, has a
deep commitment to surrounding itself with allies that are in both
NATO and the European Union. Schroeder, whose first six months in
office have been stormy and who has sometimes given an appearance
of frivolity, Friday made himself the voice of this vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not win the lottery by gaining any reduction in German
payments,'' said Schroeder, who presided over the meeting. ``But in
order to make compromises, we had to take into consideration all
countries. What has come out of our negotiations is an agenda that
reflects a truly unified Europe, and therefore the meeting was a
success.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first months in office, Schroeder vigorously demanded
that Germany's net annual contribution of about $12 billion be cut,
saying his country was paying most for European ``waste.'' The
statement recalled some of Margaret Thatcher's in the 1980s and
suggested to some that Germany's commitment to the consolidation
and extension of the European Union was waning.
</P>
<P>
   But reversing course Friday, Schroeder accepted a reform package
that will provide his country no financial relief. His decision
seems to be a political gamble in which the populist attraction in
Germany of a refund was outweighed by his need to demonstrate that
a serious leader sits at the summit of Europe's most powerful
country.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached after a final negotiating session that
lasted more than 20 hours and often seemed on the brink of
collapse, is aimed at holding farm subsidies at their current level
of $44.5 billion a year from 2000 to 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The Union's agricultural policy, intended to protect farmers
from lower world prices, is notoriously costly and backed with a
notorious vigor by the million French farmers who receive about 22
percent of total farm spending.
</P>
<P>
   French resistance to any cuts was therefore strong, and
Schroeder had several difficult discussions with President Jacques
Chirac of France, officials said. Italy and Spain, two other
principal beneficiaries of the farm policy, also fought hard to
resist changes.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is to keep its annual rebate of about $3.2 billion,
representing about 60 percent of the difference between what it
pays into the European budget and what it receives, despite
vigorous protests by several countries.
</P>
<P>
   While discussion on the budget took up most of the time, Kosovo
inevitably weighed heavily, and the Middle East was also discussed.
</P>
<P>
   With four neutral countries in its midst, the union stopped
short of explicit backing for the NATO airstrikes but said it was
up to President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia ``to stop the
military action by immediately stopping his aggression in Kosovo
and by accepting the Rambouillet accords.'' The accords call for
self-government for the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo, with the
prospect of independence after three years.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on the Middle East, the European leaders
supported ``the continuing and unqualified Palestinian right to
self-determination, including the option of a state'' and said they
looked forward to the ``early fulfillment of this right.''
</P>
<P>
   They said those rights, to be achieved through negotiation, were
``not subject to any veto.''
</P>
<P>
   The wording was a stronger expression of support for a
Palestinian state and a stronger rejection of any Israeli right to
veto it than the Europeans have formally made before.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders said Israel and the Palestinians should extend
the current ``transitional period'' leading to statehood beyond May
4, adding, ``It should be possible to conclude the negotiations
within a target period of one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the European position went beyond publicly stated
American views, some officials suggested that it had been
coordinated with Washington to encourage the Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to remain patient on May 4, the date on which he has
indicated he may unilaterally declare statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was adopted despite an extraordinarily vehement
denunciation of European leaders by Netanyahu before the conference
ended. He was apparently reacting to a draft of the final
statement, a draft that proved accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is especially saddening that Europe of all places, where
one-third of the Jewish people perished, sees it as correct to try
to force a dangerous solution upon Israel that jeopardizes its
interests,'' the prime minister said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting ended at dawn Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
