u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-TUNNEL-FIRE-AR     03-26 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-TUNNEL-FIRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE KILLS AT LEAST 35 IN ALPS TUNNEL LINKING FRANCE AND ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French and Italian officials said Friday that at least
35 people had died in a fire that erupted Wednesday deep inside the
Mont Blanc tunnel in the Alps. The blaze, which began in a heavy
truck and quickly engulfed some 30 other vehicles, was finally
brought under control Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Details about the casualties were slow to emerge because
firefighters from France, Italy and Switzerland were prevented by
searing heat and toxic smoke from reaching the scene of the
disaster, almost exactly halfway through the seven-mile tunnel. One
firefighter died of a heart attack and some 27 others were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said that at one point the temperature in the
tunnel reached 1,800 degrees Fahrenheit. With the motors of fire
trucks stalling for lack of oxygen, the firefighters, wearing masks
and carrying oxygen tanks, were forced to continue on foot. One
fire official, Jean-Guy Laurent, said many victims were found at
the wheels of their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the Mont Blanc Tunnel and Autoroute, made up of
the French and Italian agencies that operate the tunnel, said
Friday that ``despite extreme difficulties in counting the victims,
the toll of about 30, which was indicated previously, should
unfortunately be reached.'' Later reports said the death toll could
reach 40.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 24 charred bodies have been found, although only nine
have been identified. The names of many of those feared dead have
been provided by anxious relatives and truck companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire is out and we have now examined all the tunnel,''
Ruggiero Borgia, managing director of the Italian Mont Blanc tunnel
agency, said Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot said the tunnel, Europe's
longest when it was inaugurated by President Charles de Gaulle in
1965, will be closed for several weeks because some of its concrete
casing and rock surface had collapsed. The two-way single-lane
tunnel, which connects France and Italy, is used by as many as
5,000 vehicles daily and has never before suffered a fatal
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The fire began at around 11 a.m. Wednesday on a
Belgian-registered truck carrying 20 tons of flour and margarine.
According to some accounts, several other large tractor-trailer
trucks ran into the first truck and soon caught fire. The tunnel
agency said eight trucks driving toward France as well as 12 trucks
and 10 or 11 cars heading for Italy were trapped over a 1,000-foot
stretch of the tunnel. Gilbert Degrave, the driver of the truck
where the blaze began, was able to escape along with at least four
other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   A Belgian newspaper quoted Degrave as saying that he looked in
his rear-view mirror and saw smoke rising from the back of his
truck where, he believed, fuel had leaked onto the exhaust pipe.
``Everything was ablaze in half a minute,'' he told the newspaper,
Het Laatste Nieuws. ``I ran for my life. Behind me, all hell broke
loose. In a few minutes, the tunnel was like an oven.''
</P>
<P>
   France's Transport Ministry has ordered a full inquiry into the
accident, but already complaints are being heard that the tunnel's
ventilation system was inadequate and obsolete. Philippe Sardin,
director of the Tunnel Research Center in Paris, said the tunnel
was built with 1950s technology that had never been modernized even
though new ventilation and fire prevention techniques now exist and
were installed in the Channel tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Charlet, the mayor of Chamonix, the ski resort town in
Haute-Savoie at the French end of the tunnel, Friday called for
heavy trucks to be banned from using the tunnel. ``For years, we
have been telling the central authorities that this high mountain
valley cannot handle 800,000 trucks per year,'' he said, adding
that France should follow Switzerland's example of switching cargo
transportation from highways to railroads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
