<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE STOCKS LOOK BETTER FROM AFAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of Nikkei 225 index, year-to-date, is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Never mind that unemployment is rising, consumer
spending and capital investment continue to decline and only
government officials are willing to express confidence that the
economy here will show growth in the fiscal year that begins this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The bulls are on the rampage in Japan, pushing the benchmark
Nikkei 225 stock index up almost 20 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the horned beasts are foreigners, who have piled
back into the market in huge numbers since the beginning of the
year. ``Foreign investors are giving the benefit of the doubt to
Japan,'' said Kathy Matsui, chief strategist at Goldman Sachs
(Japan) Ltd. ``They're seeing a flow of restructuring announcements
and have hopes for additional stimulus on the policy side from the
Bank of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   In the week that ended March 12, the most recent week for which
data are available, foreigners bought 770 billion yen worth of
stocks, about $6.5 billion at current exchange rates. It was an
even bigger spending spree than in 1994, when, during one week in
February, outsiders spent 540 billion yen, about $5.1 billion, on
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by this,'' Ms. Matsui said. ``I'm definitely
surprised by the amount of foreign influence we've seen in the
market this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese investors, always more cautious than their foreign
counterparts, are doing exactly the opposite. Everyone from pension
fund managers to bank treasurers is selling or hedging against
future falls in the equity market.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of Japanese fears shows up in the September futures
contracts on the Nikkei. Traders say Japanese banks and life
insurance companies, which maintain large stock portfolios, have
been selling futures contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Such transactions would guarantee them the right to sell the
index in September at current prices, about 16,000. In other words,
even if the Nikkei were to fall to 12,000 by September _ a level no
one now foresees _ they have locked in its current value. Banks and
insurers are thus betting that the Nikkei will tumble.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Japanese investors historically are bearish on
Japanese stocks at this time of year, in part because they suspect
the government of artificially propping up share prices in ``price
keeping operations'' designed to insure that the value of corporate
and bank portfolios is robust when the books are closed on March
31. The government never confirms such operations.
</P>
<P>
   So what do foreign investors see in Japanese stocks that
Japanese investors do not? The biggest factor seems to be the
belief that a quiet revolution is occurring in corporate Japan that
will transform lumbering, loss-producing Japanese companies into
nimble, moneymaking global competitors.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Japanese companies _ Toshiba, Sony, Sumitomo Rubber
Industries, to name a few _ have embarked on what could be major
overhauls of their operations, and their efforts have gained a
flurry of press attention. Not only are they paring their labor
forces (though such measures mean less in a time of deflation),
they are also streamlining their businesses and embracing new
management philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Asahi Chemical. In January, it announced that it would
sell its food business to Japan Tobacco. The company is shutting
down its chemical fertilizer operations, and analysts believe that
it may pull out of the petrochemical business altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really just nibbling around the edges so far,'' Garry
Evans, the strategist at HSBC Securities in Tokyo, said of Asahi's
efforts. ``But they've taken steps in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that dramatic changes like those at Asahi
Chemical have received such widespread coverage in the foreign
press _ always desperate for signs of change _ that there is a
danger of perceiving a revolution when what is happening may be far
more evolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 70 companies that have announced plans to ``restructure''
since the beginning of the year, only 22 have actual cost-cutting
targets that can be identified, according to Evans _ and, on
average, the goal for cost reduction is just 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, then, that the more cautious Japanese investor is
hedging his or her bets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
