<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILHARMONIC-DUTOIT-N     03-26 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILHARMONIC-DUTOIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTOIT SHARES SPOTLIGHT WITH POULENC AND YOUNG CELLIST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Conductors generally know what their strengths are or
at least what the public perceives as their strengths, and although
some occasionally rebel against their reputations and try to play
against type, most keep close to what works for them.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dutoit has been successful with early-20th-century
showpieces, works that dazzle with bright hues and picturesque
effects and that use volume to pack a visceral wallop. For his
visit to the New York Philharmonic, which began on Thursday evening
and ends Saturday night, he did the sensible thing, which was to
draw on that repertory.
</P>
<P>
   More sensible still, he balanced the familiar and the novel in
an unusual way. The two pillars of the program, Poulenc's
orchestral suite from his 1924 ballet, ``Les Biches,'' and Holst's
mighty astronomical compendium, ``The Planets,'' are works
listeners know well from recordings, but that don't find their way
onto concert programs that often, at least in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Biches'' inhabits the nether region that ballet scores
call home; only Stravinsky's have achieved full-fledged symphonic
stature. ``The Planets'' requires an organ. Avery Fisher Hall
doesn't have one (nor does Carnegie), and orchestras tend to
dislike the available solution, which is to use an electronic
organ, as the Philharmonic did on Thursday. Four speaker columns
descending from the ceiling were reminders that the hall is
insufficiently equipped.
</P>
<P>
   It is not as though ``The Planets'' were an organ concerto, of
course, nor is the organ line as prominent as it is in the
Saint-Saens Third Symphony, another casualty of this shortcoming of
New York's concert halls. Holst's greatest demands are on the
orchestra's brass, which punch out the bellicose chords of ``Mars''
and sing with lyrical abandon in ``Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   Brass playing has not been the Philharmonic's great strength
over the last dozen years, but in the last few weeks the orchestra
has performed several brass-heavy works, and the playing has been
spectacular. Philip Myers' horn solos in ``Venus'' were impeccable,
both in pitch and in shapeliness, and throughout the suite,
particularly in Dutoit's fluid account of ``Jupiter,'' the horn,
trumpet and trombone choirs played with a solidity that gave
Holst's tone paintings both power and dimension. The strings
contributed notably as well, both in the hefty, long-lined melodies
of ``Jupiter'' and the icy shimmer that, in league with the women's
voices of the Judith Clurman chorale, illuminated the mystical side
of ``Neptune.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Poulenc, the brass share the spotlight with the winds,
both central components in the Gallic urbanity that Poulenc
projects. ``Les Biches,'' revived in honor of the composer's
centenary, reveals Stravinsky's pervasive influence on young
composers in the century's early decades, but it also shows
Poulenc's determination to find his own distinctive voice.
</P>
<P>
   Dutoit put the weight of his reading at the service of that
distinctiveness, emphasizing the characteristically French
sensuality in the opening Rondeau, the easygoing charm of the slow
movements and the light-spirited fleetness of the hornpipelike
closing Presto.
</P>
<P>
   Between the Poulenc, which opened the program, and the Holst,
which closed it, Han-Na Chang made her Philharmonic debut as the
soloist in the Saint-Saens Cello Concerto No. 1. Ms. Chang, who won
the Rostropovich International Cello Competition when she was 11,
is now 16. Technically, she is agile and focused, and gets a good
variety of timbres from her instrument. If her interpretation was
hard driven and slightly airless at first, when she lightened her
touch, the music floated appealingly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
