<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-OPINION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN PUBLIC DECIDEDLY AMBIVALENT ON KOSOVO ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sent Americans to their almanacs
for a crash course on the Balkans this week, but the lesson has
failed to convince a skeptical public that Kosovo is worth dying
for.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of U.S. and NATO air strikes against Serbian
forces, polls consistently show that Americans are confused about
the roots of the conflict, pessimistic about the chance of success
and deeply concerned about the possible loss of American lives.
</P>
<P>
   The ambivalence of average Americans mirrors the misgivings of
many foreign policy experts. As each day brings new risk of allied
casualties, skeptics continue to question the wisdom of U.S.
involvement in a region that has been a tinderbox of ethnic tension
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of enthusiasm for the Kosovo mission underscores the
political risks for Clinton, a lame duck president whose
credibility has been battered by the White House sex scandal. Even
the president's supporters concede that the public mood could sour
quickly if there are significant American losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Support is remarkably thin, given that the fighting has
started. That's usually when the rally-round-the-flag effect
starts,'' said William Hartung, an arms control expert at the World
Policy Institute, a foreign policy research center in New York.
``That hasn't happened in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   In a striking departure from previous military actions,
traditional expressions of support for U.S. troops from members of
Congress have been accompanied by stinging denunciations of their
mission. Rather than rallying behind the president, some of
Clinton's critics seem to be closing ranks for an I-told-you-so
chorus if things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, reiterated his opposition as the first
wave of bombs and missiles thundered into Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``American soldiers should be ordered into battle only when the
vital national interests of the United States are at stake,'' he
said in a prepared statement. ``To risk American lives for anything
less is wrong and I cannot and will not support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some key allies of Clinton in previous military excursions have
bailed out on his latest use of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been this uneasy about any American military action
since I left government,'' former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger said on ABC's ``Nightline'' program. ``We will win the
first round, but my nightmare is what happens as this unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   Separate polls for CNN, CBS and the Los Angeles Times indicate
that Americans with far less foreign policy experience have similar
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In all three polls, a slim majority of the respondents supported
the air strikes despite their reservations. But the national
telephone surveys also showed that most Americans expect U.S.
casualties and adamantly oppose the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Only 34 percent of the respondents in a CBS poll of 527 adults
Wednesday felt that the goal of ending Serbian attacks on ethnic
Albanians would be worth the loss of American lives.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN poll of 675 adults found that most Americans do not think
any vital U.S. interests are at stake in the conflict. Fewer than
half thought the mission would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   In a Los Angeles Times poll of 544 adults Thursday, only 36
percent predicted that the air strikes would lead to a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   All three polls have a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points, meaning that the results could be off that much
in either direction because of sampling errors.
</P>
<P>
   The other notable consistency in the polls is the lack of
knowledge about the Balkans. Most Americans cannot name the warring
factions whose dispute in the former Yugoslavia has triggered the
international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a third of the respondents in a Fox News poll could not
say which side NATO forces are bombing, and 9 percent incorrectly
guessed that the attacks are aimed at ethnic Albanians, the people
that NATO forces are trying to protect.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the adults contacted in the CBS poll had no
opinion on the air strikes, a level of uncertainty unmatched in the
network's previous polls on recent military operations in Iraq,
Afghanistan, Sudan, Bosnia, Haiti and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is way behind the curve on this,'' said Rep. Martin
Frost, D-Dallas, who supports the Kosovo operation. ``Any president
who commits American forces needs to make the case with the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who urged Americans to consult an almanac in a speech
to a labor group Tuesday, readily acknowledged the difficulties in
making a convincing case for the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a slam-dunk,'' he said. ``This is a difficult
decision. I believe that the position I have taken is the best of a
lot of bad alternatives. But you didn't just hire me to make the
easy decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   His supporters in Congress can only hope that he is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to give the president the benefit of the
doubt and hope the policy works,'' Frost said. ``There will be
plenty of time for talk about it if it doesn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
