<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENIGNI-OSCAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIANS ARE BEAUTIFUL: BENIGNI'S UNBRIDLED JOY RUNS AWAY WITH OUR
HEARTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BENIGNI-SPEECH and BENIGNI-SOPHIA) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one in Hollywood steps on Steven Spielberg. Except Roberto
Benigni. Last Sunday night, this goofy-haired, rubber-legged
Italian taught us that sometimes, the greatest joy knows no
etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scene we'll see again and again, as long as there are
Oscar-night reminiscences. A ravishing Sophia Loren announces the
winner for Best Foreign Film _ Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful.''
Benigni thrusts his legs into the air and climbs the seats in front
of him, including that of Spielberg, who reaches to clasp Benigni's
hands in an act of both congratulation and self-preservation. Then
comes Benigni's bunny hop up the stairs to the podium, and an
acceptance speech just this side of gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like now, ready to dive in this ocean of generosity,''
he bellows. ``This is too much!''
</P>
<P>
   He was honored for a movie set in a Nazi concentration camp. The
film's look at the evils there, while unusual, is unstinting.
Clearly, there is a time to cry. But even in the sorrow, Benigni
seemed to insist on Sunday, life IS beautiful. Sorrow is but a
necessary counterpoint to joy, and when it comes, joy should be
embraced with the fervor of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Benigni's reaction to his Oscar triumphs (he also won Best
Actor) will live among the century's most enduring and endearing
public displays of exuberance. Benigni made the acceptance speech
of Cuba Gooding Jr. a few years back look morose by comparison. He
stepped on Spielberg's chair, and in the process, lifted our
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   JOY OUT OF SADNESS: Italy has known his happy example for years.
He grew up there in poverty but was a class clown, his comedic
talents inspired and supported by his parents and older sisters.
His Chaplinesque farces eventually made him Italy's biggest star
and moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the slapstick genius was the lesson gained from a
father who survived a Nazi work camp, an experience the older man
spoke about obsessively for years. Eventually, to spare his
children, Benigni's father began to describe the old horrors in a
different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started to use the story with gladness, in a very light
way, trying to be light and funny because it happened also some
funny stories there,'' Benigni recently told Charlie Rose. ``When
he started to smile, he stopped have nightmares also. So, it was
over. So this was very touching to me ... this moment when he
started to tell his story in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   So Benigni tells us the familiar story in a different way, too.
A father and son are trucked off to a concentration camp. But in
``Life Is Beautiful,'' this father spares the child from the worst
horror with laughter, by transforming the experience into a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragedy and comedy,'' Benigni would tell Rose later. ``They
sometimes touch. No? ... Sometimes only clowns can reach some
summit of tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the back of Spielberg's seat, we witnessed the summit
of joy. As well as anyone, Benigni knows that the two go
hand-in-hand, always touching. There was one part of his speech
Sunday that was not gibberish at all:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank those who are not here,'' he told the audience
of stars, and of millions watching at home, ``who gave their lives
so that we can say, `Life Is Beautiful.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
