<SLUG> BC-BENIGNI-SOPHIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPHIA STILL WINS THE `AMORE' OF AUDIENCES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BENIGNI-OSCAR) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just from appearances, they made an odd couple up there on the
Oscar stage _ the impossibly wacky Roberto Benigni, the impossibly
gorgeous Sophia Loren.
</P>
<P>
   But Loren was the perfect choice to present the Oscar to her
countryman. Like Benigni, she first came to major American notice
for an Italian film in which she played a starring role; hers was
``Two Women,'' for which she became the first foreign actress to
win a Best Actress Oscar nearly 40 years ago. That she got to pass
on an Oscar to her friend Benigni was an ideal bit of Hollywood
typecasting: When she waved the envelope aloft and joyously cried,
``Roberto!'' there could not have been an audience member who
didn't feel her warmth and exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades since her debut, of course, Loren has become a
legend, the result of her beauty and sensuality and earthiness as
much as her acting. Just look at how the crowd swooned when Loren
came out as a ``presenter'' during the Oscars. This, despite the
fact that many in the audience had probably seen few of her films
on the big screen. Indeed, when you look at Loren's filmography,
you'll find such notorious misfires as ``A Countess From Hong
Kong,'' ``Man of La Mancha'' and ``Ready to Wear.''
</P>
<P>
   This, truly, is a definition of a star: No matter how many times
your films disappoint, the public will forgive you and adore you.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some Loren films worthy of praise:
</P>
<P>
   ``Houseboat'': Loren had been paired with Cary Grant before, in
the misguided 19th-century action pic ``The Pride and the
Passion,'' but this 1958 film was an improvement: She becomes
Grant's housekeeper and surrogate mother to his kids, in the kind
of fluffy romantic comedy Grant excelled at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Women'': Loren won her Best Actress Oscar _ the last
acting Oscar for a foreign-film performance until Benigni's win
this year _ for this wrenching survival story about a woman and her
daughter who are raped by Allied Moroccan soldiers during World War
II. Vittorio De Sica, one of Italy's top filmmakers, directed the
1960 film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'': Loren teamed with De Sica
again for this 1964 trio of vignettes about women's, er, persuasive
effect on men. Featuring Loren's infamous striptease for frequent
co-star Marcello Mastroianni, which Robert Altman paid tribute to
in the otherwise lumpy ``Ready to Wear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabesque'': Lighthearted _ which almost goes without saying
with a Stanley Donen film _ espionage tale pairs Loren with Gregory
Peck in this 1966 movie about an assassination plot. Made during
Donen's ``If Hitchcock can do it, so can I!'' period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cassandra Crossing'': One of many '70s all-star disaster
movies, this 1976 film about a plague-plagued train bound for a
weakened bridge (two disasters in one!) included Loren in its
all-star cast. It also included O.J. Simpson, but at the time it
was considered one of the better entries in the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grumpier Old Men'': Loren's most recent performance (1995)
cast her as Walter Matthau's love interest. Now that's acting!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
