<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, March 27, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT-OOPS (Los Angeles) _ Despite pledges by Mayor Richard
Riordan and other high-ranking city officials backing the $744
million public safety bond measure, the sample ballot mailed to all
voters this week failed to include the itemized list of police and
fire projects that the money would be spent on. City officials said
they were very upset that the language was left off the ballot but
were hard-pressed to explain how the snafu could have occurred. By
Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LAX-SHRIMP (Los Angeles) _ Entire cities and powerful
politicians are allied against Los Angeles International Airport's
expansion plans, but it seems that the airport's most formidable
foe for now is an endangered shrimp. By Peter Hartlaub. (Will move
in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POW-MEDAL (Los Angeles) _ William Schiffmacher waited 56 years
for recognition from the United States government for his capture
and imprisonment in Romania where he was shot down during World War
II in an air raid on an oil field. On Friday, the Northridge man
will receive the POW Medal of Honor from the Air Force. By Lisa
Weiss. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PANTRY-CHEFS (Los Angeles) _ The oldest hash house in Los
Angeles, a landmark for late night revelers and early birds working
downtown, celebrated its 75th anniversary Friday with celebrity
chefs trying to improve on The Original Pantry's pancakes. The
pancakes won. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ELEPHANT-OUCH (Los Angeles) _ Tara, the 33-year-old African
elephant at the Los Angeles Zoo, got her trunk caught in some
hydraulic barn doors this week and severed about 4 inches trying to
pull it out. Zoo veterinarian P.K. Robbins said Tara is expected to
recover, and ``will keep the sore clean by herself. By Yvette
Cabrera. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SABBATH-SEMAPHORE (Los Angeles) _ Starting Friday, walk signs at
several intersections in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley frequently
crossed by observant Jews on their way to synagogues no longer had
to be activated by pedestrians pushing a button. To observe the
sabbath, which began at sundown Friday, Orthodox Jews abstain from
using electronics _ including button-activated walk signs _ as a
tangible symbol of their religious contemplation. By Jesse
Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
