A5837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-COUNCIL-NYT &LR;      03-26 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-COUNCIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SECURITY COUNCIL REJECTS RUSSIAN BID TO END AIRSTRIKES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-MIGS, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-INFORMATION, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(wg) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In a victory for the United States and NATO on
Friday, the Security Council rejected, 12-3, a Russian resolution
demanding an immediate end to NATO's air attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Voting in favor of the measure were two of its sponsors, Russia
and China, and Namibia. Voting against were the five council
members who are NATO members _ the United States, Britain, France,
Canada and the Netherlands _ together with Argentina, Bahrain,
Brazil, Gabon, Gambia, Malaysia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   While the resolution was almost certain to be defeated, the
scale of Russia's defeat surprised many diplomats and was described
by several as politically significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a landmark debate for the United Nations and an
enormous triumph for NATO and the United States,'' said Fernando
Enrique Petrella, Argentina's representative. ``A large majority of
nations have acted together to say that no longer will you be able
to violate human rights massively over a long period of time
without evoking a reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrella added that while the vote could not be described as a
U.N. endorsement of the NATO attacks, given the staunch opposition
of Russia and China, the council's overwhelming defeat of the
resolution could only bolster the ``legitimacy of what NATO is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote was an admission that action was necessary,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergey Lavrov, the Russian representative, refused to
acknowledge the defeat. Many of those who voted against his
resolution and with the United States were ``embarrassed'' to have
done so, he said, and had made this clear to him in private
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech seeking support for the resolution, which was also
sponsored by India and Belarus, Lavrov argued that the military
action was a ``flagrant violation of the United Nations Charter''
because it disregarded Yugoslavia's sovereignty. Those who favored
such action, he said, had placed themselves outside international
law, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's vote is not just on Kosovo, but on the Security
Council's role in the world community,'' Lavrov said. ``What is in
the balance now is law and lawlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burleigh, the American representative, said the allegation
that the military action violated the U.N. Charter ``turns the
truth on its head.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least two resolutions, he said, the Security Council had
specified what Yugoslavia must do to end the crisis. But rather
than agree to the political solution mediated by the so-called
Contact Group, whose six members include Russia, President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia had chosen to ``defy repeatedly the will of
the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   The charter, Burleigh said, ``does not sanction armed assaults
upon ethnic groups or imply that the international community should
turn a blind eye to a growing humanitarian disaster.'' A vote in
favor of the resolution, he warned, would ``only encourage
President Milosevic to continue or even to intensify military
repression of the civilian population of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their votes and their speeches, the overwhelming
majority of Security Council members agreed with Burleigh's
argument that Yugoslavia, not NATO, had violated the charter and
international law by killing civilians and repressing the people of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hasmy Agam, of Malaysia, which has occasionally been very
critical of American policy, said Yugoslavia's leadership bore
``full responsibility'' for the failure of the international
mediation efforts which, in turn, had prompted the need for
military action to protect the people of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the harshest attacks on the resolution's co-sponsors came
from Peter van Walsum, the recently appointed representative from
the Netherlands, a NATO member. While the Dutch were initially
``grateful'' to Russia for having contributed to the pressure that
the Contact Group brought on Yugoslavia, he said, ``at every
critical juncture'' since then, ``Russia has somehow succeeded in
making the pressure less credible, so that in the end NATO had no
choice but to make good on its threat'' to use force. The
alternative, he concluded, was ``to sit back and simply let the
humanitarian catastrophe occur.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lavrov's arguments were warmly endorsed by Belarus, India
and China.
</P>
<P>
   India's representative, Kamalesh Sharma, said that although the
resolution was overwhelmingly defeated by the council, the debate
suggested that nations representing ``half of humanity have said
they do not agree'' with the military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   China reiterated its position that Kosovo was an internal
Yugoslav concern. Qin Huason, Beijing's representative and current
president of the council, declared, ``We oppose power politics of
the strong bullying the weak.''
</P>
<P>
   This theme was echoed more aggressively by Yugoslavia's
representative, Vladislav Jovanovic, who accused NATO and the
United States of ``outperforming even the Nazis in their animosity
and hatred against Serbians and Montenegrin people.'' (Serbia and
Montenegro are the last remaining republics in Yugoslavia.)
</P>
<P>
   The alliance, he said, is perpetrating an ``orgy of destruction
and havoc against a small, peace-loving country.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most poignant appeals for support for NATO came from
Bosnia and Herzegovina, a former Yugoslav republic also racked by
Serbian aggression.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian representative, Muhamed Sacirbey, noted that the
United Nations and its Security Council were ultimately ``savaged''
for not stopping the war in his country. Suppressing his ``moral
outrage'' over what he called the ``ethnic cleansing'' of his
country and now Kosovo, he said, he applauded the resolution's
rejection. ``Let us not allow the Security Council to be seen as
ineffectual as it was in Bosnia and Herzegovina for three and a
half years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
