<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5843 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-HEDDA-SFCHRON     03-26 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-HEDDA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENING BACK ON STAGE WITH STEEL, FIRE IN `HEDDA GABLER' 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Annette Bening has made a career of doing the
unexpected. She's doing it again in ``Hedda Gabler,'' with a steely
performance in Henrik Ibsen's 1890 tragedy that's about as far from
crowd-pleasing glamour as she could get. The show opened a
four-week run at the Geffen Playhouse this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the year's most hotly anticipated theatrical homecoming, the
film star and onetime ingenue at San Francisco's American
Conservatory Theater has met one of the theater's most difficult
and enigmatic roles with an interpretation every bit as unsolvable.
Bening's first stage appearance in a decade is not the triumph
publicity machines crave but a riddle at once fascinating and
strange.
</P>
<P>
   With her pensive stares, scalding sarcasm and nearly repellent
neck-straining tics, Bening encases Ibsen's unhappy bride in
fearsome isolation. Everything she does in Daniel Sullivan's
production _ a restless walk through the expanse of Riccardo
Hernandez's set, the defiant poses she strikes with her husband,
the patronizing manipulation of another woman _ seems preordained,
unwilled. It's as if Hedda were sleepwalking toward her doom.
</P>
<P>
   Only the truth startles her fully alive. ``I have a talent,''
she crescendoes, ``for boring myself to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Informed of a former lover's suicide, she declares it
``liberating'' with that lustrous Bening voice that can make a
single word sound orchestral. Then her voice tightens and her gaze
spirals inward again. ``I mean for (set ital)me,(end ital)'' she
adds. What this woman might ever do with her freedom remains a
mystery to her.
</P>
<P>
   Bening looks magnetic in her dark bodice-hugging gowns and
loosely coiffed hair. She can raise the stage temperature in an
instant with a smile calculated to kill _ shades of her menacing
screen heat in ``Valmont'' and ``The Grifters.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing remotely charming or seductive about this
Hedda. If anything, Bening's performance borders on a kind of
tactical rigor that leaves the character's interior shrouded, to us
and even to Hedda herself.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the sort of career-buffing choices Hollywood
actresses tend to make when they step from screen to stage. Bening
rejected a Noel Coward proposal for her Geffen engagement and
insisted on Ibsen instead. She commissioned a crisp new vernacular
adaptation, by ``The Substance of Fire'' playwright Jon Robin
Baitz. The cast includes Paul Guilfoyle, who appeared with Bening
in the recent psychological thriller ``In Dreams,'' as a snide
Judge Brack.
</P>
<P>
   Bening is billed above the title, but there's not a hint of star
turn in the show. Sullivan's staging is conventional, almost
ordinary. A brief thought of updating the action to the 1950s
vanished. Only the occasional colloquialism in the text _ one
couple decides not to ``see each other'' anymore _ marks this
``Hedda Gabler'' as something new.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Jennings, Bening's fellow ACT alumnus, plays Hedda's
spineless husband, Tesman. His voice is an apologetic purr to
Bening's sharp bark, and he barely registers her open taunts and
undisguised sarcasm. The imbalance is a problem. This sham marriage
seems too weightless to bind Hedda.
</P>
<P>
   Guilfoyle's smug Judge Brack and Patrick O'Connell's smoldering
Lovborg, Hedda's former lover and victim-in-waiting, open up
Bening's range more. Shooting out her window one morning, she fires
off a throaty laugh as well as a bullet in the judge's direction.
When she lures Lovborg to a downstage ottoman, Hedda's sexuality
comes on like a heat lamp. Pat Collins' lighting warms along with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Bening's long absence from the stage shows. She doesn't have the
unforced presence and fluid transitions she tossed off in ``Coastal
Disturbances'' in New York a decade ago. She poses a bit too much,
aping the portrait of Hedda's father, and relies on her grimaces
and far-off looks.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone who remembers Bening's magnificent 1982-85 run at
ACT _ ``The Chalk Garden,'' ``The School for Wives,'' a glowing
``Arms and the Man'' with Jennings _ her return to the stage is
sweet. Her voice, now as it was then, is an amazingly supple
instrument, burrowing into the meaning and harshly beautiful music
of a line. Even in repose, Bening has always been irresistible to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   She's a different artist now, a different person, with more at
stake and more to tap. The life of a star and celebrity wife is
about as far from Hedda's curdled ambitions as a provincial 19th
century Norwegian town is from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bening is making a hard journey back to the place where she came
from and flourished, a classic drama in a regional playhouse. It's
not a headline grabber. And that, finally, may be the best news of
all about this unflashy ``Hedda Gabler.'' Bening has come out of
the glare, at least for a month, and back home to the life of the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
