Advance for Monday March 29 
(Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file) 
By LEAH GARCHIK 
c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALTRANS HONORS CHAVEZ WITH GIFT OF SIGNS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robert Cromey &LR; , rector of San Francisco's Trinity Episcopal
Church, isn't usually an impatient man, but he was wondering last
week, four years after the Board of Supervisors renamed Army
Street, and despite the recent induction of  &UR; Cesar Chavez &LR;  into the
Department of Labor's Hall of Fame, why there's still no freeway
sign directing drivers to Cesar Chavez Street.
</P>
<P>
   Cromey's query was well-timed. This week, said Caltrans' &UR; Greg &LR; 
 &UR; Bayol &LR; , in keeping with the United Farm Workers' celebration of
Chavez's birthday on March 31, two new signs directing drivers on
Highway 101 to Cesar Chavez Street will be unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   They're not big signs, Bayol said, because so far the city
hasn't been willing to foot the bill to replace the big overhead
freeway signs, estimated at $900,000 a few years ago just after the
name was changed. If the street name were shorter, Bayol said, and
the signs could be fixed rather than replaced, the bill would be
only $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans realizes, says Bayol, that shortening the name might be
a delicate issue; at the same time Caltrans knows that people are
getting lost. While the city figures out how to pay the bill, the
two new signs provide Chavez with a posthumous birthday gift that
duplicates the gift he always had: an unfailing sense of direction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Richard Holbrooke &LR; , the American diplomat who's been trying
to negotiate peace in Kosovo, has signed a deal with HBO to turn
his 1998 book about negotiating peace in Bosnia into a TV movie.
The Washington Post says the movie, based on the book ``To End a
War,'' will cast Holbrooke as an international hero in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Luciana Morad &LR; , the Brazilian model who says she's expecting
 &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; 's baby, says that she will send him to Eton. ``I love
those boys' accents, and their little uniforms,'' she told the
Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Melanie Griffith  &LR; told People magazine she wasn't invited to
the Oscars, but she doesn't care. ``I'd much rather watch at
home,'' she said, ``because you can get up and smoke and do
whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eight spanking new cars _ from Ford, General Motors, Fiat,
Honda and Toyota _ will be on display in the sculpture garden of
the Museum of Modern Art in New York this summer, reports
artnet.com. ``Cars at Moma'' is apparently intended to be a
blockbuster show. Critics will be offered test drives.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Eileen Kauffman &LR; , a woman on the cutting edge of Y2K mishaps,
received a bill from Kaiser for medication that regularly costs her
$5, for $9,999.99.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Calista Flockheart &LR; 's new boyfriend is  &UR; Ben Stiller &LR; , says
the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teen magazine says that  &UR; Courtney Love  &LR; is studying Kabbalah,
the mysticism of choice of  &UR; Madonna &LR;  and  &UR; Sandra &LR; 
 &UR; Bernhard &LR; . Meanwhile,  &UR; Susan Rublein &LR;  take note of a Society for
the Anthropology of Consciousness conference, in Berkeley this past
weekend, on ``Is the Self an Autonomous Agent?'', and if you need
help deciding, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   _ Browsing through the Yale University Press ``Literary and
Literary Criticism'' catalog and stumbling upon ``The Death of
Tragedy,'' ``The Rise and Fall of English,'' ``The Failure of the
Word,'' ``Literature Lost'' and The Death of Literature,''  &UR; Steve &LR; 
 &UR; Finacom  &LR; found himself downright depressed.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you don't have a tape measure handy and you want to measure
an inch, says Maxim magazine, use a quarter, or a business card
folded in half horizontally. Elsewhere in the wide world of
invention, &UR; Keith Overbeck &LR;  suggests that the glowing substance
proposed for human consumption be added to dog food, thereby making
it safer for pedestrians to walk the sidewalks at night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOT TIMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Susan Sarandon  &LR; told Mirabella magazine that there was so much
sexual tension between her and co-star  &UR; Sean Penn &LR;  during the
making of ``Dead Man Walking'' _ she played a nun, he played a
killer on death row - that director Tim Robbins, Sarandon's
significant other, stopped the shooting one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `I can't watch this,' '' said Sarandon. `` `It's
gotten into something else.' There was a big discussion of whether
it was too sexual. Sean said, `Yes, it is, but that's what it is.'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual tension is all about connection,'' said Sarandon,
``about two people seeing each other in a way nobody else does. And
Sean and I were definitely connected.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``During National Salad Month in May, Americans can celebrate
salads.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you don't have a party hat, you can substitute a lettuce
leaf, but don't go overboard. Muscle &AMP; Fitness magazine warns about
the dangers of salad dressing.
</P>
