<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story: 4-col. hed
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ As NATO forces stepped up their
bombing assault into the daylight hours, President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia maintained fierce resistance both on the
ground and in the air. Two of his MIG-29 fighters shot down on what
NATO claimed was a foray into neighboring Bosnia. The sweep by Serb
troops through the ethnic Albanian villages of Kosovo continued
unabated, NATO said, despite the third straight day of air assaults
that NATO officials emphasized would be unrelenting until Milosevic
accepted peace. By Francis X. Clines and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who claims he
has helped more than 130 people commit suicide, was convicted today
of murder. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-INDICT (New York) _ Developments in the wake of the
indictment of four police officers for the shooting of West African
immigrant Amadou Diallo. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ The allied military
strategy for stopping Serbian attacks against ethnic Albanian
rebels in Kosovo rests largely on the hope of a specific Serbian
response to the heavy NATO bombing that began on Wednesday,
according to officials here. The hope, allied officers and
diplomats say, is that intense airstrikes will cause so much damage
to Yugoslavia's army and its sophisticated air-defense system that
Serb commanders may soon pressure him to back down and accept
allied terms before they lose everything. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TUNNEL-FIRE PARIS _ French and Italian officials said
Friday that at least 35 people had died in a fire that erupted
Wednesday deep inside the Mont Blanc tunnel in the Alps. The blaze,
which began in a heavy truck and quickly engulfed some 30 other
vehicles, was finally brought under control Friday afternoon. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB (Washington) _ On reports of new Serb massacres,
other atrocities. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INFORMATION (Washington) _ In the 1991 Gulf War, the
military gave detailed briefings twice a day, in Washington and in
Saudi Arabia, announcing the number of combat flights, targets hit
and Iraqi troop movements. Things have changed. Even as President
Clinton's national security advisers flood the television airwaves
with back-to-back-to-back interviews to justify NATO's air campaign
against Yugoslavia, the American military has clammed up on the
most basic details of the operation. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
