</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NATO PINS ITS HOPES ON A SHORT FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-MIGS, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-INFORMATION, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(wg) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The allied military strategy for stopping
Serbian attacks against ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo rests
largely on the hope that Serbian military commanders will seek an
end to the intense NATO bombing before it destroys their army and
air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The hope, allied officers and diplomats say, is that the strikes
that began Wednesday will cause so much damage that the Serbian
high commanders will pressure President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia to back down and accept allied terms before the military
loses everything.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what basis there was for such a hope, one senior NATO
diplomat said, ``There have been signs that the army was reluctant
to get involved in Kosovo, and that it was forced by Milosevic to
engage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His strategy is retaining power,'' the official said. ``The
longer NATO action continues, the more he is in danger of losing
his grip.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Balkans have often demonstrated a logic of their own.
From Milosevic's point of view, there may be good reason to hope
that the longer the bombing continues, the greater the chance that
fissures will develop within the alliance _ a hope that may be as
illusory as NATO's own hope about dissension in the Serb ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently, Milosevic moved to strengthen his control over
the army and security forces, replacing the army's longtime
commander last October and the chief of his internal security
forces just before the start of the most recent offensive in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And in Serbia, according to the Western reporters who were
expelled from Belgrade this week, Milosevic's popularity seems to
be soaring, not plummeting, as Serbs rally around him in defiance
of the allied bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the allies are counting on the intensity of the
bombing to convince Milosevic that his best course is to call off
his operations in Kosovo. On Friday, alliance officials said,
Yugoslavia lost two more of its supersonic MiG-29 fighter-bombers.
It had 15 of the MiGs at the start of the bombing, and lost three
in earlier dogfights.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said the planes had flown
to Bosnia on Friday with the apparent intention of attacking the
NATO peacekeeping force there. Allied planes shot them down, and
allied troops were searching for the two pilots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be in a situation where eventually it will become
clear to the leadership that the price of this campaign is too
high,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the peace agreement that the Serbs refused to sign in
France a week ago will still be on the table if it takes weeks to
bring Milosevic around is unclear. ``If we said we would continue
bombing Milosevic until he signs the Rambouillet agreement, we
could be bombing for years,'' one diplomat said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5868 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS-2N     03-26 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS, Belgium: diplomat said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bombing continued for a third day after allied warplanes
attacked more than 50 targets during the first two days, military
commanders said. According to the allied command, almost all those
sites were either command centers for the Yugoslav army, internal
security police who have been rounding up suspected rebels and
burning Albanians out of their homes in Kosovo, or air-defense
radar, missile and anti-aircraft sites the allies need to eliminate
before they can do anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing out the anti-aircraft batteries should take a few more
days, officials said. At that point, there would probably be a
pause while NATO Secretary General Javier Solana consults with
allied leaders to see whether they still agreed that allied
warplanes should start going directly at the tank bases, arms
arsenals, fuel depots and artillery bases that the army and
interior ministry police forces in Kosovo have been using in their
campaign against the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But even Gen. Wesley Clark, the American top commander of
``Operation Allied Force,'' said Friday that there was no way the
bombing, however long it lasted and however intense it was, could
stop all Serb assaults against civilians on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always understood from the outset that there was no way
we were going to stop these paramilitary forces from going into
these villages and attacking,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   But allied attacks against those forces and their
infrastructure, Clark and other officials said, would leave Serb
forces much less capable of carrying out big sweeps like the ones
that have sent tens of thousands more ethnic Albanians fleeing for
their lives in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Milosevic does back down, that kind of bombing could go
on for weeks or months, with periodic air attacks against Serb
mobile anti-aircraft guns and missile sites when they turned on
their radars and threatened allied planes much like the pinprick
war of attrition the forces Clark commands in Turkey have been
waging against air defenses in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The European allies, according to some of their representatives
here, are just as prepared as the United States is to see the
bombing continue for many days, if not weeks, if it takes that long
to get Yugoslavia's leader to back down.
</P>
<P>
   But their resolve might not survive the pressure that would come
if allied planes were shot down and pilots were taken prisoner, or
if misfired allied bombs caused heavy civilian casualties in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in NATO would like to see the bombing stop as soon
as possible,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Greece is probably the NATO ally with the most reservations
about the attacks. But even Italy, the country from which most of
the 400 allied missions have been launched against Serbia, would
like to take advantage of a pause in the bombing to get diplomatic
efforts restarted, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to diplomats from several European countries, no
allied ambassadors here have dissented from the consensus
supporting the bombing. The 19 countries in the alliance, Solana
said, were as one, at least in daily meetings of its North Atlantic
Council here, in support for continuing the bombing in the hope it
would lead Milosevic to back down and end the violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As for an exit strategy for the allies, the sooner he backs down
the better for them, because the longer the bombing continues, the
harder they believe it will be to revive the peace negotiations and
send a NATO-led international military force into Kosovo to police
the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is whether the allies, who have insisted so far
that they have no intention of becoming the air force for the
Kosovo Liberation Army, would consider providing support for the
rebels if the Serbs did not back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this goes on, we may have to reassess some aspects of our
basic policy but we are still a long way from that,'' a senior
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for the rebels signed the peace accord in Paris on
March 18 under which Kosovo and its ethnic Albanian majority would
regain their autonomy within Yugoslavia, and an international
peacekeeping force would be deployed in the province. But the
Serbian leader, like many of his compatriots, believes Kosovo is
sacred Serbian ground, on which Orthodox Christian Serbs fell as
martyrs to Islamic Turk invaders five centuries ago, and has
rejected any international military presence.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has also told Western mediators that he believes the
proposed peace agreement and the peacekeepers would just provide
international cover for the secession of the province, with a
referendum on independence at the end of a three-year transition
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic cannot destroy the Kosovo Liberation Army with the
military option,'' a senior official said. It remains to be seen
whether NATO's military option can end Milosevic's defiance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
