<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      03-26 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
NATO PLANES DOWN TWO YUGOSLAV MiG-29s 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a dramatic, daytime escalation of the Balkan
fighting, NATO said Friday its warplanes shot down two Yugoslav
MiG-29s that were apparently readying a raid on Western
peacekeepers in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said U.S. F-15Cs fired on the
Russian-built jets when it was clear they were entering the no-fly
zone over Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Initially NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the MiG pilots
parachuted from the crippled planes, were captured and would be
held by allied forces until the end of the Kosovo engagement, which
entered its third day Friday. Bacon said he could not confirm the
capture: ``We do not have the pilots. We don't know if the pilots
are alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic denied the NATO
claim of shooting down the MiGs, but wire services reported
sightings of planes crashing about five miles inside Bosnia near
the town of Bijeljina. CNN showed wreckage of what it said was one
of the Yugoslav planes.
</P>
<P>
   Following two nights of aerial bombardment, NATO started the
daylight action by firing a cruise missile from the USS Philippine
Sea in the Adriatic. After dark, more missiles and bombs hammered
Yugoslav military targets in what Bacon called a ``large'' assault
from an aerial array that included B-52s and F-117 stealth
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Targets on the third night of attacks included installations
closer to the center of Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, according
to wire service and broadcast reports. And there were signs the
target list was widening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gradually increasing the emphasis on attacking targets
in Kosovo itself,'' Bacon said, including the Serb special police
associated with growing reports of atrocities against ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration continued to say that it did
not plan to use ground troops in the assault, national security
adviser Samuel Berger told NBC News: ``One can never anticipate all
possibilities in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced 100 combat-ready U.S. Marines were
being sent to Skopje, Macedonia, to protect the embassy, which
anti-American demonstrators attacked Thursday. Skopje, the
Macedonian capital, is less than 50 miles from the border of the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   No progress was reported on the diplomatic front. The U.N.
Security Council rejected a Russian resolution calling for an
immediate end to the NATO military drive. President Clinton and his
European allies are seeking to force Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to stop fighting with ethnic Albanians in the province of
Kosovo and to allow western troops to police the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials said the violence by Milosevic's forces
against Kosovar Albanians had increased. NATO's deputy military
chief, Air Commodore David Wilby of Britain's Royal Air Force, said
Milosevic's police had released ``300 hard-line Serbian prisoners''
to join paramilitary troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav MiG sortie over Bosnia-Herzegovina, an independent
republic formerly part of Yugoslavia, marked a potentially
dangerous step up in the response by the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon called the MiG flight into Bosnia ``a serious challenge,
and so far a challenge that we've been able to repel.''
</P>
<P>
   If the aim was to draw NATO planes over Yugoslavia and make them
better targets, Bacon said, ``it backfired egregiously on the
Yugoslavs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that the downing of the two MiG-29s on Friday and the
destruction of three others as the NATO attacks began Wednesday
meant that Yugoslavia had lost a third of its top-of-the-line
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The first two nights of NATO air strikes saw little active
defense from the Belgrade government, especially from Yugoslavia's
well-regarded air-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces are in Bosnia to police the 1995 U.S.-sponsored
agreement that ended fighting there between Muslims and Serbs, most
of whom are orthodox Christians and were supported by Milosevic and
his military. The NATO contingent in Bosnia _ the so-called
``stabilization force'' or ``SFOR'' _ numbers 30,000, of which
6,700 are U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Bosnian deal, known as the Dayton accords,
Yugoslav military aircraft are prohibited overflight.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav MiGs were intercepted by NATO planes from Operation
Deny Flight, which operates primarily from some of the same
airbases in Italy that are mounting the aerial assault on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright expressed satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are satisfied with the way that the air campaign is
going,'' Albright said in a CNN interview. ``Nobody expected that
there would be a turnaround in five minutes or 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the administration view that the United States is
in the NATO operation for the long haul, Clinton did not make a
public statement Friday _ except a taped appearance that was beamed
to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking through a translator who read the president's
remarks in Serbo-Croatian, said Milosevic had condemned Yugoslav
``sons to keep fighting a senseless conflict that you did not ask
for and that he could have prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright delivered a similar radio message, reading it in
Serbo-Croatian she learned as a girl when her father was a Czech
diplomat in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be one knockout blow, but day after day,
if he does not stop his genocidal attacks on the Kosovo people, we
will take larger and larger lumps out of his military force,''
British Defense Secretary George Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the reported appearance of the MiGs over Bosnia, military
officials at NATO and the Department of Defense had been somewhat
puzzled by the lack of response from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of Yugoslavia's mobile SA-6 surface-to-air missiles had
been fired in the engagement, and it did not hit a NATO target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it's an indication of the success of our operations,
or a husbanding of resources,'' British Air Commodore Wilby said.
Some defense analysts have suggested the Yugoslavs are waiting
until NATO sends in slower and lower-flying planes before
activating more of its air-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In its current stage, Wilby said, the operation is ``very
systematically taking out the meat of the (air) defense systems.''
And NATO spokesman Shea said, ``We have to be in a situation where
we have taken out sufficient air defense assets so that our pilots
can operate with a relatively greater degree of safety in Yugoslav
air space.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said in the first two nights NATO conducted about 400
sorties against 50 targets. Pentagon sources said about half were
flown by U.S. crews.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
