<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-     03-26 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMATION ON SERB REPRISALS AGAINST KOSOVARS IS SKETCHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-MIGS, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-INFORMATION, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAZINCE, Macedonia _ On a rocky hill overlooking the village in
Kosovo 20 yards across the border that he fled last week, Agim, 27,
squinted through binoculars at two Serbian armored vehicles parked
in the middle of his town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen soldiers looting televisions and refrigerators,'' he
reported. ``They chased us all away, and now they are stealing
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Such furtive glances through binoculars are what pass for
monitoring of the situation in Kosovo these days. International
monitors pulled out just before NATO began bombing, foreign aid
workers left or seem to be under house arrest and the last foreign
journalists were expelled Thursday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, the world is relying on rushed and emotional
accounts by the few refugees who are able to sneak or bribe their
way through Serbian roadblocks, and scratchy mobile-phone calls
from ethnic Albanians trapped inside their homes in Kosovo, the
southernmost province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The descriptions of Serbian reprisals against Albanians since
the bombings began range from harassment and property damage to the
killings of civilians. But in one of the worst crises Europe has
faced since World War II, information about what is really
happening is sketchy and unverifiable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With reporters out and aid workers grounded, there really
isn't very much we can do,'' said Fernando del Mundo, an aid worker
with the United Nations High Commission on Refugees. He had worked
in Kosovo for eight months until he was evacuated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not to say that atrocities are not happening,'' he
added. ``I'm sure a lot of it is, but we have no means to confirm
it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday the refugee commission reported from its headquarters in
Geneva that it had received information from 174 Albanian Kosovars
who fled to northern Albania that there had been a massacre in
Goden, their village.
</P>
<P>
   According to the refugees, Serbian police came into the village,
set houses and the school on fire and shot 20 men, then marched the
174 villagers to the border and expelled them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot confirm it,'' del Mundo said. ``That's just what
they told us. Some is probably true, but different people have
different ways of telling their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   There have also been news reports, based on a statement by the
separatist guerrilla group that calls itself the Kosovo Liberation
Army, that 20,000 ethnic Albanians were rounded up from Cirez, near
a Serbian munitions factory, to serve as human shields to deter
NATO bombings. No reporters or aid workers have been able to
confirm it, and del Mundo described the figure of 20,000 as
ludicrous, if only because Cirez only has 5,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Yugoslav government of President Slobodan Milosevic,
which expelled all foreign journalists from Belgrade on Wednesday,
is only letting out information that serves its own purposes,
ethnic Albanians want to put his regime in the worst possible
light. Finding the truth in between has become almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,400 monitors for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, who left Kosovo before the bombing, are in
hotels in Skopje and Ohrid, a Macedonian town to the south, with no
real means of gathering reliable information. The organization
plans to send most of them home, keeping a core of 250 monitors in
Macedonia to prepare for a possible return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, William Walker, the American who directs the monitors,
told reporters that the situation in Kosovo was deteriorating, but
his staff members say they cannot really determine how far. They
must rely on rumors and sketchy accounts provided by local
employees left behind in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But those people, like local employees of international aid
organizations, are at risk, and communicating with western agencies
outside only increases it. ``Do you really want to put people's
lives in danger just to find out what might be happening?'' said
Urdur Gunnersdottir, a spokeswoman for the monitors.
</P>
<P>
   International aid workers and journalists have sought refuge in
Macedonia, but it has not turned out to be so reassuring a haven
for U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   When pro-Serbia demonstrators rioted outside the U.S. Embassy in
Skopje on Thursday, setting vehicles on fire, smashing windows and
pulling down gates, Macedonian riot police only belatedly dispersed
the crowd. U.S. soldiers assigned to the United Nations operation
in Macedonia, whose mandate expired in February, were called in to
secure the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   During the disturbance, Ambassador Christopher Hill and 40 other
embassy employees sought refuge in a bunker inside the compound,
communicating with the State Department and the Macedonian police
by cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the U.S. soldiers were replaced with an armored vehicle
equipped with a cannon and a cordon of armed U.S. marines, who
stood guard behind a newly placed barrier of barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department announced that all nonessential personnel
and their families would be allowed to leave Macedonia for their
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Hill issued a statement saying the riot was ``caused by an
organized mob whose goal was to cause damage and increase anxiety
during these uneasy times.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, whose hotel was also surrounded by hundreds of
demonstrators who attempted to burn the Kosovo monitors' vehicles,
blamed the attacks on Milosevic. Calling the riots ``well-organized
and planned,'' Walker said his monitors had received information
weeks ago that Serbia planned ``as much trouble as Milosovic could
stir up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian police said Friday that 60 demonstrators had been
arrested, including Dragisha Miletic, leader of the Democratic Serb
Party, an ethnic Serbian political group in Macedonia. He was later
released, The Associated Press reported, and a demonstration
planned for Friday was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
