<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKS-INVEST27-COX     03-26 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-INVEST27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seminar aims to create black investors
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A conference today is aimed at encouraging
African-Americans to spend less and to save more.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions, sponsored by the 5,000-member Coalition of Black
Investors, offer advice on stocks, mutual funds, 401(k) plans, IRAs
and taxes, as well as talks by former Atlanta Mayor Maynard
Jackson, television personality Tavis Smiley and the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization exists to turn more African-American
consumers into investors,'' said COBI President Carol Davis, who
founded the group in 1997 with her husband, a financial adviser
with First Union Brokerage Services. ``We are just trying to help
people be more aware of the things they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Black people represent about 14 percent of the nation's
population, but only 7 percent of the income. And while many black
people have moved into professional jobs, affluent blacks are not
necessarily as secure as their incomes might indicate.
</P>
<P>
   According to Northeastern University Professor Thomas Shapiro,
co-author of ``Black Wealth/White Wealth,'' a typical black family
averages 11 percent of the wealth of a white family. Among the
middle class, the figure improves to only 25 percent, Shapiro
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said a key reason that blacks account for just 3 percent
of the nation's wealth is a lack of investments. But it is not just
a matter of money, Davis said: Black people have $500 billion a
year in buying power, but instead of investing, they have responded
far too well to the barrage of enticements to buy.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1998 study by Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., black
households have an average of $117,000 saved or invested, compared
with $224,000 for whites.
</P>
<P>
   One handicap is the lack of inherited wealth, the kind of
affluence that is fueling the transfer of an estimated $6 trillion
in wealth into the hands of baby boomers during the next several
decades. Only a tiny fraction of that money will come to black
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if not for you, but for the next generation, we want to
break this vicious cycle,'' Davis said. ``It's not rocket science.
It's as easy as having an automatic debit for your checking
account.''
</P>
<P>
   Registration for the conference, at the Renaissance Waverly
Hotel, begins at 7:30 a.m. and costs $99. A separate session
focused on the leadership role of the church starts at 8:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (888) 411-COBI (2624) or (336)
922-6240, or visit the group's Web site (www.cobinvest.com).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
