<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small Business agency to hold Y2K seminar
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Your company's computer has passed the Y2K checkup,
but what about the copy and credit card machines and the elevator?
Are the accounting and delivery services you use up to par
Y2K-wise?
</P>
<P>
   At most Fortune 500 companies, a Y2K team takes care of these
concerns. For most small business owners, the job probably falls to
the owner or a relative.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a disturbing thought for the federal and state Small
Business Administration, as many of Georgia's 265,000 small
businesses are just beginning to deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K is a business and management issue, not just a technology
issue,'' said Fred Hochberg, who helped build and run his family's
catalog company, Lillian Vernon Corp., before becoming the
second-in-command at the federal agency in May. ``Y2K is a problem
we can address. No business should be hurt by Y2K if they take
prudent and proper precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency will hold a nuts-and-bolts workshop Tuesday in
Atlanta during Y2K Action Week. It is the largest Y2K conference in
the Southeast and is expected to draw 200 to 250 people. Hochberg
will speak at the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of information, conferences and seminars to
make small businesses aware,'' said Charles Anderson, Georgia's SBA
director. ``This is a conference to give small firms the
information they need to fix the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Disaster experts Julie Freestone and Rudi Raab suggest companies
look at everything from how their employees will get paid if banks
are unable to operate to where critical materials and equipment
will come from if suppliers are paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Freestone and Raab, authors of the book ``Disaster Preparedness:
Simple Steps for Businesses,'' says the Y2K problem could force
companies to create disaster plans.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop will help companies learn how to test their
computer equipment, figure out if they need to call outside help
and where to get it, help pick a consultant and set up contingency
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop is 9:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. at the Georgia Public
Broadcasting Center, 260 14th St. For details and to register, call
(888) 248-5681 or go online to www.222.sba.gov/y2k.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
