<SLUG> BC-FOLLIES-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-FRILLS `FOLLIES' STILL HAS SONGS AND LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Great Britain)   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A warm laugh rises from the audience when, in the
finale of ``Ziegfeld Follies of 1936,'' Howard McGillin steps
forward and sings: ``We're not explaining the plot/You cannot
explain what's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ira Gershwin's sharp lyric aptly gives a kind of shape to this
effervescent, attenuated mishmash of a revue, revived by the
Encores musicals-in-concert series and running through Monday at
City Center. A list of what this period showcase is not could, in
fact, fill pages. It is not, for instance, uproariously funny,
gloriously tuneful or drenched in glamour. But all of this one
might have anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Tailored as a Depression-era star vehicle to the specific
talents of, among others, Fanny Brice, Bob Hope, Eve Arden and
Josephine Baker, the 1936 edition of Flo Ziegfeld's long-running
variety show was as much a perishable product of its time as an
installment of David Letterman or Conan O'Brien is sure to seem 63
years from today.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was a swell idea by Encores to bring back the Ziegfeld
Follies. Despite a dearth of the intoxicating highs one has come to
expect from this exquisitely produced concert series of old
musicals, Mark Waldrop's production of the songs by Vernon Duke and
Gershwin and sketches by Gershwin and David Freedman represents a
fascinating evening of time travel. Thanks to newsreels, movies and
musicals like ``Funny Girl,'' not to mention Stephen Sondheim's
``Follies,'' which transformed iconic aging versions of the
showgirls into metaphors for an increasingly cynical nation,
theatergoers have an inkling of what the Follies were like.
</P>
<P>
   But to appreciate the impact of the Ziegfeld style more fully _
its influence can be sensed today in everything from television
sketch comedy to music videos _ there is no substitute for the kind
of warts-and-all immersion that Encores provides.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrop, whose expertise in the revue genre was confirmed with
his direction of the camp Off Broadway hit ``When Pigs Fly,'' was a
smart choice for this venture, which opened on Thursday night.
Wisely, he does not brook any camping it up, even in the worst of
the sketches, some of which seemed creaky to critics in January
1936 when the show opened at the Winter Garden Theater. One
empathizes completely with the uphill battle waged all evening by
Mary Testa and Peter Scolari, filling the roles played in the
original by Brice and Hope; they have the roughest assignments,
performing skit after hackneyed skit about nutty psychiatrists, fey
bluebloods and even in a flat Hollywood parody featuring Brice's
trademark comic creation, Baby Snooks.
</P>
<P>
   In the totally unpredictable manner of a Broadway revue, a show
in which the plot is absolutely ``not,'' the moments of endearment
arrive with all of the serendipity of a singing telegram. When, for
instance, Karen Ziemba appears with Bob Walton and Jim Walton early
in the proceedings for ``My Red-Letter Day,'' a buoyant ditty in
three-part harmony, this terrific trio catches the audience off
guard with its brio and polish and swinging segue into tap.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie Henshall, the creamy-voiced London musical actress making
a smashing New York debut, has similar success with ``Words Without
Music,'' a torchy number with dancing by Jonathan Sharp and the New
York City Ballet soloists Jock Soto and Jenifer Ringer. Scolari and
the versatile Christine Ebersole, an enchantment in skit and song
alike as the Eve Arden character, do very nicely by Gershwin's
sprightly ``I Can't Get Started.''
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of its mandate, Encores does not trade in excessive
opulence _ the tasteful visual touches are confined to Art Deco
chandeliers and a lovely back curtain of translucent dangling
strands _ which is at variance with everything lavishly
Ziegfeldian. (In the clever opening number, McGillin, promising
that ``the day of the girlie-girlie show is through,'' immediately
makes way for a procession of leggy showgirls in jeweled
headdresses.) The lighting designer Peter Kaczorowski jazzes up the
visuals with his accustomed wizardry, but in this production it is
chiefly the job of the choreographer, Thommie Walsh, to create the
sense of spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziegfeld Follies of 1936'' gives him multiple opportunities to
accomplish this _ the revue has so much dancing that Scolari gets
the laugh line ``Yeah, I know what you're thinking: the show needs
another dream ballet'' _ and Walsh pulls many of them off with
style to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The sexiest number is ``Island in the West Indies,'' later to
become a Bobby Short standard. It's sung here by Ms. Ebersole and
danced, MGM movie style, as a splashy, shoulder-bouncing
jungle-fever extravaganza. ``The Gazooka,'' the parodistic Act I
finale, has a witty introduction, mocking the hype of period movie
trailers, but the number itself is a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   The only occupant of the bottom of the barrel is ``Night
Flight,'' an oddly wan tribute to aviation: this is 1936, after
all. As danced by Ms. Ringer, it looks a bit like a follow-up to
the loopy interpretive film-score dancing on Sunday night's Academy
Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Baker, portrayed here by Stephanie Pope, came under
attack at the time for what was described in some reviews as her
wooden contribution to this Follies, but the material may have been
to blame; it is hard to imagine she could have done much more with
``5 a.m.,'' a limply sultry song, than the undulations Ms. Pope can
manage. No one suffers the vitamin deficiencies in the writing more
poignantly than the show's lesser comics, played by Kevin
Chamberlin and Stanley Bojarski, naturally funny actors who here
never stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziegfeld Follies of 1936'' is by no means one of Encores'
greatest hits, but it does help to place in perspective some others
among its recent offerings; deeply flawed shows like ``DuBarry Was
a Lady'' and ``Babes in Arms,'' by comparison, almost qualify as
fully integrated book musicals.
</P>
<P>
   The Follies, through dozens of incarnations in the early part of
the century, were of course never meant to resemble anything close
to that. But that doesn't diminish their significance. What
Waldrop's faithful staging reminds us of is the exalted stage
Broadway once represented as the premier, star-studded pedestal for
American show business, where the talents loomed so large it hardly
mattered if there was a plot, or not.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ZIEGFELD FOLLIES OF 1936'
</P>
<P>
   City Center Encores: Great American Musicals in Concert. Lyrics
by Ira Gershwin; music by Vernon Duke; sketches by David Freedman
and Gershwin; directed and adapted by Mark Waldrop. Kathleen
Marshall, artistic director; Rob Fisher, musical director; the
Coffee Club Orchestra, Fisher, conductor; sets by John Lee Beatty;
costume coordinator, Gregg Barnes; lighting by Peter Kaczorowski;
sound by Scott Lehrer; projections, Eyewash Inc.; production stage
manager, Arturo Porazzi; original orchestrations by Robert Russell
Bennett, Conrad Sallinger, Hans Spialek and Don Walker; musical
coordinator, Seymour Red Press; choreography by Thommie Walsh;
ballet choreography by Christopher Wheeldon. Presented by City
Center, Judith Daykin, president and executive director, in New
York.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Christine Ebersole, Ruthie Henshall, Howard McGillin,
Stephanie Pope, Mary Testa, Peter Scolari, Bob Walton, Jim Walton,
Stanley Bojarski, Kevin Chamberlin, Jock Soto, Jenifer Ringer,
Jonathan Sharp and Karen Ziemba.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
