u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-TEXAS-H     03-26 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, CORNYN URGE COURT TO OVERTURN PRAYER BAN AT TEXAS FOOTBALL
GAMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Attorney General John Cornyn and Gov.
George W. Bush jumped into a dispute over prayer in public schools
Friday, asking a federal appellate court to reconsider a decision
banning prayers at high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, joined by Bush, filed a brief supporting the Santa Fe
Independent School District's efforts to continue its practice of
allowing student-led prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the First Amendment rights of students to gather and
participate in protected religious speech,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Griffin, a Galveston attorney who represents the
unidentified plaintiffs in the case, said Cornyn and Bush's
decision to intervene ``shows how sacred football is in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The school district has asked the full 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in New Orleans to review a three-judge panel's Feb. 26
decision that forbids prayer at football games but allows it at
high school graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn and Bush, along with the school district, want prayer
allowed in both places.
</P>
<P>
   In its 2-1 decision, the court noted a previous ruling that
prayer is appropriate at such solemn events as graduation but that
football games are ``hardly the sober type of annual event that can
be appropriately solemnized with prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges ruled that prayer at graduation could be allowed as
long as it is non-sectarian and non-proselytizing.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornyn says that ruling puts the state in the middle of the
issue, because Texas public school officials would have to review
the prayer to make sure it is non-sectarian and that it doesn't try
to convert someone to a particular religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The panel's decision asks the state to decide what type of
prayer should be allowed. To ask the state to supervise religious
speech is clearly unconstitutional,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that the Santa Fe school district's policies for
graduation and football-game prayers meet constitutional
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``These policies ensure that the schools remain neutral while
allowing for student-initiated speech. The purpose behind the
policy is not to advance religion, but that of promoting
solemnization and good sportsmanship,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffin said that practitioners of minor religions would be
placed in a ``very precarious position'' if students were allowed
to decide the content of graduation ceremony prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be majority rule every time, and that means
Christian prayers in Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin represents two families _ one Roman Catholic and one
Mormon _ with children in the district. The families, who remain
anonymous because they feared retaliation, filed suit five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe school district policy allows a graduating class to
choose by secret ballot whether to have an invocation and
benediction as part of its graduation ceremony. Before the court
ruling, students could similarly elect to have a brief invocation
during the pre-game ceremonies before home varsity football games.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court panel held that even student-initiated prayers
are never permissible at school-sponsored football games.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unheard of for a governor to join a legal brief,
although filing such documents is the responsibility of the
attorney general, the state's chief lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn took the lead in preparing the school prayer brief, and
Bush added his name to it.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said Bush's anticipated presidential race may have
affected the governor's decision. Support for school prayer is
strong among conservative Republicans, who will have an important
role in nominating their party's next presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must be close to 2000,'' Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor ``supports the
rights of students to participate in the free exercise of religion,
a right that is guaranteed by the Constitution, and he believes the
government should not dictate or censor the content of student-led
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty Legal Institute, a Plano, Texas-based organization
specializing in the defense of religious freedom and First
Amendment rights, also asked the 5th Circuit to overturn the Santa
Fe decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision will require open government bigotry against
religious students if it is not overturned,'' said Kelly
Shackelford, a lawyer for the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graduation students may pray, but not in the name of Jesus or
anything specific. Prayers that are unacceptable to the government
will be eradicated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
