<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-ANALYSIS-NYT &LR;      03-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ANALYSIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FOR GOP BUDGET, THE EASY PART IS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republican leaders took care of the
easy part of this year's budget battle in passing their tax and
spending plan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By managing to hold their fractious caucus together and dampen
rivalries between the party's leaders in the House and Senate,
Republicans managed to lay out a cohesive agenda built around a
sweeping tax cut, fiscal austerity, a strong military and smaller
government.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the budget resolutions in the two chambers sets up a
clean debate with Democrats and President Clinton. Republicans say
the overriding priorities as the nation decides how to divide
anticipated budget surpluses should be shoring up Social Security
and returning as much money as possible to taxpayers, with more
money carved out as well for the Pentagon and education.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats agree that Social Security should top the list, but
say the remainder of the projected windfall should be apportioned
among Medicare, spending on a broad range of domestic programs and
tax cuts for low and middle income people.
</P>
<P>
   But the process of turning the Republican budget guideline into
tax and spending legislation that can pass Congress and be signed
into law by Clinton promises to be messy, contentious and slow.
Making it even more difficult are the looming problems in Social
Security and Medicare, which are casting a long shadow over the
budget debate and seem increasingly unlikely to be resolved this
year.
</P>
<P>
   If there has been any clear message this year, it is the
enduring power of Social Security to shape the policies and
politics of both parties. Where the deficit once constrained
Republican tax-cutting efforts and forced Democrats to limit their
calls for new spending, each party's fear of being accused by the
other of raiding Social Security money has created an unlikely but
far-reaching consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties now agree that the bulk of the surplus, roughly
$1.8 trillion out of $2.6 trillion over the next decade, should not
be used for spending or tax cuts. Rather, they say, it should be
used only to help Social Security, either indirectly by reducing
the national debt, or directly by financing a Republican-backed
plan to create private investment accounts within the retirement
system.
</P>
<P>
   That $1.8 trillion represents the portion of the surplus
generated by Social Security payroll taxes in excess of what is
needed to pay benefits over the next decade. Although successive
Congresses and administrations have dipped into the Social Security
surplus for years to finance general government operations, that
pool of money has quickly become so sacrosanct that the two parties
are arguing about who can do more to wall it off from the rest of
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument that we should not use Social Security taxes for
anything else has turned out to be far more compelling than most
folks anticipated,'' said Carol Cox Wait, president of the
Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, a fiscal watchdog
group.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much of the surplus is now agreed to be untouchable,
the fight over what is left is that much more intense.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways it will be a nuts and bolts legislative fight, with
lawmakers of both parties trying to win money for what they
consider pressing needs. To hold House Republicans together in the
budget vote Thursday, Speaker Dennis Hastert had to mollify the
powerful chairman of the Transportation Committee, Rep. Bud
Shuster, R-Pa., by promising more money for airport expansions and
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, a bipartisan majority agreed at the last minute
to increase financing for child care. In both chambers, legislators
made pleas for more aid for hard-pressed farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of Republicans to stand by their pledges of
fiscal austerity will not be truly tested until this summer, when
they vote on appropriations bills that will have to slash many
domestic programs to remain within tight spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Then Republicans will face the challenge of negotiating with
Clinton to get their tax and spending bills signed into law. The
President has proved skillful in outmaneuvering Republicans in the
budget endgame in recent years, not only achieving enough of his
goals to claim victory but also leaving Republicans at each other's
throats.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum sent Friday to the Republican leadership, two
influential conservatives, Stephen Moore of the Cato Institute and
Lawrence Kudlow, a supply-side economist, said the party could face
a meltdown if it mishandled the budget this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP must at all costs avoid last year's fiscal collapse,
when Congress agreed to enormous election-eve spending bills, and
tax cuts were scuttled altogether,'' the memorandum said.
``Repeating those mistakes later this year will so dispirit the
conservative pro-growth wing of the GOP that the party will risk
losing everything in November of 2000: the House, the Senate and
the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore and Kudlow would not have been heartened by a statement
made by Hastert on Friday during an online chat with students.
Asked what kind of tax cut Republicans would pursue with the $15
billion they anticipate will be available for that purpose next
year, Hastert responded that he was not sure how much would be left
once the spending bills were completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
