<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-FESTIVAL27-COX     03-26 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FESTIVAL27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wealthy interest in the Web
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When, exactly, did South by Southwest
Interactive become $X$W?
</P>
<P>
   The young festival, which continues to be overshadowed by its
film and music counterparts, had a serious face lift this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's festival was very much about expanding the
possibilities of the Internet _ how it could be broadened as a tool
for communication, enlightenment, education and culture. This year,
however, talk of page views, Internet alliances and the
ever-looming specter of the Initial Public Offering dominated the
discussion. The festival, in a word, was about cash.
</P>
<P>
   While there was a series of panels on money and marketing last
year, it was just one of five areas covered. This year, the
business side of the Web accounted for a third of the panels and
pervaded discussion at many of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the lofty ``technology for human evolution'' talk
survived, it was like watching Tom Hanks navigate the beach in
``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the snarky editors of Suck.com and local Web icon Harry
Knowles, creator of the www.aint-it-cool-news.com Web site about
movies, spent a good portion of their time fielding questions about
banner advertisements and their money-making potential in addition
to questions about cultural relevance and what Internet
publications are doing to change the reader/writer relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is a bad thing. The interactive festival is just
reflecting a shift that is happening on the Net itself. Net stocks
are hot. Internet business has generated a buzz and captured the
imagination of Wall Street. Every company that hopes to compete in
the next century must get on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   As talented and independent Web 'zine publisher Nikol Lohr of
www.
</P>
<P>
   disgruntledhousewife.com told me, ``I think it's this awesome
unanimous revelation that we're suddenly a legitimate industry, and
we deserve to get a little scratch for what we're doing. So viva la
dough!''
</P>
<P>
   The few success stories that the Web has spawned _ Yahoo, eBay,
Dell's phenomenal Web-based sales _ have proven that there is money
to made on the Web. Unfortunately for those who dreamed of a
multimillion dollar advertising deal for mom and pop literary
magazine, the money to be made is not in content.
</P>
<P>
   For every Amazon.com, there are several thousand Web sites that
have compelling, highly readable content. But with no product to
sell and a fragmented market, page views alone rarely translate
into dollars for these Web ventures.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no wonder that SXSW has turned its attention to the
bottom line. The billions of dollars being generated by the few
Internet success stories is a siren call to all those who'd hoped
they could strike it rich with only their talent.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, the Net is becoming a place of business, and
the smart sites are those that are balancing great content with
good business sense _ The Onion, for instance, is more than just an
online humor 'zine. It has developed a huge audience, attracted
appropriate advertisers and sold merchandise through its site.
</P>
<P>
   The shift, most likely, was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But at a gathering in which some of the brightest minds in the
industry laid out their brains for the picking, it was
disheartening to see so much interest in the riches to be made from
the Net and so little attention paid to what a year ago seemed to
have limitless potential as a medium of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Like those who have begun to turn Las Vegas into the family
entertainment destination, the taming of the Internet has rendered
it another tool for commercialism. But before we condemn it for
this, let's not forget the artists and techies who laid the
groundwork for the medium _ their long-overdue payday may finally
come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
