<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S GIVE SOME CREDIT TO FORMER HARVARD PRESIDENT PUSEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching for a way to convey how remarkable it seemed that a
once-small Rhode Island bank earlier this month had acquired
through merger the once-impregnable symbol of Yankee dominion
formerly known as the First National Bank of Boston, I stirred up a
certain amount of protest when I suggested that Nathan Pusey was
entitled to the credit or blame.
</P>
<P>
   Pusey, who at 91 still summers in Maine, was president of
Harvard University when Terrence Murray, the future president of
Fleet Financial Group, was admitted to Harvard College in 1958. As
the son of a factory hand from Woonsocket, Murray was not the
stereotypical Harvard man of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Murray in those days (or at least others of his ilk)
was more likely to be found beating the tar out of the likes of
Charles ``Chad'' Gifford, who grew up to be his opposite number at
BankBoston Corp. As a teenager bound for Europe, Gifford stepped
from the SS Andrea Doria to the decks of rescue steamer Ile de
France after the passenger liner was rammed and sunk by a Swedish
ship in the autumn of 1956 _ without so much as getting his feet
wet.
</P>
<P>
   To momentarily recall Harvard's aggressive search in the 1950s
for boys such as Murray seemed like a way of calling attention to
the role the college played over more than a century in undermining
the rule of the old White Anglo-Saxon Protestant ascendency and
creating the far more nearly equal-opportunity society in which we
live today.
</P>
<P>
   A number of persons called or wrote to say that I had singled
out the wrong man as author of the policy of inclusion. Herb Regal,
for example, said it was James B. Conant, president before Pusey,
who really opened up the college. It was Henry Chauncy, an aide to
Pusey who later served as president of the Educational Testing
Service, wrote William Wrean. The policy of geographical
diversification ``spread to Yale and `Yanked' me right out of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided to take a closer look. I turned to John T. Bethell,
who edited Harvard's alumni magazine for 30 years. To celebrate the
magazine's centenary last year, Bethell published ``Harvard
Observed: An Illustrated History of the University in the Twentieth
Century,'' a survey as lively and various as its subject. In the
book, among much else, I found the story of Paul Buck and the
``floppy ducklings.''.
</P>
<P>
   A few words about Harvard's place in the firmament of US higher
education. It was the first college, and therefore all others have
evolved in contrast to it, whether the old universities of the Ivy
League (Yale, Princeton;) the South (William and Mary, Virginia;)
the myriad little colleges (Amherst, Bowdoin, Williams, and the
like;) the land-grant universities (Michigan, Wisconsin,
California;) the German-style research institutions (Johns Hopkins,
Chicago, Stanford;) or the great regional universities of the
present day (Northwestern, Duke, Rice.)
</P>
<P>
   All owe their identity to some extent to having become what
Harvard is not. This is even more the case in Boston, where the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Boston College, Boston
University, Brandeis University, Northeastern University and
Wellesley College _ not to mention Bentley, Suffolk, Emerson,
Simmons, Emmanuel and Pine Manor _ share niche space with the
Cambridge college whose origins date to 1636.
</P>
<P>
   People who know Harvard well say that it can best be understood
as a franchise. There are a college, its alumni, the school of arts
and sciences, its departments, the various professional schools,
the hospitals, museums, libraries, forests and villas: each largely
self-governed, yet susceptible in the end to some forms of overall
management. Hence the vital role of presidents of the university.
</P>
<P>
   It was Charles W. Eliot who set out to transform Harvard from a
New England college into an institution of national standing in
scope, Bethell says. During the 40 years he served as president
(starting in 1869), Eliot often said that he aimed to make Harvard
``a college of broad democratic resort,'' where students with
``much money, little money, or no money at all,'' would feel at
home, ``provided they all have brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the turn of the century, Bethell noted, Harvard
always had a larger proportion of Jewish and Irish students than
any comparable college. In 1919 an Irish Catholic was elected to
the Corporation that governed the university; by the mid 1920s,
representation of Jews body had reached 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   True, said Bethell, A. Lawrence Lowell, who succeeded Eliot,
unfortunately endorsed a Jewish quota. He also expressed
reservations about the presence in the college of
African-Americans. But Lowell, too, embraced a democratic vision of
college life and pursued the freshman dormitories and upper-class
houses that are Harvard's most successful integrating institutions.
</P>
<P>
   James B. Conant took Eliot's vision a step further with a
program of national scholarships instituted in 1934, designed to
bring promising graduates from the hinterlands. Where Eliot and
Lowell both had been Boston Brahmins, Conant's roots were in the
middle class, Bethell noted. Pusey, who succeeded Conant, was from
Iowa, of all places; Derek Bok, while technically from
Philadelphia, had been raised mainly in California; and Neil
Rudenstine, the current president, is half-Jewish and half Italian.
His mother was a waitress.
</P>
<P>
   Bethell says that when he set out to write his book he expected
to show that generational changes were bound up in changes in the
body of knowledge and applications of technology. That was true
enough, he said. ``but as I plowed ahead with my research it became
clear that there was one great agent of change that loomed much
larger than any other; one powerful catalyst that sped up the
processes of change already at work at all levels of society. It
stood out like the proverbial elephant in the drawing room. And
that, of course, was war.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the World war II, more than any other, that propelled
Harvard farthest into the vanguard of change. In 1949, for example,
veterans counsellor John Munro, noted the presence of fewer than 20
African Americans in the college and argued that a program of
recruiting ``really excellent Negro students'' would help
``materially on one of the country's sorest social problems.'' But
it was an article in the alumni bulletin in February 1946, to which
Bethell devoted a sidebar, that really caught my eye _ since it
offered a pretty good insight into how Fleet Financial's Terry
Murray advanced to the top of that bank.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Buck was a history professor; he served as provost, or
Conant's second in command during the War, and was the logical
candidate to succeed him as president in 1953, except that he
declined the honor. He died in 1978. In 1946, Buck was caught in
the middle between those who wanted Harvard to admit only those
applicants with the highest test scores, and those who wanted as
more fully rounded class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I share the often heard view that (the) College would be
improved if it had a larger share of the healthy, extrovert kind of
American youth which is so admired by the American public,'' wrote
Buck. Applications received through the veterans office compared
favorably with those coming in through the College examination
Board, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect 95 percent of (applicants) from the large
metropolitan public high schools of New york and New Jersey are of
one category _ bright, precocious, intellectually overstimulated
boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``For another example, I suspect a large proportion of the
Harvard applicants from the larger private schools of those same
states are not at all representative of those schools but are
weighted with the delicate, literary types of boys who don't make
the grade socially with their better-balanced classmates who, in
turn, head for Yale or Princeton.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard ``has done much to supply skillful, sympathetic advice
and medical treatment to the sensitive, neurotic boy who has some
talent. The result is that solicitous parents connive with
harrassed schoolmasters to send their floppy ducklings our way. And
the pressure to deposit them in our small pond increases in
proportion as we improve their survival rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not propose that we should take any action to stop the
flow to Harvard of the studious or sensitive type of boys. We must
not lose the advantage we now have from the appeal of Harvard to
the exceptional boy, even if he is a bit `queer' from the
standpoint of his fellows.'' Instead, Buck proposed an extended
scouting organization to search out a different sort of student. It
was one of these, presumably, who endorsed Terry Murray's
application.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, of course, is history. Harvard opened its doors ever
more widely. It began actively recruiting African-American students
in the 1960s. In the 1970s, it fully integrated women into its
classes and set a target of one for one. The 1980s saw an influx of
non-traditional students, due to changes in the Immigration Act of
1965. And in the millenial class of 2001, Bethell writes, 48.5
percent are women. Some 35 percent of the 2,040 students represent
ethnic minorities: 18 percent Asian American, 8.6 Hispanic, 8
percent black and 0.7 percen Native Back in the 1950s, when this
trend was becoming unmistakable to the alumni of the college,
Bethell's book recounts an  &UR; evening &LR;  when Nathan Pusey fielded a
question from a slightly tipsy old grad at a Harvard Club dinner.
What about my son, the member asked, ``whose ancestors came over on
the Mayflower, and whose father went to Harvard, and his father
went to Harvard, and his father went to Harvard, and now he. .
.can't. . .get. . .in!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Pusey, ``We can't send him back. The Mayflower
doesn't run any more.''
</P>
<P>
   4m
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
