<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN WANTS TO PUT BOXING, OLYMPICS INTO HOT SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain has been in more hot seats than most of us put
together. There was the Corvette he drove too fast in his early
20's; the Navy trainer that crashed into Corpus Christi Bay when
the engine quit; the A-4 Skyhawk that blew up as he awaited takeoff
on the carrier (begin itals) Forrestal; his second Skyhawk, that
got shot down over Vietnam; the cell in the Hanoi Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Survive enough of those kinds of scrapes, and the notion of
chairing hearings of the Senate Commerce Committee, or even running
for the Republican party's presidential nomination, does not
exactly fill you with dread. But all his life _ as pilot, POW,
politician, presidential possibility _ McCain has been a sports
fan. Sports nut is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he was sitting ringside at the Holyfield-Lewis
heavyweight fight that ended in a draw, to the disgrace of
professional boxing, and the ire of Muhammad Ali. The three-time
champ wrote McCain, supporting the Arizona senator's intent to
reform boxing by outlawing the kind of legal bondage that enables
promoters like the infamous Don King to manipulate the rules, the
laws and the contracts in ways that lead to outrageous outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional boxing can be reformed in a manner that will
honor its athletes, respect its fans, and serve the public's
interest in honest competition,'' declared McCain, who's pushed
boxing reform for six years.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note that number: Six. It signifies McCain is
no publicity-hungry, vote-sniffing political bull-slinger, hopping
on an issue when its hot, and unsaddling when it cools. As he
proved in fighting the Big Money interests in the
telecommunications reform struggle, the tobacco war in Congress,
and in the losing struggle for campaign finance reform, when John
McCain comes to the fray, he stays to fight. To the end, as his
Vietnamese captors learned.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the International Olympic Committee should be very
nervous. The IOC, and Juan Antonio Samaranch, the dictatorial
bureaucrat who runs this intensely private and intensely profitable
monopolistic cabal, have been ``invited'' by McCain to a Senate
hearing on April 14 to discuss corruption at the highest levels of
the IOC's secretive oligarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Around the planet, athletes, fans, governments and sport
federations will watch to see what happens. McCain's former
colleague, George Mitchell, who's become the man to pick when a job
needs doing right, headed the commission probing Salt Lake City's
winning bid for the 2000 Winter Olympics. The IOC was tarnished by
widespread bribery and vote-peddling by IOC members, who are
handpicked by Samaranch. It turns out the IOC is a totally private
organization which legally owns the legal rights to the Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell found ``a culture of corruption.'' McCain, as the
appropriate Senate chairman, wants to see more reform than the
pallid, cosmetic clean-up presided over by Samaranch. In this
endeavor, McCain is heartily supported by David D'Alessandro, CEO
of John Hancock, whose Boston-based insurance company has forked
over $100 million in Olympic sponsorship over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro is the most outspoken American sponsor who's raised
cain (and McCain) about the rot at the core of the Olympic
movement. Threatening to withold Hancock's $20 million in sponsor
fees for the upcoming Olympics, D'Alessandro has become the
toughest of the 11 major corporate sponsors. The spokesmen for
outfits such as Xerox, Visa, Coca Cola and others are less vocal.
</P>
<P>
   And the bosses at NBC, who have a lot of dough riding on their
broadcast rights, have been choking on their muffins. All the suits
with money on the line are watching McCain's lips. Because the old
jet jockey is packing some heavy weaponry. Here's a hint, buried in
a letter McCain sent to the IOC: ``The IOC enjoys tax-exempt status
. . . Corporate sponsorships by US corporations represent a
substantial majority of IOC revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: You people better clean up your act, pronto, or a
bill to change the US tax laws to obliterate the tax breaks may
quickly follow. It is the tax laws that enable big corporations to
pay for the sponsorship that puts on the games and eventually
filters down to the amatuer athletic foundations around the planet
that train the kids. This is no idle threat. D'Alessandro, who
carries no olive branch for Samaranch, says Samaranch took only
cosmetic action, firing nine IOC bribe-takers, and disciplining
some others. ``It's a brilliant job of PR, but a terrible job of
reform,'' said the Hancock chief.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro is delighted at McCain diving into the twin swamps
of Olympic bribery and boxing corruption. ``He (McCain) is talking
about something that will really get the sponsors' attention.
Because he's suggesting that the tax deductibility of sponsoring
might get eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   What should happen, of course, is that the 78-year old Samaranch
get blasted out of office, and the IOC, as Mitchell recommends,
should be reformed to open up the books and dismantle the
autocratic bureaucracy assembled by Samaranch. And after that, when
McCain gets around to boxing, later next month at a date yet to be
settled, the notorious Don King should get the rubber-hose
treatment in front of the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   King and Samaranch are very similar in character, if not in
diction: both men are longtime schemers who have cemented
themselves at the very center of the spider web which flourishes
off the corrupt exercise of exclusive rights to sporting
extravaganzas in the television age.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man will willingly don the handcuffs and march offstage.
It is the sponsors who are ultimately accountable to the public,
and it is the sponsors, as D'Alessandro enthusiastically predicts,
who must eventually take responsibility for cleaning up sport
empires corrupted by entrenched, unaccountable, oligarchs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
