<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5929 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-INFORMATION-NY     03-26 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INFORMATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING A SCRIPT, U.S. OFFICIALS REVEAL LITTLE ABOUT NATO
CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-MIGS,
KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(wg) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the military allies
gave detailed briefings twice a day, in Washington and in Saudi
Arabia, announcing the number of combat flights, the targets hit
and Iraqi troop movements.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters complained of being spoon-fed only what the Pentagon
wanted them to know, without a chance to confirm independently the
damage to Baghdad's forces.
</P>
<P>
   But at least it was something, which is considerably more than
is being disclosed about the bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The American military has clammed up on many of the most basic
details of the operation. Pentagon briefers have refused to discuss
what the pilots are trying to bomb, or whether they have destroyed
particular targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly taking a more conservative approach than in the
past,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. ``We want to give
adversaries as little information as possible about our techniques,
intentions and expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they are trying to protect pilots
flying risky missions who could be shot down and captured by Serb
forces. They are also worried about offending the sensibilities of
a shaky European coalition.
</P>
<P>
   There is rising concern among senior officials that the
government has become overly casual in its handling of classified
information, a complacency that Bacon attributed to a belief that
American interests are less at risk in the post-Cold War era. There
is also, he said, a growing hunger for operational details from
news media driven by 24-hour news cycles.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said relatively little about last summer's
airstrikes against suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and
Sudan (even a subsequent awards ceremony for the pilots was held in
secret) and the current low-level bombing campaign against Iraq (so
as not to upset Persian Gulf allies).
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivities of the 19-member NATO alliance have added
another element to the Serbia operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some European allies who don't like this portrayed
as too much of an American show, and there are other allies who
don't want information about their role put out at all,'' said a
senior spokesman for one branch of the armed forces, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO military commander, who has
authority over what information to release, pays careful attention
to these nationalistic idiosyncracies.
</P>
<P>
   At headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, on Friday, a British air
commodore, David Wilby, gave the first details on the total number
of NATO flights (400), a partial list of some of the Yugoslav
targets (18 of 50 sites), the damage inflicted to them (light to
totally destroyed) and videotapes of some of the successful
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance's spokesmen still are not talking about
casualties on the ground, the operation's cost, the dogfights that
downed a total of five Yugoslav MiG's and the country-by-country
makeup of the attacking air forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, senior administration officials are following a
tightly choreographed script as they seek to manage information and
perceptions of the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright appeared on three of the
television morning news shows on Friday, repeating the
administration's deter-or-be-destroyed mantra to Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. But she shied away from specific questions on
reports of massacres by Serbs in Kosovo or attacks on American
embassy employees in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what the administration would do if Milosevic does
not bow to the bombing, the president's national security adviser
Samuel Berger, sidestepped the question: ``There's one end state if
we do nothing. The end state in the other direction is either a
peace, which we hope to be the case, or a severely diminished
military capacity for Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   And Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton, the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, say it is too early to
discuss publicly the impact of bombing by B-2s and B-52s.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe with journalists. But in an effort to keep a skeptical
Congress supportive, or at least not hostile, military intelligence
analysts gave lawmakers an upbeat, richly detailed classified
assessment on Thursday of the early attacks, proudly showing off
satellite photographs of heavily damaged Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going extremely well,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton of
Missouri, the ranking Democrat on the House Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Given the secrecy surrounding ongoing military missions,
administrations have the upper hand in controlling the flow of
information and the spokesmen for that news.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter suggested to Bacon that he might buff his
credibility by admitting that some American bombs missed their
mark, as a British military spokesman said this week about some
British strikes, the Pentagon spokesman acknowledged the
information lock-down: ``You haven't heard about many bombs hitting
their targets, either. I think we've been pretty even-handed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
