<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYS-RESIGNATION-NYT &LR;      03-26 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-RESIGNATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J. )  
 DRYSIAK RESIGNS AS PRESIDENT AND COO OF TOYS `R' US  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a year after arriving at Toys ``R'' Us as second in
command, Bruce W. Krysiak has resigned as president and chief
operating officer of the beleaguered retailer.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement announcing his abrupt departure, the
company gave only the obligatory explanation that he was leaving
``to pursue other interests.'' But the resignation of Krysiak, 48,
is emblematic of the continuing turmoil at the company, the world's
largest toy seller, analysts said. Management is struggling with
increasing competition and declining profits.
</P>
<P>
   In the company statement, Krysiak insisted, ``This has been a
difficult decision that has nothing to do with the direction in
which Toys `R' Us is headed.'' A company spokeswoman said he was
unavailable for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Krysiak, who was also president of the American toy store
division, had made no secret of his aspirations to be the company's
next chief executive. The analysts said that he apparently
concluded that he would either not be elevated to that level or
that the company's troubles were worse than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he probably took the position that `If I can turn this
thing around I'll be CEO,''' said Sean P. McGowan, an analyst with
Gerald Klauer Mattison. ``When a guy steps into a situation with
one set of expectations and sees that they are not going to be met,
maybe he moves on.''
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us, which is based in Paramus, N.J., said that Mike
Shannon, 47, executive vice president, had been named president of
the United States division. The company did not name an executive
to replace Krysiak as president of the overall company and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us has been struggling with how to hold on to
once-loyal shoppers who have grown weary of its mammoth stores, as
well as how to compete more effectively with discount chains like
Walmart that are selling a wide selection of playthings at
affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Those pressures contributed to a plunge in the company's profits
and prompted a restructuring last year. Management closed dozens of
outdated stores and dismissed thousands of workers. Even after
those steps, the company's financial performance has remained
dismal.
</P>
<P>
   After disappointing results in 1997, the company posted a $132
million loss, or 50 cents a share, last year, largely stemming from
charges related to its restructuring. In the last quarter of the
year _ during the all-important holiday shopping season _ Toys
``R'' Us' profits fell 18 percent on flat revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Krysiak, who was president and chief operating officer of the
Dollar General Corp. before joining Toys ``R'' Us in February 1998,
was brought in to help revive the company. At the time, investors
cheered the appointment because Toys ``R'' Us had been criticized
for having an insular culture in which management lacked the sort
of fresh vision that often comes from outsiders with a new
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``I think he was probably not the right man at this
time,'' said Walter F. Loeb, of the investment firm Loeb
Associates. ``He came from Dollar General, which has a lot of
stores but doesn't have the seasonality of the challenges of Toys
`R' Us.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his arrival a year ago, however, Robert C.
Nakasone, the Toys ``R'' Us chief executive, said that ``Bruce
Krysiak's years of experience in retail operations, merchandising
and marketing will be invaluable as we move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Nakasone, who has been chief executive for only a year,
said in the statement that, ``we appreciate his contributions over
the past year and wish him well in his future endeavors.'' Through
a spokeswoman he declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced the management changes after the market
closed. Its shares were virtually unchanged at $17.625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
