<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VICTOR': ESCAPING CHILDHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The French director Sandrine Veysset has a special
gift for envisioning the world through the eyes of a child. Her
first film, ``Will It Snow for Christmas?,'' an examination of the
Spartan life of a French farming family, found everyday magic in
children's outdoor games and in the mystique of snow and holiday
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   In her second film, ``Victor,'' Ms. Veysset explores the
daydreams and nightmares of a young boy who runs away from home
after witnessing his parents in a kinky game of sexual bondage. The
brief glimpse we get of his parents' activities reveals little of
what's going on between them. It's enough, however, to drive the
boy out of the house. It's only much later that Victor (Jeremy
Chaix), when asked about the source of his pocket change, reveals
that his parents paid him to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing his home in the middle of a winter night, the boy ends
up riding the merry-go-round over and over at a nearby traveling
carnival. At the end of the evening, he faints into the arms of
Mick (Mathieu Lane), a young carnival worker who takes the lost
child to the apartment of his part-time girlfriend, Triche (Lydia
Andrei), a streetwalker.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie observes the deepening bond between the
boy and the prostitute, who becomes a protective surrogate mother.
Victor also develops a friendship with another boy who lives in an
apartment downstairs, and the movie affectionately observes their
childhood games, which include rummaging through Triche's clothes
one day while she is out of the house and dressing up and painting
themselves with her makeup.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, adapted from a novel by Denis Belloc, also follows
Triche on her dreary rounds, which consist mostly of hanging out in
doorways and having sex with strangers in cars. Late in the movie
we learn that Triche herself fled a sexually abusive background. As
her nurturing relationship with Victor begins to heal some of her
wounds, she summons the courage to stand up to her greedy madam.
Eventually she decides to quit prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   The studiedly drab movie, which New Directors/New Films is
showing Sunday at 6:30 p.m. and Monday at 6 p.m. at the Museum of
Modern Art, is dominated by shades of brown, gray and black, and
this minimalist look reflects the movie's world of numb, cauterized
feeling. That mood is so predominant that ``Victor'' feels
strangely detached.
</P>
<P>
   The closest it comes to evoking strong emotion is in its brief,
viscerally powerful dream sequences in which Victor finds himself
running in panic from a mob. At these moments, the movie does a
remarkable job of capturing the overwhelming terror of a common
nightmare in which there is no escape from an ominous, implacably
evil pursuer.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `VICTOR'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sandrine Veysset; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Ms. Veysset, based on the book ``Les Ailes de
Julien'' by Denis Belloc; director of photography, Helene Louvert;
edited by Mathilde Grosjean; music by Henri Ancilotti, with lyrics
to the song ``Pendant qu'il est trop tard ...'' written by Ms.
Veysset; production designer, Thomas Peckre; produced by Humbert
Balsan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jeremy Chaix (Victor), Lydia Andrei (Triche), Mathieu Lane
(Mick) and Skan Guenin (Robert).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
