<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS: RUSSIA, BRITAIN, ARGENTINA, MEXICO, SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Anti-Semitism Inquiry Pressed
</P>
<P>
   Russia's chief prosecutor, Yuri Skuratov, has ordered an
investigation into anti-Semitic statements by Albert Makashov, a
Communist lawmaker. Makashov virtually invited a group of Cossacks
to ransack Jewish homes during a speech in the southern town of
Novocherkassk. He also said he was changing the name of his
political movement to ``Movement Against the Yids.'' The regional
prosecutor had refused to investigate the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pet Rules Relaxed
</P>
<P>
   The 100-year-old quarantine rules for pets entering Britain,
requiring them to spend six months in confinement, will be replaced
by a new system in 2001 permitting entry to animals from
rabies-free countries in Europe and the Commonwealth. A pet will
have to travel with a ``passport'' containing information about
necessary vaccinations and blood tests. A microchip will also be
inserted in its neck to prove the document matches the animal.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: $3 Billion Payout for Miners
</P>
<P>
   The Cardiff High Court approved a government plan that could pay
out more than $3 billion to English and Welsh miners or their
widows. The awards end Britain's biggest ever industrial injuries
case and acknowledge responsibility for not having provided the men
protection against coal dust that caused emphysema and chronic
bronchitis, known as black lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem Party Vote
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Justicialist Party postponed their presidential
primary a second time, from May 9 to July 4, to give President
Carlos Saul Menem time to find a candidate to oppose the Buenos
Aires Gov. Eduardo Duhalde, an archrival. With his own re-election
hopes fading, Menem is hoping to convince Sen. Carlos Reutemann of
Santa Fe province that he has time to start an effective campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Reaching Out to Catholics
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo helped inaugurate a Roman Catholic
cathedral in a Mexico City suburb, an unprecedented gesture for a
Mexican chief executive. Despite the government's longstanding
anti-clerical tradition, Zedillo is reaching out to the huge
majority of Mexicans _ about 90 percent _ who profess to be
Catholic as the most competitive presidential election campaign
ever gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Mandela's Last Address
</P>
<P>
   President Nelson Mandela made his last address to Parliament,
saying the first post-apartheid government had laid the foundations
for a better life. Legislators put aside their differences to heap
praise on Mandela for his dedication and fairness. The head of the
largely white-supported New National Party said Mandela had managed
to rise above party politics and be everybody's president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
