<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ONBOARD27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boeing's wide-bodies built in 98-acre plant
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ The world's biggest twin-engine jet is built in
the world's largest factory.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co.'s wide-body plant in Everett, about 20 miles north of
downtown Seattle, defies the usual descriptions of big industrial
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company, 75 football fields or 10 whole
Kingdome arenas could fit inside the plant, which covers 98.3 acres
and has 2.2 miles of outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, built in 1968 and expanded in 1993, produces the 777,
747-400 and 767. Smaller narrow-body jets such as the 757 and 737
are built at another complex south of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has just under 100,000 employees in the area, even after
recent cutbacks, about one-third of them at the Everett complex.
</P>
<P>
   Each 777 consists of 3 million parts, some of them included in
prefabricated components shipped in from suppliers and others built
from scratch at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   It currently takes 45 days to assemble a 777 from start to
finish, down from 71 days when production began in 1995. The goal
is to reduce the time to 31 days by the end of this year and 20
days by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Major components are moved around the plant at night by overhead
cranes, in a delicate procedure known as ''the dance of the
cranes.'' The cranes cruise along 31 miles of overhead track, and
the operators are among the best-paid workers at the plant, since
multimillion-dollar components ride on their skill in gently
placing them in the correct spot.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing boasts that the 777 is its most precisely built aircraft,
owing to its computer-aided design and new laser alignment
processes on the assembly line. The company says fuselage sections
come within a few thousandths of an inch of perfect alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Once assembled, new planes are moved to a separate facility for
painting. While the amount varies by airline, Boeing says a typical
777 is covered by 586 pounds of paint.
</P>
<P>
   After that, planes are moved to a flight line for tests, where
they are lined up in an international parade of paint schemes
ranging from the sedate gray-blue of United to the new radical
dayglo tail design of Aeroflot, the Russian carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The first plane delivered to an airline might get a dozen or
more hours of flight testing. Once deliveries are under way, new
planes usually make only a two- or three-hour flight for certain
government-mandated checks before the customer accepts them.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, an airline could even sell tickets on the
outbound flight from Seattle. But carriers normally first take the
planes to their home base.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
