<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA27-COX     03-26 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New plane joins Delta fleet
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A huge and expensive piece of the future has arrived
for Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier took delivery Friday of its first Boeing 777, a $108
million giant that will become the carrier's premier international
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Triple 7'' is the world's biggest twin-engine airliner _
it looks like a 767 on steroids, with engines almost as big around
as a 737's fuselage _ and is the first new model Delta has added to
its fleet in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   A company delegation led by Chief Executive Leo F. Mullin
received the first 777 in a runway ceremony outside a Boeing
facility here, then rode the plane home to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously the new queen of our fleet,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, well-practiced in the art of making customers feel good
about their multimillion-dollar purchases, gave the group factory
tours Thursday and then hosted a delivery eve dinner at the
company's impressive aviation museum in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, the plane lifted off the Boeing Field runway
about 9 a.m. Seattle time (Noon EST) with two Atlanta-based
captains, Rod Smith and David Haines, at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I probably have the most enviable job in the airline
as far as pilots are concerned,'' said Smith, one of a handful who
got advance training and now will oversee instruction for others.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival in Atlanta 4 1/2 hours later, Smith and Haines flew
the 209-foot-long plane low over the runway at Hartsfield
International Airport, where Delta employees lined up outside the
airline's hangar and stared skyward.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rocked the wings back and forth in the universal aviation
greeting, then pulled the plane up and circled again for landing.
Hartsfield firetrucks gave the plane a water cannon salute as it
taxied to a gate.
</P>
<P>
   The first 777 had 13 hours of test flight time before Friday's
takeoff. It now will be used for about a month to train Delta
pilots, flight attendants, mechanics and ground handlers. It enters
service May 1 on the popular Atlanta-London route.
</P>
<P>
   Delta isn't the first airline to fly the 777. The plane is
already used by numerous airlines, including United, American and
Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Delta isn't even the first to fly it at Hartsfield; British
Airways beat it to the punch by putting a 777 on its Atlanta-London
route last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 777 delivery is a tangible symbol of Delta's
financial resurgence in the latter half of the '90s. It's part of a
massive new airplane order Delta placed in 1997, after it had
recovered from a slump that forced it to cancel most aircraft
purchases and hold on to older planes longer.
</P>
<P>
   The plane also showcases Delta's new BusinessElite international
front cabin, with electrically operated recliner seats and
expansive legroom. BusinessElite replaces separate first- and
business-class sections on international flights and is being
retrofitted in Delta's older widebodies.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is gambling that a single, improved premium-class section
will lift its service image among international business fliers,
although most airlines are sticking with a three-class approach.
</P>
<P>
   Coach passengers won't notice much dimensional difference on the
777, but it features individual video screens mounted in each coach
seatback, making Delta one of only a handful of airlines offering
the technology. In addition, the coach cabin has new seats with
padded headrests and more comfort adjustment options.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the airplane, overhead bins were designed to slope up
more sharply, creating a noticeably airier feeling and more
headroom.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's 777s are powered by Rolls Royce Trent engines that
generate 40 percent more thrust, yet more quietly, than the engines
on the smaller 767.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is buying 13 777s for $1.4 billion and will have nine by
the end of this year. The second 777 will be delivered next week
and will be deployed briefly on an Atlanta-Orlando run for training
purposes, then on a Cincinnati-London route.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also has options, or reserved production slots, on
more of the planes once its initial order is filled.
</P>
<P>
   Delta plans to use the 777 on high-volume trans-Atlantic flights
from its hubs in Atlanta, Cincinnati and New York to places like
London, Frankfurt and Paris. It will continue to use extended-range
versions of the 767, as well as the MD-11, on other international
routes.
</P>
<P>
   The airline hadn't planned to get the first 777 until later this
year, but two production slots opened about a year ago, and Delta
took them.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a 12-month turnaround from initial order to
first delivery, the shortest time since Boeing began selling the
plane, officials in Seattle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it in record time, and it's a beautiful airplane,''
said Fred Sandow, who oversees Delta's Boeing orders.
</P>
<P>
   Delta already is taking regular delivery of ``next generation''
737s that were part of the order. They are used for on short- and
medium-range domestic routes and will replace aging 727s.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also is developing an extended version of the 767, slated
for initial delivery in May 2000. Delta will use the 767-400 to
replace L-1011s in high-volume domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's 1997 Boeing order essentially committed the airline to
the Seattle-based aerospace giant as its sole airplane supplier. It
came just as Boeing encountered much-publicized production problems
that forced it to re-engineer manufacturing processes _ mainly in
the 737 program _ and overhaul management.
</P>
<P>
   Sandow said Delta ``had some concerns'' about Boeing's troubles
after placing the order but has since been satisfied they won't
significantly delay deliveries or hurt quality.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the 777 has been a huge success for Boeing, helping the
company grapple with the increasingly tough competition from
European consortium Airbus Industrie. Boeing has orders for 459
777s, and the program accounts for $9 billion of its $14 billion in
widebody sales.
</P>
<P>
   While the 777 isn't an especially distinctive airplane visually,
it has acquired a more glamorous reputation than any airliner since
the bubble-topped 747, which Delta has long eschewed as too big for
its routes.
</P>
<P>
   The 777 was the first plane designed entirely on computers and
is the first Boing aircraft to use ``fly-by-wire'' technology, in
which controls are operated by electric signals sent from the
cockpit to small motors in the wings and tail, as opposed to
cables.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing allowed PBS to film a documentary on the 777's design and
first flight, adding to popular interest in the model.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting plane for us,'' said Mary Alice Shinall, a
veteran Delta in-flight service manager who was part of the Delta
team that worked with Boeing on configuration issues.
</P>
<P>
   She likened it to the 767 bought by employees in 1983 and the
MD-11 painted in a special Olympic livery before the 1996 Atlanta
Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rank it right up there with the Spirit of Delta or the
Olympic plane,'' Shinall said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
