<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, March 26 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday passed, 58-41, a resolution supporting
President Clinton's decision to deploy air strikes against Serb
forces in the Kosovo province of Yugoslavia. Supporters said
inaction is unacceptable when innocent people are being killed and
that Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic must be contained.
Opponents said it was too risky of an endeavor and there was no
clear strategy to end the assault. A ``yes'' vote favors the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: SENATE BUD
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 55-44, a $1.7 trillion budget
plan that outlines spending goals for the next year. The plan would
cut taxes over the next several years, help finance the ailing
Social Security system and increase spending for education and
defense. Supporters of the Republican proposal said the bill saves
Social Security while still providing tax cuts and staying within
the parameters of a balanced budget. Opponents said the bill only
provides tax relief to the rich and does not adequately address the
need to save Medicare. A ``yes'' vote favors the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: EMERGENCY
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 220-211, a $1.2 billion
emergency supplemental spending bill that includes aid for Central
America, farm relief and for Jordan's implementation of the Wye
Peace accords. The measure almost failed, but the Republican
leadership held the vote open until they could lobby enough votes
to pass the bill. Opponents said while they support the intent of
the bill, they were concerned that important programs would be cut
in order to offset the cost of the package. Supporters said it is a
necessary package and therefore the offsets are justified. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: HOUSE BUD
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 221-208, a $1.7 trillion budget
plan that outlines spending goals for the next year. The plan would
cut taxes over the next few years, shore up the Social Security
system by setting aside the Social Security surplus revenue and
increase spending for education and defense. Supporters of the
Republican proposal said the bill saves Social Security while still
providing tax cuts and staying within the parameters of a balanced
budget. Opponents said the bill only provides tax relief to the
rich and does not adequately address the need to save Medicare. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
