<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAKS-FILM-REVIEW-NY     03-26 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OF FREAKS AND MEN': WINKING AT YESTERDAY'S EROTICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Russia)  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A sustained off-color joke directed with high visual
style, Aleksei Balabanov's film ``Of Freaks and Men,'' is extremely
close in mood and attitude to the work of Guy Maddin, the eccentric
Canadian director whose oddball period fantasies have earned him an
enthusiastic cult following. ``Of Freaks and Men'' is also a
striking change of direction by this Russian director, whose film
``Brother,'' a brutally powerful gangster movie set in contemporary
St. Petersburg, was respectfully received when it opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in orange sepia, ``Of Freaks and Men'' was inspired, the
director has stated, by a collection of vintage erotic photographs
of young women being flagellated. The movie, set in
turn-of-the-century St. Petersburg, takes meticulous pains to
recreate the look and atmosphere of period daguerreotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with today's X-rated fare, of course, the photographs
of women bending over and being roundly but not viciously flogged
on their bare buttocks by a stern nanny seem laughably modest.
Among other things, Balabanov's film, which New Directors/New Films
is screening Saturday night at 9 and Sunday at 12:15 p.m. at the
Museum of Modern Art, is an exercise in cultural and temporal
relativism. Yesterday's naughty erotica, it reminds us with a wink,
is today's quaintly exotic detritus.
</P>
<P>
   Around these old photographs, the director has constructed a
whimsical melodrama about the corrupting influence of erotica on
two interconnected St. Petersburg families, as well as an allegory
on the genesis of Russian movie pornography. Although it is a
talking picture, ``Of Freaks and Men'' uses inter-titles between
scenes and a physically exaggerated acting style to evoke the
silent film era.
</P>
<P>
   The heads of the two households into which the erotic pictures
infiltrate like a poison gas are a railroad engineer (Igor
Shibanov) and the doctor (Aleksandr Mazentsev) treating him for a
heart condition. Among those obsessed with the pictures are the
engineer's daughter (Dinara Drukarova) and the doctor's housekeeper
(Tatyana Polonskaya).
</P>
<P>
   Other characters include the grim, poker-faced pioneering
photographer (Sergei Makovetsky), his fiendish gap-toothed
assistant and smut peddler, Siamese twins (under the doctor's care)
who are temperamental opposites (one is a goody-good, the other a
hopeless drunk) and the doctor's beautiful blind wife (Lika
Nevolina), who becomes a photographic subject.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean? Not terribly much. Beyond being a witty,
inventive exercise of historical imagination and cinematic style,
``Of Freaks and Men'' is a movie that remains emotionally locked
inside its own dream world. It is the film equivalent of watching a
vintage tableau vivant re-enacted on a stage: an elegant curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `OF FREAKS AND MEN'
</P>
<P>
   Written (in Russian, with English subtitles) and directed by
Aleksei Balabanov; director of photography, Sergei Astakhov; edited
by Marina Lipartia; production designer, Vera Zelinskaya; produced
by Sergei Selyanov and Oleg Botogov.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sergei Makovetsky (Johann), Dinara Drukarova (Lisa),
Viktor Sukhorukov (Viktor Ivanovich), Lika Nevolina (Yekaterina
Kirilovna), Igor Shibanov (Radlov), Aleksandr Mazentsev (Dr.
Stasov), Tatyana Polonskaya (Darya) and Alyesha De and Chinghiz
Tsydendabayev (Kolya and Tolya). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0327-     03-26 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO STRIKES BEGIN TARGETING SERB FORCES, BUT STILL SAYS NO TO
GROUND TROOPS
 &HT;    EDs: With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0327.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American-led NATO forces entered a new phase of
airstrikes against Yugoslavia on Friday, increasingly targeting
Serb army and police forces amid growing concern about atrocities
against ethnic Albanians in the southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The subtle evolution of the NATO air strategy came as the White
House sought to end speculation that NATO ground forces would
eventually be necessary to force Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to accept a peace plan for Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians
have been fighting for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of using ground troops in this
circumstance,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart emphasized
Friday after NATO warplanes shot down two of Yugoslavia's
Soviet-made MiG-29 jet fighters over neighboring Bosnia -- a
dramatic example of how the conflict over Kosovo was spilling
outside the borders of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said allied forces have yet to
determine the intentions of the MiG pilots, but acknowledged that
one possibility was an attack on the 30,000 peacekeeping forces
under NATO command in Bosnia. Those forces include 6,900 Americans
from the 1st Cavalry Division based at Fort Hood, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the third night of NATO bombing against Milosevic,
the heaviest yet in the conflict in ``Operation: Allied Force,'' as
the mission is known, continued to strike Yugoslavia's formidable
air defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea, basically, is to try to make the skies as safe as
possible for our pilots so then they can begin concentrating on the
next goal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as we make progress against the air defense system -- and
we have made progress, particularly against its command and control
elements -- we are gradually increasing the emphasis on attacking
targets in Kosovo itself, particularly the Serb army . . . and the
Serb special police,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Serbia, one of the two states making up
the current Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon suggested that bombing targets had been ``recalibrated''
as a result of ``very disturbing reports'' of brutality by Serb
forces against ethnic Albanians, including executions of civilians
and the destruction of villages. Although the reports are
unconfirmed, ``there is reason to fear for the worst, and we do
fear for the worst,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin voiced the same concern
earlier in the day, saying the United States is ``extremely
alarmed'' by the reports of atrocities in Kosovo. He noted that war
crimes ``have no statute of limitations'' and that Serb commanding
officers and political leaders could be held responsible for the
actions of subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing began three days ago, NATO planes have
concentrated mostly on Yugoslavia's air defense system. At the same
time, however, they have struck at Serb military targets in Kosovo,
including troop headquarters, fuel supplies and ammunition storage
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``As these strikes continue over the following days, we will, as
appropriate, increase the concentration and focus on targets within
Kosovo itself,'' Bacon said. He did not provide any details
concerning about the timing or targeting of the campaign in the
coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very clear from the beginning that our goal is in
fact to degrade Milosevic's ability to continue his predations
against the Kosovar Albanians. And we are turning to that goal,''
he added. ``Whether it's air defenses, whether it's air force --
offensive air force or defensive air force -- whether it's his
ground troops, we are working to suppress them, to whittle them
back, to shrink them down, to make them less potent, and we are
having some impact.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0327-     03-26 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO STRIKES BEGIN TARGETING SERB FORCES, BUT STILL SAYS NO TO
GROUND TROOPS
 &HT;    EDs: With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0327.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
