<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE MINNESOTA TWINS WHO PLAY FOR GEORGIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Ga. N.C., Ohio, Tenn.)   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE , Calif. _ After three years of a Tennessee waltz, you
needed a game program this time around to help with all the new
faces taking their rightful control of the women's Final Four.
Peppi Browne, the Duke defensive ace who chased Chamique Holdsclaw
all the way to the end of her college career, only needed to
distinguish between two.
</P>
<P>
   Her assignment Friday night in the national semifinal against
Georgia was a Miller twin, possibly Kelly, probably Coco, maybe
whoever had the hotter hand. It's a good thing these Duke players
are so academic, so observant, because the only way to tell the
Millers apart is by number, or by freckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly has one right here that I don't have,'' Coco said,
pointing to her left cheek. Go ahead, Coach. Break that down in
your pre-game films.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game Friday night, it was the so-called Duke Double
against the Miller twins. Would Joe Alleva, the Duke athletic
director, have to return by private jet from the men's site in St.
Petersburg, Fla., for the women's title game Sunday night? Or would
the Millers play on to confuse one last opponent?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was reported recently that there were 17 sets of
twins playing Division I women's basketball this season. None were
as good, or as alike, as the Millers, the 5-foot-10-inch sophomores
out of Mayo High School in Rochester, Minn., who this season each
averaged slightly more than 18 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   This undoubtedly came as no surprise to the researchers at the
University of Minnesota, who, according to Coco, after a one-day
study three years ago found them to be the most corresponding set
of twins they had ever come across.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us math tests, reading tests, random questions, and
we just about scored the same,'' she said. She smiled and shrugged,
apparently used to such uniformity by now. Their SAT scores were
roughly equivalent. They are both majoring in pre-med, with 3.5
grade point averages. Kelly has produced better statistics during
the tournament, but Coco has Georgia's single-game record of 45
points. In the best game they ever played together, in high school,
they combined for 68 points. Thirty-four apiece.
</P>
<P>
   They have shared clothes, a room, ball-handling
responsibilities. They enjoy the same food. When placed in
different classes after first grade, they confounded teachers at
recess by gravitating to the same friends. When they got on the
plane after their visit to Athens, Ga., they immediately agreed
that Andy Landers was the coach for them.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, he had coached two sets of twins and recognized
that, sooner or later, there had to be some separation, for the
sake of themselves and their team. He focuses on what each does
better. Kelly's rebounding. Coco's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly is more calculating, taking advantage of what the
defense gives her,'' said Landers, which is why he made her the
point guard. ``Coco is more attack-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Landers is rubbing off on them. On Thursday, practice day,
Coco wore a gray Georgia sweatshirt and blue jeans. Kelly wore the
sweatshirt, with blue jeans shorts.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, no such luck; they wear their hair in ponytails,
with bangs, and sweatbands on the left elbow. Duke's Browne decided
to spend Thursday crunching numbers: Kelly, 23. Coco, 35. The rules
say you can't switch jerseys, a prank they sometimes pull in
practice that always works.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Miller presented the challenge of Holdsclaw, for whom
Browne had been preparing for years against boys, on the black tops
of Akron, Ohio. But Duke needed to handle one of them, at least, if
it was going to keep Alleva from taking Sunday off in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever differences Landers has found in the Miller twins,
about all the Duke men's and women's programs have in common is a
campus and a gym. Shouldn't an enlightened institution of higher
learning and basketball tradition be a tad embarrassed that it took
so long to grow a women's team? Its recruiting budget was a
minuscule $10,000 when Gail Goestenkors took over as coach in 1992.
Now Duke is big-time, doubling its pleasure, trying to survive a
case of double Miller vision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
