</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield ending `broken' marriage
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield filed for divorce from his wife,
Janice, on Friday in Fayette County Superior Court, effectively
ending a marriage he has admitted was a mistake from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of the divorce complaint comes six months after
Holyfield publicly admitted fathering two children out of wedlock
during his marriage to Janice Holyfield, his second wife, and two
weeks after Holyfield's stature in boxing was damaged in a disputed
draw with Lennox Lewis for the unified heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Evander and Janice Holyfield have been separated since July and
living in separate houses on the same Fayette County estate.
Neither returned phone calls Friday. Barry McGough, Holyfield's
divorce attorney, also did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's long-time attorney, said, ``Evander
still has the highest regard for Janice, and we are hopeful that
all the issues can be worked out amicably.''
</P>
<P>
   John Mayoue, Janice Holyfield's attorney, declined to comment on
the case ``until after I've had a chance to review the pleadings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the complaint, Holyfield seeks divorce from the former Dr.
Janice Itson, whom he married Oct. 4, 1996; joint custody of the
couple's 6-month-old son, Elijah; and a judgment that would allow
him to keep ``all of his separate property'' and ``an equitable
portion of the marital property.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holyfield's marriage ``is irretrievably broken and there
exists no possibility of reconciliation,'' the complaint reads.
Holyfield also requested a mediator for negotiations and asked that
the details of the settlement remain private.
</P>
<P>
   The Holyfields did not have a signed prenuptial agreement. But
attached to the complaint was a transcript of an alleged telephone
conversation on Oct. 22, 1996, between Janice Holyfield and Thomas,
in which she gives the attorney her approval to an agreement. The
transcript quotes Janice as saying, in the case of divorce, ``I
will agree to a settlement of whatever Evander feels is
equitable.''
</P>
<P>
   A letter stating as much was typed up by the law firm of Long,
Aldridge and Norman. But if Janice Holyfield ever signed it, she
never returned it to Holyfield's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Holyfield said he realized almost immediately
after his marriage to Janice that he did not love her but that the
two went through counseling, at her request, to try to work out
their problems. But soon after, Holyfield resumed his problems with
infidelity, which was a basis for the divorce from his first wife,
Paulette, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Holyfield impregnated two women, then suggested
to Janice that they divorce ``quietly,'' so she could avoid
humiliation. But she declined and the two remained married.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said at the time, ``If Janice had said, `Well, let's
go,' it would have made things a lot easier. I thought it would be
better to do it right away rather than wait five years, and then
say you made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holyfields stayed married, and Janice became pregnant in
February 1998. Elijah Jedediah Holfield was born Sept. 11. Janice
and the child have been living in Holyfield's older home; Evander
has been staying in the new mansion next door.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has nine children: three with his first wife Paulette,
one with Janice; and five others with four women out of wedlock.
Paulette Holyfield received a divorce settlement of approximately
$4 million in 1991 after six years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has grossed $205 million in ring purses in his pro
career, including $92 million for his last five fights during his
marriage to Janice.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield met Janice at a religious crusade in Philadelphia in
1994. The two dated briefly, then and became friends later. In
1996, Holyfield asked Janice, who was practicing medicine in
Chicago at the time, to help care for his children while he was in
training in Houston for a fight against Mike Tyson. It was during
that period that he resumed his relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   Very few people, even those close to Holyfield, knew about it
when he flew back to Atlanta one weekend in October to marry
Janice. The two were wed by a justice of the peace.
</P>
<P>
   In ensuing weeks, Holyfield asked Janice to take over some of
his business dealings. She oversaw Holyfield Management and, later,
the Holyfield Foundation. She still has voice-mail in the office
but, according to Thomas, no longer works there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
