<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE OF BUSINESS _ AND FINANCIAL JOURNALISM _ IS ELECTRONIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, The New York Times Co. (which owns The Boston
Globe) announced that it would expend $15 million in cash and
services to obtain a minority interest in a financial news Web site
called TheStreet.com. News of the Times's investment preceded by
one day the announcement that Goldman Sachs would soon take
TheStreet.com public.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com is one of the best financial-news Web sites on the
Internet. Its initial public offering is likely to be a smash hit
on Wall Street. So it is not inconceivable that the Times's
interest in TheStreet.com is purely financial _ make a quick buck
on the IPO and get out just as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But the more likely scenario is that the Times has considered
the way it does business and the way TheStreet.com does business
and decided that the on-line business model might just be the
future of financial journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The cost structure of on-line journalism, financial or
otherwise, is revolutionary. Gone are the massive expenditures on
paper, ink, and other materials. Gone are the huge printing plants
in cities and towns across a wide geographic area. Gone are the
hundreds of trucks needed to physically ship the finished product
hither and yon. Gone are the motor pools and gasoline depots needed
to keep the trucks rolling. What remains are a few dozen Sun
Microsystems or IBM servers locked away in a basement somewhere,
connecting consumers to the journalistic product.
</P>
<P>
   Once established, Web sites like TheStreet.com are free to
devote the majority of their working capital to editorial concerns.
One of the oldest rules of off-line journalism is that 85 percent
of expenditure goes to circulation and 15 percent goes to
editorial. The new rules of on-line journalism are that 20 to 35
percent goes to marketing, advertising, and distribution and all
the rest goes toward maintaining and upgrading editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   One does not have to be a rocket scientist to ``get'' that
eventually the higher quality editorial product will win out. This
is especially true in the field of financial journalism. People who
have their life savings invested in the bond and stock markets are
highly motivated to gather the best available information about
those investments. News organizations that are able to spend the
most money on editorial will eventually offer the best available
information. It really is that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most on-line journalism is really just off-line
journalism digitally converted for Web consumption. One can read
this column in the Boston Globe newspaper or on the Boston Globe's
Web site, but it's the exact same column. In the next 10 years,
however, on-line journalism will quickly become a journalistic
force unto itself. Nowhere will this be more true than in the
category of business and financial news.
</P>
<P>
   There are three reasons why. First, the technological
infrastructure will be fully operational. Consumers of business and
financial news already are disproportionately techno-capable. Once
the system is up and humming, they'll be even more addicted to its
use. Second, consumers of business and financial news will need and
demand real-time news services. Since they are, by demographic
definition, the most attractive targets for advertisers, they'll
get what they want.
</P>
<P>
   Third, and perhaps most important, the world's financial markets
are likely to merge into one 24-hour-a-day, 7-days-a-week global
supermarket. The New York Stock Exchange has already announced
plans to extend its trading day into the evening. European and
Asian markets would like nothing better than to merge with Wall
Street to create a market available at all times to a global
customer base via the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Once the markets go ``24-7,'' time is altered. Today, US
financial markets open at 9:30 a.m. and close at 4 p.m. Stuff
happens. Journalists write stories about what happened. Editors
check those stories for accuracy, and everybody is home for dinner
by 7 o'clock. The paper is printed later in the evening, delivered
the next morning, but the information contained therein is still
accurate until the opening bell rings at half past nine.
</P>
<P>
   In 24-7 time, however, the market is always open. Stocks that
are selling at $10 a share at 4 p.m. might be selling for $6 at
midnight. In this environment, the newspaper version of business
and financial news is literally untenable. Who would read a stock
table page based on information that was eight hours old?
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, the only place to get business and
financial ``news'' would be on the World Wide Web. Off-line
reporters are quite literally out of business. The only people who
can cover this brave new world are on-line journalists, because
they are the only ones who are technologically capable of providing
accurate information in real time.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers today are divided up into sections. The one section
that will be completely transformed by technology in the next 10
years is business. By the year 2010, it won't be all the business
and financial news that's fit to print. It will be all the business
and financial news that's fit to double-click.
</P>
<P>
   John Ellis is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
