<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-26 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSES CONTRIBUTE TO DUDLEY SQUARE'S HIGH RATE OF ASTHMA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tiny swatch of open space outside Dudley Square _ just a
median strip, really _ has come to symbolize the fastest-growing
political movement in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   There, a tidy memorial is dedicated to Walter Reid Kirnon, a
14-year-old Fort Hill boy who died of asthma in 1996. Many of his
neighbors believe he was a victim of the air pollution that chokes
the neighborhood daily. And they believe the Massachusetts Bay
Transportation Authority is ultimately to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the MBTA's 970 diesel-fueled buses are housed in or near
Dudley Square, serving a community that relies on public
transportation, but also, residents believe, contributing mightily
to the highest incidence of asthma in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   While the causes of asthma are complex, there is growing
agreement that pollution plays a significant role, along with
deteriorating housing stock, poor access to health care, and other
environmental factors. According to city health statistics,
hospitalizations for asthma are 11.2 per 1,000 residents in
Roxbury, more than five times the statewide average of 2.1 per
1,000 residents. Even MBTA officials acknowledge that the diesel
buses contribute to the high rate of asthma in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Monday with MBTA officials, residents will once
again ask Massachusetts to join New York, Los Angeles, Atlanta, and
Cleveland in modernizing its bus fleet by gradually phasing out
diesel in favor of buses that run on alternative fuels, such as
compressed natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of six groups _ including Alternatives for Community
and Environment, the Bowdoin Street Health Center, the Egleston
Square Neighborhood Association, the Committee for Boston Public
Housing, the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group, and the
Union of Concerned Scientists _ has organized residents to call on
the T to cut emissions in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that we wanted to focus on diesel buses, in
particular, because we, as the bus riders and taxpayers, pay for
that system,'' said Penn Loh, associate director of Alternatives
for Community and Environment. ``It makes no sense to pay 60 cents
for a system that's polluting us and choking us.''
</P>
<P>
   If coalition members expect the T to pull the buses off the
road, they shouldn't hold their breath. They can probably look
forward to vague promises and pledges, with no due date, backed by
little political will, if the state responds as it has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The MBTA has taken some tentative steps to reduce pollution: The
400 diesel buses it has purchased in the past four years run as
much as 85 percent cleaner, and buses are idling less, reducing
exhaust. But those steps fall short of what is needed.
</P>
<P>
   T officials might have a greater sense of urgency if they spent
some time talking to Tamika Davis, a 15-year-old who lives near
Dudley Square, in the area city health officials refer to as
Boston's ``asthma belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamika would tell them she is treated at Boston Medical Center
approximately every other month for a condition that seems to
worsen the more she travels around her neighborhood. Despite a
regimen that includes pills, inhalers, and a nebulizing machine,
Tamika's capacity to breathe has steadily worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her what she thinks the cause is, and Tamika says simply,
``It's probably the buses and the pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Herzenberg, deputy chief operating officer of the MBTA,
says the agency accepts the notion that its buses are serious
polluters whose emissions damage the health of residents. But at a
cost of $250,000 per bus, the agency has no plans to just abandon
diesel buses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The MBTA has agreed to a small pilot project to determine what
alternative fuel source it should consider in the future. But
Herzenberg made it clear that the current diesel buses will run
until they can't any longer, which means the T will likely operate
diesel buses for almost another decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our buses are only four years old,'' Herzenberg said.
``We're not going to throw them out. We're going to get the useful
life out of these buses.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pathetic. The MBTA owes more to the health and quality of
life of those it serves than to simply shrug at disease and death,
while its officials blandly quote figures from a balance sheet. The
technology to end this environmental outrage exists. It's time for
Massachusetts to finally take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
