<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-GRAY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traffic stop nabs Gray
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hawks backup guard Ed Gray, arrested Thursday on a
number of traffic violations, faces suspension if found guilty of
charges of driving under the influence and possession of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Results from an April 27 court appearance will determine Gray's
fate. If he is found guilty, Hawks general manager Pete Babcock
said, the team would seek ``the harshest'' penalty permitted
against Gray under the recently negotiated collective bargaining
agreement. NBA spokeswoman Teri Washington said the degree of
punishment is at the team's discretion, meaning that the Hawks
could suspend him for part or all of the season. The club also
could decide to release him.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the 76ers' Allen Iverson and then-Trail Blazers
Isaiah Rider and Clifford Robinson _ Robinson is now with Phoenix _
were involved in marijuana incidents, and their teams did not
suspend them. However, commissioner David Stern intervened and
sidelined them from one to three games.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock sounded as if he would not need Stern's persuasion in
punishing Gray, 23, who also would have to receive treatment and
counseling under the NBA's marijuana program. Gray will fly to New
York on Monday to meet with NBA security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are the facts,'' Babcock said. ``I met with the team
and with Ed individually, and I told them both that when you're a
member of the family, we'll help you, whether it's legal help or
counseling. At the same time, however, if he's found guilty, I told
him that he'll be penalized in the harshest manner allowed under
the new (labor agreement).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious, serious issue. When you're talking about a
DUI, you're talking a blatant disregard for other people's lives,
because you put other people's lives at risk. We're very surprised
and extremely disappointed and concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   A state trooper stopped Gray's 1991 BMW about 8 p.m. Thursday
near downtown Atlanta after noticing that the car's windows were
tinted darker than state law allows and that his California tags
had expired, spokesman Gordy Wright of the Georgia Department of
Public Safety said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the trooper found in the car less than an ounce of
marijuana and an open container of alcohol. In addition to drug
possession and DUI, he said, Gray was charged with driving with an
open container of alcohol and driving on a suspended and revoked
license. Blood-alcohol tests are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Gray had no comment Friday after the Hawks' shoot-around for
their game with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, a 1997 first-round draft pick making $866,600 this season,
was suspended four games and fined a total of $57,000 last year for
being late for games and practices and for missing medical
appointments during rehabilitation after foot surgery. This season,
he was late for practice just once, but his history, the
seriousness of the pending charges and the fact that he has had a
poor season so far _ shooting 25 percent from the floor _ could
place his Hawks career in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Gray is the third Hawk recently to run afoul of drug laws. In
1996, point guard Mookie Blaylock pleaded guilty to possession of
56 grams of marijuana in a Vancouver suburb and was given absolute
discharge by the court.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, former backup center Greg ``Cadillac'' Anderson
pleaded guilty to one count of possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
