<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S BURGESS CONSIDERING UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Duke sophomore and Orange County native
Chris Burgess confirmed Friday that he has considered transferring
to UCLA after the season but won't make a decision for at least
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of talk about it,'' Burgess said. ``It
might go through my mind. But right now, I'm not thinking about it.
It's a burden. It's a stress, and we don't need that distraction.
We'll see, whatever the future holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgess, who is Mormon, ruled out Brigham Young as a possible
destination but said he'd consider Utah and/or a church mission.
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically about UCLA, he said: ``Sometimes I think
about it, because it's been a frustrating year.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgess, a 6-foot-10 forward/center, is averaging 16 minutes per
game. His best friend is UCLA manager Jason Tilton, a former
teammate at Woodbridge High in Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   He hinted that his future may hinge on two factors: whether Duke
center Elton Brand stays in school or bolts for the NBA, and
whether highly touted recruit Carlos Boozer signs with the Blue
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Boozer, a 6-8 forward, is also considering UCLA and St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie's secret: Ohio State junior guard Scoonie Penn has shown
no effects of sitting out last season after transferring from
Boston College. Averaging 17.1 points, Penn was named Big Ten
Player of the Year and third-team All-American.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 48 points in two games in the South Regional in
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ``His approach to practice really helped him,'' said second-year
Buckeyes coach Jim O'Brien, who was at Boston College with Penn.
``We told him, `Treat your practices like your games. Try to win
every situation.' That's what happened. In practice, he was playing
with three or four walk-ons, and they'd beat our starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think his familiarity helped. He was much more familiar
with what we wanted to do than the kids who had been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hello, again: Duke and Michigan State played Dec. 2 in the Great
Eight in Chicago. The Blue Devils, who had lost to Cincinnati four
days earlier, jumped to a 17-2 lead and held on for a 73-67
victory.
</P>
<P>
   What effect will that game have today? After coming so close,
the Spartans probably think they can win. Then again, Duke knows to
be wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a much different team,'' Michigan State coach Tom Izzo
said. ``We're a lot better than we were, and they're a lot, lot
better than they were.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-timers: Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski is making his
eighth Final Four appearance. O'Brien, Izzo and Connecticut's Jim
Calhoun are making their first.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as if it's an advantage or not, I don't know,''
Krzyzewski said. ``What I learned is you can't do everything for
for all the people that ask of you. You have to do as much as
possible for the people who are closest to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaskan connection: Duke senior Trajan Langdon is an Anchorage
native who attended grade school with folk singer Jewel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a biology class together, lab partners for a
semester,'' Langdon said. ``I guess it was my sophomore year (at
Duke), and Mateen (Cleaves, of Michigan State) came up to me and
said, `Do you know Jewel? She's from Alaska.' I was shocked she had
gotten to the level she had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
