<SLUG> BC-WALKS-MASSACHUSETTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING IS AS GOOD A TIME AS ANY TO TAKE A WALK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't quite say that spring comes to Eastern Massachusetts.
It comes, then goes, comes again and then probably goes again _ by
which time, it's summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's still early in the season, and it could still snow. But it
also could turn sunny and 55. And, as Henry Lee of the Friends of
the Public Garden says, ``it's sometimes good just to see a few
signs of things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   So, after four months of frost, it's time to slip outside to
seek the early bloom of the season, whether in its coming or going
mode. The perfect early spring walk requires some planning. You'll
want a sheltered walk to keep the elements at bay; a gentle one,
because the days themselves can still be rugged enough; and a
close-at-hand walk in case the weather shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Covering those criteria, here are six early spring walks, most
recommended by the people who know them best:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: The Public Garden
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit thin now,'' says Lee, but there should be a good
show of crocuses and daffodils this weekend, and there is still
some color in the witch hazels along Beacon Street. It's not really
a place for wildlife (the best known in the garden is man-made: the
swan boats, due back in mid-April, and the ``Make Way for
Ducklings'' sculpture), but Lee says to keep an eye out for
red-tailed hawks. ``We have three or four all the time,'' he says.
``They go after the squirrels and pigeons.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: The closest T stop is Arlington on the Green
Line.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Boston Parks Department. 617-635-7381. Free.
</P>
<P>
   QUINCY/MILTON: Blue Hills Skyline Trail
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge,'' admits MDC Ranger Maggi Brown (9 miles,
start to finish, over some rough terrain), but this is the best
time of year to make the hike, or part of it _ precisely because
the best views from the hilltops are now, before the trees begin to
leaf out. On a clear day you'll see Wachusett Mountain, some 40
miles to the west, and Mount Monadnock, some 80 miles to the
northwest. And there may be turkey vultures in the sky overhead.
``They're fun to watch,'' says Brown. ``They tend to soar a lot and
stay in one spot so you can watch them for hours _ so bring a
lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Park at either end, at the Shea Rink on Willard
Street, Quincy, or by Houghton's Pond near the MDC Headquarters on
Hillside Street in Milton.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Metropolitan District Commission. 617-698-1802.
Free. Maps available at headquarters 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH NATICK: Broadmoor Wildlife Sanctuary
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place where you can come and walk in undisturbed
nature,'' says Elissa Landre, sanctuary director of the
Massachusetts Aubudon Society. In the next few weeks, a new
overlook at the sanctuary's vernal pond will be an attraction. The
skunk cabbage is just coming up, and in the pond there may be wood
ducks, along with bugs and beetles, and perhaps painted turtles
basking in the sun. Overhead, Landre says, the spring bird
migration is on, and ``there's something new turning up every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: 280 Eliot St., South Natick, 1.8 miles west of
South Natick Center on Route 16. Visitor Center open 9 to 5
weekdays, 10 to 5 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Massachusetts Audubon Society. 508-655-2296 or
781-235-3929. Free to Audubon members, $3 for nonmember adults, $2
for nonmember children. Maps available at Visitor Center. No dogs
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   HINGHAM: World's End Reservation
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest spot this time of year,'' says Michael
Tougias, author of ``Nature Walks in Eastern Massachusetts'' and
``More Nature Walks in Eastern Massachusetts.'' The winds off the
ocean are ``getting balmy after the winter chill,'' and there may
still be some sea ducks lingering before they head offshore. A
favorite spot for Tougias is the cliffs on Rocky Neck, which juts
out into the Weir River. And, he says, ``there's a `big sky'
feeling when you walk out on the drumlins.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: From Route 3A at the Hingham Rotary, east 0.3
miles on Summer Street, left on Martins Lane. Open dawn to dusk.
Warning: Parking is tightly limited.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Trustees of Reservations: 781-821-2977. Free to
trustees, members, and children under 12, $4 for adults.
</P>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER: Ravenswood Park
</P>
<P>
   There's a scenic hike here. And, if there's an early spring
snow, there could be good cross-country skiing and snowshoeing
along the 10 miles of trails and carriage roads maintained by the
Trustees of Reservations. The trails provide views of Gloucester
Harbor to the east as they cross through fields of glacial
erratics, or boulders, a glimpse into the last glacial retreat from
the Massachusetts coast. The trail through Great Magnolia Swamp
leads into the northernmost locale of sweet bay magnolia (from
which the neighboring village of Magnolia gets its name).
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Off Western Avenue. Two miles south on Route 127,
from the junction with Route 133. Open dawn to dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Trustees of Reservations: 978-356-4351. Free.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON: Wachusett Mountain
</P>
<P>
   Time for making plans. There may be a few early hawks migrating
north already, but large groups probably won't arrive before
mid-April, according to Paul Roberts, head of the Eastern
Massachusetts Hawk Watch. Most common are broad-winged hawks, and
the best times for watching are mornings when there's a southwest
wind. The best viewing is from the ledges near the overlook on the
southwest side of the mountain, reached by a trail (a little over a
mile, and steep in places) from the Department of Environmental
Management's Visitor Center. Along the trail, look for spring
wildflowers just coming into bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: From Route 2, take Route 140 south 3.7 miles to
Mile Hill Road. Follow the road past the ski area to the Visitor
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Department of Environmental Management.
617-727-3180. Trail maps available at Visitor Center. Free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
