<HEADER>
A5980 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEVORKIAN-670&AMP;ADD-NYT     03-26 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVORKIAN CONVICTED OF 2ND-DEGREE MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who claims he has helped
more than 130 people to commit suicide, was convicted Friday of
murder for giving a fatal injection to a man with a terminal
illness.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trial that people on both sides of the assisted-suicide
debate believe will have a profound impact on future discussion of
this contentious, emotional subject now that the most visible and
controversial proponent of euthanasia and assisted suicide could
spend much of the rest of his life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, 70, was convicted in the death of Thomas Youk, a
52-year-old man from a Detroit suburb, who suffered from
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease. Prosecutors
had originally charged Kevorkian with first-degree murder in Youk's
death. First-degree murder involves premeditation, but the jury,
which deliberated for 13 hours, returned a verdict of second-degree
murder, which does not.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian faces a minimum sentence of 10 to 25 years in prison
on the murder charge. Kevorkian, whose medical license has been
revoked in Michigan, also faces up to seven years in prison on a
second charge, delivery of a controlled substance.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian reacted impassively as the jury read its verdict,
blinking several times as he looked toward the jury box. Released
on bond until sentencing in mid-April, he declined to speak with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fifth time in a decade that prosecutors had tried
Kevorkian for his role in the deaths of seriously ill people. Three
trials ended in acquittals, while a fourth ended in a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, Kevorkian was charged not with murder but with
violating laws against assisted suicide, for helping people to use
a contraption called a ``suicide machine'' to give themselves fatal
injections. Juries in those cases had been swayed by emotional
statements from the families of the dead, who defended Kevorkian's
actions as compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   But this trial was different because prosecutors had unusually
direct evidence: a videotape Kevorkian made of himself injecting
Youk with lethal chemicals last September. Kevorkian brought the
tape to the CBS News program ``60 Minutes,'' which broadcast it in
November, along with an interview in which Kevorkian dared
prosecutors to file charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kevorkian was charged with murder, the judge instructed
the jury that the issue of whether Youk consented to his death was
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we knew it wasn't, was it wasn't assisted
suicide on trial,'' said a juror, a young man who would not
disclose his name. ``That was unequivocal. I mean we knew why we
were there.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``what it came down to was the evidence proved
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strikingly short trial in which Kevorkian insisted on
defending himself, betraying his lack of legal skill as he asked
legally impermissible questions and failed to persuade the judge
that his proposed witnesses were relevant to the case. Likening
himself to such heroic figures as Martin Luther King Jr. and Rosa
Parks, he appealed to the jury to send a message that laws against
euthanasia and assisted suicide were unjust.
</P>
<P>
   The same juror, the only one of the 12 who would speak to a
reporter, said the jury was not influenced by Kevorkian's
self-representation. But he said: ``There wasn't much defense. All
we were left with was the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The juror said that he perceived Kevorkian to be telling the
jury, ```Here's the tape. Now make a decision as to whether
assisted suicide is going to go on.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that wasn't what that was about,'' the juror said.
``We knew it was about the facts, we knew it was about a murder
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian's lawyer, David Gorosh, said the defense would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is certainly unjust to try to equate an act of
compassion with an act of murder,'' Gorosh said. ``What he did was
a complete act of mercy. He was invited into the Youk home. Tom
Youk requested help, and he was suffering.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prosecutors had originally charged Kevorkian with assisted
suicide as well as murder, but they dropped that charge when Judge
Jessica Cooper ruled that the defense could present testimony about
Youk's pain and suffering with an assisted-suicide charge and not
with a murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   John Skrzynski, the lead prosecutor on the case, said the
decision to drop the assisted-suicide charge, considered a huge
gamble at the time, ultimately proved successful.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Youk's wife and brother could not testify and,
apart from the videotape, which showed how much Youk was suffering
when he was alive, no testimony was presented about Youk's painful
condition and his apparent desire to end his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trials in the past were always emotionally based,''
Skrzynski said. ``We tried to put it on a legal playing field, not
an emotional playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, Youk's wife, Melody, and brother, Terrence,
hurried out of the courthouse without speaking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The trial attracted people with strong passions about assisted
suicide and euthanasia, both supporters and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Girsch, executive director of the Hemlock Society, was
dismayed by the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``To call it murder is barbaric,'' she said. ``It highlights the
necessity to change the law all over the country and in the world
so that a compassionate physician can help a suffering patient
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Coleman, the founder and president of a group of disabled
people who have given themselves the name ``Not Dead Yet,'' was
heartened.
</P>
<P>
   She said the euthanasia movement was ``very threatening to a
disabled person,'' and added, ``I hope this will send a message
that this steamroller has got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrzynski was asked after the trial if he felt this would
silence Kevorkian, who has been flamboyant and outspoken in his
advocacy of euthanasia and assisted suicide, sometimes in ways that
alienated people who might be inclined to support his position on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silence him?'' Skrzynski said. ``I think as a practical matter
he'll go to prison and you know, prisoners don't usually have press
conferences. And I think he's going to be surprised that he's not
going to be able to maintain the public interest in the media that
he's gotten in the past once he becomes a prisoner. In a way he
kind of silenced himself by doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorosh said Kevorkian's views would ultimately be vindicated and
``Dr. Kevorkian will be lauded as a hero in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Judge Cooper, who was patient with
Kevorkian's legal stumbling, implored him to allow himself to be
represented by lawyers. He refused, saying he felt he could express
his views to the jury better.
</P>
<P>
   But once the jury began deliberating, Gorosh, frustrated because
he was relegated to whispering advice to Kevorkian during the
trial, said he told his client, ``'There's nothing left for you to
argue here. These are legal issues that are better served by
lawyers who are experienced.'''
</P>
<P>
   So on Friday, Kevorkian asked Judge Cooper if his lawyers could
represent him from then on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now?'' the judge asked, before granting his request.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian has said he would starve himself if sent to jail, and
both Gorosh and prosecutors said Friday that they hoped that would
not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Skrzynski was asked if he had created a martyr. He replied, ``I
created an inmate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
