<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-MEETING-NYT &LR;      03-26 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH WARY ON INFLATION, FED LIKELY TO LEAVE RATES UNCHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve is almost certain to leave
interest rates unchanged when its policy-making committee meets
Tuesday, but the central bank remains wary of resurgent inflation
because of the economy's continued strength, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   With overall price increases negligible and growth appearing to
slow a bit from the blistering pace at the end of 1998, the Fed has
no rationale for an immediate rate increase, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank's Federal Open Market Committee, meeting
for the second time this year, may move toward adopting a policy
bias favoring higher rates _ a tilt that would put financial
markets on warning that a rate increase might be in the cards in
coming months. Still, analysts put the chances of the Fed adopting
a tightening bias next week at well under 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is absolutely on hold,'' said Bank of America chief
economist Mickey Levy. ``While the economy is strong and the
unemployment rate very low, inflation remains low and increases in
wages have actually diminished,'' Levy said. ``Then there are the
international considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   The global financial crisis that prompted the Fed to cut rates
three times in quarter-point increments last fall has eased
considerably. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said in congressional
testimony in February that the improved situation in the markets
could eventually justify taking back some portion of those rate
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil's stabilization is tenuous, and Fed officials are not
convinced that Japan's economic slide has bottomed out. So the Fed,
analysts say, remains wary about the effects on the rest of the
world of a rate increase in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, it is the economic weakness in much of the rest
of the world that is keeping the United States from overheating.
The monthly trade deficit hit a record of nearly $17 billion in
January, meaning that a growing volume of imports and declining
exports are taking some of the pressure off domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
   The hit from trade appears to be enough to slow the overall rate
of growth in the economy, analysts said. Moreover, higher interest
rates over the last month are beginning to slow the main engine of
the expansion these days _ consumer spending _ in part by cooling
what had been a red-hot housing market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be some concern about the pace of domestic
spending,'' said Robert DiClemente, an economist at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``Yet it's quite plausible that market forces themselves
will bring about some kind of tempering without any active role
from the Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still a debate within the Fed over the reasons behind
the unusual combination of robust growth and stable prices. On one
side are those who say the economy is simply benefiting from a
confluence of temporary factors that are holding down inflation for
now. On the other is a faction that thinks something fundamental
has changed to allow higher rates of noninflationary growth than
traditional models would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Those who see the current combination of strong growth and
dormant inflation as temporary point to the recent rise in oil
prices as evidence that what had been an unbroken string of good
news for the economy will not last forever.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of Fed officials seem to have fallen in
line with Greenspan in giving serious consideration to the idea
that huge investments in technology over the last decade may have
helped to tame inflation by improving productivity, or output per
worker.
</P>
<P>
   The economy expanded at a 6.1 percent annual rate in the fourth
quarter of last year, matching the fastest quarterly pace of the
1990's. While it appears to have slowed somewhat in the first few
months of this year, the economy is still growing at a pace that in
the past would have been expected to generate higher inflation,
economists said, especially with unemployment at just 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, faced with a similar situation, the Fed decided to
move to a tightening bias in late March. It retained that bias
until August, when Russia's debt default rocked global financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, Fed officials seem more comfortable with
allowing the economy some leeway, especially since there is
virtually no inflation. The Consumer Price Index rose just
one-tenth of 1 percent in each of the last three months and just
1.6 percent over the last year. Although oil prices are spiking up
after a sharp drop, prices in other areas are likely to remain
stable. And wages, although rising, are not gaining ground fast
enough to be a serious inflationary threat, largely because
productivity has been growing at a faster pace, too.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a recent speech, Robert Parry, president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco and one of the Fed's chief
inflation hawks, appeared more open to the idea that the economy
could grow faster without generating more inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's too soon to say for sure whether the productivity
surge is temporary or permanent, two pieces of evidence do seem to
point to a fundamental shift in productivity,'' Parry said.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, the phenomenal pace of consumer spending _ it
grew 5.25 percent in 1998 _ appears to reflect an assumption among
individuals, based on what they see happening at their own jobs,
that their incomes will continue growing.
</P>
<P>
   The second piece of evidence, Parry said, is the collective
judgment of the stock market, which seems to think that companies
can continue generating strong profit gains.
</P>
<P>
   David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital Markets,
observed that at least half a dozen Fed governors and bank
presidents have made statements in recent weeks expressing
confidence that inflation is contained.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than I can remember in the past,'' Orr said, ``they seem
to be comfortable that if inflation is going to pick up it's not
going to be sudden or anything they're behind the curve on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
