<SLUG> BC-HACKER-SENTENCED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 COMPUTER HACKER SENTENCED TO 46 MONTHS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin D. Mitnick pleaded guilty Friday to computer
fraud and wire fraud in a plea agreement that will result in a
sentence of 46 months.
</P>
<P>
   Given the time he has spent in prison and time off for good
behavior, Mitnick could be released as early as a year from now,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick's lawyer, Donald C. Randolph, said Mitnick could be
released to a halfway house as early as the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnick has been in prison since February 1995, when he was
captured in North Carolina after being on the run more than two
years. During that time, according to what Mitnick admitted Friday,
he broke into computers, intercepted computer communications and
stole proprietary software from several cellular telephone and
software companies. Often, he called up the target company
pretending to be an employee in order to get passwords and access
to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Mitnick will not be able to use a computer
or cellular phone for three years after leaving prison without the
permission of his probation officer.
</P>
<P>
   He also agreed to surrender proceeds from publications, movies
or other commercial ventures related to his crimes for seven years
after his release.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer accepted the plea
agreement but left open the question of how much money Mitnick
would have to pay in restitution to victims of his crimes and to
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would seek millions of dollars, while
Randolph argued there should be no restitution because Mitnick
would have limited abilty to earn money.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a dark suit in court here, the 35-year-old Mitnick
looked more like an investment banker than the teen-ager who once
stayed up nights prowling the electronic networks.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mitnick, the defendant's father, said he was ``ecstatic''
about the agreement. Mitnick himself is relieved and ``can now see
light at the end of the tunnel,'' Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mitnick still faces California charges stemming from
separate accusations of computer fraud. No trial date has been set
for the state charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-CHINA-RIGHTS-470     03-26 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-RIGHTS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO BACK THE CENSURE OF BEIJING OVER HUMAN RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The administration announced Friday that it would
sponsor a U.N. resolution next month condemning Beijing for what
the resolution calls the wholesale violation of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Last year President Clinton decided to drop Washington's
tradition of sponsoring such a resolution at the U.N. Human Rights
Commission annual meeting in Geneva, arguing that China's behavior
was improving and that seeking a public rebuke was
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter China signed the International Convention on
Civil and Political Rights, which commits Beijing to guaranteeing
freedom of expression, assembly and religion.
</P>
<P>
   But so far China has not ratified the convention, and as the
economy has slowed and protests have erupted, the government has
imprisoned more dissidents and cracked down on all efforts to
organize political opposition.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said Friday that in
the past year, ``China's human rights record has deteriorated
sharply.''
</P>
<P>
   The new resolution was announced less than two weeks before
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji is to arrive here for an official visit.
The trip has already become intertwined with Washington's
intensifying debate about nuclear spying, soaring trade deficits
and China's efforts to win American approval for entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, rarely has the administration's policy of separating
trade and human rights been starker than today: even as the State
Department was making its announcement, American and Chinese
negotiators were trying to fashion a deal on China's membership in
the trade group in time for Zhu's arrival in Washington, which is
scheduled for April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insisted Friday that their decision to
go ahead with the resolution condemning China was driven chiefly by
China's crackdown on dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   But, speaking on condition of anonymity, they readily
acknowledged that it was also linked to the increasing hostility
toward China on Capitol Hill, where the questions of its rights
record and fitness to join the trade organization seem inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Congress have threatened to block China's entry. By
sponsoring the resolution condemning China, the White House hopes
to argue that it is using the Geneva forum to try to punish the
Chinese _ without punishing American exporters or others doing
business with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense that the president has to show Congress he can
get tough,'' one administration official said, ``without sinking
the whole relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department did not release the wording of its proposed
resolution Friday, but if the past is any guide, the measure stands
little chance of passage. Since their introduction in 1990, a year
after the shootings at Tiananmen Square, similar resolutions have
consistently been defeated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That reality _ along with politically symbolic gestures by the
Chinese in 1998, including the release from jail of Wang Dan and
other prominent democracy advocates _ led the administration to
decide last year to skip the ritual at the Geneva meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But the environment has radically changed. Economic troubles
have brought on anti-government protests in China. The State
Department's rights report, released last month, condemned Beijing
for a new wave of repression.
</P>
<P>
   But even then several administration officials said they thought
the report alone might serve to register Washington's protest. They
hinted that the United States might again forgo sponsoring a
resolution. In a foreign policy speech last month, Clinton
suggested that China was ``moving away from the rule of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, however, unanimously passed a nonbinding resolution
calling for a condemnation of China at the Geneva meeting, which
began this week and will continue through April. And the
administration, a senior State Department official told reporters
Friday, concluded that was the only realistic choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having chronicled the facts and the deterioration,'' the
senior official said, ``we had no choice but to go ahead with the
resolution as part of our strategy of engagement on human rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
