<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: DISCORD OVER NATO ATTACKS ON YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polls show Americans are divided over the decision this week by
the United States and other NATO members to bomb military targets
in Yugoslavia. It is a division that also extends to religious
organizations, even as many of those organizations echo the concern
voiced by the NATO governments over the Yugoslav military's attacks
on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province, the situation that led to
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Since the air strikes began, the church world service committee
of the National Council of Churches has called for an end to the
bombing, as has the Roman Catholic peace organization Pax Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Some American Muslims, as well as leaders of social action
groups within Reform Judaism, have backed the NATO action as a way
of pushing the Yugoslavs to a peace agreement with the Kosovo
Albanians, many of whom are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   As if noting the division, the president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, Bishop Joseph Fiorenza, said in a
statement that disagreement among ``persons of good will'' may be
inevitable. While attempts to protect the Kosovo Albanians from
further violence was a legitimate goal, he wrote, ``What is less
clear are the consequences of the use of force.''
</P>
<P>
   But few religious organizations are likely to feel the
conflict's complexities as acutely as the World Council of
Churches, which is comprised of more than 300 Protestant and
Orthodox Christian churches. Member churches can be found in
countries on both sides of the conflict _ in Yugoslavia (and its
dominant state Serbia), in Russia, whose government has strongly
denounced the NATO air strikes, and in the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the air strikes began, the council's general
secretary, the Rev. Dr. Konrad Raiser, dispatched a pastoral letter
to the heads of three Yugoslavian churches, expressing the
council's ``solidarity'' with them and stating that only a
negotiated peace could be ``a durable and just'' one.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the council's headquarters in Geneva by telephone
Thursday, Raiser said the organization was not interested in
assigning blame for the conflict, but instead wanted to express
concern for its victims and to explore possible avenues to peace.
</P>
<P>
   The council's governing Assembly met last December amid
well-publicized internal tensions, when some Orthodox members
complained their concerns were being disregarded in an organization
where Protestants form the majority. Dr. Raiser said that, as far
as the council is concerned, the conflict in Yugoslavia is not
helpful to relations among churches in these two branches of
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an Orthodox perspective, it is at least conspicuous that
the main powers involved in the NATO action are, of course, powers
shaped by a predominately Protestant ethos,'' he said, referring
primarily to the United States, Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Raiser said the council wanted to call attention to religious
voices within Yugoslavia that do not share their government's
militaristic attitude. He said those voices have not been heard
widely enough.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he cited a public statement Thursday by Patriarch
Pavle, head of the Serbian Orthodox Church, the largest Christian
organization in Yugoslavia, in which the patriarch called for an
end to the bombing, for negotiations to end the crisis and for
Yugoslavian and Serbian authorities ``to do everything so that
peace may be established.''
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch serves as president of the church's Synod of
Bishops, a body represented last week at an interfaith meeting on
peace in Kosovo by Bishop Kyr Artemije, who comes from Kosovo. The
meeting, organized by New York Rabbi Arthur Schneier's Appeal of
Conscience Foundation and held in Vienna, produced a declaration
asking for peace and tolerance in Kosovo that was signed by Bishop
Artemije and two other Kosovo religious figures, Roman Catholic
Bishop Marko Sopi and Professor Quemal Morina, vice dean of the
Faculty of Islamic Studies in the Kosovar city of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The document, written at a time of gradually escalating violence
between the Yugoslav military and Kosovo Albanians, called for an
end to the killing and establishment of a ``viable system'' to
represent the province's people, without violating any minority's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fighting ends,'' said Rabbi Schneier, ``you will need
a force that can re-connect the community, and this is where
religious leaders can play an important role.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiser said the council had supported the meeting and the
declaration. ``I think we should take their voice seriously,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
