<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-ADVANCE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riding the bench proves vital lesson
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Duke's Elton Brand would rather not think
of the Blue Devils' 73-67 victory against Michigan State on Dec. 2.
It was, after all, pretty embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's 6-foot-8, 260-pound sophomore center was anything but a
dominant force that night in Chicago. Woefully out of shape, at
least by coach Mike Krzyzewski's standards, Brand was helpless as
Michigan State pounded Duke on the offensive boards, 25-5. Brand
had only three rebounds and committed six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't in the best of shape, I know that,'' Brand said. ``As
a team, we weren't in good shape either. We couldn't get a rebound
at one point.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke won the game, but Krzyzewski was not happy with his budding
star. Three games later he benched Brand and told him to shape up
or expect to get less playing time.
</P>
<P>
   It turned Brand's season around.
</P>
<P>
   In tonight's Final Four at Tropicana Field, Michigan State will
see a much different Elton Brand than the one who dragged his tired
body around the United Center on Dec. 2. Brand, Duke's leading
scorer and rebounder (17.8 ppg, 9.6 rpg) has become the best big
man in college basketball and a major reason why the No. 1 Blue
Devils are 36-1 and favored to win the national championship. He
will, said Michigan State coach Tom Izzo, be a load for the
Spartans to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that Elton is playing a lot
harder and a lot better than he did back in December,'' Izzo said.
``He is really something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his benching by Krzyzewski in December, Brand has played
the game with a greater sense of passion. He hit the stationary
bike several times a day until he got into good shape. Over the
past two months he has been virtually unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Since an eight-point outing against Wake Forest on Jan. 13,
Brand has scored in double figures in 20 consecutive games. In that
stretch he has also had 11 double-doubles.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Brand returned to Chicago to play DePaul on Feb. 24,
he was a star, scoring 20 points and pulling down 14 rebounds as
the Blue Devils won easily 96-64.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from that period,'' said Brand, who was chosen
Associated Press Player of the Year on Friday. ``I learned that I
have to be in shape or I'm going to miss easy shots. It was a very
important lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski warned his team Friday not to think too much about a
game that was played almost four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're better but they're a lot better too,'' said Krzyzewski,
in his eighth Final Four at Duke. ``It helps because we know how
big they are and how they play, but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand will play better today, said Krzyzewski, but so will
Michigan State point guard Mateen Cleaves, who was held to 3-of-17
shooting on Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two best players are in a lot better shape now than they
were then,'' Krzyzewski said. ``It's like two totally different
teams and so anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
