<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Point men crucial component of all Final Four teams
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ All four teams in today's NCAA Final Four
have at least one thing in common: An exceptional player at point
guard who is significantly responsible for them being here.
Coincidence? Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a great point guard to run your team and be an
extension of the coach on the floor, you're not going to get
here,'' Michigan State coach Tom Izzo said. ``A great point guard
makes all the other players on the floor better. And these four
guys certainly do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo should know. With the Midwest Regional championship on the
line last Sunday against Kentucky, Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves
took control with two 3-pointers that led the Spartans to a
73-66victory.
</P>
<P>
   Duke has two All-Americans in its starting five but the MVP for
the 36-1 season has been sophomore guard William Avery, whose speed
and quickness breaks down even the best defenses. Even Elton Brand,
the national player of the year, said Avery is the key to the Blue
Devils' success.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State went from 8-22 a season ago to the Final Four through
the sheer force of Scoonie Penn's will. The Buckeyes' leading
scorer made big play after big play in the 77-74 victory against
St. John's for the South Regional title.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's Khalid El-Amin had one of the worst games of his career
(0-for-12 from the floor) in the West Regional championship against
Gonzaga. But he made the free throws down the stretch and ran the
offense while the Huskies protected the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game is on the line, the ball has to be in their
hands,'' UConn coach Jim Calhoun said. ``They are guys with nerves
of steel. And we'll have four great ones out there Saturday
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Football friends
</P>
<P>
   Some say Michigan State plays the game with the fierceness of
football. That should not be a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo is a former football player and coach and most of the
team's top players, including Cleaves, are former high school
football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it gives us a toughness that we really need,
especially playing in the Big Ten,'' Cleaves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football coaches, I think, are really good at getting the most
from the players they coach,'' Izzo said. ``I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad timing
</P>
<P>
   Our vote for the most frustrated player this weekend? That would
be Michigan State's Mike Chappell, a transfer from Duke. Chappell
left Duke after playing 54 games after it became obvious he would
not get a lot of minutes in the future. He had to sit out this
season and thus cannot play Saturday. He had to pay his expenses to
get to Florida but will be allowed to work out with the Michigan
State team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
