<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-ADVANCE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huskies depending on Moore's ability to adjust
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Ohio State is in the Final Four because
it has one of the nation's best backcourts. In fact, Scoonie Penn
(17.1 ppg) and Michael Redd (19.7 ppg) are responsible for 49
percent of the Buckeyes' offense each game.
</P>
<P>
   For Connecticut's Ricky Moore, that fact meant a late Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be doing a lot of film watching,'' the senior
guard said Friday afternoon. ``A lot of film watching.''
</P>
<P>
   For UConn to beat Ohio State in tonight's Final Four, Augusta's
Ricky Moore must have a very good game.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Moore, UConn's 6-foot-2 defensive stopper, will start
on Penn, the Buckeye point guard who shared Big Ten Player of the
Year. But if Redd gets hot, Moore will have to switch.
</P>
<P>
   He has a track record of success in stopping the opponent's top
player:
</P>
<P>
   _ In last week's West Regional championship victory against
Gonzaga, Moore held high-scoring Matt Santangelo to 1-for-9
shooting, and UConn won 67-62.
</P>
<P>
   _ After Miami's Johnny Hemsley scored 18 first-half points
against the Huskies on Jan. 20, Moore took over. Hemsley went
scoreless in the second half, and UConn won 70-68 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Dec. 5, Moore forced Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves, the
other Big Ten Player of the Year, to miss 13 of 15 shots in a 82-68
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 27 years as a head coach, I've never had a kid who could
cut the head off a dragon like Ricky,'' UConn coach Jim Calhoun
said. ``When he is playing well, he thinks he is worth 20 points a
game, and I agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore didn't come to UConn as a defensive specialist. After
leading Westside High to a 33-1 record and a state championship in
1995, Moore became the starting point guard at UConn as a
sophomore, averaging nine points a game.
</P>
<P>
   But last season, UConn signed Khalid El-Amin and gave him the
starting job at point guard. Moore moved to shooting guard and
never complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Khalid came in, I knew I would have to do some different
things, but I didn't have a problem with it,'' said Moore, who has
been the team's co-captain the past three years. ``I knew he was
going to give us another option on offense, and I thought that was
important to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is the perfect example of the kind of kids you have to
have in your program in order to win,'' Calhoun said. ``He was
asked to change his role and has done a magnificent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
