<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-SAWGRASS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ozaki leads, but Duval looms in 2nd
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ It's a mirage. Everybody knows it.
Japan's Joe Ozaki is in the lead after 36 holes of the Players
Championship, but David Duval is in control.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing promises to be easy for the weekend, that is, unless
they replace the billiard felt on the surfaces that are passing for
greens at the TPC at Sawgrass. But if a tough task gets tougher,
the smart money might go on the Jacksonville native who lives just
down Highway A1A, plays the TPC at Sawgrass year round and has
nearly as much confidence as money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Duval, who fashioned a 3-under-par 69 Friday and is one
shot behind Ozaki at 6-under 138, tries to downplay his comfort
zone, don't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, they don't keep this golf course like this _ hard and
6-inch rough,'' Duval contended Friday. ``I don't have any
advantage that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ozaki _ this is Joe, not Jumbo _ who shot a 68, the
second-lowest score of the day, and is at 7-under 137, isn't
feeling too secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was sitting in the same chair, with the same score
and I ended up in 18th place,'' Ozaki said. ``Being the halfway
leader doesn't mean a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It might in Duval's case. Certainly, there are enough
indicators. He has enough friends in the gallery to fill a high
school football stadium in Jax Beach. He knows the spots in Pete
Dye's sadistic layout where you can still miss the green and make
par. Heck, maybe this is the week Duval and his father, Bob, both
win. The old man shot a 61 on the Senior Tour Friday to lead by
four shots at the Emerald Coast Classic in Milton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that?'' the younger Duval said. ``He clipped me by
eight. ... I don't think that golf course is as hard, though.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a two-man race, however, for the $900,000 first
prize at Sawgrass. Bruce Lietzke, 47, who hardly ever plays on the
PGA Tour but always seems to contend, also shot a 68 and stands two
shots back at 139. Joining Ernie Els (67) and Curtis Strange (69),
Sea Island's Davis Love III is three behind at 140 on a pair of 70s
and sounded like man who would take two more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good position with two days to go,'' said Love, the
tournament's 1992 champion, ``because I don't think it's going to
get any easier out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is four shots back at 141 after a 1-under 71.
First-round co-leaders Brian Watts and Bob Estes both shot 74s and
are at 142.
</P>
<P>
   Love can't seem to get through a tournament without a glitch or
two. He bogeyed his last two holes Thursday. He lost ground Friday
with a double bogey at the 12th, taking two pitches to navigate a
mound in the rough. When players eventually got to the greens, they
were Augusta-like in their speed and difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're right on the edge, that's for sure,'' Love said, ``but
that's where they want them.''
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at 4-over 148, pushing out Atlanta's Stewart Cink,
Lee Janzen, Greg Norman, Tom Lehman, Bay Hill winner Tim Herron and
Ben Crenshaw. John Daly withdrew because of a sore hip.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
