<SLUG> BC-PROWLER-PILOT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROWLER PILOT DESCRIBES MISSION OVER YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's a 29-year-old EA-6B ``Prowler'' Navy pilot out of Whidbey
Island (Wash.) Naval Air Station. Thursday night, under a clear sky
and bright half-moon, he spent four hours in the dangerous skies
over Yugoslavia and Kosovo jamming Serbian radar.
</P>
<P>
   His radio call sign is ``Tool.'' While military officials at
Aviano Air Force Base in Italy vouch for his identity, the
seven-year veteran can't give his name or discuss strategic details
for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It was quiet in the darkened, two-man cockpit as the plane flew
over Yugoslavia, he said in a phone interview. Little radio chatter
was a good sign as the plane jammed Serbian radar, providing an
electronic shield to armed fighters and bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Prowlers are not heavily armed, but are among the first planes
sent in during an attack. Their job is to confuse enemy
communications and radar, providing cover for attacking planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quieter it is the better,'' Tool said. ``On the radio you
hear threat warnings, whether there is surface-to-air, or
air-to-air missiles. There are certain things you want to hear, but
you want it to be quieter. If you hear very little, it means things
are going well.''
</P>
<P>
   The warnings typically come from friendly surveillance or other
planes, relaying information about anti-aircraft missile sightings,
or enemy aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Tool flies one of three Prowlers with VAQ 134 squadron of
Whidbey's Electronic Attack Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Each prowler carries four aviators, a pilot and three electronic
countermeasures officers. Nearly 200 maintance and support people
from Whidbey also are in Aviana to keep the planes flying.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the attack missions over Kosovo and Yugoslavia
were going better than expected, he said. Military officials, who
feared casualties from the vaunted Russian-made air defense system
employed by the Serbs, said it was mysteriously absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected more (anti-aircraft missiles) than we're seeing,''
Tool said. ``Maybe they're holding back, maybe they aren't, and a
lot of it is that we're doing a good job. The missions are
well-planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Tool's best defenses are primarily the confusion he can wreak on
an opponent, and the protection of friendly fighters. The Prowlers
are used by Navy and Marine pilots to provide a protective umbrella
to fighters by jamming opposing radar and communications. They can
travel at 575 mph, cover 1,150 miles, reach a ceiling of 37,600
feet, and carry complex, long-range electronic warfare equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Tool's Whidbey Island Prowlers are joined by others from the
Marine Corps Air Station at Cherry Point, S.C., and faster U.S. and
Canadian Air Force jamming planes, evidence that serious attention
is being paid to the Serb's air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The jets are among more than 130 Air Force, Navy and Marine
fighters, support planes, and cargo aircraft at Aviano as part of
the 31st Air Expeditionary Wing.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Tool said, the squadron was ``on the hook'' for
similar missions in Iraq, but was called back halfway over.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members focus on getting the job done efficiently and
safely, he said, though when there's a break, thoughts drift to
loved ones back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss my wife and family,'' he said. ``We're doing great and
tell everybody our spirits are high. So far we've had no particular
difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the group only flew into Aviano last Sunday, there's been
little time to find a niche in which to relax, he said. Some make
use of the base gym to work out, but most spend time planning,
believing preparedness best minimizes the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it continues along, then we will find other things to do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like every American, some flyers have strong opinions about
their role and about the potential for the conflict to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But frankly, we're so concentrated on the mission that that
stuff doesn't play into it,'' he said. ``We're just here to do it
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking to myself as I was flying (to Kosovo) Thursday
night that it was like all the exercises I've ever done in
training,'' he said. ``You never know how good your training is
until you get into the actual situation. But all the stuff we heard
on the radio (in the cockpit) and the procedures have been pretty
much the same as we practiced them at Nellis Air Force Base.''
</P>
<P>
   Tool, who has been with the Whidbey based Prowler squadron for
2-1/2 years, said he's felt fear come and go, depending on how busy
he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most nervous I was was yesterday, before we started,
during the briefing,'' he said. ``But then you start doing your
pre-flight checks and the familiar takes over, and the training
kicks in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a certain amount of time to get down (to the attack
areas in Yugoslavia) from Aviano, so you have some time to think
about it. As you get closer, you think about it. But then you get
too busy to be scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
