<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B2-BOMBS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B-2 BOMBS USE BOEING-MADE GUIDANCE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's B-2 stealth bombers that are being used in combat for
the first time this week over Yugolslavia are carrying special
2,000 pound bombs fitted with a Boeing-built guidance system that
can hit a target even in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the first time that the bomb guidance system, known
as the Joint Direct Attack Munition, or JDAM, has been used in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   The cheap strap-on kit that turns dumb bombs into smart ones
could be worth as much as $5 billion in military sales to Boeing
over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the plan is for JDAM to be fitted on smaller general
purpose bombs carried by fighters. For now, though, JDAM has
allowed the nation's expensive and little-used Cold War bombers
like the B-2 to finally play a vital role in conventional warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The billion-dollar B-2 was designed to carry nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   JDAM (pronounced jay-dam) has undergone extensive testing over
the last couple years, and has been certified to be used on the
B-52, B-1 and B-2 bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing inherited JDAM when it acquired McDonnell Douglas in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The kits are assembled in a building near the St. Louis airport,
not far from where the Boeing F-18 and F-15 fighters are built for
the Navy and Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the B-52s that have been used in Operation Allied Force
over Yugoslavia have carried only cruise missiles. A cruise missile
also can hit a target with pinpoint accuracy, but they each cost
upwards of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   JDAM is far cheaper, and almost as accurate. Each kit cost about
$18,000. Boeing believes it might even get the cost down to about
$15,000. That is several times less than the cost of a typical
laser-guided bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Laser-guided bombs were used extensively for the first time
during the Gulf War and are being used again on NATO bombing raids
over Yugoslavia. But laser-guided bombs are affected by clouds and
can only be used when the pilots can see their targets. JDAM works
in any kind of weather because it is guided to a target by the
Global Positioning Satellite System.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is buying 62,000 JDAM kits from Boeing, and the
Navy 25,000 more. The total value of the Defense Department
contract is more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has described the B-2 missions over Yugoslavia as
``very successful.'' That could translate into more JDAM orders for
Boeing if JDAM performed as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   The JDAM project grew out of the lessons learned in the Gulf
War. The military wanted a cheap weapon that could be used to
attack targets in all kinds of weather and with great accuracy, and
one that could be used by a bomber force that was built for nuclear
strikes, not a conventional war.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Pentagon figured each JDAM kit would cost about
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was able to get the costs down by using commercial parts
and practices. The Pentagon also backed off from some performance
requirements that would have made the weapon more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The JDAM kit straps on the rear of existing 1,000 and 2,000
pounds bombs. Tail fins steer the bomb to the target. An electronic
navigation system in each unit is programmed while the plane is in
flight with the ground coordinates of the intended target.
</P>
<P>
   The B-2 can carry 16 2,000 pound JDAMS in its internal rotary
launcher.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb is dropped up to 15 miles from its target and signals
from the global positioning satellite system help keep it on track.
</P>
<P>
   The network of 24 satellites, orbiting about 11,000 miles in
space, is under the control of the Air Force. The system can
measure to within a few feet, though the military deliberately adds
inaccuracy to the satellite signals for civilian use.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon required JDAM to be accurate to within 13 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said it got the accuracy down to 10 meters. The
company is now developing JDAM kits for general purpose 500 pound
bombs, and is working on wing kits that extend the the range of the
weapon. Improvements also are being made to the guidance system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
