u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      03-26 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Saturday, March 20 and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   PROWLER-PILOT (Undated) _ He's a 29-year-old EA-6B ``Prowler''
Navy pilot out of Whidbey Island (Wash.) Naval Air Station.
Thursday night, under a clear sky and bright half-moon, he spent
four hours in the dangerous skies over Yugoslavia and Kosovo
jamming Serbian radar.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber. (Story has moved in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SEALAUNCH (Undated) _ In the equatorial waters of the
Pacific Ocean near Christmas Island, a 208-foot-long
Ukrainian-Russian Zenit 3SL rocket is set to blast off Saturday. If
the historic demonstration launch is successful, it could give The
Boeing Co., principal partner in the venture known as Sea Launch, a
competitive advantage in its goal of being the world's premier
provider of satellite launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story has moved in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   B2-BOMBS (Seattle) _ When B-2 stealth bombers were used in
combat for the first time this week in Yougolslavia, they carried
special 2,000-pound bombs that use a Boeing-built guidance system
to zero in on their target.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story has moved in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Seattle) _ Seattle SuperSonics host L.A. Clippers.
</P>
<P>
