<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irwin concerned with seconds, not mph
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Tex. _ Kenny Irwin climbed out of the No. 28 Ford
Taurus after his qualifying lap, teammate Dale Jarrett asked
``how'd that feel?'' and Irwin replied ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's how driving really fast feels.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin whipped around Texas Motor Speedway's reconfigured 1-1/2
mile trial in a record 190.154 mph (28.398 seconds) to win the pole
for Sunday's Winston Cup Primestar 500. He'll start 10th in today's
Busch Coca-Cola 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have guessed we were that fast,'' said Irwin,
whose only other pole came last November in Atlanta. ``When you're
out there, you feel the car's loose, that it's pushing and it's not
all that fast. I honestly didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   And he'd rather not know, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a driver, all of us, we don't know miles per hour, we know
seconds,'' Irwin said. ``Whether it's 28 seconds or 29.3 or
whatever. But mph is what all the fans want to know. That's fast,
yeah. But I'd rather not know miles per hour. Then you'd go slower.
Kind of like knowing more.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of impressive times on the stopwatches: 39
cars beat the previous track qualifying record, 185.906, set by
Jeremy Mayfield last April. Irwin said changes made to the track
after water seepage problems last year have made it faster.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte qualified second in the No. 18 Pontiac at 189.853
mph, a week after breaking his right shoulder in a Busch practice
at Darlington. He's got Busch driver Matt Kenseth standing by again
to relieve him if need be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask my wife, I'm not very tough,'' Labonte said. ``Trust me. I
can lean back on the seat the way we've got it all taped up. I
don't want to take any licks at all. The way it's positioned, it's
not as bad as I thought it would be. I can reach up and grab the
wheel. I can shift gears.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Park, qualifying third, had the best showing of the
Chevrolets, running his lap in 189.341 mph. It's his career-best
qualifying effort. His best start this season had been 23rd at
Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Park said it takes a great deal of confidence to drive a car
near 190 around a speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just need a lot of guts,'' Park said. ``And a lot of
confidence in your car. It's one of the situations where the
confidence factor comes in again. You hear the crew chiefs say it
all the time. They'll stick their head in the window the last
minute and say 'I promise you this things's gonna stick.' And
you're like, all right, hop in the passenger side and if it doesn't
we'll all suffer the consequences. It all goes back to your
confidence in the car and your abilities. The only way you get that
is by going out and running good and proving to yourself that the
car will stick when it's down in the corner going 190 miles an
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte and Ward Burton qualified fourth and fifth,
respectively, followed by defending champion Mark Martin (188.957),
who had broken the track record in morning practice with a lap of
190.127 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable qualifiers included Jeff Gordon (eighth), Bill
Elliott (ninth) and Mike Skinner (23rd). Darrell Waltrip, out of
provisionals, was 46th fastest (184.666), beating only Buckshot
Jones (183.955). Dale Earnhardt also failed to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
