<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-NOTE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lietzke eases way into contention
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Bruce Lietzke is every man's hero on
the PGA Tour. While others grind, the 47-year-old Texan just rolls
along. He hasn't had a lesson in 26 years. He built a sure-fire
fade in the '70s, and he isn't messing with it.
</P>
<P>
   While others are playing 25 events a year or hopping around the
world for appearance fees, Lietzke enjoys being a dad in North
Dallas and coaching his son's high school golf team. Later this
summer, he's going to put a 1927 Ford in hot rod condition.
</P>
<P>
   When he hits 50, Lietzke is certain to play on the Senior Tour,
but he isn't likely to be fanatical about it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, what's the rush? The package still performs. He's two
shots off the lead in the richest full-field tournament in golf and
could be just two lazy days from beating all those range-ball crazy
kids on the PGA Tour for Sunday's $900,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something to be said about guys that work too
much,'' Lietzke said. ``I'm a big believer that you can hurt
yourself on the practice range as much as you can help yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lietzke, who made five birdies and a bogey while hitting 14
greens Friday, just hopes the greens still will be there when he
gets up this morning. Cut at 1/10th of an inch this week and baking
every day, they're taking on the color of a Texas tortilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens look real sickly to me,'' he said. ``I have kind of
a problem with ... trying to ride the borderline of fairness and
unfairness when you put the health of the greens in peril for
people who want to play the golf course the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly exits again
</P>
<P>
   The Players Championship and John Daly continue to be an unlucky
combination. In 1997, after an opening 76, he hit Jacksonville
Beach for a drinking binge, withdrew the next day and headed for
the Betty Ford Clinic. Friday before the second round, Daly, who
shot an 83 Thursday, withdrew because of what his representatives
said was a bad hip.
</P>
<P>
   Filling it up
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Bernhard Langer and Fulton Allem both holed out for
eagle 2s at the par-4 fourth hole Friday, prompting playing partner
Mike Hulbert to say later after his 4, ``There wasn't enough room
in the cup for my ball.'' ... England's Nick Faldo enjoyed only a
day away from his miseries. After a 71 Thursday, Faldo came back
with a 75. Nick Price, who shot one of three 67s Friday to stand
four shots back at 141, is having sinus problems because of the
pollen, which doesn't bode well for Augusta. ... Bob Friend managed
the tournament's second ace of the week, holing out at the 221-yard
eighth hole with a 4-iron. ... Atlanta's Billy Andrade made the cut
at 147 with a 74. ... After two days of play, 23 balls have gone in
the water at the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
