u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERB-700&AMP;ADD-N     03-26 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERB-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUFUGEES FLEEING KOSOVO REPORT ATTACKS ON ETHNIC ALBANIANS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-MIGS, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-INFORMATION, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(wg) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and a European security
group said on Friday that they had received reports from refugees
fleeing Kosovo and others that an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 ethnic
Albanian civilians were put on a forced march in central Kosovo by
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The administration cautioned that it did not have satellite
imagery to confirm the accounts. But the State Department warned
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia that it would use its
technological capabilities to monitor ``unfolding events in
Kosovo'' and would collect evidence of any war crimes, like summary
executions.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said that United States aerial
``assets'' were now being trained on the central Drenica region
where the civilians, believed to be refugees from attacks on
villages, were reportedly being pushed along a road with Serbian
tanks at their backs.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday night, the State Department had received more accounts
of a forced march from ethnic Albanian refugees who were
interviewed after reaching Macedonia, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Organization for Security and Co-Operation
in Europe, the Vienna-based group whose monitors were evacuated to
Macedonia from Kosovo last week, said that the monitors had been
receiving telephone reports from local groups inside Kosovo. Those
reports estimated the numbers on a forced march at about 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman suggested that the Serbs might be planning to
use the large group of ethnic Albanians as a human shield to
prevent NATO planes from attacking Serbian military installations.
</P>
<P>
   Other accounts of atrocities against ethnic Albanians continued
to surface on Friday. Human Rights Watch, a New York-based group,
said the bodies of a prominent human rights lawyer and his two sons
were found at a gas station near Pristina, possible evidence that
the Serb forces had stepped up their actions during the day while
NATO planes tried to punish the Serb military at night.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpectedly low number of refugees leaving Kosovo was
another possible indicator that the population was being terrorized
by the Serbs, meaning most people were too scared to leave their
homes, let alone try to flee, the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely concerned that people are being terrorized
and are not able to move,'' said Panos Moumtzis, a spokesman for
the U.N. refugee agency. ``We've heard of villages being burned,
houses being burned and people being in a siege situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee agency reported that 20 ethnic Albanian males
had been executed in the village of Goden in southern Kosovo. Women
who escaped and trekked into Albania told refugee officials that
Yugoslav forces separated men from women and children and killed
the men in front of them, Judith Kumin, a spokeswoman in Geneva
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the third night of the NATO bombing, a Pristina man
spoke by phone to a friend of his here in Washington and told of an
atmosphere of terror. His friend would only describe the Pristina
resident as an artist to try to protect his identity. In a tape
recording of the conversation, made available to The New York Times
by the friend, the man said: ``It's a great fear among all the
people here.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on: `Armed civilians are robbing all stores, stealing
everything. Firing is going on in lots of parts of town. They're
killing people, just executing them. There are reports in
Djakovica, 50 or more were killed. In Mitrovica, some parts are
burning. The situation is not good. We don't have electricity,
water, cell phones for two days have been cut. We are sitting here
waiting for the worst. It's a big terror because the Serbs are
doing what they want. They are armed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration acknowledged the escalating violence
by the forces of Milosevic, but suggested little could be done
except to collect evidence for prosecutors at the international
court for war crimes at the Hague. ``The United States is extremely
alarmed by reports of an escalating pattern of Serbian attacks on
Kosovar Albanian civilians,'' State Department spokesman James
Rubin said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6028 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERB-2NDTAKE-N     03-26 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERB-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: James Rubin said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noting the length of time it took to get satellite images to
confirm the massacre of Bosnian Muslims at Srbrenica in Bosnia in
1995, State Department officials said it could be some time before
any evidence of a forced march became clearer. It was ``some
weeks'' before intelligence agencies had sifted through the photos
taken by U2 pilots on ``sanction busting'' missions and identified
the Srbrenica massacre site, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that intelligence officials were not able to
confirm a forced march or other reports of violence was that
analysts are focusing their work now on bomb damage assessment and
other tactical military issues in support of the NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. spy satellites, unmanned spy planes and U-2s are being used
to focus primarily on military targets for the airstrikes,
officials said. There may be some imagery or other intelligence
that will show evidence of the violence, but it will take time to
process, review and analyze.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Balkan wars, opponents have accused one another
of atrocities, sometimes unfounded or unconfirmed, to gain an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, however, State Department officials gave reports of a
forced march considerable credence, without hard evidence. They
told allies the reports seemed ``horribly right,'' a Western
diplomat said. After being briefed on the reports this morning, a
senior State Department official said: ``Very likely it's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House reiterated on Friday that NATO had no plans to
send troops into Kosovo right now to end the violence or to use a
ground force to back up the air campaign against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   After the international monitors left last weekend and Western
journalists were forced out on Thursday, the province became an
isolated preserve with Milosevic's well-armed forces free to do
what they wanted without observation from outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air campaign, intended to inhibit and degrade the
ability of the Serb forces to attack ethnic Albanians had not done
so in the first two nights, officials said. In some instances, the
night time air bombardments might have emboldened the Serbs while
they still had time, some military experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of readily accessible information, human rights
groups and individuals telephoning into Kosovo on Friday described
some of the violence: the burning and looting of stores and
restaurants owned by ethnic Albanians in Pristina and other towns.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Bajram Kelmendi, a human rights lawyer and his two
sons, Kastriot and Kushtrim, were found shot dead at a gas station
between Pristina and Kosovo Polje, southwest of the capital. The
lawyer and his sons were taken from their home early Thursday
morning by police, according to Human Rights Watch. Kelmendi had
defended many political prisoners in Kosover over the last decade
and had recently defended the Albanian-language newspaper Koha
Ditore, which was shut down by the police earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Isa Zymberi, who serves in London as an information official for
the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, said he learned of the looting and
burning of shops and restaurants in Pristina through a telephone
call to a friend in the capital on Friday morning. The friend, who
is a film director, said he had the impression that the Serb
authorities were planning to film the destruction and broadcast it
as evidence of wreckage caused by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of other destruction included the burning of the
Pristina warehouse of the Mother Theresa Society, the largest local
humanitarian organization in Kosovo. The warehouse was filled with
food and medicine and the society had to suspend operations, Human
Rights Watch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-ADVANCE     03-26 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-ADVANCE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spartans steel resolve for Duke
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Tom Izzo believes in being honest with
his players. That's why the Michigan State coach has minced no
words with his team concerning tonight's game with No. 1 Duke at
the NCAA Final Four at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they play their `A' game, then not many teams are going to
beat them, including us,'' said Izzo, whose Big Ten champions
(33-4) bring a 22-game winning streak into tonight's contest.
``It's our job to make sure they don't play their `A' game. It's a
great opportunity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are one of the top teams of all time,'' Michigan
State point guard Mateen Cleaves said. ``But after all the hype and
hoopla, you still have to go out and play 40 minutes of
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, said Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski. ``We certainly don't
feel we're invincible,'' said Krzyzewski, who plays five sophomores
and a freshman in his top eight players. ``With our level of
experience, we can lose to anybody. It's simple. If somebody
outplays you, they can beat you. We just have to make sure they
don't outplay us.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's first game is the ``feel good'' matchup of the Final
Four, with two teams that are happy just to be here.
</P>
<P>
   After seven Sweet 16 appearances and three regional championship
losses, Jim Calhoun finally has taken UConn (32-2) to its first
Final Four. The Huskies, who won the West Regional, play Ohio State
(27-8).
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ohio State was 8-22 and finished last in the Big
Ten. This year, the Buckeyes rode the talented backcourt of Scoonie
Penn and Michael Redd all the way through the South Regional and
their first Final Four appearance since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we've said to our players now is, `Don't settle,''' coach
Jim O'Brien said. ``Yeah, it's great to be here. But is this what
we want, or do we want just a little bit more?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
