<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-ART-2     03-26 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW CLEAR LESSONS FROM NATION'S FIRST SCHOOL-CHOICE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Nine years into the nation's first school-voucher
program here, there is no question that the concept has taken hold.
More than 6,000 poor children, 6 percent of the city's students,
receive publicly financed vouchers of nearly $5,000 a year to
attend private or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   But for cities that are hotly debating vouchers, like New York,
where Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew recently threatened to quit over
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's support for them, Milwaukee's experience
shows that time and familiarity neither cool passions nor _ so far
_ prove or disprove the value of vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never settles down,'' said Howard Fuller, Milwaukee's
former superintendent of schools and an advocate of letting parents
choose their children's schools. ``Vouchers represent a fundamental
change in the way public schools are governed and financed, and the
people who stand to lose power aren't ever going to say, `Oh,
fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   While school officials and politicians debate whether the
vouchers hurt the city's public schools, researchers who have
studied the voucher system here, the Milwaukee Parental Choice
Program, are just as divided, offering warring studies on the
effects of vouchers on student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is clear that vouchers have brought profound change to
Milwaukee, spurring the creation of private schools, giving
low-income parents new choices and bolstering Roman Catholic
schools in particular.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Joan Antida High School, a Catholic girls' school where
the ninth-grade theology class spent a recent afternoon analyzing
psalms, a quarter of the students pay their tuition with $4,894
vouchers from the state. (Giuliani has not specified the value of a
voucher in New York, but most estimates place the figure at $2,000
or less). Parents apply for vouchers through the school they want
their child to attend, and the school agrees to accept the voucher
as full payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of education I want for my children,'' said
Valerie Johnson, who has two daughters at St. Joan Antida and two
sons at another Catholic school. ``I'm not against public
education, but I'm against low-quality education, and I don't want
my kids in a place where they have to go in and be scanned for
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Catholic, but I'm very glad to have them get the
religious instruction here, as enrichment.''
</P>
<P>
   Voucher opponents say the program is sapping much-needed money
from the 101,000-student public school system. This year the state
paid private and parochial schools about $28 million to take
children with vouchers. But while enrollment fell by about 1,000,
the district's spending per pupil increased 8 percent this year, to
$8,914, and the overall budget increased about 7 percent, to $921
million.
</P>
<P>
   Even the number of students who have left public schools because
of vouchers is arguable. Only 1,295 of the more than 6,000 children
receiving vouchers this year also did so last year. According to
state data, 1,367 were enrolled in public schools last year, 1,114
were not enrolled in any school, but by far the largest group _
2,274 _ were already enrolled in parochial schools, which were not
eligible for the state program until this year. Many of those
children had privately financed vouchers from a group called
Partners Advancing Values in Education, or PAVE, making it
difficult to determine how many would be in public schools if not
for vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent of schools in Milwaukee, Alan Brown, said it
was still too early to assess the long-term impact of vouchers on
public schools and their students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vouchers and choice are still experiments,'' he said.
``There's no good evidence that turning poor kids over to a private
school will get books in their hands, cure their poverty, make for
better parents or change their lives. And parents aren't abandoning
the public schools in the droves predicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brown said, the public schools are doing a better job
of publicizing their successes. ``Our reading scores went up for
the first time in five years,'' he said, ``and we're starting a
reading guarantee for children entering kindergarten: that by the
end of second grade, if they're not reading on grade level, we will
pay for tutoring.''
</P>
<P>
   What the public schools are not going out of their way to
publicize is the voucher program. The district's 55-page pamphlet
on choosing a school never uses the word ``voucher'' and includes
only one paragraph in the glossary mentioning the Milwaukee
Parental Choice Program, giving an 800 number for information.
Despite years of headlines, court battles and impassioned debate in
education circles, many poor inner-city families who would be
eligible for vouchers do not know the program exists.
</P>
<P>
   At the Milwaukee Public School headquarters recently, Diannia
Merriett was trying to transfer her 5-year-old niece, Lakisha
Childs, out of LaFollette school, where she was unhappy. Although
the district allows a wide choice of schools, Ms. Merriett and
Lakisha's 82-year-old grandmother, Martha James, were finding
frustration at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to a reporter's question, they said they had not
considered the voucher program because they had never heard of it.
But they were extremely interested when it was explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like just what we want,'' Ms. James said. ``I love
Catholic schools, but I don't have the money. I think she'd get
more attention there.'' Wisconsin has authorized vouchers for as
many as 15,000 Milwaukee children, a potential loss to the public
schools of $75 million a year, but the expansion is likely to be
slow because local private schools do not have room for 9,000 more
students.
</P>
<P>
   But adjusting to the loss of students and money is not simple
for the city, Brown said: ``When you have 30 children in a class,
and one leaves on a voucher, you lose the money for that child but
you can't reduce the temperature in the room one-thirtieth, you
can't get rid of one-thirtieth of a custodian.''
</P>
<P>
   School district employees discuss the program with a certain
battle-weariness. ``We live with it, but it remains divisive,''
said Karen Salzbrenner, a spokeswoman for the district. ``All the
arguments for vouchers are at the expense of the Milwaukee public
schools. And whenever we do something well, even something we've
worked on for years, they say it's because of them.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
