<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-ART-2     03-26 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MILWAUKEE: of them.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, as in many cities, schools have been shaped by a
desegregation order and continuing efforts to fight racial
isolation in a district that is largely black.
</P>
<P>
   Even before vouchers, school choice was an essential part of the
effort. Parents may choose neighborhood schools or citywide magnet
schools, and about three-fourths get their first choice. Black,
Hispanic and Asian children in areas with few whites can attend
suburban public schools. And new schools are springing up, both
charter schools and schools designed to draw students using
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Marva Collins Preparatory School of Wisconsin, now in its
second year, is a private school that would not exist without the
vouchers that pay for 154 of its 180 students.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rauh, the principal, said there had been immediate
interest in the back-to-basics school for kindergarten through
fourth grade because the surrounding poor black neighborhood had
1,500 elementary school pupils and room for only 500 in the
neighborhood schools, leaving the rest to be bused out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we had 320 applications for our 180 spots, and we
did a random drawing to choose,'' Rauh said. ``We believe everyone
can learn, and we're not trying to skim the best students. I don't
see us as sapping resources from the public schools, but as meeting
the neighborhood need.''
</P>
<P>
   Few students have used vouchers to leave Elm Creative Arts
School, a racially mixed magnet school where a lively gallery of
student art is crammed with soft-sculpture penguins, hanging
trapeze sculptures, three-dimensional stage models, painted wooden
snakes and cat-shaped pillows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only known one child to leave in my eight years here, but
if it threatens the Milwaukee public schools and the schools'
money, it threatens us,'' said Jean Kovac, an art teacher,
referring to the voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tenorio, the assistant principal at Elm, said he felt
threatened. ``Parents often have the image that public means
problems, and private means better,'' Tenorio said. ``I worry about
losing the active, education-conscious parents that make such a
difference. Even if our budget isn't cut directly, it hurts us if
the system loses money for curriculum and testing and other things
they provide.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of high school principals recently, many said they
had particularly resented that the Milwaukee voucher program
charged the school system for thousands of students who had been in
parochial schools for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Milwaukee public schools lost millions of dollars for
students we were never serving, students who were already in
parochial schools,'' said Mary Ann Zapala, the principal of
Riverside High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like competition, if it's fair,'' Ms. Zapala said. ``What
seems so wrong about this is that the playing field is not level.
We have unionized teachers, licensing rules, required assessments.
They don't. We have to take everyone. They can take a kid, get the
money, and if there's any misbehavior, they can send him back to us
midyear.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Milwaukee schools accepting vouchers, 32 are secular and
56 are religious, mostly Catholic. Originally, the voucher program
did not include parochial schools. But in 1992 PAVE began to offer
thousands of low-income students vouchers for half of their tuition
at religious schools, and in 1995 state lawmakers expanded the
Milwaukee program to include religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   That was immediately challenged as unconstitutional, but in June
1998, the Wisconsin Supreme Court upheld the expanded voucher
program.
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear an appeal of the
Wisconsin ruling, the issue may ultimately be decided by the court
in one of the other school-choice cases making their way through
the system.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Milwaukee's Catholic schools are reaping the benefits.
Messmer High School, a Catholic school where almost half the
students receive vouchers _ and only about a third are Catholic _
is about to begin building that will allow it to increase
enrollment to about 500, from 355.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Robert Smith, the president of Messmer, sees his school
as an attractive alternative to North Division High School, a
nearby public school where, according to the city's school
accountability report, more students drop out than graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are happy stay where they are,'' Smith said. ``But
for people who aren't happy, we can offer something different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion hasn't been an issue for the families coming on the
choice program,'' Smith said. ``They know what they're coming here
for. No one has opted out of religious instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, many of those on both sides agreed, excellent public
schools are the best defense against vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to get and keep the best kids is to create a
program that attracts them,'' said Susan Brown, a guidance
counselor at John Marshall High School, a city school that is
starting a prestigious ``international baccalaureate'' program to
entice strong students. ``And maybe vouchers contributed to our
doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
