<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6037 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-MILITARY-KAN &LR;      03-26 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MILITARY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATUS OF WOMEN IN MILITARY IS SUBJECT OF PANEL DISCUSSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEAVENWORTH, Kan. _ Attention surrounded Elizabeth Hoisington
after she and another woman became the first women generals of the
U.S. Army on June 11, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Anna Mae Hayes, the native Kansan's picture appeared
on the front page of The New York Times and both were interviewed
by Barbara Walters. Hoisington's military career had begun in 1942,
and she eventually became director of the Women's Army Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought women in the Army were cooks or did cleaning,
but we surprised them,'' said Hoisington, who spoke in a panel
discussion about women in the military Thursday morning at Fort
Leavenworth as part of Women's History Month.
</P>
<P>
   Hoisington retired a year after her promotion, and since that
time, she's seen more of the barriers between men and women in the
military broken.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the sexes train together _ the Women's Army Corps was
dissolved in 1978. And more women have been promoted to higher
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members, however, expressed frustration about the
struggles that remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're starting to fade away, but separate and secure
barracks? To some, that is one step backward,'' said Army Col.
Velma Richardson. ``And separate laundry rooms _ I guess some
people think there's something tawdry about sharing a laundry
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonya Martin, a colonel in the Army Reserves, recalled
participating in an operation in which the men and women were in
the same tent. Someone ordered, however, that there should be
same-sex tents instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That change made it so there were no communications,'' Martin
said. ``It made it difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoisington said women should be separated from men in the
military because of their ``physical and emotional differences.''
She thinks it will be a long time before people accept women in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be another generation before that happens,'' she
said. ``I don't think people are ready to see women come back in
body bags.''
</P>
<P>
   Most women on the panel said they have had to choose between a
military career and a family.
</P>
<P>
   Army Sgt. Maj. Cynthia Pritchett said she had been engaged and
her fiance, who also was in the military, wanted her to quit. Since
military assignments are demanding in time and location, it's
extremely difficult to raise children unless one parent remains at
home, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett dropped the engagement and chose the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to it, you have to make the choice between
your personal life and the military,'' she said. ``If not, there
will be mediocrity somewhere down the road and something's got to
give.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said she is married, but chose to never have
children. None of the high-ranking female officers she knows has
children, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sacrifices and treatment of women in the military,
panel members said the nation is now more than ever willing to
elect a woman president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk about Liddy Dole, they talk about her
connections and capabilities,'' Martin said. ``They talk less about
her gender.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
