<HEADER>
A6040 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-POLICY-2NDTAK     03-26 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-POLICY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: is not genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the roughly 2,000 ethnic Albanians killed by Serbs in
Kosovo don't approach the massacres of Bosnia or the machete
slaughter of fleeing refugees in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian concerns often are trumped by American
self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps if the country doing the killing is not an ally,''
said Doug Bandow, a senior fellow at the libertarian Cato
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Because the United States needs a military foothold by the
Mediterranean Sea, Bandow said, it does not come to the defense of
Kurds killed by Turkey's government.
</P>
<P>
   The people of East Timor have struggled against Indonesian rule
for generations, but America stayed out because there was a
strategic advantage in standing behind the Suharto regime. Russia
lodged a civil war in Chechnya and the United States remained idle
rather than tangle unnecessarily with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president says we're there for humanitarian reasons,''
said Michael Klare, a professor of peace and world security studies
at Hampshire College in Massachusetts. ``But this has not
characterized U.S. behavior in the past. We've got other things we
think about first sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback said Clinton put American forces in danger
without justifying the risk by establishing that Kosovo is special.
</P>
<P>
   ``If oppression is our standard, then there are far more places
that would require far less U.S. involvement,'' the Kansas
Republican said. ``In Sudan, just supplying food and materials to
the southern Sudanese would go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, the United States should enter another country's civil
war only after extended debate, both within NATO and in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   What to debate?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a legitimate question...of whether the price
is worth the benefit,'' said Solarz, a former Democratic
congressman. ``But if we're not prepared to pay any price at all,
then we had better get out of the business of trying to provide
global leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests weighing several factors. Is, for instance, there
true genocide? Can sending American planes or troops save more
lives than it risks? Does popular support exist at home?
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. involvement is prompted by strategic rather than
humanitarian worries, Solarz suggests again calculating the odds of
success, the mission's support at home and if the military action
will ``generate more problems than it solves.''
</P>
<P>
   In any estimation, he said leaders must understand that any
battle ``will inevitably exact a price in blood and treasure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
