<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-ECONOMIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ASIAN ECONOMIES SHOULD STABILIZE THIS YEAR, TAIWAN'S ENVOY
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The economies of many Asian countries should
stabilize this year and begin rebounding next year, Stephen S.F.
Chen, Taiwan's ambassador to the United States, said Thursday in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little bit optimistic,'' Chen said. ``I think economies
in Asia have bottomed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen spoke at an event sponsored by the International Relations
Council, the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce and the Taipei
Economic and Cultural Office in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Japan and Korea will come back. They are hard-working
peoples,'' Chen said earlier in the day during an interview at The
Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   The economy of Taiwan, which Chen called ``free China,'' has
been resilient, growing at almost 5 percent last year. He
attributed that strength to low inflation, low unemployment, a
savings rate of more than 25 percent and a trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said Taiwan's $18 billion annual imports from the United
States had made it America's second-largest export market in Asia
and its seventh-largest trading partner globally.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan regained this relationship during more than 20 years of
effort after the United States broke relations with Taiwan in favor
of China in 1971, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Taiwan did not take issue with Washington's present
policy of constructive engagement with China. Economic reforms
there will eventually lead to democratic reforms, and that will
lead to reunification of the two Chinas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to the eventual unification with mainland
China, but under freedom and democracy,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted it would be 30 years before China had a democracy
that approximated that of Taiwan. Until then, Taiwan must be able
to plot its own survival, Chen said. To do that, it needs to belong
to groups such as the World Trade Organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan is in final negotiations for entrance into the World
Trade Organization but has encountered resistance from European
countries wanting to consider the applications of both Chinas
simultaneously. China is not yet ``qualified'' to belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not qualified, it is unfair for us to have to wait
indefinitely,'' Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
