A6042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLDSTUDENT27-COX     03-26 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDSTUDENT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman, 65, edges closer to college degree
 &HT;    By Don Horine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ It's been awhile since Evelyn Fein started
college _ about 65 years, in fact. But she's getting closer to
getting a degree, and she's doing it in style _ with straight A's.
</P>
<P>
   Fein, 83, has been taking one course a year at Palm Beach
Community College for six years _ ever since her husband, Martin,
died. This week the college honored her as one of two
nontraditional students of the year for the central campus.
</P>
<P>
   In appreciation, her son, Sandy, arranged for the college to get
a $10,000 donation from a private foundation he works for in Des
Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Fein, who lives in Lake Worth, first took college courses in
1934 at City College of New York. She later took more classes at
Brooklyn College, where she was secretary to the dean of students.
She didn't earn college credit for some of the courses because they
were of a business rather than academic nature. But eventually she
realized what she really wanted was a liberal arts degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt I missed something in life by not having a
degree,'' she said. ``Besides, what can a woman my age do with
herself? She can play cards or read. Study is the next best
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She lacks four courses for an associate of arts degree. She's
earned only A's in all six courses at PBCC. Her overall grade point
average isn't 4.0 _ but it's close, she said, about 3.8 or 3.9.
</P>
<P>
   PBCC speech instructor Kathleen Asher, from whom Fein took a
course last fall, said, ``She was a delight to have in class. She
took such an interest in the young people. She wanted to learn from
them, but the interesting thing is, the young people wanted to
learn from her, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Said her son: ``She's really focused on learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
