<HEADER>
A6043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      03-26 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECT AGAINST FUTURE INFLATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 41 and would like to retire at age 50 with an income
stream of $50,000 a year. My IRA consists of $20,000 in Janus
Overseas and $20,000 in Vanguard Specialized Health Care funds. I
also have a taxable account of $64,000 invested in Vanguard Total
Stock Market Index. I contribute $2,000 a year to the IRAs and $200
a month to the taxable account. I also anticipate a pension of
$1,200 a month at age 50. If I work until age 55, it will be
$1,800. How am I doing?
</P>
<P>
   N.N., Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. I suspect you supplied the information about the pension
value at age 55 because you have an inkling that retirement at age
50 will be pretty tough. If so, you're right.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the numbers work out. If you continue savings at your
current rate and achieve average annual returns of 10 percent for
the next nine years, your pool will be 307,754. After collecting
your $1,200 monthly pension, you'd need $2,966 a month from your
investments to bring you to that $50,000 annual income stream. To
bring in such a sum without invading principal, you would require
investment returns of 11.57 percent _ out of the question for an
income-oriented retirement portfolio. Let's look at retirement at
age 55. With the boost in your pension, your monthly income
requirement would fall to $2,366. And with the extra five years of
contributions and portfolio growth, your retirement savings would
be $523,633 _ again presuming 10 percent average earnings. That sum
would fill your income needs if you averaged only 5.4 percent
portfolio returns. Put another way, you could invest about $440,000
of the retirement portfolio in fixed-income holdings to supply your
income stream, leaving the remainder in growth vehicles to build an
account to protect you against future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Are these comfortable figures? No. I'd rather see you with a
total pool of about $640,000 at age 55 _ giving you a more
substantial amount of savings that should serve to protect against
future inflation. But to get there would require an additional $264
in monthly savings during the next 14 years. In the end, there are
only two ways to get to the target _ save more now, or wait longer
to retire. In considering all this, remember one truism _ the
earlier you retire, the more money you will need in reserve to
protect against inflation in your later retirement years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have held shares in Heartland Value since 1996, and at the
beginning of 1998 they were worth $14,850. At the end of the year
they were worth $13,148, representing a loss of $1,702. But I
received a form 1099 from Heartland for $47 in dividend income and
$255 in long-term capital gains for 1998. How can this happen when
I lost $1,702? Can I claim any capital loss?
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Boxford
</P>
<P>
   A. The truth of the matter is that most mutual funds are managed
with little or no regard to the tax implications of the portfolio
changes. The reason you got the form 1099 was that Heartland Value
distributed 6 cents per share in dividend income last year and 63
cents per share representing its net realized capital gains. These
are far from horrific levels. Can you remember back to 1997, which
was a more pleasant year for Heartland Value. That year the fund
distributed 17 cents per share in dividend income, and a whopping
$4.87 per share in capital gains distributions. But I'm sure you
didn't quibble about that much more substantial tax liability,
because in 1997 Heartland Value produced total returns of 23.19
percent. Yes, it is a completely different feeling to get a tax
bill for a year in which your fund lost 11.46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As for claiming a loss on the shares, that can be done only if
you sell them, and even then the question of whether you have a
gain or a loss depends not on what happened in 1998, but on how
much you paid for your shares back in 1996, and, if you have been
reinvesting distributions, through the subsequent purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Mutual Funds argues that the fund's woes can be
traced to its asset base, which currently stands at $1.46 billion.
Such an amount would not be a big burden in most investment
spheres, but it's a lot of money to manage carefully if you're
focusing on micro-cap stocks. For that reason, Morningstar suggests
the fund is unlikely to return to the strong levels of its glory
years _ from 1991 through 1995, during which it grew from $29
million to $1.19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 56. My portfolio includes a retirement plan at work in
which I have $43,350 in American Century Income and Growth, $11,800
in American Century Twentieth Century Ultra, $45,450 in Fidelity
Contrafund, and $11,300 in IDS New Dimensions. I add $530 a month,
and my employer contributes $220 monthly. In addition I have an IRA
through an insurance company, with $1,950 in a high-yield bond
account, $17,600 in managed account, $2,880 in an equity account,
and $2,110 in an international growth account. Finally, I have a
Roth IRA of $2,315 invested in Enterprise Growth. What do you think
I will have if I retire at 62 and/or 65?
</P>
<P>
   E.G., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A. Aside from your insurance company IRA, you have substantially
all of your money concentrated in one market sector _ large-cap
domestic stocks. Over the longer haul, I think you'll find that a
more diversified portfolio will serve you better.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you might consider reducing the risk level by moving the
investments toward more conservative holdings. It's time to begin
the process of winding down risk. You say that you don't have many
other choices with your employer's plan, but I'll bet what you mean
is the plan doesn't offer many choices that seem particularly
attractive based on their past performances. I would be much
happier if that retirement plan included a balanced fund, a
fixed-income element, a small-cap offering, and an international
fund. If you were able to put 10 percent of the plan assets in each
of these categories, you would go a long way both toward reducing
risk and building diversification.
</P>
<P>
   Where might you be in six or nine years? Let's begin with an
assumption of 8 percent average annual growth. With ongoing
contributions at current levels, the pool would grow to $288,614 in
six years and $393,913 in nine. Want to dream? Then plug a 10
percent growth assumption into the computer, and the six-year
accumulation comes out at $318,414, and the pool would be $455,042
after nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker will answer questions in the Sunday MutualFunds
and Monday Money sections. Send letters, including your name,
address, and telephone number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston
Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
