<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY AREA WOULD BE IN BIG TROUBLE WITHOUT THE MAGIC COUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Do you know that the annual earnings of
workers in Johnson County, Kan., surged more than 125 percent, from
$4 billion to more than $9 billion, from 1986 to 1996? Do you care?
If not, you're overlooking the area's most mind-boggling economics
saga of the postwar era.
</P>
<P>
   It's usually a good idea to steer clear of lots of numbers when
writing for a general audience, but this effort is an exception to
the rule.
</P>
<P>
   The County Economic Research Institute puts out what it calls
``An Economic Primer'' of Johnson County that is chockablock with
numbers. It's an annual statistical snapshot designed to emphasize
Johnson County's prodigious presence in the metropolitan area and
the state of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   It fits easily into a jacket pocket, the better for business and
political leaders to carry and share with those who might be key to
furthering the county's incredible progress.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone interested in things economic knows Johnson County is
an 800-pound gorilla in Kansas and the area. A scan of this
brochure, however, reminds us that this King Kong may be even
larger than imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 update, for example, offers these tidbits:
</P>
<P>
   - From 1987 to 1997, Johnson County accounted for 55 percent of
the area's population growth and 61 percent of Kansas population
growth.
</P>
<P>
   - From 1986 to 1996, Johnson County accounted for 56 percent of
the area's net job growth and 38 percent of new Kansas jobs. At its
pace of job creation, it has been generating the companywide
employment of Hallmark every 23 months, Farmland Industries every
14 months, and Hoechst Marion Roussel every three months.
</P>
<P>
   - From 1986 to 1996, Johnson County added about 400 businesses a
year and accounted for 55 percent of the area's net gain in
business establishments and 57 percent in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   - In 1995, the latest year with available data, Johnson
Countians paid 25 percent of the state's total income tax revenue.
In fiscal 1997, county sales tax collections were 24 percent of the
Kansas total from this source. In 1997, assessed value of the
county's real and personal property amounted to more than 20
percent of the state's total.
</P>
<P>
   - From 1986 to 1996, the 21,500-plus retail jobs created in
Johnson County represented 56 percent of all such new jobs
generated in the area and 32 percent of the growth in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   - From 1986 to 1996, Johnson County accounted for one-third of
all job growth in the construction sector for the state and the
area. Construction wages in the county were nearly 30 percent
higher than the state average and 6 percent higher than the area
average.
</P>
<P>
   - Although manufacturing jobs are only 7.4 percent of Johnson
County's employment, compared with 13 percent statewide, the county
accounted for 13 percent of all the state's new manufacturing jobs
from 1986 to 1996. While the overall area lost more than 7,700
manufacturing jobs during that time, Johnson County added more than
3,000 in this sector.
</P>
<P>
   It's often been said, present company included, that this area
derives its identity and prestigious cachet from Kansas City. This
is true, no doubt, but as these telling statistics show, Johnson
County has become the primary engine of the area's growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
