<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6049 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-POLICY-2TAKES     03-26 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-POLICY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN POLICY IS COMPLICATED IN CHOOSING WHICH BATTLE TO FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON and RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Depending on who does the counting and how, anywhere
between a few dozen and 100 armed conflicts fester in various
countries on a given day.
</P>
<P>
   So why is America taking sides in Yugoslavia's civil war?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton argues that the United States and its NATO
partners have a humanitarian obligation. To simply stand aside, he
contends, gives a green light to genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, critics note, the United States has mostly sat by during
the slaughter of ethnic groups in Rwanda, Sierra Leone, Bosnia and
the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, Clinton says, this first-ever offensive strike by NATO
guards a strategic interest as well.
</P>
<P>
   Left unchecked, he maintains, the Yugoslav military could run
roughshod in the region. That, in turn, could tempt Albania and
Macedonia to take up arms. And that could beget trouble between
Greece and Turkey, NATO allies but historic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the critics question the thinking. Russia has made clear
its anger about the air strikes. So American meddling in the
Balkans, they suggest, could do more to spread the conflict than
contain it. It wouldn't be the first time a world war started
there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet pressed for a set of rules or a rank of factors to decide
when to intrude in another country's civil war, the criticsback
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is,'' said Stephen Solarz of the Brussels-based
International Crisis Group, ``no magic formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead there emerges a tenuous agreement that foreign policy,
especially today's post-Cold War foreign policy, is unavoidably
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's critics concede Slobodan Milosevic has the blood
of thousands of Kosovar Albanians on his hands and that containing
Yugoslavia's hatred won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is over how to stem the crises and whether Kosovo
outranks other trouble spots on the American agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars at the University of Hamburg in 1998 identified 31
full-scale ``wars'' and 18 ``armed conflicts'' around the world.
India alone was the theater of at least four wars in 1998; more
than a dozen wars raged in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States truly were basing these decisions on
human suffering, then it should have gotten involved long ago in
Algeria, Sudan, Zaire and Rwanda,'' said Michael Renner of the
Washington-based World Watch Institute. ``Suffering in Kosovo, so
far, is on a much, much lower scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the color of the victims does play a role in the
United States' action in these matters.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, U.S. intervention could be rationalized as
part of the larger cause to prevent the spread of communism. The
national interest of the United States, simply put, was whatever
foiled the national interest of its superpower rival, the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   With Kosovo, the Clinton administration bases its call to arms
on humanitarian concerns _ a dubious argument to those who note
that civilians have been slain by the tens of thousands elsewhere
in recent years without their killers feeling the sting of American
cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In Rwanda, government-orchestrated genocide in 1994 brought the
deaths of more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and politically
moderate Hutus. Though the United States now backs the new
Tutsi-led government there, United Nations peacekeepers chose not
to intervene when the killings began.
</P>
<P>
   Elswhere in Africa, an estimated 80,000 people have been killed
in Algeria, 1.5 million have died since 1983 in the Sudan civil war
and perhaps 10,000 have died the last couple of weeks in the
Ethiopian-Eritrean war, according to the Transnational Foundation
for Peace and Future Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economics is often the basis of foreign policy, and there's
the perception that there's not much to be gained for the United
States in Africa,'' said Richard Knight, a researcher for the
Africa Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the military to matter is different, too, he
said. In Sierra Leone, the guerrilla fighting is waged street by
street, door to door. For American troops, it could prove full of
the sort of elusive targets that bedeviled troops in Somalia, where
18 U.S. troops were killed in an ambush and their corpses were
dragged through cheering crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Serbs, at least you've got a real army to go after,''
Knight said. ``At the same time, the message is sent that the
United States isn't going to put its prestige and resources on the
line in Africa, so things get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19 NATO allies trying to tame the Yugoslavs say that
outsiders should not enter every civil conflict, but that violence
in Kosovo demands a response because it is genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now (the Serbs have) started moving from village to village,
shelling civilians and torching their houses. We've seen innocent
people taken from their homes, forced to kneel in the dirt and
sprayed with bullets,'' Clinton said. ``This is not war in the
traditional sense....
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending this tragedy is a moral imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton didn't specifically call Serb action in Kosovo
genocide, he compared it to the ethnic cleansing in the Bosnian war
that killed more than 200,000 and left 2 million homeless.
</P>
<P>
   White House polling, according to the Chicago Tribune, shows
that Americans would stand behind the president despite U.S.
casualties as long as the mission is designed to prevent ethnic
cleansing or genocide.
</P>
<P>
   But are the Serbs committing genocide against Albanian Kosovars?
Is it the systematic killing of an entire ethnic group, or are
civilians caught in a crossfire between the Serb government and the
Kosovo Liberation Army?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every victim wants to claim genocide today, and I don't say
that to demean the cause of the Kosovars,'' said Arch Puddington,
vice president of research for Freedom House, a human-rights group
that studies political and religious struggles around the globe.
``(But) a couple of thousand people killed in a bloody political
battle is not genocide.'' MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
