<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Web Site for Conference Calls &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors have been shut out of companies' conference
calls with analysts for just about as long as corporations have
been conducting such chats. Now, a new company is using its Web
site to keep individuals abreast of when such conference calls are
scheduled, providing dates, times and phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The new site, www.bestcalls.com, is the creation of Mark Coker,
33, who is president of Bestcalls.com and also runs a public
relations firm. The purpose of the site is to encourage investors
to contact companies that are holding conference calls and to
demand to be included. Often, Coker said, ``they can be invited if
they just ask to attend.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the site comes as Arthur Levitt, chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, has made the issue of selective
disclosure _ the release by corporations of financial information
exclusively to, say, Wall Street analysts or institutions _ a major
focus of the regulatory agency. Conference calls that exclude the
media and individual investors are a prime example of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing couldn't have been any better,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bestcalls.com uses two researchers to track down scheduled
conference calls; it also relies on corporate investor relations
officials and subscribers to post the information. Since it started
on March 20, about 7,000 subscribers have registered on the site,
which is free. Within two months, Bestcalls.com plans to start
posting advertisements on the site, Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Janus effect. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that an enormous chasm has developed between the
funds investing in large-capitalization growth companies and almost
every other type of fund. But even among large growth funds, Janus
20 continues to stand apart.
</P>
<P>
   After blowing away the rest of the nation's 25 largest funds
last year _ returning 73.4 percent _ it is looking like a repeat
winner for the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This year through March 25, the fund, which has about $20
billion in assets and usually holds 20 or so stocks, gained 18.6
percent, the best performance of the 25 biggest funds, according to
Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 stock holdings of the Janus 20, most with lofty
price-to-earnings ratios, made up almost 60 percent of its
portfolio as of Oct. 31. Shades of the Nifty 50? Shareholders
aren't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   A sibling, the Janus Fund, is running a distant No. 2 among the
25 biggest funds, with a 10.7 percent gain. The largest fund, the
$86 billion Fidelity Magellan, has returned 7 percent, good enough
for the No. 4 spot. And $78 billion Vanguard 500 Index fund and its
$23 billion institutional twin, aren't far behind, each with a
return of about 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By general equity categories, funds that mimic the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index have performed best in the quarter,
returning 5.1 percent, on average, followed by growth funds and
capital appreciation funds, at 3.7 percent and 3.0 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Losers were small-capitalization, microcap and midcap funds,
with declines of 8.0 percent, 4.5 percent and 2.1 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter has been witness to several turnarounds _ the
most prominent, perhaps, by the fund manager Garrett Van Wagoner,
who has surged since last October, after two disastrous years. Four
of Van Wagoner's funds are among the top performers on the overall
list so far this year, including Van Wagoner Technology, at No. 6
with a 47.7 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   The winner in all categories was the Internet Fundrt-specific
fund, which returned 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
