A6052 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-BILL-KAN &LR;      03-26 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BILL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO LIMIT ABORTIONS WINS TENTATIVE APPROVAL IN KANSAS HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ A new attempt to restrict abortion in Kansas won
tentative approval Thursday from the Kansas House.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, girls 17 and younger who want an abortion would
first have to get written consent from a parent or approval from a
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dare say that 99 percent of the Kansas families out there
want to know when their daughter's in trouble,'' said Rep. Susan
Wagle, a Wichita Republican and a leading anti-abortion lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Critics called the bill unnecessarily intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're messing where we don't belong,'' said Rep. Sue Storm, an
Overland Park Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Debates over abortion have become an annual event in the
Legislature, with anti-abortion forces wielding considerable
strength, particularly in the House. The vote in favor of the
latest bill was 67-35.
</P>
<P>
   Current law requires that before a girl 17 or younger receives
an abortion, a parent or legal guardian must be notified. The bill
approved Thursday would change that to require written consent.
</P>
<P>
   If a girl objected to the parental consent requirement _ or if
consent was denied _ she could petition a county district court for
a waiver of the requirement. An adult could help her with the
application. A judge could, depending on the circumstances, approve
an abortion. The legal proceedings would be confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill point out that teen-agers typically must get
parental approval for all sorts of activities, including school
field trips.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, including Missouri, already require parental
approval before underage girls receive an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   How the Senate would act on the consent bill isn't known. There
have been indications, however, that Gov. Bill Graves may veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently whether he supported a parental consent bill, the
governor replied: ``No, we don't think it's a very good bill. There
are concerns about whether it's even constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill wasn't a top priority of the anti-abortion lobbying
organization Kansans for Life.
</P>
<P>
   David Gittrich, executive director of the group, said he hoped
the Legislature would first try to straighten out a confusing law
enacted a year ago to ban a procedure that anti-abortion groups
call ``partial-birth abortion.'' No bill on that subject has gone
through the House or Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Kansans for Life applauds the parental consent bill,
Gittrich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's saddening over the years when we hear of parents who
don't want an abortion and find out someone has performed an
abortion on their girl,'' he said. ``There's nothing they can do
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the bill could lead to more minors having babies
against their will, or to delays in providing abortions, which
would increase costs and risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What protection does consent provide that notification does
not?'' asked Erika Fox, vice president for public policy for
Planned Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ralph Tanner, a Baldwin Republican who previously has cast
anti-abortion votes, told the House he would vote present instead
of yes or no on the latest bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we ought to be debating this proposition,''
Tanner said. ``Let us get away from this kind of business, let us
leave these kind of decisions to the family home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
