r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-SEX-KAN &LR;      03-26 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-SEX-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TEACHER PLEADS GUILTY TO HAVING SEX WITH 12-YEAR-OLD BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A former Kansas City area teacher pleaded
guilty Thursday to having sex with a 12-year-old pupil.
</P>
<P>
   Amy M. Rodriguez, 39, struggled with her emotions at times as
she answered lawyers' questions about what happened between her and
the boy last May and June. She had been a long-term substitute at
Raymore-Peculiar Middle School, where the boy attended.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she knew he was younger than 14. Yes, she had sexual
intercourse with him on three separate occasions at her Greenwood,
Mo., home. And yes, as her voice broke into a sob, she understood
it was illegal and could send her to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Circuit Judge John Moran then accepted the guilty
plea from Rodriguez, found her guilty of three counts of
first-degree statutory rape, and scheduled a June 18 sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Geary Jaco, Rodriguez's attorney, said after the proceeding that
Rodriguez wanted to shield her two children and the victim from the
pain caused by a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very difficult time for Mrs. Rodriguez,'' Jaco
said. ``She made the decision based on her concern for those three
children and any others who have been harmed by this.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez took the stand, she appeared mostly calm as she
answered scores of questions affirming her intent to waive a trial.
But her voice cracked when she talked of her involvement with the
boy and the range of punishment she faced.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the guilty plea, assistant Jackson County
prosecutor Ted Hunt recommended that Rodriguez spend no more than
15 years in prison. She could get probation. Without the agreement,
Rodriguez faced five years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Rodriguez and the boy began the
sexual relationship last May, including once when she told him to
tell his mother that he was sleeping over at a friend's house;
instead, he spent the night at the teacher's home. The records also
indicate that the boy's mother found romantic letters exchanged by
the boy and his teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez previously offered to surrender her Missouri teaching
certificate and will do so again after she is sentenced. Jaco said
Rodriguez is still living with her husband and children. He said
she has received psychological counseling since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Missouri Department of Elementary and
Secondary Education said certain convictions, such as sexual
offenses involving children, require the automatic revocation of a
teaching license. The department has monitored the case against
Rodriguez and has waited for its resolution before taking official
action.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said the agreement allowed the judge several options,
ranging from the full 15 years in prison to a mixture of prison and
sex-offender programs to probation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
