<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MIGS-NYT &LR;      03-26 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MIGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTTIME TRAINING AND AWACS CAPITALIZE ON WEAK SPOTS OF YUGOSLAV
MIGS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-INFORMATION, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Yugoslav MiG-29s are among the world's top
fighter jets. But NATO has Awacs radar planes to track their every
move, long-range air-to-air missiles to shoot at them and better
trained pilots who anticipate the Yugoslav pilots' antiquated
Soviet-style tactics.
</P>
<P>
   And that, American and Yugoslav military experts said, is why
NATO has shot down 5 of Belgrade's 15 most advanced MiGs in three
days.
</P>
<P>
   NATO generals have been puzzling over why Yugoslavia sent up
three MiG-29s on the first day of the air campaign _ only to have
American and Dutch pilots shoot them down _ and have fired one of
its formidable surface-to-air missiles. It missed.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery deepened Friday, when two American F-15Cs shot down
two more MiG-29s that had crossed from Serbia into Bosnia. Four
other MiGs fled or were chased off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know why they were flying into Bosnia,'' said a
spokesman for the Pentagon, Kenneth Bacon, who suggested that the
planes might have been trying to attack allied forces in Bosnia or
lure the American jets into an ambush in Yugoslav airspace. ``If
this was the scheme, it backfired egregiously on the Yugoslavs.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and NATO have a sophisticated system of
tracking all aircraft in the air over Yugoslavia. Airborne Awacs
planes, playing traffic cop in the sky out of harm's way, can spot
an enemy plane as it takes off and, as the Awacs did Friday,
dispatch fighters to intercept it.
</P>
<P>
   With any element of surprise lost, the MiG pilots very quickly
found themselves in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their MiGs are at a disadvantage, because we're very good at
detecting anything that flies with our Awacs,'' said an American
Air Force general who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, they're very regimented in their tactics. It's
very Soviet style, in that everything they do is controlled from
the ground. They don't think for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The general said the U.S. planes had probably shot down the two
MiGs with long-range air-to-air Amraam missiles. Bacon said it was
unclear which of the four weapons aboard the F-15s had downed the
MiGs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another problem is that their pilots have very little flying
time,'' Lt. Col. Miljenko Radich, a retired Yugoslav Air Force
officer, said in a telephone interview from Zagreb. ``They are
trained for dogfights in the day, not at night. NATO selected the
time of attack marvelously.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots who shot down the MiGs are extremely familiar with
the plane's strengths and weaknesses. Top-of-the-line former Soviet
aircraft have long been sought by American intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   So the Pentagon knows quite a bit about their electronics and
airframes, helping train Air Force pilots to knock them out of the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Soviet Union, the United States has had
even closer looks at the planes _ simply by buying them. As part of
its efforts to stop the sale of sophisticated weaponry from the
former Soviet Union to unfriendly countries, the United States in
1997 bought 21 MiG-29s from the former Soviet Republic of Moldova.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
