</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-SCHOOLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS TURN KOSOVO INTO CIVICS LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Conn.)  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-MIGS,
KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-INFORMATION,
KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In schools around the country, a complicated lesson in
geopolitics has suddenly sprung from the textbook onto the
television screen. And like many of their parents, students are
struggling to make sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   Few had heard of Kosovo before NATO began air strikes on
Wednesday. In interviews Friday, the military assault and its
historical background puzzled students at every grade level.
</P>
<P>
   But they, their parents and their teachers said the fighting in
the Balkans offered a chance to link current events and history.
And teachers were seizing the moment.
</P>
<P>
   At a Brooklyn high school named for Edward R. Murrow, famous for
his radio reporting of the bombing of London in World War II, only
a few hands went up Friday when James Patsaricas asked his
10th-grade social studies students if they knew what was happening
in Kosovo. One belonged to Dimitri Chudnovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some kind of war going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other students seemed just as fuzzy on the details. But
Patsaricas, who teaches about World War II, pressed on. To
understand Stalin, he said, ``you need to understand someone named
Slobodan Milosevic,'' the president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to relate old repression with new ``to understand
this man's mind-set,'' he said, ``because we are going to talk
about another dictator named Stalin who had a similar mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, students were comparing the NATO rationale of
stopping the potential destruction of Kosovo's Albanians with
recent lessons about the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the bombing seems hard to understand because it runs
counter to schools' emphasis on resolving disputes through talk,
not fighting. ``The kids wanted to know why we aren't doing that
now with Yugoslavia,'' said Shirley Rinaldi, who teaches fifth- and
sixth-graders at Poughkeepsie, N.Y., Day School in the Hudson
Valley. ``That was very hard for me to answer. I don't think there
is a straight answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Janna Walters-Gidseg, 11, one of Ms. Rinaldi's fifth-graders, is
hoping for one. ``I'm kind of worried about how President Milosevic
won't talk,'' she said. ``NATO and the U.N. and our president all
want to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Older students, who recall the Persian Gulf war of 1991,
including bombing of Iraq, are more familiar with the ways of war
in the late 20th century _ the cycle of stalled talks and bombings,
and more talk and more military action.
</P>
<P>
   Tedd Levy, president of the National Council for the Social
Studies, a teachers organization, said the rash of ethnic conflicts
around the world since the end of the Cold War, and ample news
coverage of them, had made such events almost impossible to ignore
in the classroom. ``It has become an issue of great importance in
the social studies classroom,'' said Levy, a middle-school teacher
in Norwalk, Conn. ``I'm sure teachers are focusing more and more on
those issues of ethnic conflict, and this is the latest example.
It's sad to say, but violent issues engage kids more easily than
others. So this sad situation often makes it easier in the
classroom to motivate kids.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case at Miramonte High School, near San Francisco,
where students said they had discussed Kosovo in government classes
after seeing television reports of the NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see another thing like what happened with
Hitler, with a terrible person taking over countries,'' said Laura
Leslie, a senior. ``We don't want to have to look back on some
historical tragedy that could have been prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul Bruckner, the principal at Edward R. Murrow High in
Brooklyn, still teaches social studies there. He said that in
advance of his scheduled lessons next week on NATO and postwar
alliances, he had been questioning his students about Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Several said they had followed developments in newspapers and on
television but, as with other recent conflicts, they were difficult
to absorb because Kosovo seemed so distant. ``It's kind of
surreal,'' said Michael Feldman, a junior, ``because you hear about
war on TV shows and movies. But when you see it on the TV news, you
realize you are part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mollie Isaacson, a junior, said it took a trip to Israel, where
she saw soldiers carrying rifles as they strolled on the streets,
for the concept of war to hit home. ``I'd never seen someone with a
gun up close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With some prodding, students in Patsaricas' class achieved his
goal: They engaged in a lively exchange over whether the United
States was improperly interfering in a sovereign nation's affairs
or justifiably seeking to end a conflict that could escalate into a
broader war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's already been a lot of violence,'' said Joshua
Kershner. ``Things could get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What business do we have sticking our nose in another
country's business?'' asked Monique Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to stop a genocide from occurring,'' Dimitri
Chudnovsky responded.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was on to Stalin.
</P>
</TEXT>
