<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLANNERY-LETTERS28-CO     03-26 2037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLANNERY-LETTERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Through the mail, reclusive Atlantan befriended and inspired
great writers
 &HT;    Embargoed for Sunday, March 28.
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLATNTA _ Hazel Elizabeth Hester took the bus to downtown
Atlanta every morning, where she worked as a clerk at a credit
bureau. She never married and never had children. She lived in
various apartments, amid towering stacks of books and a changing
menagerie of cats. For 76 years, she was seemingly invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Many were therefore surprised to discover, when she took her own
life this past Christmas season, that she made a bigger impact than
they knew. Betty Hester was, in fact, a prolific writer, a
self-taught philosopher and a vigorous, contentious critic of
modern literature.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was her criticism exercised in a vacuum. She exchanged
hundreds of letters with Flannery O'Connor and Iris Murdoch, two of
the greatest minds in modern fiction, both of whom seemed to crave
her commentary and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   This correspondence eventually provided a priceless window into
O'Connor's work. It was in O'Connor's 250 responses to Hester, whom
she called ``my adopted kin,'' that O'Connor gave perhaps the
clearest accounting of herself as an artist, a scholar and a Roman
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Connor scholar Sally Fitzgerald published O'Connor's
collected letters in 1979 as the book ``The Habit of Being,'' the
letters to Hester were by far the most numerous and the most
interesting. Through those letters, O'Connor ultimately explained
herself to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   And the world needed an explanation. O'Connor was widely
misunderstood as a Southern grotesque, a misanthrope or a modernist
skewering the meaninglessness of life. Hester saw through
O'Connor's brutal tales to the possibility of grace that shines
within those narratives.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are stories about God, aren't they?'' Hester asked in
her first letter, in July 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know who this is who understands my stories,''
the writer responded.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a relationship between two intellectually thirsty
women, sending thoughts between Milledgeville and Atlanta at a rate
sometimes of a letter a week. They would correspond for nine years,
until O'Connor's death in 1964. ``The distance is 87 miles,'' wrote
O'Connor, ``but I feel the spiritual distance is shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   Hester kept quiet about the correspondence, even after
O'Connor's death. She was reluctant to turn over her letters to
Fitzgerald and agreed to allow their publication only if her
identity was kept secret. Hence she is identified in ``The Habit of
Being'' only as ``A'' _ for ``Anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't want to be pursued by scholars and reporters,''
says Fitzgerald from her home in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes and philosophy
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor and Hester had much in common. Both were slightly
reclusive, bespectacled, diminutive women who lived with relatives,
never married and were amused by _ or indifferent to _ the
conventions of Southern society. Both lived and breathed ideas, and
in their letters they discussed Anton Chekhov, Henry James, Sigmund
Freud, Carl Jung, Simone Weil, Aristotle, Andre Gide, Elizabeth
Sewell, Truman Capote and Eudora Welty.
</P>
<P>
   Both made an art of self-deprecation, and O'Connor was
pleasantly surprised when they met for the first time in the summer
of 1956, after she invited Hester down to Milledgeville for a
weekend. The Atlantan was not as outlandish as she had described
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared for white hair, horn-rimmed spectacles, nose of
eagle and shape of ginger-beer bottle,'' wrote O'Connor after that
visit; ``you ain't even passably ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the young woman from Rome, who attended Young Harris
Academy in the late 1930s, was subtly attractive, with a mass of
dark curls and a Giaconda smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she was the pussycat's whiskers,'' says Anne Dunlap,
a roommate of Hester's at Young Harris, a small, rural campus where
Hester attended four years of high school and two years of junior
college. ``I have a vivid picture of her sitting cross-legged in
the middle of her bed, smoking one cigarette right after another,
expounding deep, dark philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap remembers being shocked by Hester's professed atheism,
her disdain of ``men and men's ideas'' and her distaste for
romance. At a school with compulsory chapel attendance, this was a
sophisticated stance.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Hester didn't dance or date or go out for fun. She wrote
for the school newspaper, smoked cigarettes and read voraciously
and endlessly. Her appetite was broad and deep, and ranged through
literature and philosophy into mathematics, physics and history.
``I felt illiterate in her presence,'' says friend Owen Moore, a
professor of French at West Georgia College.
</P>
<P>
   Hester would, through the influence of O'Connor, become a
Catholic from 1956 until 1961. During that time she wrote book
reviews for the diocesan publication The Bulletin, as did O'Connor.
They would be among the few of Hester's many writings to be
published.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing correspondence with British novelist Iris Murdoch
began to lead Hester in a different direction, says Fitzgerald.
``She wandered afield in pursuit of new intellectual life.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, who died this year, wrote 26 novels and lectured in
philosophy at Oxford University. She was friend and colleague to
such giants of 20th-century philosophy as Jean-Paul Sartre and
Ludwig Wittgenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Sartre's existentialism and Wittgenstein's ``Tractatus
Logico-Philosophicus'' were meat and potatoes for Hester, who read
deeply in philosophy and, repudiating Christianity, created her own
idiosyncratic ideology. ``I intend to out-Aquinas Aquinas,'' she
wrote to friend William Sessions, in a letter about a 1966 essay of
hers titled ``Metaphysics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a remarkable woman who never gave up on her search for
the Absolute, with a capital A,'' says Sessions, a professor of
literature at Georgia State University and Hester's literary
executor.
</P>
<P>
   Hester and Murdoch enjoyed a correspondence that lasted for
three decades and rambled through discussions of topics high and
low, from Meister Eckhart to cats. Even after Murdoch developed
Alzheimer's disease and was unable to respond, her husband, John
Bayley, urged Hester to keep communicating: ``Please go on writing
to her because it means a lot to her,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping on the couch
</P>
<P>
   While the young woman's spiritual and intellectual life grew,
her material status was never flush. She worked for years at the
former Credit Bureau Inc. (now part of Equifax), doing typing and
filing. She owned neither a house nor a car, and took the bus to
work every day. For years she shared apartments with her aunt, Mrs.
Gladstone Pitt (whom everyone called ``Clyde''), first on Rumson
Road in Buckhead and then on 11th Street near Piedmont Park. Having
no room of her own, Hester slept on the living room couch,
surrounded by books and ashtrays. In the late 1970s Hester retired
early to help tend to her ailing aunt, and they moved to the
Cheshire Bridge Road-area ranch house where Hester would finish her
days. Her aunt died shortly after they moved.
</P>
<P>
   Without a connection to her friends at work, Hester's life was
more solitary than ever, and she began to reach beyond her
cloistered circumstances. At age 55, she decided to get a driver's
license and buy a car. She ran errands for neighbors and drove an
older friend to Mass every Sunday. (Hester stayed in the car and
worked crossword puzzles.)
</P>
<P>
   She looked after neighborhood children and seemed to have a
strong rapport with youngsters. ``She would encourage my
imagination, in a positive way, and not a lot of adults do that,''
says Oona Callaay, one of her former charges. Hester picked up
11-year-old Oona every day after school, read Beverly Cleary's
``The Mouse and the Motorcycle'' to her, typed her school papers on
an ancient manual typewriter and drove her to riding lessons. She
also helped Oona cope when her parents were going through a
divorce. ``She was in my life when I really needed somebody,'' says
Callaway, now 27 and living in Los Alamos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   `This is the time'
</P>
<P>
   Hester showed some of her writings to neighborhood friends, such
as the novel ``The Sun My Slave'' and the short story ``Lover,''
but pooh-poohed suggestions that she try to publish them. ``I don't
know why she didn't try to get them published; they were
well-written,'' says neighbor Vi Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   She continued to trade letters with writers who intrigued her,
including Atlantan Greg Johnson, author of ``Pagan Babies,'' who
had published an essay about O'Connor that caught Hester's
attention. ``To be read by someone with Betty's intelligence and
rich literary background was certainly flattering,'' says Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   She was, as Johnson sensed, lonely, but prickly and determined
to be self-sufficient. ``Betty was a hard person to do things for,
she was so independent,'' says Oona's mother, Judy McConnell, who
invited Hester over for Thanksgiving dinner every year.
</P>
<P>
   When Hester fell down the steps in her front yard, McConnell's
husband, Bruce, insisted on building a banister for her. ``He did
that over Betty's loud protests,'' says Moore.
</P>
<P>
   She was surely under financial pressure, relying on Social
Security and a small inheritance from her aunt. But she refused
help and in fact was known to send a check to a family in need.
``Iris used to offer her money, but she was just too proud to take
it,'' says Bayley.
</P>
<P>
   Hester's health began to fail last year, and she saw a doctor
for the first time in a decade, Sessions says. Her physical
problems kept her at home and probably aggravated a lifelong
tendency toward depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were beginning to fail in her body,'' says neighbor and
friend Feriel Feldman-Johnson. ``She very simply said, `This is the
time. It's not going to get better and I don't want it to get
worse.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas afternoon, the day before she shot herself with a
hollow-point bullet, Hester met with Sessions, and she seemed to be
in a good humor. She gave him all her manuscripts, which he says
should have been a tip-off that something was going to happen.
``I'm just a dull kind of practicing Catholic, and it never occurs
to me that people kill themselves,'' Sessions says, looking back. A
neighbor went by Hester's house the next day when she couldn't be
reached by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   A woman alone
</P>
<P>
   Betty Hester was fiercely independent all her life, and she
sacrificed a great deal to be able to live the way she wanted to,
trading a conventional social and family life for a world absorbed
in books and ideas. Perhaps, say her friends, the thing she feared
most was losing that hard-won freedom to think. Joanne House, who
is married to Hester's nearest relative, a nephew in Houston, says,
``I think Betty couldn't bear to think she couldn't take care of
herself and would have to be dependent on other people.''
</P>
<P>
   During the holiday week between Christmas and New Year's, Joanne
and Royce House came to Atlanta to help with funeral arrangements
and organize one last get-together at Betty's favorite Chinese
restaurant. ``I think it's amazing that on a rainy, cold Sunday,
with only a day and a half notice, 35 people showed up for that
brunch,'' says Joanne House.
</P>
<P>
   Though living alone, in a world apart, Betty Hester contributed
heartily to her own community. And with her invisible connections
to a larger community of writers, she made a lasting contribution
to the world of ideas, a contribution that will become better
understood as Sessions edits her letters and manuscripts and
completes a writing project about this singular, self-taught
eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne House believes that, although Hester eventually rejected
God as a product of humankind's wishful thinking, God would never
reject this lovable woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to think that God would get a kick out of her,'' she
says. ``I'm a Christian, and I truly believe there must be a spot
in God's heart for someone like Betty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
