<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NUHN-COLUMN27-COX     03-26 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHN-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When is it going to end, Ohio State's Savoic asks
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Slobodan Savovic would not talk about the
NATO airstrikes, the 1,000-pound bombs screaming into Kosovo, the
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   He is from Montenegro, a republic of Yugoslavia that shares a
border with Kosovo. His parents still live there in the small town
of Herceg-Novi. They are thus in danger. Make no mistake: Everyone
in that area is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   And yet here Savovic is, 19 years old, a freshman basketball
player at Ohio State, preparing for OSU's most important game in 31
years, a national semifinal against Connecticut tonight.
</P>
<P>
   War or basketball, which do you think dominates his thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   ``Does basketball have your full attention?'' he was asked
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no distractions?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   He is torn inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about it,'' he said again and again. ``It's very
hard for me to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once did he slip.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did he say, ``A lot of innocent people are going to
get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   His face showed no emotion as he said it, but you knew inside he
was bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where your politics fall, you realize that. You
realize no matter who holds the moral high ground, innocent people
will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, however, Savovic did talk about the bombing
with a reporter for the Cleveland Plain-Dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hurt,'' he said. ``Who wouldn't be? My country has been
at war for the last 10 years and I don't even know why. Who knows
why?''
</P>
<P>
   And then this: ``I don't want to say too much because I am from
Serbia. I just feel bad for both sides. There are kids everywhere,
and they don't know if they are going to die tomorrow, and it is
not their fault.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally: ``I don't get into politics. I don't care about
politics. I just want it to stop. I don't want anybody to get hurt.
I don't like anybody to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is all politics, and he knows it, and he hates it, and he
can do nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   That's his main torment: Helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   The kid his teammates call ``Boban'' grew up in a Yugoslavia
where basketball pushed soccer for most popular sport.
</P>
<P>
   Savovic was a great basketball player, but when he turned 18,
his amateur eligibility ended. He either had to turn pro or give up
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Not as pat as it sounds. Turning pro in Yugoslavia is like
forfeiting your future. Kids must sign a seven-year contract, ``and
although you sign for $30,000,'' Savovic said, ``they might give
you $5,000 and then they keep saying, `We give the rest later. We
give the rest later.' And you never get it.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to complete his education, so he drove to Belgrade,
far from home, and applied to the U.S. Embassy for a visa. He
wanted to move to America, live with his uncle in Newark, N.J., and
finish his final year of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the embassy like 30 times,'' he said, ``and they
always find something why I can't go. `You don't have this or you
don't have this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, without telling him why, they gave him the visa.
</P>
<P>
   When he climbed on the plane two summers ago, his idea of
America came strictly from the movies. ``I expected everything to
be great,'' he said, ``everybody to be rich, nobody to have
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And what movies did he see?
</P>
<P>
   He thought for a while. ``Terminator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' a writer said, ``that prepared you for Newark.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the cliched tall, dark and handsome _ with brown eyes and
black, curly hair cropped in Julius Caesar style.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has not been disappointed by America, even though he
came with such lofty expectations. ``From the first day I was
here,'' he said, ``everybody has treated me like part of the
family. The best thing about America is the freedom. Everybody's
got the same rights.''
</P>
<P>
   We take that for granted. Nobody else does. Sometimes it's good
to be reminded.
</P>
<P>
   Savovic's high school won the New Jersey 4A State championship,
and he narrowed his college choices to St. John's and Ohio State.
When St. John's fired Coach Fran Frischilla, Savovic was
Columbus-bound.
</P>
<P>
   He has been one the Buckeyes' innumerable role players. A
6-foot-6, 230-pound forward, he is averaging 5.3 points in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't seen his parents, Nikola and Olivera, since he left
home two years ago. He sends them tapes of the games. As did he,
they have been stonewalled trying to get visas from the American
embassy to come see their son play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long trip to Belgrade,'' he said. ``And they've tried
a lot of times. But every time they go to the embassy, they won't
let them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the NCAA Tournament is big news in Yugoslavia. And Ohio
State's victory over St. John's was in big headlines. OSU's
semifinal game tonight will be shown live in Montenegro at 2:40
a.m. He said many people will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   If the camera is at the right angle, his countrymen back home
will see part of a tattoo sticking out from under Boban Savovic's
game jersey on the back of his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo addresses the violence and bloodshed in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo says it all.
</P>
<P>
   The tattoo says: When is it going to end?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
