<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMER-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ISSUES INVOLVED IN NATO'S OFFENSIVE AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A brief look at the issues involved in the US-led air offensive
on Yugoslavia:
</P>
<P>
   How long will the raids last?
</P>
<P>
   At first, President Clinton and other officials said Operation
Allied Force would end when Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan
Milosevic, agreed to sign a peace agreement giving autonomy to
Kosovo Albanians. As the air campaign got under way, however, the
administration shifted to a goal of forcing the Yugoslav Army to
halt its offensive in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Is the air campaign changing Milosevic's mind?
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence yet. And so far there is no indication that
Yugoslav forces have stopped their campaign against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo. Quite the contrary: There were reports Friday
of Serb massacres of Albanian men in western Kosovo, of Albanian
leaders gunned down in Pristina, and of Yugoslav jets attacking
Kosovo Liberation Army positions. Milosevic even tried to widen the
war Friday, losing two MiGs in an attempted air attack on NATO
positions in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   What do the Serbs want?
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Milosevic wants to push Albanians out of
northern Kosovo and establish it as a Serb enclave. This would fit
Milosevic's goal of creating a ``greater Serbia'' out of the
remnants of the Yugoslav federation, which broke up in 1991. All
that remains of the old Yugoslavia are the republics of Serbia and
Montenegro, both overwhelmingly populated by Serbs. Ethnic Serbs
also control the eastern third of Bosnia along the border with
Serbia. A Serb enclave in Kosovo would be similar to the one in
Bosnia and might contain the Serbian-Orthodox monastery at Pec,
holy sites at Devic, Decani, and Gracanica, and the battlefield of
Kosovo Polje, where Turks defeated Serbs in 1389.
</P>
<P>
   How much of Operation Allied Force is being shouldered by the US
military?
</P>
<P>
   NATO has 19 member nations, including the United States.
Thirteen of those members have contributed aircraft; eight have
been involved in bombing raids. With by far the best-equipped
military, the United States usually does the big work for NATO, and
NATO's commander, General Wesley Clark, is an American. Most of the
heavy weapons _ cruise missiles, long-range bombers, and tactical
fighter-bombers _ are American. US intelligence and reconnaisance
provide information on targets. US ships in the Adriatic stand
ready to dispatch helicopters to extract downed NATO pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Will US ground troops be called on?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, said
Friday that there is no plan to send NATO ground forces into
Kosovo. However, if Milosevic agrees to halt operations in Kosovo,
many of the more than 10,000 NATO troops in Macedonia would be part
of a peacekeeping force to police a cease-fire. NATO is very wary
of fighting its way into Serb territory on the ground. In World War
II, Serb guerrillas tied up as many as 300,000 invading German
troops. Fighting on their own territory in the rugged hills that
make up much of Kosovo, Serbs almost certainly would inflict high
casualties on any invading force.
</P>
<P>
   What is NATO's military plan?
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the NATO commander, said the alliance will continue
pounding Yugoslav air defenses and military assets,
``systematically and progressively'' reducing Milosevic's ability
to make war. The next phase would be intense attacks on Yugoslav
troops in Kosovo _ a more dangerous mission for NATO pilots because
it would require close-in bombing that could make them vulnerable
to ground fire. Beyond that, secondary military targets throughout
Yugoslavia might be hit.
</P>
<P>
   Could this have been settled peacefully?
</P>
<P>
   There was a plan to do so. It would have given autonomy to the
Kosovo Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's
population. Milosevic rejected the plan, fearing that self-rule for
Albanians would quickly lead to an independent state. He and other
Serbs have argued that Kosovo is a province of Serbia and that no
outside power has a right to interfere in the internal affairs of a
sovereign nation. The United States and its European allies,
however, say the unfolding ethnic cleansing _ killing of ethnic
Albanians by Serbs _ in Kosovo created a moral imperative to act to
stop it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
