<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-PREVIEW27 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Other guys' may decide win between Ohio St.-UConn matchup
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun calls
forward Kevin Freeman the X-factor: a sometimes overlooked player
who can score and rebound and serve as that little needed extra in
a game.
</P>
<P>
   For Ohio State, power forward Jason Singleton and center Ken
Johnson could have that same tag. Not flashy or dominant, the two
can still decide a game with their play.
</P>
<P>
   With the guard matchups getting all of the attention as Ohio
State and Connecticut prepare to face off today in the Final Four,
coaches and players say the teams' role players could be the ones
to swing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matchups are going to be pretty even and could, in the
long run, cancel each other out,'' OSU coach Jim O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Calhoun: ``The game, quite frankly, might be decided by the
quote, `other guys.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the Huskies, the other guys include Ricky Moore, Jake
Voskuhl and Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, considered the team's best defender, is the third guard.
He's likely to draw Penn as his defensive assignment. The two
played against one another when Penn was at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the workhorse,'' Penn said of Moore. ``And if he
covers me or if he covers Mike (Redd), he's gonna have to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Freeman and Voskuhl are largely responsible for
Connecticut averaging seven more rebounds a game than its
opponents. Freeman is fighting a cold and an ear infection and
participated in a full practice for the first time this week on
Friday. Against Gonzaga in the regional final he felt fine and his
13 points, career-high 15 rebounds (10 offensive) and two free
throws with 6.2 seconds left were critical to the Huskies' win.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl, like Johnson, is a shot blocker who occasionally
contributes some double-digit scoring efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do a good job with Voskuhl and Freeman,'' O'Brien.
``I think that that's going to be a key factor for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, meanwhile, are going to have to watch out for
players such as Brian Brown, George Reese, Singleton and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The latter duo combined for 25 points in the Buckeyes 77-74
regional final victory against St. John's. Johnson had seven blocks
in the game as well.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, OSU's third guard, has improved the team's perimeter
defense and allowed Penn more freedom to score. His 3-point
shooting, including a 3-for-3 performance in the second round
against Detroit, also has helped make up for the absence of Neshaun
Coleman, who was ill early in the tournament. Reese had a
career-high 15 rebounds against the Titans and has been an
important frontcourt reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Both Calhoun and O'Brien said it's important that their centers
stay out of foul trouble. Johnson was able to do that against St.
John's and the Buckeyes reaped the rewards. The soft-spoken 6-11
center who is majoring in art at Ohio State, said increased
confidence has been the main reason for his improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I looked at guys as being better and always felt I
was gonna get beat up ... because I was too skinny or so forth,''
he said. ``This year, I've played against everybody and I haven't
been dominated yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the same will hold true today against Voskuhl and the
Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
