<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOST-SCOONIE27-     03-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-SCOONIE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scoonie oozes leadership, engergy
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ With his wide, gap-toothed grin and
endless energy, it's hard to imagine James ``Scoonie'' Penn as
lethargic. But last year was a year without competitive basketball
for Penn, a transfer from Boston College, and he just wasn't
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got mopey,'' OSU coach Jim O'Brien said of the Buckeyes'
junior point guard. ``There was no reward for him from all his hard
work in practice every day. I think he got to the point where he
was almost like a forgotten guy. People across the country forgot
that Scoonie Penn even existed.''
</P>
<P>
   One year later, as the Buckeyes prepare to face Connecticut in
the Final Four today, Penn needs no introduction. His game has
become as memorable as his nickname. His role on this Buckeye team
as irreplaceable as the team's chemistry. To many Ohio State fans,
he is Superman in Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt all along that he is a premier player,'' said
O'Brien, Penn's coach at Boston College before the two came to Ohio
State last season. ``And he's a better player now than during his
two years at BC. He's stronger, he's a brighter player, he's more
mature.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also the difference in a Buckeye team that went from 8-22
last season to 27-8 this year, one of the most dramatic turnarounds
in Division I college basketball history. More than his keen court
sense and 3-point shooting, Penn's leadership has proven to be the
missing ingredient for a previously hapless OSU program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the team was lacking last year,'' fellow guard
Michael Redd said.
</P>
<P>
   That and confidence, a quality Penn oozes. It was Penn who
predicted the Bucks would make it to the NCAA
</P>
<P>
   Tournament when everybody else was simply hoping for a winning
season and maybe an NIT berth. O'Brien was not thrilled with his
point guard's public prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach said to turn it down and not to talk like that so
much,'' Penn said.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien also knows when to let his point guard loose, to let
him follow his instincts. Against Auburn in the South Regional
semifinals last week, the top-seeded Tigers had cut OSU's lead to
two with 31 seconds remaining in the first half. O'Brien wanted his
team's final shot to come with just a few ticks left on the clock.
But with 18 seconds to go, Penn launched a 3-pointer. O'Brien
grimaced, then relaxed. Penn's shot swished the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoonie made a big shot but it was not a shot that I was
really happy that he took, quite frankly,'' O'Brien said. ``When I
talked to him about it, he said he just kind of felt it. And I
said, `OK, fine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to let good players go. I have confidence
in his decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien also has confidence in Penn's ability, even when his
game falters.
</P>
<P>
   After a red-hot seven-game streak in which Penn averaged 22
points, he injured himself in the Bucks final regular season game
Feb. 27. In the next four games in the Big Ten and NCAA Tournament,
he averaged 12.7 points. Observers wanted to know what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Penn said leg cramps and stiffness in his bruised hip
and buttocks affected his quickness and jump shot. But even after
he recovered, his shot was still not dropping. The questions got
louder. Penn kept shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it affected my confidence at all,'' he said of
the slump. ``I wasn't too down on it because I went through a
seven-game stretch where I was hitting everything. I knew that
couldn't keep up forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Auburn, Penn finally regained his offensive rhythm. He
made four of his seven 3-point attempts and finished with a
game-high 26 points. Against St. John's in the regional finals, he
was 7-of-13 from the field and scored 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, with a trip to the Final Four secured, he raced
around the court, swinging his No. 12 jersey above his head and
yelling to the crowd. He found his mother, Allegra, and squeezed
her tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe this? The Final Four!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother smiled and told him she knew it all along.
</P>
<P>
   Allegra, who raised four children on her own, had supported her
son's move from Boston College to Ohio State two years ago, even
though other family and friends advised Penn against it. At first,
Penn was apprehensive about leaving his home for Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Ohio was gonna be cornfields and animals and things
like that,'' Penn said. ``But it surprised me the type of place
Columbus is.''
</P>
<P>
   It was OSU's foundering basketball program that really attracted
him, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what I saw most was the challenge,'' Penn said. ``This
is a program that needed help being turned around. And that was
kind of the situation that I walked into at BC. And it is something
that I accepted. I don't mind a challenge at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The year before Penn arrived at BC, the Eagles were 9-19. His
freshman year, they improved to 19-11 and then 22-9 his sophomore
season. They made the NCAA Tournament both years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoonie gave us problems when he was at BC and he certainly
has given other teams problems while at Ohio State,'' Connecticut
coach Jim Calhoun said. ``He's one of the best pure athletic guards
in the country. And he leads the team both physically and
emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes will find out today if he can lead them to the
national title game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
