<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTENEGRO-DEBATE-BOS     03-26 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ As loud explosions shook this city and
fiery flashes lit up the sky on the third straight night of bombing
here Friday, the Yugoslav Army was moving to evade intensifying
blows of NATO's punishing air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 1 a.m., a series of blasts appeared to come from
the direction of the adjacent civilian airport and the military air
base outside the city, which had been hit in previous nights.
</P>
<P>
   But as with the previous two nights of bombardment, the Yugoslav
Army appeared not to put up any visible defense, despite having as
many as 2,000 surface-to-air missiles. Analysts said President
Slobodan Milosevic appeared to be trying to endure the intensifying
attacks while preserving as much of his military capacity as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, in a pattern reportedly repeated throughout
Yugoslavia, troops and military hardware were relocating from their
bases both to remote areas and to civilian locales. Hundreds of
soldiers from a military base near this regional capital set up a
temporary encampment on the wooded hillside of a national park on
the outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   But even as NATO stepped up its campaign to batter Milosevic's
regime, this deeply divided state was convulsing as leaders of
parliament struggled to reach an uneasy truce and avert a civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of the NATO attack has been a political upheaval
in Montenegro, the smaller of the two republics that make up what
is left of a crumbling Yugoslavia. Half the republic supports the
Serbian nationalist aspirations of Milosevic, but the other half
favors independence from Serbia, including the more liberal,
Western-leaning coalition that currently governs Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos and fear brought on by the air strikes, there has
been widespread speculation that Milosevic would wrest control from
the Montenegrin government or that the government might seize the
moment to declare independence.
</P>
<P>
   Either scenario would probably throw the republic into open
warfare, leaders of both factions said. But late Friday, after
three long days of debate, both the pro-Milosevic parties and the
pro-Montenegrin parties voted for a resolution affirming they would
try to work together to preserve the fragile status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Even as NATO warplanes reappeared in the skies overhead Friday,
Montenegrins seemed more focused on the live coverage of the
parliamentary session. Cooks and waiters at a restaurant gathered
around a television. People stopped on the street and listened to
radios in stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what people care about. The NATO bombs will end soon,
but Montenegro is being pulled apart,'' said a taxi driver, Ganjo
Nejad, who sat glued to his car radio.
</P>
<P>
   One of Yugoslavia's national heroes, Jano Kapicic, 80, a
legendary World War II general and close political adviser to
former Communist President Josip Broz Tito, was one of many elder
statesmen in Montenegro trying to defuse the palpable tension
before it could explode into civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 78-member Parliament's nearly unanimous vote for
conciliation, Kapicic was still worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think America understood the results within Yugoslavia
of their actions,'' he said. ``Today there are words from
politicians, but the problems are still here. It is a very
explosive situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a civil war here, the NATO bombings will seem like
nothing,'' he said. ``A war here would be blood everywhere. Blood.
Nothing else. Young and old. I hope it doesn't happen, it would be
a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranko Krivokapic, a liberal member of Parliament, said after the
session, ``Montenegro should be independent, but this is not the
time. Everything is under control for now. But only for now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
