A6075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOST-NOTES27-co     03-26 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-NOTES27-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Behind-the-scenes players enjoying the ride to Final Four
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Dayton is not without representation on
this overachieving Ohio State team.
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Kwadjo Steele, who played three years at Dunbar
High School, and Mike Ullmer, a team manager from Centerville, are
two key behind-the-scenes members of the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   Steele is mainly a practice player who has played just 37
minutes all season. Ullmer is one of 10 team managers whose
responsibilities include everything from washing team uniforms to
fetching errant rebounds at practice to doling out players' per
diem on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Not flashy stuff but nonetheless important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the Final Four was a goal that we all had and I helped
reached that goal even if I was in the background,'' said Steele,
who played his senior year of basketball at Westerville North High
School in Columbus. His mother, Carolyn, still lives in Dayton and
works as a counselor at Sinclair Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Ullmer, a former basketball manager at Alter, said he was never
good enough to play high school or college basketball but wanted to
be involved with the sport. ``I love basketball,'' he said. ``I
figured this was a great way to be part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The two said so far the trip to the Final Four has been great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to three Final Fours at Alter and this is not even
close,'' Ullmer said. ``It's unbelievable. Everything is
first-class. It's the red-carpet treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele said being an unknown, little-used player has its ups and
downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is I don't have to deal with some of the
pressures the other guys deal with,'' Steele, a zoology major at
OSU, said. ``The bad side is you don't get recognized. I still have
family that don't know I play on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Team hideaway
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the circus-like atmosphere that surrounds a major
event such as the Final Four, Ohio State officials and coaches
wanted quiet, out-of-the-way accommodations for their stay. A place
where fans and boosters and agents couldn't hound players _ or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the Bucks wound up at a secluded and well-guarded
condominium complex about 20 miles from Tropicana Field, the site
of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolled by private security guards and protected by a six-foot
high fence, the brand new complex is closed to reporters, fans and
anyone else not affiliated with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The players say the accommodations are plush: Each player has
his own bedroom and bathroom and shares a kitchen with his
condo-mate. There are washers-and-dryers on site and plenty of
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the team's digs, reserve Devon Smith said: ``If we
tell you, we have to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Said reserve Shamar Herron: ``If my apartment could be that nice
at home, I would be living the life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
