A6076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMOS-MASSACHUSETTS-72     03-26 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-MASSACHUSETTS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY FIND A CHAMPION AGAINST HMO DRUG CUTBACKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ William Galvin, the low-profile Massachusetts secretary
of state, is normally more even-tempered. But he just got too
outraged, he says, by the hundreds of phone calls his office was
getting from elderly people suddenly struggling to afford their
prescription medicine.
</P>
<P>
   So Friday, Galvin, who as secretary of state has the power to
regulate corporations, held an informal hearing of staff members
and representatives of health maintenance organizations as part of
an unusual political salvo against HMOs: he called for public
comment on whether a handful of Massachusetts HMOs deserved to
retain their nonprofit status.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that he would pursue more formal legal proceedings
that could strip them of their nonprofit status, and perhaps the
tax exemptions that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to operate like a business, and tell people
such as these that `For financial reasons, we're cutting you off,'
they should be treated like a business,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``Why should Massachusetts give them the benefit of
nontax status?''
</P>
<P>
   What touched off Galvin's offensive was a change in law that
essentially brought Massachusetts HMOs in line with those in the
rest of the country. A 1994 state law, unique to Massachusetts, had
required the state's HMOs, which are widely considered some of the
best in the country, to offer their elderly members the option of a
plan that would fully cover their prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But because a 1997 Federal law prohibited states from requiring
the HMOs to offer full drug coverage, the HMOs stopped offering it
as of Jan. 1 and changed their pharmacy plans significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Galvin said, calls of distress have mounted from
elderly people, including couples in which one spouse has been
forgoing drugs for chronic conditions to help pay for treating the
other spouse's more acute illness.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Friday's hearing, the president of the
Massachusetts Association of Health Maintenance Organizations,
Robert Hughes, questioned whether Galvin had the authority to
revoke their nonprofit status. Hughes said legal steps by other
bodies would be required, and he questioned the wisdom of Galvin's
whole approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of `no good deed goes unpunished,''' Hughes
said, arguing that under the recent changes in prescription
coverage, ``I think the vast majority of seniors are better off,
not worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   Of about 52,000 elderly Massachusetts people who had HMO
prescription drug benefits at the end of 1997, he said, perhaps 75
percent benefit by the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this is not to minimize in any way the problems of
those who were made worse off,'' he added. ``There could be several
thousands who are in fact experiencing difficulty in paying for
their drugs if they have high drug needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But the HMO group prefers to seek a solution in the Legislature,
Hughes said, by helping to design a pharmacy assistance program to
help the worst-off elderly; and the state's congressional members
are working on the issue as well, he noted. He asserted Galvin was
``focusing on completely irrelevant issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But they do not seem irrelevant to Arthur Morrissette, a master
mechanic and lung transplant recipient, who has been backing up
Galvin from his hospital bed in Massachusetts General Hospital,
where he is fighting pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Morrissette said that he and his wife intentionally signed up
for an HMO because of its unlimited drug benefits, and that he was
counting on those benefits when he decided to go ahead last August
with a lung transplant to counter his emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late last year, after the transplant, he was informed that
from now on, only $800 a year of his medication would be covered.
The 10-odd drugs Morrissette takes can run up to $1,500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   He left the HMO, went back on Medicare and bought expensive
insurance to cover the gap between it and his drug needs, and
things are basically working out, he said; but thousands of others
have been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have companies like Harvard Pilgrim who say they're
nonprofit and are trying to get rid of high-risk patients because
they cost them too much, don't tell me they're nonprofit,''
Morrissette said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Galvin and his staff said they also planned to examine the
relationships between the nonprofit HMOs and other parent, sister
or subsidiary entities that are for-profit. ``If a nonprofit is
being used as a shield to funnel money to a private entity,
individual or corporate, I believe the law in Massachusetts does
not tolerate that entity remaining nonprofit,'' Galvin told the
hearing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response Friday, Harvard Pilgrim Health Care
officials said they had not violated their corporation charter, and
continued to perform charitable functions. They argued that they
had been financially forced to move away from full drug coverage
because drugs were the fastest-growing component of health care
spending, and said that nonetheless, 86 percent of their Medicare
members were better off, or no worse off, under the new system.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox in Galvin's move on Massachusetts HMOs is that they
have been repeatedly ranked among the best in the country, and are
considered unusually successful both in keeping members healthy and
treating them when they fall ill.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those that Galvin named Friday, including Fallon
Community Health Plan, based in Worcester, Mass., Tufts Health Plan
and Harvard Pilgrim Health Plan, were at the top of the U.S. News
and World Report's list of the best managed-care plans late last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Galvin said the willingness of the HMOs to end the drug
benefits, even though they partly replaced them with transitional
aid, raised serious questions about whether they were benevolent
enough to qualify as nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plight of these people persuades me there's a serious
problem here,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
