<SLUG> BC-BKC-BASKETBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN ST. WILL BEAT DUKE _ IN YOUR DREAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Five reasons Michigan State will beat
Duke:
</P>
<P>
   1. Dastardly defense: Sure, Duke leads the nation in scoring
(92.9) with a dynamic, balanced attack the Spartans can't come
close to matching. But it doesn't matter. Since the 3-point line
was introduced in 1987, the winner has averaged 80.3 points in the
title game. Nerves and pressure combine to slow the pace, and it
won't be any different today.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans are the best defensive team Duke has faced since
they met Dec. 2 in Chicago _ a 73-67 Blue Devils victory. Tough and
athletic, Michigan State has yielded an average of 57.8 points in
the NCAA Tournament and held opponents to a stifling 38.5 percent
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   When they slow the tempo and tighten the defensive clamp,
frustration takes a seat on the Duke bench.
</P>
<P>
   2. Historically speaking: No, it's got nothing to do with this
being the 20th anniversary of Michigan State's only national title.
Instead, the pertinent history dates to 1991, when Duke upset
mighty Nevada-Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in that game came when Rebels point guard Greg
Anthony committed his fourth foul early in the second half. He
eventually fouled out with about five minutes left, leaving the
Rebels without their floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess Duke's weakness _ its only weakness? The Blue Devils
don't have a backup point guard. When William Avery is tired or in
foul trouble, they use Trajan Langdon and Chris Carrawell as
makeshift points. That won't cut it today, when Michigan State
point guard Mateen Cleaves lures Avery into early foul trouble and
the Duke machine starts to sputter.
</P>
<P>
   3. Paging Mr. Chappell: The Spartans have insider knowledge of
Duke's system and personnel, courtesy of junior forward Mike
Chappell _ a Southfield (Mich.) native who transferred from Duke to
Michigan State in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Chappell played for Duke for two years, then bolted because of
scarce playing time. He sat out this season but has spent
considerable time discussing the Blue Devils' personnel and
explaining their offense. Some things don't show up on film.
</P>
<P>
   4. Loaded tank: One of Duke's greatest strengths is its depth,
which enables coach Mike Krzyzewski to keep his starters fresh and
overwhelm fatigued opponents in the second half. But Michigan State
has the depth (talented and experienced) to withstand Duke's
40-minute assault.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans' reserves _ leading scorer Morris Peterson, A.J.
Granger, Thomas Kelley and Doug Davis _ have outscored opposing
benches 26.5-14.9 this season. They outplayed Kentucky's respected
reserves 35-27, and they'll do the same thing today.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mighty Mateen: The only way to beat Duke is control tempo and
limit turnovers, which prevents the Blue Devils from scoring easy
transition baskets. It's a job for an elite point guard, a job for
Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 195-pound Cleaves is a first-team Associated Press
All-American with a knack for performing under pressure. He's
strong with the ball and won't wilt against Duke's defense. He'll
control the pace and make sure the Spartans get good shots in their
half-court offense. And if the structure breaks down, Cleaves will
create scoring opportunities with his one-on-one skills....
</P>
<P>
   And one reason Michigan State will not beat Duke:
</P>
<P>
   _Margin for error: Duke has it, Michigan State does not. The
Blue Devils don't have to be at the top of their game, but the
Spartans must play flawlessly, especially in the second half. It
won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   A word on Romar: For peace of mind and financial security,
Lorenzo Romar had no choice but to leave Pepperdine and accept the
head coaching position at Saint Louis. He almost quadrupled his
salary, from $125,000 per year to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   We'll miss his easy manner, his morality _ a rare commodity in
coaching _ and his deft touch with people. (He got Jelani Gardner
to play defense, after all.) Romar's genius is his ability to make
everyone around him feel important without sacrificing his
scruples. He's a great communicator and a better listener
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Pepperdine will find a better coach, but it won't find a
better man.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Cal played March the way most of us expected it
to play February....
</P>
<P>
   More evidence CBS analyst Billy Packer doesn't have a clue: in a
St. Petersburg Times story on the best coaches of all time, Packer
named (in order) John Wooden, Adolph Rupp, Bob Knight, Mike
Krzyzewski and Hank Iba.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Packer omitted Dean Smith, who stands with Wooden as
the greatest innovator of all time. Changing defenses and multiple
substitutions were two his many contributions....
</P>
<P>
   Now it's official. Pac-10: conference of (NIT) champions....
</P>
<P>
   Four words of advice for St. Mary's mammoth, albeit
tender-footer center, Russ Millard, who's considering a jump to the
NBA: Go big fella, go....
</P>
<P>
   How to screw up a coaching search, courtesy of San Diego State
athletic director Rick Bay: Waste your time pursuing Utah's Rick
Majerus, who was never going to take the job, and sacrifice
everything to find a ``name'' coach for your new arena.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it's Steve Fisher, the former Michigan man whose
teams had nearly as much trouble following NCAA rules as they did
executing fundamentals. What an awful hire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DUKE vs. MICHIGAN STATE &QL; 
Backcourt: Duke's William Avery and Trajan Langdon form one of the
nation's top backcourts. Avery is a scoring point guard who can
dissolve defenses with penetration. His counterpart, Mateen
Cleaves, is quick and strong enough to withstand Duke's relentless
pressure. Limiting turnovers and getting good shots are the key to
Michigan State's survival. Edge: Duke  &QL; 
Frontcourt: Michigan State has a slew of role players (Antonio
Smith, Jason Klein, Andre Hutson) against Duke's brigade of
McDonald's All-Americans. If the Spartans are overly concerned with
Elton Brand (17.8 ppg), then Chris Carrawell and Shane Battier will
pounce on the opportunities. Edge: Duke  &QL; 
Bench: Both teams have great ones. Duke's includes freshman forward
Corey Maggette, a top NBA prospect. Michigan State forward Morris
Peterson is the nation's best sixth man; he leads the Spartans in
scoring (13.5 ppg) and was a first-team All-Big Ten selection. A.J.
Granger is the top 3-point threat. Edge: Even  &QL; 
Coaching: Duke's Mike Krzyzewski has two national titles and eight
Final Fours. Michigan State's Tom Izzo has none and one,
respectively. Edge: Duke  &QL; 
Outlook: Duke has manhandled everything in its path, but don't
expect this one to be easy. Duke has not played a close game since
Feb. 6 (at Georgia Tech). How will the Blue Devils react if this
one's tight? Edge: Duke by eight  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OHIO STATE vs. UCONN &QL; 
Backcourt: Ohio State has the best in the country in Scoonie Penn
and Michael Redd, who combine for 36.8 points and 9.5 rebounds.
Both can shoot, score off the dribble and defend. Meanwhile,
Richard Hamilton is UConn's only dependable scorer. Ricky Moore is
its best defender and probably will guard Redd. Edge: Ohio State  &QL; 
Frontcourt: The realm of the role players, with Ohio State center
Ken Johnson as the great unknown. If he plays the way he did
against St. John's (12 points, seven blocks), the Buckeyes win.
UConn's Kevin Freeman is a prototypical power forward (12.6 ppg,
7.3 rpg) and Jake Voskuhl a solid center. Edge: Even  &QL; 
Bench: Ohio State uses four reserves who combine for 18 points;
forward George Reese is the best of the bunch. Albert Mouring (7.4
ppg) and Edmund Saunders lead the Huskies. Edge: Even  &QL; 
Coaching: Connecticut's Jim Calhoun has beaten Ohio State's Jim
O'Brien (formerly of Boston College) the last 18 times they've met.
But O'Brien has made all the right moves this season. Both are
making their first Final Four appearance, but the pressure's on
Calhoun. Edge: Ohio State  &QL; 
Outlook: O'Brien and Penn (ex-Boston College) know the UConn system
and personnel. Ohio State is playing better than its No.4 seed,
while UConn is playing worse than its No. 1. Edge: Ohio State by
six &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
