<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing Prospects Of Room at the Top &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated middle managers wondering if they will ever have a
chance to move up could be in for a pleasant surprise: Some
demographics of the workplace are turning in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   One-fifth of 260 companies surveyed by Development Dimensions
International, a human resources consultant in Bridgeville, Pa.,
say they expect to lose 40 percent or more of their executive
management by 2004 _ partly a reflection of baby boomers' nearing
the retirement age, according to William C. Byham, the firm's
founder. Their replacements, it seems, will come from a younger and
smaller population group _ and from a crop of middle managers
depleted by corporate downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   The companies in the survey ranged in size from 80 to 330,000
employees. Many of those businesses followed a national pattern of
large-scale hiring in the 1950s and 60s, as demand for goods and
services grew and boomers went to work. Now many of those workers
don't have many years before their retirement parties.
</P>
<P>
   The number of workers aged 35 to 44 _ typically the group that
is tapped to replace departing leaders _ will decline 5 percent
between 2001 and 2005, according to Census Bureau data. But the
Bureau of Labor Statistics predicts that the number of jobs
available to general managers and top executives will rise 10
percent to 35 percent, depending on the industry, by 2006. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN J. WELLS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Redecorating on a Screen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even when they have enough money to buy designer furniture,
shoppers can face a different squeeze: The item doesn't fit the
room and has to be returned. The Web site of the Herman Miller
Store (www.hmstore.com) has a room-planning feature that reduces
the hazard by letting users move chairs and tables around on a
floor plan before a truck arrives with the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, users start with a floor plan scaled to a room's
dimensions and add stock diagrams to represent their existing
furniture. The payoff for Herman Miller comes when users browse
menus of its merchandise and fit in items like a compact sofa
designed by Charles and Ray Eames or a Meinecke Collection 7 rug.
</P>
<P>
   Furnishings by Herman Miller, which are sold in high-end stores,
can be expensive. The rug by Kurt Meinecke is $2,260, and the Eames
sofa is $2,526. All the more reason to minimize the chance of
having to send a selection back to the store and start shopping all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHELLY FREIERMAN
</P>
</TEXT>
