A6082 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-MARVIN-CONFLICT-$     03-26 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MARVIN-CONFLICT-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HANDSHAKE DEAL GONE BAD LEADS TO A BITTER LEGAL FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, March. 28) 
 (rk) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARROAD, Minn. _ Bill Marvin can remember when a handshake and a
promise were good enough to do business with his company. That was
the way he built a small-town lumber company into the largest
custom window manufacturer in the world. Now a handshake deal gone
bad may prove to be the company's undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Still based in this tiny town six miles from Canada where Bill's
father, George Marvin, founded it in 1912, the privately held
Marvin Lumber and Cedar and its principal subsidiary, Marvin
Windows and Doors, now have 4,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Those include 12 members of the Marvin family, including Bill,
the chairman and chief executive, and his daughter Susan, the
president. Simple values are and always have been its way of
business, he says.
</P>
<P>
   One company that Bill Marvin shook hands with for decades was
PPG Industries, once known as Pittsburgh Plate Glass. Marvin and
Bob Ponchot, PPG's Minnesota sales representative, were longtime
fishing buddies.
</P>
<P>
   On a summer morning in 1984, Ponchot, Marvin and his son Jake,
now chief operating officer of the window company, met on Jake's
front lawn to hear Ponchot pitch a new product PPG was selling, a
wood preservative called PILT.
</P>
<P>
   The Marvins' decision to buy PILT set in motion a decade-long
chain of soured business dealings, finger-pointing and legal
wrangling that continues today. Bill and Bob's friendship doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   PILT was used on Marvin windows over four years in the mid-'80s.
A few years later, the company started getting customer complaints
about premature wood rot. Marvin Windows studied the rotting
windows and, based on when they were manufactured, concluded that
PILT was the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Windows told customers that even though the windows were
no longer under warranty, it would replace them at no charge, at a
cost to the company that has since run into the tens of millions of
dollars and last year forced Marvin Windows to cancel employees'
holiday bonuses for the first time since a catastrophic plant fire
in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Marvin asked PPG to help cover the costs. To his shock, PPG
refused.
</P>
<P>
   According to its lawyer, PPG told Marvin Windows that its own
analysis found PILT blameless, and that other window makers had
used the preservative without problems. PPG said Marvin Windows had
simply been growing too fast and was churning out faulty windows
just to keep up. And besides, PPG asserted, there was no written
agreement obliging PPG to chip in.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by PPG's stance, and stung by what Marvin felt was a
betrayal by a longtime business partner, Marvin Windows sued PPG in
1994, claiming breach of contract, breach of warranty and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Since then a bitter legal and public-relations war has raged, in
and out of various courts and even in the Minnesota legislature,
with Marvin saying that PPG's recalcitrance and the cost of
replacing the rotting windows were a threat to the company's
survival.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said Mike Nilan, the lead lawyer for PPG. ``They like
to tell you about a family-run business from a small town in
Minnesota who does business with a handshake,'' he said. ``That's a
pretty picture to paint, but it's simply not true. They are a
hundred-million-dollar international corporation with a long
history of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the courts have agreed with PPG's stance. After four
years of arguments and depositions, the suit was thrown out in
January; Marvin is appealing the dismissal. U.S. District Judge Ann
D. Montgomery ruled that too much time _ more than four years _ had
elapsed after Marvin's last purchase of PILT for Marvin to sue over
breach of contract and that the facts of the case did not support a
claim of fraud, to which a longer time limit applies.
</P>
<P>
   Nilan said Marvin had only itself to blame: ``Experienced
merchants ought to be smart enough to write a contract outlining
who is responsible for what if the product they are buying doesn't
work properly. Marvin didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Marvin said promises were made on Jake's lawn that summer
morning, and he had a right to rely on them. ``I'm very surprised
with the position PPG is taking,'' he said. ``We've never had a
written contract, and I don't think that's naive. They reneged on a
handshake deal and, simply speaking, that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponchot, the PPG representative who Marvin said did the
promising, has retired; he said the situation saddened him. ``I was
very close with all the Marvins,'' he said. But he also resents
that they did not give PPG more credit for helping Marvin Windows
grow. ``I'd look Bill Marvin in the eye tomorrow and say that if it
were not for PPG's technology, they would still be a
nickel-and-dime operation.''
</P>
<P>
   After early rulings in the case cast doubt on the viability of
Marvin's claim of fraud, the company turned to the Minnesota
legislature. The Marvin family approached lawmakers in St. Paul
last year, urging passage of a special bill that would override
existing law and apply retroactively to include Marvin's claims.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced late in the session, the bill failed to pass before
the legislature adjourned, but the Marvins didn't give up. Saying a
legal defeat would likely put Marvin Windows, one of the state's
largest employers, out of business, the Marvin family pressed Arne
Carlson, then the governor of Minnesota, to call a special session
to get the bill through. This time, it passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin Windows is a constituent of mine,'' said Leroy Stumpf,
the state senator who sponsored the new bill. ``They are a great
corporate citizen and they needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal magistrate advised Montgomery that the retroactive
aspect of the law was unconstitutional, and the law was ultimately
ignored in her ruling. Despite PPG's stance and the losing streak
in court, Susan Marvin said her company would replace rotted
windows whose owners have already reported the problem. But to
protect itself, the company has adopted a policy of offering
discounts, not free new windows, to customers who complain in the
future after their warranties expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on the satisfaction of our customers in this
business,'' she said in an interview at the company's headquarters,
``and we're standing behind our products; that's just the right
thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
