<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TEXAS-QUALIFYING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN TOPS 190 MPH FOR TEXAS POLE POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Kenny Irwin says that when he is running a
qualifying lap, he does not know the difference between 185 and 190
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not know miles per hour,'' Irwin said yesterday at
Texas Motor Speedway. ``We know seconds, whether it's 28 or 29.3 or
whatever. But that's what all the fans want to know, `You went 190
mph!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Irwin claimed the pole for tomorrow's Primestar
500 with a TMS record hot lap at 190.154 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Or in driver-talk, 28.398 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the magic numbers around the reconfigured, repaved
and really fast TMS on a day when 37 drivers exceeded Jeremy
Mayfield's former NASCAR Winston Cup pole record. Mayfield toured
the 1.5-mile quadoval in 29.047 seconds/185.906 mph April 4, the
morning after qualifying had been postponed by water seeping out of
Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   Recent open testing indicated that the revamped layout could
raise speeds by 2 or 3 mph. Both defending race champion Mark
Martin and Geoffrey Bodine posted practice speeds in excess of 190
yesterday, but the effects of the revisions to the entrance into
Turn 1 and the exit out of Turn 4 did not show up on the speed
chart until the official qualifying session.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was the only driver to break the 190 barrier when it
counted, but the injured Bobby Labonte just missed with a hot lap
at 189.853 mph., second-fastest in qualifying. Row 2 is filled by
second-year driver Steve Park at 189.341 mph and native Texan Terry
Labonte, Bobby's big brother, who ran 189.122.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fast,'' said Irwin, driver of the No. 28
Texaco/Havoline Ford Taurus. ``I would have never guessed we were
that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the physical changes made to the track, Cup cars
also are running here for the first time under NASCAR's revised
aerodynamic changes to the ``5-and-5 Rules.'' The Cup cars now have
taller rear spoilers and lower front air dams, changes designed to
make them more stable _ and faster _ through the 24-degree banked
turns.
</P>
<P>
   But Irwin left no doubt where the biggest improvements have been
made since last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all the racetrack,'' said Irwin, who notched his
second career Cup pole in his 42nd start. ``I think the changes
they made in \Rturns\S 1 and 2 are the biggest reasons. Very little
to the rules. I think the type of speeds that we get on one lap
doesn't affect it as much as during the race with the 5-and-5, the
way it was last year. The track is just faster. I'd say
everything's better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, who broke the tip of his right scapula (shoulder
blade) in a practice crash at Darlington Raceway last Friday,
gutted it out to gain the second spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain about that,'' said Labonte, driver of the No.
18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand Prix. ``It's tough getting in
and out of the car, but once I get in there it's OK. I'm taking it
one lap at a time right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who ran 43 laps at Darlington last Sunday before giving
way to Busch Grand National regular Matt Kenseth, has been
undergoing therapy treatments on his shoulder all week with
trainers from the NFL's Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think \Rtoday\S how I feel in practice is the big key,''
said Labonte, referring to his game plan for race day. ``I'll be
running more laps, and there's a lot more of a load here on your
side and body than at Darlington. We'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, meanwhile, posted his career-best Cup qualifying effort.
His previous best had been 23rd at the Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just need a lot of guts'' to qualify at TMS, said Park,
driver of the No. 1 Pennzoil Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``We've been
working on our car and working on the driver to figure out what I
really need to go faster in qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   The fast four were followed in the top 10 by Ward Burton,
Martin, Ken Schrader, reigning Cup champion Jeff Gordon, Bill
Elliott and Wally Dallenbach Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Included among the 25 drivers who locked up starting spots
yesterday was Jeff Burton, winner of the first Cup race here in
1997 and the current points leader. He is 20th on the grid.
Mayfield broke his own record from last year, but his speed of
186.477 mph was only good for 29th.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt stands 38th, the first
driver not to exceed Mayfield's former record. And three-time
series champion Darrell Waltrip, who is out of provisionals and
needs to crack the top 36 on speed to start the race, will be 46th
when second-round qualifying starts today.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
