<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REZULIN-FDA-NYT &LR;      03-26 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REZULIN-FDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRICTER RULES ARE URGED ON USE OF A DIABETES DRUG  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, N.J.)   By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Amid reports of deaths and serious liver damage
caused by the diabetes drug Rezulin, a panel of scientific experts
Friday recommended that the government place stricter limits on the
use of the drug, and urged that patients take it only when other
therapies have failed.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of votes, the committee stopped short of
recommending that the drug be withdrawn from the market, as some
consumer safety advocates had urged. Instead, the panel told the
Food and Drug Administration that Rezulin, which is used by about
750,000 Americans, should not be used on its own unless the label
is changed to warn patients that it carries very grave risks.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this restriction, some panel members seemed uneasy
with their decision. ``I'm very uncomfortable about it,'' one
member, Dr. Jules Hirsch of Rockefeller University in New York
City, said after the vote. ``I think some of these people are going
to get liver failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation is not binding, although the FDA generally
follows the advice of its outside experts. It came after a
contentious daylong hearing at which agency officials and the
drug's manufacturer offered wildly different estimates of Rezulin's
risks. Endocrinologists, who specialize in treating diabetes,
begged the panel to leave the drug on the market, while consumer
safety advocates characterized Rezulin as a threat to public
health.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing provided the first public accounting of the reports
of deaths and injuries caused by the use of Rezulin. The FDA and
the manufacturer agreed that 43 patients had suffered acute liver
failure that was possibly due to Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, 28 died, seven required liver transplants and five
recovered. The outcome of three others was unknown. But the agency
and the manufacturer could not agree on whether those reports
represent the sum total of the harm the drug has caused or is
capable of causing.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin, made by Parke-Davis, a division of the Warner-Lambert
Co. of Morris Plains, N.J., has been prescribed to 1.58 million
people in the United States since it was introduced in March 1997.
Known generically as troglitazone, it is the first in a promising
new class of medicine designed to treat Type II diabetes, the adult
onset form of the disease, which afflicts an estimated 15 million
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   About four-fifths of all patients who use the drug do so in
combination with other diabetes drugs, and the committee found that
when used that way, the benefits of Rezulin still outweigh the
risks. Parke-Davis was pleased with that finding and said it should
give doctors ``renewed confidence'' in the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's hearing, which was jammed with reporters,
pharmaceutical executives, doctors and patients, marked the fourth
time the food and drug agency has re-evaluated Rezulin; on three
previous occasions it has issued warnings about the drug and
advised doctors to monitor their patients closely. Parke-Davis
officials maintained that the risk of liver problems has plummeted
since last July, when the FDA issued the most recent warning.
Company officials said the risk of developing liver failure is now
1 in 57,000, compared to 1 in 36,000 previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approximately 100 patients with diabetes have died since the
beginning of this meeting,'' Dr. Robert Zerbe, the company's senior
vice president of clinical research, told the committee. ``These
patients desperately need medications to help them control their
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. David Graham, an epidemiologist for the agency, said
that the risks of Rezulin appeared much higher than previously
believed and that the drug became more dangerous the longer a
patient took it. He calculated that only 10 percent of all cases of
acute liver failure had been reported. ``I think the number is
closer to 400 than it is to 43,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account the underreporting, Graham predicted that
one out of every 1,800 patients who used Rezulin for six months
would have serious liver failure. By comparison, he said, the
average person's risk of developing acute liver failure is one in a
million, about equal to the risk of being struck by lightning.
``What we see,'' he told the committee, ``isn't reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people attended Friday's meeting in a ballroom
at the Holiday Inn here. The room was so crowded the FDA had to set
up a closed-circuit television in the hotel's second-floor lobby to
accommodate the overflow.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, a parade of endocrinologists lauded the drug's
benefits. ``Asking people to treat diabetes now without Rezulin,''
said Dr. William Clark of Houston, ``would be like asking a coach
to win a track meet after cutting off one leg on all of his
athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there a shortage of patients willing to testify to the
drug's benefits. Robert Andersen, 78, a retired government worker
and part-time farmer in Westerlo, N.Y., said he had been taking the
drug since it was approved. The drug helped stabilize his blood
sugar, which he said previously fluctuated dramatically, sometimes
leaving him feeling dangerously weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had incidents late at night milking cows,'' he said. ``When
I got that clammy feeling, I barely made it back to the house. I
was weakened out. It was a risky matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Diabetes Association estimates there are 16 million
patients with diabetes in the United States, 15 million of them
with Type II diabetes, the adult-onset form of the disease.
Diabetes is the nation's seventh-leading cause of death and a
leading cause of heart disease, stroke, blindness and limb
amputations. In Type II diabetes, patients develop resistance to
insulin, the hormone that controls blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin is the first, and so far the only, FDA-approved
medication in a new class of drugs, and experts say it is the first
diabetes drug to control blood sugar levels by attacking the
underlying cause of the disease. The FDA recommends that doctors
who prescribe Rezulin monitor their patients' liver function every
month for at least eight months, but whether those warnings were
heeded was the subject of intense debate Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Parke-Davis presented data showing that most patients receive
the monitoring. But Graham, drawing from records provided by an
insurance company, United Health Care, said only 2.7 percent of
patients who had taken Rezulin for three months were monitored
according to FDA recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   But the company said that United Health's Care's data were
incomplete and that most patients did get the monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting data frustrated the panel. ``We are seriously in
need of new information,'' complained Hirsch, the panel member from
Rockefeller University. ``I have almost never had a meeting here
that so confounded me.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to improve the monitoring, Parke-Davis plans to
issue its own warnings about Rezulin, telling patients who have a
history of liver problems not to take the drug. The company plans
to send monthly reminders to doctors telling them to test their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the committee voted that the benefits of the drug
when used in combination with other medicine still outweigh the
risks, Zerbe, the company's research executive, said doctors should
have ``renewed confidence'' in Rezulin.
</P>
</TEXT>
