<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICINE-CABINET27-co     03-26 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-CABINET27-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making sure home medicines aren't hazardous to your health
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Open up your medicine cabinet. What do you see?
If you're like many people, what's there isn't reassuring: old
prescription bottles, half-empty containers of expired aspirin, a
couple of cotton balls, a caked bottle of foundation you must have
bought in '88, a travel-size toothpaste, some Vicks VapoRub from
when your grandmother was visiting, a mystery mascara, a dusty vial
of Old Spice.
</P>
<P>
   Odds are that the contents wouldn't help someone who needed
first aid _ or even someone with a sore throat. A combo cleanup and
stock-up will mean you'll be ready when someone in your family
comes down with the flu, gets an insect bite or has food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to throw out all the expired stuff, or
anything that looks suspiciously old. (It's a bad sign if you can't
remember when you bought it or if the liquid or pill has changed
color.) Also, that old mascara may be the most toxic thing in your
bathroom. Mascara, eyeliner and eye makeup remover more than six
months old should be thrown in the trash. They're easily
contaminated and may cause severe eye infections.
</P>
<P>
   Next, figure out what you need, using our guide. Once it's
updated, go through the cabinet every six months or so, weeding out
the expired stuff. Another good idea is to purchase a first-aid kit
and have one in your car or with your camping equipment (if you're
going to a remote area, you might want to get a snakebite kit, too.
They're available at sporting-goods and outdoor-recreation stores).
</P>
<P>
   The last step is to make sure your medicines and cosmetics can't
get into curious young hands: More than 1 million children younger
than 6 are poisoned each year this way. Most inadvertently got into
their parents' personal care products or makeup, or consumed huge
amounts of aspirin, laxatives or vitamins, which to them might look
like candy. Lock it up.
</P>
<P>
   What should be in your medicine cabinet?
</P>
<P>
   Experts recommend:
</P>
<P>
   _ An analgesic (like aspirin), acetaminophen (like Tylenol), or
ibuprofen (like Advil), to reduce pain and fever.
</P>
<P>
   _ Band-Aids, bandages or gauze pads, for cuts and wounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adhesive tape, to fasten bandages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alcohol prep pads, for disinfection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hydrogen peroxide, to clean wounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Antibiotic ointment, to treat scrapes and cuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Antacid, Pepcid AC or other treatment for upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Immodium AD or another diarrhea treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Benadryl or another antihistamine, for allergic reactions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oral and rectal thermometers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Q-Tips and cotton balls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heating pad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hydrocortisone cream, for rashes, insect bites or burns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tweezers, without teeth, to remove splinters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gel pack, to use as an ice or heating pack.
</P>
<P>
   _ After Bite or similar treatment for insect bites or stings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Caladryl, Cortizone-5, Lanacane or another product with
benzocaine or calamine lotion, for poison ivy, poison oak and
poison sumac.
</P>
<P>
   If you have young children, add:
</P>
<P>
   _ Syrup of ipecac, to induce vomiting if a child has swallowed
something poisonous (use this only with the advice of a medical
professional. It is not recommended in all cases).
</P>
<P>
   _ Diaper cream.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rubber bulb syringe, to clear out an infant's stuffy nose.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oral rehydration solution, like Pedialyte, to help dehydrated
children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Petroleum jelly, to lubricate a rectal thermometer or
moisturize dry skin.
</P>
<P>
   _ A liquid antihistamine like Benadryl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Liquid Motrin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chewable Tylenol.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Children should not take aspirin because of the risk of
Reye's syndrome, particularly when they have the flu or chicken
pox. Reye's syndrome is a rare but serious illness that may follow
a viral infection. It can cause stomach upset, intestinal bleeding,
disorientation and lethargy leading to coma. Children should be
given acetaminophen instead.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an elderly person in the home:
</P>
<P>
   _ A laxative like Metamucil, because many prescription medicines
are constipating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cream for osteoarthritis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prescription medications. (The best place for many medicines,
pharmacists say, is not the bathroom medicine cabinet, which can be
hot and humid, but a cool, dry shelf or cabinet.) You should have
at least a two-week supply on hand.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glucose tablets for diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   _ A list of prescription medications. Take the list with you on
trips; keep it handy in your home to give to a doctor or emergency
personnel if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   How long do medicines stay effective?
</P>
<P>
   _ Check all products for expiration dates. Discard anything that
is expired.
</P>
<P>
   _ You should not have any prescription antibiotic left over.
Take the whole prescription each time; don't stop just because you
feel better. If you do have leftover antibiotics in your bathroom,
throw them out. Some, like tetracyline, can break down into toxic
substances.
</P>
<P>
   _ You can keep leftover pain medication (for example, Vicodin.)
It's safe to use it until the expiration date, if someone has a
broken bone and needs a painkiller. It should be reserved for
emergencies and severe pain. For common headaches or muscular
aches, stick with aspirin or acetaminophen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leftover prescription diarrhea medication stays good for a
couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call a pharmacist if you are not sure if the medicine you have
is still good.
</P>
<P>
   _ It is illegal to give prescription medication to someone it
wasn't prescribed for.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask the pharmacist to put the expiration date on the label of
any prescribed medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Other items in your home that are helpful in an emergency:
</P>
<P>
   _ Disposable or regular diapers: Use as a compress to control
bleeding or as a padding for splints.
</P>
<P>
   _ Towels, sheets, linens: Can substitute for bandages or a
compress.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diaper or safety pins: Pin bandages or slings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Large scarf or handkerchief: Use as an eye bandage or a sling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Magazines, newspapers, umbrella, pillow: Double as splints for
broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fan: Cool heatstroke victim.
</P>
<P>
   Keep these emergency numbers next to your phone:
</P>
<P>
   _ 911
</P>
<P>
   _ Poison Control Center, answered 24 hours a day: 1-800-POISON-1
(1-800-764766-1).
</P>
<P>
   _ Your own address and phone number (for a baby sitter or
visitor who might be calling 911)
</P>
<P>
   _ Pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dentist.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hospital emergency department.
</P>
<P>
   _ Next-door neighbors
</P>
<P>
   Sources: J. David Harper, pharmacist, Crestview Pharmacy in
Austin. American Medical Association's ``Complete Guide to Your
Children's Health'' and ``Handbook of First Aid and Emergency
Care.'' American Academy of Pediatrics' ``Guide to Your Children's
Symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
