<HEADLINE>
TALKING YOUR WAY TO CAREER FAILURE 
LOOK WHO'S JOINING THE INTERNET PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Kan., N.Y., Ohio, Va.) (FOR RELEASE Sunday, March. 28) 
 (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you were thinking it was the crucial assignment you
flubbed, or the glaring gap in your resume, or petty politics in
your office, or even illegal discrimination that was holding you
back from the rapid career advancement you crave.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, no, according to one of the latest secrets-of-success
books: It's how fast you talk.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Benton, a consultant from Fort Collins, Colo., is
promoting her new book, ``Secrets of a CEO Coach'' (McGraw-Hill),
by releasing a list of the ``Top Five Self-Sabotaging Behaviors
People Do to Hurt Their Career Advancement.''
</P>
<P>
   On the list are: talking too fast (``Makes what you say seem
unimportant''), giving others too much detailed information, being
judgmental of others, being too self-critical and using weak body
language and a timid tone of voice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Benton offers by way of explanation that most people think
working harder is all that matters, but that bosses are looking for
``executive maturity as expressed in behaviors.'' What effect the
habitual use of irritating jargon like ``behaviors'' might have on
a person's career, Ms. Benton omits to mention.
</P>
<P>
   Look Who's Joining The Internet Parade
</P>
<P>
   The Internet seems to have an odd catnip quality for political
heavyweights, and vice versa. Vice President Al Gore hardly had
time to live down his widely ridiculed recent remarks seeming to
claim partial credit for inventing cyberspace, when along came word
that a hot Internet stock has added none other than Bob Dole to its
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   OneMain.com went public last week in rather spectacular fashion,
raising $187 million, nearly doubling its stock price on its first
day of trading and closing on Friday at $32, up 45.5 percent from
its offering price of $22. The year-old company buys up Internet
service providers in places like Portsmouth, Ohio, and Winfield,
Kan., that are well away from major metropolitan areas; it has
acquired or agreed to acquire 17 so far, with about 331,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The digits-to-the-heartland strategy seems to be what attracted
Dole, who few would call an avatar of technofuturism, to the
company, only the second board he has joined. (The other is TB
Wood's, a utility equipment maker.)
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the company seems attracted to powerful
connections: A Harvard Business School professor, Thomas Eisenmann,
is one of Dole's two fellow outside directors, and the company is
relocating from Long Island, N.Y. to the Washington suburb of
Reston, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
