</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-DUKE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Bulldogs leashed by Duke
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ As suddenly as Georgia jumped back into a
Final Four semifinal contest in which it never really had any
control, the Lady Bulldogs gave it right back to Duke in a critical
sequence in the second half Friday, losing 81-69 as the Blue Devils
poured grease on the fire in the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia (27-7), totally flustered by Duke's swarming perimeter
pressure defense, showed its youth at the worst possible time. The
Lady Dogs' hopes of delivering a national title to coach Andy
Landers after five Final Four trips withered away in the last 9:10
before a capacity crowd of 17,709 at San Jose Arena. Duke limited
Georgia to 33 percent shooting in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Erickson led Duke with 22 points, Michele VanGorp had 20
and Georgia Schweitzer 13. Georgia's Miller twins were shut down
most of the game, although Coco Miller scored 18 and Kelly Miller
13. Tawana McDonald had 14 and Deana Nolan added 12.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (29-6), which upset Tennessee in the East Regional finals
to get here, proved it is no fluke. The Durham, N.C. school is now
in the enviable position of having a chance of being to become the
first in NCAA Division I history to win men's and women's national
basketball championships in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   After digging themselves a 15-point hole early in the second
half, the Bulldogs made several modest comebacks
</P>
<P>
   Georgia got to within six at 60-54, but then Kiesha Brown took
two ill-advised jumpers and committed a foul that gave Duke a 64-54
cushion at the 7:38 mark. With under six minutes to play, Erickson
scored on a baseline drive and then nailed a 3-pointer for a 70-55
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
