<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE PROFITS ARE TASTY, BUT ARTIFICIALLY FLAVORED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Md.)   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The winter quarter ends on Wednesday, and as the crocuses
emerge, public attention turns to profits. The stock market in the
coming weeks will ride _ up or down _ on the quarterly profit
reports that will spew forth soon from corporate America. Will
those reports signal continuing economic strength? If so, is
corporate America reporting its profits truthfully?
</P>
<P>
   That may seem a startling question to pose in the United States.
Crony capitalists in emerging countries may inflate profits
irresponsibly without raising eyebrows. But the phenomenon is
popping up right here in disciplined America, and not just among a
handful of black-sheep companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear we are witnessing a gradual, but noticeable, erosion in
the quality of financial reporting,'' Arthur Levitt, chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission, said last week, repeating a
diagnosis that first appeared in his speeches last fall.
</P>
<P>
   That icon of business, Warren Buffett, has also weighed in,
rather bluntly. Like Levitt, he blames the stock market for
pressuring chief executives into reporting ever higher earnings so
that their companies' stock prices will keep up with the
ever-rising market, like a cat chasing its tail. They try to
achieve the necessary earnings legitimately, Buffett wrote
recently, but when they fail to do so, they ``resort to unadmirable
accounting strategems'' that ``manufacture the desired
`earnings.'''
</P>
<P>
   The potential damage is alarming. Profits have climbed rapidly
in recent years, and this growth has contributed mightily to the
stock market's euphoria and to the impression that corporate
America has outclassed other countries in the global economy.
Rising profits, in fact, have become an emblem of the nation's
apparent success.
</P>
<P>
   And now the emblem may be less than advertised _ considerably
less, if enough companies, prodded by the SEC, find themselves
forced to change their accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that, on average, reported profits are
overstated,'' said Baruch Lev, a professor of accounting at New
York University's Stern School of Business. ``My intuition tells me
that profitability in the United States is basically solid, but
there is a layer of earnings that is illusionary.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has quantified how many billions would disappear if
accounting practices changed, but there are hints. One gimmick
involves the stock options that corporations increasingly award to
executives as a way to fatten pay. Under current accounting rules,
those options do not have to be listed as a cost and subtracted
from earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the large companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gave out $10.4 billion in options without reporting
them as compensation expense. That was 3 percent of the companies'
$325 billion in after-tax earnings, so their actual earnings were
closer to $315 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options are relatively easy to track; they appear as
footnotes in reports filed with the SEC. Jack Ciesielski of R.G.
Associates in Baltimore, which researches accounting issues, came
up with the $10.4 billion figure by going through the filings.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger source of overstated profits _ corporate restructuring
charges _ is harder to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a big corporation that announces a $2 billion
restructuring charge to cover the cost of integrating a newly
acquired company and the cost of severance for laid-off workers.
The $2 billion is all charged against this year's earnings, making
them look bad, although the actual costs are spread out over two or
three years.
</P>
<P>
   But the $2 billion is intentionally overestimated; the actual
cost turns out to be $1.5 billion. And the company has a de facto
$500 million reserve that is fed gradually into quarterly earnings
reports, making net income seem to rise robustly.
</P>
<P>
   From news reports last year, Ciesielski's firm tracked 1,400
restructuring charges totaling $76 billion. ``I think that is a
light figure,'' he said. ``We probably missed quite a few.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there are other ways to make profits seem bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate executives increasingly manipulate charges related to
research and development and to depreciation, the accounting device
that recognizes the gradual wearing out of machinery and other
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Or they stop the clock, as Walter P. Schuetze, chief accountant
of the SEC's enforcement division, noted in an acerbic speech last
December. He cited one company that had ``turned back its computer
clock that recorded and dated shipments so that out-of-period
shipments, and consequently revenue, would be recorded'' in the
just-ended quarter, fattening that quarter's profit.
</P>
<P>
   Such deeds do not just affect shareholders of the business. Some
well-known companies _ for example, Sunbeam, Sensormatic and Livent
Inc. _ have had to restate earnings in recent months, correcting
one or another accounting misstep. Such announcements have often
caused a company's stock to plunge, contributing to the market's
considerable volatility.
</P>
<P>
   There is a broader concern. The robust growth in corporate
profits in recent years has been billboard advertising for the
American market system, which has seemed more successful than the
less prosperous, and more regulated, European and Japanese models.
</P>
<P>
   Now the American billboard needs a warning label, one that using
Ciesielski's words might say: ``Earnings gaming is widespread.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6105 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     03-26 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSHING IN AS INSIDERS RUSH OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in early February, an investing site on the
World Wide Web called Trading-places.net generated a flurry of
excitement among investors who followed the advice of its guru and
owner, Chris Rea. Known on the web as Merlin, Rea puts his picks
out to members, who then tend to pile into the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Rea _ now under investigation by the Securities and Exchange
Commission for his site's relationship with a brokerage firm he has
recommended to customers _ definitely has pull. The shares he often
touts make impressive trading spikes. But when the buying stampede
slows, the stocks quickly drift down.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stocks Merlin touted the first week of February were
Bull &AMP; Bear Group, a mutual fund company; Imaginon, a money-losing
software concern, and three brokerage firms: J.B. Oxford Holdings,
Muriel Siebert &AMP; Co. and M.H. Meyerson &AMP; Co. They went up when he
waved his wand and dropped when he stopped.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that all the Merlin followers who piled into
these stocks were able to get out before they fell. But documents
now trickling in show that another cast of characters made big
money on the sudden popularity of these shares _ corporate
insiders.
</P>
<P>
   On the very day that Merlin was advising investors to plunge
into Bull &AMP; Bear Group, for example, five of its insiders were
selling stock. Insiders sold a total of 127,500 shares on Feb. 4 at
prices between $7.19 and $9.25, generating almost $1.1 million for
the sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a day's work _ especially considering that two
trading days later, the stock had fallen back to around $4. It
closed last week at $3.75.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders at M.H. Meyerson &AMP; Co. did even better. As investors
piled in from Feb. 3 to Feb. 5, the company's five top executives
were getting out. They sold 501,760 shares, generating $6.4
million. Martin H. Meyerson, the brokerage firm's chairman and
founder, sold 200,000 shares _ almost 8 percent of his holdings _
at prices between $8.99 and $15.88. He reaped almost $2.5 million.
M.H. Meyerson shares closed at $4 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there were the insiders exiting Imaginon Inc., a
favorite that Merlin has touted more than once. On Feb. 5, as
Merlin was pushing the stock, an insider named Henry Fong sold $1.2
million in Imaginon shares at prices between $6 and $7.19 each. The
stock has since fallen to $4.875.
</P>
<P>
   None of the executives who sold their shares in February
returned phone calls Friday seeking comment. But Imaginon's
president, David Schwartz, who has complained publicly about the
manic price swings in his stock, said Fong told him that his sales
were for personal reasons and that their timing was coincidental to
the surge in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong, of course, with insiders taking profits
in a rising stock. But such sales may suggest that the people who
know a company best don't expect the shares to keep going up. Bob
Gabele, who tracks insider transactions for First Call in
Rockville, Md., put it simply: ``Investors who are rushing to buy
have to worry about who's heading for the door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
