<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-AUTO-CANADA-ART-     03-26 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-AUTO-CANADA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS PROFIT BY BUYING CARS IN CANADA THEN SELLING THEM IN
U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ American entrepreneurs have been buying tens of
thousands of vehicles cheaply at Canadian dealerships and reselling
them in the United States, making substantial profits and in the
process sidestepping U.S. fuel-economy rules.
</P>
<P>
   This cross-border commerce is booming because cars and trucks,
including those made in the United States, cost less in Canada
these days _ as much as $5,000 less for big sport utility vehicles
and large cars. The Canadian dollar's value has tumbled, dropping
nearly 9 percent against the U.S. dollar the last two years.
Automakers have been reluctant to raise Canadian prices to
compensate because the Canadian economy is weaker and incomes are
lower than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Imports of new and used vehicles from Canada have risen nearly
12-fold the last two years because of the price gap and are still
rising. Roughly 10,000 vehicles a month are entering the country
under a special program originally designed mainly to help
immigrants from Canada bring their cars here. Factories in the
United States are shipping thousands of vehicles to Canadian
dealers who put them on trucks back to the United States for resale
as new cars by dealers here.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian prices tend to be particularly low for large models,
notably full-size sport utility vehicles. Canadian taxes keep
gasoline prices about 20 percent higher than in the United States,
limiting demand for big gas guzzlers. Most of the vehicles being
brought south are large and built in the United States but are
exempt from federal rules aimed at improving the fuel economy of
the nation's fleet of family vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Average Americans cannot simply go to Canada, buy a cheap
vehicle and drive it back, because they would face weeks or months
of paperwork before crossing the border. The Transportation
Department issues licenses to businesses, known as registered
importers, to bring in vehicles and companies are lining up for
these licenses; the number of registered importers has risen to 144
from 80 the last 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Of 74,413 vehicles brought into the United States last year, all
but 400 or so came from Canada. The reason is simple: cars and
trucks imported from anywhere else, including Mexico, require
thousands of dollars in modifications to meet U.S. safety and
environmental rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Canada has followed U.S. safety standards for years and
adopted U.S. vehicular pollution rules as of Sept. 1, 1997.
Registered importers usually just replace the Canadian speedometer
and odometer, which are calibrated in kilometers instead of miles.
</P>
<P>
   Most registered importers serve as middlemen between Canadian
and American dealers and do not have the staff to sell vehicles to
the general public. It is up to the American dealer whether to pass
on the savings to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The registered importers contend that they are helping consumers
by providing American car dealers with a way around the steep
markups that automakers now charge in the United States,
particularly on large vehicles. ``All we do is relocate vehicles to
someone who can help them,'' said Richard Izzo, the president of
Superior Auto Sales Inc., a registered importer in Hamburg, N.Y.,
near Buffalo, which ships cars as far south as Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Palczewski, a milk processing company executive in Orchard
Park, N.Y., and his daughter, Tracey, bought a new, Mexican-made
silver Volkswagen New Beetle from Canada for her in early January
rather than go on a four-month waiting list for a Beetle imported
directly from Mexico. ``It has been great,'' Palczewski said.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers and individuals have been trading cars across borders in
Europe for years to take advantage of currency shifts, and national
differences in car prices have become a big consumer issue there.
Here and in Europe, some automakers have tried to discourage the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The registered importers are exempt from U.S. fuel-economy
regulations, which require that the average fuel economy for all of
the cars sold by each automaker must be at least 27.5 miles a
gallon. The average fuel economy for each automaker's sales of
sport utility vehicles, vans and pickup trucks must be at least
20.7 miles a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   A computer printout supplied by the Transportation Department of
virtually all the vehicles brought in last year shows that there
were very few small cars and fairly few small sport utilities,
pickups or minivans; the list is dominated by large, heavy vehicles
with poor fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have not calculated the average fuel economy of
vehicles being brought in by the registered importers because no
law requires them to do so. By contrast, direct imports from
automakers' overseas factories total about two million vehicles
each year, and these are subject to fuel economy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly shipments of registered imports are currently equal to a
little less than 1 percent of all vehicles sold in the United
States, too small a number to have a significant impact on the fuel
economy of any manufacturer. Still, even at the margin, from a
regulatory standpoint, the shipments are helpful to the automakers,
which are under severe pressure to meet the fuel-economy targets.
General Motors has been taking particularly drastic measures, like
cutting short the 1998 model year of the giant Chevrolet Suburban
after just five months of production to keep GM's corporate average
up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Executives from GM, Ford Motor, DaimlerChrysler and several
foreign automakers say they absolutely do not have a policy of
avoiding fuel-economy rules by shipping big vehicles to Canada and
then letting them trickle back into the United States. Indeed, the
automakers have financial incentives to limit the cross-border
trade and are taking some steps to do so. Their profit margins are
smaller on the vehicles they sell at lower markups to Canadian
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   James Holden, DaimlerChrysler's executive vice president for
North American sales, pointed out that executives who deliberately
tried to subvert the Corporate Average Fuel Economy rules could
face criminal prosecution. ``We don't play games on CAFE, and I
don't believe that any other manufacturer would play that game,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM president Richard Wagoner said automakers preferred to sell
cars and trucks for higher prices in the United States. ``If
anything, the Canadians have to squeal to get their fair share,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's computers have been programmed to spot cases is which
Ford cars originally shipped to Canadian dealers were taken in for
warranty work at Ford's dealers in the United States. While Ford
pays for the warranty work, it also traces the serial number to
determine if the vehicle was sold across the border soon after it
was shipped to Canada. If it was, Ford identifies the Canadian
dealer who originally received the vehicle from the factory and
charges that dealer a fee equal to the dealer's estimated profit on
the vehicle's sale.
</P>
<P>
   Ford sells an Expedition XLT full-size sport utility vehicle
with four-wheel drive for $32,730 retail in the United States.
North of the border, Ford charges the Canadian equivalent of
$27,550.
</P>
<P>
   Some automakers, like Volkswagen, put no limits on the
cross-border shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Only one automaker, Honda Motor, has really crimped the
registered importers by limiting the availability of replacement
speedometers and odometers in recent months. Art Garner, a Honda
spokesman, said the automaker wanted to make sure dealers told
customers when they were buying a vehicle meant for the Canadian
market, which is difficult to determine once the speedometer and
odometer have been changed.
</P>
<P>
   Honda, one of the few automakers that does not have a problem
meeting the average fuel-economy rules, also has an unusually
stringent warranty policy. American Honda dealers who sell cars
purchased from Canadian dealers are required to pay for any
warranty work done on the cars anywhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Registered importers are furious at Honda, contending that it is
limiting American dealers' freedom to acquire vehicles at the
lowest possible cost. But the policy appears to have been
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Honda started enforcing the speedometer policy with its Odyssey
minivans, for which there are long waiting lists at its American
dealerships; only eight Odysseys were brought in from Canada by
registered importers last year, according to the Transportation
Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
