<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      03-26 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV JETS DOWNED AS SERBS CONTINUE ASSAULTS IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND LOUISE D. PALMER AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO planes Friday downed two Serb jets that made a
surprise incursion over Bosnia during an intensified third day of
bombardment that lasted through the night, while Yugoslavian forces
reportedly unleashed a new round of assaults on ethnic Albanian
civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The activity on both sides drew reaction from around the world
amid hints of the conflict's potential to widen. At least two NATO
nations stepped up their protests against the bombing, while US and
other Western officials insisted the airstrikes were crucial in
ending the Serbs' ethnic cleansing of Kosovar Albanians. Expressing
alarm over reports of new killings, President Clinton repeated his
conviction that ``only swift action can save peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a third day in a row, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic showed no signs of capitulation. Indeed, despite NATO
reports of vast damage to the country's military infrastructure,
Serb jets went on the offensive, swooping down over Bosnia in a
possible attempt to fire on NATO peacekeeping forces stationed
there. US planes shot down two of the three intruding MiG-29s, but
officials interpreted the move as a sign that the fighting was not
about to end.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened skirmishing came as Clinton invoked the War
Powers Act, notifying Congress that troops were engaged in active
duty abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees poured across
the borders of Kosovo into Macedonia and Albania, according to
eyewitness reports, as violent protests against the bombings
continued to sweep the region. Civilian demonstrations in Bulgaria,
Macedonia, Athens, Toronto, and other cities were accompanied by
official objections in Greece, Italy, and Russia, where various
leaders said the bombings should stop.
</P>
<P>
   Russia issued the most vehement disapproval. Expelling NATO
officials from the country, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
said those who ordered the bombings were war criminals, and
demanded they stand trial. Russia also demanded that the United
Nations Security Council vote to halt the attacks. But in the
15-member council, only China and Namibia agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In Greece _ where 15,000 protesters chanted ``Clinton, fascist,
murderer'' during a march to the US Embassy _ officials also called
for an end to the attacks. In Italy, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
pleaded for the bombings to be as brief as possible, though he
conceded they were both ``necessary and inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright refused to acknowlege a
crack in NATO unity. Instead, in a message delivered in
Serbo-Croatian and beamed inside Yugoslavia, Albright urged
civilians to understand NATO's goals. She said she did not believe
the Serbs had been properly informed of the Rambouillet agreement
designed to end a year of ethnic strife in the Serbian province of
Kosovo. The Kosovar Albanians ultimately accepted the plan, but
Milosevic refused to sign, triggering the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragically, Serb leaders rejected the agreement, renewed the
campaign of terror in Kosovo, and forced NATO to do what no one in
the alliance wanted to _ which is to begin airstrikes,'' Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued a similar message in the broadcast, saying, ``The
United States and our European allies have no quarrel with the
Serbian people.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``The mission of the airstrikes is to demonstrate
the seriousness of NATO's purpose so that the Serbian leaders
understand the imperative of reversing course.''
</P>
<P>
   On the military front, Friday's offensive began at 8:20 a.m.
Eastern Standard Time with one Tomahawk missile, marking the first
daylight attack since airstrikes began Wednesday. The skirmish over
Bosnia took place at 11:35 a.m., when three MiG-29 planes were
picked up on radar by US Airborne Warning and Control System, or
AWACS, planes nearby, according to Defense Department spokesman
Kenneth H. Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   American F-15C fighter pilots shot down two of the Serb planes.
But despite earlier reports that the pilots of the two downed
MiG-29 jets had been taken into custody, Bacon said NATO officials
did not know their whereabouts. Nor, he said, could they be certain
of their motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, one reason could be to attack'' peacekeeping
``forces in Bosnia,'' he said. ``A second possibility is that they
were involved in some sort of a Serb scheme to shoot down one of
our planes . . . Obviously, if this was the scheme, it backfired
egregiously on the Yugoslavs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the intrusion constituted an ``attack'' and an
``escalation'' of the conflict. He also signaled a shift in
military priorities. In an attack the day before, officials said 20
percent of the targets were directly related to the Serb killing of
ethnic Albanians. By Friday, Bacon said Serb troops constituted 40
percent of the targets, meaning that enough infrastructure had been
damaged to allow pilots to turn their attention elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   After the midair battle, Bosnia's ambassador to the United
Nations, Muhamed Sacirbey, issued a protest, accusing the Serb
military of having ``crossed into the sovereign airspace of Bosnia
and Herzegovina with the intention of committing military strikes
against our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacirbey interpreted the intrusion into the Bosnian no-fly zone
_ where some 30,000 NATO peacekeeping troops have been stationed
since 1995 _ as an apparent ``attempt to broaden the war and
undermine the peace in Bosnia and Herzegovina.'' He quickly
requested an emergency Security Council meeting, saying it was
necessary to ``address this aggression into my country.''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than focus on the possibility that fighting was on
the verge of expanding throughout the region, attention in the
United States remained on the brutalities in the villages of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serb police, along with other masked men, reportedly burned
villages and massacred civilians throughout western Kosovo, sending
the survivors fleeing for the borders. While NATO planes launched a
fresh wave of attacks Friday &UR;  &LR; night, sending missile-equipped B-52
bombers and F-117 stealth fighter jets with laser-guided munitions
back over Kosovo, the State Department issued a reaction to the
killings. Spokesman James Rubin said officials there were
``extremely alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry also expressed ``serious concern if there
is an escalation of the very thing we are trying to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about what's happening on the ground in
Kosovo than whatever minimal resistance is being met in the air,''
Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona, warned: ``Let's not
go wobbly here, as Margaret Thatcher used to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in it,'' McCain said in an interview. ``This is not
going to be a day at the beach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
