<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB MILITARY TAKES ADVANTAGE OF UNPREDICTABILITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What began as a swift NATO bomb-dropping raid
appeared Friday to be evolving into a far more complicated game of
cat-and-mouse in the Yugoslavian skies, as the Serbian Air Force
continued to play to its greatest asset: unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts did not expect the Serbs to send more than
half of their best jets into the skies, only to be decimated by
NATO forces within the first 48 hours. On the other hand, officials
did assume Serbs would have by now launched their powerful
surface-to-air missiles, which so far have remained almost entirely
out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   And yet that is exactly the peculiar air war that has played
out, forcing analysts and officials to concentrate their
assessments of the situation, and alter their predictions of what
will come next.
</P>
<P>
   One treacherous possibility, according to experts and US defense
officials: Yugoslav forces are purposely hoarding their air-defense
missile systems, which could be wiped out by high-altitude planes
overhead if pilots spotted them being fired.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some analysts believe the Serbs are ratcheting
up their brutal assaults on Albanians in part to outrage NATO
forces. Because NATO has vowed not to send in ground troops, their
best remaining tool to fight the atrocities on the ground would be
low-flying planes such as the A-10 fighter _ known as the ``flying
bathtub'' for its durability _ which are designed to hit targets
such as tanks, but are also highly vulnerable to anti-aircraft
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs, according to defense analyst John Pike, may have stumbled
upon a strategy ``that would provoke NATO aircraft, that they could
then shoot down with all the SA-6s that they have been holding in
reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the dilemma that is present today,'' said Pike
of the Federation of American Scientists. ``NATO is very far from
suppressing Serbian air defenses. But there's a reluctance to stand
by and see the Serbs kill more people this weekend than they've
killed in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona, said the renewed
killings were a ``major concern'' and may be the reason ``we are
hearing some murmurs about the fact that we have not sent in our
A-10 aircraft to take out some of the Serbian tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is driven by the fear of the surface-to-air missile
threat,'' McCain said. ``The reason we got in was to stop that
ethnic cleansing. We've got to keep our nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Serbs are now at a greater disadvantage in the
air war, having lost half of their best planes in the last two
days.
</P>
<P>
   According to military analysts and officials, the Yugoslav
military started out in possession of some 12 or 15 MiG-29 fighter
jets, which are Soviet-made planes on par with jets used by the
United States and NATO. They have since lost five of those jets and
are left with a mostly outdated fleet of MiG-21s, as well as
several dozen smaller homemade planes and helicopters _ planes that
could still drop lightweight bombs, for example, on troops in
Bosnia, but would stand little chance of survival against an
American F-15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
