<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIOACTIVE GARBAGE WELCOMED IN NEW MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. _ A flatbed truck carrying six drums of
radioactive garbage rumbled through this remote mining city before
dawn Friday, heralding the long-delayed opening of the world's
first permanent nuclear waste dump.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the first shipment to the Waste Isolation Pilot
Plant set off a celebration among Carlsbad residents eager to make
a 240,000-year commitment. That is how long, give or take a few
millennia, until the plutonium on clothes, tools, sludge, and other
trash being buried in an ancient salt bed will deteriorate enough
to be almost free of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Protests and legal challenges, almost exclusively by out-of-town
groups, had postponed the opening of the $1.8 billion, federal
government-owned facility _ generally known by its acronym, WIPP _
since its 1988 completion. But with opponents' last-minute appeals
exhausted, the plant was declared open, thrilling local leaders and
most of Carlsbad's 25,000 residents, who see economic salvation and
hundreds of jobs in the carcinogenic import.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word nuclear scares the pants off people, and the word
waste doesn't enhance it any. But we think it's safe,'' said Tracy
Hill, executive director of the Carlsbad Chamber of Commerce. ``We
see this as a solution to a national challenge, and there's
opportunity in it for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, opponents continued to voice fears about using public
highways to transport radioactive byproducts of the US military and
research nuclear programs. They also doubt the reliability of the
plant, which will entomb the drums a half-mile below the cactus and
tumbleweeds that dot the region.
</P>
<P>
   As the specially designed truck bearing the wastes made its way
along a 356-mile route from the Los Alamos National Laboratory, it
was met with a mix of cheers by supporters and jeers by about 70
drum-beating, sign-carrying protesters. One man was arrested for
trying to block the truck's path with his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``WIPP is in the wrong place,'' said Betty Richards, who owns a
mobile home park in Carlsbad and is one of only three local
opponents. ``They say the salt beds are so stable because they're
so old, but they destabilized them by drilling into them. There are
cracks and fissures there that we believe will bring waste to the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sad because the people here are going to be the
next generation of guinea pigs by the Department of Energy,''
Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Though most trash will come from materials used in the
production of nuclear bomb and other defense-related activities,
Friday's shipment consisted of six 55-gallon drums of trash _ each
weighing up to 1,000 pounds _ generated while building deep-space
NASA probes.
</P>
<P>
   The drums made the trip inside three 10-feet-high,
thermos-shaped containers built to prevent the release of
radiation, even in an accident or emergency. Federal officials
anticipate more than 37,000 such shipments, consisting of 850,000
barrels of nuclear waste, will make their way to WIPP in the next
35 years.
</P>
<P>
   The truck's arrival just before 4 a.m. set off cheers from about
400 people who gathered at the heavily guarded facility, built on
an isolated site 26 miles from downtown Carlsbad. A blast from the
truck's horn was greeted by flag-waving, noisemakers, hugs,
back-slaps, and the burst of camera flashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've waited so long for this. I can't believe it finally made
it,'' said Pat Kilgore, a WIPP employee.
</P>
<P>
   A cordoned-off area for protesters was empty except for a dozen
WIPP supporters who were unable to gain credentials to enter the
gated compound.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the WIPP began in the mid-1970s, though the idea for the
dump dates to the mid-1950s, when scientists began worrying about
how to deal with the clothing, debris, equipment, and other
materials inevitably contaminated when working with radioactive
elements. Most of that waste _ growing steadily by the year _ has
been stored in above-ground repositories while awaiting burial at
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Once at WIPP, the disposal process calls for workers to remove
the drums from their protective containers, then transport them via
elevator into the salt beds about 2,150 feet below ground. They are
destined for holding rooms 300 feet long, 33 feet wide, and 13 feet
high, the walls and ceilings glistening with salt crystals. Once
filled with drums, the entrances to the rooms will be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Energy Department officials say, the salt will do the
work. Over seven to 10 years, the rooms will collapse. Over the
next 100 to 150 years, the salt will solidify, trapping the wastes.
WIPP planners expect to fill 56 such rooms in the salt bed, which
they say has remained remarkably stable since it was formed 225
million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread support for the WIPP can be traced in part to the
people here being used to thinking about time in epochal
increments. They also are uniquely able to recognize the value of
underground resources. The reason: A cornerstone of the city's
economy is tourism at nearby Carlsbad Caverns, the site of
magnificent underground passages and limestone cave formations that
began taking shape 500,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the dump's opening, the city was dotted with
``Welcome WIPP'' and ``WIPP YES'' signs, and a local radio station
posted a simple message on its lawn that spoke for many here:
``Finally.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong, however, to interpret Carlsbad's embrace of
the WIPP as evidence the community is immune to the
not-in-my-backyard syndrome. Recently, plans to build a mental
health facility in a residential neighborhood were abandoned
because of local opposition, said Mayor Gary Perkowski, who is also
an assistant principal at the middle school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks here like the WIPP, but they aren't ready for everything
that means economic development,'' Perkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic promise of the plant was a prime factor in its
acceptance. Westinghouse Co., the main government contractor, has
brought hundreds of jobs to the city and has also become a
cherished corporate citizen through hefty donations of money and
volunteer hours. Carlsbad also imagines itself becoming a global
destination for the study of nuclear waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just nuclear waste that's coming in with it, it's
jobs and money,'' said Franklin Holt, a cashier at a gas station
near the caverns.
</P>
<P>
   The trash destined for the WIPP will come mainly from 10 major
defense-related nuclear production facilities scattered around the
country, as far east as Savannah, Ga., and as far north as Hanford,
Wash. A smaller amount will be sent from 14 other temporary
disposal sites, laboratories, nuclear reactors, and research
facilities. Several are from the Northeast, but none are from New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the material being taken to the Carlsbad dump is
contaminated with plutonium, but the trash will contain other
radioactive elements as well. Federal law prohibits concentrated,
high-level nuclear wastes and spent nuclear fuel from disposal in
the WIPP.
</P>
<P>
   The WIPP site will contain only government-generated nuclear
waste. It will not accept radioactive garbage or other wastes from
commercial nuclear power plants. There is no permanent resting
place for those wastes, which for now remain in temporary storage
facilities or repositories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
