<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-MISSING-NYT &LR;      03-26 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-MISSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY OF 3RD MISSING WOMAN FOUND ALONG HIGHWAY LEADING TO YOSEMITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The sorrowful mystery of what happened to three
tourists who disappeared from Yosemite National Park was in large
part answered Friday when the authorities announced that a body
found along a highway leading to the park was that of the last
missing person.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, the authorities said that the body found
halfway between where the three women were last seen six weeks ago
and where their charred rental car was found last week with two
bodies in the trunk was that of Julie Sund. On Monday, the
authorities had identified one of the bodies in the trunk as that
of Julie's mother, Carole Sund. The authorities now assume that the
other body found in the car, whose identity was close to being
positively identified through DNA tests, is that of the third
member of the trio, Silvina Pelosso, a family friend visiting from
Argentina. Results of DNA tests are expected next week.
</P>
<P>
   But big questions still remain in a case that has captured the
attention of much of the nation: Who killed these women, where and
why?
</P>
<P>
   The women's disappearance touched off the most intensive
missing-persons search in recent memory, involving six
law-enforcement agencies, and the women's fate has sparked fear
among residents of the small, quaint towns in the Sierra Nevada
foothills, where the bodies were found, that a killer or killers
are among them. But it has also created a deeper, wider fear,
especially among women, that no one is safe anywhere when an
innocent weekend adventure for three can result in such a horror
story.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday evening in Sonora, the Tuolumne
County seat, James Maddock, the FBI special agent in charge of the
case, said that investigators searching for suspects were still
following up on hundreds of tips that have been made to an FBI hot
line over the last week. He said the case was being designated ``a
major case'' so that the authorities could bring as many resources
as they needed to solve the crime. He refused to comment on whether
they were close to making an arrest, on how investigators had
located the third body, and on the cause of death for any of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund, who was 42, had taken her eldest daughter, Julie,
15, and Silvina, 16, who was visiting the family in Eureka, to
Yosemite for a holiday on Presidents' Day Weekend. They were last
seen alive, according to the authorities, on the night of Feb. 15,
when they left the restaurant adjacent to the Cedar Lodge in El
Portal, a remote outpost at the western entrance to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, the only concrete clue as to what might have
happened to the women was Mrs. Sund's wallet, found intact off a
highway in Modesto, two hours from El Portal, four days after the
trio disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had searched Modesto and the mines, ravines and
woods around El Portal, only to have a passerby stumble upon the
car three hours away, in Tuolumne County, at a spot local residents
use as a dumping ground for cars and large appliances. The find was
baffling, given its location, but the discovery of the third party
lends some logic to a possible murder scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Sund's body was found near the town of Moccasin, on the
fastest route from El Portal to Sierra Village, where the torched
shell of the rental car with two of the victims inside was found.
The killer or killers could have dumped the one victim before
arriving at the spot where the car was set on fire. The location
where the body was found is also about halfway between El Portal
and Modesto, where relatives of the women have been staying at a
Holiday Inn since Carole Sund's wallet was found there.
</P>
<P>
   Jens Sund, Mrs. Sund's husband, went into seclusion about two
weeks ago in Eureka, with the couple's three other children.
Francis and Carole Carrington, Mrs. Sund's parents, and Raquel and
Jose Pelosso, from Cordoba, Argentina, have remained in Modesto to
answer questions from the press and keep the case prominent until
it is solved, they say. ``Somebody knows the whole story and we
want it out,'' Carrington said Friday. ``It's hard to sit and wait
for the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carringtons are a prominent family of real estate developers
from Santa Rosa who are now mostly based in Eureka. At the time the
three disappeared, there was speculation that the women had been
kidnapped for ransom, given Mrs. Sund's family wealth. But no
ransom note was ever found, and the authorities concluded that the
women were victims of random foul play.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have said that they are poring over parole
records in the areas as part of a hunt for suspects. Two men _ one
a convicted sex offender and the other on parole after a domestic
violence conviction _ who had been working at the Houtz Family
Restaurant, where the women were last seen, have been in custody in
the Mariposa County jail on unrelated charges, at the request of
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   A third man, who has convictions for attempted murder and rape,
and who grew up near where the charred car was found and now lives
in Modesto, was arrested last week on charges that he shot an
officer who tried to stop him for a routine traffic violation.
Neighbors say that in recent days investigators have questioned
them about the man and the Sund-Pelosso case.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and business people in towns near where the burned car
was found say they spotted the three a day or even two after the
last confirmed sighting, but investigators say that many of the
sightings cannot possibly be true. They say a roll of film found
near the charred rental car showed that the last date the women
were sightseeing was Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   While the car and everything near it was burned, the roll of
film, found among other items strewn near the charred car, was
intact. The authorities kept most of the developed roll as
evidence, but on Monday they released seven snapshots to the
victims' families. They are pictures of one or two of them at a
time, obviously taken by the third, and they show them in jeans and
sweatshirts, ice skating, posing in front of a breathtaking
waterfall, hiking along a river. They are postcard photos, the kind
placed in albums to rekindle memories of a wonderful time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
