<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEVORKIAN-VERDICT-BOS     03-26 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-VERDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVORKIAN FOUND GUILTY OF SECOND-DEGREE MURDER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who challenged authority on
national television when he injected a seriously ill man with a
lethal dose of chemicals, was found guilty Friday of second-degree
murder.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which marks the first time a jury has convicted
the world's most famous assisted-suicide advocate, is seen as a
symbol of the shift against Kevorkian and the right-to-die
movement. But even prosecutors said the issues are far from
settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never my intent or desire to participate in the
martyrdom of Dr. Kevorkian,'' said Dave Gorcyca, Oakland County
prosecuting attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the issue of mercy killing and assisted suicide
will remain a complicated moral and legal, medical and ethical
issue upon which we may never unanimously agree, despite the guilty
verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian showed no expression when the guilty verdicts on
charges of second-degree murder and delivery of a controlled
substance were announced. The former count carries a maximum
sentence of life in prison, while the latter has a maximum term of
seven years. Prosecutors said they would probably seek a sentence
in accord with guidelines that call for a minimum of 10 to 25 years
for a second-degree murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian promised the judge, who waived his bond, that he would
not participate in any assisted suicides until his sentencing on
April 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have kept my word up until now,'' said the 70-year-old
retired pathologist. ``And I will keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he quietly left the courtroom, evading journalists.
</P>
<P>
   But David Gorosh, Kevorkian's legal adviser, denounced the
decision to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unjust to try to equate an act of compassion with an act
of murder,'' he said. ``I will say this _ Dr. Kevorkian will be
lauded in history as a hero. This issue will be resolved in our
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorosh said Kevorkian has filed an appeal and has vowed to take
the case to the Supreme Court if needed.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 17, Kevorkian videotaped himself injecting Thomas Youk,
52, with a lethal dose of a chemical. Kevorkian provided the tape
to CBS, which broadcast the video on its ``60 Minutes'' program.
Youk was suffering from amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, better known
as Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   On the video, Kevorkian dared prosecutors to charge him with
murder: ``I've got to force them to act,'' Kevorkian said on the
show. ``They've got to charge me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian was charged with first-degree murder, which would have
carried a mandatory life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Convicting him means the jury believes he was guilty of one of
the most serious crimes on the law books,'' said Larry Dubin, a
University of Detroit law professor who has followed Kevorkian's
trials. But deciding on second-degree murder showed that jurors
felt a life sentence would have been too harsh, Dubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian says he has helped 130 people kill themselves since
1990 as part of his campaign to legalize physician-assisted
suicide. Four of those people were Massachusetts residents: Judith
Curren, 42, of Pembroke, in August 1996; Barbara Ann Collins, 65,
of Falmouth, in October 1996; Jeremy Allen, 52, of Cambridge, in
February 1998; and William Connaughton, 42, of West Roxbury, in
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Four trials on charges of violating Michigan's assisted-suicide
laws ended in acquittal three times and a mistrial in the fourth
case. In those cases, Kevorkian did not inject people, but used a
``suicide machine'' that allowed them to trigger the flow of lethal
drugs themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Kevorkian has been a beloved and sympathetic figure
in Michigan. But this decision, said longtime observers of
Kevorkian, reflected a rising sentiment against mercy killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking a little more objectively at him,'' said
prosecutor John Skrzynski. In the past, Kevorkian tried to pit
compassion against the law, but this time the law won, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, he came on the scene very quietly, advertising
his suicide machine in The Detroit Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a polarizing force almost from the start,'' said Brian
Dickerson, a columnist for the Free Press. ``He was the antichrist
for some and a prophet, ahead of his time, for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Flora Holzheimer, Kevorkian's younger sister, said that
everywhere he goes, people stop him to request an autograph.
Sometimes they roll down the window beside the car and give him a
thumbs up, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a hero,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said that in 1995 and 1996, around his third
acquittal, Kevorkian seemed to grow bolder. During that time, he
assisted with nearly a dozen suicides. The Curren case in Pembroke
was especially controversial, because a post motem showed she
suffered from obesity, but was not terminally ill. Even his
supporters began to question Kevorkian's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the weakening of his support became evident when
Michigan voters rejected a referendum to legalize assisted suicide
and voted to make it illegal to assist in a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because the the voters overwhelmingly rejected it, one
could infer that the public sentiment changed from public opinion
polls, which said most people favored the right to
physician-assisted suicide,'' Dubin said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment appears to be expressed nationwide. Only Oregon
allows assisted suicide, while the practice has been rejected or
blocked in about 20 states in recent years and voted down in
referendums in Washington and California.
</P>
<P>
   The Youk case ``is Kevorkian's swan song,'' said Arthur Caplan,
director or the University of Pennsylvania's Center for Bioethics
in Philadelphia and a critic of Kevorkian. While saying that
Kevorkian did bring the right-do-die movement into the public
consciousness, Caplan said, the doctor now is ``running on fumes _
the fumes of media notoriety.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, many question whether Kevorkian will follow through on his
threat to go on a hunger strike and kill himself if sentenced to
prison. ``That would be a tragedy,'' said Gorosh.
</P>
<P>
   Holzheimer said that starving definitely is a possibility, but
hoped it would never get to that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said that he will be an example at any cost,''
Holzheimer said. ``It hurts the sister, but I respect every wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe correspondent Jon Hall contributed to this report from
Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
