u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPREWELL-NYT &LR;      03-26 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: SHARING JUST ISN'T SPREWELL'S STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Latrell Sprewell was talking hoops Friday night, how
it feels to dribble down the court and launch a jumper on a whim.
This is called ``balling'' on the playground, and the term is best
reserved for those players who move at warp speed and have no
conscience when they miss two, three, four shots in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's fun,'' Sprewell said. ``And that's when
basketball is fun, going up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I would like to be in a system that caters to that
style of play. At this point in my career, I'm not going to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy convinced his bosses two months ago that
Sprewell, for all his baggage, was worth the risk. But if Sprewell
cannot decelerate and show he wants to do more than just play, the
coach who went to bat for him _ at a time when everyone else in the
organization was worried sick over Sprewell's coach-choking image _
could be out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   That vortex known as Patrick Ewing and the Knicks' offense has
absorbed the talents of many gifted players, and it could be said
that Ewing and his teammates need to get their rears down the floor
if they want to play with Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, at least two of Sprewell's teammates wish he
would wait for them to cross midcourt sometimes before chucking the
ball. They like his aggressiveness, but they question whether he
can incorporate them into his offensive mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits die hard, even on the court.
</P>
<P>
   This is a player, after all, who ran the floor unabated at
Golden State, the All-Star who had a green light and responded to
every defensive challenge the only way he knew how: shoot and shoot
some more.
</P>
<P>
   He played for a team that was used to losing, so there is a part
of him that must be wondering what all this New York fuss is over.
In the Bay Area, 15-13 is a more-than-decent record. Kurt Thomas,
the new power forward, played the last two seasons for a dismal
Dallas franchise. Marcus Camby, the other key off-season
acquisition, toiled for terrible Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are 6-9 with Sprewell in the lineup. Before he was
suspended for choking P.J. Carlesimo in December 1997, the Warriors
were 1-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one of those stats,'' he said. ``That doesn't
bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, it should. Attitude means so much in this league,
and if losing was tolerated where you came from, it often takes a
while to cleanse that line of thought from your mind.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it takes longer than a three-games-in-three-nights
season.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main culprits for the Knicks' losses has been the
lack of practice time. There is a reason Van Gundy has not lost a
first-round series in his career, though the Knicks were underdogs
in two of them. Given three or more days, his preparation is
unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hurt us offensively,'' he said before last night's
game against Phoenix. ``You're trying to teach guys to play without
the ball and go through other players instead of waiting for the
ball to be brought to them. You're trying to show them it can work
better this way instead of playing four separate games of one on
one.''
</P>
<P>
   People can say the Knicks are too predictable, and blame Ewing
for every playoff failure if they want a convenient scapegoat. They
can say that Allan Houston is too soft and that the club needs a
bona fide point guard.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprewell is the key to this club turning its fortunes
around. You watch him pour in points, dunk and run the court, and
it masks the chemistry problems of this team. Watch the eyes of his
teammates when he pulls up and there is no one underneath the rim
for a rebound, and you will see.
</P>
<P>
   They have that look that kids at the playground have when a
self-anointed star is in their midst. He might be scoring, keeping
them in the game and looking good in front of all his peers. But
deep down, they wish they would have picked someone else up that
passed the ball and made everyone else feel like they belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I fit in,'' Sprewell said. ``I don't feel I've had a
problem adjusting. I just don't particularly care for coming off
the bench.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
