<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-NYT &LR;      03-26 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT'S `COST KILLER' FACES TOUGH MISSION: RESCUE NISSAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Japan, Germany, Belgium, Brazil, Lebanon)   (EDS: Skedded as RENAULT-GHOSN on early budget.)  
(DW) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Here is the question confronting Carlos
Ghosn: can his team of 40 French executives rescue a loss-plagued
Japanese car company with 40,000 employees?
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn, an executive vice president at Renault SA who is known as
Le Cost Killer, is now leading the French car maker's plan to
invest $5 billion in Nissan Motor Co., Japan's No. 2 auto maker.
That arrangement is expected to be formally announced Saturday in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   No other Western executive has ever reached such a pivotal
position in one of Japan's corporate giants. Even few Japanese
executives have had to push through the breadth of change needed by
Nissan, which has at least $21.2 billion in debt, five straight
years of losses and a poorly selling array of boring-looking cars
and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Renault itself was once plagued by losses and inefficiency until
Ghosn reversed the trend. His game plan at Nissan will depend on an
ability to push through drastic changes in Nissan's dull designs,
its Byzantine purchasing system and its entire socio-economic chain
of suppliers and affiliated companies, which altogether employ
200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn, who is originally from Brazilian, is expected to become
what amounts to Nissan's chief operating officer under the
agreement that will give Renault a 35 percent stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with Renault's operations say Ghosn will lead a
group of 40 Renault executives who will try to make Nissan more
efficient and fuse the two companies' strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn, who turned 45 a few weeks ago, joined Renault at the end
of 1996 and oversaw a wrenching program to reduce costs, earning
him the nicknames Le Cost Killer the Parachutist.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was born in Brazil, Ghosn spent much of his youth in
Lebanon and then studied engineering and business at France's elite
universities. He then worked for nearly two decades at Michelin,
the French tire producer, and ended up running its North American
business. Renault's chairman, Louis Schweitzer, recruited Ghosn as
his second-in-command and put him charge of the cost-cutting
program.
</P>
<P>
   Though analysts say Ghosn hardly deserves sole credit, Renault
has enjoyed a spectacular turnaround since his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Renault's sales had stagnated, its costs were out
of control and its 1996 losses _ the first in 10 years _ were
nearly $1 billion. In 1998, helped by brutal cost-cutting and its
popular line of minivans, it earned more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer, a shy and outwardly colorless executive, already had
decided that painful cuts were necessary by the time he recruited
Ghosn. But it was the exuberant Ghosn who mapped out the details of
a plan to trim about $3.5 billion in annual costs by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The plan unleashed a political uproar in Belgium, where Renault
announced that it would shut one of its newer factories and lay off
2,700 workers. Belgian labor unions and political leaders angrily
charged that Renault, in which the French government owns 44
percent of the shares, had callously decided to inflict the
harshest pain on Belgian rather than French workers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the protests, Renault did close the plant. It also made
major changes in the way it purchased components, greatly reducing
the number of its suppliers and working more closely with the ones
that it kept. Like many other European and American car companies,
Renault also reorganized its production by building as many
different models as possible on a single platform, or skeleton of
common components.
</P>
<P>
   ``We announced a 20-billion-franc cost-cutting program and said
that 40 percent of that would be achieved in 1998,'' Ghosn said in
a recent interview. ``In fact, we achieved 48 percent of those
reductions by 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Renault's interest was disclosed this year, Renault's
share price has fallen by nearly a third to about $37. Much of
decline is from investor fears that Nissan will be nothing but a
black hole for money.
</P>
<P>
   It also remains unclear how much control Renault will have.
Though Renault will be able to name several members to Nissan's
board of directors and obtain a veto over major corporate
decisions, the companies have not explained how they will share
power.
</P>
<P>
   But Ghosn has made it clear where Renault sees the
opportunities. Nissan, he noted recently, has a weak purchasing
system in which the company relies heavily on components made
in-house rather than by independent suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   One market analyst who has worked with Renault noted that
Western companies now rely on outside suppliers for about 70
percent of their components. Nissan buys less than half from
outside suppliers. If Nissan adopted Renault's system, analysts say
it could shave the cost of parts by 3 or 4 percent, which would
translate to hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn is also focusing on simplifying Nissan's platform
strategy. As essentially the invisible underpinnings of a car, a
platform is a broad series of components that are common to several
models. Renault produces 2 million cars a year on seven different
platforms. Nissan, which has many more models, produces 2.8 million
cars on about 25 platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Renault executives also say they will bring some flare and
excitement to Nissan's staid line. Throughout its ups and downs,
Renault has often been clever and creative in designing appealing
new vehicles. Its most recent hit is the Scenic, Europe's first
minivan, but one that is more compact than American vans, yet
roomier than European hatchbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nissan has very boring cars, though they have some that are
fabulously well-engineered,'' said Simon Miller, an automobile
analyst at Credit Lyonnais in London. ``The one thing Renault has
proven is that it is good at coming up with cars that people want
to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that nobody knows whether Ghosn and his small
band of outsiders will be able to steer Nissan in a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   As logical as it might be to buy more parts from outside
suppliers, the essence of Japan's industrial system amounts to
tight corporate networks that link big manufacturers with their
suppliers. Companies routinely own big stakes in many suppliers,
which makes it difficult to cut them off.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the questions about resistance to change within
Nissan's own ranks. Ford Motor Company struggled for years after it
acquired a minority stake in Mazda. Nissan, Japan's biggest car
company after Toyota, is much bigger than Mazda and has played a
crucial role in Japan's industrial policy.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Renault, speaking on condition of anonymity,
insist the company's executives scrupulously analyzed the risks.
They have spent weeks poring over financial records in order to
fully understand Nissan's off-the-books liabilities through
affiliated companies.
</P>
<P>
   Renault also had to make its decision in the uncomfortable
spotlight created by DaimlerChrysler AG, Nissan's first choice,
when it walked away from a deal with Nissan on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, of Credit Lyonnais, said Nissan might prove more willing
to change than outsiders expect. ``Nissan is in trouble and they
know they're in trouble,'' he said. ``They're being offered a
lifeline, and they're being offered a partnership with a company
that has been successful in its own market and won't want to tread
too much into its own market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
