<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0327-2     03-26 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0327-2NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: new 7th-8th grafs replacing 7-10th grafs on forced march of
Kosovar refugees
 &HT;    NATO, YUGOSLAVIA SHOWDOWN ESCALATES, EXPANDS
 &HT;    EDs: With KOSOVO-MILITARY-0327; KOSOVO-AVIANO-0327.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS  
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. and allied forces tore deeper into the heart of the Serb
military machine Friday in a third day of air strikes across
Yugoslavia, as American warplanes shot down two Serb fighter jets
near a base of U.S. troops in neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, thousands of Serb troops backed with tanks
deepened their year-long campaign of terror, attacking villages and
ravaging homes amid unconfirmed reports of round-ups and summary
killings of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Across the region, anti-American violence swept as far away at
Greece, where an estimated 10,000 protesters marched on the U.S.
Embassy in Athens, hurling stones and bricks until they were
dispersed by riot police firing water cannons.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration found itself waging a
global campaign for public support for continuing the assault, even
as the Pentagon hunkered down for what could be a prolonged air war
on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin voiced outrage over the
escalating violence against ethnic Albanians, citing ''ominous''
reports of widening atrocities and warning that perpetrators would
be regarded as war criminals subject to trial and punishment once
the crisis ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are increasing reports of atrocities against Albanian
civilians in Kosovo,'' Rubin said. ``We are extremely alarmed by
these reports, and we are putting a great deal of resources and
effort into checking these out, as quickly as we can and as
thoroughly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the unconfirmed reports the administration was looking
into were allegations by large numbers of refugees fleeing Kosovo
that up to 20,000 ethnic Albanians had been put on a forced march
by Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking into it as best we can through the various means
that we have,'' said National Security Council spokesman P.J.
Crowley. ``I don't think that we are in a position to confirm any
details, but we are definitely checking into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Yugoslavia's Foreign Minister, Zivadin
Jovanovic, went on the CNN television network to decry the reports
of atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethnic Albanians (in the Serbian province of Kosovo) are
Yugoslav citizens,'' Jovanovic insisted. ``They enjoy equal rights,
equal opportunities, but terrorists have to be neutralized.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade claims that its military campaign in Kosovo has been
necessary to combat rebel groups of Kosovar Albanians pressing for
independence for the province of 2.2 million people, 90 percent of
whom are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin cited reports that Serb forces executed 20 ethnic
Albanians in the village of Goden on Thursday. The alleged killings
were reported by refugees from the region to the United Nations
High Commission on Refugees, which is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials would not confirm the killings, the
International Crisis Group, a private private humanitarian
organization in Washington, has monitored the situation. The
group's Balkans program coordinator Albert Cevallos reported the
following alleged atrocities:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Friday, Albanian lawyer Bayram Keljmendi, who was
representing the Koha Ditore, one of the largest Albanian
newspapers, and his two sons allegedly were taken from their home
in the Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina, and executed by
Serbian troops. The three mens' bodies were reportedly seen about
one mile outside of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Thursday, the warehouse for the Mother Theresa Society, one
of the largest local humanitarian organizations, was burned to the
ground near Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Friday, the press agency for the separatist rebels, the
Kosovo Liberation Army, reported that 20 Albanians had been killed
in a mass execution in the town of Orahovac, and another 10 in the
town of Podujevo.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Thursday, the warehouse for the Mother Theresa Society, one
of the largest local humanitarian organizations, was burned to the
ground near Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the starkest testimony to the terror has been the number
of ethnic Albanians -- 365,000 as of Friday -- who have fled their
homes, most with only those belongings they could carry, to escape
the onslaught of Serb troops and thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the horror, NATO officials in Brussels reported Friday
that 300 hardened Serb criminals have been released in recent days
and added to the ranks of the rampaging patrols in Kosovo, a
reprise of a tactic Serbs unleashed to brutal effect in their 3
1/2-year war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said it would step up its satellite surveillance of
Kosovo by flying unmanned drone aircraft into the region to monitor
by low altitude camera what can no longer be witnessed firsthand in
a province where international monitors, journalists and aid
workers have been forced to flee.
</P>
<P>
   To date, NATO attacks have focused on Serb air defenses, early
warning radar sites, fuel and ammunition dumps, power stations and
command and control systems.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks began around 9 p.m. local time Friday in Yugoslavia,
with news reports of explosions in at least 11 suburbs ringing the
capital of Belgrade, where air sirens blared and a city-wide
blackout was imposed for a third straight night.
</P>
<P>
   While hitting at the headquarters and supply centers of the Serb
army, police and special forces believed responsible for the bulk
of the Kosovo oppression, the U.S. Air Force has refrained from
using its extensive capabilities for pursuing tanks and troops in
the fields and on the roads of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   That could change in the days ahead, however, Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth Bacon told reporters in Washington, as the NATO strikes
continued to weaken Serb air defenses, reducing the dangers to NATO
pilots flying missions directly targeting Serb forces in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``As these strikes continue over the following days, we will, as
appropriate, increase the concentration and focus on targets within
Kosovo itself,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials insisted, however, that the Serbs' ongoing
attacks on civilians are an extension of the very Serb repression
that has prompted the NATO strikes and should not be regarded as
retaliation for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be somehow quite perverse to put the cart before the
horse and somehow conclude that it's NATO action which has given
President Milosevic a pretext to crack down,'' NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea told reporters at alliance headquarters in Brussels. ``He's
been cracking down without any pretext at all for the best part of
a year. We are intervening to stop that from happening, and to stop
it once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic is the president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it vowed to ratchet up air attacks directly on the Serb
forces conducting the repression in Kosovo, though, the Pentagon
got a bone-rattling reminder of the perils of continued conflict in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Yugoslav MiG-29 fighter jets managed to get within 25
miles of Tuzla, base for the 6,900 U.S. troops taking part in the
NATO peacekeeping operation in Bosnia, before being shot down by
two American F-15 fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb aircraft were spotted by a U.S. AWACS airplane flying
surveillance over the region, Bacon said. The AWACS alerted the
F-15 pilots, who were flying combat air patrols in the area and
quickly intercepted and destroyed the MiGs.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Friday, NATO patrols were searching for the Serb
pilots and the wreckage of the aircraft. Bacon said the MiGs'
mission remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculated, however, that Milosevic might have
hoped to slip past the NATO air defenses to stage a surprise attack
on the U.S. troops, stationed not far from where the MiGs were shot
down near the town of Teocak.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Mach 1, that's about 10 seconds from the Tuzla air base,''
said Balkans expert Bill Stuebner of the U.S. Institute for Peace,
a quasi-governmental think tank in Washington, D.C. ``Milosevic
must have decided to take a chance and send home body bags to the
United States to see how that would affect the dynamic here at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to polls showing thin domestic support for
U.S.-led NATO strikes in Yugoslavia, a mission over which the
public is divided in a roughly even split.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to build public backing for his policy, President Clinton
planned to devote his Saturday radio address to the Kosovo crisis,
an issue he addressed the nation on when the air strikes began on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to reiterate his resolve to wage a long-term
air campaign against Serb military forces, unless Milosevic agrees
to an international peace plan for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers National correspondent Susan Schultz contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
