<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS STARTING AT SHORT _ FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ With both Dave Hollins and Troy Glaus playing
well enough to earn the starting job at third base, Anaheim Angels
manager Terry Collins found himself with a tough decision. But he
has found the answer: Both will play.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins will start at third and Glaus will move to shortstop _
at least for the next couple of days. Glaus started at short Friday
and made two plays without an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got good-enough hands, he's got a strong-enough arm,''
Collins said. ``We've got to position him as best we can according
to the defensive charts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do whatever it takes,'' Glaus said. ``Obviously,
it's not permanent with Gary (DiSarcina) coming back. But it just
takes a few grounders for me to feel comfortable there. I've played
there all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks tunes up: Singer Garth Brooks was in uniform with the San
Diego Padres on Friday at Tempe Diablo Stadium, and as he has all
spring, signed autographs for fans, spoke with reporters and called
everybody ``sir'' and ``ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is hitting .067 (1 for 15) in 10 games, and has made one
error in left field. He faced the Angels' Mike Magnante in the top
of the eighth Friday with a runner on third and two out. On the
first pitch, Brooks fouled out to the first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pitch him any different than anybody else,'' Magnante
said. ``I threw a fastball low and away, just like I did the batter
before with Ruben Rivera.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' agreement with the Padres called for him to play with
the team for only a week. In turn, he would donate all of his
salary to the Touch 'Em All Foundation, a collaboration among
major-league players, entertainers and corporate partners that
benefits children's charities.
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks has stuck with it all spring, and said playing for
one of the Padres' minor-league affiliates _ possibly the Single-A
Rancho Cucamonga Quakes _ is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question will be, am I there to sell tickets or to play
baseball?'' Brooks said. ``... If I play in the minors, I don't
want to take someone's spot who deserves to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said his biggest fear playing with the Padres this spring
was embarrassing himself. ``But if you worry about that, you might
as well stay in the house all day. Of course, at my house that's
not so bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
