<HEADER>
A6142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MED-ETHICS27-COX     03-26 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MED-ETHICS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ethics of dying a quandary for legislators, physicians
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A 72-year-old man suffers a stroke
during coronary artery bypass surgery and goes into a coma. The
man's living will forbids the doctor from keeping him on life
support after a week, but his children want the doctor to do
``whatever it takes'' to restore his health.
</P>
<P>
   What should be done?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to die at some point,'' said Dr. David Cohen,
chief of the renal section at the Veterans Affairs Medical Center
in West Palm Beach. ``The question becomes how do we use medical
technology in the best way to keep people healthy, but not misuse
it so we prolong the process of dying and the suffering that goes
along with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Medical professionals, ethicists and now state legislators are
struggling to strike a balance.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed bills in the Florida Senate and House would protect
health care providers who follow patients' Do-Not-Resuscitate (DNR)
orders from criminal prosecution and lawsuits and direct the state
to develop standard DNR forms valid in all health care settings.
The bills also would require more ethics training to med students
in end-of-life care.
</P>
<P>
   The bills' most controversial aspect, however, would remove the
requirement that two doctors classify a patient as terminally ill
before following the patient's wish to abandon life-prolonging
procedures. Patients could state in living wills that they want
life-prolonging measures stopped or withheld if they are both
mentally and physically incapacitated.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say few doctors agree on how to define a ``terminally
ill'' condition. Florida law defines it as a condition ``caused by
injury, disease or illness from which there is no reasonable
probability of recovery and which, without treatment, can be
expected to cause death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The practical consequence is a lot of people are treated
against their will because an institution can't muster up two
physicians who will agree the patient is terminally ill,'' said
Kenneth Goodman, director of the University of Miami's Forum for
Bioethics and Philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 doctors, nurses, hospice workers and lawyers discussed
the ethics of end-of-life care at a Friday conference in Fort
Lauderdale led by the forum and sponsored by South Florida
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   One opponent of the bills said removing the requirement for two
doctors' approval could have harmful effects on patients,
especially the poor, elderly and minorities in a cost-conscious
health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some corridors, there's a financial incentive to deny
care,'' said Jim Towey, president of Aging with Dignity, a
nonprofit organization in Tallahassee. ``A lot of the elderly say
they don't want their lives extended, then they get in that setting
and change their mind.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
