<HEADER>
A6143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-OHIOST-NYT &LR;      03-26 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-OHIOST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARDS IN FOREFRONT OF UCONN-OHIO STATE CLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Khalid El-Amin was sitting behind the
microphone, his head bobbing, his legs jiggling, all the energy he
infuses into the Connecticut offense seeping out with nowhere to
go. An hour later, his counterpart, Ohio State's Scoonie Penn, sat
in the same spot, leaning his head so low over the table his
shoulders practically disappeared, his voice low, no movement
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   They are the players that, with their magnificent skills but
vastly different personalities, have carried their teams to the
Final Four and the brink of a national championship. For Ohio State
and its coach, Jim O'Brien, being here is a wonderful surprise, a
shocking result in a season he had hoped would end with a bid to
the National Invitation Tournament. For Connecticut's Jim Calhoun,
this tournament is long-sought redemption and validation, for all
the years he has won while building Connecticut into a national
power, and all the years his ability to reach basketball's promised
land has been doubted.
</P>
<P>
   They will meet Saturday, in the first national semifinal. And
Calhoun is probably thrilled he drew the Buckeyes (27-8) in the
semifinal, because he has owned O'Brien of late, beating him in
their last 18 meetings. But it is unlikely that in all those games,
there has ever been a guard matchup quite as compelling as the one
anticipated Saturday, a face-off between two tandems with opposite
strengths, but who are integral to their teams' chances of
advancing to Monday's championship. If O'Brien had had a backcourt
at Boston College like the one he has now, he would have won more
than three games in 23 tries against Calhoun. If Calhoun had always
had backcourts as good as this one, this wouldn't be the first trip
to the Final Four for the Huskies (29-3).
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's guards _ point guard Penn and shooting guard
Michael Redd _ make up perhaps the best backcourt in the nation.
They are the offensive bedrocks for the Buckeyes, the only players
who average in double figures _ Penn, 17.1 points and Redd, 19.7.
They have propelled fourth-seeded Ohio State on their remarkable
run through the tournament. They have provided more than half of
the Buckeyes' points in the tournament, and each has raised his
game in the last two weeks, with Redd averaging 21 points in the
four tournament games and the 5-foot-10-inch Penn, who is averaging
17.5 points, improving on defense and leading the team in
rebounding with 29 in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say they're the best backcourt we've faced all year,''
Connecticut's Ricky Moore said. ``No other backcourt does 70 to 75
percent of the scoring. Khalid and I can go out and prove that
we're one of the best backcourts in the country as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's backcourt is better known than the Buckeyes'
largely because of the outsized personality of point guard El-Amin.
The plump spark plug, despite being an erratic scorer, launches the
Huskies' locomotive of a transition game, leading the team with 56
steals.
</P>
<P>
   But the real strength of this backcourt is not offense. Moore,
the shooting guard, is perhaps the best defensive player in the
tournament. He has guarded the opposition's greatest threat all
season: he held Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves to 6 points on
2-of-15 shooting in December, and he will probably start against
Penn on Saturday. But if Redd, who will likely be guarded by
Richard Hamilton to start the game, gets hot early, Moore will
switch to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 27 years, I've never had anybody _ and I've had some great
defenders _ that could literally tear the head off a dragon, stop a
jump shooter,'' Calhoun said. ``He's played kids from 5-6 to 6-8.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Kevin Freeman said, ``I have as much confidence in him
as I have in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of backcourt duel was anticipated in the South
Regional final between Ohio State and St. John's. It never
materialized. Redd and Penn thoroughly outplayed Erick Barkley and
Bootsy Thornton, holding them to 21 points on 11-of-27 shooting,
while Redd and Penn scored 42 points on 15-of-30 shooting. That
sort of dominance is unlikely to be repeated here because neither
Barkley nor Thornton is the defensive stopper that Moore is. These
backcourts are more likely to cancel each other with high levels of
play, leaving the game to be decided by their respective front
courts, in which Connecticut would have the edge with the
all-American Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair to say that one or two players will dictate the
game,'' Connecticut center Jake Voskuhl said. ``It's a total team
effort. If you say the guards are shooting great, who is setting
the picks to get them open? If we set the picks and they don't hit
their shots, no one looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Duke center ELTON BRAND has fended off questions about whether
he will leave college for the National Basketball Association after
this season. But his teammates expect Brand to go. ``I have to be
honest with you, I don't think he'll be back,'' CHRIS BURGESS said.
``I wouldn't bet on him returning. If it were in his position, I'd
go, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
