r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-FREDRICKSON     03-26 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-FREDRICKSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS SNATCH FREDRICKSON FROM LIONS  
 MILLER'S RETURN UNLIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Four days after linebacker Jamir Miller rejected
the Cardinals' final offer, the team outbid the Detroit Lions for
outside linebacker Rob Fredrickson and signed him to a four-year
contract on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The move likely ends Miller's chances of returning to the
Cardinals, who offered him a two-year, $6 million deal last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With Fredrickson signing an $8 million deal, which included
about a $2 million signing bonus, the contract will count about $2
million against next season's salary cap, leaving the Cardinals
with about $1.7 million available under the $57.3 million cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily over, but it diminishes the likelihood
that something will happen with Jamir,'' Cardinals Vice President
Bill Bidwill Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the Cardinals' first-round draft pick in 1994 and their
leading tackler last season, visited the Chicago Bears and New
England Patriots but didn't receive an offer from either team. The
Tennessee Titans also have shown interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's agent, Steve Baker, said he wasn't surprised the
Cardinals signed Fredrickson, 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Cardinals told us on Monday that if Jamir didn't
accept their offer at $6 million, Jamir realized they likely would
sign another player,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday afternoon, Fredrickson, a 6-foot-4, 240-pound
fifth-year pro, appeared headed back to the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals then stepped up and increased their offer, beating
the reported $1.9 million a year the Lions had offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little numb,'' said Fredrickson, a 1994 first-round pick
of the Los Angeles Raiders out of Michigan State. ``It did happen
so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to be playing for the Cardinals. I felt I was
wanted here. They really embraced me. I didn't get that feeling
with the Lions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson's Phoenix-based agent, Eric Metz, said that ``from
the first day of free agency (Feb. 12), Rob wanted to be an Arizona
Cardinal.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson won't necessarily replace Miller in the lineup. The
Cardinals could place him on the right side and move Patrick Sapp
to the starting left linebacker spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still likely have to address our linebacker need in
the draft, but it takes a little bit of pressure off of us having
to do it quite as early in the draft,'' said Rod Graves, the
Cardinals assistant to the president who oversees pro and college
scouting. ``It gives us the luxury of adding another position or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who choose eighth and 21st overall in next
month's draft, could spend their two first-round picks on filling
needs at wide receiver and offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers coach Glenn Pires said he has been impressed with
Fredrickson since he began studying him two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing he brings to the table is he's a very intelligent
player who is extremely versatile,'' Pires said. ``From a coverage
standpoint, he has a lot of ability. He makes good decisions when
he plays. He's a very instinctive guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson has started 67 games in five seasons, including all
16 games for the Lions last season. He is coming off his best
statistical year, finishing with 116 tackles, 2.5 sacks and one
interception.
</P>
<P>
   He played 98 percent of the Lions' plays last season, which is
unusual in this age of situational substitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes him so valuable,'' Metz said. ``Guys usually
play the run very well or the pass very well. Very few guys can do
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also a guy who will play hurt. . . . He realizes that the
most important thing is durability.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Fredrickson, ``When you're getting paid a lot of money,
you're not getting paid to sit on the bench.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
