r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINAL-4-KRZYZEWSK     03-26 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL-4-KRZYZEWSKI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE COACH RANKS AS BEST OF THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. - The ranks are full of slick-talking
contenders and white-haired wonders, climbers who have won in
backwater outposts and miracle-workers who have revived programs
pinned with a coroner's certificate.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no ambiguity at top. Mike Krzyzewski is simply the
best coach of his time. End of debate, beginning of a new era.
</P>
<P>
   He is a coach who built a dynasty in Dean Smith's back yard,
only to watch it crumble from a hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   A coach reduced to a shell of a man, frightened and frail,
wondering if his run was permanently over.
</P>
<P>
   A coach who looked in the mirror, re-evaluated the landscape of
college basketball, re-defined his own being.
</P>
<P>
   Architect of another budding powerhouse, in a time when they
shouldn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that is this program stems from him,'' Duke star
Trajan Langdon said.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe now that Duke is threatening to book-end the
decade with sheer domination, but sometime in 1994, after a
three-pointer from Arkansas' Scotty Thurman prevented a third
national championship, it all fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Valvano, one of his closest friends in the business, died of
cancer. Then came the aching in his back and the day his wife told
him he couldn't come home until he saw a doctor. Then the back
surgery and a foolhardy return to the office within a week. And,
finally, surrender. A return to the hospital, a diagnosis of
exhaustion, a mandate from the administration that he was done for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Under a gentleman named Pete Gaudet, Duke finished 13-18 that
season, 2-14 in the ACC. The pipeline of talent had burst, and the
program had diverted into the hands of strange company, players
like Eric Meek, Chris Collins, Steve Wojciechowski.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in short, a mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat a lot of nights together where he questioned whether he
would ever do this again, whether he could do this again, whether
it would be too hard for him, whether he would have what it takes
to ever do it again,'' his wife, Mickie, told ESPN last week. ``He
knew he'd be starting over.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski is nothing without his roots, a man who grew up on
the south side of Chicago, served his country, played under Bobby
Knight at West Point. An old-school sort who landed at Duke as an
unknown curiosity. But in his darkest hole, he changed.
</P>
<P>
   He hired a time manager to handle his schedule. He revamped his
coaching staff, employing three former players _ Johnny Dawkins,
Quin Snyder and David Henderson _ who could relate to kids in a new
age of recruiting. And he hit the road with a renewed purpose, to
restore the glory of Duke.
</P>
<P>
   He snagged Elton Brand from New York, plucked William Avery out
of Georgia, snagged Shane Battier from Michigan. And he pulled off
the impossible, landing Corey Maggette without the bait of a
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Some professional scouts will tell you with a straight face that
Maggette would be the No. 1 pick in the upcoming draft. To convince
him is to convince the world, that Krzyzewski, above everyone else,
is the coach you want to play for.
</P>
<P>
   He took his team to the Great Alaska Shootout, Langdon's
hometown. He scheduled a game in Chicago so Maggette could perform
in his own backyard. And you wonder where the loyalty comes from?
</P>
<P>
   He took the best of Bobby Knight and left the worst behind.
Knight is a dinosaur, a man who refuses to change, which is why he
doesn't even rank among the top 20 coaches anymore. Knight caused a
stir after a victory over Northwestern this season when he
misinterpreted crowd chants of ``Who's Your Daddy,'' embarrassingly
ignorant to the lingo of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski has stayed current, and that's why he's here. A man
who matched John Wooden's 47 tournament victories last week and may
one day pass Wooden's record of 12 Final Four appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed this whole year as much as I've enjoyed any
year,'' Krzyzewski said. ``Going through a few things, that's
helped me appreciate even more the journey that you go on with
these kids. I feel as good as I've ever felt about coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   You can forget the chatter about this Duke outfit ranking among
the best teams in history. There are 29 players in the NBA who
could've affected this tournament, and if you allocate them among
the top 10 programs, the face of college basketball changes
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1976, 18 teams have entered the tournament with one
loss or less. None of those teams ever cut down the nets, and
whether this tournament is remembered as the Duke Invitational
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't make it, believe me, we'll be very disappointed,''
Krzyzewski said. ``But we will have had a great experience, and
that's where I think I've been better as a coach. If you talk to
our kids, I would hope that you'd never feel they were under any
pressure. Rather, they've enjoyed what they do. And you have to
give them time to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, some things haven't changed. Krzyzewski, 52, is still tough
on the tongue and demanding of his players. He can still swear like
a sailor and drown you with numbers, none more staggering than
seven Final Four appearances in nine years, eight altogether. But
they only frame the story, and inside is a remarkable journey of a
coach who rolled with the times when so many resist. A man who
re-dedicated himself to a mission that has landed the Blue Devils
in the familiar garb of favorites.
</P>
<P>
   He walks with a limp now, slated for hip replacement surgery in
the off-season. But if all goes well, he will scale the ladder once
again, scissors in hand, trophy on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he doesn't, the toughest climb is over. A man who went
up and down and back again. Right to the top of his profession. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
