<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6146 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PIR-IRL-VS.-CART-     03-26 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PIR-IRL-VS.-CART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL HAS A FUTURE, PIR OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In time, Tony George and Andrew Craig may decide one
sanctioning body is better than two. Then again, they may not.
</P>
<P>
   For now, George, who heads the Pep Boys Indy Racing League, and
Craig, the Championship Auto Racing Teams leader, appear content
with the status quo, even if the status quo means attendance woes
at some venues and poor television ratings at most.
</P>
<P>
   But that's OK, said Arie Luyendyk, a two-time Indianapolis 500
champion sitting out Sunday's IRL-sanctioned MCI WorldCom at
Phoenix International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I think the IRL will be very successful with just
oval-type racing because Americans tend to love oval racing,'' said
Luyendyk, whose only on-track appearance this season will be at the
Indy 500. ``So quit comparing it to CART. Comparing the IRL with
CART is like comparing NASCAR to CART. It's a different ballgame,
two different series.
</P>
<P>
   ``So leave it alone. Take the IRL for what it is on its own. If
you just looked at what's been going on at the racetrack, it's
wheel to wheel racing.''
</P>
<P>
   No argument there.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, last season included several exciting IRL on-track
skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   CART, too.
</P>
<P>
   But what also has transpired in the three years since the split
is fans appear to have become polarized.
</P>
<P>
   It seems fans either love CART or hate it.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   The love-or-hate relationship has been especially noticeable at
PIR, where three previous IRL productions have been box-office
flops.
</P>
<P>
   Although CART crowds were dwindling at PIR before the break-up,
down to about 45,000 in its final season here in 1995, IRL
attendance has been abysmal.
</P>
<P>
   PIR refuses to release attendance figures, but it is believed
last year's attendance was a paltry 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   PIR officials repeatedly have stated their intent to remain an
IRL-affiliated track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that we've had growth every year since the
first IRL race here,'' PIR Vice President and General Manager Robin
Braig said. ``No matter what anyone says, we're making money on IRL
races and we think over time it's going to continue to grow and
grow. We're in this for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tony George said it would take several years to grow the
series, he wasn't lying about that. We knew it would take time. But
we, too, have the courage to grow our event as well as support the
IRL.''
</P>
<P>
   When told to take the IRL or leave it, however, some fans have
left it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to love to go to Phoenix and watch Indy-car races,''
said fan Patric McNulla of Edison, N.J. ``There used to be six of
us who'd meet in San Diego and drive over. But none of us go
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even watch the (Indy 500). And I won't buy any sponsor
product connected to the IRL. I felt like if I did, all I'd be
doing is perpetuating (the IRL). The whole thing is really
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stupid, yes, Brad Edwards of Plainfield, Ind., agreed. But CART
is the guilty party, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony George did the right thing in forming the IRL to save
open-wheel racing,'' Edwards said. ``The drivers who busted their
guts on the bullrings of America were being shunned by CART.
</P>
<P>
   ``CART did absolutely nothing to enhance open-wheel reacing in
the 1980s. They let NASCAR run away with the fans and did nothing
to curtail this from happening. CART's egotistical owners could not
agree on anything that was for the betterment of the sport. All
they cared about was what was best for them.''
</P>
<P>
   All fan Ken Foust knows is that he's unhappy with the IRL
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRL is basically a glorified club racing league, led by
famous dirt racing heroes,'' said Foust, who splits time between
homes in Phoenix and Sacramento. ``The IRL is just not in the same
league as CART.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL car owner Dick Simon has been on both sides. A former CART
driver and team owner, Simon pledged his support with the IRL
following its creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRL is the best thing in the world,'' Simon said. ``The
media has tried to create this animosity and competitiveness
between the two series, saying we need to get back together, that
we're ruining racing. But that's not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TV ratings are getting better and the fan base is growing
rapidly. People talk about us losing New Hampshire (International
Speedway), but I remember when it was a CART race and they were
begging the crews to sit in the (grandstands).
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, everything will be rectified. We're two different
series. You've got a Formula One series in America called CART, and
you've got an Indianapolis-type racing series called the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``And with my $3.5 million budget, I can compete with anyone for
the front row in the (Indy 500).''
</P>
<P>
   But what has happened to the Indy 500? Has it lost some of its
luster, as some suggest?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, yes,'' said Luyendyk, who won a second Indy
500 in 1997. ``But the second year it was a little less (tarnished)
and the third even less. As we go along, it will be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it always takes time to develop something. You
can't be great right out of the box. But if you look at the drivers
in the IRL, they're good drivers. They're just not known to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it used be that way in CART, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending Indy 500 champion Eddie Cheever Jr., a native
Phoenician now living in Orlando, has grown weary of the CART vs.
IRL subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irrelevant,'' Cheever said. ``They (CART) have their
series and we have our series. All this animosity, let's just get
over it. It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be done, McNulla said, until the two sides reach a
mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's quit all the arguing and find a way to compromise,''
McNulla said. ``We need to bring the two together because I just
don't think there's room for both series.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
