<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-FINAL-FOUR-NYT &LR;      03-26 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-FINAL-FOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE WOMEN ELBOW THEIR WAY INTO CHAMPIONSHIP GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ga., Ind., La.)  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Duke, a bit player in women's college
basketball until recent seasons, continues its captivating run
through a tournament usually dominated by a select few powerhouse
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils advanced to Sunday's title game of the NCAA
tournament with a thorough 81-69 victory over Georgia Friday night
at the San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils will play the winner of Friday night's second
semifinal game between Purdue (32-1) and Louisiana Tech (30-2).
</P>
<P>
   Duke (29-6) won as it did when it upset three-time defending
national champion Tennessee in Monday's East Regional final _ with
the dependable inside play of 6-foot-6 center Michele VanGorp and
the scrappy play of guards Nicole Erickson, Georgia Schweitzer and
Peppi Browne.
</P>
<P>
   And Duke won with an infectious enthusiasm and a weaving,
pass-happy, team-oriented offense that involved every player on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils do not like to be called the underdogs of this
tournament; their coach, Gail Goestenkors, maintains that their
goal was a national championship all along. But Duke is at least
the wunderkind of the tourney and its best story, especially since
its men's team is the favorite to win the national title in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Duke controlled most of the first half and charged to a 13-point
lead early in the second. But Georgia's pressure defense allowed
the Lady Bulldogs (27-7) to cut Duke's lead to 6 points at the
midpoint of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The twins Coco and Kelly Miller each hit baskets, taking
advantage of the absence of VanGorp, who sat out for three minutes
with three fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller's two free throws cut Duke's lead to 60-54, but
Hilary Howard sank two free throws to rebuild Duke's 8-point edge.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams seemed fatigued as the game _ played at a frantic
pace from the opening tip _ wound into its final eight minutes. And
with that fatigue, contact between the players was more common,
something that played to Georgia's disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Duke shoots 77 percent from the free throw line as a team, with
a handful of its players making more than 80 percent of their foul
shots this season.
</P>
<P>
   When Schweitzer made two free throws with 7 minutes 38 seconds
left in the game, Duke's lead was once again in double figures,
64-54. VanGorp added two free throws to extend the lead to 12
points.
</P>
<P>
   On Georgia's next possession, Coco Miller went to the foul line
but missed the front end in a one-and-one situation. Erickson
followed with a driving layup, VanGorp then blocked a shot by
Tawana McDonald and Erickson hit a fallaway jumper as the shot
clock expired to give Duke a 70-55 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a basket by McDonald, Erickson delivered another
staggering blow to any Georgia hopes of a comeback, hitting a
3-point shot from the corner. If that didn't wound Georgia's
morale, then a 3-pointer by Lauren Rice with 3:02 left must have,
as it gave Duke a 76-57 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, however, scored 10 unanswered points, cutting the Duke
lead to 76-67 with 1:22 to play, when a Duke turnover led to Kelly
Miller's layup. Erickson hit another 3-point basket with 47 seconds
left to protect the Blue Devils' lead.
</P>
<P>
   The furious pace of the first half initially suited Duke, which
sprinted to a 17-7 lead. But the Blue Devils' offense was mostly
perimeter shooting, which masked a bigger Duke problem _ its
inability to get the ball inside to VanGorp.
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp rarely touched the ball early in the game and faced a
double-team when she did. She took just two shots in the game's
first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Duke was concerned that its star guards,
Schweitzer and Erickson, who are both 5-6, would have trouble
getting open looks at the basket against Georgia's twin guards,
Kelly and Coco Miller, who are both 5-10. But motion and a series
of screens in the backcourt repeatedly sprung both Schweitzer and
Erickson, who combined for 16 first-half points. Schweitzer's
3-point basket gave Duke a 10-point lead, but Georgia quickly
scrambled back.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs did so with the tenacious defense that has become
their trademark. Georgia held four previous tournament opponents to
an average of just 58 points and had an average victory margin of
16 points. Georgia's frontcourt tandem of Angie Ball and McDonald
kept VanGorp out of sync as Georgia rallied.
</P>
<P>
   Coco Miller hit a leaning jumper off a screen set by her sister
and Deana Nolan drove the baseline for two baskets. Ball and
McDonald added inside baskets as the Lady Bulldogs tied the game at
25-25.
</P>
<P>
   Then VanGorp suddenly found her game. VanGorp, the star of
Duke's upset victory over Tennessee in the East Regional final,
scored 8 of the Blue Devils' last 12 points as Duke took a 40-34
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp's inside task was made easier by the penetration of
Erickson and Browne. Ball and McDonald had to leave VanGorp's side
to defend Browne, leaving VanGorp open near the basket for easy
putback points.
</P>
<P>
   The intermission did not cool VanGorp's hot hand, and she
started the second half with a 3-pointer from the corner. It was
only VanGorp's second 3-point shot of the season, and she added a
pull-up jumper on Duke's next possession.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Andy Landers had feared that his team's aggressive
defense would send Duke players on a parade to the free throw line
and get his team into foul trouble. It did not happen in the first
half when Duke shot just five free throws. But in the second half,
Duke's backcourt quickness seemed to be wearing on Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
