</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-REVIEW-MAGIC-BIRD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAGIC VS. BIRD' A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Every basketball fan knows that Larry Bird and Magic
Johnson saved the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Before they came along, the league had descended into a haze of
selfish play, declining ratings, drug rumors and half-empty arenas.
Their personal rivalry, along with that of the Boston Celtics and
the LA Lakers, changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   What's sometimes lost in the swirl of memories is the way the
two changed March Madness as well.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't remember the 1979 NCAA Championship, in which
Bird's undefeated Indiana State Sycamores met Magic's Michigan
State Spartans _ or even if you do _ tune in to Fox Sports Arizona
at noon Sunday for ``Magic vs. Bird: the Game That Changed the
Game.'' It's a detailed look not just at the final game, but at the
two teams' march toward it. Hosted by Chris Myers (still kind of
weird to see him on a network other than ESPN), the show includes
interviews with the two principals, of course, as well as with
teammates, coaches and broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic vs. Bird'' isn't the best documentary you'll ever see,
but plenty of great clips make it well worth watching. The
producers have done an excellent job of providing footage of
seemingly everything anyone talks about.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Magic says he learned to handle the ball by
dribbling to the grocery store. He dribbled with one hand on the
way there; on the way back, he dribbled with the other hand while
carrying groceries. And sure enough, in a grainy home movie, we see
little Ervin balancing a full grocery bag while keeping his
dribble.
</P>
<P>
   In another segment, a teammate of Bird's describes a legendary
move in which a defender blanketed Bird in a corner. Bird took the
ball behind his head and passed it, with both hands going over the
defender's head.
</P>
<P>
   Except that he didn't. Bird didn't let go of the ball. The
defender leapt around, looking for the pass. Bird straightened up
and nailed a long-distance jumper. When the description ends, we
see it. And it is fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   Like any sports documentary, ``Magic vs. Bird'' suffers from an
overdose of seriousness; sometimes it seems as if the people being
interviewed are talking about the invasion of Normandy instead of
college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the game ``was'' important, at least in the sports
universe. It's rare when you can predict that any player will
become larger than the sport, but here were two of them in the same
game.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, the network that broadcast the NCAA Finals then, realized
this and hyped the game accordingly. A pre-``Today'' show Bryant
Gumbel introduced the coverage, promising a treat for ``those who
believe in Magic and those who appreciate the beauty of a rare
Bird.'' (It paid off _ this is still the highest-rated NCAA Finals
ever.) So thank the network for the endless March Madness
promotions we see on CBS today. Or blame it, depending on your
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bird says he didn't even notice the televised build-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to play and win the game,'' he says. ``All that
outside stuff meant nothing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fun to see and hear the old triumvirate of Dick Enberg,
Billy Packer and Al McGuire call the game. And it's always
entertaining to see the short shorts that players wore in the
pre-Jordan era.
</P>
<P>
   But it's downright inspirational to relive Bird and Magic's play
_ their teamwork, their passing, their incredible skill. As Enberg
says, it's almost as if they were NBA players competing in a
college game.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State won handily, a fact that obviously still pleases
Magic and bothers Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart,'' Bird says. ``It really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic understands, he says, and offers a clue to the secret of
their rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know these type of things,'' he says, ``because we're
winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Winners, as ``Magic vs. Bird'' shows, from a long way back. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 602-444-8828 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
