<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHST-NYT &LR;      03-26 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE COULD OVERRUN   SPARTANS' GAME PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Michigan State has a plan. Reduce the
94-foot court to an 8-foot battle zone. Crowd the foul lanes at
both ends of the floor with elbows spread. Contain the Duke
sharpshooters and slow down the pace of the Final Four semifinal
game at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   Like most plans, Michigan State's looks pretty good on paper.
The Spartans have outrebounded 35 of 37 opponents and, in four
tournament games, pulled down an average of 11 more offensive
rebounds than their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   They have demonstrated mental toughness by winning 33 games,
seven of them decided by eight points or fewer, four of them
masterpieces that went down to the wire and were won by a single
basket.
</P>
<P>
   Against Kentucky in the Midwest Regional final, Michigan State
did not panic after being down 13 points in the first half and
showed that its grit was marbled with poise.
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan State coach Tom Izzo acknowledges the difficulty in
making his strategy succeed. His team needs to execute it against a
Blue Devil team that has won 36 games by an average of 25.9 points
and boasts dominant players in point guard William Avery, center
Elton Brand and the all-America guard Trajan Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a point guard like they do, they can
penetrate,'' Izzo said. ``When he does, he'll kick out to Langdon,
who will either shoot or pound it into Brand. Some said they
haven't rebounded well as a team. I look at them and see they're
not missing many shots, and getting a lot of steals. When you do
that, you don't have to get a lot of rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils shot 60 percent overall and 58 percent from the
3-point line while winning the East Regional final over Temple. But
Michigan State has plenty of bodies _ a nine-deep rotation _ to
chase Langdon and company on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Spartans' bench, led by its leading scorer,
Morris Peterson (13.5), has been outscored only once this year. The
Spartan substitutes understand how important their roles are if
they are to beat Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the potential to go on some runs during the game and
if we can weather those and hang tight and go on our runs, too, it
should play a big part in the game,'' said A.J. Granger, the
Spartans' 6-foot-9-inch forward.
</P>
<P>
   In Mateen Cleaves, Michigan State has a tenacious point guard to
challenge Avery. Cleaves perhaps is the key to forcing the game
inside on both ends of the floor, as well as dictating the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that they're a great rebounding team,'' Duke
coach Mike Krzyzewski said. ``It's also obvious that they can
really move the ball up the court quickly to get early offense.
Those are two areas we have to be good in. If we don't, we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves needs to play better and make wiser decisions than he
did in a 73-67 loss to Duke in December. Avery had 14 points, five
assists and one turnover, while Cleaves scored just nine points on
3-of-17 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to concentrate on doing a better job for my team,''
Cleaves said. ``I don't want shooting to dictate my game. This time
I have to do a better job running my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski has prepared his team for a slow, physical game. The
Spartans' Antonio Smith _ a 6-9, 250-pounder _ will try to minimize
the number of times Brand touches the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebounding is one of the keys to the game,'' Brand said.
``Check the stats: they have rebounded almost 50 percent of their
missed shots in the tournament. There's going to be a lot of
banging and wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski acknowledged that a tight game favors Michigan State.
While the Spartans have demonstrated the ability to win close
games, Krzyzewski's young team has played in only four games
decided by 8 points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a huge advantage there and many other areas,''
Krzyzewski said. ``I expect it to be a close game. They're too
good. I think we're good. And so I would hope that when our kids
are in that position that we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo and the Spartans just want a chance to win. It would mean
that the game plan put them in position to beat a team that Izzo
calls flawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lie to my guys,'' Izzo said. ``If Duke plays their `A'
game, I don't think many teams can beat them, including us. Our job
is to make sure they don't play their `A' game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
