<SLUG> BC-CBS-KINGWORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS-KING WORLD DEAL TALKS REPORTED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS has been in preliminary discussions to acquire King World
Productions, the syndicator of such hit shows as ``Oprah'' and
``Wheel of Fortune,'' executives close to the talks said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two companies have been talking for several weeks,
the discussions are still premature and could end any time. King
World's stock price hit a 52-week high of $31.3125 Friday in active
trading, before closing up $1 at $29.9375. Any deal is expected to
have a small premium because of King World's recent stock price
runup, said the executives.
</P>
<P>
   While some have suggested that Mel Karmazin, president and chief
executive of CBS, is willing to pay cash for the company _ King
World has a market value of $2.1 billion _ it has not been ruled
out that any deal could be a stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   A possible combination makes sense, analysts said. CBS and King
World have been successful partners with the new ``Hollywood
Squares,'' which is broadcast on CBS. But King World's other
brand-name shows, like ``Jeopardy'' and ``The Oprah Winfrey Show,''
are syndicated to ABC stations well into the next millennium. That
could prove troublesome for CBS or any buyer if the stars of those
shows, particularly Oprah Winfrey, decided to bolt once those
contracts had expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oprah can bolt at any time,'' said Harry DeMott, a broadcast
analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``I can't see her working
for Mel. She doesn't need to answer to anyone.'' Still, he added,
``If there is value there, Mel is the one to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin could have his eye on King World's full coffers. The
company has almost $1 billion in cash on hand, and CBS could use
the money to buy a television station. CBS and King World would not
comment on the possible talks.
</P>
<P>
   King World was established in 1964 to syndicate films and
television programs to stations nationwide and is currently run by
the founder's sons: Roger King is chairman and Michael King is vice
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company originally specialized in reruns, but by the late
1970s it bought rights to distribute game shows like ``The Joker's
Wild'' and ``Tic Tac Dough.'' The company produced its first
in-house show, ``Inside Edition,'' in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
