<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-REICHEL-A     03-26 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-REICHEL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES HIT JACKPOT  
 REICHEL DOES ALL THEY EXPECTED HIM TO DO _ AND THEN SOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They thought about Adam Oates from the Washington
Capitals. They considered Theo Fleury from the Calgary Flames. They
were intrigued with Mark Recchi of the Montreal Canadiens. And they
almost zeroed in on his teammate, captain Vincent Damphousse.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came time to pull the trigger on a deal for a
second-line center, the Coyotes got the player they secretly
coveted the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been talking with the Islanders about Robert Reichel
for quite a while,'' General Manager Bobby Smith said. ``He's a
player we think is tremendously gifted. He's got the flair for the
power play that no other player on our team has, that no other
player since this team has been in Arizona has had. Hopefully, it
will mesh with us quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   It has. Smith made those comments less than an hour before
Reichel's debut with the Coyotes on Sunday against the Los Angeles
Kings. On Reichel's first shift, he took a shot that nearly fooled
goalie Jamie Storr and definitely fooled the goal judge, who
prematurely clicked on the red light.
</P>
<P>
   On his third shift, Reichel took a pass behind the net, faked,
and looking the other way, fed Keith Tkachuk right in front for a
1-0 lead. The play drew a rousing standing ovation from the crowd.
Later, Reichel brought them to their feet again, scoring a nifty
empty-net goal on a power play after the Kings pulled Storr for an
extra attacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to like having this guy around,'' Tkachuk
said. ``If he keeps making plays like those, we're going to be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   He has. They are.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel, whose 60 points (22 goals, 38 assists) rank second on
the team behind Jeremy Roenick and 21st in the NHL, set up another
Tkachuk goal in his next game against Dallas. Then on Thursday, in
a 4-2 win over Washington, the native of Litvinov, Czecholslovakia,
scored twice on a night when he very well could have put in four or
five.
</P>
<P>
   He missed on a third-period penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's three goals and two assists in three games
entering tonight's match-up at 8 against the Calgary Flames at
America West Arena. With another win, the Coyotes (35-25-12) can
wrap up a four-game home stand at 3-1 and reach the 84-point
barrier, the most since they finished with 87 in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have 10 regular-season games remaining and have a
shot to threaten the franchise record for most points in a season _
96 in 1984-85 _ but would have to finish strong. If Reichel keeps
working his magic, centering a rejuvenated Greg Adams and Rick
Tocchet, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good here,'' said Reichel, 27, who needs one point
to reach the 500 milestone. ``They're giving me a chance to play
with good players and I'm trying my best. So far, things are going
my way, the team is winning and it's coming at a very good time
with the playoffs coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who traded 21-year-old wing Brad Isbister to the
Islanders for Reichel and an exchange of draft picks _ Phoenix also
swapped third-round choices and received a fourth-round pick from
an Islanders deal with Ottawa _ has always been impressed with
Reichel's offensive talents. He's on pace to finish with his best
NHL season since amassing 93 points for Calgary, recording his
second straight 40-goal season, six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch him out there and he can make the pass, find a guy,
find the seam that other guys can't,'' Smith said. ``He can find a
guy in the middle of the box, the other side of the box, take a
shot, find another guy open on the side of the net. He doesn't just
make the basic play.''
</P>
<P>
   Reichel gives the Coyotes and Coach Jim Schoenfeld a different
look they didn't have while trying an assortment of players on the
second line behind Tkachuk, Roenick and Dallas Drake. He creates
scoring chances on almost every shift and is deceptively quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an elite hockey player, and we knew exactly what we were
getting,'' Schoenfeld said. ``He's as good as advertised, and I
think he's shown everyone who was wondering what type of player he
is exactly what type he is. He's a great playmaker and has a
tremendous shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Reichel should kick-start the team's sagging power-play unit,
which ranks among th worst in the league. He also should take some
pressure off Roenick's shoulders, according to Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be great for JR,'' Tkachuk said.
``Robert's going to push him, but also take a little bit of the
weight off JR. You need two good solid lines and we've got that
now. We've just got to get past the first round of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something the franchise hasn't accomplished in a dozen
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
