<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6154 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAWL-AZR &LR;      03-26 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAWL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECK-LEE BAT TLE SPARKS ILL WILL BETWEEN D-BACKS AND CUBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, ARIZ. - When the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa hit two home
runs against the Diamondbacks on March 17 and bowed after each one,
a bit of bad blood might have oozed between the two clubs after
Arizona pitcher Todd Stottlemyre claimed Sosa was showing him up.
</P>
<P>
   But after what happened Friday when they met again at HoHoKam
Park in Mesa?
</P>
<P>
   Forget about it! The bad blood's not oozing any more: It's
flowing like a river.
</P>
<P>
   As a capacity crowd of 12,423 looked on, both benches and
bullpens emptied when Arizona right-hander Rich Batchelor plunked
Cubs second baseman Mickey Morandini in the back with a pitch.
Morandini moved toward the mound, jawing at Batchelor, and the
clubs exchanged shoves and expletives, but no punches. Diamondbacks
catcher Damian Miller claimed he was kicked in the stomach,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had my chest protector on but I still felt the
spikes,'' Miller said. ``The guy hid behind two other guys
(teammates). Do I know who he is? Yeah, and he does, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The fuse was lit in the top of the sixth inning when the
Diamondbacks, who rocked Cubs starter Steve Trachsel for 15 runs on
11 hits over the first 2 1/3 innings, started using veteran closer
Rod Beck for target practice.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Steve Finley hit a homer off Beck, his second of
the game, and second baseman Hanley Frias hit a double. Then Beck,
who had not pitched in a game in three weeks due to a disc problem
in his back, hit Diamondacks first baseman Travis Lee on the back
of the right shoulder near the base of the neck. It appeared
initially that Lee had been hit in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, entering his second season, stared at the burly
right-hander before moving toward first base. He said Beck told him
the pitch was not intentional, but his veteran teammates and
Manager Buck Showalter believed otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the (strike) zone the first few pitches and I took a
big cut at one,'' Lee said. ``Then I saw this one coming in on me
and I thought, `Holy crap.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One of the veteran Diamondbacks, outfielder Luis Gonzalez, slid
hard into Morandini as the Cubs completed a double play to end the
inning and the two exchanged words.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit our guy, so I was just sliding hard. It was part of
the game,'' said Gonzalez, who played for the Cubs in 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Batchelor pitch in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of got away from me,'' Batchelor said. ``When you let
the ball go and it starts to go in there (toward the hitter), you
have to think that it (batter charging the mound) might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Order was restored and no one was ejected, but tempers simmered.
Sosa, who had hit his ninth homer of the spring, stepped to the
plate and hit a rocket off Batchelor's left leg, just below the
knee for a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Diamondbacks became livid when they saw Cubs third
baseman-catcher Tyler Houston standing on the top step of the
dugout, clapping as Arizona trainers tended to Batchelor. Finley
had to be restrained. Houston hit a home run later in the inning as
the Cubs scored seven runs, but Arizona held on for a 17-10
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Finley kept his emotions in check afterward, saying, ``That's
not something you want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Batchelor, whose leg was swollen slightly and was due to get a
precautionary X-ray when the team returned to Tucson, said he did
not see Houston, didn't doubt his teammates and said the move
``showed a lack of character. It was tasteless.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the pitch that hit Lee, Beck said, ``I wasn't trying to hit
him. I've got no reason to hit anybody in spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter wasn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the experience he's had throwing on the side, throwing in
the bullpen, it's a little hard to fathom that he would let a pitch
get away like that,'' Showalter said. ``Anybody watching the game
who knows anything about the game knows it was intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   Morandini cautioned reporters: ``Don't interview me, because I
ain't saying nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Diamondbacks would remember Friday's events when
the clubs meet for the first time during the regular season at Bank
One Ballpark June 7-9, Gonzalez said, ``What do you think?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
