<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS DOES HIS POUNDING AT THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, ARIZ. -  &UR; Matt Williams didn't have to say it. The look on
his face spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   A swirl of emotion was rushing through his veins after the
Diamondbacks' 17-10 victory over the Chicago Cubs on Friday at
HoHoKam Park in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to enjoy his first big offensive effort at the plate
this spring, four hits in five trips with seven RBIs, including a
three-run homer, but it was lost amid events surrounding a
bench-clearing incident in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Right in the middle of it was Williams' former San Francisco
Giants teammate and friend, right-hander  &UR; Rod Beck, who hit Arizona
first baseman  &UR; Travis Lee in the shoulder with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the next batter, hit a hard shot to third baseman
 &UR; Tyler
 &UR; Houston for a forceout. Then in the bottom of the sixth, Williams
was among those pouring onto the field when the Diamondbacks'  &UR; Rich
 &UR; Batchelor hit the Cubs'  &UR; Mickey Morandini.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any comment on that,'' Williams said, teeth
clenched.
</P>
<P>
   He did say that he is encouraged by the way he is starting to
swing the bat with the season opener a little more than a week
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made good contact all five times, even on the out,'' he
said. ``I'm trying to hit the ball hard.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Gregg Olson threw 18 pitches without discomfort in
his right forearm and wrist during a minor-league intrasquad game
Friday in Tucson and likely will pitch in a similar-type game on
Sunday. Right-hander  &UR; Amaury Telemaco, who has been battling
shoulder tendinitis, also is expected to pitch in the same game on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Diamondbacks' scouts will gather Sunday and Monday
to discuss what they have seen in the Grapefruit and Cactus leagues
this spring and if there are any players that the club should
consider acquiring.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly lost in the offensive display by both clubs on Friday was
a hustling play by  &UR; Steve Finley in center field in the first
inning. With the Cubs'  &UR; Henry Rodriguez at first,  &UR; Scott Stahoviak
hit a ball off the fence in left-center. Finley got over to field
the carom, whirled and threw to the cutoff man to keep Rodriguez
from scoring, holding him at third. Houston then flew out to Finley
to end the inning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
