u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      03-26 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SHOW US THE MONEY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 27: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible casualties of the furious budget bargaining
in Albany is Gov. George Pataki's request for $28 million in new
money to begin construction of the Hudson River Park along
Manhattan's West Side. The Republican-controlled Senate knocked the
appropriation out of its budget bill, in part because Pataki has
spent only $4 million of $20 million approved last year, leaving a
$16 million carryover. The Democrats in the Assembly approved $21
million of the $28 million request. When the governor and the
legislative leaders sit down to discuss differences, Pataki must
insist, at the very least, on the Assembly's more generous figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans argue that it makes no sense to tie up another
chunk of money in the park when there are more immediate needs.
They say they will relent if Pataki quickly produces a detailed
plan on how the money will be spent. That is an unrealistic
request. The governing board that will run the project _ and hence
has the authority to spend money _ was appointed only last month.
Even so, it is important to have the money on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The board inherits a solid general plan that calls for replacing
the rotting piers on Manhattan's West Side with an inviting mix of
open space and commercial development. The engineers cannot be
expected to finish the design work and let construction contracts
on the basis of political promises.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens' coalition supporting the park required 13 years to
develop a plan on which rival politicians and competing interest
groups could broadly agree, and another year on top of that to win
legislative approval. The political will is now in place to move
this project forward. The economy is robust.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is fully on board and has
pledged $100 million from his capital budget over the next four
years. The Legislature should deliver on its part of the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6208 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-FINAL-4-DUKE-GEOR     03-26 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-FINAL-4-DUKE-GEORGIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE RUNS TO TITLE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The Duke women's basketball team looks like dough and
plays like money.
</P>
<P>
   Except for 6-foot-6 All-America Michele VanGorp, the Blue Devils
are as unathletic looking a national finalist as can be imagined.
Yet they not only humbled the Three Meeks in ousting three-time
defending NCAA champion Tennessee but by downing Georiga, 81-69,
Friday night at San Jose Arena are a step away from a title in
their first Final Four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be athletic to be a great player,'' Duke
Coach Gail Goestenkors said. ``We're very smart. If someone has got
a weakness, we take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia weakness was an inability to cover both VanGorp
inside and the perimeter sharpshooters Nicole Erickson, Georgia
Schweitzer and Hilary Howard. VanGorp ran up 20 points while
Erickson had a game-high 22 as the Devils shot 56.3 percent from
3-point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spread you offensively because they can,'' Georgia Coach
Andy Landers said. ``You find yourself yo-yoing from a very
talented post player to very talented shooters. It's almost as if
you choose your poison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of those players are pretty damn good players.''
</P>
<P>
   The best player for either side in the first half was Georgia
backup guard Deana Nolan, who eight points in 12 minutes exceeded
her season average by one. Her athleticism stabilized the Bulldogs,
down 17-7 after the opening 5:11 off a 12-2 Duke run.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan had two buckets in a 12-3 run that brought Georgia within
one, 20-19, just past the middle of the first half. The Bulldogs
scored eight straight points to lead, 27-25, for the first time
since a game-opening 3-pointer by Coco Miller.
</P>
<P>
   But VanGorp and Howard took control in the final 3:34 of the
first half and opening 1:29 of the second. They scored all but two
of Duke's points in a 16-5 run that turned a tie at 31 into the
beginning of a runaway, 47-36.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia (27-7) fought back within 60-54 with 9:10 remaining then
a pair of free throws each by Howard, Erickson and VanGorp put Duke
(29-6) safely ahead 66-54 and started a game-clinching 16-3 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with tremendous poise,'' Goestenkors said. ``We
played with confidence and also very relaxed, with a championship
mentality that we've showed all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia guard Coco and Kelly Miller combined for 31 points,
within range of the twins' season average of 37, but Kelly was
limited by Howard to 13, 20 fewer than she scored in the Mideast
Region final.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer initially covered Coco Miller until Erickson took
over the job, a switch that kept Georgia's transition game in
check.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to run when we score and take care of the ball,''
Goestenkors said.
</P>
<P>
   Young Georgia, with just one senior starter, exits its fifth
Final Four still seeking the brass ring. Duke, at least until later
today, is one step ahead of its powerhouse men in the school's
pursuit of the first ever sweep of NCAA titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know our limitations,'' said the 5-6 Howard, who had five
of her eight points in the late first/early second-half run and two
particularly pretty assists. ``We know we're undersized, that we're
not the quickest players or the most athletic on the court. Our
biggest thing is team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
