<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL-4-OHIO-STATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'BRIEN HAS REVIVED BUCKEYES IN A HURRY  
 COACH SEEKS END TO CALHOUN JINX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Anticipation and preparation are part of
the reason Ohio State Coach Jim O'Brien and his three counterparts
are here at the Final Four. So not only was O'Brien ready for the
question he knew would come, he launched a pre-emptive strike
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to share a funny story with you,'' he told the media on
Friday. ``I know somebody is going to ask about 18 straight losses
to Jim Calhoun. We might as well talk about it right this minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Might as well, Jim. Ever since Ohio State beat St. John's in the
South Region final last Saturday to set up a date with Connecticut
today at Tropicana Field in the opening national semifinal game, a
hot topic has been the 18 straight times Calhoun and UConn beat
O'Brien's Boston College teams between 1989 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, O'Brien said, the four coaches _ he, Calhoun, Duke's
Mike Krzyzewski and Michigan State's Tom Izzo _ were together the
night before. Calhoun, ``obviously a wonderful guy,'' according to
O'Brien, said to Krzyzewski, ``It's nice to see you,'' and he said
to Izzo, ``It's nice to see you,'' and what do you think he said to
O'Brien?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim, it's ``really'' nice to see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rim shot, please.
</P>
<P>
   That was funny, but the truth is this: Boston College is old
news. O'Brien last coached there during the 1996-97 season, before
a bitter dispute with his alma mater's administration left him no
recourse but to leave. Ohio State was glad to take him.
</P>
<P>
   There are few reminders in O'Brien's office of his Boston
College days, one of them being a Big East Coach of the Year
trophy. It's a new team for O'Brien, a new chapter in his life.
Calhoun knows this, which is why he said of the streak, ``The
relevancy of it here is non-existent.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun's teams always seemed to be a little bit better than
O'Brien's. When Boston College was good, UConn was very good. When
Boston College was very good, UConn was great. This time, in this
setting, Calhoun's Huskies may be a tad better than O'Brien's
Buckeyes. Maybe not. Even if they are, the better team doesn't
always win.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it comes down to which team handles the moment the
best. There seems to be little O'Brien and his team can't handle.
This is a guy whose love for his wife, Christine, was the one, true
thing in his life, and then Christine died suddenly of a heart
attack in 1991, leaving O'Brien to raise two daughters by himself.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Erin, now 24, recently told a reporter, ``We all
sort of fumbled our way through it at first. We weren't the perfect
daughters, and he couldn't be the perfect father. . . . It could
have been terrible. It could have torn us apart. But Dad was
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   After rebuilding a family, how tough is it to rebuild a
basketball program?
</P>
<P>
   Under Randy Ayers, whose descent from national Coach of the Year
to former coach was shocking in its rapidity, Ohio State was 39-72
in the four seasons preceding O'Brien. Last season, O'Brien's
first, the Buckeyes were 8-22 and 1-15 in their conference, 11th in
the Big Ten. There might be a joke in that, but it wasn't very
funny back in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   But there was hope. O'Brien's power of persuasion had enticed a
kid named Michael Redd, from just down the street at Columbus West
High School, to stay in town. And O'Brien's ability to lead,
combined with fears of bad days ahead at Boston College, prompted a
tough, mature point guard named James ``Scoonie'' Penn to transfer
along with O'Brien to Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Redd, a 6-foot-6 sophomore guard who can shoot the
three-pointer, take it to the basket and create the shot of his
choice, led the Big Ten in scoring as a freshman last season, even
though, O'Brien said, ``We created a little bit of a monster with
Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a real hard time scoring points a year ago, and Michael
got away with murder because he was allowed to take a lot of shots,
a lot of poor shots,'' said O'Brien, whose first college coaching
job was as an assistant at UConn in 1977. ``We talked to him about
the need for him to score a bundle of points.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, O'Brien said, ``It's all changed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's changed because of Penn, the Most Valuable Player of the
1997 Big East Tournament. Penn, whose original nickname, ``Uno''
(for No. 1 son), morphed into ``Scoonie,'' has lightened much of
Redd's scoring load and has set Redd up for better shots.
Meanwhile, Penn has proven to be a force of his own.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-10 junior, Penn can score and pass and basically do whatever
you'd like your point guard to do. He and Redd form perhaps college
basketball's most dynamic backcourt. Not to minimize the roles of
center Ken Johnson, forward Jason Singleton and the others, or what
O'Brien adds to the mix (Calhoun calls him ``as efficient an
offensive coach as anybody in America''), but it has primarily been
the Penn-Redd duo that has brought the Buckeyes to a very special
place.
</P>
<P>
   They have related especially well during the NCAA Tournament.
They have scored more than half of the Buckeyes' points.
</P>
<P>
   It sets up an interesting dilemma for Calhoun, whose Huskies
play exceptional defense partly because UConn guard Ricky Moore has
been known to effectively remove the opponent's best offensive
player from the game. Whom does the 6-2 Moore defend, Penn or Redd?
Logic dictates Penn, but what happens if Redd gets hot?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he covers me or if he covers Mike,'' Penn said, ``he's
gonna have to work.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
