<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL-4-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS NOT ALONE IN BELIEF THAT UPSET OVER DUKE IS POSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Michigan State lost to Duke by just six
points during the Great Eight Tournament in Chicago in December,
and the Spartans think they can pull off one of the greatest upsets
in college basketball history against the Blue Devils tonight in
the national semifinals at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have much company, however. Duke is a prohibitive
favorite. But a firm believer in Michigan State's chances is Ohio
State Coach  &UR; Jim O'Brien, who lost to the Spartans, 76-71, in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Michigan State is a real good opponent for Duke,''
O'Brien said. ``The thing that makes them special is their
toughness. . . . I think you have to be a physically and mentally
tough team to be able to play a team like Duke.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's players concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why people are wigging out,'' guard  &UR; Michael Redd
said. ``They're (Michigan State) a great team.  &UR; Mateen Cleaves is a
great leader.'' &QL; 
Rebounding &QL; 
Despite losing, Michigan State outrebounded Duke, 41-25.  &UR; Elton
Brand, the Blue Devils' 6-foot-8, 260-pound All-America sophomore
center, scored 12 points but grabbed just three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that was because of the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've rebounded about 50 percent of their missed shots in
the tournament,'' Brand said. ``That's an outrageous stat. They're
just relentless on the boards.'' &QL; 
Playing footsy &QL; 
Duke's other All-American, senior guard  &UR; Trajan Langdon, doesn't
seem to have many worries. But he was more than a little concerned
when a strained left foot caused him to miss three games, including
the Blue Devils' NCAA Tournament opener against Florida A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very scared,'' he said. ``I didn't really know how to
react, how quick I would recover. . . . But I stayed positive and
did what the trainers and doctors told me to do. I'm fortunate to
be back here.'' &QL; 
Age differential &QL; 
Somebody asked Connecticut Coach  &UR; Jim Calhoun about his
conversations with his flaky sophomore point guard,  &UR; Khalid
El-Amin. Calhoun has said that talking with El-Amin was like
talking to a 35-year-old. But Calhoun wanted to clarify that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It varies between 35 and 15,'' Calhoun said. ``Fifteen we all
understand. . . . The 35, he just seems to have things in
perspective better than most people that I've ever been around.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
