u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NOTEBOOK-BASEBAL     03-26 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NOTEBOOK-BASEBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: IT'S GREAT BEISBOL, BUT DIPLOMACY LITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA ROSENBERG   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of the Baltimore Orioles (79-83 last season) have learned
not to expect too much, and that is good advice for those looking
for political fallout from the Orioles' baseball game Sunday
against a Cuban all-star team in Havana. The Orioles are the latest
American athletes to be pressed into service as diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   But the game, part of a modest package of measures to expand
American contact with ordinary Cubans, is likely to give only a
slight boost to relations between Washington and Havana. Sports
diplomacy has produced dramatic breakthroughs only when the
governments using it were looking for one.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic was the 1971 initiative that came to be known
as pingpong diplomacy. After 20 years with no contacts between
China and the United States, Prime Minister Zhou Enlai invited the
U.S. table tennis team to visit China on its way home from the
world championships in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 players and three reporters who went to Beijing probably
represented more American visitors than had set foot in China since
1950. The Americans said afterward that their hosts, obviously
superior players, let them win many of the games. Three months
after the matches the national security adviser, Henry Kissinger,
made a secret visit to arrange President Nixon's triumphal trip the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly the low point of sports diplomacy came in 1987, when
Heinz Weifenbach, the owner of a cash-strapped ice hockey team in
the West German town of Iserlohn, made a deal with Moammar Gadhafi.
In exchange for the promise of $900,000 from the Libyan leader, the
Iserlohn players wore jerseys advertising the ``Green Book,'' a
compilation of Gadhafi's wisdom. The book was a best seller in
Libya, needless to say, but to Gadhafi's frustration had enjoyed
only limited readership elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's ice hockey federation and local politicians quickly
halted the arrangement, in part because the year before Libya had
orchestrated the bombing of a West Berlin nightclub frequented by
American soldiers, killing three people and injuring hundreds.
Although Weifenbach compared the sponsorship deal to Ping-Pong
diplomacy, it seems to have failed to improve German-Libyan
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been a spate of sports diplomacy lite. In
1991 North and South Korea, bitter enemies, fielded a joint table
tennis team at the world championships in Japan. Last year the
Stars and Stripes flew in Tehran as five American wrestlers
competed, to warm applause. A month before, Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami had proposed a program of cultural exchanges with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' trip _ and a return engagement that the Cuban team
will play in Baltimore in May _ will most likely have a similarly
modest effect. Along with authorizing the baseball games, the
Clinton administration in January approved other cultural exchanges
and allowed Americans to increase the amount of money they can send
Cubans. But wary of alienating right-wing Cubans and their
supporters, the administration did not lift the economic embargo on
Cuba or approve the bipartisan commission many senators had backed
to re-examine Cuba policy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Orioles' trip will open the door to other
high-profile exchanges _ and, perhaps, to better baseball. George
Steinbrenner has been invited to Cuba to talk about a visit by the
Yankees.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
