<SLUG> BC-BKC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL HAS THE NBA BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's edition of The Sporting Muse, which remains devilish
despite tremendous respect for guys named Mateen, Khalid and
Scoonie:
</P>
<P>
   Besides the money, and there will always be the money, what
separates and raises college basketball over the NBA is the
opportunity for guys like Scoonie Penn, all 5-10 of him, to
dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I see NBA teams stuff a court with 3,000 pounds of
manhood and let the ponderous take over the game, my ardor for
college basketball grows stronger. The NBA is the league in
greatest need of an enema.
</P>
<P>
   College basketball just needs better PR, the kind it will
display to the nation today. It's perplexing that more hoop fans
don't favor the collegians. Maybe now with Michael Jordan gone,
fans will begin to drift back to the younger set.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Today in St. Pete, Scoonie Penn (Ohio State), Mateen
Cleaves (Michigan State), the rotund Khalid El-Amin (UConn) and
William Avery (Duke) are the men most likely to be the key a NCAA
title, and that is said with all the respect in the world for their
bigger and better known teammates.
</P>
<P>
   UConn-Ohio State might turn out to be the best game of the
weekend, if only because it's the only one that won't include
odds-on favorite Duke. The Buckeyes passed a lot of stiff tests to
get here, and Penn will not be fazed in the slightest by El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   The thought here is that UConn has yet to play its best game yet
in this tournament, and that it may be due. When Jim Calhoun's team
is on, its running game can obliterate any opponent, even one as
good as OSU.
</P>
<P>
   The other game has the potential to be the best of the
tournament, if Michigan State can stay with Duke and avoid any of
their patented 12-0 runs. When the two teams met earlier this year,
Duke jumped out to a 17-2 lead. Michigan State rallied but lost by
six, and Cleaves finished with an unmemorable 3-for-15 night.
</P>
<P>
   If the Spartans, who have exceptional depth and are solid
defensively, can avoid repeating both experiences, they can stay
with Duke and make it a game in the final five minutes. The one
thing Duke hasn't had to deal with this season is close games. ...
</P>
<P>
   In other words, UConn by 10 and Duke by two in a classic. ...
</P>
<P>
   Duke's William Avery has usually been the last point guard
mentioned in discussions of the four in St. Pete. The other points
are better known, and so are Avery's teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But Avery shot 49 percent this season, the best of the quartet,
and he averages 15 points a game and has a 2-to-1 ratio of assists
to turnovers. ...
</P>
<P>
   If Duke stumbles, the burden may fall on the relative youth of
the team. Six of the top eight players are freshmen or sophomores.
If Duke wins it all, then the burden falls on UCLA, which has the
same kind of youth but was cashiered in the first round. ...
</P>
<P>
   Billy Packer is an excellent basketball analyst. But he can
drive you crazy with some of his predilections.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he put together a 64-team dream tourney comprised
of 60 past NCAA champs and four at-large teams as part of an
advertising package in Sports Illustrated, and has played mythical
games between them in search of a Final Four and all-time national
champ.
</P>
<P>
   In getting to the round of 16 in the March 22 issue, he didn't
show too much cronyism to his beloved ACC. Only three of his Sweet
16 teams are from the ACC. But he somehow had the 1962 Cincinnati
team knocking off unbeaten UCLA teams (1964 and 1967) back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   He also shows his age by heavily favoring older teams. Only four
teams in his Sweet 16 come from the 1980s or 1990s. ...
</P>
<P>
   Small world department: Duke's Trajan Langdon was a high school
classmate of pop singer Jewel. The fact they're both from Alaska
makes it a real, teeny, tiny world, too. ...
</P>
<P>
   San Diego State should consider itself lucky to get a coach as
good as Steve Fisher, who took three Michigan teams to the Final
Four. Now all Fisher has to do is find a new Fab Five somewhere
between Carlsbad and Otay Mesa. ...
</P>
<P>
   Would it be gloating to tell you I had Gonzaga in my office
draft pool? Only if I didn't tell you I also hads North Carolina
and UCLA. ...
</P>
<P>
   Know why the Dodgers gave Kevin Brown $107 million? Because they
factored in all the times Brown will have to relay Todd Hundley's
throws to second base.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Prospectus 1999 projects Hundley will hit .246 this
season with 19 home runs and 50 RBI. Please note that Charles
Johnson, much-maligned last year as a hitter in the shadow of Mike
Piazza, hit .227 with 14 homers and 38 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The same magazine projects Johnson to hit .236 with 21 homers
and 58 RBI with the Orioles this season. As bad as the Mike Piazza
decision was, the Johnson-for-Hundley exchanges may be an all-time
stinker. ...
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember a pitcher whose decline was as predictable as
Hideo Nomo's, who was just waived by the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he was 13-6 for the Dodgers, with a 2.54 ERA and 236
K's and only 124 hits in 191 innings. But his ratios all started to
turn in the wrong direction a year later. The number of walks and
hits allowed per outing increased while his ERA ballooned. He ended
last year by averaging almost six walks every nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   His slider still has bite, but his fastball is now below average
and his control all over the map. That said, it wouldn't hurt the
Angels to scout him, since the A.L. hasn't seen that much of him.
Maybe he could fool them for another 150 innings. ...
</P>
<P>
   Let's see here, Major League Baseball makes its first trip to
Cuba in 40 years, and it includes the Baltimore Orioles' Albert
Belle as one of its ambassadors?
</P>
<P>
   If I'm Bill Clinton, I keep those nuclear firing codes real
close this weekend. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
