<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUCKS-QUALIFYING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRAGUE WINS 4TH PIR POLE  
 RECORD LAP A SURPRISE TO TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jack Sprague won another NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
pole position Friday at Phoenix International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   For Sprague, it was his 13th career pole and fourth at PIR,
where he also has won three times.
</P>
<P>
   But for the life of Sprague, he can't figure out how he did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our practices were terrible,'' Sprague said. ``We're still
trying to find the balance with the new (GMAC Financial Services
Chevy Silverado) truck. We're just going through a learning
curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Some curve.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sprague crashed in the season-opener last week and
finished 22nd, he was a pole cat at PIR, setting a new 1-mile
qualifying record with a speed of 128.402 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Crawford, who earlier had snapped the qualifying mark with
a 128.105 mph lap, will start next to Sprague on the front row.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Sprague) cheated,'' Crawford mused.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Harvick, Greg Biffle and Ron Hornaday Jr. complete the top
five.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wallace, last week's winner, starts seventh in today's
Chevy Trucks 150.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague was as surprised as anyone to make it atop the
qualifying ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled last week,' Sprague said. ``And we went through
three different setups here. I said, `Let's just change the whole
thing again (before the end of practice).'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea we'd be this good. We changed the springs,
shocks, sway bar. I don't know what to say. It shouldn't have
happened, but he (crew chief Dennis Connor) hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what usually happens with champions, right? Sprague won
the series crown two years ago and twice has finished runner-up to
Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to pick, this would be my favorite racetrack,''
Sprague said. ``This is the place we won our first race.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague has won 12 since that first truck victory, including two
at PIR when he started from the pole.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack's been good here,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crawford hasn't won at PIR, he at least has put his
best foot forward in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't let any grass grow underneath (the truck),'' Crawford
said. ``I drove it into the corners, and it worked really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sprague, Harvick also was somewhat surprised with his
starting position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've actually been concentrating on our race setup,'' Harvick
said. ``This was just an added bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Although disappointed with a fourth-row start, Wallace made up
for it in NASCAR Winston West qualifying for today's NAPA Parts
100.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace outdueled Steve Portenga for the pole, unloading a
record fast lap clocked at 129.296 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Portenga checked in at 128.365 mph, which was slightly better
than Hornaday (128.100 mph).
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have taken some of my frustration out after the truck
qualifying,'' said Wallace, younger brother of Rusty Wallace. ``I
thought I had a pole truck there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been really focused on the truck, but we're going to run
four Winston West races, trying to prepare to run four (Winston)
Cup races later in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock car, Wallace said, was purchased from Kranefuss-Haas
Racing, whose Winston Cup driver is John Andretti. Robert Yates
Racing prepared the motor.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Thompson of Phoenix, who finished sixth last season in the
NTB Trans-Am circuit, qualified a respectable 10th in his first
Winston West race. Thompson, 24, put The RoomStore Ford Taurus on
the outside of the fifth row with a speed of 127.348 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Burns of Phoenix starts in Row 14, and Billy Kann of Tempe
starts in the 15th row. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
