<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-BATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD BATS A HANDICAP FOR CUBAN BASEBALL TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Cuba _ When the Cuban hitters face Scott Erickson on
Sunday, it could seem like New York on an April night.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the temperature will be in the mid-80s and the
sun will be shining brightly when the Cuban all-star team plays the
Baltimore Orioles. If Erickson's sinker is working and running into
Cuba's right-handed hitters, ``ouch,'' or worse, could be the
byword of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans can blame it on the new wood bats they will be using
instead of the aluminum bats that have been used in Cuba since
1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is really a big change,'' said Tony Bernazard, a former
major league second baseman, who is in Havana as a representative
of the players association. ``Your hands, the way you grip the bat,
every swing you take, the ball will sting. It's like the first days
of spring training. Guys complain. You feel every pitch. It hurts.
With a sinkerball pitcher, it's even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles would never have played this game with aluminum
bats, but as it happens the Cubans changed to wood two weeks ago
after the International Baseball Association mandated the change
beginning with this summer's Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be a problem for the national team; they've
got four months,'' Tony Castillo, the baseball commissioner for
Havana, said Friday, referring to the Pan Am competition. ``But
it's definitely an advantage for the Orioles.''
</P>
<P>
   Castillo echoed the view registered just the night before by a
waiter who identified himself as a fervent fan. ``I think it's
going to be hard for the Cubans, using wood bats,'' said Victor,
the waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo talked about wood bats while visiting Ciudad Deportiva,
a sports training complex, where the Industriales team had just
finished working out for the start of its Cuban League championship
series against Santiago de Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take two or three months of continuous
practice,'' Castillo said. ``We've had 23 years that we've been
playing with aluminum bats. It's tough for the whole world.
Everyone has to change over.''
</P>
<P>
   But the whole world does not play the Orioles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The batters don't like it, but the pitchers like it,''
Castillo said of the conversion to wood. ``The offensive production
has dropped a lot. There haven't been many long balls hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one home run had been hit in the 20 games that had been
played with wood bats. But yet another change could end the easy
life for pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Because aluminum bats produce harder-hit balls, thus putting
pitchers in jeopardy only 60 feet 6 inches from home plate, the
Cuban League used a ball that was not as hard as the balls the
major leagues use. They continued to use the locally made ball, La
Batos numero 2, when they switched to wood, but the Rawlings ball
used in the United States is to be the pelota of choice for the
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur teams around the world, including virtually all American
high schools and colleges, initially switched to aluminum as an
economy move decades ago. The bats didn't break, like wood, and
lasted far longer. But each new generation of metal bats turned out
to be more potent _ and dangerous. An increasing number of serious
injuries stemming from hard-hit balls prompted various
organizations, including the NCAA, to look at the bats and begin
placing limits on the type of alloys allowed or to change
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   When officials from the major leagues and the players
association came here two weeks ago, they brought the Cubans four
dozen wood bats, and they brought some more when they arrived
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The use of aluminum bats has made it difficult to judge Cubans
in relation to major league hitters. A batter can hit the ball off
the handle of an aluminum bat, and instead of breaking, as wood
often does, the bat sends the ball looping over the infield for a
single or along one of the foul lines for a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit the ball with an aluminum bat and it goes,'' Bernazard
said. ``With wood bats, you have to hit the ball in the four or
five inches of the meat of the bat. With aluminum bats, you hit it
anywhere and you can get a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   With aluminum bats, too, he added, batters had a tendency to
develop longer swings. With wood, Cuban batters will have to cut
down those swings, getting the head of the bat through the hitting
zone faster.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever disadvantages might exist, though, the Cubans eagerly
looked forward to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will sort of test our level of play against the level of
play in the big leagues,'' Castillo said. ``A lot of time has
passed since a big league team came here to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
