<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCERN ABOUT DRUG ISSUES SENDS STOCK MARKET LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell as Merck and Warner-Lambert suffered setbacks on
profitable drugs. Oracle and other software companies traded on the
Nasdaq gained on speculation that investors overreacted to concern
about slowing sales in the personal computer industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 14.15 points, to 9,822.24,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 7.19 points, to
1,282.80, with drug makers accounting for 18 percent of the loss.
The Nasdaq composite index declined 15.63 points, to 2,419.17.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN UNION APPROVES A BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   The European Union agreed to cap its budget at $92 billion a
year through 2006, enabling three Central European countries _
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary _ to join. The union also
advocated Palestinian statehood within the next year in more
forthright terms than it had previously used or than the United
States had ever backed, provoking a furious reaction from Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   LIMITS BACKED FOR DIABETES DRUG
</P>
<P>
   A panel of scientific experts recommended that the government
place stricter limits on the use of the diabetes drug Rezulin,
following reports of deaths and serious liver damage. The committee
urged that patients take the drug only when other therapies had
failed but declined to recommend that it be withdrawn from the
market.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT OF TOYS `R' US DEPARTS
</P>
<P>
   Just a year after arriving at Toys ``R'' Us, Bruce W. Krysiak
has resigned as president and chief operating officer of the
beleaguered retailer. Analysts said that he had concluded either
that he would not be named chief executive as he wished, or that
the company's troubles were worse than he had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ASTHMA DRUG WINS FDA APPROVAL
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor received Food and Drug Administration approval to begin
marketing a new asthma-treatment drug that is a variation on the
best-selling asthma drug.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT AT NESTLE TOPS EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Nestle reported a 2.6 percent profit increase for 1998, to 4.29
billion Swiss francs ($2.92 billion). That beat forecasts, which
analysts had pared after a warning from the company. Demand for
products like Perrier mineral water and Alcon contact lens solution
in the United States and Western Europe outweighed slumping income
in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM GIVES CHIEFS STOCK OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Viacom gave its top three executives stock options together
valued at about $104 million last year. Sumner M. Redstone, who is
chairman of the media company, received options to buy four million
class B common shares, valued at $52 million, after adjusting for a
2-for-1 stock split scheduled for later this month. Two deputy
chairmen, Philippe P. Dauman and Thomas E. Dooley, each received
options for two million shares, valued at $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   CBS IN TALKS TO ACQUIRE KING WORLD
</P>
<P>
   CBS has held talks to acquire King World Productions, syndicator
of such hits as ``Oprah'' and ``Wheel of Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   BOND PRICES DECREASE SLIGHTLY
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell as Citigroup and other companies sold $3.8
billion of debt, sapping demand for government securities. The
yield on the 30-year Treasury rose to 5.59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NOMURA SECURITIES LOST $4.6 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Nomura Securities disclosed one-time losses of about $4.6
billion after pumping money into an affiliate, Nomura Finance. Some
of the losses reflect the poor performance of Nomura's U.S.
subsidiary, Nomura America Holding Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
