<HEADLINE>
KWAN TUMBLES INTO FOURTH PLACE AFTER SHORT PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ The day after Aleksei Yagudin leaned over
and kissed the ice after flirting with perfection, Michelle Kwan
skidded across the ice after falling on her double axel.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two teen-agers who came here to defend their world
titles, Kwan figured to have the easier path to another gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   But while Yagudin has already won the men's event, Kwan's path
is now cluttered with skaters who performed better under pressure
than she did in the short program Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't on; I haven't been on all week,'' Kwan said.
``Usually I'm pretty solid and consistent, but I've been a little
shaky.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, who has been suffering from a head cold, would end up
finishing a rather generous fourth in the short program and is
fourth overall after two phases of the three-phase women's event.
</P>
<P>
   Though she still has a chance to win her second consecutive
title, Kwan will need more than an excellent performance Saturday
in the free skate.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan will need help from Mariya Butyrskaya, the 26-year-old who
skated one of the cleanest and smoothest short programs of her
career Friday to move into first place.
</P>
<P>
   Butyrskaya's Russian teammate, Julia Soldatova, is in second.
Vanessa Gusmeroli of France is third. The encouraging news for
Kwan, who will skate last on Saturday, is that none of those three
has won a world or Olympic title, and Butyrskaya and Gusmeroli have
a history of letting nerves get the better of their potential.
</P>
<P>
   Butyrskaya can finish second in the free skate to Kwan and still
win her first world title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly can win the long,'' Kwan said. ``But now I don't
control my own destiny. It's hard to rely on other skaters to miss.
It's bad karma.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is also in position to become the first country to win
all four events during one world championships.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Russian victories in the men's and the pairs, the
ice dancing team of Anjelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsyannikov won their
country's third gold medal here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Krylova and Ovsyannikov, who have trained and lived in Newark,
Del., since 1994, won by the narrowest of margins over Marina
Anissina and Gwendal Peizerat of France.
</P>
<P>
   The French free dance, set to music from the movie ``Man in the
Iron Mask,'' was more accessible and romantic than the Russians'
frenetic and relentlessly exuberant performance to the sound of
African drums.
</P>
<P>
   The judges scored it 5-4 in favor of the defending world
champions. Even if the French had won, Russia could have claimed
some credit, because Anissina was born and raised in Moscow. The
bronze medal went to the Canadians Shae-Lynn Bourne and Victor
Kraatz, their fourth straight bronze at the worlds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kwan's missed double axel was not the only cause for concern
during her performance. On her opening jump, she began listing as
she spun in the air but somehow managed to right herself in time to
land her triple lutz and then complete the combination with a
double toe loop.
</P>
<P>
   After her fall, Kwan briefly looked stiff and disoriented. She
ended up receiving marks ranging from 5.1 to 5.5 for technical
merit (a fall in the short program incurs a mandatory 0.4
deduction). Kwan still received her customarily high marks for
presentation: all 5.8s and 5.9s, but three of the nine judges
placed her fifth, one placed her sixth, another seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan conceded that she felt fortunate to be fourth. ``I'm very
disappointed in how I skated; I looked into the monitor and saw I
was fourth and didn't believe they held me up there,'' she said of
the judges.
</P>
<P>
   While Kwan was fourth and driven to tears, 13-year-old Sarah
Hughes of Great Neck, N.Y., was ninth and delighted. Though Hughes
still lacks the speed and polish of her elders, she landed all of
her required jumps Friday: a double axel, a difficult triple
lutz-double toe combination and a triple flip in her first event at
this level.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes also shrugged off the remarkable disparity in her scores,
with her technical marks ranging from 4.4 to 5.4 and her artistic
marks from 5.0 to 5.7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to skate my program and look like I belonged,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
