<HEADLINE>
TORRE VISITS CLUBHOUSE 8 DAYS AFTER CANCER SURGERY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Just eight days after undergoing surgery to remove
his cancerous prostate, manager Joe Torre showed up in the Yankees'
clubhouse Friday, assuring his players in a closed-door meeting
that he is on the way to a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was important for them to see that I'm
feeling fine, and it's just a matter of time, basically,'' Torre
said afterward, sitting in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher David Cone said it was comforting. ``It's quite
remarkable to see him in such good shape,'' Cone said, ``moving
around so well and in such good spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, 58, said he planned to be with the team every day for the
rest of spring training, ``or at least two of every three days.''
</P>
<P>
   But he emphasized that he was in no rush to resume managing and
that he had no intention of establishing a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to set something I can't live up to and then all
of a sudden the flag goes up, saying, `Uh-oh,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether he will be at the Yankees' home opener on April 9
against Detroit, he said: ``I may be visible, but I'm not going to
be directing the team. Don Zimmer's done enough of that during his
career, a lot longer than I have. That doesn't mean I'm going to
stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre had surgery on March 18 in St. Louis and left the hospital
three days later. Torre's doctor, the noted urologist William
Catalona, suggested on Thursday that Torre meet with his team three
days earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just thought I needed a little more stimulation,'' Torre
said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager's biggest challenge now, he said, is to get his
strength back. ``That's the thing where the question comes in. Just
because of the surgery, your blood count goes down and you tend to
be a little anemic. That's the area where you have to keep an eye
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said that to regain his strength he would eat heartily and
take daily iron pills.
</P>
<P>
   Catalona had said after the surgery that Torre should expect to
resume managing the team in 6 to 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the day I'm fine,'' Torre said. ``Then it just sort
of tapers off. I can't wait to get out of bed; then all of a sudden
it disappears. I'm going to make sure that gets better. I'm not
going to be anxious in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   His first post-surgery baseball work took place by telephone
earlier in the week. He talked with outfielder Darryl Strawberry,
who is recovering from colon cancer surgery, about Strawberry's
chances of making the opening day roster. On Thursday Torre
participated via telephone in a two-hour discussion on Yankee
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to rely more on people who've seen these players
play,'' Torre said. ``But I'm still involved in making decisions.
Actually there's not very many decisions to be made. I'm sure you'd
like another utility man, but right now that guy isn't apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said the only significant decisions left are whether the
opening day roster should include pitcher Andy Pettitte, who is
working his way back from left elbow tightness, and Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Torre expects to be re-examined in about a month to make sure he
does not require any radiation or chemotherapy. But he is starting
to feel frisky again. He can tell that, he said, because he is
beginning to recapture the feeling that winning baseball games is
the most important thing in the world to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the initial shock, when you feel wonderful and find
out you're not, is tough to get over,'' he said. ``But now that the
surgery is behind me, my mental outlook is better.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte said the first thing he does daily when he wakes
up is to test his left elbow for tightness. ``It feels great,'' he
said Friday. ``I want to pitch, but they're not giving me any
answers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
