<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   And Our Next Sports Car Will Be Called the Blue Devil &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Originally, G. Richard Wagoner Jr., president of General Motors,
was going to be the host of a reception Monday night at Cipriani
42nd Street, in advance of the New York Auto Show. But GM had a
change of heart after a restaurant workers' union ran a newspaper
ad urging a boycott of the Rainbow Room, another establishment run
by the Cipriani family, and saying, ``a lot of people think the
Ciprianis have hearts of stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The car maker promptly switched the site to Vanderbilt Hall of
Grand Central Terminal, but the change it highlighted in large
letters in its letter to the media was something else altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Wagoner was a member of Duke University's
basketball team in the 1970s and remains a fanatical follower of
the Blue Devils. He planned to attend Saturday night's matchup with
Michigan State and, whether Duke won or lost, to catch the national
college championship game Monday at 9:18 p.m. So, the revised
invitation reads, ``As an added attraction, we'll stick around
after the reception and invite you to join us for an NCAA Finals
party.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It Beats Hanging Out at the Cooler &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who says the workplace has to be about carpel tunnel syndrome?
``There are a lot of demented minds out there ready to have fun,''
said Matt Weinstein, the mastermind behind the fourth annual
International Fun at Work Day on April 1. Weinstein, founder of
Playfair Inc., a San Francisco consulting firm, has signed up
hundreds of companies, including Federal Express and AT&AMP;T, for the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the folks at A Business Conference Call, in Chaska,
Minn., dressed backwards and talked backwards (``Now lunch to going
am I''), while Sprint employees in 20 cities took snapshots of
themselves doing goofy things like sitting on a police car or
playing catch with a dog. This year, a guru in Madras, India, will
hold laughter seminars and employees at the Mutual Aid Association
in Nebraska will post photographs of their bare feet on bulletin
boards. ``It's treating people at work like you would treat your
family,'' Weinstein said, ``if you had fun with your family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Attractions of Asian Art &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rich and famous came out in force on Wednesday at the
International Asian Art Fair in Manhattan, but they were mostly
just looking. Veronica Hearst, wearing part of a diamond stomacher
with a big pearl drop, said her husband, Randolph Hearst, chairman
of the Hearst Corp., ``likes jade, and if I see something I like,
I'll surprise him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Petrie, widow of the retailing giant Milton Petrie,
focused on coloration. ``I love blue and white, and that's what I'm
looking for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving, Winston Fowlkes, former treasurer at the old Time
Inc., said, ``I saw a couple of things that are under serious
consideration.'' His wife, Isabel, beamed.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, though. The event raised $400,000 for the Asia
Society. Besides, even royalty balked at the price tags. When the
Crown Princess of Greece, the former Marie-Chantal Miller, allowed
that ``there are some beautiful things here,'' her husband, Crown
Prince Pavlos, arched his eyebrows in regal alarm. ``Not yet,'' he
declared. ``We can't afford it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bridging Boundaries in Israel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With ethnic conflict rampant in the world, reconciliation is
suddenly big news in Israel. This month, Rana Raslan became the
first Arab Miss Israel, Abdel Rahman Zu'bi became the first Arab
appointed to the Israeli Supreme Court and an Arab member of
parliament said he would run for prime minister. It was the sort of
ethnic intermingling that a couple of New York money managers, one
Jewish, the other Arab-American, have promoted for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the events that raise the consciousness of the Jews
and Arabs of Israel,'' said Alan B. Slifka, founder of the Abraham
Fund, which recruits donors to ``adopt'' programs in Israel, from
theater groups to day-care centers, that bring the two communities
together. ``We can be viewed as a coexistence mutual fund.''
Slifka, the managing principal of Halcyon/Alan B. Slifka Management
Co., added that the fund has offered to sponsor a tour of the
United States by Ms. Raslan.
</P>
<P>
   James D. Awad, the founder of Awad Asset Management and a member
of the fund's board, says the grass-roots contacts it fosters are
the best hope for peace in the Mideast. The grandson of Arab
Christians who fled Syria, he says half his clients are Jewish, but
he also manages money for Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
