<HEADLINE>
PERRY RETURNS TO FOOTBALL, MIGHT BE TROJAN AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former USC wide receiver Rod Perry has met with
coach Paul Hackett, and the Trojans are among several schools Perry
is considering transferring to from Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   Perry left USC last summer and enrolled at Cal State Fullerton
after he decided he would rather become a full-time baseball
player.
</P>
<P>
   But he quit the Titans baseball team three weeks ago after
experiencing a change of heart, and is taking at least five
football recruiting trips before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and his dad came in,'' Hackett said. ``I said, `I really
don't know you. I haven't seen you play. I'm not going to start
recruiting you, but I'm not going to close the door.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wanted to come here, we would find a scholarship for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry is visiting Penn State this weekend. He has already
visited Nevada-Las Vegas, which is coached by John Robinson, who
recruited Perry to USC.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he goes, Perry will be eligible immediately, because he
has not participated in a college football practice since 1997,
meaning he would fall under the NCAA's two-year no-participation
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Spring practice opens: The Trojans held their first official
practice at Howard Jones Field on Friday. Looking in midseason form
was wide receiver R. Jay Soward, who was AWOL from the program for
several weeks and considered applying for the NFL's supplemental
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fun. It was good to be back playing football and not
just running, running, running,'' Soward said. ``I just realized
how much I missed it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
