<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MILOSEVIC'S CAMPAIGN OF TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (changes spelling of Keljmendi to Kelmendi) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For three days now, on Slobodan Milosevic's orders,
Serbian policemen, soldiers and paramilitary thugs have been
spreading terror across Kosovo. They have burned and shelled
villages, driven thousands of ethnic Albanians from their homes and
carried out dozens of assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of the terror campaign has not fully registered in the
outside world because Milosevic has expelled Western journalists
and cut off television links. But enough details have got through
to make clear that a human disaster is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   One example: On Thursday a respected source saw many thousands
of civilians making a forced march from the town of Qirez. Serbian
tanks were behind a column, a mile or more long, of men, women and
children. What happened to them is not known.
</P>
<P>
   A second example: At 1:10 a.m. on Thursday armed men in black
uniforms with Serbian police insignia broke into the Pristina home
of a leading Kosovo Albanian human rights lawyer, Bajram Kelmendi.
His wife said they shouted, ``You have five seconds to come out of
your rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The policemen ransacked the house, beat Kelmendi and took him
and his two sons away. At daybreak Mrs. Kelmendi went to police
headquarters, where she was told to take her troubles to NATO and
the Kosovo Liberation Army. Friday Kelmendi and his sons were found
shot dead a few miles from Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   A third: Serbian police shot the elderly doorman at the last
Albanian-language newspaper in Kosovo, Koha Ditore, as they shut
the paper down. The publisher, Veton Surroi, went into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has targeted for kidnapping and assassination the top
Albanian editors, lawyers, doctors and educators. The idea is to
decapitate the leadership _ exactly what his killers set out to do
in Bosnia seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic terror campaign mocks one of the main purposes
given by President Clinton and others for the NATO operation. In
the president's words, that is ``to deter an even bloodier
offensive against innocent civilians in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   If we and our allies did not act, Clinton said, ``President
Milosevic would read our hesitation as a license to kill. There
would be many more massacres _ tens of thousands more refugees,
more victims crying out for revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has, rather, made the NATO operation a license to
kill. The massacres are occurring, and there are tens of thousands
of new refugees. That puts a heavy responsibility on Clinton. He
faces a humanitarian debacle. What should he do?
</P>
<P>
   First, he should support the NATO Supreme Commander, Gen. Wesley
Clark, in his desire to intensify the air attacks. The scale of the
operation so far has been nowhere near large enough to make
Milosevic believe we mean business _ much less to destroy his
military power.
</P>
<P>
   Second, NATO must begin using in Kosovo the aircraft that
operate against tanks and artillery: attack helicopters and A-10
Warthogs. They have been held back because they fly lower and
slower, and hence are more vulnerable to anti-aircraft weapons. But
not using them means giving a free hand to Milosevic in his Kosovo
terror campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the United States has compelling evidence of what
Milosevic is doing in Kosovo: high-resolution photographs from
satellites that show burning villages and shattered houses. We
should publish those pictures to counter Milosevic's tactic of
shutting out the world.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, NATO has to face the fact that more than air power may
be needed to save the people of Kosovo. Clinton and the Europeans
have said that no ground forces would go in unless Milosevic
agreed. But we are beyond that now. We have to think about a
protection force on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy, and it never was going to be. But caving in to
Slobodan Milosevic would be inestimably worse. He is using the
tactics of the Gestapo. His regime increasingly has the smell of
the first fascist state in post-Cold War Europe.
</P>
<P>
   What will NATO celebrate at its 50th anniversary party next
month if it has allowed Kosovo to become a graveyard? What will
become of the humanitarian ideal, of what Clinton called ``a moral
imperative''? One former diplomat said: ``If they don't get
serious, Kosovo will be the humanitarian Bay of Pigs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-99 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990326.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-PROTESTS-NY     03-26 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-PROTESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLS TO PROTEST DIALLO KILLING TAPPED INTO FRUSTRATIONS OVER NYC
POLICE
</HEADLINE>
  (also see NY-POLICE-INDICT)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The plan was simple, an old-fashioned civil
disobedience campaign to protest the Feb. 4 shooting death of
Amadou Diallo. But when the Rev. Al Sharpton counted his troops
early this month, he had only about 80 people willing to get
arrested for the cause.
</P>
<P>
   They were mostly professional protesters, fist shakers,
tried-and-true community advocates. Not exactly the stuff of
front-page headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But after the first week of protests outside Police Headquarters
in lower Manhattan, the Rev. Gary V. Simpson of Concord Baptist
Church in Brooklyn called his black, middle-class congregation to
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting arrested,'' he said at a Sunday morning service.
``Who's going with me?'' More then 30 nurses, teachers, students
and retirees rose to their feet. ``I stood slowly, but I stood,''
said Makeba D'Abreu, 30, a divinity student who had never been
arrested before Wednesday. ``I was scared, but I had to do it. It
was all piling up. It was a pattern of police abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   After the second week of protests, Arthur Strimling signed on,
too, invited by his rabbi. For years, Strimling had viewed street
marches as relics of the 1960s. But he was outraged by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's refusal to discuss concerns about the police
with moderate black politicians and others. ``This is the only way
to get him to listen,'' said Strimling, 57, a theater director from
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   And by this week, the third week of daily protests, it was clear
that what Sharpton started had become one of New York City's most
successful protest machines. The demonstrations, which sputtered to
a start with 12 arrests on March 9, swelled into one of the largest
and most diverse civil disobedience campaigns in recent years, with
police tallying 216 arrests Friday for a total of 1,009.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly why Sharpton's call ultimately appealed to
so many. Some marchers clearly came for the glory of it all, to
shake their fists for the television cameras and to ogle
celebrities like Susan Sarandon and Ossie Davis who were handcuffed
in Diallo's name.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, more than a dozen protesters said Sharpton
had tapped into their frustrations with overly aggressive policing
and with a stubborn mayor, who refused to meet or talk with his
critics, including respected elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators also found comfort in the carefully
choreographed procedures, which allowed people to schedule arrests
and to experience little discomfort. (Protesters could even buy ice
cream and chocolate bars from vending machines while their arrests
were processed.)
</P>
<P>
   Workers could arrange to take time off and march with their
churches, unions and neighborhood groups. And the presence of
moderate black politicians and ministers helped persuade some white
people to put aside their distrust of Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it was just one of those things going on in this
city, far away from my normal life,'' said Strimling, who lives in
Park Slope and was arrested on Wednesday. ``It was Sharpton and his
followers, and God knows, that's not my world. I'm a nice, white
middle-class guy. I don't get arrested. I have no love for
Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton has said that the daily protests will continue until
the indictments against the officers in the Diallo shooting are
unsealed. But callers are still burning up the phone line at his
Harlem office. One woman called this week, trying to sign up for
next Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
