<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-DRUNK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN SEIZED FROM NYC OFFICER CHARGED WITH DRUNKEN DRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An off-duty police officer backed his Chevrolet van
into a Queens liquor store, knocking down part of a wall and
prompting the first confiscation of a vehicle from an officer
accused of drunken driving, police said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, James Schmidt, 41, was charged with driving while
intoxicated and his 1986 Chevrolet Suburban was impounded by the
police. The van struck a wall of Leiser's Liquor at the
intersection of Sanford Avenue and 162rd Street in Flushing about
11 p.m. Thursday, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got into his van, it moved backward and crashed into a wall
of a liquor store,'' said Mary DeBourbon, a spokeswoman for the
Queens District Attorney.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting the wall, the officer got out of the van and fell
down, cutting and bruising himself to the extent that he had to be
taken to New York Hospital Medical Center of Queens for treatment,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who has been on the force since 1997, was suspended
after the incident. The police would not disclose the level of
alcohol in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   The van punched a hole about 10 feet high and 15 feet wide in a
side room, not the liquor store itself, which was closed.
</P>
<P>
   The police began confiscating cars from drivers with a blood
alcohol content greater than 0.10 percent in late February. Through
Thursday, 167 vehicles had been confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Madelyne Colon said the van taken from Schmidt was the
first vehicle confiscated from a police officer under the new laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
