<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPTON-NYT &LR;      03-26 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RAIN, SERENA WILLIAMS POURS IT ON HINGIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ The juggernaut went for the jugular Friday
afternoon in the women's semifinals at the Lipton Championships.
Serena Williams, wielding her racquet like a graphite howitzer,
turned her sights on the world's top-ranked player, Martina Hingis,
and throttled her, 6-3, 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never beaten the No. 1. player in the world before, so I
guess this is my biggest victory,'' said Williams, who will face
either her sister, Venus, the Lipton's defending champion, or the
five-time Lipton champion Steffi Graf in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-seeded Williams, invincible in 16 consecutive matches,
admitted to harboring a slight preference about the identity of her
final-round opponent. ``If I play Venus, it wouldn't really matter
who won or who lost; the trophy would definitely go to our house,''
said Williams, who is 0-2 against her older sister and 1-1 against
Graf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus has always been in front, but I guess you could say
we're even now,'' said Williams, indubitably the world's most
confident 16th-ranked player. A final-round confrontation between
the Williams sisters would be the first time that two sisters
butted heads for a title since 19-year-old Maud Watson defeated her
26-year-old sibling, Lillian, in the 1884 Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's rain-delayed, 1-hour 26-minute power play thrust the
17-year-old Williams into her third straight final. Not since
Hingis, 18, monopolized the scene in 1997 has a teenager wreaked
such sustained insurrection against the rest of her peers on the
WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who hasn't lost a match since the thorny third round
of the Australian Open to Sandrine Testud on Jan. 23, captured her
first career title by beating the Australian Open runner-up Amelie
Mauresmo in Paris on Feb. 28 and instantly followed that milestone
by overpowering Graf two weeks ago in the Evert Cup final at Indian
Wells, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's victory, her first demotion of Hingis in three
attempts, brought vindication for the two match points she wasted
against Hingis in their quarterfinal here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how I felt when I won two, three tournaments in a row;
I was like, `OK, nobody's better than me,''' said Hingis, who saw
that feeling embodied in Williams belting and pelting balls at her
from across the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time for her, not for me,'' said Hingis, whose
performance suffered from an irregular first serve that rarely hit
80 mph and an anemic second serve that floated over the net like
dandelion fluff and was routinely pounded into oblivion by
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the amply muscled Williams maintained a 100 mph
average on her own first serves and, after a jittery start where
she took 100 mph swipes at all of her ground strokes and turned
most of them to swashbuckling unforced errors, happily settled into
her role as dictator of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things didn't go the way I planned in the beginning,'' said
Williams, ``but I just told myself to fight. I've never given up in
my life. I just don't have that spirit in me. If it was, it's no
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis took a 4-0 lead in the first set, which began three hours
late and was momentarily suspended when sprinkles started falling
three games and nine minutes into what looked initially like a rout
for the Lipton's 1997 champion.
</P>
<P>
   But when Williams finally got her arsenal in order and held for
1-4 with a crafty backhand lob, the match did an about-face and
Hingis dropped eight straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden I was behind 6-4, and then she was leading 2-0
quite quick: She was always a step faster than me,'' said Hingis,
who found her deficit so insulting that she poured on the precision
and nudged her way to a 5-2 lead in the second set. But closure
there eluded her. She squandered three opportunities to serve for
the second set, and on her second try was robbed of a set point at
5-4 by a non-call on an apparently out-of-bounds forehand return by
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis was angered more by her inability to close out the set on
the chances she had before and after that missed call to blame it
for her misfortunes: ``You definitely don't love it, but it
happens. I should have made it before, and I had another chance
after, big chances and I didn't use them,'' said Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   In the tie breaker, Williams powered her way to her first and
only match point with a backhand blast that glazed the sideline,
and then, at 6-3, snaked a down-the-line forehand past Hingis and
immediately raised both arms in the air to celebrate.
</P>
</TEXT>
